data.text:
&lt;p&gt;Well, this &lt;b&gt;past&lt;/b&gt; weekend was the annual &lt;b&gt;Feast of the Hunter&#039;s Moon&lt;/b&gt; festival at &lt;b&gt;Fort Ouiatenon&lt;/b&gt;, West Lafayette.  The Feast is an &lt;b&gt;annual&lt;/b&gt; event that recreates a 18th century French-Indian trading post that was in this area.  Many many people (something like 45,000 this year) come to the festival from all over the country to see &lt;b&gt;interesting things&lt;/b&gt; and sample &lt;b&gt;interesting foods&lt;/b&gt;.  Many of the people come dressed up in period clothing, dressed as 18th century traders and voyageurs &lt;b&gt;(&lt;a href=&quot;http://dictionary.reference.com/search?q=voyageurs&quot;&gt;look it up&lt;/a&gt;)&lt;/b&gt;.  Since I was here at Purdue (just down the &lt;b&gt;Tippecanoe river&lt;/b&gt; from Fort Ouiatenon), I went to the Feast with my &lt;b&gt;family&lt;/b&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

	&lt;p&gt;I have gone to the Feast for &lt;b&gt;several years now&lt;/b&gt;, and &lt;b&gt;the same sort of thing always seems to happen to me&lt;/b&gt;.  Once I get over the initial shock of seeing so many &lt;b&gt;weird people&lt;/b&gt; wearing weird things all at once, and I stop trying to look &lt;b&gt;cool&lt;/b&gt;, I begin to see just how little there is to do.  The whole event is spread out over an area about the size of &lt;b&gt;two football fields&lt;/b&gt;, and most of it is devoted to campers who go to stay the entire weekend.  About &lt;b&gt;half way through&lt;/b&gt; the thing, however, I realize that it&#039;s not about &lt;b&gt;doing stuff&lt;/b&gt; and &lt;b&gt;seeing stuff&lt;/b&gt;, but it is actually just about simply &lt;b&gt;being&lt;/b&gt;.  It&#039;s just about being part of the &lt;b&gt;whole experience&lt;/b&gt;.  I don&#039;t care where I go or what I do, because I feel like part of a &lt;b&gt;community&lt;/b&gt;, like I grew up and live with all of the &lt;b&gt;weird people everywhere&lt;/b&gt;.  Eventually I can ignore all of the &lt;b&gt;stroller pushing suburban families&lt;/b&gt; who do nothing but complain and get in the way (their children all have &lt;b&gt;fake&lt;/b&gt; wooden swords and rifles).&lt;/p&gt;

	&lt;p&gt;Everywhere you go the whole weekend, there may not be anything to do, but something is &lt;b&gt;happening&lt;/b&gt;.  People are &lt;b&gt;singing&lt;/b&gt;, or cooking something, or doing some sort of &lt;b&gt;presentation&lt;/b&gt;.  We heard a great song about the various &lt;b&gt;amputational sacrifices&lt;/b&gt; that one must make to become a pirate.  We had delicious handmade &lt;b&gt;apple dumplings&lt;/b&gt;.  We saw some &lt;b&gt;Irriquois&lt;/b&gt; presenting an example of their &lt;b&gt;native dance&lt;/b&gt;.  It was a chance to escape the homework and &lt;b&gt;ego bashing&lt;/b&gt; that is College, and go to a different time and place.  At least for a while.&lt;/p&gt;

	&lt;p&gt;I had a great time with my parents, too.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I just got word that Half Life 2, possibly the most advanced game ever, is finally finished, and will be coming out on November 1st. I am extermely excited about it, but I am also a little worried. The game was originally scheduled for release on September 30th, 2003. That&#039;s a long time to wait for a game, not knowing just when it will come out. The real problem is that this is not a rare case. Most games are delayed, and most of those are delayed by an incredible ammount. Duke Nukem Forever, the proposed next game in the Duke Nukem series (extremely intellectual games), was supposed to be released some time in 1997. &lt;i&gt;DNF&lt;/i&gt; is still &lt;b&gt;not out yet&lt;/b&gt;, and the developers have &lt;b&gt;no idea when it will be released&lt;/b&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

	&lt;p&gt;Other games, like &lt;i&gt;Daikatana&lt;/i&gt; had similar fates.  However, when they finally did come out, they were horrible games, destroyed by the hype that came up because of the delay.  Whenever a huge game is delayed, the game is surrounded with so much hype that it could not possibly live up to expectations.&lt;/p&gt;

	&lt;p&gt;I have two comments to give about this.  First is what will happen to &lt;i&gt;Half Life 2&lt;/i&gt;?  I have no question about it&#039;s success (it is the sequel to the game that most people consider to be the greatest game of all time, and it looks simply breathtaking, so there is no question that it will sell), but will it be a good game?  I have preordered my copy already, and I have watched the &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.e3expo.com&quot; target=&quot;body&quot;&gt;E3&lt;/a&gt; videos on a regular basis.  Am I getting too pumped for this game?  Movies can have the same effect happen, too.  Just look at &lt;i&gt;&lt;b&gt;Star Wars: Episode 1&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/i&gt; (hey, I loved it, but a lot of people didn&#039;t).  Am I destined to be dissapointed by &lt;i&gt;Half Life&lt;/i&gt;?  Only time will tell.&lt;/p&gt;

	&lt;p&gt;My other comment is this: how can &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.valvesoftware.com/square.htm&quot; target=&quot;body&quot;&gt;they&lt;/a&gt; justify a delay of this magnitude?  When was the last time the creators of a movie decided to delay the release an entire year, just a week before it is scheduled to be released?  You don&#039;t see commercials on Fox for a new show, only to learn that it won&#039;t be on till the season after next (well, maybe that was a bad example).  Should the game industry be allowed to hold the &lt;b&gt;carrot in front of our noses&lt;/b&gt; for so long?  For the most part, the games themselves are really the only things that get hurt, so one would think that developers would care enough to wait a little while before announcing a game.&lt;/p&gt;

	&lt;p&gt;Maybe I am jumping the gun a little bit.  &lt;i&gt;PC Gamer&lt;/i&gt; has reviewed &lt;i&gt;Half Life 2&lt;/i&gt;, and gave the game the highest score to date: &lt;b&gt;98%&lt;/b&gt;.  Perhaps it&#039;s not that bad after all, hype or no hype.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;b&gt;Hello, visitors.&lt;/b&gt;  My site is now officially &lt;b&gt;up and running&lt;/b&gt;, so those of you who were waiting anxiously for the site to go &lt;b&gt;&quot;gold&quot;&lt;/b&gt; can finally get what you were waiting for.  For the rest of you -- the section of the population that couldn&#039;t care less whether or not this site exhisted -- begin &lt;b&gt;not&lt;/b&gt; reading this site.  I am going to try to get a &lt;b&gt;measly viewing base&lt;/b&gt; up and running, which may be hard, but I want to see just how many people can be interrested in a college student&#039;s &lt;b&gt;incoherrant, meaningless, mostly misspelled&lt;/b&gt; ramblings.

			&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Once again, hello!
			&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

