data.text:
&lt;p&gt;The guys next door to me have a mock &lt;i&gt;Time Magazine&lt;/i&gt; cover on there door that has a picture of George Bush, and the phrase &lt;b&gt;&quot;We&#039;re F**ked&quot;&lt;/b&gt; underneath it (with the asteriks).  That about sums up my opinion.&lt;/p&gt;


	&lt;p&gt;I &lt;b title=&quot;Actually I threw my vote away.&quot;&gt;voted&lt;/b&gt; in my first presidential election two days ago, and I must say that it one of the &lt;b&gt;funniest ordeals&lt;/b&gt; in my life (and not in the good way).  I will express my disgust and rage at the government here, where &lt;b title=&quot;Well, anyone who comes to my site, that is.&quot;&gt;all&lt;/b&gt; can enjoy and be enraged by it.  I will go ahead and throw my oppinions and frustrations into the fray with the &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.bushin30seconds.org&quot; title=&quot;Liberal Propoganda, or mostly truth?&quot; class=&quot;black&quot;&gt;&lt;b&gt;hundreds&lt;/b&gt; of other web complaints out there&lt;/a&gt;.  Bush must not surf the internet much.&lt;/p&gt;

	&lt;p&gt;I will try to stay away from just saying what everyone else has been saying for four years now.  All that stuff about Bush lying, cheating, and stealing his way through the United States.  Oh, well I guess I did say it.  That&#039;s not my point, though.  I have a series of ideas (read: crazy schemes) that I think would make this country a better place to live in.  But first, I will tell my story.&lt;/p&gt;

	&lt;p&gt;I woke up on Tuesday refreshed and ready for a day&#039;s hard work, coding my next web project (read: computer games).  I sat down in my desk chair, and remembered that it was Election Day.  Whoopie!!  For the first time in my life, I finally had a voice.  I could finally express what I felt for all these years with a simple hanging chad.  I hurredly got on my bicycle and rode off to Cary (Ironic? perhaps) Quadrangle, the local (read: only) polling place on the Purdue Campus.  I left in such a hurry that I forgot to take my registration card, or a book to read (you&#039;ll see why that was a problem later in my epic story).&lt;/p&gt;

	&lt;p&gt;So I get to Cary (I still think that&#039;s a little weird), and follow the My Man Mitch signs to the small door that leads to the small room in the basement where an entire college campus was to vote.  You may be starting to see my problem.  I &lt;b title=&quot;With full Cramming Power!!!&quot;&gt;crammed&lt;/b&gt; myself inside, squeazing past the pseudo-line to get shelter from the drizzling rain that had gotten my bike seat all wet during the night.  I figured that it wouldn&#039;t be too long, judging from past election days and the primaries that I have witnessed.  I figured that voting was a smooth, quick process that only takes a few moments per person, so although the line was long, it would move fast.&lt;/p&gt;

	&lt;p&gt;I couldn&#039;t have been more wrong.&lt;/p&gt;

	&lt;p&gt;I heard rumors up and down the line of the 15 minute wait.  The 30 minute wait.  THE 45 MINUTE WAIT.  And, with a hushed voice, the horrible, legendary monster: &lt;b&gt;the hour long wait!!!!&lt;/b&gt; &lt;i&gt;**gasp**&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

	&lt;p&gt;&lt;i title=&quot;with maybe a few other cuss words in there, too. . .&quot;&gt;Damn,&lt;/i&gt; I thought, &lt;i&gt;I should have brought my book to read in line.  Oh, well, I can just strike up a conversation with this really attractive&lt;/i&gt; (read: hot) &lt;i&gt;girl in front of me.&lt;/i&gt;

	&lt;p&gt;I didn&#039;t strike up a conversation with the hot girl in front of me.  She was studying, and I - um - didn&#039;t want to  - uh - &lt;i&gt;bother&lt;/i&gt; her.  Yeah, that&#039;s it.&lt;/p&gt;

	&lt;p&gt;Anyway,  that hour long wait would have been nice.  We waited and waited, the hot girl and I, and it seemed like my whole adult life was going to be spent standing in line.  It didn&#039;t really seem that bad (I went to the Star Wars Celebration 2, where I actually did spend most of the time in line).  It was annoying, however, because I just wanted to throw my vote away and get out of there.&lt;/P&gt;

	&lt;p&gt;As we got closer to the little doorway of hope, we could see that people were spending up to ten minutes voting.  &quot;What, did they add an essay question this year? What&#039;s taking so long?&quot; I said in the best smart-ass college student attitude I could muster.  The students around me, who are used to essay tests, all laughed.  We started chatting.&lt;/p&gt;

	&lt;p&gt;As it turns out, the &lt;b&gt;board of elections&lt;/b&gt; only sent &lt;i&gt;three&lt;/i&gt; voting booths to Purdue University.  Three booths were to support an entire campus of hyped up, hip, voting college students.  What were they thinking?  The guy in charge said that they &lt;b&gt;didn&#039;t expect many voters&lt;/b&gt;, with the small turn out at the primaries.  Okay, am I the only one who finds that stupid?  First of all, the primaries are really worth nothing, at least this year.  Secondly, didn&#039;t he see Purdue&#039;s own newspaper, which has reported record numbers of registered students this year?  How could anyone in their right mind possibly think that three booths are enough for a giant campus of unruly students?&lt;/p&gt;

	&lt;p&gt;My only consolation is that they gave us &lt;b&gt;stickers&lt;/b&gt; when we voted.  Yes, that makes it all worth it: a sticker that says &lt;b&gt;&quot;I voted.&quot;&lt;/b&gt;  &lt;i&gt;Joy&lt;/i&gt;.  The guy behind me was annoyed because he got a &lt;b&gt;pin&lt;/b&gt; four years ago.  &quot;They must have spent all of their money on voting booths&quot; I said with a chuckle.  Everyone laughed again.  I wish someone important heard that.  Or the hot girl.&lt;/p&gt;

	&lt;p&gt;So after two of those monsterous hour long waits, I finally got to vote.  I was a little worried that without my registration card I wouldn&#039;t be able to vote, and all that wasted time would be - well - wasted.  Actally it was not a problem.  All I needed was my &lt;b&gt;expired learner&#039;s permit&lt;/b&gt; (yep), and I was able to fully waste my vote by writing in &quot;RALPH NADER.&quot;  Indiana has voted Republican since God knows when, so it wouldn&#039;t matter just who I voted for.  A vote for NADER is a vote for BUSH as far as Indiana is concerned.&lt;/p&gt;

	&lt;p&gt;I didn&#039;t even get to vote for the gay marriage issue.&lt;/p&gt;

	&lt;p&gt;So, yeah.  The United States voting system has some serious problems.  I heard that later in the day students were waiting upwards of &lt;i&gt;five hours&lt;/i&gt; to vote.  CNN had already colored Indiana in with red before some of my friends were even able to cast their vote.  That&#039;s just not right.&lt;/p&gt;

	&lt;p&gt;So just to make my opinion &lt;i&gt;really&lt;/i&gt; heard, I am going to list my ideas for how to make the US electoral system better.  Here they are, in no paticular order:&lt;/p&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;b&gt;No person&#039;s vote should go uncounted.&lt;/b&gt;  Why should we continue to work with a system that was invented for a nation of ignorant illiterates.  I don&#039;t want some &quot;electoral college&quot; voting for me.  I want my vote counted.  The popular vote means absolutely nothing when you get right down to it.  Somebody has to agree with me on that one.&lt;/li&gt;

	&lt;li&gt;&lt;b&gt;More voting booths&lt;/b&gt;  Wouldn&#039;t too many voting booths be better than too few?  &lt;i&gt;Honestly&lt;/i&gt;.  I would even forgoe my sticker, if it means that I don&#039;t have to wait for two hours.&lt;/li&gt;

	&lt;li&gt;&lt;b&gt;We need another party&lt;/b&gt;  Simple as that.  We need another party.  I am sick of the Republocrats running everything.  Somebody needs to step up.  Libertarians?  Greens?  Hell, even the Communist party would be a refreshing change of pace.&lt;/li&gt;

	&lt;li&gt;&lt;b&gt;The parties that exhist need better candidates&lt;/b&gt;  Well, that&#039;s probably not going to happen, but I think that the Democrats could have done better than Kerry.  The Republicans could probably have done better than Bush, too.  When your candidate can&#039;t even explain his point clearly, you have a problem.  When your candidate can&#039;t even express a thought clearly, you have a problem also.  Try somebody else.  Al Sharpton?  I wish.&lt;/li&gt;

	&lt;li&gt;&lt;b&gt;Have more faith in the system&lt;/b&gt;  At the very least, have faith in the system.  My problem is that I was told that they didn&#039;t expect many voters, so they didn&#039;t plan for a large croud.  &quot;We didn&#039;t think that we would have many voters.&quot;  Not with that attitude, you won&#039;t!&lt;/li&gt;

	&lt;li&gt;&lt;b&gt;A new voting system&lt;/b&gt;  When &lt;i&gt;America&#039;s Idol&lt;/i&gt; gets ten times more voters than the Presidential election, that&#039;s a problem.  I know, I know.  &lt;i&gt;America&#039;s Idol&lt;/i&gt; is very different than the Presidential election, but we could still learn from it.  How about a show where all of the presidential candidates (all of them.  Dean, Kerry, Al Sharpton, Bush, Nader, everyone) live together in a house, and every week the American people vote one off until only one remains?  I would tune in to see that.  It could be on Fox!  Imagine the possibilities!  It would be better than &quot;Amish in the City&quot; at least.&lt;/li&gt;

	&lt;li&gt;&lt;b&gt;No multible terms&lt;/b&gt;  How can Bush be allowed to spend half of his term campaining for the next one?  If Presidents are allowed only one term at a time, they would get a lot more work done, and be much more willing to give a crap.  Maybe.&lt;/li&gt;

	&lt;p&gt;All I know is that the Government ows me &lt;b&gt;2 hours&lt;/b&gt;.  I don&#039;t know how I want them paid back to me yet, but I will think of something.  Also, that internship that I was pondering at Relic entertainment (in Canada) is look more inviting every day. Both people I have told that to asked me the same smart-assed question:  &quot;So you don&#039;t care about the high taxes?&quot;  No.  I don&#039;t, thank you.  If if means that I can go about my life without &lt;b title=&quot;It exists.  Face it&quot;&gt;Big Brother&lt;/b&gt; looking over my shoulder, then no I don&#039;t mind the taxes.  Jesus.  Whatever.  I am not going to go on about the mess that this country is in (that&#039;s what the other web complaints are for), just the electoral system.&lt;/p&gt;


	&lt;p&gt;There are probably more things to add to that list, but my rant is getting really long as it is, and I have homework to do.  I would love to hear some feedback on some of this, but since I have no audience, it may not happen too soon.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Things can change very quickly.  I&#039;m not really talking about anything in paticular, just &lt;b&gt;things&lt;/b&gt;.  Complicated things.  Like, for example, when you are being chased by a &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/images/bear.jpg&quot; title=&quot;A scary bear&quot; class=&quot;black&quot;&gt;bear&lt;/a&gt;.  A big bear, maybe a grizzly.  It just keeps chasing you &lt;b&gt;relentlessly&lt;/b&gt; knocking over everything in its path.  Whenever you think that you are away from the beast, it breaks through the &lt;b&gt;brush behind you&lt;/b&gt;, ready to maul you completely.  You &lt;b&gt;run and you run&lt;/b&gt;, trying to escape the bear.  You didn&#039;t do anything to it; it found you.  &lt;b&gt;Okay&lt;/b&gt;, so maybe you gave it a &lt;b&gt;steak&lt;/b&gt;, which has given it the taste for blood, and now it wants to try something a little more &lt;b&gt;gamey&lt;/b&gt;.  You cast off everything that might lure the bear.  The &lt;b&gt;beef jerky&lt;/b&gt; in your pocket that you were saving for later.  The &lt;b&gt;bottle of bear pharamones&lt;/b&gt; that you used to lure the bear in the first place.  You even give up your &lt;b&gt;bear skin hat&lt;/b&gt;, thinking that perhaps the bear was wanting revenge.  You turn to face the bear, thinking that you might be able to &lt;b&gt;scare it away&lt;/b&gt;.  I just keeps lumbering down upon you, and your fear makes you run.  You get very tired.  You think that you can&#039;t go on any more, and the bear will surely &lt;b&gt;catch you and maul you&lt;/b&gt; at any moment.  You just want to be rid of the bear forever; you just want to have &lt;b&gt;peace&lt;/b&gt;.  With your last ounce of strength, you &lt;b&gt;climb a tree&lt;/b&gt;.  You pull yourself up into the tree with all of your might.  The stray branches cut your skin, and the action strains your muscles, but you keep climbing without caring about the pain.  Finally, you think you are &lt;b&gt;safe&lt;/b&gt;.  You relax, and then you look down.  The bear begins to climb the tree after you.  There is &lt;b&gt;no escape&lt;/b&gt; now.  You jump down, climb out of the tree, and await your &lt;b&gt;doom&lt;/b&gt;.  The bear looks into your eyes, you feel its breath against your face.  It reaches up its paw and leaps at you.  With a great force, you fall to the ground, the bear on top of you.  &lt;i&gt;This is it&lt;/i&gt;, you think.  The bear has you.  You hope it kills you quickly.  The bear&#039;s head gets closer.  It opens its mouth.  &lt;b&gt;It licks your face&lt;/b&gt;.  It just wanted to &lt;b&gt;thank you&lt;/b&gt;.  You now have a &lt;b&gt;new friend&lt;/b&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;See?  Things can change very quickly.  First you think that the bear is going to kill you, but then it turns out to be your friend after all.  &lt;b&gt;Metaphor&lt;/b&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I feel really Taoist right now.  I think I will change my &lt;b title=&quot;at the top of the page&quot;&gt;quote&lt;/b&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;And &lt;b&gt;another&lt;/b&gt; thing:&lt;/p&gt;

				&lt;p&gt;I think that I got my &lt;b&gt;housing situation&lt;/b&gt; planned out for next year.  I will be living in one of the larger rooms here at &lt;b&gt;Meredith Hall&lt;/b&gt;.  They are pretty nice: &lt;b&gt;p&lt;/b&gt;r&lt;b&gt;i&lt;/b&gt;vate bathroom, a comfortable a&lt;b&gt;m&lt;/b&gt;mount of space, high s&lt;b&gt;p&lt;/b&gt;eed internet, everything a guy like me &lt;b title=&quot;Excepting, of course, a girlfriend.&quot;&gt;needs&lt;/b&gt;.  I hope to room with my current next door neibor, &lt;b&gt;Barry Schatz&lt;/b&gt;.  Or maybe &lt;b title=&quot;Boldface Type!!!!&quot;&gt;Chris Fancher&lt;/b&gt; (he&#039;s looking over my shoulder right now).  He always jingles his keys from a lanyard, which is getting a little tattered.  &lt;b&gt;Anyway&lt;/b&gt;, I think that it will be pretty good for &lt;b title=&quot;My current roomate and best friend of 4 years&quot;&gt;Scott&lt;/b&gt; and I to take a break from constantly &lt;b&gt;seeing&lt;/b&gt; each other.  We really &lt;b&gt;catalyze&lt;/b&gt; many of each other&#039;s problems.  Don&#039;t get me wrong, he&#039;s &lt;b&gt;awesome&lt;/b&gt;, and I &lt;b&gt;love&lt;/b&gt; him, but we have our &lt;b&gt;flaws&lt;/b&gt;, just like every relationship in the &lt;b title=&quot;Even Protons and Neutrons have their disagreements&quot;&gt;universe&lt;/b&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I have spent the entire weekend working on my &lt;b&gt;second web project&lt;/b&gt; for &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.tech.purdue.edu/cgt/courses/cgt141/&quot; title=&quot;Check it out&quot; class=&quot;black&quot;&gt;CGT 141&lt;/a&gt;.  This web site is about &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.tron-sector.com&quot; title=&quot;Tron: the nerdiest movie ever made&quot; class=&quot;black&quot;&gt;&lt;i&gt;Tron&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/a&gt;, and it will &lt;b&gt;probably never see the light of day&lt;/b&gt;.  It&#039;s okay, nobody cares about &lt;i&gt;Tron&lt;/i&gt;.  You can check my &lt;a href=&quot;../portfolio.htm&quot; class=&quot;black&quot;&gt;projects&lt;/a&gt; page if you really &lt;b title=&quot;jees! give it a rest!&quot;&gt;care that much&lt;/b&gt;.  I may put it up locally, but only if I get &lt;b title=&quot;Only 1 email per household, please!&quot;&gt;at least 20 e-mails&lt;/b&gt; from fans recommending that I do so.  Ha.  Take that.&lt;/p&gt;

				&lt;p&gt;I &lt;b&gt;love&lt;/b&gt; the movie &lt;i&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0338013/&quot; title=&quot;IMDB. What does that stand for?&quot; class=&quot;black&quot;&gt;Eternal Sunshine of the Spotless Mind&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/i&gt;.  It&#039;s great how it doesn&#039;t just show relationships as perfect.  &lt;b title=&quot;Relationships.&quot;&gt;They&lt;/b&gt;, like everything else in the universe, have flaws.  &lt;b title=&quot;Eternal Sunshine of the Spotless Mind&quot;&gt;It&#039;s&lt;/b&gt; not just a perfect love story.  The music is great, too.  I - um - &lt;i title=&quot;downloaded&quot;&gt;bought&lt;/i&gt; the soundtrack, and it makes me cry every time.  I can&#039;t listen to it; it&#039;s too much.  No, I actually just &lt;b title=&quot;yeah, a tear&quot;&gt;had something in my eye&lt;/b&gt;.  Yeah, that&#039;s it.  right.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;blockquote&gt;
						&lt;b&gt;CLEMENTINE&lt;/b&gt;:  I wish you&#039;d stayed.
						&lt;br /&gt;&lt;b&gt;JOEL&lt;/b&gt;:  Me too. I wish I had done a lot of things.  I wish I&#039;d. . . I wish I&#039;d stayed.
&lt;/blockquote&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I wish I&#039;d stayed, too.  &lt;b title=&quot;That bear was a really good friend&quot;&gt;I&#039;m sorry.&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

			&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;You know what sucks?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Crashing on your bike.  Landing on your face, and your hand.  Your writing hand.  On concrete.  Wearing a heavy backpack (which does crash into the back of your head).  Yeah.  That sucks big time.  I am wincing as I type this, because I have lost some skin on my left hand, and I will soon have a massive bruise on my elbow.  I broke my front reflector on my bike, scraped up the front of my handlebars, and almost broke my watch.  Yeah, that sucks.  I have a freaking scratch on my chin.  I can only hope that people think that it&#039;s acne.  Yeah, that sucks.  Damn curb.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Oh, well.  I am still alive, and no bones are broken (I think).  I get to play &lt;i title=&quot;7h47 9375 4// u83r //007, h4x0r5!!&quot;&gt;Half Life 2&lt;/i&gt; tonight, so everything should turn out okay.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;When it happened, I just wanted to lay there for a while.  Let my head stop swimming.  Let the pain catch up to me.  It turns out that you can&#039;t do that when you fall down.  If you don&#039;t get immediately up and ride off, people think you&#039;re dead.  That might end up being a problem.  Therefore, it&#039;s best to just hop back on that bike, and ride off.  As I rode off, I thought about that Neosporin commercial (the one where the kid crashes on her bike, and her mother gives her some neosporin).  That kid had a big cut on her chin (much bigger than mine, so it could be worse).  It really made me think about neosporin commercials, though.  They always show comparisons of cuts with neosporin and without, and they are identical cuts.  How the hell do they do that?  Do they pay people to get scarred for life, or is it makeup?  I don&#039;t know which is worse.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p title=&quot;I was probably just thinking about that just to keep from thinking about how painfully embarrassed I was&quot;&gt;Just makes you think. . .&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I&#039;m back from the craziest Thanksgiving week ever &lt;sup&gt;TM&lt;/sup&gt;, and I am ready for the last three weeks of school.  Right now I am watching &lt;i&gt;Back to the Future&lt;/i&gt;, which is a great movie.  My family and I watched the whole trilogy in the days before I came to school, and I am getting ready to finish the semester.  It makes me wish that I was back home.  And just this morning I was with my parents at home, wanting to get back to my computer.&lt;/p&gt;

				&lt;p&gt;I really promise to give the whole scoop about the week, and I will deliver on that promise.  Just give me a little time.&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Okay, so Thanksgiving was great.  Here&#039;s the scoop:&lt;/p&gt;

				&lt;p&gt;Check out the rest of my site, too, because I made a bunch of little tweaks, changes, and I have hidden lots of &lt;b title=&quot;Try the notch of of my &#039;initial G&#039;&quot;&gt;cool suprises&lt;/b&gt;.
			&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;I remember the drawn out Thanksgiving hype that I was forced to engage in in elementary school.  I remember the story (probably mostly untrue) about the &quot;Pilgrims&quot; having a feast &lt;b title=&quot;on&quot;&gt;with&lt;/b&gt; the &quot;Indians&quot;.  I remember the story of the &lt;i&gt;Mayflower&lt;/i&gt; and her uneventful voyage to &lt;b title=&quot;Freedom to prosecute whoever you wanted, maybe&quot;&gt;religious freedom&lt;/b&gt;.  The weird thing about this Thanksgiving is that I live on a college campus, and I live here with several &lt;b title=&quot;Asian&quot;&gt;foreign&lt;/b&gt; students.  I think that most Americans take for granted the fact that we are the only group who celebrates the holiday.  One of my foreign friends asked me what Thanksgiving was all about.  It made me think about kindergarten.  I was suprised that I was telling someone the story, instead of someone telling it to me.  Yet a vast majority of humans don&#039;t even know it exists.&lt;/p&gt;

	&lt;p&gt;Then I went home&lt;/p&gt;

	&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;THE DOG&lt;/b&gt; My parents got this new dog.  It&#039;s a mix between a rotweiler and a groundhog.  No, actually it&#039;s rotweiler/german shepherd, but it does look like a groundhog.  It likes to chew.  It especially likes to chew on people.  Hopefully it will get past that and realize that it really hurts when a dog chews on you.  His name is Theadore Edward Bear, or &lt;b&gt;Ted E. Bear&lt;/b&gt; for short.  Or Tedward, for really short.&lt;/p&gt;

	&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;THE FAMILY&lt;/b&gt; The &lt;b title=&quot;My Mom, My Dad, My sister, and I&quot;&gt;four&lt;/b&gt; of us went up to Lafayette for thanksgiving day.  My mom&#039;s mom lives there, so we weren&#039;t just going to Purdue for thanksgiving.  We ate at this huge Thanksgiving banquet that some place has every year.  It was really good food, and I wish that I could have eaten more, but I have just had less and less appetite lately.  It really made me mad that I wasn&#039;t able to eat as much as I wanted.  Oh well, that&#039;s a different story.  After we left Grandma&#039;s house at about 4 PM, we headed to my Dad&#039;s brother&#039;s house for the other half of Thanksgiving.&lt;/p&gt;

	&lt;p&gt;On the way there, we almost got in a huge crash with a car that was running a stoplight (we had a green light).  They looked at us like they were extremely mad at us, and when we drove around them, they turned across several lanes of traffic and started tailing us!  They were about six inches from our back bumper, and if it wasn&#039;t for my father&#039;s excellent action movie quality driving skills, they would have probably pulled out various assault rifles and shot us to pieces.  It was a very weird experience for a Thanksgiving evening.&lt;/p&gt;

	&lt;p&gt;We finally got to Uncle Dan&#039;s house, and everyone had already finished eating.  We were really late because we were at my other Grandma&#039;s house all day.  My uncle flew in from California, and my other uncle drove in from Denver, so everyone was there.  All seven siblings of the McGill family, their spouses, and children.  It was a wild several hours.  I talked to some of my relatives, but unfortunaltely I wasn&#039;t able to really talk to most of them.  The space was limited, and so are my slowly-developing social skills right now.  Most of the time was spent playing wild and crazy games of improvosation with all of my cousins (there are many).  It was a lot of fun.  I hadn&#039;t seen my cousins from California in about six years, and I hardly recognized them; I also hadn&#039;t seen my cousins from Denver in a while.  I went to Denver a couple summers ago, and I had a great time with Sean and Lake, my cousins.  It was great just goofing around with everyone.&lt;/p&gt;

	&lt;p&gt;A couple days earlier, I was watching &lt;i&gt;Oprah&lt;/i&gt; and Jim Carrey was on.  He is one of my idols, and for a while I wanted to be just like him when I grow up.  I find it so amazing that he can do funny things just non-stop.  As I watched the show, I wished that I could be that funny all the time.  While we were goofing around at Dan&#039;s house, I realized that I was that funny with them.  To my cousins (who are all younger than me by quite a bit), I &lt;i&gt;am&lt;/i&gt; Jim Carrey.  Whenever I feel bummed out, like nobody likes me, all I have to do is remember that with that group of people, I am a celebrity.  From all of my cousins looking up to me (well, they literally do, I am 6&#039;8&quot; after all), to all of my uncles and aunts interrested in my computer animation work, I feel so wanted.  Everybody needs something like that.  I can&#039;t wait till Christmas so I can see all of them again.&lt;/p&gt;

	&lt;p&gt;People were at our house from Wednesday night, all the way to Saturday night.  It was nonstop action.  It was one of the greatest weekends ever.&lt;/p&gt;

	&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;THE INCREDIBLES&lt;/b&gt; I also got a chance to watch &lt;i&gt;The Incredibles&lt;/i&gt;, the new movie from Pixar.  As somebody who does computer animation, paticularly skeletal character animation, I can tell you that it is the most amazing movie ever made.  Pixar was able to capture every nuance, every little detail about each character.  The animation was the greatest piece of work that I have ever seen.  The graphical detail was also superb.  The hair was amazing, the shadows an lighting was perfect, the models were spot-on, the voice acting was excellent, etc. etc.  It really is quite Incredible.  Now my parents are going to drag me to the Polar Express, which looks stupid.  It just looks like the creators wanted to show how cool computer graphics are.  In every clip I have seen about that movie, somebody&#039;s doing a backflip.  They need a decent story before they can create a good movie.  &lt;b title=&quot;too much motion capture&quot;&gt;Plus they cheated&lt;/b&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

	&lt;p&gt;All of my relatives watched the movie with me, and after it was over, they started asking me all sorts of questions about how it was done.  Being a freshman in Computer Graphics I didn&#039;t really know, but I was able to make up enough stuff that sounded right!  I also want to mention that every time the HP commercial comes on where the guy has picture frames and they magically have pictures of him in them, my relatives ask me how they did that.  I think I know, but I can&#039;t really explain it too well.  It gets a litle annoying after a while.&lt;/p&gt;

	&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;THE RETURN&lt;/b&gt;When I finally got back to school, I wished that I could just stay home, where every one loves me, and I have a great time all the time.  The problem is that life isn&#039;t always like that.  Usually, life consists of being made fun of and always trying way too hard to keep your dignity.  For me anyway.  I constantly have to have an argument like &quot;No, the GeForce 6800 isn&#039;t as good as the x800 XT!&quot; or &quot;yeah, that nForce 4 is going to rock&quot; or whatever.  Everything is a posturing battle of pontification.  Maybe the problem is that I don&#039;t really have any friends outside the dorm, or maybe the problem is that I don&#039;t have a girlfriend.  I don&#039;t know.  I only have one week of classes left this semester, and I can&#039;t believe just how fast it&#039;s going.  This really is one of the greatest times of my life, and it&#039;s blazing at breakneck speed.  It&#039;s weird that we never do anything on weekends.  For example, this weekend I am really looking forward to reformatting my computer, and reinstalling windows with a secondary boot of Gentoo Linux.&lt;/p&gt;

	&lt;p&gt;I need a girlfriend.&lt;/p&gt;

