data.text:
&lt;p&gt;Update: Star Wars Celebration 3&lt;p&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;Click here&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;Yeah, ok, so that promise of an update every day was pretty dumb.  I got back really late Friday night, and I knew at that point that I wouldn&#039;t be able to post anything else all weekend.  So I&#039;ll talk about the whole thing right now!&lt;/p&gt;

			&lt;p&gt;In the last four days, I&#039;ve seen every single variation of &quot;trooper&quot; imaginable.  Stormtroopers, Scout troopers, Clonetroopers, Commando Troopers, Imperial Guard troopers, Snow troopers, Imperial Pilots, Imperial Officers, FAT stormtroopers, FAT pilots, the Elvis stormtrooper (yes), the construction worker stormtrooper, Rebel troopers, rebel pilots, etc, etc, etc.  It&#039;s the fat ones that crack me up.  Sombody dropped a little ice cream in their clone vats, I guess.  I saw a couple Darth Vaders.  I saw a couple Hans, Lukes, Leias, Chewies, Landos, Ewoks, Yodas, even a couple &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.starwars.com/databank/character/generalgrievous/&quot; title=&quot;Check him out&quot;&gt;General Grievouses&lt;/a&gt;.  A bunch of people dressed up for this thing.  My sister got a picture of a table near the food court.  Sitting at the table were two Han Solos, Two Luke Skywalkers, a Leia in a gold bikini, and a Wookie with his head sitting on the table.  I will try to get the picture up here in the coming days.&lt;/p&gt;

			&lt;p&gt;At least 100,000 people were there over the 4 day event.  You honestly could not go anywhere where you would be more than 2 feet from someone else.  Lines stretched around the building.  The wait for the celebration store (where you could purchase the special Celebration 3 Darth Vader action figure, plus a bunch of clothes) was 7 hours long at one point.  To see any of the shows or talks, you had to get in line at least a half an hour before the thing started, and walk for a while to find where the line ends.&lt;/p&gt;

			&lt;p&gt;The different talks were pretty awesome.  On Friday, &lt;b title=&quot;My Mom and Dad, My Sister, and Myself&quot;&gt;we&lt;/b&gt; saw Ray Park (Darth Maul), and he wowed us with his martial arts.  Later on Friday, we went to the &quot;Rick McCallum Spectacular&quot; which was spectacular (hold on a sec).  Then on Saturday, we just made it to see George Lucas himself.  It was one of the coolest moments of my life, because Master Lucas is something of an Idol to me.  I could go on and on about how great he is, but that&#039;s another story.  George explained why the prequels are so different from the originals, and he talked about his plans for a live action Star Wars television show.  Seeing him made the whole thing worth it, for me anyway.  Later in the day, after we watched the &quot;spectacular&quot; again, we saw Warwick Davis (Wickett the Ewok, various other small characters).  Warwick was totally awesome, and he had a lot of great stories about his carreer, and indeed his resume is nothing to scoff at.  Later in the night, my Sister and I saw John Knoll&#039;s presentation on the special effects of the whole series.  It was a really interesting presentation.  On Sunday, we saw Peter Mayhew (Chewbacca) and he is 7&#039;4&quot; which is really cool for me.  I don&#039;t usually get to see people that are taller than I am.&lt;/p&gt;

			&lt;p&gt;Now then, about that Rick McCallum Spectacular.  It was a 10 minute reel of clips from Episode 3, with another 10 minute reel of ILM special effect breakdowns from the movie.  The first video is without a doubt the coolest thing I have ever seen in my entire life.  The special effects look absolutely outstanding.  I cannot wait to see this movie.  I still have the wonderful music from the video stuck in my head.  It was just something they dug up to put on it, but it really worked well.  After the 10 minute clip, they showed a clip with a bunch of ILM special effects from the movie.  It was pretty cool, too.&lt;/p&gt;

			&lt;p&gt;I could go on and on, but I&#039;ll stop here.&lt;/p&gt;

			&lt;p&gt;I&#039;m going to start a countdown to the movie, so that I can tell how long I have to wait.&lt;/p&gt;

