Chapter 1, Part 1
			&lt;p&gt;Read&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;A tear landed on the cold metal floor.  The floor shook with the force of the shuttle&#039;s engines.  Transport Lieutenant Mark Soren paced from the fore of the passenger compartment to the rear.  His uniform boots were loudly knocking against the metal floor panels as he walked.  His hands were wrapped behind his back, his back was straight, his strides even.  In the front of the shuttle, the &quot;In Transit&quot; light was on, accompanied by the constant warning beep which is standard for the fleet&#039;s transport craft.  In nearby seats, some petty officers were loudly debating football scores.  Outside Shuttle 15-23, the SDS &lt;i&gt;Vigor&lt;/i&gt; slowly drifted along, awaiting her shuttle back.  Behind the cruiser, Morsus was slowly rotating about Beta Centauri.  Behind Beta Centauri hovered an infinite universe of infinite discoveries.  A tear slid down my cheek and landed on the cold metal floor.  It was the only sound I heard.  It was the only thing I saw.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I am Lieutenant Tristan Marcus, command Lieutenant for the Solan Defense Fleet.  I graduated with honors from the SDF academy on Earth.  My first position was as an Ensign on a small frigate.  I was one of 8 officers on the ship.  Earth apparently decided that my paticular talents would be best suited on a larger, more active ship, so I was transferred to the &lt;i&gt;Vigor&lt;/i&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;As the shuttle carying Leutenant Soren and I left the point defence perimeter of the &lt;i&gt;Vigor&lt;/i&gt;, the last 4 years were swirling around in my head.  As shuttle 15-23 set a course for the surface of planet Morsus, I thought about all of the things that I would be losing.   I was leaving the ship to be court-martialed.  I had to wait on Morsus for the next SDF ship that would be headed to Earth.  The Solan schedules listed no ship going from Morsus to Earth for at least 5 local days, so I was stuck there with nothing but my remorse.  I didn&#039;t mind leaving the fleet.  I wasn&#039;t afraid of having to deal with a dishonorable discharge.  I didn’t really care at all.  I had friends on that ship, though.  I felt like I had a family on that ship.  I made the terrible mistake of falling in love with a lieutenant named Carys Patrick.  A court-martial meant that I would never see her - or any of my other friends in the fleet - ever again.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Morsus worried me, as well.  I had never met a Terran before, and I wasn’t excited to be one of the only humans on this planet.  At the time, I assumed that I deserved it.  I was being court-martialed after all.  I felt like I didn’t deserve to live.  I didn’t want to live.  Not without her.  I joined the academy so many years ago because I had nothing better to do with my life.  I don’t have any particularly useful skills, and there isn’t much that I enjoy doing.  As I watched Lieutenant Soren’s feet pass by me, I would have given anything to go back and live my life over again.  I wished that I had never joined the academy.  I had no idea what I had ahead of me.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The shuttle hit the Morsus atmosphere and I watched patterns of the ships shields dance around the window.  We still had 20 minutes before the shuttle would reach the garrison, so I closed my eyes.  I had a dream that I was stranded alone in the middle of a vast desert.  I walked and walked, but I got nowhere.  I was clutching something in my hand, but I couldn&#039;t tell what it was.  Then everything dissappeared and all I could see was Carys&#039;s face.  She looked sad.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Leutenant Soren woke me up when we landed.&lt;/p&gt;

