&lt;p&gt;Ok, the DSE needs to be stopped.  I don&amp;#039;t know what it is, but somebody really needs to start reading these emails.  I just got one with the following subject:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;DSE_Info:  Come to Speed Dating to Help St. Jude Children&amp;#039;s Research Hospital&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;What does that even mean?...&lt;/p&gt;

data.text:
&lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;The Matrix: The Path of Neo&lt;/i&gt; is one of the worst games I have ever played.  How in the world could someone have played that game and decided that it&#039;s ready to be released.  There are graphical glitches every 5 seconds (not even exaggerating), and animation glitches every single time you do &lt;i&gt;anything&lt;/i&gt;.  It brings several interesting points to mind.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I&#039;m starting a list.  Let this be not the definitive, but the ever adapting list of rules for game development.  They aren&#039;t mandatory or anything, it&#039;s just things you should do if you want to make a good game.  Go ahead and follow Shiny&#039;s plan of releasing whatever filth you come up with just to milk the cash cow.  However, if you don&#039;t want 50 million suicides on your hands, you might want to think about making a &lt;i&gt;decent&lt;/i&gt; game.&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;Shauvon&amp;#039;s simple rules of game development.&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;table&gt;

&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td valign=top&gt;1.&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;Do not release a game with obvious bugs.&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Okay, if it occasionally crashes on certain video cards with a paticular driver, it&#039;s fine.  If some random side NPC has a weird animation bug, don&#039;t worry about it.  If you&#039;re way over budget already, just relase it.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If all of your dynamic lights cause bizarre texture corruption, or every other animation screws up and ends up looking terrible, or characters often randomly disappear from the screen in the middle of a cutscene, or the graphics will completely and totally die (absolutely nothing works correctly) on certain systems when turned all the way up, or  the terrible hit collision system causes walls that the player hasn&#039;t touched to explode on the other side of a room, or the camera just decides to go through a wall and make everything impossible, or character models have various polygons sticking out of them, or LOD changes occur and random times right in front of the camera, or bullets shoot backwards when you point the gun at a certain angle, you should do something about it.  Any one of those glitches could ruin a perfectly good game.  &lt;i&gt;Path of Neo&lt;/i&gt; happens to exibit all of them, and many more.  They all happen frequently enough to make it obvious in the first several minutes of play, too.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;For the love of God, just play through the game ONCE before you release it.  This is what Beta testing is for.  Patches are fine, but a game shouldn&#039;t have this many problems when it comes out.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I had to laugh at one point in &lt;i&gt;Path of Neo&lt;/i&gt;.  After failing a jumping puzzle for the 10th time, Neo reappears at the beginning and says &quot;This is getting old.&quot;  &lt;i&gt;No kiding.&lt;/i&gt;  They even aknowlege that the game has problems, but they aren&#039;t willing to address them.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;

&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td valign=top&gt;2.&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;Extra useless levels need to be removed.&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;You may think that you are doing gamers a favor by including more levels, but really you&#039;re destroying a good game.  For example, after defeating agent Smith in the subway station (an infuriating and stupid battle, by the way), Neo gets stuck in a different subway station which has been corrupted by bad code.  He has to jump around a badly modeled train car and hit the brake to get out of an infinite loop.  Then he goes and fights Smith again in another station.  How was that important to the story?  It wasn&#039;t in the movie.  If they did write or even shoot the scene, they cut it out because it would have ruined the movie.  Why can&#039;t developers go through a game and cut out scenes and levels that aren&#039;t important?  Movie makers have been doing it for years now.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Side quests are perfectly acceptable, but not for a first person shooter.  Bonus missions are great, but make them bonus missions instead of forcing the player to wade through piles of crap just to get back with the storyline.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I would rather play a short game than a shit game.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;

&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td valign=top&gt;3.&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;If you are going to make some gimic a key element of the game, make it something that the Player ejoys having.&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;Max Payne&lt;/i&gt; has bullet time.  &lt;i&gt;Aliens vs. Predator&lt;/i&gt; has the ability to be the Alien.  &lt;i&gt;Dead to Rights&lt;/i&gt; has bullet time.  &lt;i&gt;Messiah&lt;/i&gt; has taking over people&#039;s bodies.  &lt;i&gt;Enter the Matrix&lt;/i&gt; has bullet time.  &lt;i&gt;Brother&#039;s in Arms&lt;/i&gt; has the ability to order your squad around.  &lt;i&gt;FEAR&lt;/i&gt; has bullet time.  &lt;i&gt;Half Life 2&lt;/i&gt; has the gravity gun.  &lt;i&gt;The Path of Neo&lt;/i&gt; has bullet time.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Bullet time is almost a new genre, it&#039;s used so much.  This rule should just be &quot;If you are going to use bullet time in a game, play &lt;i&gt;Max Payne&lt;/i&gt; first.&quot;  For some reason, the original &lt;i&gt;Max Payne&lt;/i&gt; is still the only game to do it well.  The only exception to that is &lt;i&gt;FEAR&lt;/i&gt; which is one of the most amazing games ever made.  In &lt;i&gt;Path of Neo&lt;/i&gt;, the &quot;focus&quot; button feels more like the &quot;make everything impossible to control and see&quot; button.  Gun combat in &lt;i&gt;PoN&lt;/i&gt; is the single worst thing I have ever had the misfortune to experience.  The only game that even comes close is &lt;i&gt;Enter the Matrix&lt;/i&gt;.  When you try to dive in any direction in &lt;i&gt;PoN&lt;/i&gt;, Neo flys twenty feet in the air, making it impossible to hit anything.  It shouldn&#039;t be so hard to do what &lt;i&gt;Max Payne&lt;/i&gt; did so brilliantly.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Please, if you are going to use a gimic in a game, make it a blessing like &lt;i&gt;Half Life 2&lt;/i&gt;&#039;s Gravity Gun, not an eye-gouging annoyance like &lt;i&gt;PoN&lt;/i&gt;&#039;s &quot;focus.&quot;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;

&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td valign=top&gt;4.&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;Just because you use DirectX 9, it doesn&#039;t mean you need to layer on every vertex and pixel effect possible.&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Just 5 minutes with &lt;i&gt;Path of Neo&lt;/i&gt; and you&#039;ll start to hate bump mapping.  You&#039;ll hate it almost as much as ID software loves it.  They bump map everything, just because they can.  The difference is that ID uses normal maps to improve the detail in their levels (&lt;i&gt;Doom 3&lt;/i&gt;, &lt;i&gt;Quake 4&lt;/i&gt;), whereas in &lt;i&gt;PoN&lt;/i&gt;, they use bump mapping to make his suit look wrinkly, but it just ends up looking like Neo has been severely stabbed repeatedly in random places.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;Anachronox&lt;/i&gt; used the Quake 2 engine, and it still manages to tell a story infinitely better than &lt;i&gt;Path of Neo&lt;/i&gt;, even without all of the vertex processing and pixel shaders.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Keep it simple, and it will stay entertaining.  Good graphics can do a lot to improve a game, but lousy graphics can do so much more to ruin it.  As soon as you see Neo&#039;s terrible suit, you are taken out of the game.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;

&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td valign=top&gt;5.&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;Don&#039;t shoot yourself in the foot by butchering your storyline.&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Peter Jackson can tell us all about butchering stories, but he isn&#039;t here.  Peter is a good example, though.  I don&#039;t think we will ever know just why he felt it necessary to completely rewrite the &lt;i&gt;Lord of the Rings&lt;/i&gt;, but it ruined the movies.  The Wachowski brothers (they made &lt;i&gt;The Matrix&lt;/i&gt;, and they&#039;re also famous for being really creepy and scary), did the same thing with &lt;i&gt;Path of Neo&lt;/i&gt;. They added stupid scenes, rearranged things, and changed important lines.  There is absolutely no reason for them to do any of that.  Playing the game, you can just see the Wachowskis wandering around the development studio, claiming to be &quot;gamers&quot; and telling the poor developers to put a bunch of stupid ideas into the game, like the end boss battle where Neo has to fight a giant agent Smith made of buildings.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Dear Wachowski brothers,&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If you sit around all day watching anime and playing Playstation, you aren&#039;t a gamer.  If you think jumping puzzles are important to throw into every game ever made, you aren&#039;t a gamer.  If you think that the Playstation is the best gaming platform on the planet, &lt;i&gt;you aren&#039;t a gamer.&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I would tell you to stick to making movies, but you have proven your inadequacies there, too.  Just crawl back into the hole you came from, and stop torturing people.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;

&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td valign=top&gt;6.&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;Games fail as movies, and movies fail as games.&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I would really love for someone to prove me wrong here, but the truth is you can&#039;t.  The point of games is that they give the player the ability to choose his fate.  Movies are a completely different form of entertainment.  I wish they would stop trying.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;It&#039;s worse knowing that the following games will become movies:  &lt;i&gt;Half Life, Dungeon Seige, Duke Nukem, American McGee&#039;s Alice, Splinter Cell, and Deus Ex.&lt;/i&gt;  Some of those have a chance of being good, but so did &lt;i&gt;Doom&lt;/i&gt;, for crying out loud.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;One more thing, I&#039;m sick of these stupid movie games that just let you play every battle in the game.  &lt;i&gt;Star Wars: Revenge of the Sith&lt;/i&gt;, and every &lt;i&gt;Lord of the Rings&lt;/i&gt; game, for example.  I&#039;m not playing another game like that again, not that I did to begin with.  &lt;i&gt;Enter the Matrix&lt;/i&gt; and &lt;i&gt;Path of Neo&lt;/i&gt; are pretty much the same thing, just with guns and &quot;make everything impossible to control and see&quot; buttons.  &lt;i&gt;Look, we can make a game look and feel just like a movie, except we&#039;ll throw in a bunch of extra levels that make no sense and don&#039;t contribute to the story at all.&lt;/i&gt;  Fine, now make an actual game.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;

&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td valign=top&gt;7.&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;Improve your voice acting.&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Movies suck when they have bad actors in them, even if they are written and directed well.  Look at any Keanu Reeves movie.  Why would games be immune to bad acting?&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If people are just going to skip every cut scene to avoid the terrible voice work, just leave them out all together.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The annoying thing is that the voice actor&#039;s union is fighting to get more money.  They must not be able to get payed much because they have such a hard time expressing their wishes.  They must have a hard time expressing anything, for that matter.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;It&#039;s also depressing to see bad screen actors turning into bad voice actors.  Keanu Reeves makes &lt;i&gt;Path of Neo&lt;/i&gt; worse and worse every time he opens his unarticulated and semi-retarded mouth.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;

&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td valign=top&gt;8.&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;Leave big decisions up to the Player.&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;It&#039;s what computer games are all about.  Games have far bigger emotional impact than movies because the Player is actually involved in the decisions.  Games today feel more like &lt;i&gt;Pac Man&lt;/i&gt;, just weaving through tight corridors with only two ways to go, forward and backward.  We need more &lt;i&gt;Deus Ex&lt;/i&gt; and &lt;i&gt;Grand Theft Auto&lt;/i&gt;, and less &lt;i&gt;Medal of Honor&lt;/i&gt;.
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;

&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td valign=top&gt;9.&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;Bad controls + terrible gameplay = waste of time and money.&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&quot;IF NEO PUNCHES IN THE WRONG DIRECTION ONE MORE TIME I SWEAR TO GOD . . . &quot; is something that shouldn&#039;t have to be said during a game.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The gun combat in &lt;i&gt;PoN&lt;/i&gt; makes me want to shoot myself because the controls are so terrible.  Neo never shoots in the direction he is pointing, or in the direction the cursor is aiming.  You would think that he would shoot in one of those two directions.  The camera is in such an akward place, and the perspective is so bad that it just makes it worse.  I can never tell what&#039;s going on, so I just randomly hit buttons and move around until the combat is over.  When you get moves off on enemies, like jumping on them or whatever, it&#039;s only satisfying because you finally got the paticular combination of keys correct.  The only reason I haven&#039;t shot myself yet is because I&#039;m afraid that using a gun is actually like that.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;WASD + Mouse is a good standard.  Considering how often games come out that have half decent controls, it&#039;s so suprising that games still come out that are impossible to control.  Sticking to standards like that leads me to the last one. . .&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;

&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td valign=top&gt;10.&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;Develop standards, while avoiding standards.&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This is a tough one, but not really that tough if you play games on a semi regular basis.  Things like WASD and the general layout of the HUD is pretty standard now.  There is no reason why control response or the user interface are as terrible as they are in some games.  Standards can help you get past simple things, so that you can move on to develop the more important things, like the &quot;make everything impossible to control and see&quot; button.  There is no reason to reinvent the wheel.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;However, standards can really ruin a game.  &lt;i&gt;Quake 4&lt;/i&gt; was so extremely boring because I&#039;ve played that game hundreds of times already.  Certain standards like &quot;enter room, spawn enemies, destroy enemies, give health / ammo, repeat&quot; need to end.  When games like &lt;i&gt;The Sims&lt;/i&gt; or &lt;i&gt;Black and White&lt;/i&gt; come out that completely redefine everything, they are applauded and succeed.  That sort of innovation needs to continue.  I&#039;m all for denying conformity, after all.  But keep in mind that games like &lt;i&gt;Enter the Matrix&lt;/i&gt; and &lt;i&gt;Daikatana&lt;/i&gt; are hated because they refuse to follow the simple pattern that gamers are used to, like playability.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;It&#039;s a fine line, but it shouldn&#039;t be that hard for &lt;i&gt;computer science and math experts&lt;/i&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;

&lt;/table&gt;

&lt;p&gt;That&#039;s just what I think.  As always, I&#039;m open to your comments / additions / criticism.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;December 15&lt;sup&gt;th&lt;/sup&gt;, 0800 hours.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;T-Day.&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Three tests, one day, hours of studying.  So far things are going great.  I knew my CPT 267 test was going to be easy, but then I saw the first question, &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;font-family: courier new, monospace; display: block; width: 40%; margin-left: 20%&quot;&gt;1.) What is the value of &#039;x&#039; after the following code: &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt; x = 17 % 9
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt; A. 9
&lt;br /&gt; B. 1
&lt;br /&gt; C. 8
&lt;br /&gt; D. 10
 &lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I almost fell out of my chair.  It only got easier from there.  My favorite was:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;font-family: courier new, monospace; display: block; width: 40%; margin-left: 20%&quot;&gt;15.) What header file should you include to have access to the string class?
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt; A. &amp;#60;fstream&amp;#62;
&lt;br /&gt; B. &amp;#60;string&amp;#62;
&lt;br /&gt; C. &amp;#60;iostream&amp;#62;
&lt;br /&gt; D. &quot;math.h&quot;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;hmmmmmmmm, what could it be . . . . ?&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The only confusing thing about the test was when I realized that there were two #42&#039;s, one of several stupid mistakes on the test.  I love it when I could have taken my final a year ago and still gotten an A on it.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I&#039;m not looking forward to the other two tests today.  If another person tells me that I could have rescheduled them, I&#039;ll go insane.  I am completely aware that if you have more than 2 tests on a single day you can reschedule one of them.  I just didn&#039;t want to, because I don&#039;t really care.  I like being able to take care of all of my tests in a big chunk.  I&#039;ll be sure to post after The Economics and the Raster Imaging tests to let you all know how T-Day turned out.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;One bonus of having to get up so early for the stupid test:  being albe to blast my music at 9 in the morning and hoping that all of the morons in my hall are really annoyed by it.  It&#039;s revenge for everyone who was yelling and screaming last night when I was trying to sleep, or for everyone who was yelling and screaming while I was trying to study, or for everyone who was yelling and screaming while I was trying to sit here without people yelling and screaming.  There is far too much yelling and screaming in this hall.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;For anyone who didn&#039;t find those two questions quite as easy as I did, it&#039;s fine.  They are both just really easy programming questions.  The first one is dealing with modulus (%) which takes two numbers and returns the remainder after deviding them.  It&#039;s one of the simplest concepts in programming, and it basically means that a lot of the test was just simple elementary school math.  The second question is slightly more complicated, but it&#039;s still insanely easy.&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

