data.text:
&lt;p&gt;The show went really well.  I had fun, and I think everyone else did, too.  It really is a breathtaking spectacle, and everyone who can should see it.  After the show tonight there was this reception for everyone.  They had some cookies and punch out and everyone gathered to discuss the show.  The audience was mostly older people tonight, but there were some younger folks as well.  Richard Rand saw the show tonight, and he really enjoyed it.  Rich directed &lt;i&gt;Road&lt;/i&gt;, which I was in last semester, and he&#039;s an amazing director to work with.  I felt really akward, though.  For some reason I feel like I&#039;m in a different show than everyone else.  I sit backstage and watch the show through the closed-circuit television, and then I go on for a couple minutes to say my lines.  Of course the only things people said to me tonight were mentioning how tall I looked in my costume.  That&#039;s really my only function.  My sole purpose is to look impressive.  I don&#039;t have to act.  I just have to be tall.  I can&#039;t really say that I&#039;m not excited to be able to use my only strong physical characteristic.  To be honest, I have been training for this my entire life.  I just feel sepparated from the rest of the cast for some reason.  It must just be me, because I felt this way about &lt;i&gt;Road&lt;/i&gt;, too.  I do have fun, and I enjoy goofing around with everyone backstage.  I can&#039;t help but feel like the only reason I&#039;m there is because I am abnormally and freakishly tall, and they are exploiting the fact that people like to stare at me.  Other people talk about their lives, like what they&#039;ve done recently, or movies they like.  People only talk to me about how tall I am.  It&#039;s ok, though, beacause my life is pretty boring, so I wouldn&#039;t really have anything else to talk about anyway.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It&#039;s just really hard to describe how I am feeling.  Maybe I should write a movie about it.&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Tuesday evening, at 5:30 PM, the cast of &lt;i&gt;The Winter&#039;s Tale&lt;/i&gt; played the first official games for the Purdue Theatre Basketball League (PTBL).  We had 14 people show up, so we set up 3 teams.  Two of the teams had five people, and one had 4.  We commenced a four on four on four tournament.  I was on the four person team, with my Li&#039;l Chum and Stevie Chaddock.  We also had a guy who was a friend of one of the cast.  I don&#039;t know where this guy came from, but I sure was glad he was on our team.  Even though we had one less player than the rest of the teams, we still held our own.  The first game we played we lost, but then after recouperating and watching our two competitors play, we performed much better.  We beat both teams, and then beat the first one again for the hell of it.  We are therefore the ultimate PTBL champions.  It feels very good to be on top, even though many of my muscles don&#039;t.  The next game is next Tuesday at 5:30, so we&#039;ll have to defend our title then.  I don&#039;t think it will be very hard, considering we are champions.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Also, I made my first slam dunk on Tuesday, which is pretty exciting.  Ok, so it was more of a lay-up where I touched the rim, but it went in.  I&#039;ll keep working, and soon I&#039;ll be a slam dunk champion, too.  I sure have more dunks on my record than anyone else in the PTBL.  I&#039;m starting to see why people always wonder if I play basketball.  I am pretty awesome.&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;There are some pretty rediculous things going on right now.  Here&#039;s another one.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I found an idiot.  It&#039;s really not that hard to find an idiot around here, but I&#039;m pretty proud of this one.  He&#039;s a &lt;i&gt;really&lt;/i&gt; stupid one.  His name is Joey Marburger, and he is the assistant features editor for the Purdue &lt;i&gt;Exponent&lt;/i&gt;.  This man (boy) is one of the primary reasons why the Purdue student newspaper is knicknamed the &quot;Excrement&quot; by most of the students.  Here is Joey&#039;s column from Thursday, April 20&lt;sup&gt;th&lt;/sup&gt;, entitled&lt;/p&gt;

			&lt;p&gt;Excise proves freedom isn&amp;#039;t free&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;div style=&quot;width: 250px; margin: auto; font-family: times new roman; background-color: #cccccc; padding: 10px&quot;&gt;
&lt;b style=&quot;font-size: 40px&quot;&gt;Excise proves &#039;freedom isn&#039;t free&#039;&lt;/b&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I&#039;ve got a problem.  It runs in packs, costs hundreds of dollars and makes me sick.  Yes, I&#039;m talking about excise police.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;With the sexiest party day of the year upon us, these bounty hunters of the underage drinker will be out in full force to make sure you might not have a good time.  Now hold on, before this gets too intense, I must say that I respect local police and their efforts to provide security and make students safe.  But excise police just don&#039;t do it for me.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I guess you can get a rush out of busting parties to which you weren&#039;t invited, writing tickets ruining someone&#039;s social life for quite some time, and making personal money off another&#039;s misery.  But is the safety for underage drinkers really the issue?  What if all minors quit drinking and there weren&#039;t any tickets to hand out anymore?  Well, poop.  I suppose excise would be out of a job and the crap ton of money they, and the fine state of Indiana, make.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Really the issue is Indiana spends money on these guys to crawl around and bust kids while murderers and rapists roam the streets.  You know why?  Because busting hardcore criminals doesn&#039;t pay good money.  So please excise, if you care about people&#039;s safety, try being a real cop and make a difference.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Oh, if you get on the Indiana Excise Police Web site (&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.in.gov/atc/what.htm&quot;&gt;link&lt;/a&gt;) you might notice the third purpose in their mission statement is &quot;to provide for the raising of revenue.&quot;  That &quot;revenue&quot; might go to education, or something beneficial for the state, but I&#039;m sure a good bit of it goes right to excise officers&#039; pockets.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;And for those who wish to party this weekend just remember from the fine creators of &quot;Team America World Police,&quot; freedom isn&#039;t free.  It costs about $500 after court services.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;Joey Marburber is a junior in the College of Liberal Arts.  He believes he will be singled out for a P.I. this weekend due to this column.  He can be reached at features@purdueexponent.org.&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;p&gt;That is exactly how the article appeared in the Excrement.  I don&#039;t know if I should even say anything about the article.  It really speaks for itself.  Joey Marburger is an idiot.  I wish I could get the picture he has next to this, because it is another good argument for his idiocy.  He has one of those emo haircuts, with hair covering his right eye.  He has a black shirt and a red striped tie.  His right arm is stretched forward, his thumb akwardly jutting upward at a strange angle.  The picture looks like it was taken a half second early, that he was in the middle of smiling and giving us all a &quot;thumbs-up.&quot;  The picture looks like the camera man took it just a bit early, so poor Joey&#039;s smile hadn&#039;t really formed yet, and his thumb was stuck at that weird pergatory somewhere between the presidential thumb&#039;s up gesture and the thing a painter does to measure his subject.  The picture looks like it was captured at an akward time, but I bet Joey&#039;s just one of those people who always look like that.  His writing seems like it was taken just a bit too early, too, and if he had just let those thoughts develop a little bit more, he would have realized that it was such a terrible idea.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I suppose I should at least elaborate on some of the things he&#039;s talking about.  The &quot;sexiest party day of the year&quot; is referring to the fact that it is Grand Prix week, which is just a rediculous excuse for everyone on campus to be completely drunk all weekend.  Considering how much underaged drinking happens on a regular basis on campus, this week is most definitely a good time to bolster the police force.  As much as he hates the excise police, I can almost gaurantee that they won&#039;t to the job anywhere near well enough to curb the amount of alcohol abuse here.  Oh, and that link that he lists in his column (the link above is exactly what he listed) is not about excise police, it&#039;s just the Indiana State Alcohol and Tobacco Commision.  Providing for the raising of revenue is just talking about the fact that they give licenses to people to sell alcohol.  It has nothing to do with excise police at all.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Boy I hope he gets arrested this weekend.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Some day, this website will have a list of idiots who are drags on society and rediculous excuses for human beings.  John Deely and Joey Marburger will top that list.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;My sister, Aili (who readers of this site have met already) has made several proud accomplishments.  She recently accomplished one.  My sister is a homeowner.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;

&lt;table&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td rowspan=1 valign=center&gt;
&lt;p&gt;So here&#039;s the new house (new to her).  It obviously needs some work, but that&#039;s what she&#039;s looking for.  The transaction completed last week.  My mother and I arrived at about noon o&#039;clock today to help out with the early stages of fixing this place up.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;&lt;img src=../assets/images/ailihouse/house01.jpg /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;

&lt;td rowspan=2 valign=center&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Aili and her dog, Lucy had already arived.  Lucy was already bored, but was interested in mom&#039;s feet for a while.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;&lt;img src=../assets/images/ailihouse/house06.jpg /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td&gt;&lt;img src=../assets/images/ailihouse/house07.jpg /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;

&lt;td rowspan=1 valign=center&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Dad works just down the road from Aili&#039;s house, so he showed up to help out with the deadbolt.  I&#039;m not sure what Aili was talking about.  Aili said something about a task that she thought was important.  She was worried about the necessary equipment or materials that would be needed for said task.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;&lt;img src=../assets/images/ailihouse/house02.jpg /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;

&lt;td rowspan=1 valign=center&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Mom expressed her disagreement that said task was as necessary as Aili thought.  Mom then went on to convey her lack of faith in the entire project and her annoyance at something either Aili the dog or myself was doing.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;&lt;img src=../assets/images/ailihouse/house03.jpg /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;

&lt;td rowspan=1 valign=center&gt;
&lt;p&gt;My task was to put some nails into the ceiling.  I had to make sure that I looked cool while I did it, so I wore my sunglasses.  I eventually covered one of those holes full of  electrical danglies with a smoke detector.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;&lt;img src=../assets/images/ailihouse/ceiling01.jpg /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;

&lt;td rowspan=1 valign=center&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Then I put some nails into the floor.  The blood rushed to my head and I got a little loopy for a while after this.  At least I still looked cool.  It&#039;s annoying that the floor had some electrical danglies, too.  That&#039;s more smoke detectors than a room needs, in my opinion.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;&lt;img src=../assets/images/ailihouse/ceiling02.jpg /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;

&lt;td rowspan=1 valign=center&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Aili told me to get some pictures of the house.  I didn&#039;t feel like her paticular usage of the words &quot;goofball&quot; and &quot;weirdo&quot; was really necessary.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;&lt;img src=../assets/images/ailihouse/house08.jpg /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;

&lt;td rowspan=1 valign=center&gt;
&lt;p&gt;So, ok, here&#039;s the rest of the house.  Namely the stairs going up.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;&lt;img src=../assets/images/ailihouse/house09.jpg /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;

&lt;td rowspan=1 valign=center&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The upstairs bedroom.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;&lt;img src=../assets/images/ailihouse/house10.jpg /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;

&lt;td rowspan=1 valign=center&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The upstairs bathroom with flanking shower heads.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;&lt;img src=../assets/images/ailihouse/house11.jpg /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;

&lt;td rowspan=1 valign=center&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The unfinished upstairs back room.  Text reads: &quot;Temp Wall&quot;  &quot;Do not screw with&quot;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;&lt;img src=../assets/images/ailihouse/house12.jpg /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;

&lt;td rowspan=1 valign=center&gt;
&lt;p&gt;A closeup of the AC plug.  It is not plugged in, and as a result the outlet is asleep.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;&lt;img src=../assets/images/ailihouse/house13.jpg /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;

&lt;td rowspan=1 valign=center&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Here is a shot of the nice view from the rear window.  Speedway!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;&lt;img src=../assets/images/ailihouse/house14.jpg /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;

&lt;td rowspan=1 valign=center&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Here&#039;s the other room upstairs.  It&#039;s a nice little office.  There are a handful of network plugs under the desk there.  I know they&#039;re connected, because I tested them, but I can&#039;t for the life of me figure out where the hub is.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;&lt;img src=../assets/images/ailihouse/house15.jpg /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;

&lt;td rowspan=1 valign=center&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Going back downstairs.  Financial status should be based on how many turns are in your stairs.  Aili has two.  How many turns are in your stairs?&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;&lt;img src=../assets/images/ailihouse/house16.jpg /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;

&lt;td rowspan=1 valign=center&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The nice lady across the street noticed that the house needed a new tire.  This one was flat.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;&lt;img src=../assets/images/ailihouse/house17.jpg /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;

&lt;td rowspan=1 valign=center&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Lucy had some &#039;splaining to do.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;&lt;img src=../assets/images/ailihouse/house28.jpg /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;

&lt;td rowspan=2 valign=center&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Dad and I got to work.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;&lt;img src=../assets/images/ailihouse/house18.jpg /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td&gt;&lt;img src=../assets/images/ailihouse/house19.jpg /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;

&lt;td rowspan=1 valign=center&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Mom helped.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;&lt;img src=../assets/images/ailihouse/house20.jpg /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;

&lt;td rowspan=1 valign=center&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The jack needed to be positioned right under those little notches.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;&lt;img src=../assets/images/ailihouse/house21.jpg /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;

