data.text:
&lt;p&gt;I wish I could make an extended post mocking the lame news coverage of voting, but I don&#039;t have the time.  The 2006 Primaries were this past Tuesday, if some of you didn&#039;t notice.  I can understand if you weren&#039;t extremely excited about who your county commissioner, prosecutor, or sheriff is.  I&#039;m sure you&#039;re even less interested about who could possibly be running for those positions in the fall.  That&#039;s the really pointless thing about these primaries.  You&#039;re not voting for anything (with one exception, which I&#039;ll get to), you&#039;re just voting for who you want to vote for in November.  Plus, you have to pick a party and just vote for them, and in Hancock county (where I&#039;m from), only one party exists.  Hancock has voted Republican in every election since Lincoln.  That&#039;s a legacy we&#039;re not soon to give up.  As a result, you&#039;re stupid if you vote for any other party (I say that like it&#039;s a big choice, there&#039;s only one other party) in the primaries, because they will lose, without fail.  So, yes, I am sorry to say that I am currently classified as a Republican.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The one important thing (and the only reason I went home during finals), was the school board race.  People might remember my long post about Dr. Riggs and his crazy construction plan (&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/content/olds.php?post=00027&quot;&gt;go ahead and click anywhere between these parentheses to read that post&lt;/a&gt;).  His crazy construction plan was turned down by the public, thankfully, but we need people in the board to tell him that he&#039;s an idiot and stop him before he does anything else really stupid.  My mom was the campaign manager for a candidate who promises to do just that.  These two guys, David Bush and Shelton Oakes ran for school board with the local taxpayers in mind.  The board needed two new members.  Shelton Oakes was elected, but David Bush unfortunately came in third place.  A lady (the only woman running) got the first seat.  I will avoid getting into the politics of it all, but needless to say we&#039;re somewhat upset that Bush didn&#039;t get elected.  We&#039;re almost as upset as when that other Bush &lt;i&gt;was&lt;/i&gt; elected.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Anyway, I stood with my Mom outside one of the voting places to hand out buttons and tell everyone that David Bush and Shelton Oakes would appreciate their vote.  I believe that&#039;s called Electioneering.  In total, about 250 people showed up at the Fortville Boys and Girl&#039;s club to vote.  That&#039;s out of about 1200 registered voters who were supposed to go there, and that&#039;s about of about twice that many eligible adults in that part of Fortville.  That makes it about a 10% turn out.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I voted at my old high school (going back to that place was a very tramatic experience).  I was number 194, and I voted at about 1:30.  The poles were open at 6:00.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It just really gets me that so few people care.&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;Some pictures&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;table&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td rowspan=1 valign=center&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This sign sat outside the door of the Boy&#039;s and Girl&#039;s Club.  Fifty feet was judged to be about the doorway, so as long as we stayed outside the building we were fine.  It&#039;s crazy that it is a felony to electioneer.  Imagine being convicted, and never being able to vote again, just for the two or so people who were ever in the place at one time.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;&lt;img src=../assets/images/vote06/vote01.jpg /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;

&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td rowspan=1 valign=center&gt;
&lt;p&gt;They don&#039;t like &lt;i&gt;Electioneering&lt;/i&gt;.  &lt;i&gt;Subterranean Homesick Alien&lt;/i&gt;, and &lt;i&gt;Karma Police&lt;/i&gt; are fine.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;&lt;img src=../assets/images/vote06/vote02.jpg /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;

&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td rowspan=1 valign=center&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Budd Gray showed up and hung out for a while.  The guy on the phone and the guy with the sunglasses are a couple of cronies who showed up with him.  Budd is running for Sheriff.  The whole thing had a huge mafia vibe, with the two muscles following him around.  Budd got by far the most votes (because he had by far the most money, that&#039;s how democracy works), so he will be sheriff in the fall.  I say he will be sheriff, even though he&#039;s just the Republican candidate, because nobody is going to vote for the Democrat.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;&lt;img src=../assets/images/vote06/vote03.jpg /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;

&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td rowspan=1 valign=center&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The judge came out a couple times to make sure we were playing the right Radiohead songs.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;&lt;img src=../assets/images/vote06/votejudge.jpg /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;

&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td rowspan=1 valign=center&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Budd Gray is a pretty big guy.  He&#039;ll probably make a good sheriff, just because nobody is going to mess with him.  I&#039;m taller, though, so he&#039;s just a little guy to me.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;&lt;img src=../assets/images/vote06/buddgray.jpg /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;

&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td rowspan=1 valign=center&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&quot;David Bush and Shelton Oakes would appreciate your vote for School Board.&quot;  If Mom had said that one foot further, she could have been arrested.  If she had just gone inside wearing all of the &quot;Bush Oakes&quot; buttons that she had on, she could have been arrested.  Awesome.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;&lt;img src=../assets/images/vote06/electioneering.jpg /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;

&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td rowspan=1 valign=center&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This guy, Kim Dailey, is currently on the school board, and he was running for reelection.  He didn&#039;t win.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;&lt;img src=../assets/images/vote06/loser.jpg /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;

&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td rowspan=1 valign=center&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Here I am voting, right where they told me to.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;&lt;img src=../assets/images/vote06/votehere.jpg /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;

&lt;/table&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Peter Kremidas has written the first Deny Conformity guest column.  Here it is for your viewing pleasure.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This column was written by Peter Kremidas, and is his intellectual property.&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;Guest Column&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: center; font-weight: bold; font-size: 20px&quot;&gt;&lt;img src=../assets/images/guests/peter2.jpg /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
by Peter Kremidas&lt;/div&gt;	

&lt;p&gt;I have to write my thoughts down by hand, with a pen and paper. It slows me down, let’s the ideas form themselves and become concrete. I’m sitting in village coffee shop, about 4 hours before the second to last exam I will ever take. There is a ceiling fan right below a ceiling light, so the light is pulsing like kitten’s quickly beating heart on my paper. There is bad music in the background. It sounds like sad John Mayer. So it must be John Mayer, or Coldplay.&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;Conversations about people’s problems and upcoming tests appear and disappear at random, fading in and out with the ‘Ts’ and ‘Ss’ cutting the short silences with the most clarity. The words don’t even register in my mind. These are only sounds humans make; it’s best not to try and make sense of them.&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;The occasional clinking of silverware, turn of a paper, and other various clicks, movements, and sounds of friction come in and out and complete the message that there is life here.&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;All these people are just like me. We have our whole lives ahead of us, and we don’t even know it. We can’t know it. When I think about how much my current decisions really effect the rest of my life, my handwriting suddenly gets small and nervous, and I don’t want to do anything so that I can stay safe and mistake-less. It’s a pressure that nobody isn’t aware of, but everybody ignores. Maybe that explains the escapism. Maybe early twenty-somethings drink as much as they do in order to make that pressure go away. If not drink, we all have our own brand of escapism. Video games, TV, movies, the internet, art, masturbation on an epic scale, whatever dips your proverbial chip.&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;Imagine going through every day fully realizing just what the fuck you’re doing with your life here. It’s no wonder that we periodically act as if our actions had no consequences. After all, we’re on the edge here, right between childhood and adulthood. It’s no wonder that college is one part cerebral boot camp, and another part playground for big kids. Most of us just aren’t grown up enough yet to live in a world full of consequences.&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;I was…well, still am among those lacking the strength to completely accept the world as it is. And it’s high time I learned. My mode of escapism was the same as most people’s. I drank, I did drugs. But, unlike others, I picked another poison as well. I picked comedy. I was picked by the crazy monkeys. And now I’m graduating and it’s time to go on to what my dad calls “bigger and better things.”&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;Being as analytical as I am, I can’t help but think about this supposed “bigger and better” world. I think about it, and I have had by far the best times of my life here. I have laughed the hardest, loved the most, danced the hardest, accomplished the things I am most proud of, made my best friends, learned the most, and done it all more here than anywhere else. Ever.&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;But there was another side to this. My worst times happened here, too. There were many times when I didn’t think I would ever get better, that I would never be happy again. There were times I cried so hard that I left stains in cold pavement. I hurt more here than anywhere else, and I’ve got the scars to prove it. And by the way, if you think all that was over one woman, you’re giving her way too much credit.&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;And all through it all, I stood on a stage with some “Crazy Monkeys,” with all these life long friends that have come and gone through the years.&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;And we laughed.&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;We laughed no matter what.&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;And so, when my dad talks about things getting “bigger” and “better” for me, I think he’s right. I think things will get bigger for me. I really do. But I don’t think they’ll ever get any better than this.&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;Thanks so much, and goodbye.&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;I’d better get back to studying.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: right; font-weight: bold&quot;&gt;-Peter Kremidas, May 5th, 2006.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;Peter Kremidas is a graduating senior at Purdue University.  He is planning on pursuing a career in comedy and life.  I guess I shouldn&#039;t say that he&#039;s planning.  He isn&#039;t really planning on doing anything, and that&#039;s what makes him special.&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

