data.text:
&lt;p&gt;I recently spent some time in the Louisville area, working on my aunt&#039;s yard with my cousin, Pat.  I was really interested in the signs that populated the area.&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;Click here to see them.&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;div style=&quot;width: 640px; margin: auto&quot;&gt;

&lt;b class=&quot;center&quot;&gt;Street Signs&lt;/b&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/louisville_signs/hawley.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Here&#039;s a delightful little sign.  It was just down the street from my aunt&#039;s house.  An interesting thing about this area is that many of the signs are lacking the cross street, like this one.  If someone was driving along Hawley Gibson Road, and they came to this street, how do they know what it is called?  Well, the name of the street pictured here is actually...&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/louisville_signs/oldfloyds.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;p&gt;...Old Floydsburg Road, which is not to be confused with...&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/louisville_signs/floyd.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;p&gt;. . . Regular Floydsburg Road.  Floydsburg and Old Floydsburg actually intersect, but unfortunately there are no road signs at the intersection.  It really makes you wonder, though.  Which came first, Floydsburg or Old Floydsburg?  Did they make a street called Old Floydsburg before they made a street called Floydsburg?  Another interesting pair of streets are&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/louisville_signs/oldlagrange.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;p&gt;OLD LAGRANGE&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/louisville_signs/lagrange.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;p&gt;and Regular LaGrange road.  These two pictures are actually of the same intersection.  It goes in LaGrange, and comes out OLD LAGRANGE.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/louisville_signs/kavlane.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This is the street my aunt lives on.  Kavanaugh lane.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/louisville_signs/kavroad.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;p&gt;But just down the street is Kavanaugh road.  These two roads are completely unrelated and unconnected.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/louisville_signs/1447.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;p&gt;State Road 1447.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/louisville_signs/chamberlain.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Chamberlain Lane.  Seems a little redundant.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/louisville_signs/bypass.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I&#039;ll meet you at the corner of Old Floydsburg Road and 329-BY-PASS Road.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/louisville_signs/short.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The end of the pavement there is the end of Woodcreek Crossing Way.  It isn&#039;t wooded, it isn&#039;t anywhere near a creek, and it crosses nothing.  This isn&#039;t a road.  It&#039;s a driveway.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;

&lt;b class=&quot;center&quot;&gt;Misc Signs&lt;/b&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/louisville_signs/madtruck.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The truck in that sign is very angry.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/louisville_signs/meat.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Oh boy.  Beef Brisket, Pork Butt, and &lt;i&gt;Amish&lt;/i&gt; Chickens.  Who buys &lt;i&gt;Amish&lt;/i&gt; Chickens??&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/louisville_signs/rugman2.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;The Rug Man 2: Captain Carpet&#039;s Revenge&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/louisville_signs/ott.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Somebody needs to turn those &#039;t&#039;s into &#039;f&#039;s.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/louisville_signs/snakes.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This is a great sign.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/louisville_signs/downup.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Up and down are apparently both down now.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/louisville_signs/toob.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;p&gt;It&#039;s a good thing Bob Evans has plenty of Dino Toobs.  You wouldn&#039;t want to run out of Toobed Dino.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/louisville_signs/roadwork.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;p&gt;These roadwork warning signs are absolutely everywhere.  Five hundred feet down this road, there is another sign saying &quot;Road Work 500 Feet.&quot;  Four hundred feet from that sign is a sign that says &quot;Road Work 100 Feet.&quot;  And then one hundred feet from that sign is nothing.  Roadwork signs clutter the streets, but there no actual road work happening anywhere.  I wish I could have gotten a picture looking down a hill where you can see roadwork signs every hundred feet.  Almost as frequent as these signs are signs that say &quot;end roadwork.&quot;  They seem more like a political campaign than a road construction warning.  Judging from how much road work is actually happening on these roads, the campaign seems to have been a success.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;

&lt;b class=&quot;center&quot;&gt;Interstate Signs&lt;/b&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/louisville_signs/ends.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Gene Snyder Freeway Ends In Kentucky.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/louisville_signs/zorn2.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;p&gt;NO, not Zorn!  His evil plot to take over the world can not succeed!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/louisville_signs/zorn1.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I need more time to prepare my hyper plasma quantum molecular partical accelerator beams.  I must defeat the evil Zorn!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/louisville_signs/zorn.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;p&gt;CURSE YOU, ZORN!!!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;

&lt;/div&gt;

			&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;p style=&quot;font-size: 22px; text-indent: 0px; margin-top: -10px&quot;&gt;A list of things to be increased periodically until the end of time. &lt;br /&gt; In no paticular order.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul class=&quot;listofthings&quot;&gt;

&lt;li&gt;&lt;b&gt;3.&lt;/b&gt; Have really high expectations for something.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/content/news.php?post=00143&quot;&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/misc/snakes_small.jpg&quot; /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;

&lt;li&gt;&lt;b&gt;7.&lt;/b&gt; Go to the movie theatre and see a movie, by yourself.&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt;&lt;b&gt;10.&lt;/b&gt; Buy a t-shirt from Goodwill.&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt;&lt;b&gt;19.&lt;/b&gt; Watch all six &lt;i&gt;Star Wars&lt;/i&gt; films back to back.&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt;&lt;b&gt;22.&lt;/b&gt; Run through a 5K marathon that you haven&#039;t signed up for.&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt;&lt;b&gt;25.&lt;/b&gt; See the creepy &quot;Purdue Are Slow&quot; sign at the American Legion Park in Fortville, Indiana. &lt;/li&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/content/img.php?image=00001&quot;&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/weekly_image/small_purdue-slow.jpg&quot; width=&quot;150&quot; /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;

&lt;li&gt;&lt;b&gt;26.&lt;/b&gt; Ride a lunch tray down Slater Hill at 1 AM in the middle of January.&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt;&lt;b&gt;28.&lt;/b&gt; Eat an entire pizza, even just a small one.&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt;&lt;b&gt;31.&lt;/b&gt; Legitimately use a die that doesn&#039;t have six sides. &lt;/li&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/misc/dice.jpg&quot; /&gt;

&lt;li&gt;&lt;b&gt;32.&lt;/b&gt; Play a table top, pen and paper roleplaying game.&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt;&lt;b&gt;36.&lt;/b&gt; Build a computer from scratch.&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt;&lt;b&gt;37.&lt;/b&gt; Bake a cake from scratch.&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt;&lt;b&gt;43.&lt;/b&gt; Run the opposite way through an extremely large moving crowd.&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt;&lt;b&gt;54.&lt;/b&gt; Go bald on purpose. &lt;/li&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/content/olds.php?post=00134&quot;&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/hair/1a.jpg&quot; width=&quot;150&quot; /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;

&lt;li&gt;&lt;b&gt;61.&lt;/b&gt; Leave a tip greater than 50%.&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt;&lt;b&gt;70.&lt;/b&gt; Play capture the flag.&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt;&lt;b&gt;83.&lt;/b&gt; Stand in a several mile long line for something.&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt;&lt;b&gt;89.&lt;/b&gt; Create a beautiful work of art, and immediately destroy it.&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt;&lt;b&gt;90.&lt;/b&gt; Take sugar packets from one restaurant and plant them at a different one, thereby confusing the hell out of the wait staff.&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt;&lt;b&gt;97.&lt;/b&gt; Do not allow rock levels to sink below max.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/misc/01.jpg&quot; width=&quot;150&quot; /&gt;

&lt;li&gt;&lt;b&gt;103.&lt;/b&gt; Create a list of things you want to do before you die.&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt;&lt;b&gt;103.&lt;/b&gt; Take a vacation to your own backyard.&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt;&lt;b&gt;110.&lt;/b&gt; Play an accordion. &lt;/li&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/content/img.php?image=00013&quot;&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/weekly_image/accordians.gif&quot; width=&quot;150&quot; /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;

&lt;li&gt;&lt;b&gt;118.&lt;/b&gt; Ride a bike down State Street at Chauncy Hill during rush hour on move-in day.&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt;&lt;b&gt;123.&lt;/b&gt; Watch someone skydive from the relative safety of the ground below them.&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;If you have any comments, feel free to express them.  If you have an idea for something you think should be on the list, you can email it directly to &lt;a href=&quot;mailto:things@denyconformity.com&quot;&gt;things@denyconformity.com&lt;/a&gt;.

&lt;p&gt;The first Wednesday of the semester is a student&#039;s first test of the semester.  Students are challenged to remember where all of the classes they had on Monday are.  Here&#039;s a list of classes that I&#039;m taking this semester.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;dl&gt;
&lt;dt&gt;&lt;b&gt;Ethics&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/dt&gt;
&lt;dd&gt;One night, you go to sleep.  When when you wake up, you see that you are in a hospital room, with a bunch of tubes connecting you to someone in the bed next to you.  You learn that the champion orchestral troupe has kidnapped you because their star violinist has taken ill and you are the only person who can keep him from riding the bullet train to deadsville.  Are you morally obligated to stay until the violinist gets better, or are you ethically justified in giving them all a big &quot;screw you&quot; and leaving?  Welcome to Ethics 101.&lt;/dd&gt;
&lt;dt&gt;&lt;b&gt;Voice for the actor&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/dt&gt;
&lt;dd&gt;The most attractive of the Purdue theatre grad students teaches me how to properly use my voice(s).  At the end of last year, she and a few other grad students mentioned that I have a really good voice, so I quickly signed on for this course.  I now see that it was just a ploy to help her meet her quota.&lt;/dd&gt;
&lt;dt&gt;&lt;b&gt;Stage Combat&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/dt&gt;
&lt;dd&gt;Richard Stockton Rand, the professor I am creating a web site for, is a pretty amazing little man.  In this class, I learn how to beat the crap out of someone without actually touching them.  Later, I will learn how to swordfight, and perhaps eventually broadswordfight.  Rich is teaching me mental and physical discipline, which right now translates to extreme muscle fatigue.  I am sore in places I didn&#039;t know I had muscles.  Perks:  a really gorgeous, over-six-foot-tall volleyball player named Alex.  Cons:  always being paired up with her and realizing that she is quite a bit more physically fit than I am.&lt;/dd&gt;
&lt;dt&gt;&lt;b&gt;Acting Workshop III&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/dt&gt;
&lt;dd&gt;The heroes from &lt;i&gt;Acting Workshop II: Curse of the Meisner-Monster&lt;/i&gt; meet up once again, but this time, it&#039;s personal.  The evil Zorn Avenue is going to destroy the world, and only the performance of classic American and European realism will stop it.  Zorn&#039;s weakness  is Henrik Ibsen, as it turns out.&lt;/dd&gt;
&lt;dt&gt;&lt;b&gt;Intro to Lighting technology&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/dt&gt;
&lt;dd&gt;We all have to sign up to work on lights for a paticular show taking place this semester.  I signed up for the winter dance show, hoping to get a chance to hang out with some scantily clad dancers, and impress them with my mental and physical discipline.  It probably won&#039;t happen, but a guy can dream.&lt;/dd&gt;
&lt;/dl&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It&#039;s a pretty light schedule, but I also have a job this semester (don&#039;t ask me what it is; I have no idea, to be honest).  I&#039;m somewhat glad I don&#039;t have more, because after just the third day, I&#039;m exhausted.  If that Stage Combat class doesn&#039;t have me toned and fit by the end of the semester, it can&#039;t be done.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In other news, I finished my first draft of my screenplay.  Now all I have to do is pick up everything and move to LA.  I&#039;ve sent a few copies to a few of my peers, and the initial reactions seem to be positive.  Stay tuned to see how this works out.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;My first Crazy Monkeys show will be Friday, September 8, at 8:00.  It will be at the Village Coffee house, and it will be free.  Come see me be nervous and terrified.&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

