			&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;In which Shauvon is accepted to college, and visits a pulmonologist.&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In 2004, I was accepted to Purdue University.  It was a pretty exciting moment in my life.  Well, not that exciting, I suppose, considering they accept somewhere around 50,000 new students ever...&lt;/p&gt;

data.text:
&lt;p&gt;I recently upgraded to a digital SLR camera, the Canon EOS 350D (her friends call her Digital Rebel XT).  It is definitely a sweet piece of technology.  One of the greatest things about digital SLR cameras is the ability to record images as a digital negative, or Camera Raw format.  Basically, it stores as much data as possible, so that you can tweak almost everything later on a computer.  White balance, exposure, contrast, saturation, shadows and many more settings can all be manipulated later on.  It allows the photographer to worry more about the shot, and less about all of the technical nitty gritty.  Of course, you still have to deal with shutter speeds and aperture values, but that&#039;s what photography is.  I&#039;ll show you just how powerful Camera Raw format can be.  Also, I&#039;ll show off some sweet pictures I took with my new tripod.  They are some awesome shots.&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;You&amp;#039;re an awesome shot.&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;div class=&quot;center&quot;&gt;

Shot one:  Long exposure street.
&lt;br /&gt;
Here it is as I shot it, with generic white balance and exposure.  It looks ok.  I set up the tripod next to State Street and shot off a 20 second shutter speed.
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/rawrules/rawrules01.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Here is the shot, after I tweaked it in Photoshop using the camera raw plugin.  This isn&#039;t photoshopped, though, all I did to it was tweak the raw settings built into the image.
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/rawrules/rawrules02.jpg&quot; /&gt;

&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
Shot two: horizon glow.
&lt;br /&gt;
This is a shot of the halo eminating from Battleground, I believe (a town just north of Lafayette).  This shot was taken from the footbridge crossing the Wabash.  
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/rawrules/rawrules03.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Now after tweaking.  Primarily, all I did was adjust the white balance.
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/rawrules/rawrules04.jpg&quot; /&gt;

&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
Shot three: under the bridge.
&lt;br /&gt;
The Wabash is running really low right now, so I could walk out onto the bank and get some nice shots of the State Street bridge.  
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/rawrules/rawrules05.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Again, the only major change was the white balance.
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/rawrules/rawrules06.jpg&quot; /&gt;

&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
Shot four: under the bridge II.
&lt;br /&gt;
I didn&#039;t get many good shots of the State Street bridge from the footbridge, but I got a few nice onces from the ground below.  
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/rawrules/rawrules07.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Again again, the only major change was the white balance.  I had a huge &quot;holy crap&quot; moment when the sky popped out like this.
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/rawrules/rawrules08.jpg&quot; /&gt;

&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
Shot five: under the bridge III.
&lt;br /&gt;
I don&#039;t have enough shots with me in them, so I turned on the timer and ran out to be in this one.  
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/rawrules/rawrules09.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
I really like how the sky looks on these.
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/rawrules/rawrules10.jpg&quot; /&gt;

&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
Shot six: State Street&#039;s crotch.
&lt;br /&gt;
This is the point where State street changes from two roads to one.
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/rawrules/rawrules11.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Our world is very yellow, it seems.  I prefer blue.
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/rawrules/rawrules12.jpg&quot; /&gt;

&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I need to buy my own food this semester.  I know that doesn&#039;t sound like much, but I&#039;ve never had to do it before.  In order to afford all of the Tang and pizza rolls, I&#039;ve gotten a job.  What does this mean to you?&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;Entertainment&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;I&#039;m working for the ECN (Engineering Computer Network).  They have a website (&lt;a href=&quot;https://engineering.purdue.edu/ECN/&quot;&gt;https://engineering.purdue.edu/ECN/&lt;/a&gt;).  Part of this website is a &quot;Wall of Fame&quot; (&lt;a href=&quot;https://engineering.purdue.edu/ECE/Alumni/WallOfFame&quot;&gt;https://engineering.purdue.edu/ECE/Alumni/WallOfFame&lt;/a&gt;), where they list all of the past graduates from Electrical and Computer Engineering.  It&#039;s essentially just a huge database of names and pictures.  I&#039;m working on that database.  Actually, the database is already made, I&#039;m just - well - I don&#039;t really know what I&#039;m supposed to be doing.  All I know is I come here quietly for two hours every day, and they quietly put $150 or so into my checking account every other week.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I am working, though, so it&#039;s not like I just come here and do nothing (it&#039;s almost nothing).  On my first day, my boss told me that I would have to figure out how to work with the database.  She didn&#039;t mention that I would also have to figure out what exactly I&#039;m supposed to do.  At this point, I still don&#039;t know what I was hired for.  On one of my first days, I was just exploring around the site, seeing what it was all about (I&#039;ll save you some time and tell you it&#039;s not really about anything).  I noticed as I looked through the listings that the lists of graduates (broken up by year) that show up on the website are different than the actual lists in the database.  Many, and some times many many people are missing from the list.  That&#039;s a problem, and it probably results from the fact that nobody who does anything actually knows what they&#039;re doing.  The upshot is that it creates a new industry of people who&#039;s purpose is to redo everything everyone does.  This of course applies to anybody anywhere in the world, not just people who create extremely faulty databases for extremely seldom-visited websites.  Maybe my job falls into the second category, maybe it falls into the first.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I found out that all I have to do to fix the database is go to each offending record (the people who don&#039;t show up), and click &quot;update.&quot;  That&#039;s right.  For the last several weeks, I&#039;ve been going to hundreds if not thousands of pages to edit individual graduates and clicking a single button.  Early years were easy, because only a handful of people graduated from Purdue those years.  However, the 90&#039;s had hundreds of graduates each year.  For the later years, I have to look at the list on the website with the list in the database and find each and every guy who is in one but not the other, and then click a button.  How exciting my job is!&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/ECN/ECN01.gif&quot; class=&quot;center&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The list of graduates from the year 1900.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/ECN/ECN02.gif&quot; class=&quot;center&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The list of graduates from the year 1990.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This is pretty mindless, as I&#039;m sure you can guess.  I usually occupy myself with episodes of &lt;i&gt;Curb Your Enthusiasm&lt;/i&gt; on my Creative Zen Vision:M.  One time I watched &lt;i&gt;Blade 2&lt;/i&gt; while I clicked that little &quot;update&quot; button several hundred times.  Sometimes I only work for an hour, but I write two onto my time card.  I don&#039;t think I even need to go in on Fridays at all, because nobody else does.  I really feel like George from that one episode of Seinfeld, where he never does any work, but just makes it look like he is always really busy.  I think most of the episodes of Seinfeld were about George not working, now that I think about it.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;My boss is an interesting character, and I&#039;m still trying to decide if she creeps me out or if she&#039;s just eccentric.  I&#039;m leaning toward the latter, frankly.  I don&#039;t think she cares that I don&#039;t really have anything to do, it&#039;s not her money that&#039;s being quietly deposited in my account every other week.  She has to know that this website gets maybe five hits a year, and that it&#039;s such a huge piece of junk it needs to be completely rebuilt.  All I know is that she wears some pretty rediculous outfits, things that I could never hope to put into words.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Long story short, I have no attachment to this job whatsoever.  If I was fired (because they realize that I&#039;m completely unecessary), I could get a hundred more little bean counter jobs like this one in a week.  I therefore have no qualms about being one of the worst employees this world has ever seen.  Take right now, for instance.  My boss told me that she wasn&#039;t going to be here all week.  That gives me an interesting challenge.  The challenge is to do as little work as possible, while still making it look like I&#039;m not just watching &lt;i&gt;Curb your Enthusiasm&lt;/i&gt; for two hours.  Right now, for example, I&#039;m making a long post to my website about it.  If it wasn&#039;t for the random people who occasionally walk by and can verify that I didn&#039;t show up, I probably wouldn&#039;t even come in at all.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I&#039;m getting very close to the end of the database.  I&#039;m almost out of years to fix.  I don&#039;t want to get there, because it means I have to find something else to do.  That, my friends, is not an easy task.  I think my boss mentioned something about pictures . . . ?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Ok, so now we get to the upshot for you, tonight&#039;s loyal fans.  As I go through each and every student who got an Electrical Engineering degree at Purdue, I run across some semi-interesting names.  For example,&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/ECN/picture01.gif&quot; class=&quot;center&quot; /&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;This one isn&#039;t so great, I just think it&#039;s an interesting name.  Plus, I have to love the name Tang.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/ECN/picture02.gif&quot; class=&quot;center&quot; /&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Eric is a lame and unworthy name for a Schwinghammer.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/ECN/picture03.gif&quot; class=&quot;center&quot; /&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Oh Yoshimi, they don&#039;t believe me, but you won&#039;t let those robots defeat me.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/ECN/picture04.gif&quot; class=&quot;center&quot; /&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;I don&#039;t care what James Michael told you, because James Michael Lies!&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/ECN/picture05.gif&quot; class=&quot;center&quot; /&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Are you Charles?  Hardley.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/ECN/pictures06.gif&quot; class=&quot;center&quot; /&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;I hope these guys were really good friends, and that everyone called them &quot;french fries.&quot;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/ECN/pictures07.gif&quot; class=&quot;center&quot; /&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;This guy should have been a surgeon.  &quot;This guy needs surgery, fast!&quot;  &quot;Make way for &lt;b&gt;Dr. Thrash&lt;/b&gt;!&quot;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/ECN/pictures08.gif&quot; class=&quot;center&quot; /&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;What&#039;s the history of a name like that?&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/ECN/pictures09.gif&quot; class=&quot;center&quot; /&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;&quot;Hello, Roberts.&quot;  &quot;We&#039;re on a first name basis here, call me Robert.&quot;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;p&gt;And now, my favorite.  For some time, I&#039;ve been searching for a stage name to go by in play programs and things like that.  I have found it.  I will be&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/ECN/pictures10.gif&quot; class=&quot;center&quot; /&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;He definitely looks like a Fankboner.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Well, that&#039;s all, mainly because it&#039;s 5:30 and time for me to go home.  One perk about my job is that there&#039;s a webcam pointed directly at the place I park my bike.  So if you&#039;re really bored you can take a look and see if I&#039;m here pretending to work.  If you see the giant blue and sliver bike, it&#039;s probably mine. If you&#039;re lucky (and watching at half past the hour), you might just see me!&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://engineering.purdue.edu/ECN/WebCam/cam06/index&quot;&gt;Click here, and then click on the big picture to see the live footage.&lt;/a&gt;

