data.text:
			&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;or Every Abortion of Critical Thinking has Consequences&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/content/news.php?post=00152&quot;&gt;Read part one&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/content/news.php?post=00153&quot;&gt;and part two&lt;/a&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/curse/windowgone.JPG&quot; class=&quot;weekly&quot; /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&quot;Do you want to go to this Halloween party?&quot; Andrew asked me on Saturday evening.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&quot;That&#039;s the first time someone has asked me to go to a Halloween party,&quot; I replied, &quot;and the second time I&#039;ll say yes.&quot;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;We had to wait for Andrew to get off work.  I went home to put a lousy costume together.  What our costumes were is not important, because as it turns out&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;font-size: 25px; color: red&quot;&gt;WE WOULDN&#039;T NEED THEM!&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;On my way back to where Andrew works (the coffee shop in front of the alley where he found the coffin), a group of partially inebriated men stopped me and asked me where Chances Are was.  Chances Are is a show club on the far side of Lafayette, just past the Gypsy&#039;s house Andrew and I went to the day before.  I told the gentlemen that they were in very-much-the-wrong place, and they kindly asked me if I could take them there.  If I had held out a little longer, I probably could have gotten them to pay me.  &lt;i&gt;Act of Fate C: if I had shown the gentlemen where Chances Are was, perhaps the fateful events of Saturday night would not have happened quite the same way.&lt;/i&gt;  Luckily (or unluckily), Andrew called me when the gentlemen were discussing this matter with me, so I had an easy excuse to get rid of them.  They went off down Chauncy hill, presumably walking to Chances Are.  I doubt they made it, because it&#039;s about fifteen minutes away from Chauncy Hill by car.  On slightly inebriated feet, I&#039;m sure it&#039;s a much longer journey.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Andrew called me and told me to meet him at the coffee shop.  We were going to meet at his car, but he forgot some things (like his wallet), so he had to go back for them.  &lt;i&gt;Act of Fate D:  if Andrew hadn&#039;t forgotten his wallet, we would have been just a few minutes earlier, and perhaps the fateful events of Saturday night would not have happened quite the same way.&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Andrew got his things and we left.  Some crazy guy was saying something about a missing box that he keeps in the alley.  I don&#039;t know what that was all about.  Eventually, Andrew and I got to his car.  Andrew drives a Subaru Outback station wagon.  It&#039;s a nice car.  It has enough room for a rather large coffin, or an average-sized Gypsy&#039;s organ, or five comfortable Crazy Monkeys.  It has cup-holders, an FM radio, power windows, and&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;font-size: 25px; color: red&quot;&gt;A SEVERE DESIGN FLAW&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;We were driving out on 200 North.  Friends call it Lindberg Road.  That is the road that leads to Andrew&#039;s apartment.  It is also the road the leads to my Grandma&#039;s house.  Look it up on Google Maps on your own time.  We had just passed the Celery Bog, and I was about to note that the road was getting bumpier.  There is a particular stretch of Lindberg Road that goes over the Celery Bog which gets particularly bumpy (corrugated cardboard style).  They have rebuilt the road several times, but each time it just gets bumpy again (corrugated cardboard style).  We had just passed that particular stretch of Lindberg Road, and I was about to note that the road was getting bumpy yet again.  I made it through the following words before Andrew&#039;s window exploded:  hey, this, road, is, and getti.  &#039;Getti&#039; isn&#039;t actually a word.  I was trying to say &#039;getting,&#039; but I was cut short when Andrew&#039;s window exploded.  I usually mention something about that particular stretch of Lindberg Road whenever I ride on it, because it seems like every time I do, it gets bumpier and bumpier (corrugated cardboard style).  However, at this particular moment, certain events were slightly more important.  Right as I was about to speak the voiced velar nasal sound at the end of the word &#039;getting&#039;, Andrew&#039;s car made it&#039;s own voiced velar nasal.  Granted, Andrew&#039;s car lacks several key points of anatomy to properly emit a true voiced velar nasal, but it did what it could with what it had.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;There was a loud bang, followed by a loud pop, followed by the sound of millions of glass shards falling all over the back seat of Andrew&#039;s car, followed by the sound of Andrew and me experiencing simultaneous &#039;brown alerts.&#039;  By a show of hands, who here has been in a car when a window exploded?  Sometimes I forget that the internet isn&#039;t a lecture hall.  If you have experienced the spontaneous explosion of a car window, you know the horrible fear that consumes everyone in the car when such an event occurs.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;There was a short period during which various expletives were said.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&quot;That means someone is shooting at us, right?&quot; Andrew asked.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The answer is, of course, &quot;no, don&#039;t be ridiculous.&quot;  However, the surging levels of adrenaline in my body caused me to say some form of the expression &quot;shit, I don&#039;t know, man, but I think so.&quot;  We made it to Andrew&#039;s apartment, both of us ducking below the level of the dashboard, and we got out to survey the damage.  I had my camera, and took some pictures of the car.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Here is where I&#039;ll put the bold text saying,&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;CONSEQUENCE NUMBER 2: THE EXPLODING WINDOW&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/curse/wondow1.JPG&quot; class=&quot;weekly&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;This doesn&#039;t do justice to how much broken glass was everywhere.  The door is actually full of it, so every time we closed it, it rattled in a rather comical way.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/curse/wondow2.JPG&quot; class=&quot;weekly&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Car glass is coated with a poly-bunka-junka-chloro-mega-hydro-floxy-stuff, which prevents it from shattering into horrible flying shards of death, like regular glass.  As a result, car glass breaks into these nice, neat chunks.  Except for the bits that don&#039;t, they just turn into millions of tiny pieces.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/curse/wondow3.JPG&quot; class=&quot;weekly&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Although these glass chunks might look like a delicious new rock candy confection, they are not actually very delicious at all and very harmful if swallowed apparently.  However tempting it might be, please refrain from eating the glass chunks.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Andrew took his car to the police to report the damage, just in case someone was shooting at us.  The police apparently told him the correct response to that question.  I stayed at his apartment, sorting things out with the organ.  Mainly I just turn on the auto rythm, auto bass, and magic chord systems, and hold down the one key that works while I dance around it for hours at a time.  It never gets old.  Someone was saying something about wanting to destroy something.  I don&#039;t know what that was about.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Andrew returned with beer.  We had made a non-verbal agreement not to go to the Halloween party, and hide in his Apartment instead.  Madness quickly set in.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;CONSEQUENCE NUMBER 3: VARIOUS MADNESSES&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Gen had the ocean madness, Pat had the space madness, I had the label madness, and Andrew caught a rare case of the Australian Digeridoo madness.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/curse/madness.gif&quot; class=&quot;weekly&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Dear. God.  RUN!&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/curse/maddness01.JPG&quot; class=&quot;weekly&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;I also like this image, but it didn&#039;t really look very good in the animated Gif above.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The window was a little terrifying, and the madness was as well, but as curses go, this one was pretty entertaining.  I&#039;ve already forgotten about the missing lego pieces, as I&#039;m sure you have as well.  Cut to the next day, however, and we get the worst curse of all!&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;CONSEQUENCE NUMBER 4: DIET COLA&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/curse/diet01.JPG&quot; class=&quot;weekly&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;&quot;Dayna, can I have a drink of your Coke?&quot; &lt;br /&gt; &quot;Sure.&quot;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/curse/diet02.JPG&quot; class=&quot;weekly&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;&quot;Oh God, it&#039;s Diet!  Blork!&quot;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Haunting.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Andrew took his car in to get the window fixed, and the mechanic said that it was a specific defect in that particular car.  Apparently when you transport cursed organs in certain Subaru Outback station wagons, the rear driver side window explodes.  That&#039;s important to know.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Well, I think I&#039;ve just about said all there is to say about this adventure.  If anyone has anything to add, that&#039;s what I made the comment system for.  I hope everyone enjoyed reading about the Gypsy&#039;s organ about as much as we enjoyed being cursed by it.&lt;/p&gt;

