&lt;p&gt;A terrible thing has happened to me recently.  Those of you who know me well will understand what a blow this is.  Kraft foods has repackaged and re-formulated Tang.  Yes, everyone&#039;s favorite astronaut drink has been changed.  It is no longer the tang I used to know and love.  It is different, and it is disgusting.  I am hereby beginning a full boycot on Kraft Foods, to end only when they give me back my Tang.&lt;/p&gt;
			
			&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/tang/oldtang.gif&quot;   align=&quot;right&quot; hspace=&quot;10&quot; /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Food companies repackage their products all the time.  Usually this is a harmless attempt to look cooler or better than the competition.  The change in packaging has no effect on the contents.  Usually this is the case.  When such a change occurs, the package will be labeled with phrases such as &quot;new package, same great product.&quot;  Food companies have very specific recipes for their products, and consumers need to be reassured that those recipes are unchanged.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Let&#039;s discuss for a moment why a company would choose to repackage a product.  Perhaps a competitor has repackaged their product, and the company wants to keep up.  Perhaps a new competitor has appeared on the scene, and the company needs to compete.  Neither of these situations apply to tang.  Sure, Koolaide has a very large market, but there is no product that matches the, well, &lt;i&gt;tanginess&lt;/i&gt; of Tang.  Let me repeat:  There is no proper substitute for Tang.  With no competition, it should be Kraft&#039;s prerogative to keep Tang the way it is, so as to avoid customer confusion.  As soon as Tang lovers think Tang is no longer the same, they will flee into the waiting arms of the Koolaide man.  This is precisely what is happening with me.  Wait, Kraft also owns Koolaide.  Great.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/tang/oldtangnutrition.jpg&quot;   align=&quot;right&quot; hspace=&quot;10&quot; /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Tang has a very long and illustrious history.  Tang was invented in 1957 by William A. Mitchell.  Mitchell also invented Pop Rocks, Jell-O, and Cool Whip, so Tang comes from a very powerful family.  Tang didn&#039;t find success until 1965, when it was used by NASA in Gemini flights.  Tang caught on, and it has been associated with astronauts since then.  Tang has gone unchanged for fifty years (yes, this year is the fiftieth anniversary of Tang).  Tang has been unchanged, until now.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In November, 1985, General Foods (the company responsible for Tang) was acquired by Philip Morris Companies (the company responsible for tobacco in America).  General Foods had made some acquisitions of their own.  General Foods owned several companies, such as Oscar Mayer, Burger Chef, and Perkins Products Company (the maker of Koolaide).  When Philip Morris bought General Foods, it was the largest non-oil acquisition ever.  Shortly later, Philip bought Kraft Foods, and merged the two companies together.  Little did they know that Kraft would screw it all up in twelve years.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;According to Wikipedia, Lyndon Johnson, Jimmy Carter, Ronald Reagan, and Bill Clinton all loved Tang when they were in office.  They loved it before Kraft destroyed it.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;For a very long time, Tang was served in big plastic containers that held enough Tang for either six quarts or nine quarts.  You did not need to add sugar.  This is what separated it from Koolaide.  Koolaide needs to be mixed with sugar in order for it to work.  Tang was specifically formulated to mix directly with water and drink.  The nutrition facts can be seen to the right.  Those were taken directly from the Kraft website.  Look at that.  Nothing but sugar.  I liked it that way.  I don&#039;t need anything else.  Sugar and flavors.  That&#039;s all I want.  Kraft doesn&#039;t care.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/tang/tang02.jpg&quot;   align=&quot;right&quot; hspace=&quot;10&quot; /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A few weeks ago, I went to Wal-Mart with my friend Andrew Monkey.  I needed to buy some more tang and pizza rolls (I&#039;m almost 21, but I eat like a 10 year old).  Wal-Mart had no tang.  A gaping hole was left in both the powdered drink mix aisle, and also my heart.  A couple weeks later, I returned ot Wal-Mart to try again.  They had Tang, but it was not the same Tang.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I had a very bad feeling about this.  First of all, the new container is a really weird size.  It&#039;s about a third the size of the old six quart container.  The new one makes eight quarts, too.  How can it be smaller, but make more?  It does tell me that it &quot;makes 33% more than 6 quart Tang.&quot;  It is also pretty open about its low sugar content.  That&#039;s a bad sign.  The worst harbinger of doom is the fact that nowhere on the new package does it say &quot;new package, same great product.&quot;  Instead, it has some new &quot;Fruitrition&quot; logo.  I was wary.  &quot;Fruitrition&quot; shares an awful lot of syllables with &quot;Nutrition,&quot;  and that&#039;s not something I drink Tang for.  I decided to give them the benefit of the doubt, and buy the new Tang.  I had no choice, anyway, because as was stated earlier, there is no proper substitute for Tang.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/tang/tang03.jpg&quot;   align=&quot;right&quot; hspace=&quot;10&quot; /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Wikipedia acknowledges the new packaging.  The new containers are smaller because they contain a more concentrated formula.  That makes sense, really.  Our technology has advanced quite a bit since 1957.  Why can&#039;t our Tangology have advanced as well?  It must be that Tangologists have merely made a breakthrough in Tanguistics, and now they are able to make the Tang powder more efficiently.  They have also apparently made some breakthroughs in Fruitrition, a complex science reserved for only the top scientific minds.  Technological advancements are good.  However, Tangological advancements are not.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/tang/tang03B.jpg&quot;   align=&quot;right&quot; hspace=&quot;10&quot; /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A look at the back of the package shows that the concentration is not the only thing that has changed.  The new Tang contains only 9 grams of sugar, as opposed to Olde Tang&#039;s 24.  Further examination shows the following ingredients in the Ingredient List:  Maltodextrin; Sucralose, Acesulfame Potassium, and Neotame (sweeteners).  Why would Tang need sweeteners?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Interestingly enough, I happened to glance at an empty Splenda packet that my roomate left on the counter.  I immediately recognized the ingredients &lt;b&gt;Sucralose and Maltodextrin.&lt;/b&gt;  New Tang is made with Splenda.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/tang/tang04.jpg&quot;   align=&quot;right&quot; hspace=&quot;10&quot; /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It is apparently important to Kraft for Tang to have less sugar than juice.  That is why they have redesigned it.  They haven&#039;t made any breakthroughs in Tanguistics.  They&#039;re just picking a fight.  They&#039;re taking on juice as Tang&#039;s competitor.  That is a strange choice.  Kraft has a hundred other drink products that they could put in this &quot;better than juice&quot; bracket.  Why do they need to ruin my the drink I have had my entire life?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;New Tang is not the same product as Olde Tang.  &lt;b&gt;I can taste a difference.&lt;/b&gt;  You may not notice anything different, but that is just because you do not have the same skills in Tanguistics that I have.  My claims are supported by the fact that the ingredients and Nutrition Facts are different.  New Tang contains Splenda.  It has the distinct artificial sweetener after-taste that Olde Tang did not have.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;We all grew up with Tang.  Tang hasn&#039;t changed significantly in half a century.  If you are like me and you believe that Kraft should not be changing a classic product on its fiftieth aniversary, please voice your opinions directly to them.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Kraft Foods Global, INC. &lt;br /&gt;Northfield, IL 60093&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;1-800-431-1002&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.kraftfoods.com/main.aspx?m=contact_us/cu_form1&quot;&gt;Click here to send a comment to Kraft&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Kraft is a large corporation owned by an even larger corporation.  Chances are our voices will not be heard.  However, as consumers we have the greatest power of all over them.  We control whether or not they make money.  I hereby announce that from this moment on I am in a full boycot of Kraft products (and their parent company Philip Morris) until they give Tang back to us.  I invite you all to join me in this.  Tell your friends.  Denyconformity.com is now officially denying Kraft Foods.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The spammers have taken their next move, so now I am forced to implement a system I was hoping I wouldn&#039;t have to implement.  An easy system has been around for a long time to prevent spammers, by proving that the entity attempting to access a page is truly human.  I will soon be implementing a Completely Automated Public Turing test to tell Computers and Humans Apart, or CAPTCHA.  These devices have been around for some time, and I&#039;m sure most of you have seen one in one form or another.  Usually, they are used on account setup pages to keep automated bots away.  In most CAPTCHAs, you are required to look at an image, and type out a handfull of letters or numbers that appear in the image.  I will try to make my CAPTCHA as easy to use and unobtrusive as possible, while still requiring just enough logic to prove that you are human.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It will have something to do with the following code, so you can go ahead and start memorizing it now.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt; 09-F9-11-02-9D-74-E3-5B-D8-41-56-C5-63-56-88-C0&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Okay, so I am not going to make you all memorize that code.  Still, it&#039;s a good code to remember.&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Hello everyone.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I just wanted to mention that I am collecting a few things, and you can all help out.  I have big plans for these things, and if we all team together, we can accomplish something really cool.  Stay tuned for exactly what it is that I have planned.  I have an idea for them which might turn out to be something really awesome.  Sure, it could turn out to just be a waste of time, but what isn&#039;t these days?&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Anyway, I need any and every bottle cap I can get my hands on.  That&#039;s right, I&#039;m collecting as many standard metal bottle caps as I can.  Anyone out there who opens a bottle of soda, root or sans-root beer, or any other metal cap style glass bottle, please collect them for me.  Let me know if you get some and we can work out a system for you to get them to me.  This should require next to no effort on your part, and you can find satisfaction in knowing that you were a part of a grand scheme.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Also, Dr. Pepper currently has a sort of sweepstakes going.  Inside the bottle caps (not the same kind of bottle caps that I&#039;m collecting) of specially marked 20 oz. bottles of Dr. Pepper, you can find codes and enter them online to earn points and be entered into prize drawings.  I&#039;m not interested in the prizes, just the points.  Each code is worth four points, so I need a bunch of them.  If you find any of these special yellow bottle caps, I would really appreciate it if you would collect them for me as well.  If any of them win prizes, you can have the prize.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Denyconformity.com thanks you for keeping a diligent eye open for these easy to collect and most likely free items.&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;I am currently unemployed.&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;As a result, I&#039;ve had to resort to some interesting things to pay my cable bill, while I continue looking for a job.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;One of those things is selling stuff on ebay.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Another thing I&#039;ve tried is craigslist.  &lt;a href=&quot;http://indianapolis.craigslist.com&quot;&gt;Craigslist&lt;/a&gt; is an interesting web site, where you can find all sorts of stuff in your general area.  I wandered into the &quot;web/info desigs&quot; category to see if there was anything I could do.  I found a few listings for freelance jobs, a few listings for more permanent positions, and a few random other things.  I can&#039;t really do anything permanent, since these are all in the Indy area, and I&#039;m living in West Lafayette (70.6 miles, according to &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/googlemaps.php&quot;&gt;Google Maps&lt;/a&gt;).  I sent emails to the few freelance jobs I saw.  Most of those didn&#039;t respond.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;a href=&quot;../../assets/images/suspicious_listing.JPG&quot; style=&quot;width: 550px; display: block; margin-right: 0px; margin-left: auto; float: right; padding: 20px&quot;&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;../../assets/images/suspicious_listing_small.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;Web Designers needed NOW.  Earn dollar signs!!&quot; /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;

&lt;p&gt;One entry I found (pictured at right), asks for web designers to work from home creating web graphics.  I&#039;m getting pretty desperate at this point, so I decided to inquire.  I know it looks pretty suspicious, and asking directly for my PHONE NUMBER (clue number one) is a little creepy, but I was curious.  The use of three whole dollar signs was sure enticing (clue number two).  I emailed them my INFORMATION including my PHONE NUMBER, and waited for the same null response that I&#039;ve gotten from pretty much everything else I&#039;ve tried to make money.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I got the call this morning.  My phone rang out with the CTU ringtone (from the show &lt;i&gt;24&lt;/i&gt;) that I think is delightfully ironic and amusing.  The &quot;restricted number&quot; that was calling immediately made me excited.  I hoped it was the photography store I applied to yesterday, which I would really love to work at.  I was greeted by a sleezy sounding man with a slight accent.  &quot;Show-von McGill?&quot; he asked.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&quot;This is he.&quot;  I replied.  Another zany name adventure for &quot;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/content/olds.php?post=146&quot;&gt;Sho-von&lt;/a&gt;&quot; had begun.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&quot;You responed to an entry on Craig&#039;s List about Web Designer positions?&quot;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&quot;Yes.&quot;  The chances of this being about that photography store are getting worse and worse.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&quot;Okay, well how old are you, Show-von?&quot; Clue number three.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&quot;I&#039;m 21.&quot;  I just turned 21 a few weeks ago.  I still don&#039;t drink.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&quot;Okay, that&#039;s no problem, then.  You&#039;re at Purdue?&quot;  Judging from my email address, I suppose.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&quot;Yes, I am.&quot;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Then there was a pause, where I suppose there was some sort of connection problem.  He came back saying &quot;Are you still there?&quot;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&quot;Yes.&quot;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&quot;Are you still there?&quot;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&quot;Yes, I am.&quot;  This whole thing is getting a little too weird.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&quot;Are you at Purdue?&quot;  I guess he didn&#039;t hear me answer the first time.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&quot;Yes, I am.&quot;  I replied again.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&quot;Were you afraid to answer?&quot;  He asked, apparently he heard nothing after he asked the first time.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&quot;No.&quot;  I answered.  At this point, I wanted the conversation to end and for him not to have my number anymore.  However, I was still curious where this was going.  I would soon find out.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&quot;Well, we work with some adult material, would you be comfortable with adult content?&quot;  He asked.  The cat was out of the bag.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I was not interested in doing porn.  I am not yet that desperate.  Even if I was, I could make quite a bit more dollar signs than that working independently, I feel.  Anyway, my answer was a quick &quot;No.&quot;  Without even saying anything, the dude hung up.  I guess nobody in the &quot;adult&quot; industry is known for being polite, but a simple &quot;that&#039;s not what we&#039;re looking for&quot; would have sufficed.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The cat was out of the bag.  Curiosity sure killed that cat.  Moral:  &quot;multiple dollar signs working with web graphics in the comfort of your own home&quot; means porn.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;If anybody knows anybody who needs a website, please hook me up.&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

