data.text:
&lt;p&gt;As most of you probably guessed, I&#039;m a pretty big fan of giant battling robots.  When I judge how cool something is, I judge it on a scale of one to ten.  On this scale, one is represented by a bad laser-jet printing of a picture of a skinny man wearing a fanny pack.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Ten is giant battling robots, in space, with lasers.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It should therefore come as little surprise to you that I was somewhat excited about the new Transformers movie.  Transformers are the quintessential fulfillment of the absolute coolest thing, beating out Lego, Star Wars, G.I. Joe, and even Battletech.  Nothing is cooler to a ten-year-old boy, and I am most certainly a ten-year-old boy at heart.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I certainly lost most of my hard earned respect when I referenced Battletech, so I&#039;ll get to the point.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Film critics hate Transformers.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I hate film critics, and by extension, film reviews.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I am therefore not going to write my own review of a movie which I obviously have serious biases for.  I will instead write reviews of the reviews.&lt;/p&gt;

			&lt;p&gt;Let us begin.&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.rottentomatoes.com/click/movie-1165257/reviews.php?critic=columns&amp;sortby=default&amp;page=1&amp;rid=1649217&quot;&gt;Transformers review, by Jeffrey Westhoff&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;Deny Conformity ReviewScore:  &lt;b&gt;1%&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The first review I will be critiquing was written by the questionably literate newspaper writer Jeffrey Westhoff.  Westhoff hails from the Northwest Herald, out of Crystal Lake, Illinois.  It would seem that the only thing this newspaper will “herald” is the end of any sense of credibility in printed media as we know it.  That this puerile and almost vulgar insult to writing is actually distributed to a wide audience is sickening.  Westhoff succeeds only at pushing his useless and unintelligent industry further into the deepest, darkest circle of Hell reserved only for him and his kind.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Westhoff begins his asinine rant with the first of many personal attacks on Transformers&#039; director, Michael Bay.  Whatever dark, haunting trauma Westhoff endured in his past to cause him to be so ruthlessly opposed to Bay may never be discovered.  However, hatred this raw and irrational is certainly unhealthy.  Westhoff’s intended punching bag is obvious, with comments like, &quot;The Transformers, those robots disguised as jets and sports cars, arrive in theaters battling one of the most malevolent forces in the galaxy: Michael Bay. . . &#039;Transformers&#039; fails because it is a Michael Bay film, terrible for the same reasons all this egomaniacal hack’s films are terrible.&quot;  Ouch.  Westhoff then goes on to call Bay a &quot;Jerry Bruckheimer castoff,&quot; and insults Steven Spielberg merely for associating with Bay.  Like the film he is so respectfully reviewing, the review itself doesn’t actually start until half-way through.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;With the personal attacks off his chest, Westhoff finally gets around to performing the public service he is paid to perform.  I guarantee that whatever salary Jeffrey Westhoff earns, even if he works for free, he is paid far too much for what he does.  Somewhere, buried in his constant references to Michael Bay’s failures, one might be able to scrape together a few sentences that actually pertain to the film he is theoretically reviewing, but they hardly form much in the way of thoughts.  Certainly, the reader instantly gets an understanding of Westhoff’s opinions of the film’s director, but he completely fails to provide many clues to his actual opinion of the film.  Certainly the director is not the only one contributing to the process.  In fact, many of the complaints Westhoff points directly at Bay, for example the inane subplots thrown into the film to waste our time, could not possibly have been Bay’s fault, as he had nothing to do with the screenplay or the story.  Again and again, Westhoff proves that the only thoughts rattling around in that balding empty head of his are about how much he hates Michael Bay.  With a perfectly middle-of-the-road 2 out of 4 that he gave the film, he didn’t really seem to hate it quite as much as it sounds.  Indeed, the review would hardly be different even if he hadn’t seen the movie, which could quite possibly be the reality.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;If all of that was not damning enough evidence to prove that Jeffrey Westhoff is a raving lunatic, there is still the most startlingly disgusting aspect of his review left to discuss.  Let us return to the beginning of his review for a moment.  Westhoff bellows, &quot;Whatever chance that &#039;Transformers,&#039; which is based on the toys that debuted in the 1980s along with a cartoon and a comic book, might have been a decent movie disappeared the moment Bay was hired to direct.&quot;  Certainly, his Bay-bashing intentions are clear, but take a moment to read that sentence again.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Jeffrey Westhoff has been writing published film reviews since 1989, yet he is still incapable of forming a proper sentence?  Was he so intent on his rage for Michael Bay that he couldn’t stop to edit his own writing?  That first, painful sentence stands like the Gates of Hell, warning to &quot;abandon hope all ye who enter here.&quot;  That first, painful sentence screams at you, pleading with you to just stop reading any further.  Perhaps you think the review could not possibly go anywhere but up after that.  Maybe you continue to read, unable to look away from this horrible car crash you can’t help but watch.  Whatever the case, somehow Westhoff is able to sink further and further, and you realize that those gates standing at the entrance to Hell could not possibly have prepared you for the horrors contained within this putrid review.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;He ends his review with yet another painful insult.  This one is not directed at Bay, however.  This insult is pointed directly at the Transformers themselves.  Westhoff compares the movie to Go-Bots, the biggest insult to robot-kind that ever was and ever will be.  All this came from the man who called &lt;i&gt;Spiderman 3&lt;/i&gt; &quot;an entertaining, coherent and poignant story.&quot;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In a field which itself is a pointless failure, Jeffrey Westhoff is a pointless failure.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Stay tuned for more reviews of reviews on Denyconformity.com!&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The time has finally come.  Denyconformity.com has finally been given its first active defense against the spammers.  Now, all comments will be screened by a simple logic question.  Something that computers will hopefully be unable to understand, but which will hopefully be a breeze for any human.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The term CAPTCHA, or &quot;Completely Automated Public Turing test to tell Computers and Humans Apart&quot; was first coined by Luis von Ahn, Manuel Blum, Nicholas J. Hopper (all of Carnegie Mellon University), and John Langford (of IBM).  You can learn more about the CAPTCHA concept on &lt;a href=&quot;http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Captcha&quot;&gt;Wikipedia&lt;/a&gt;.  Most CAPTCHAs involve a scrambled image of some type, depicting certain text.  The user has to type that text into a box in order to continue.  The problem I see with such a system is that it is simple enough for a computer to decipher.  Spammers have the technology to get the text out of an image, even if it is rather thoroughly scrambled, and enter it, violating the CAPTCHA.  I am exploring a different approach to the system.  My idea is that while computers can easily decipher scrambled images, they still fail to complete even the simplest logic tests.  Denyconformity.com will use a system based on that theory.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Now, when you comment on a post, you will have to answer a simple question in order to continue.  Instead of just copying text from an image, you will actually be required to think.  Hopefully this will screen out anything that I don&#039;t want posting comments on the site, like computers or stupid people.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;If you have any comments or questions about the system (if, for example, you are unable to answer a CAPTCHA question), feel free to contact me.  Send an email to:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;smcgill (put an &#039;at&#039; sign here) denyconformity (put a single period here) com&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It turns out that computers can also find email addresses on web sites and add them to spam lists.  Spelling out the &quot;@&quot; and the &quot;.&quot; are simple ways to avoid that, apparently.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I thought up many different questions I can ask to prove that you are human.  I decided not to use questions that are too complicated, difficult, or stupid.  Unused CAPTCHA questions include:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;In C++, how many bytes are allocated for an &quot;int&quot; variable type?&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt;Plato often spoke of his Theory of Forms.  In two thousand words or less, describe your own thoughts on the theory.&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt;Suppose a standard 8x8 chessboard has two diagonally opposite corners removed, leaving 62 squares. How can you place 31 dominoes of size 2x1 so as to cover all of these squares?&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt;While on my way to St. Ives,I met a man with seven wives.Each wife had seven sacks;Each sack had seven cats;Each cat had seven kits. Kits, cats, sacks, wives; How many were going to St. Ives?  (Yes, this is a &lt;i&gt;Die Hard&lt;/i&gt; reference)&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt;Would you like to go on a date with me?  Saying &quot;no&quot; will verify that you are human.&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt;Which of the following would you most prefer? A: a puppy, B: a pretty flower from your sweety, or C: a large properly formatted data file?&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt;What year was Khan Noonien Singh born in?&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt;Integrate the following equation: &lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/afx_formula.png&quot; style=&quot;vertical-align: middle&quot; alt=&quot;Really long, complicated formula.&quot; /&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;What questions would be good for CAPTCHAs?&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;Tang Update&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;Tang Update&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;Tang Update&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I went up to the food mart in town, which specializes mostly in foreign groceries, and I found something very interesting.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/content/news.php?post=00164&quot;&gt;Read the scoop on Tang, as it stands.&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/tang/hn_tang1.jpg&quot; height=&quot;587&quot; width=&quot;500&quot;&gt;&lt;p&gt;What does this strange package contain?  It claims to be Tang, but it is really?  This isn&#039;t orange, at any rate.  The package is very up-front about its &lt;b&gt;MANGGA FLAVOR INSTANT DRINK MIX&lt;/b&gt;.  The title declares the contents to be &quot;Kraft Hi-Nutrition Tang,&quot; and it bears a logo very similar to the &quot;frutrition&quot; logo of the blasphemous American New Tang.  However, the ingredients foretell of a glorious non-Splenda future for those who partake in the Hi-nutrition drink.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/tang/hn_tang4.jpg&quot; height=&quot;485&quot; width=&quot;500&quot;&gt;&lt;p style=&quot;width: 300px; padding: 10px; background-color: #ffff00&quot;&gt;Ingredients:  Sugar, Citric Acid, Sodium Carboxymethylcellulose, Calcium Phosphate, Sodium Chloride, Vitamins, Permitted Artificial Colors (including Tartrazine), Iron Salt, Flavors.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;First of all, Sugar at the top of the list is a very good sign.  Secondly, &quot;Sucralose&quot; is nowhere to be found, meaning Splenda is not involved.  &lt;i&gt;What the hell is Sodium Carboxymethylcellulose?&lt;/i&gt;, I ask myself.  Wikipedia lists Sodium Carboxymethylcellulose as an emulsifier, basically the agent which causes the powder to mix with water.  New Tang does not list such an agent in its list of ingredients, and I have a theory for this, which I will get to shortly.  Moving down the list, Calcum Phosphate prevents &quot;caking&quot; because nobody wants Tang cake.  Sodium Chloride is table salt.  Vitamins sounds like when you go to the store and next to the steaks are containers labeled &quot;meat.&quot;  Tartrazine is a yellow dye, which obviously plays the starring role in this drink mix.  I have no idea what Iron Salt is.  Flavors are apparently the least important ingredient, which I will return to shortly.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/tang/hn_tang3.jpg&quot; height=&quot;504&quot; width=&quot;500&quot;&gt;&lt;p style=&quot;width: 300px; padding: 10px; background-color: #ffff00&quot;&gt;&lt;b&gt;DIRECTIONS&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;b&gt;By The Glass:&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br&gt;Maglagay ng 1 1/2 tablespoons ng Hi-Nutrition &lt;b&gt;TANG&lt;/b&gt; sa isang baso.  Lagyan ng malamig na tubig para makagawa ng 200 mL na drink.  Stir and serve.
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;b&gt;By the pitcher:&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br&gt;Maglagay ng 8 tablespoons ng Hi-Nutrition &lt;b&gt;TANG&lt;/b&gt; sa isang pitsel.  Lagyan ng malamig na tubig para makagawa ng 1 liter na drink.  Stir and serve.
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
NO NEED TO ADD SUGAR&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The entire package is covered with an odd mixture of English and some other language. The back of the package lists the Philippine Importer, which is a possible clue to the product&#039;s origins.  The front of the package declares the drink to be &quot;Charged with CALCIUM.&quot;  Directly below that, we see that the package &quot;PANG 4 LITRO.&quot;  The side asks, &quot;Ano bang meron ang Tang?  Ang Tang ay siksik sa nutrients na makakatulong sa maraming paraan!&quot;  Then we see a list of vitamins, and what they do for you.  My favorite is next to Vitamin A, &quot;Nakatulong sa healthy skin and hair.&quot;  Below the vitamin information, is the following:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;width: 300px; padding: 10px; background-color: #ffff00&quot;&gt;Available din sa CONCENTRATED Litro Pack.  Isang Litro pack lang, isang pitsel na!  Siksik sa hi-nutrition benefits and great fruit taste na eksaktosa inyong panlasa.  Wata nang tantsa-tantsa.  So easy and convenient.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/tang/hn_tang5.jpg&quot; height=&quot;555&quot; width=&quot;500&quot;&gt;&lt;p&gt;When I opened the top, a poof of the Calcium Phosphate charged powder assailed me directly in the nose.  Instantly, my hopes skyrocketed.  It really looked and smelled an awful lot like Olde Tang, or at least what my fading memories remember it to be.  I scooped some into a spoon to take the above picture.  I only spilled a little on the new couch.  The powder is a little more yellow than the legends describe Olde Tang to be.  The whole thing was rather yellow.  It&#039;s hard to see in the pictures, but there is a picture of a mango on the package.  Yellow mangoes in front of a yellow background was not a great choice.  It really smells like Olde Tang.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;But how does it taste?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I mixed it together, exactly to the specifications listed in &lt;b&gt;DIRECTIONS&lt;/b&gt;.  I Maglagayed exactly 1 1/2 tablespoons ng Hi-Nutrition &lt;b&gt;TANG&lt;/b&gt; directly sa isang baso.  The spoonful and a half of powder was enough to makagawa ng 200 mL na drink, so that&#039;s exactly what I, well, makagawad.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I tentatively stirred, and served.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/tang/hn_tang6.jpg&quot; height=&quot;333&quot; width=&quot;500&quot;&gt;&lt;p&gt;I could immediately tell that this was not Tang.  This was not Orange Tang, by any means, but it wasn&#039;t even Tang at all.  Whatever flavor a drink called Tang might take, it is pretty specific about whether or not the flavor should be tangy.  Without that tang, you&#039;re just drinking orange Koolaide.  Simply put, Hi-Nutrition Tang has no tang.  That being said, it&#039;s not bad.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;As stated before, Hi-Nutrition Tang includes an emulsifier, to help it dissolve with the water.  Since other drink products don&#039;t contain such emulsifiers, I was curious as to why Hi-Nutrition Tang does.  My theory is that, in order to more acurately represent the &quot;Mangga Flavor,&quot; the creators added an agent that would give the liquid that tropical feel.  It&#039;s difficult to describe, but there&#039;s a certain &lt;i&gt;thickness&lt;/i&gt; to Hi-Nutrition Tang.  The flavor is very subdued (last on the list of ingredients, even), and it almost has more of the texture of real juice to Tang.  Juice texture works out fine for juice, but I just don&#039;t know if it works out for the H-NT.  It really does taste like I figure &quot;Mangga&quot; tastes like, but the general lack of &quot;tang&quot; left me unsatisfied.  I feel like every &lt;i&gt;other&lt;/i&gt; sip is delicious, which is an odd sensation.  In the end, H-NT is just not delicious enough to make the $2.79 price tag for only Panging 4 Litros.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I have one last observation to say about the Hi-Nutrition Tang.  The package containing the powder is one of the worst things ever.  There is no way to properly position the package that won&#039;t lead to powder somehow falling out of it all over my desk.  As I type this, I&#039;m trying to think of a way to clean this bit of Tang powder from my desk without getting it inside my keyboard and computer.  The bottom of the package is not made to stand upon, so it&#039;s impossible to just stand the the thing up without it falling and shooting a large cloud of powder all over whatever poor victim happens to be in that direction.  It pangs ng large mess.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Unfortunatly, it would seem that the quest for the True Tang will continue another day.  It was refreshing to have some Tang without Splenda for a change, but Hi-Nutrition Tang was ultimately unsuccessful at filling that void in my soul.  It looks like the Kraft Boycott is still on.&lt;/p&gt;

