data.text:
&lt;p&gt;I had this idea today:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I was standing in Discount Den, a local convenience store, waiting in line to pay for the large cup of Dr. Pepper that was about to be my fix for the day.  The infectious, ear-splitting Aphex Twin acid was pumping directly into my brain, loud enough for most of the inhabitants of the store to hear.  I often hope that someone will recognize the endless, insanely complex drum loops AFX does so well, and strike up a conversation.  No dice today, I&#039;m afraid.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It was hard for me to not notice that the girl standing in front of me in line is one of the most gorgeous women on the face of the planet.  That is an important addition to the story simply because she served as the catalyst for my idea, not necessarily because I think beautiful women should be treated differently.  It is simply a vastly interesting aspect of this universe that extremely gorgeous women happen to catalyze the highest levels of creativity.  Perhaps this reaction in my brain was catalyzed in such a fashion, perhaps not, but nevertheless, as a matter of literary description, the person standing in front of me was breathtaking.  I don&#039;t even remember anything specific about her.  She just had the general air of someone who is interesting and truly beautiful in every way that counts.   She was getting a tube of chap-stick when I entered the line behind her.  The pure efficiency of her &quot;enter the line, then get the things you need&quot; game plan was what probably attracted me to her in the first place.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;She had one earbud in her left ear.  Her head was turned toward the chap-stick, minor pain killer, and contraceptive section, which placed her right ear - the one without a headphone - toward me.  I was praying to every possible god that she would recognize the Aphex Twin I was listening to and further prove herself to be the most attractive woman alive.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;She didn&#039;t.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;If I was anybody else on the planet I would have been able to talk to her.  I would have said &quot;nice day for chapstick,&quot; or &quot;nice weather we&#039;re having,&quot; or even &quot;you&#039;re the most beautiful woman I&#039;ve ever seen.&quot;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I didn&#039;t.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Instead, we both did what everyone else in the store was doing.  We filed on, quietly and patiently awaiting our turn at the registers, trying to ignore the guy standing behind me talking on his cellular phone at an obnoxious volume.  &quot;Oh, they&#039;re having sex tonight?&quot; he cooed.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;If I was anybody else on the planet I would have told the guy off, thereby impressing the gorgeous girl in front of me, and saving the world once again from the perils of people who don&#039;t know how to behave in public situations.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I didn&#039;t do that, either.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Instead, I waited patiently for my turn.  Finally the girl in front of me and I both made it to the registers.  This particular establishment has two such systems, allowing twice the flow of a similar, but less equipped store.  It just happened that the two registers, and the two partially-punk clerks standing behind them became available at the same time.  The gorgeous girl and I quietly (except for the AFX) went up to the plate.  I had my giant cup of Dr. Pepper, and she had her extremely efficient chapstick.  She quickly asked her clerk to give her a particular pack of clove-cigarettes, another trait that did nothing but add allure to her already divine appearance.  It was around this point that I came up with my idea.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;What I thought was nothing new, but as a foolish young man with an impossible insta-crush on a gorgeous girl I&#039;d never met, I thought I was a genius.  The partially-punk clerk standing at register number one asked me if the drink I was carrying was all I had.  I paused for a few insanely complex drum loops, and responded with the affirmative.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;If I only had a few more moments, a few more insanely complex drum loops to compose myself, I would not have nodded at my partially-punk clerk.  &quot;Why, no it isn&#039;t,&quot; I would have said, &quot;I&#039;m also paying for her.&quot;  I would have made a quick nod to the gorgeous girl, who was waiting for her partially-punk clerk to get her the particular brand of clove-cigarettes she asked for.  I would have added the gorgeous girl&#039;s items to my charge, and I would have paid for them with a smile.  &quot;Don&#039;t even worry about it,&quot; I would have told her, &quot;I just want to do a nice thing for a pretty girl.&quot;  I would have been on my way, feeling like the nice kind of guy, the self-less kind of guy, and also the outrageously nervous, heart&#039;s-about-to-explode kind of guy.  I would have maybe introduced myself, and then I might have had a name to put with the gorgeous girl, instead of just &quot;gorgeous girl.&quot;  I might have done all of those things.  I wouldn&#039;t even have needed to be anybody else on the planet to do all of those things.  I had all that inside me, and I was completely determined and ready to do it.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;But I didn&#039;t.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I panicked, gave the nod to my clerk, paid extremely fast, and got out of the place as fast as I could.  I almost turned around and went right back in, ready to say &quot;actually, I&#039;m going to pay for hers, too.&quot;  But I still didn&#039;t.  You could, quite accurately, say that I unarguably and unequivocally manned down.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;However, the experience was not a total loss.  I thought about the idea as I was hiding somewhere afterwards, and I definitely think it could be a very good one.  Not to pick up women, although that would certainly be a nice bonus, but just to add a bit of kindness to an otherwise cruel and &quot;boner-killing&quot; world.  Imagine a world where people do that sort of thing all the time.  Wouldn&#039;t you be more excited about going out and socializing if things like that happened all the time?  Why would we hide behind our earbuds and our Aphex Twin if we knew the world wasn&#039;t so cruel after all?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;My friends, I invite you to get out there and do something nice for someone.  It could be the gorgeous girl you see at Discount Den, or it could be an elderly woman who is having trouble carrying her groceries.  Open a door for someone who has their hands full.  Tell someone they look nice today.  Bring the person who has been outside handing out fliers all day a bottle of water.  Talk on your cellphone more quietly, or even consider turning it off sometimes.  Humor someone, tell a stranger a joke, or just smile every once in a while.  Do it enough, get other people doing it, and eventually it won&#039;t be a task anymore.  Eventually, it will just be one huge friendly society.  It may be a stupid idea, and I&#039;ll probably just get my boner killed in a very short amount of time, but it could also work.  It won&#039;t kill us.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;We could, dare I say it, &lt;i&gt;change the world!&lt;/i&gt;  Haven&#039;t you wanted to change the world?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;If anybody has any thoughts, comments, or experiences with this idea, that&#039;s what the comments box down below is for.  Just please try not to kill my boner too hard.  Also, I&#039;m sorry for using such a vulgar term like &quot;boner-killer.&quot;  It&#039;s just a term I use to describe something that is an extreme emotional let-down, except that it flows off the tongue easier than &quot;extreme emotional let-down.&quot;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Here&#039;s my Windows Vista tip of the day.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Open Windows Explorer.  That&#039;s [Windows Key]+[E] if you were unaware.  Now look on the left-hand side of the window.  See &quot;Favorite Links&quot; there?  Have you ever wanted to change those links?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;You can.  It&#039;s really simple.  Windows XP users might not even attept to change them, because XP forced users to stick with whatever folders were there by default.  Sure you could change them, but it involved complicated forays into the registry, which is something most people are not comfortable with.  However, Windows Vista allows you to put whatever you want into your Favorite Links.  Here&#039;s how.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;There&#039;s two ways to do it.  One is easy, and the other is really easy.  First, navigate to your User Folder.  That should be right under &quot;Desktop&quot; under &quot;Folders&quot; on the left side of Windows Explorer.  Next, go into your Links folder.  There they are, the shortcuts that appear in the Favorite Links panel.  Open a second Explorer window, and navigate to whatever location you want.  Click the right mouse button on whatever folder you want to send to the Links, and while holding the right mouse button down, drag it to the Links folder.  Release the right mouse button and click &quot;Place Shortcut Here.&quot;  You&#039;ve done it.  The easier way is to just drag folders or other shortcuts directly to the Favorite Links panel in Windows Explorer.  Give it a try, it&#039;s fun and it increases productivity surprisingly well.  I have a link to Downloads, Videos, Documents, and Program Files (x86) in mine.  Unfortunately, you can only put shortcuts to folders there, so you can&#039;t add your most common programs to the list.  You can resize the Favorite Links panel, though, to accommodate additional shortcuts.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;That does it for today.  Keep using that Vista, and you&#039;ll be doing things you never even dreamed of in no time, such as actually liking Windows Vista.&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

