data.text:
&lt;p&gt;Hello everyone.  I&#039;ve finally finished the Crazy Monkeys&#039; website (to a point where it can be viewed, at least).  Please please, everyone who exists on this planet, take a look at the site, and let me know what you think!  The exclamation mark was to emphasize the importance of that command.  Please let me know if something doesn&#039;t work right for you, if you can&#039;t find something, or you think something should be changed.  I will be adding many things (both secret and non-secret) to the site over the coming forever, so any feedback you give me will most likely be implemented.  I worked really hard over the last couple weeks to get this site up, and I think it&#039;s the best website the Crazy Monkeys have ever had.  Please leave your feedback in comment form on this post.  Thank you.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.thecrazymonkeys.com&quot;&gt;http://www.thecrazymonkeys.com&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Valve software (the creators of the &lt;i&gt;Half Life&lt;/i&gt; computer games) is going to release a new collection of games on October 9th.  They have these three games, each extremely interesting, and they decided (brilliantly) to release them all at once, in the same package.  It&#039;s called &lt;i&gt;The Orange Box&lt;/i&gt;, and it&#039;s one of the most highly anticipated games of the year (move over, &lt;i&gt;Halo 3&lt;/i&gt;).  The three games are &lt;i&gt;Half Life 2: Episode 2&lt;/i&gt;, &lt;i&gt;Portal&lt;/i&gt;, and &lt;i&gt;Team Fortress 2&lt;/i&gt;.  The new chapter of Half Life is a really big deal, because it has all the excitement and emotional attachment of &lt;i&gt;Lost&lt;/i&gt;, &lt;i&gt;Heroes&lt;/i&gt;, and &lt;i&gt;Grey&#039;s Anatomy&lt;/i&gt;.  Seriously, this one is a big deal.  &lt;i&gt;Portal&lt;/i&gt; is a very intriguing pseudo-puzzle game, which you really have to see to properly understand.  You can Google it if you wish.  Finally, &lt;i&gt;Team Fortress 2&lt;/i&gt; is a multiplayer game with such unique art design and production qualities that it really stands above all other multiplayer games.  I&#039;m not a huge fan of the online experience, but I&#039;ve been playing &lt;i&gt;Team Fortress 2&lt;/i&gt; more in the last week or so than any other game I&#039;ve had in quite a while.  Valve decided to release a &quot;beta&quot; version of &lt;i&gt;Team Fortress 2&lt;/i&gt; ahead of the other two games in the package, just to give the thousands of people who bought the game already something to do.  I am one of those people.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So here is my list of ten things I like about &lt;i&gt;Team Fortress 2&lt;/i&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
&lt;li&gt;The game is extremely easy for beginners to pick up.  The game has nine different classes (which changes your appearance, skills, and weapons), and they each have their own pros and cons.  Each class supports a different play style, so if you aren&#039;t comfortable with running around and shooting people, you don&#039;t necessarily have to.  This allows new players to warm up to the more complex game mechanics by starting off with some of the easier classes.&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt;The game is instantly recognizable.  Nobody can look at a screenshot of &lt;i&gt;Team Fortress 2&lt;/i&gt;, and confuse it with a different game.  Just look at some pictures of it on Google, and you&#039;ll see what I mean.  It&#039;s gorgeous.&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt;The game is simple, but not too simple.  It is very easy to know exactly what you need to do and what the general situation is, but it&#039;s not boring.  There&#039;s plenty to think about without being overwhelmed.&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt;The game is meticulously designed.  Absolutely every aspect of the design is painstakingly thought out, to ensure that nothing detracts from the experience.  Valve playtests all of their games thoroughly, so that they see exactly how players react to specific aspects.  This means that every single rock, piece of wood, building, and map is in the most perfect location to ensure balanced and fair play.  The game only has a handful of maps, because they are so meticulously poured over.&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt;The game hardly gets old.  Sure, the novelty of the amazing graphics wears off a little bit, but the game itself does not get boring as you get used to it.  If you&#039;re sick of a certain class, or you just can&#039;t seem to get anything done, you have eight other classes to choose from.  Simply switch classes, and it&#039;s like you&#039;re playing an entirely different game.&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt;The game has commentary.  Just like a DVD, you can load up a special version of a few levels and listen to the developers talk about the game and the processes involved with designing it.  This is an extraordinary addition, which allows you to see just how much thought went into it.&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt;The game is on Steam.  There has been much argument over whether Steam is good or bad.  However, having the ability to instantly join your friends in a game (even when you&#039;re not in the game at all), and the automatic updating system is a very good thing.&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt;The game is fun.  Even when everything is working, and 24 players are all shooting rockets at each other, and you&#039;re losing, and you can&#039;t seem to get anything accomplished, the game is still pretty fun.  Sure it&#039;s challenging, and it makes you think, but it is also fun, which is important.&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt;The game promotes camaraderie.  I can easily recognize other guys on my team, and after a while I can really develop a bond with them.  I really enjoy helping guys who have helped me out, and it is very motivating to know exactly who keeps scoring kills against me.  This is the strength of an online game, because all of the other players are human.&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt;The game has incredible detail.  I&#039;ve played it for 20+ hours over the last week and a half, and I&#039;m still finding new things in the levels and characters.  All of the different classes yell out taunts and other phrases, and it&#039;s a really great feeling to do something really awesome and hear your character yelling out his approval.  Each level has hundreds of little secret nooks and crannies, which will take years to fully explore (especially while people are shooting at you).&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;/ol&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I know that many of you are excited to see the video from Crazy Monkey shows on their &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.thecrazymonkeys.com&quot;&gt;website&lt;/a&gt;.  Get ready to be surprised.  Are you ready?  I&#039;m the person who puts that video online!  Isn&#039;t that surprising??  I knew it would be.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Anyway, as a treat to purveyors of the Crazy Monkey website, I thought I&#039;d let you all in on the routine that I go through to get ready for, perform in, and produce video of every Crazy Monkey show!  Now you will all know my high-tech, patent pending secrets.  Prepare your mind to be BLOWN.  At the very least, I&#039;m making all of this up, so hopefully it will be partially amusing to you.&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;See the routine here!&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;As a treat to purveyors of the Crazy Monkey website, I thought I&#039;d let you all in on the routine that I go through to get ready for, perform in, and produce video of every Crazy Monkey show!  Now you will all know my high-tech, patent pending secrets.  Prepare your mind to be BLOWN.  At the very least, I&#039;m making all of this up, so hopefully it will be partially amusing to you.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Here is the breakdown, in order of operation.  Use this list of procedures in your own life to get the most out of whatever, blah, blah, etc.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;FURTHER ADO.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;

&lt;li&gt;Get up the &lt;strike&gt;morning&lt;/strike&gt; afternoon of the Crazy Monkey show and eat a grilled cheese sandwich, made in Andrew Monkey&#039;s sandwich maker.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Pat Sherman.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Remember that you have to turn in a paper today in one of your classes; decide not to skip it after all.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Throw on some clothes, grab jacket, put an Aphex Twin track on MP3 player, and hop on bike.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;If you almost get hit by less than three cars on your way to campus, you&#039;re having a boring day.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Get to class and turn in paper.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Get home, open Adobe Dreamweaver.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Spend three hours writing a javascript function that loads up a secret page talking about -I don&#039;t know- lungfish, or something, on the Crazy Monkey website.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Make a grilled cheese sandwich for lunch.  Get 32oz. Dr. Pepper from the Discount Den ($.55).&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Return home, and Greet John Monkey, who has just woken up on couch.  He is still hanging out at the apartment, where he has been since Crazy Monkey Practice on Tuesday.  Help him find his pants.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Pat Sherman.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Suddenly remember that you have to pick up the camera and tripod that you had on reserve in the lab.  Finish grilled cheese sandwich (lunch), queue up more Aphex Twin, and hop back on bike.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Almost get hit by three more cars (give or take a few).&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Get the camera and tripod.  Sign the check-out contract as &quot;Harland W. Fankboner, esq.&quot;  Inquire about steam locomotives.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Strap Backpack, Photography Camera Bag, Video Camera Bag, and Tripod Bag to self, being careful to balance them for maximum balance on bike.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Ride home, with traffic, despite being weighted down by tens of pounds of equipment, gear and video game magazines.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Get home, greet Andrew Monkey, who has started playing Team Fortress 2.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Start playing Team Fortress 2.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Load a server playing either ctf_2fort or cp_hydro.  Play as Scout for a while, but get fed up with dying so much and switch to heavy.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Complain about always having to play Heavy, because nobody else ever plays Heavy.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Keep track of dudes in your basement.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Get bored with Team Fortress, and quit.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Pat Sherman.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Load up this week&#039;s episode of &lt;i&gt;My Name is Earl&lt;/i&gt; and watch it, hoping that Andrew and John Monkeys will validate your existence by finding the show you like funny.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Cook two more grilled cheese sandwiches.  Eat them.  Buy can of Dr. Pepper from pop machine outside.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Realize that show starts in an hour, decide it&#039;s time to start getting ready to go.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Put on lucky pants, lucky shirt that your mom made for you, lucky suspenders, and have Andrew Monkey tie bow tie for you.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Grab camera, video camera, extra tapes, primary tapes, email list clipboards, monkey binder, briefcase, extra grilled cheese sandwich, can of Dr. Pepper, shoes, hat, wrist bands that make you look really sweet, phone, MP3 player, and John.  Pile into Andrew Monkey&#039;s car.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Drive two blocks, remember that you forgot tripod.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Drive back, get tripod.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Pat Sherman&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Drive three blocks to campus, park in parking garage.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Grab all things, go to Matthew&#039;s Hall.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Set up camera, discuss and plan setlist for the show.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Watch newbies set up banner.  Say, &quot;Look at banner, Michael!&quot; to Mike Monkey.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Argue that since parents are going to be there, you should be considered for the best stuff.  Actually, you&#039;re just trying to impress pretty girl who said she was coming to show.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Check self in mirror, making sure you look extra-awesome for pretty girl.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Warm up for show, pretending to do yoga or something so you look like you&#039;re serious about craft.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Group warmup time.  Get in a circle with others, say only prime numbers when trying to count to 20 as a group.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;In bibbity-bibbity-bop, call Stonehenge on everyone at once.  That&#039;s always good for a laugh.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Do show, trying to look extra awesome and hilarious for pretty girl.  Actually, look ridiculous and dankly.  Begin to wish you had actually warmed up.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Say really funny thing, without realizing it, and make it look like you meant to do that.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Play Evil Twin (as the evil twin), try not to threaten to rape anyone, but accidentally threaten it anyway, since you can&#039;t think of anything more evil to do.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;End show.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Stand at front doors of Matthew&#039;s hall, thanking everyone for coming out.  Search through crowd for pretty girl.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Suddenly realize that pretty girl has come up to you to congratulate you.  Freeze up, and don&#039;t think of anything good to say, even though you&#039;re an improv comedian.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Go back inside, watch as newbies take down Banner.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Collect camera and tripod, making sure tapes are kept in safe place.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Return to apartment, to hang out with Monkeys and watch them drink beer.  Drink 2 liter of Dr. Pepper, which you got at liquor store.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Brag about how pretty girl talked to you.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Eat celebratory grilled cheese sandwich.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Go to bed.&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Ok, that&#039;s the end of day one.  In the near future, I&#039;ll continue the saga and go through days 2-5 as I explain the process of capturing, editing, and uploading the video to the website.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This is all satirical and fictional, for those of you who may not have noticed, so it shouldn&#039;t be taken seriously.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;As promised, here is the continuation of my Crazy Monkey show routine.  I know it&#039;s been a while, and I&#039;m sorry.  Just calm down already, you horde of glorious fans.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Again, in order of operation, my routine for dealing with video of the Crazy Monkeys shows.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Get up at the crack of 2:30 PM.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Try to remember which person&#039;s bag or briefcase you stashed the all-important tapes into.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Realize it was in your own bag, the one the video camera was in.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Sit down at computer, grilled cheese sandwich in hand, and connect the HDV camera via Firewire.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Open Adobe Premiere CS3, and load the Monkey_HD project file.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Turn on camera.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Start the capture system by hitting F5.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Enter appropriately useless but still hilarious names for the tape and the video clip in Premiere (I like to go with a &quot;named after prehistoric mammals&quot; motif, but you can name them whatever you want.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Click &quot;capture tape.&quot;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Begin the one hour wait for the tape to capture.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;After fifteen minutes, finally decide that it won&#039;t hurt anything if you surf the internet while it&#039;s capturing.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Stumble upon a delightful picture of a cat in a pose that makes it look kind of human almost.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Play either &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.eyezmaze.com/eyezblog_en/blog/2004/05/tontie_ver1.html#monster&quot;&gt;Eyezmaze&#039;s delightful Tontie version 1&lt;/a&gt; or &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.candystand.com/play.do?id=18047&quot;&gt;Vector TD&lt;/a&gt; for a while, until the harder levels piss you off.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Notice that the tape has finished, fifteen minutes ago.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Return to Premiere and try to stop the capture.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Realize that the timecode stopped at about four minutes.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Wait for Premiere to respond, get fed up and close it through task manager.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Check the file that Premiere supposedly captured to.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Delete the broken and incorrect file that Premiere for some reason decided to create instead of the hour of video you tried to capture.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Repeat the last steps, starting with &quot;Open Adobe Premiere CS3.&quot;  Yes, repeat all steps, including this one.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Finally get fed up with crappy computer; fight the urge to throw it at something.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Gather up the camera, the tapes, the tripod, your external hard drive, MP3 player, a couple grilled cheese sandwiches, and headphones and hop on your bike to the underground library.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Descend into the depths of the DLC lab, thousands of feet below the surface of the earth.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Queue up plenty of Aphex Twin on MP3 player.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Wait for twenty minutes for a computer to open up.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Sit down, situate self, and log in.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Connect the camera. Start up Adobe Premiere CS3.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Leave the lab, get cup of coffee, browse some magazines, eat a donut or two.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Return to the lab.  Premiere should be just starting up now.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Turn on the camera, activate the capture system by hitting F5.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Name the tape and the clip something just as hilarious as before.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Capture the tape.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Do various things to amuse yourself, including browsing the internet, looking around at other people in the lab, and . . . well, that&#039;s about all there is to do.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Finally, after an excruciating 45 minutes, stop the capture and save the file.  Check it to make sure it works.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Repeat the last five steps for the other three tapes you have that you need to capture.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Once you&#039;re all done capturing the video, and you have 30 gigabytes of video, you have to copy it to your external hard drive.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Plug in the external hard drive.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;For some reason, the computer can&#039;t copy anything to your external hard drive.  Discover a sinking feeling in the pit of your stomache.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Go to the front desk and ask to rent an external hard drive, hoping they aren&#039;t out yet.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Get the last drive, and bring it back to the computer.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;The files won&#039;t copy to it, either.  Rediscover that sinking feeling.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Ask the lab monitors what the flarp.  They tell you that you can&#039;t just copy files to the drive, you have to create folders first.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Return to you desk, particularly flummoxed by this curious restriction.  Create a folder named &quot;giant sloth&quot; and copy the videos to it.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Wait another thirty minutes for the files to copy.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Once they&#039;re done, turn in the camera and the tripod, and take the external hard drive home.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Copy the files to your hard drive, where they should have been hours ago if only the stupid thing worked right.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Where there you go.  That&#039;s the process I go through to get the video of the show on my computer.  Whatever, I&#039;m bored.  Goodbye.&lt;/p&gt;

