data.text:
&lt;p&gt;Merry Christmas.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I just thought I&#039;d share an adventure I had yesterday.  Wind here was terrible, and it was messing with the power lines substantially.  We were getting surges all day.  Everything in the house flicked off and back on many times through the day.  Very surprisingly, my computer was unscathed, a testament to the skilled craftsmanship at work (I built it myself).  My dad&#039;s computer was not nearly as lucky.  One of the power surges killed his computer.  The surge killed it so hard, it damaged his registry somehow, so Windows Vista wouldn&#039;t boot anymore.  It just asked for the Vista installation disk, so that it could repair itself.  The problem was that I left the disk at school, so it was about two hours away.  What to do?  Do we just wait until I get the disk, which could be two weeks?  Do we go out and buy a new copy of Vista, which could be two hundred dollars?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;No, we turn to Bittorrent.  In just a few hours, I downloaded an ISO file of a Windows Vista disk, popped it in Dad&#039;s computer, and he was back in business.  &lt;strong&gt;BitTorrent Saved Christmas&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I currently work as a computer technician in the Agricultural Economics department at Purdue university.  It&#039;s not the most glamorous job in the world, or the most interesting, but it beats working all night at a coffee shop.  I have to work early in the morning, but that means my evenings and weekends are free.  There are certain times, however, when it is totally awesome to have my job.  One of those times happened today.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I arrived this afternoon, and sat down waiting for something to break so I could fix it.  That&#039;s the majority of my job.  One of my bosses came into the tech shop, and asked me if I knew anything about spyware.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&quot;I know a little about it, yes.&quot; I responded.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&quot;Well, one of our faculty is getting a strange error message.  When you have time, could you go up to her office and take a look at it?&quot;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&quot;Sure.&quot;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;No problem, I thought.  I&#039;ll just get a copy of AdAware and HijackThis on my Mr. Blasty, and do a thorough scan and clean of the computer in question.  I went on up to the office, and took at look.  Sure enough, there was the strange error message.  &quot;Warning, your computer is infected by spyware.  Download anti-spiware tools now.&quot; It said.  It definitely looked bogus.  Initially I thought that it was just a pop up, which can happen when you get spyware.  On closer inspection, however, I saw that it wasn&#039;t in a window, and as a result it had no close button.  I logged out of the user&#039;s account, so that I could work in the administrator account.  That&#039;s when I saw what the &quot;warning message&quot; really was.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;As Windows logged out, the warning stayed, centered in the middle of the desktop, even after everything else had closed.  It was a wallpaper.  It was nothing more than a simple desktop background.  AdAware and HijackThis confirmed that there were no questionable files anywhere on the computer.  All I did was search the local disk for &quot;*.jpg&quot; and &quot;*.bmp&quot;.  There it was, &quot;dfdfdhejahdjhiv.bmp&quot; right in the System folder.  I deleted the file, restarted the computer, and it was all back to normal.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Of course, I made up a very technical story about how I had to use a few special pieces of software to find the corrupted programs and remove them safely.  &quot;It was tough, but I was able to get it all fixed up.  These bugs just find their way onto your computer, and there isn&#039;t much you can do to stop them.  Luckily, though, I&#039;m around, and I got it fixed up.&quot;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I was a hero.&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;What a busy day today.  Here&#039;s a simple rundown of what I did today.  I&#039;m only saying, because it&#039;s interesting to me to actually quantify what I do all day.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;7:00 AM - I woke up extremely started by my alarm clock.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;7:30 AM - I arrived at work, ready to be a hero again.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;10:30 AM - I had some downtime while a computer slowly updated itsself, so I did some research for my other job (designing a flash game for a CGT professor).  This was an extremely efficient hour, working two jobs at once.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;11:30 AM - I left work and decided to go to the convenience shop to get some lunch.  I got some trail mix and Dr. Pepper.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;12:00 PM - Class, business law.  It&#039;s more interesting than it sounds, really.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;1:15 PM - Then I went to the underground library, to meet with the other members of &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ara2008.com&quot;&gt;Ara, LLC&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;1:30 PM - The other members arrived, and we found a meeting room to discuss our project.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;2:45 PM - Wrapped up meeting, with some great ideas in mind.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;3:00 PM - Stopped by PAO hall on my way home to try to find Rich Rand.  I hoped not to run into anybody, because I just wanted to get home and get to work on Job #2.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;3:30 PM - Finally arrived home, after 8 hours wondering around taking care of business.  I still had laundry to do, though.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;3:45 PM - Dropped off my stuff, found that Andrew had done the dishes (awesome) and went to the bank to get quarters for laundry.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;4:00 PM - Got $10 in quarters, got back to the apartment.  I grabbed my laundry (about 4 weeks of clothes) and set off for the laundry room.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;4:15 PM - Laundry working, I finally had a moment to sit down, watch an episode of &lt;i&gt;Boston Legal&lt;/i&gt; and have a bowl of soup (my first actual meal of the day).&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;5:00 PM - Switched laundry into dryer.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;5:10 PM - Got to work on Job #2, working up some designs for this flash game intended to keep kids in school.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;6:10 PM - Andrew went to put his laundry into dryers, and I chased after him, in a comical fashion.  I really hope the group of people we passed wondered what the Hell was going on.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;6:15 PM - Gathered up dry clothes.  I commented that this was the first time I&#039;ve ever not had to dry my clothes a second time.  They were nice and dry after round one.  Cue torrential downpour.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;6:20 PM - Andrew ran and got an umbrella for me, and we ran through the unbelievably wet world back to the apartment.  So much for my perfectly dry clothes.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;6:30 PM - Back to work on the designs.  I came up with two pretty good looking ones.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;8:30 PM - I took a break to watch another episode of &lt;i&gt;Boston Legal&lt;/i&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;9:15 PM - Back to work.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;10:30 PM - Andrew was playing Team Fortress 2, and I couldn&#039;t resist.  I fired it up, but our terrible internet dashed my hopes.  The speed here is horrible after about 8.  I wrote yet another furious email to the cable company, asking them to do something about it.  Instead of playing, I ended up just sending a few important emails scheduling a myriad of meetings tomorrow.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;11:15 PM - I decided to write a post about what I did today.  You&#039;re reading that right now.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Sheesh, what a day.  If anybody&#039;s counting, today I worked for nine hours (plus I&#039;m going to try to get another hour or two in before bed), was in class for two, and had meetings and other business for about four.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;What a start to the rest of my life . . .&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

