&lt;p&gt;Oh hey, while I&#039;ve got you here. Remember that &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/content/olds.php?post=00200&quot;&gt;video&lt;/a&gt; I made of Aili McGill, my sister? Well, I made a video of Aili McGill, my sister a few months ago. I decided to put it up for the Digital Cinema Contest this year. I hadn&#039;t worked on anything else this year, and the Documentary category usually goes to the only entrant, and it&#039;s frankly pretty awesome. Anyway, there&#039;s a viewer&#039;s choice award for this thing, so whichever video gets the most hits on youtube wins extra prizes.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;That means that I need everybody to go to the video on youtube (&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CKYF_vVwDc8&quot;&gt;http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CKYF_vVwDc8&lt;/a&gt;) and watch it a bunch of times. Also, tell all of your friends to do that, too. Feel free to make comments on how awesome it is, too. Thanks.&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;There are these two girls in my Physics Lab. They sit in the middle of the room, and their desk faces my desk. As you can probably imagine, I&#039;m pretty bored a lot in Physics Lab, so I spend a lot of time watching them. I just drift off while my lab partner calculates all of the gratuitous calculations, and they happen to be the best thing in the room to look at. Is that creepy? I&#039;m just going to continue as if it&#039;s not.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The thing is, they could be sitting in a room full of actors from the OC (don&#039;t call it that), and they would still be the best thing in the room to look at. They could be sitting in an art gallery, and they would still be . . . anyway you get the idea.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;They&#039;re &lt;em&gt;gorgeous&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Of course I don&#039;t know anything about them, except that they&#039;re friends, &lt;strong title=&quot;This is definitely a class for non-majors&quot;&gt;not physics majors&lt;/strong&gt;, and &lt;em&gt;perfect&lt;/em&gt;. Sure, I&#039;m embellishing a little, just don&#039;t tell them that. Maybe it&#039;s just the content of the class, or the bimbo management students who sit at the next table over from me. Maybe it&#039;s the way the blonde&#039;s golden hair shines in the midday sun, or the brunette&#039;s curt and gentle smile. Maybe it&#039;s just the fact that they are consistently dressed so well for a pointless, 200 level class. Maybe it&#039;s just my nature to fall deeply in like with whomever sits on the other side of the room.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Maybe I&#039;m just a creep.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It occurred to me today, as I watched the blonde walk across the room to get something from the printer, that these will be the last girls I will admire from across a classroom. I&#039;ve done it constantly since I was six, since even before I started wearing two different colored socks every day. I always see a beautiful woman on the other side of the room, think something poetic and sad about how I&#039;ll never meet them, and then move on to the next class. Sometimes I&#039;ve &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/content/olds.php?post=00075&quot;&gt;talked&lt;/a&gt; to them, usually I &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/content/olds.php?post=00176&quot;&gt;do&lt;/a&gt; nothing.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I don&#039;t think it&#039;s really worth talking to people. Of course, here, I&#039;m referring to people in general. They&#039;re never what I hope they are. They can&#039;t live up to the expectations I unconsciously place on them based only on appearances. At best, they&#039;ll give me something to do for a while, and at worst they&#039;ll cause me a considerable amount of pain and hatred. Ninety-nine out of a hundred people you meet will do nothing but frustrate and annoy you (that&#039;s one of Shauvon McGill&#039;s patent-pending laws of life). I don&#039;t like having to talk to people, but since I am a human being, I have to. It turns out that&#039;s ok.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;One out of those hundred times, they&#039;ll change your life.&lt;/em&gt; Somehow that justifies everything.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Anyway, I&#039;ve been doing a lot of &quot;looking back&quot; at the last five years, thinking about what I should take from it all. Since I am an entirely different person than I was five years ago, I guess the answer is &lt;em&gt;everything&lt;/em&gt;. Still, I wonder if these two girls represent my last classroom crush, or my last chance to do the only thing I ever really wanted to do in college. Do I risk ruining the former for the minuscule chance at the latter?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Of course, since there are two of them, it&#039;s only a 1 in 50 chance that they&#039;ll break my heart . . . As if there&#039;s any chance at all that I&#039;ll actually talk to them.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Here&#039;s looking at you, cute Physics Lab girls. You may not be the last girls I admire from the other side of a room, but you&#039;ll be the last girls I admire from the other side of a &lt;em&gt;class&lt;/em&gt;room. Thank you for giving me a reason to go to class.&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I was on the news today. It&#039;s for some comedy show we&#039;re doing this weekend, and it was only like a five minute segment, but it was neat. I was also on the radio, talking to some improv people about this improv show. It got me thinking about jobs. I could totally be a TV news personality. I could totally be a radio personality. That made me think, &lt;em&gt;that WLFI weather girl is really cute&lt;/em&gt;, and also, &lt;em&gt;what other jobs could I do?&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I decided to quantify my prospects with the following handy chart:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/jobs/jobs.jpg&quot; /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It&#039;s all theoretical, at this point, and it&#039;s all just based on things I made up as I was making it, but I think it sums up the job scene pretty well. There is no scientific or mathematical basis for this graph in any way, but there isn&#039;t really in the job world, either, unless you&#039;re a scientist or mathemagician (I should add those to the graph!). I might continue to edit it as time goes on.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;What jobs are in your &quot;fun zone?&quot; What jobs would you consider high on the &quot;Gain&quot; axis? Where would you say the job you have now fits in to the graph? Are you above or below the &quot;line of qualification?&quot;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I suppose if you have a job for a few years, your qualifications will pretty quickly adapt to include that job.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Just something to think about (for me, anyway).&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Being goofy gets you weird stuff.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The Crazy Monkeys are getting t-shirts, so we need a big fat wad of cash to pay for them. We have plenty of money (too much money!) in our BOSO (Business Office for Student Organizations) account, so I went to Schleman hall to get it. It&#039;s our money, right? Apparently, it isn&#039;t. After a short conversation where I tried my best to be hilarious, all I got was a lecture about good accounting practices (I guess the best accounting strategy is not letting people have their own money).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Then I went to Greyhouse to get a cup of hot cocoa because I&#039;m annoyed and I have work to do (which I&#039;m putting off to write this). When I ordered it, the beautiful girl (everyone who works at Greyhouse is freaking gorgeous) behind the register asked if I wanted all of the bits that go on top (some sort of marshmallow fluff and chocolate crumbles). Wanting to be hilarious, I said, &quot;of course, that&#039;s the only reason I&#039;m getting this. If I could just get a cup full of that stuff, that&#039;s all I would get.&quot; I don&#039;t actually want a cup full of that stuff. I ordered a hot cocoa because I wanted a hot cocoa. I only said that because it&#039;s my responsibility as a local celebrity to be hilarious.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Anyway, here I am, drinking my cup which is only half full of cocoa, and half full of marshmallow stuff and hundreds of chocolate crumbles. Also I know more about good accounting practice.&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I&#039;m getting old.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I realized over the weekend that I&#039;m turning 23 in three weeks. That&#039;s &lt;em&gt;old&lt;/em&gt;. 23 is when ages stop mattering so much. What&#039;s the difference between 22 and 23? It&#039;s nowhere near as much as the difference between 20 and 21. Furthermore, I&#039;m noticing myself doing &quot;adult&quot; things more. I&#039;ve found a passing interest in connoisseur beer (if just to humor a couple of my friends). I can no longer drink soda or eat candy before I go to bed, because it will keep me up all night. Foods I had no problem eating before (particularly frozen foods) are disgusting, now.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I went to Lafayette Brewing Company (a bar) with John and Tom the other day, and we weren&#039;t carded. I don&#039;t know if that&#039;s so much a result of me being old or if they just weren&#039;t doing their job, but it was still weird.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I&#039;m not ready to be old, yet. There are too many things I haven&#039;t experienced.&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So, I created a twitter account. I think twitter is retarded, but people have been asking me to embed twitter on other stuff, so I figured I should figure out how to do that. Turns out you can, and I did. So now you can see my twitter feed on the right side of the news page.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;What do you think, five people who read my website? Is micro-blogging a complete waste of time? Why do you think twitter is so huge right now?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Discuss.&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I will soon be leaving the Crazy Monkeys. It&#039;s been a long, fun ride. Along with retiring my leadership and my comedy, I will be retiring my role as Dude-who-designs-most-of-the-fliers. After three years in the group, I&#039;ve designed 19 different fliers. Let&#039;s take a look back, and see where we&#039;ve gone over the years.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Click on any (almost) of the images to see a much larger version, to see the sweet detail in all of these promotional materials.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/FLIERS/FLIERS/2007_1_19.jpg&quot;&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/FLIERS/2007_1_19.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 400px; margin: auto; display: block&quot; /&gt;
&lt;/a&gt;

&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;January, 2007: The first flier I ever made. I did it because we just needed something to go up in the coffee house, so we would only print like two of them. I remember somebody mentioning how terrible this flier was, which made me decide to actually make some good fliers, which started this whole saga.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;br /&gt;

&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/FLIERS/FLIERS/2007_1_31.jpg&quot;&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/FLIERS/2007_1_31.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 400px; margin: auto; display: block&quot; /&gt;
&lt;/a&gt;

&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;January, 2007 (auditions): This time, I wanted to make something flashy, colorful, and dynamic. This is the flier that got John, Tim, Sarah, Tom, and Kaz into the group, so I think it was a successful flier.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;br /&gt;

&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/FLIERS/FLIERS/2007_4_27.jpg&quot;&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/FLIERS/2007_4_27.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 400px; margin: auto; display: block&quot; /&gt;
&lt;/a&gt;

&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;April, 2007: An interesting typographical layout. One of my earliest memories of John was him walking into practice with a few dirty words circled on one of the handbills based on this flier. Can you spot them?&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;br /&gt;

&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/FLIERS/FLIERS/2007_8_31.jpg&quot;&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/FLIERS/2007_8_31.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 400px; margin: auto; display: block&quot; /&gt;
&lt;/a&gt;

&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;August, 2007: This was the first show of the year, and I wanted to start up a graffiti-esque advertising scheme. This flier pretty much became the only outcome. The text and the graphic are too separate.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;br /&gt;

&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/FLIERS/FLIERS/2007_11_3.jpg&quot;&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/FLIERS/2007_11_3.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 400px; margin: auto; display: block&quot; /&gt;
&lt;/a&gt;

&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;November, 2007 (charity show): This turned out to be one of our best shows. Sure, it was too long, but we raised like $250 for Habitat for Humanity and the Timmy Foundation. I really like how the dual logo turned out, but the flier ended up way too busy and cluttered.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;br /&gt;

&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/FLIERS/FLIERS/2007_12_1.jpg&quot;&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/FLIERS/2007_12_1.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 400px; margin: auto; display: block&quot; /&gt;
&lt;/a&gt;

&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;December, 2007 (Big Dog Eat Child): I was in a class about persuasion in advertising, and they said that motion goes a long way to catch the eye. I found a picture that I took which had a lot of motion in it (and also a big dog, to signify the sketch group we did the show with). I think it turned out pretty well.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;br /&gt;

&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/FLIERS/FLIERS/2008_1_18.jpg&quot;&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/FLIERS/2008_1_18.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 400px; margin: auto; display: block&quot; /&gt;
&lt;/a&gt;

&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;January, 2008: On a Saturday Morning,  in my lucid, half asleep state I saw this flier. Note that this is the first appearance of Myriad Pro, and an early iteration of the new logo text. I don&#039;t know why the underscore was there, I guess I thought it looked cool at the time. I&#039;ve always wanted a poster-size version of this one.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;br /&gt;

&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/FLIERS/FLIERS/2008_1_23.jpg&quot;&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/FLIERS/2008_1_23.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 400px; margin: auto; display: block&quot; /&gt;
&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/FLIERS/FLIERS/2008_1_24.jpg&quot;&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/FLIERS/2008_1_24.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 400px; margin: auto; display: block&quot; /&gt;
&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/FLIERS/FLIERS/2008_1_27.jpg&quot;&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/FLIERS/2008_1_27.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 400px; margin: auto; display: block&quot; /&gt;
&lt;/a&gt;

&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;January, 2008 (auditions): I couldn&#039;t decide which picture best suited the slogan I chose for the &#039;08 auditions, so I picked three (they only really count as one flier, though). We ended up using the first and the third one, putting both up all over campus. This flier got Joe and Logan (or Jogan) into the group. Note that the new logo text is fully realized now. I still think that these are very sharp and visually interesting.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;br /&gt;

&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/FLIERS/FLIERS/2008_2_15.jpg&quot;&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/FLIERS/2008_2_15.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 400px; margin: auto; display: block&quot; /&gt;
&lt;/a&gt;

&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;February, 2008: Another abstract modern art whatever for the Village. I think these only went up in the coffee house, so not many of them were printed. I think I joked at the time that this flier (and the rainbow one before it) made me gay. I think this was the last show we ever did at the Village Coffee House.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;br /&gt;

&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/FLIERS/FLIERS/2008_4_19.jpg&quot;&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/FLIERS/2008_4_19.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 400px; margin: auto; display: block&quot; /&gt;
&lt;/a&gt;

&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;April, 2008: For my best friend Andrew Monkey&#039;s last show, I wanted to honor him with this vectorized, 11x17 flier. I used the Scanner Darkly poster next to my desk as inspiration. We printed a full-size poster version of this one, and everyone signed it. Joe&#039;s Mom won it at the show.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;br /&gt;

&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/FLIERS/FLIERS/2008_9_5.jpg&quot;&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/FLIERS/2008_9_5.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 400px; margin: auto; display: block&quot; /&gt;
&lt;/a&gt;

&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;August, 2008: The first show of the year, and we couldn&#039;t get Matthews Hall. We were stuck in Armstrong (the new building), and it was not great. I decided to go ahead and do what everybody else seems to be obsessed with, and use a grunge theme with lots of paint splatters. Notice that the wall shifts from red to blue to enhance the perspective.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;br /&gt;

&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/FLIERS/FLIERS/2008_10_5.jpg&quot;&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/FLIERS/2008_10_5.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 400px; margin: auto; display: block&quot; /&gt;
&lt;/a&gt;

&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;October, 2008 (auditions): We needed girls in the group, so I wanted to use a flowery, girly graphic to attract some. I made a certificate at work which they ended up not using (lame), but I didn&#039;t want it to go to waste so I turned it into this flier (sweet). The picture is from my parents&#039; new woods. Notice the reference to Harland Fankboner and Lookit the Tiny Monkey. This flier got Kelsey, Lauren, Matt, and Eli in to the group, so it was partially successful at getting girls (actually, it tripled the number of girls in the group, so that&#039;s a big win).&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;hr /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;At this point, I officially released the new Crazy Monkey logo. I made a new logo for the group for a few reasons. First, I wanted to make an impact and make sure that they never forget me (until someone else re-designs it). Second, and more important, I wanted a logo that was less phallic, arthritic, and hard to draw. The new logo can easily be sketched on a chalkboard or sidewalk. Also, I think it&#039;s neat that the new logo has the letters &quot;C&quot; and &quot;M&quot; in it.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;br /&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/FLIERS/logo_reg.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 400px; margin: auto; display: block&quot; /&gt;

&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Do you see them?&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Anyway, with the new logo, I threw together some promotional materials for it. Let&#039;s take a break from the fliers for a moment to see some of these graphics.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;br /&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/FLIERS/teaser1.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 400px; margin: auto; display: block&quot; /&gt;

&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The first teaser graphic, which I think was the picture on our facebook page for a while.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;br /&gt;

&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/FLIERS/FLIERS/alley.jpg&quot;&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/FLIERS/alley.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 400px; margin: auto; display: block&quot; /&gt;
&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/FLIERS/FLIERS/forbes.jpg&quot;&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/FLIERS/forbes.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 400px; margin: auto; display: block&quot; /&gt;
&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/FLIERS/FLIERS/logo_desktop.jpg&quot;&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/FLIERS/logo_desktop.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 400px; margin: auto; display: block&quot; /&gt;
&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/FLIERS/FLIERS/rendering.jpg&quot;&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/FLIERS/rendering.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 400px; margin: auto; display: block&quot; /&gt;
&lt;/a&gt;

&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;A series of images I made and didn&#039;t use in any way. I wished that there was a big media buzz over the new logo, but nobody really cared. I guess these images can stand as a memorial to October, 2008, which wasn&#039;t bad. I did the first three in Photoshop, and the last one in Maya. The middle one was from a photoshoot we did to finally get a group photo which was immediately invalidated by getting a bunch of new members. Devotees might recognize the alley shot from my photo series I made a while back.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;br /&gt;

&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/FLIERS/FLIERS/2008_10_3.jpg&quot;&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/FLIERS/2008_10_3.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 400px; margin: auto; display: block&quot; /&gt;
&lt;/a&gt;

&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;October, 2008: This is the first flier to have the new logo. I don&#039;t really count it as a flier, though, because it&#039;s the same as the one I had for the first show of the year, just with the new logo &quot;spray painted&quot; over it. We wanted to actually spray the new logo over the banner we have of the old logo, but we&#039;ve never been able to because that thing&#039;s huge.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Anyway, once all the buzz over the new logo died down, we got back to doing hilarious improv shows.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;hr /&gt;

&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/FLIERS/FLIERS/2008_11_22.jpg&quot;&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/FLIERS/2008_11_22.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 400px; margin: auto; display: block&quot; /&gt;
&lt;/a&gt;

&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;November, 2008: Another 11x17 flier, because we really wanted to promote the charity show. I really like how this flier turned out, but I was not very impressed with how well the audience turned out. The Ship of Fools told us that they wanted pajamas made out of a material with this pattern on it. I&#039;m inclined to agree with them.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;br /&gt;

&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/FLIERS/FLIERS/2008_12_8.jpg&quot;&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/FLIERS/2008_12_8.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 400px; margin: auto; display: block&quot; /&gt;
&lt;/a&gt;

&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;December, 2008: For Sara&#039;s last show, I wanted to do something somber. It didn&#039;t really turn out that way, and I&#039;m not really a fan of what I ended up with. This was right in the middle of a pretty serious lull in my photography (which I&#039;m only just getting out of now), so I didn&#039;t have much material to work with. I think it was an interesting idea, but it didn&#039;t really work too well. Vienna isn&#039;t a great place to do a show, FYI.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;br /&gt;

&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/FLIERS/FLIERS/2009_1_23.jpg&quot;&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/FLIERS/2009_1_23.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 400px; margin: auto; display: block&quot; /&gt;
&lt;/a&gt;

&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;January, 2009: Then I came back hard. I love this one, and I turned it into a great desktop wallpaper, too (most of these fliers can be downloaded as wallpapers from the monkey website, in the archives). I wanted to prove that I could do shiny gradients and other web 2.0 stuff, and I did just that. This was when I started to realize that the new logo is pretty spindly, though, which I&#039;m not a fan of. I wish the outer border was heavier. By the way, every show we&#039;ve done at Greyhouse has been amazing. The energy in that place is fantastic.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;br /&gt;

&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/FLIERS/FLIERS/2009_3_6.jpg&quot;&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/FLIERS/2009_3_6.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 400px; margin: auto; display: block&quot; /&gt;
&lt;/a&gt;

&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;March, 2009: I had the idea that we should try a show at Hot Box pizza, since we were unable to get Matthews all semester, and Greyhouse books all semester in advance. This show turned out okay, and we absolutely packed the place. This flier has the first actual appearance of the full text + graphic logo. I wish I made the cardboard thing actually look like a pizza box, and not just a weird piece of cardboard. Also, I hope Hot Box doesn&#039;t sue us for stealing their style.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;br /&gt;

&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/FLIERS/FLIERS/2009_4_3.jpg&quot;&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/FLIERS/2009_4_3.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 400px; margin: auto; display: block&quot; /&gt;
&lt;/a&gt;

&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;April, 2009: I had the idea a while ago to do a super-show which would take an entire evening, and feature groups doing shows in venues all over town. We only ended up getting one other group, and toned the plan down from five groups in five hours to three groups in three hours. Then I had the idea that if we did a longform show we would have one of every style of live comedy. This was the best comedy show I will probably ever be a part of. This was also the best weekend of my life.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;br /&gt;

&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/FLIERS/FLIERS/2009_4_18.jpg&quot;&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/FLIERS/2009_4_18.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 400px; margin: auto; display: block&quot; /&gt;
&lt;/a&gt;

&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;April, 2009: We finally got Big Dog down to do another show, so I made another dog-themed flier. I wish I had made it look like stacks of paper instead of cut out of paper, because using red in the background threw off the illusion. Big Dog is probably the coolest group of dudes ever. Our logo kind of looks like crap on the blue background. I wish I had just used a black and white logo.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;br /&gt;

&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/FLIERS/FLIERS/2009_5_1.jpg&quot;&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/FLIERS/2009_5_1.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 400px; margin: auto; display: block&quot; /&gt;
&lt;/a&gt;

&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;May, 2009: The last flier I will make for the last official show I will do with the Crazy Monkeys. Like Andrew&#039;s flier last year, I made an homage to this year&#039;s graduates. I don&#039;t know about Tim or Mike, but the symbolism here for me is that I&#039;m walking to Burning Man. My friend Stephanie helped me tweak the layout a little bit, mainly in the placement of the date, time, and location text. This one&#039;s in vector, so it could be blown up as big as you want and it would still look sweet. Poster?&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So there you have it, all of the fliers I made during my time with the greatest comedy group outside of Chicago.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I hope you&#039;re happy. I&#039;m crying, now.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;If you have talked to me in the last two weeks (or looked at my twitter feed), you&#039;ll know that I just finished up a big group project which didn&#039;t quite go so well. I was stuck with idiots who didn&#039;t do any work. Anyway, I had to write a report explaining how much work we all did and what it was like. I just sent mine to the professor, and hopefully it doesn&#039;t get me in trouble. I&#039;ll show it to you. I know, I kind of rip the two dudes a few new ones. I&#039;m only stating fact, and future potential employers might want to know things like &quot;is completely incompetent&quot; or &quot;incapable of understanding ASP.NET&quot; about a potential hire, and those things don&#039;t usually make it onto resumes.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div style=&quot;width: 500px; display: block; margin: auto&quot;&gt;

&lt;p&gt;To whom it may concern:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I am reasonably convinced that my group, group 3, did the absolute worst project in this class. I have looked at a few of the other groups&#039; work. They&#039;re dynamic, flashy, and interesting. Ours looks terrible, is full of bugs, and in many places doesn&#039;t work at all. That isn&#039;t a great way to start a group project report. I just want to preface the whole process with this disclaimer. It&#039;s unfair, you see, to compare our project to the other groups. It&#039;s unfair because the other groups were actually groups. Group 3 was really only one man.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I did almost all of the work on this project. I say &quot;almost&quot; because there were a few things the other two group members did which I had to completely redo to make it work right. Who put together the entire class structure? I did that. Who made all of the database interaction? I did that, too. Who built the system for displaying a list of questions, showing the answers, and all of the code to add new questions and answers (which essentially was the entire project)? I did all of it. Who wrote the code to generate a tag cloud and dynamically display it on the page? I wrote that code. Who built all of the ASP.NET panels and wrote the code behind file to sort through them all? You guessed it, it was me. In fact, I feel particularly confident that I was the only member of my group who actually knew how to use ASP.NET or C# in any productive way. I&#039;m not sure why I trusted my group members to handle just turning it in. I was out of town that weekend, so I had no choice. The only way I even knew the other two guys existed was because they were ridiculously annoying and incompetent.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Did the group work well together? We absolutely did not. We didn&#039;t work together at all. I did all the work, and the other two guys sat staring at their screens scratching their heads. Did I have any problems with any members of my group? Absolutely I did. They were morons and they didn&#039;t understand anything. If they had told me afterword that they were, in fact, 15, I would not have been surprised in the least.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I&#039;m not sure how to divide the work load. I would say between the two of them, they did maybe 5% of the overall project (if you don&#039;t count the stuff I had to redo because it didn&#039;t work). Considering the site doesn&#039;t even really work, that&#039;s essentially 5% of nothing.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Gabe did the beautiful design. Actually, he just came up with the header; the sidebar was my idea, since we needed a place for, you know, content. He immediately volunteered to design the site, which is something I am still puzzled over. He was preparing his 411 presentation at the time, so obviously he couldn&#039;t actually work on the design for this website until that was over, when all we had time for was the complete pile of trash he came up with.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;David dealt with the database structure; of course I use the term &quot;dealt with&quot; very loosely. As far as I know, he just had a friend of his do all the work. Even with a supposed expert SQL Server guru backing us, I still found things missing from the database structure on a daily basis. David also insisted we work on his personal server, instead of the space provided to us by the class. To say this was an inconvenience would be like saying David himself was merely lazy. I had to use the world&#039;s worst FTP software to manually upload every file I changed, and I  had absolutely no access to the SQL Server database to find all of the things that were missing from it. Ultimately I had to make my own page that just dumped out all of the data because I had no other way to view it. The process was slow, annoying, and unnecessary. The biggest frustration came when David decided that we should go ahead and move everything over to the class server anyway (but I could go ahead and keep working on his if I wanted to). At least he thanked me for all of my work almost constantly.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I worked on this project pretty much straight through for about six days in a row (plus off and on for the two weeks before then). I definitely did more work on this than I did for the first two projects. Unfortunately, it was just too much for one man to finish. I told them I wasn&#039;t going to be able to work on it on Friday evening or Saturday morning, figuring that they could debug anything that wasn&#039;t quite working yet. Of course, that was assuming they knew how ASP.NET worked. I have since checked the site, and of course it&#039;s broken. It worked fine when I stopped working on it on Friday morning, so obviously one of the geniuses thought they could sneak into the garage and start playing around with daddy&#039;s tools. I would be insulted that they even want to keep their names on the thing, but that wouldn&#039;t be fair to them. Sure, I&#039;m responsible for the stuff we got working, but they&#039;re responsible for all the stuff that doesn&#039;t work at all. I guess that entitles them to have equal credit.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;We&#039;re supposed to say what grade we would give ourselves if we were grading this project. I would give us a &quot;D,&quot; but only because I still want to pass. My diploma is riding on this a little bit, so it would suck to not graduate just because I was stuck with some idiots. I know one thing for certain, though. David Auble and Gabe Masters-Jackson should not pass this class. They don&#039;t know the first thing about ASP.NET, and they should not be allowed to think that they do (or make employers think they do, for crying out loud). I&#039;m not trying to throw them under the bus to save my own skin. It&#039;s just that I obviously know what I&#039;m doing, and they obviously don&#039;t. That means they should fail, and I should not.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It should mean that, anyway.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I hope it means that.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Well, cry &quot;havoc&quot; and let slip the dogs of grading. I can only apologize for the terrible site that you&#039;re forced to wade through to grade it. I&#039;m not making any excuses for anything we didn&#039;t get done. I&#039;m just letting you know that it was a miracle we got anything done at all.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;For what it&#039;s worth, you&#039;re by far my favorite professor in CGT. I&#039;m not just saying that. You&#039;re the reason I&#039;m pursuing a career in web development. Thank you, and good luck with the new class you&#039;re teaching next semester. It sounds awesome, and I really wish I could have taken it.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;
Sincerely,&lt;br /&gt;
Shauvon McGill&lt;br /&gt;
smcgill@purdue.edu
&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Let this stand as proof that if I posted it on here I probably meant every single word, because I did, and I do.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I am working on a new design for DenyConformity.com. I think it is going to be really awesome, and I hope you do, too. I want you to see what I&#039;m working on as I&#039;m working on it, because I want to know what you think about it while it is being produced. Please, take a look at my progress and see what you think about the site. Is something annoying? Is something confusing? Is there a feature you have always wished DenyConformity.com had? Please, let me know. I want this to be the best site it can be, and so I need to know what you think of it.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/future/&quot;&gt;See the site here.&lt;/a&gt; At the time of this post (May 12, 2009), it has only been tested and developed for Firefox. I plan on making sure it works in as many browsers as possible (except Konquerer), but for now if you go there with Internet Explorer, don&#039;t expect it to work right (and don&#039;t complain to me that it doesn&#039;t).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Please keep in mind that it is a work in progress, so I&#039;m not interested in hearing if something doesn&#039;t work right or something is broken.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Thanks! I hope you enjoy watching the site come together.&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So I wasn&#039;t sure if I was going to pass my Physics class or not. I didn&#039;t go a lot, and I skipped a lot of stuff. Yeah, that&#039;s not a good plan, but the whole class was so pointless, and I&#039;ve had so much else to worry about over the last few months. I did terribly on the final, and I was really worried about whether or not I would actually get the D I wanted in the class. Obviously if I didn&#039;t, I would have to retake the class, probably over this summer.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Grades were supposedly going up on Wednesday (tomorrow), but I thought I would go see if they were up yet tonight. I wanted to know if this was going to be a pretty bad summer or the worst one ever. As it happens, the grades were posted, and as it happens, I did get the D, after all. You might not be aware, but &quot;D&quot; stands for &quot;Degree.&quot;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;I am a college graduate.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;If only I weren&#039;t so lonely and unmotivated.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;If you were wondering, I got a &quot;B&quot; in my other class, the one I wrote the scathing email to my professor about. I had an A before that project, so it definitely brought me down, but it didn&#039;t hurt me too badly, apparently. I keep running into one of the dudes from my &quot;team&quot; around town, and it&#039;s pretty super awkward.&lt;/p&gt;
