data.text:
&lt;p&gt;I live in Chicago, now.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Something I&#039;m getting used to is having the comic book store considerably farther away. It means I make much less impulse purchasing of cool comics, or I at least have to coordinate them around my once-a-week trip to that part of the neighborhood.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;One of the other difficult things about being a person with only two arms and zero cars in a big city is buying groceries. Of course, the big city does mean I have a few options (although I&#039;m still looking for a great little greek-owned food mart somewhere).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Very recently, a Jewel Osco (the chain of Supermarket here) closed right around the corner from my place while they build a new one. A shiny new Jewel will be opening in the fall of 2010, but that does me little good now. The nearest Jewel is now about seven tenths of a mile away.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Also about seven tenths of a mile away is a cool supermarket called Trader Joe&#039;s. Joe runs a pretty trendy little mart, with lots of organic food and other hipster gear. Hipsters don&#039;t like brand names, so Joe&#039;s got his own. You&#039;re not going to find Nabisco, Kellog&#039;s, or Kraft here (well, you might, but it isn&#039;t as prevalent). Yes, it&#039;s a store without Kraft Foods. My &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/content/olds.php?post=00164&quot;&gt;boycott&lt;/a&gt; just got a lot easier. Joe&#039;s got a whole aisle of this super trendy stuff called &quot;wine.&quot; He may call himself a trader, but he primarily just trades wine for cash. I doubt they would accept an old pair of pants for a box of cereal, or this old hard drive I have laying around for a watermelon. Joe is, in fact, a poor trader.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Closer, at four tenths of a mile, is the nearest CVS pharmacy. I know it&#039;s a pharmacy and not a food-mart-cy, but they have essentials like ice cream, cereal, candy, and more of that &quot;wine&quot; stuff (plus plenty of drugs). Also, they have brand names, which means Oreo cookies. My &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/content/olds.php?post=00164&quot;&gt;boycott&lt;/a&gt; once again meets challenge.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Closer still, at three tenths of a mile, is a store called Whole Foods Market. I think they&#039;re implying that other stores only sell you like eight-tenths of an apple or cheese with extra holes or something. At least they&#039;re upfront about what kind of store they are. Namely, a store kind of store. I&#039;m less tempted to try to barter with them.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;By the way, in case you were wondering, the distance from ol&#039; 248 S. Chauncey #3 (my old apartment) to the Purdue Union was only three tenths of a mile. From 248 S. Chauncey #3 to La Village food mart was only one tenth of a mile. I am now farther from food and other trendy hipster amenities than I used to be.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Being the closest superfoodorium, I went to Whole Foods today to see what it was all about.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It was all about the Benjamins.&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;Read More&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;or Shauvon no longer has any money.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/wholefoods/small_IMAGE_014.jpg&quot; /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I&#039;m sorry about the poor image quality in these photographs. I only had my cell phone with me. I just noticed the Range Rover in the foreground of that picture.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The first thing you notice about Whole Foods is how overwhelmingly full of itself it is. Connoisseur beer piled right inside the front door?  Aisles of organic groceries piled on wooden shelves? Antipasto bar? Accessories like two-bottle rubber wine caddies hanging at the end of aisles? General aroma of fine cheese? This place has it all.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Really, though, once you get used to it, Whole foods is just like any Marsh or Kroger that I&#039;m used to (those are what they call supermarkets back where I&#039;m from, in the middle of nowhere). Just replace the Connoisseur beer with Bud Light, the organic groceries with moth-infested processed corporate human chow, the wooden shelves with monolithic, cold steel, mile-long shelves, the antipasto with cheese wiz, the wine caddies with NFL branded beer cozies, and the fine cheese smell with a mixture of rotting produce and fat sweat, and you&#039;ve got yourself a Kroger.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Obviously I&#039;m exaggerating a little. Sometimes they have Miller High Life.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Seriously, though, I&#039;m much more comfortable at a place like Kroger or Marsh. Probably, I suppose, because I&#039;m used to places like that. The Whole Foods was very new, and like most things I encounter here, wholly terrifying. At one point I realized I was actually lost inside the store. I was lost and scared in a maze of wooden shelves and bland, beige food packages when I began to realize that Whole Foods was an entirely different sort of store. Whole Foods is not a Supermarket. It is, in fact, a &lt;em&gt;Market&lt;/em&gt;, and it makes you wonder just what is so super about a Supermarket. They don&#039;t just have an antipasto bar, they have a place where you can sit, relax, and eat your antipasto (or presumably anything else you bought) right there in the store.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/wholefoods/small_IMAGE_011.jpg&quot; /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The produce and fresh meat selection was extraordinary. Truly, Kroger does not sell ground Bison.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/wholefoods/small_IMAGE_012.jpg&quot; /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;They had cups of fresh berries which looked absolutely unforgettable (in fact, between going there and writing this, I purchased and ate most of one of them, and I can assure you that it was fantastic).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/wholefoods/small_IMAGE_007.jpg&quot; /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Plus, where else can you buy cheese the size of a case of beer?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/wholefoods/small_IMAGE_009.jpg&quot; /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;And just look at the deli section. Everything looked way better than the generic &quot;slop salad&quot; you&#039;d find at any Kroger or Marsh deli.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/wholefoods/small_IMAGE_010.jpg&quot; /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Also, and I didn&#039;t get a picture of this, they have Almond Milk. Yes, it&#039;s pretty much what it sounds like.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Whole Foods certainly seems like the sort of place that is far healthier for you to shop than other, more &quot;super&quot; markets. Sure, Organic food is pretentious (just look at how I have to capitalize it!), but you can&#039;t deny that it at least &lt;em&gt;seems&lt;/em&gt; healthier than all that corporate human-chow. Ultimately, that&#039;s the real point, though. Whole Foods certainly &lt;em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;seems&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/em&gt; like it is a much better place for you to shop. Perhaps it is, but there is definitely a cost for that sense of &quot;super&quot;-iority.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;You see, you&#039;re paying a premium for the sort of place that Whole Foods Market is. When you walk into a place as pretentious as Whole Foods, in your mind you slowly begin to replace the word &quot;pretentious&quot; with &quot;goddamned expensive.&quot; Ultimately, those two things are synonyms. Just how much were those berries? Ten dollars a pound (and each cup was about a pound). Ground Bison is $5.99 a pound. A very small box of (non-Kellog&#039;s) cereal is $3.69. A half-gallon of 2% is $2.39 (some prices aren&#039;t terrible, but you&#039;re not going to find any deals). The Almond Milk is two 30 ounce boxes for $4 (It comes in a juice box thing, and it doesn&#039;t require refrigeration. I&#039;m so intrigued I might have to go back and buy some). A box with two small frozen pizzas is $4.99.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A woman finally asked me why I was taking pictures and notes on my cell phone, so I started to feel bad about not buying anything. I told her I was just interested in the place and wanted to tell my mom about it, so if you aren&#039;t my mom, don&#039;t read this. You hear me? &lt;strong&gt;This article is only for my mom.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Anyway, I went ahead and got a few things that I needed (like milk, bread, frozen pizzas, gluten-free waffles, and fresh fruit). I just got one basket, which turned out to be only one paper grocery bag full of food.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Just one bagful of pretentious, gluten free, organic, delicious, and admittedly cool, food. Any guesses how much the total was?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;$48.11&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Almost $50 for just one bag full of odds and sods (I&#039;ve been watching a lot of British TV). How much food can you buy at Kroger for $50? How much is one basketful of food at Marsh? Certainly not $50. I used to feel bad when a basket of food at La Village (only one tenth of a mile from my home) came to $25. Is the quality of life that Whole Foods allows you worth the added cost? These are not necessarily rhetorical questions.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The other day, I was walking down the alley behind my apartment and was passed by one of my neighbors parking his Audi A6 in his garage next to his Maserati. I suppose he (or the guy with the Range Rover in the picture up above) doesn&#039;t mind spending that much for food (he probably feeds ground Bison to his dog). I don&#039;t know if I&#039;m cool with it, though. I&#039;d rather just buy comic books.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Denyconformity.com is now four years old. Four years ago, I started this website to complain about my boring life. I don&#039;t like keeping a &quot;blog&quot; because I don&#039;t think people really care about my personal problems. I want this site to be an interesting exploration of human culture and a place for me to explore my viewpoint on life. Hopefully my unique perspective is entertaining and insightful to somebody. That is my ultimate goal for this site, to provide something interesting for somebody to read. If I can help someone avoid a bad decision, or brighten someone&#039;s day with my mis-adventures, then I believe this site will be a success.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;With moving to Chicago, I think my life has become considerably more interesting to an outside observer. Every time I told someone I was moving here, they seemed to be somewhat jealous of me and my exploits. Of course, all I felt was extreme fear, but that&#039;s another story. The thing is, I&#039;m not sure what adventures I should try to get in to up here. Therefore, for the next year of my life, and by extension the next year of DenyConformity.com, I want to commission your help. Help me make this site as good as it can be. Let me do the things you&#039;ve always wanted to do, and tell you what it&#039;s like.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I&#039;ll get interesting stories to tell on my website, and you can live vicariously through me, maybe learning a little about adventures you&#039;ve always dreamt of.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So feel free to comment on this post with any ideas, dreams, or goals that you want me to do for you in the next year. No idea is too small, and no adventure is too obscure. I can&#039;t guarantee that I&#039;ll do everything you ask me to (obviously), but I can guarantee that if it won&#039;t get me in too much trouble, I&#039;ll tell you all about it here (with plenty of pictures). Think of it like a to-do list for DenyConformity.com, and for me, Shauvon McGill.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Is there a part of Chicago you&#039;ve always wanted to see? Is there something you&#039;ve always wanted to do but you&#039;ve never quite had the money/time/patience/guts/stamina/desire to do it? Is there something that you think I should do because of who/where I am, or just because you think I should? Perhaps there&#039;s something you want a picture of, or a thing you&#039;ve always heard of that you&#039;d like to know more about. I can help make any of those things happen.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I&#039;m a young man with a sweet life but no goals and no drive. Now you have a chance to get a glimpse of this sweet life, and help me have a reason to get up in the morning. This is also your chance to have a voice in the future of DenyConformity.com.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Thoughts?&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I&#039;m currently trying to get a chance to see a thunderstorm from the top of the building formerly known as the Sears Tower. Someone recently &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/content/news.php?post=00230&quot;&gt;asked&lt;/a&gt; me to try to do this. I&#039;ve made a little progress, and I thought I&#039;d let you know what I&#039;ve discovered so far. I wanted to update you all as soon as possible to let you know that I will, in fact, actually try to do things that you &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/content/news.php?post=00230&quot;&gt;ask&lt;/a&gt; me to do.&lt;/p&gt;


			&lt;p&gt;Read more&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;Is it possible to see a thunderstorm from the top of the Sears Tower?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;To start with, I thought I&#039;d give a little history on the Sears Tower. Of course, you could just go to Wikipedia (which I am doing) and read all you want, but I&#039;ll give you the highlights. The Sears Tower is 108 stories or 1,450 feet tall. It is the tallest building in the United States (and was the tallest in the world for a while). It is currently the fifth tallest phalli - er - &lt;em&gt;structure&lt;/em&gt; in the world. Sears actually lost their naming rights in 2003, but it continued to be called the Sears tower until recently, when some company called Willis something or other bought a bunch of the building and demanded to change the name.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;There are so many groups on Facebook angry about the name change that people have started making groups angry about all the groups angry about the name change. That&#039;s how angry the internet is about the name change. How angry are you?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/willie/willis_facebook.jpg&quot;&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Personally, I think it&#039;s great. I mean, it&#039;s always been a giant willie, so now we can actually call it that.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Anyway, I think it&#039;s interesting that Sears never actually fully utilized the building, leaving it mostly vacant until the mid 90&#039;s, when it was sold it to somebody else. &quot;They&#039;re&quot; also planning on painting it silver, which I suppose would make it much easier to keep cool.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The observation, or &quot;Sky-&quot; deck opened in 1974, and it&#039;s on the 103rd floor of the building. I don&#039;t know who&#039;s office is in the 108th floor, but he&#039;s probably one of the coolest people in the world (let&#039;s face it, it&#039;s almost certainly not a woman). On a clear day, you can see Indiana from the Skydeck. The observation deck in the John Hancock building (which used to be the most phallic name for a building) is 323 feet lower. In January, &quot;they&quot; opened up a few glass bottomed balconies which extend out of the Willis Tower, and give you the sensation that you&#039;re floating 103 stories up. They sound pretty awesome, and I will try to get some pictures of them in the next week or so.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It costs $14.95 for a regular adult ticket to the Skydeck. The deck is open every day from 9 AM to 10 PM. They probably start kicking people out at 9:50, because they&#039;re tired and want to go home. I presume that working at the top of Big Willie would diminish most of the novelty of the thing. I went to the Skydeck once with a school trip at night. It was pretty neat, but I bet on a clear day it would be even more neat.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;But what about during a thunderstorm?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I&#039;ve seen Big Willie completely cloaked in clouds before, and I&#039;m sure when cloud cover is relatively low (in altitude, not quantity) the view isn&#039;t so great. It&#039;s probably still pretty interesting, but you probably can&#039;t even see the ground, let alone Indiana. If atmospheric conditions are just right, though, it certainly would be spectacular to see a thunderstorm from one of those little glass balconies. It seems like it would be quite a show, but it also seems like the sort of thing &quot;they&quot; wouldn&#039;t let you do, for safety reasons.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;My good friend Lili emailed one of &quot;them&quot; and asked if the Skydeck was open during thunderstorms. Mirian Vasquez of Skydeck Chicago responded by saying, &quot;Thank you for your interest in the Skydeck. Guests are definitely allowed on the Skydeck during thunderstorms. The view might not be so great though, since storms bring thick, dark, clouds. I hope this answers your questions!&quot;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Well, thank you, Mirian, that certainly does answer some questions. Apparently it &lt;em&gt;is&lt;/em&gt; possible to see a thunderstorm from the top of the Sears Tower, with a few caveats. First, you can&#039;t go to the &lt;em&gt;top&lt;/em&gt; of the tower, because the Skydeck is on the 103rd floor. Second, you might not actually &lt;em&gt;see&lt;/em&gt; anything, because the tower could be engulfed in clouds. Third, you&#039;ll have to pay $15, and the thunderstorm will have to be before 10PM. Finally, you technically can&#039;t actually see a thunderstorm from the &lt;em&gt;Sears Tower&lt;/em&gt;, because it has been renamed the &lt;em&gt;Willis Tower&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Hopefully that sheds some light on the whole idea, and gives you some insight into what it might actually be like. Only time will tell for sure how well it will actually work out, though. I&#039;ll have to keep my eyes on the forecast. The skies are clear tonight, and for the near future, so we&#039;ll just have to wait for the next big storm . . .&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;If you, like me, appreciate electronic music, then perhaps this might interest you:&lt;/p&gt;

