data.text:
&lt;p&gt;People are throwing around the idea that 2010 is an entirely new decade. This is justifiable. The number 10 has an extra digit, which means it&#039;s not the same as 9. However, another (smaller) group of people claim that 2010 is not the first year of a new decade, but actually the last year of the last (current) one. They claim that there was no &quot;Year Zero&quot; so the decade starts with one instead of zero.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Those people are wrong.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;For a time I agreed that 10 is the last number of the &quot;ones,&quot; and not the first number of the &quot;teens.&quot; This is true, because you don&#039;t start counting with zero. However, time doesn&#039;t work that way. There was, in fact, a year zero.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Consider the following example: when you were born, how old were you? You were not one, you were zero. You had completed zero years of life. On your first birthday, you turn one, which means that you have completed one year of life. However, you are not in the first year of your life, are you? You are in the second year of your life. When you turn ten, you are not entering your tenth year, you are entering your eleventh. When you turn ten, you&#039;ve entered the second decade of your life.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So the debate becomes not what year this is, but when we started counting. Did year one start at the beginning of time, or at the end of the first year of the modern calendar?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Theoretically, the calendar is based on the birth of Jesus Christ (who&#039;s birthday was about a week ago). If that is the case, year one should coincide with Jesus&#039; first birthday, which marks not the beginning of the first year, but the end of the first year. That would make this the end of the 2010th year, and the beginning of the 2011th, or the beginning of the next decade.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;One major problem is that the people who invented the modern 12-month, 365-day (give or take) calendar, were morons. They didn&#039;t understand the concept of zero, so the first year of the calendar is 1, and the year before that was 1 B.C (or negative-one).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;We currently use the Gregorian Calendar, which was an improvement of the Julian Calendar, which was just thought up by some dudes who were bored because nobody had invented video games yet. The problem is that these calendars mainly just describe what a year is, when leap-years are, how many months there are, and other things important to your bank and electric company. However, they kind of gloss over when it all starts.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;You can&#039;t just go from Year Negative-One to Year One. That&#039;s stupid. If the negative years are in fact &quot;Before Christ&quot; there would have to be a year that was Zero Years Before Christ. From the day before He was born to 365 days before He was born, no years had passed. Those 365 days were 0 B.C. Nobody stopped to think about that, though, because in the 1500&#039;s when the Gregorian Calendar was thought up, they were too busy going on Crusades, dying of the Plague, and other things that killed off anybody who questioned the Pope.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Astronomers, on the other hand, do recognize a year zero. In case you were wondering, astronomers are scientists who spend their entire lives studying the motions and natures of the entire goddamn universe. I&#039;m somewhat inclined to believe scientists over old dudes who sit around all day telling ghost stories. We don&#039;t need to get into a theological debate, however, because that&#039;s neither here nor there. Years have to start somewhere, so why not make it an arbitrary dude&#039;s birth way back a long time ago?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;That&#039;s where it gets muddy. You see, it&#039;s not really based on &lt;em&gt;anything&lt;/em&gt;, when you get down to it. Yes, this is 2010, which is two-thousand ten years from &lt;em&gt;something&lt;/em&gt;, presumably something that happened two-thousand ten years ago. But the thing is that that &lt;em&gt;something&lt;/em&gt; was two-thousand ten years from &lt;em&gt;something&lt;/em&gt; else, which was also probably pretty interesting, involving cavemen riding dinosaurs and Brad Pitt beating the crap out of Eric Bana or something. It&#039;s all arbitrary and ultimately completely meaningless. The current year certainly hasn&#039;t measured the entire course of human history, which I think would be a much better scale. What if we could say that it was exactly 12,010 years since Grugg first picked up a big piece of wood, bashed it against Brugg, and then stole his wife, thereby setting a benchmark for all Human Progress from then on? That would be much cooler. Imagine how much we&#039;ve done since that fateful day in Mr. and Mrs. Brugg&#039;s cave? It means as much as anything else.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It&#039;s only 2010 because that&#039;s what we call it. It&#039;s only 1459 in the Armenian calendar. It&#039;s 2960 in the Berber calendar, which sounds &lt;strong&gt;way&lt;/strong&gt; cooler than boring ol&#039; Twenty-Ten. The Byzantine calendar puts us in years 7518 and 7519. These are all just numbers. Random numbers that groups of people have been counting ever since the point that they . . . started counting.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The point is that this &lt;strong&gt;is&lt;/strong&gt; the start of a new decade, because it &lt;strong&gt;has&lt;/strong&gt; been ten years from &lt;em&gt;something.&lt;/em&gt; Who cares if it&#039;s one or zero, or two-thousand ten, or seven thousand five hundred eighteen? We have so few opportunities to celebrate something that marks our progress and achievement as a species that doesn&#039;t involve having murdered someone or coming up with a great new way to sell advertising space. Let&#039;s just take this one, because it is a big deal. It&#039;s a chance to move on from the (myriad) mistakes of the last ten years, and start with a proverbial &quot;clean slate.&quot; We need that every once in a while. In fact, if you celebrated the new Millennium in 2000 (like a normal person), then it &lt;strong&gt;has&lt;/strong&gt; been exactly ten years, so for you it &lt;strong&gt;is&lt;/strong&gt; a whole new decade, no matter what anybody says.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;And another thing: people who talk about how this isn&#039;t a new decade and who still argue that the new Millennium started in 2001 are a bunch of dwonks. They&#039;re mostly the same people who use &quot;win&quot; as a noun (the wrong way) and think cats with zany captions are the greatest thing they&#039;ve seen since their mom reupholstered their basement/bedroom. Don&#039;t listen to them. They just want you to join their World of Warcraft guild or trade some Pokeman cards with them or something.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So wear your head high, noble human. You&#039;re living in a whole new year, a whole new decade, and a whole new life! You have nothing but opportunities ahead of you, a brand new pair of socks or whatever type of clothing your parents got you for Christmas. You may have made some mistakes in the last decade, started a few wars, messed up your economy (which for that matter is also just a bunch of numbers you made up), and gave way too much attention to Paris Hilton, but none of that matters now! You&#039;re a new man (or hu-man), a fresh canvas. Sure, you&#039;ve got that weird rash and a cirrhotic liver, but who cares! Life is your oyster!&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Celebrate the new decade with pride, noble human, and next time someone tries to tell you you&#039;re wrong, just remind them that we&#039;re not in 2010 at all, we&#039;re actually somewhere between 1,262,304,000 and 1,293,839,999 (the Unix time codes spanning the next 365 days). After all, that&#039;s the only time that will really matter when the machines take over.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Oh, and that&#039;s not even getting into all that Mayan calendar malarky that my Mom has repeatedly gone on long rants about. Talk about complicated . . .&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I don&#039;t make many posts on here about computer stuff, and I feel like I should have more. I&#039;ve spent a great deal of time thinking about computers, I have tons of experience working on computers, and I have two computers of my very own. I think I probably have a lot to say that would at the least give you something to think or talk about, and might even improve your life.&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;Well, this is a post about computer stuff.&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;I use Windows on my computers, for numerous reasons which would be the subject of an entirely different post (or several). Although Windows became more secure all the time as we went through the last decade, and I have always been a very safe and responsible computer user, it is still a good idea to use additional security on my system. Apple Computer Company wants you to think that by just turning on a Windows computer without an antivirus program you will soon die of H1N1. This is not remotely true. Especially with Windows 7 (possibly the greatest computer operating system ever made), you can safely connect your computer to the internet (through a firewall-equipped router, of course) without an antivirus and you will be fine. Just don&#039;t be a knucklehead about it. Don&#039;t go to shady websites, do use Firefox with Adblock Plus, don&#039;t install anything (&lt;em&gt;anything&lt;/em&gt;) unless it&#039;s from a trusted source and you know exactly what it is, and do be careful with spam emails. Do these things, and you can live virus and spyware free (most likely, anyway).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Should you get that handy registry-fixer program you found on download.com? No. How about Super PC Cleaner 2.0? Absolutely not! If you&#039;re not sure what it is, don&#039;t install it. Really, if you&#039;re not a &quot;power user&quot; and it isn&#039;t the Firefox installer (downloaded directly from Mozilla.com), don&#039;t download it. You don&#039;t need special utilities to keep Windows running properly, especially if you have Vista or 7. You don&#039;t need that zany screensaver. You don&#039;t need that goofy theme that makes the mouse cursor into a little dancing penguin. Just don&#039;t do it.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;What you do need is an antivirus program. Ok, so you don&#039;t really need one, sure, but if you&#039;re not a genius like me, it&#039;s probably a good idea. The problem is that companies like Symantec and McAfee want you to pay them tons of money (rather frequently, if they have their way) to use their products. You shouldn&#039;t have to spend tons of money for something you shouldn&#039;t ever need. Luckily, you don&#039;t have to, because free options are available.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I&#039;ve used free antiviruses off and on for years. Purdue offered a free version of McAfee to Purdue students, and I used it some. McAfee sucks, though. You could try a program called AVG Antivirus, which is offered in a stripped-down free version. It works ok, but it gets rather obnoxious about telling you that you can give them money for a copy of the program you&#039;re already using. Another option is Avast! Antivirus, which wins the prize for most exciting name for what is ultimately an extremely boring product. I&#039;ve noticed that Avast! uses an unnecessary amount of system resources and frankly does too much. For spyware protection, you have programs like AdAware, which only runs when you ask it to. Having a scanner like that &quot;on call&quot; is good and bad, but it still isn&#039;t really an antivirus so whatever. There just isn&#039;t a good solution, anymore. I began to think that perhaps the ship had sailed, and just like the dream of being able to say things on Twitter and Facebook without my parents seeing it, the dream of a free antivirus was dead.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Then I found the solution, and - here&#039;s the kicker - it was made by Microsoft.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Welcome back. I hope you didn&#039;t hit your head when you passed out. Yes, I know it&#039;s crazy news to hear that not only has Microsoft (a multi-billion dollar corporation) made an operating system that works fine without having to install any free utilities advertised by banner ads on your favorite porn websites, but they have also created a pretty good antivirus for it. You see, Microsoft is not the same Microsoft that we all loved to hate last decade. They actually asked people how Windows 7 was before they released it, and now they&#039;re actually protecting it from all those viruses Apple wants you to think are out there. That&#039;s what a company does that actually cares.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It&#039;s called Microsoft Security Essentials, and it&#039;s available for XP, Vista, and 7, in both 32 and 64 bit versions. You can download it on &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.microsoft.com/Security_Essentials/&quot;&gt;this page&lt;/a&gt;. Before you install it, you should (this is important) shut down and remove all antiviri and anti-spyware programs currently installed on your computer (including stuff like Adaware). Then you can install MSE, and be prepared to let it download an update and run a scan as soon as it&#039;s done installing. The whole process is pretty quick, as antivirussies go. Like other antivirals, it will run in the background, but unlike most antivirucities, it doesn&#039;t take up a lot of your precious RAM.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The problem with Antiviroose is that while they&#039;re running, they take up so many resources they cause problems for everything else you&#039;re trying to do. You&#039;re supposed to turn them off when you install anything, they can cause problems in games and other intensive applications, and there are tons of compatibility issues with other programs. The cure is as bad as the disease. With MSE, however, you don&#039;t really have to worry about it as much. It&#039;s light, so it won&#039;t slow your computer down. I haven&#039;t noticed any problems with other applications, and it&#039;s getting good marks online. It&#039;s still pretty new, so compatibility issues and other problems could crop up, so don&#039;t expect it to be perfect right away. Since it&#039;s made by Microsoft, it should run pretty nicely with Windows, though. All in all, it&#039;s a great piece of kit, and the best part is that it&#039;s free.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Now, I don&#039;t know if I would recommend that you dump your current antivirus at your business and dive right in to MSE. It&#039;s still new, so you never know what problems might crop up. It might not quite be ready for full-scale deployment to systems that are important for your small business. It&#039;s no problem for your home computer, though, so I do recommend that you get it running as soon as possible. On the web page linked above is a link to the new Forefront Client Security, which is some kind of antivirus solution for business computers. It&#039;s essentially the same thing as MSE, but it can be run and managed on networked computers from a central location, like a server, which makes it great for businesses. It seems to still be in Beta, though, which means it&#039;s not necessarily finished yet. Consider it &quot;use at your own risk.&quot;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The real question here is why they didn&#039;t include Security Essentials as part of Windows 7 in the first place. Maybe they did; I&#039;m still using the Release Candidate because I&#039;m too lazy to install the actual product (I do have it, though). If that&#039;s the case, then it&#039;s super awesome. However, I don&#039;t think that&#039;s the case, and I have a theory as to why. It probably wasn&#039;t ready to be deployed yet, so they didn&#039;t want to include an unfinished antivirus in Windows 7. More importantly, however, I don&#039;t think it would be taken seriously if it were. Most of the point of an antivirus, frankly, is to make you less afraid of all of the viruses Apple keeps telling you about. Since people seem to be very weary of utilities included in Windows, it could be that nobody would trust an antivirus that they didn&#039;t install themselves. People need to go through the process of installing an antivirus, to feel like they&#039;re really doing something about that damn techno-flu. That&#039;s why, I think, Microsoft won&#039;t just include an antivirus as part of Windows for a long time.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Believe it or not, computers need placebos, too.&lt;/p&gt;

