&lt;p&gt;I&#039;ve been unemployed now for a couple months, and I&#039;m starting to get bored. I figured I would take some time talk about &lt;em&gt;Avatar&lt;/em&gt;, the big blockbuster from James Cameron. If you haven&#039;t heard about this film, then you probably have much more important things to worry about, like whatever creatures are trying to also live in your cave with you, or when the Child Fund is going to give you today&#039;s cup of coffee so you can go to school or whatever. If you don&#039;t live in a cave or in some third world country, then you&#039;ve probably heard a lot about this film, and maybe even more about how bad it might be. Allow me to give a counter point.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Now, asking you to care what I think is as wrong as blindly agreeing with what everybody else has to say. You should still read my argument, though, because I think it&#039;s important in this world.&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;Read my thoughts.&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Avatar&lt;/em&gt; followed the regular lifestyle of a major, supposedly game changing, blockbuster film. It took much longer to make than a normal film, had an army of designers large enough to invade Poland, and cost more money than God. The hype was insurmountable in the weeks before it came out, it made more money than any other movie that came out in the same year (even though it came out only a few weeks before the year ended), and then after about a week everybody started talking about how bad it was. This is the standard path of a major motion picture.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So here we are, long enough after the movie&#039;s release that everybody&#039;s either seen it or doesn&#039;t want to (or lives for less than a cup of coffee a day). People are starting to talk about how bad it was, saying it was just like &lt;a href=&quot;http://images.huffingtonpost.com/gen/130283/original.jpg&quot;&gt;Pocahontas&lt;/a&gt; or whatever. The plot was cliche, the characters flat and predictable, or the special effects were mediocre. The hyper-critical public internet opinion machine has said its piece, and that&#039;s all anybody needs to know.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Perhaps it&#039;s just because I&#039;m insane (or my &quot;Deny Conformity&quot; nature), but the more I hear people talk about how bad it was, the more I want to like it. Before I saw it I was fully prepared to be incredibly annoyed by &lt;em&gt;Avatar&lt;/em&gt; when I went to see it. I wasn&#039;t even that interested in seeing it. It seemed to me like a totally cliche and predictable futuristic &lt;em&gt;Black Hawk Down&lt;/em&gt;. Still, when you hear things like &quot;changes film forever&quot; you kind of have to see what they mean. So I saw it.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I was wrong, and so are you, if you say it was bad.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;At some point in the film, I realized why I was annoyed by it. It occurred to me that &lt;em&gt;Avatar&lt;/em&gt; isn&#039;t a film at all. It&#039;s a masterpiece. I&#039;m not saying that like, &quot;it wasn&#039;t good . . . it was great!&quot; I just mean that it was a feat beyond a normal film. It was an achievement that we&#039;ve never seen before, and will never see again.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Cameron first wrote a treatment for &lt;em&gt;Avatar&lt;/em&gt; in 1994. That was fifteen years ago. He originally thought up the basic elements of what became &lt;em&gt;Avatar&lt;/em&gt;&#039;s alien race in a film he wrote in 1976, over thirty years ago. He pretty much made Titanic so he could work on this movie. He invented technology to make movies in 3d for this movie. He waited for fifteen years for technology to be able to do what he wanted it to do. Did you notice how he never really did anything since Titanic came out in 1997? That&#039;s because he was working on &lt;em&gt;this goddamn movie&lt;/em&gt;. I think that much devotion and determination from the highest grossing director ever deserves at least a little respect.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I want you to put the plot and the characters and even the special effects aside for a moment. Think about what was done for &lt;em&gt;Avatar&lt;/em&gt;. They invented an entire language just for this movie. That&#039;s never been done before. They developed an entire culture and society based around an entire made-up planet full of thousands of made-up species of plant and animal life. This isn&#039;t just regular sci-fi design where some artists sit around and say, &quot;hey, this looks cool.&quot; A team of designers and actual, factual scientists discussed the biology of the entire planet. They designed things based on how animals would have evolved there. They spent years developing not just some cool looking creatures, but the entire ecosystem that supports them. The virtual designs and assets for Pandora filled over a petabyte of storage.  That&#039;s one million gigabytes! All that is &lt;em&gt;on top&lt;/em&gt; of the usual futuristic human spaceships, weapons, and other technology that you&#039;d find in a sci-fi movie. They invented an entire goddamn planet from scratch, and you&#039;re complaining that the characters are a little flat?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Now, how about the technical achievements in &lt;em&gt;Avatar&lt;/em&gt;? You know how a bunch of movies have been coming out in 3D lately? That&#039;s pretty much James Cameron&#039;s doing. He made the first modern polarized 3D film in 2003, and he didn&#039;t do it just to play around with new technology. He did it for &lt;em&gt;Avatar&lt;/em&gt;. He let it soak in, and waited for the novelty to wear off, so we were used to it and comfortable with it before he made his opus. He waited for us to get over that whole &quot;hey look it&#039;s 3D&quot; bullshit where stuff flies right at the screen just to freak people out. You&#039;ll find none of that in &lt;em&gt;Avatar&lt;/em&gt;. Like everything else, 3D is just part of the world, not a gimmick. It is part of the world, too. I thought it was a little weird that the photographs on a wall at one point were in 3D with everything else, until I realized that it&#039;s the future, and they simply have 3D photographs.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;They also invented a new way to do motion capture for this thing. I&#039;ve dabbled in animation enough to know that the animation for the completely computer generated alien creatures was phenomenal. Cameron strapped cameras to the actors&#039; faces so that the animators could capture every single nuance in the actors&#039; expressions. Really, the amount of work that went into just the animation on every single frame of this movie is staggering. It challenges everything ever animated before, honestly.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/avatar/transformers_vs_avatar_small.jpg&quot; style=&quot;float: right; margin-left: 10px&quot; /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Just look at the number of people involved with this movie. Pictured to the right is a comparison of the &quot;visual effects by&quot; lists on IMDB of &lt;em&gt;Transformers&lt;/em&gt; (on the left) and &lt;em&gt;Avatar&lt;/em&gt; (on the right). &lt;em&gt;Transformers&lt;/em&gt; was no slouch when it came to visual effects, and it certainly busted a few blocks back in its day, but just look at the difference. The number of people under &quot;visual effects by&quot; on IMDB for &lt;em&gt;Avatar&lt;/em&gt; is almost &lt;em&gt;three times&lt;/em&gt; the number of people listed for &lt;em&gt;Transformers&lt;/em&gt;. That&#039;s ridiculous.&lt;/p&gt; 

&lt;p&gt;Just think about this: for the first time (and maybe only time) ever, both Weta Digital (&lt;em&gt;Lord of the Rings&lt;/em&gt; and &lt;em&gt;District 9&lt;/em&gt;) and ILM (&lt;em&gt;Star Wars&lt;/em&gt;, &lt;em&gt;Transformers&lt;/em&gt;, and &lt;em&gt;Pirates of the Caribbean&lt;/em&gt;) worked on the same film. That&#039;s how complicated &lt;em&gt;Avatar&lt;/em&gt; was to make. The two largest special effects houses on the planet were &lt;em&gt;both&lt;/em&gt; required to pull it off.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Most of this movie, predictably, was shot on a sound stage entirely painted green. As most people know, special effects shots are done in front of a green screen, because they can easily cut out the green background and replace it with whatever they want to replace it with. Normally this means that while shooting the movie everybody just has to imagine what&#039;s going on around them, since all they can actually see is green walls and some camera equipment. That was not the case with Avatar. Cameron had a system where he could actually see everything he wanted to see in the shot, as they were shooting it, like a giant (planet sized) video game level. He could move around in the world as easily as he could walk around a real set, and do whatever he wanted with shots on the fly. That&#039;s a big deal, especially for actors who are sick of pretending that giant green cylinders are some kind of monster thing so much that they&#039;re developing an irrational hatred for the color. Of anything developed for &lt;em&gt;Avatar&lt;/em&gt;, this is most likely to change the way movies are made from now on, and it&#039;s the kind of innovation that most of the base plebeians on the internet (the kind who say that this is still last decade) will never know or care about.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Just think about how much work went into &lt;em&gt;Avatar&lt;/em&gt;, especially compared to other films. A regular film, especially one with a lot of special effects, is a monumental undertaking. I&#039;ve made movies that are only seven minutes long and they&#039;ve almost killed me. The work required for a feature-length film is insane, for hundreds, if not thousands, of people. &lt;em&gt;Avatar&lt;/em&gt; was at least three times that much effort, and took at least ten times as long. You&#039;re willing to just shrug that off because the plot was a little cliche?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;But yes, how about that plot, then? Yes, you&#039;re all right, it does seem to draw heavily on Disney&#039;s &lt;em&gt;Pocahontas&lt;/em&gt;. The thing is, do you know what other movie drew heavily from the story of Pocahontas? Disney&#039;s goddamn &lt;em&gt;Pocahontas&lt;/em&gt;. It&#039;s not like they wrote the story. It&#039;s a classic tale from American mythology. Plenty of movies take inspiration from mythology, and they&#039;re lauded. &lt;em&gt;Avatar&lt;/em&gt; does it and it&#039;s a rip off? That&#039;s not fair.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Discrediting a film because its plot is cliche is like discrediting Picasso for using paint brushes. There are only so many ways you can tell a story. That&#039;s just the truth. You can go buy one of a hundred books listing the thirty six dramatic situations you can use in a story. You probably shouldn&#039;t, though, because you&#039;re going to see a lot of stuff that&#039;s been done in movies before. After the ten billion or so movies people have made, it&#039;s very hard to make one that doesn&#039;t have something somebody else already thought of. So why not embrace that? Cameron, I think, &lt;em&gt;uses&lt;/em&gt; cliche. He uses it like an artists uses any of his tools. Why waste time going out of your way to explain something when you can just make it something we&#039;re already familiar with, and move on?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Face it, you didn&#039;t go to see that movie expecting goddamn Shakespeare. You weren&#039;t hoping for a brilliant plot or the most amazing character development you&#039;ve ever seen. You went there wanting to watch some giant blue aliens fight big ass robots in 3D, and that&#039;s the truth. Cameron wanted to show us this world he created. He wasn&#039;t trying to create some sort of high literature. He just wanted to show us some giant blue aliens fighting big ass robots. Why do you expect more than that?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Does anybody hate on &lt;em&gt;Terminator&lt;/em&gt; because the Terminator&#039;s character isn&#039;t developed that well? No, &lt;em&gt;Terminator&lt;/em&gt; was awesome because it was about a sweet killer robot, and that&#039;s what it delivered.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;If you look past the cliche and simplicity of the central plot (you could even call it &quot;elegant simplicity&quot;), you might actually see some interesting themes. Cameron does a lot of exploration of duality, and I think the idea of someone needing an &quot;avatar&quot; to find their place in a world is none too relevant in this increasingly internet-centered society. He delivers an poignant message about humanity&#039;s increasingly destructive path on its obsession for &quot;unobtanium,&quot; a blatant symbol for our out-of-control desire for things that we can&#039;t have, and that part of us that can never be satisfied. Having that simple, basic concept of &quot;unobtanium&quot; is a perfect example. It&#039;s perhaps cliche and unrealistic, but you immediately understand the point. It&#039;s the perfect, irresistible prize that&#039;s just on the other side of the line between good and evil.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The plot of &lt;em&gt;Avatar&lt;/em&gt; is hardly the point at all. In a way, the done-before and cliche nature of the plot is in itself an example of one of the film&#039;s most important themes, the dangers of insatiable desire, and finding peace in simplicity.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Still, I truly believe that it is inconsequential whether or not the movie is good. &lt;em&gt;Avatar&lt;/em&gt;&#039;s quality is irrelevant. What matters is that &lt;em&gt;Avatar&lt;/em&gt; stands as a monument of what a human being is capable of. It is the ultimate work of James Cameron&#039;s life, and it is his opus. &lt;em&gt;Avatar&lt;/em&gt; is Beethoven&#039;s 9th symphony. It is Michelangelo&#039;s David. It is Cameron&#039;s masterpiece, and that just doesn&#039;t happen anymore. In a world where all we care about is how much money we can make (the ultimate unobtanium), it seems like nobody cares anymore about what we can actually &lt;em&gt;do&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;That&#039;s why you should watch &lt;em&gt;Avatar&lt;/em&gt;, and why it deserves your respect.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;As with all major, supposedly game changing, blockbuster films, &lt;em&gt;Avatar&lt;/em&gt; will eventually find its place in the annals of history. Eventually I think people will, at least subconscious, think of it as a benchmark for all films to come. I think &lt;em&gt;Avatar&lt;/em&gt; might even get the consideration it deserves, long from now, when seen with the calm, malevolent eyes of hindsight. I wonder if anybody said that the Mona Lisa was a little simple and boring when it was first made.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;br /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;On the other hand, all of the subtitles (and the movie posters) are in Papyrus, the second worst font on the planet. So yeah, screw that movie.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I got a job last week.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It&#039;s pretty cool, too. I&#039;m working for a medium-sized web design company called Colossal Squid. Its a really dynamic and hard-working team, and I&#039;m both excited and terrified (good terrified) to be working there. This is the first time I&#039;ve worked with a team of dudes who are really awesome and who know exactly what I do and what they need me for. My last few positions have been more general, less hardcore, and I am nervous about the fact that this team is going to want my absolute best. I think I might just be up for the task.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Today was my first day. Of course, I didn&#039;t have much actual work to do today, and what they gave me to do was pretty basic. Today I had to create an e-mail newsletter from a Photoshop mock-up. If you know anything about web design, you probably know that e-mail clients can&#039;t really support any major styling, so you have to make them with a bunch of images and tables (as opposed to using more modern CSS with background images). If you know anything about web design, you know that making entire web pages with HTML tables is a terrible thing for all parties. However, it is what must be done, and if this is what they need me to do, I will do it.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This is my first real job, if you want to get down to it. My actual first full time job out of college was working from home, so that doesn&#039;t really count. After working from home for about six months, and then being unemployed for another three, I&#039;m not used to a normal job. For Colossal Squid, I will actually have to put on pants, take a bus to an office building (in the west loop), sit at a desk for nine hours a day, and interact with real human beings. I hope I haven&#039;t forgotten how to do all of those things. I am most worried about my roommate&#039;s cat, Alice. Without me around all day, she will have nobody to beg for her dinner for the hour or so before Sarah gets home.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Strangely, the idea of spending most of my days at work is very liberating. When I had all of my time to myself, I felt so useless if I didn&#039;t spend every single moment working on a screenplay, or this website, or writing something, or doing photography, or working on music, or looking for a job, or whatever. Now that I have something I have to do all the time, it&#039;s no longer my fault that I don&#039;t get all these crazy schemes done. I might keep some of these ideas on the backburner, though. I mean, a pizza place that specializes in double-decker pizzas? How can that fail?!&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A half-hour commute means an extra hour every day that I have to just sit quietly and do nothing. I will have to think of interesting ways to occupy myself (like how I&#039;m doing right now, because I&#039;m writing this on my way home from work). Maybe I will take up knitting, or I will practice being a DJ on the bus, or take up live-blogging, or solicit, or buy a car.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Getting a job is like getting a girlfriend. For a while, you spend a few months sitting on the couch in your underwear, eating ice cream and watching reruns of old TV shows, thinking that you&#039;re totally useless and you&#039;ll never find another one like the one you just lost. Then you slowly get over yourself, and you start to go out a little, talking to some people and getting your name out there. You give out your resume (or your phone number) to hundreds of people, and you may even hear back from one or two. You can always try to go online, which could theoretically save you a lot of time and effort, but you&#039;ll mainly only hear from weirdos and creeps who want you to do some kind of porn.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Once you find somebody you really like, the courtship begins. You&#039;ll meet up, maybe for lunch or drinks, and get to know each other a little bit. You put on your best tie and present yourself as best you can (even throwing out some smart-sounding buzz words from your field or profession), so that they think you&#039;re totally classy and intelligent all the time. If you&#039;re really lucky, they&#039;ll ask to see you again. Maybe they will show you some of their friends, so you&#039;ll see the people you&#039;ll have to hang out with if it all goes well. Of course, if it does go well, you can count on losing most of your free time because they&#039;re going to want you around pretty much all the time.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;There&#039;s a bit of a learning curve, as you figure out just how they like to do things. They might make it seem like you&#039;re free to do your own thing, but you just keep your head down and do what they tell you. Let&#039;s face it, you&#039;re really only in it for that big event every couple weeks (you know, the paycheck).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I would keep this whole analogy going, but frankly I haven&#039;t really gotten that serious with a girl or a job, so I would only be making stuff up.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It&#039;s going to take some time to get used to the whole &quot;being employed&quot; thing, but hopefully it will be as easy as what I&#039;ve been used to, which is &quot;being a loser.&quot;&lt;/p&gt;

