&lt;p&gt;I&#039;ve been working a lot, and &lt;em&gt;Left 4 Dead 2&lt;/em&gt; has burned through what little free time I&#039;ve had, so I haven&#039;t had much time to make any progress on this summer&#039;s project,&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images//webserver_logo.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;The DenyConformity.com Webserver&quot; style=&quot;display: block; margin: auto&quot; height=&quot;270&quot; width=&quot;433&quot;&gt;&lt;p&gt;So, &lt;strong&gt;step 1&lt;/strong&gt; of the process is to get things cleared with my internet provider, &lt;strong&gt;RCN&lt;/strong&gt;. As far as I know, RCN stands for Really . . . Crappy . . . well, yeah I have no idea what RCN stands for. I do know that they have pretty poor customer service, though. I&#039;m currently installing Microsoft Visual Studio for a project at work which is on a .NET environment, so I had a few hours to kill. I decided to give RCN a ring. After navigating a maze of &quot;push X for X&quot; options, I finally got a human (supposedly) voice. She, of course, had no idea what a web server was, so I decided to make things easier and just ask for a static IP address.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Ok, so here&#039;s your &lt;strong&gt;first lesson&lt;/strong&gt; about the &lt;strong&gt;internets&lt;/strong&gt;. As we all know, the internet is supposedly this vast series of tubes connecting billions of perverts with each other around the world. Actually, though, the internet is more like a vast card catalog, arranged not by some sort of Dewey Decimal or category, but by address. Since the internet operates on a specific protocol (called the Internet Protocol), every single computer (or computer network) has its own unique IP address. Yes, you, right now, looking at this website, have an IP address, even if you&#039;re connected via Cellphone Telephone, Dial-up (hi Mom), or the world&#039;s fastest fiber optic connection. That IP address is sort of like your computer&#039;s phone number, or to put it in a much more literal way, your computer&#039;s address.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Websites are just cards in this giant card catalog, and all you have to do to access them is call up that IP address. Websites are stored on computers all over the world (even giant mega-servers are just computers), and those computers (or Web Servers) have a specific IP address that applies only to them. So, to access a web server and load the website contained within, all you have to do is navigate to that server&#039;s IP address over the HyperText Transfer Protocol (that&#039;s what that little HTTP:// means). We don&#039;t need to get into specifics about what the HTTP actually is, but basically it just tells your computer how to communicate properly with the IP address it is accessing.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Here&#039;s an example (just a little sample). Google is a pretty popular website. If you don&#039;t know what Google is, then I urge you to spend a little more time acclimating yourself with our time period before you dive into the ins and outs of the internet. Also, I would like to borrow your time machine. Anyway, Google runs on a computer, just like the computer you&#039;re staring at right now. Sure, Google&#039;s servers have storage and computational ability lightyears beyond the computer you&#039;re looking at (probably), but in essence they are the same. Primarily, Google&#039;s server connects to the same internet you&#039;re connected to, and they have an IP address just like you. Google&#039;s IP address is 209.85.135.104. Just four simple numbers. Instead of typing &quot;www.google.com&quot; into your browser&#039;s address bar, you can type &quot;http://209.85.135.104/&quot; and you&#039;ll get the exact same thing. Kind of neat.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So why don&#039;t we see more IP addresses in our daily, internet drenched lives? It is because of another nifty little acronym, DNS. DNS stands for &quot;Domain Name System&quot; and it is a universal system for providing shortcuts to the cards in that giant card catalog. Just check out the &lt;a href=&quot;http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Domain_Name_System&quot;&gt;Wikipedia page for DNS&lt;/a&gt; if you&#039;re really interested. Basically, when you type in a domain name (google.com, for instance), your computer accesses a special server called a Name Server, which tells your computer what IP address is associated with that domain name. Your browser then figures out the IP address and usually a subdirectory (sometimes a single server can host multiple websites, so one IP address will have several domains associated with it) and then it calls up that address. All that happens before your computer even accesses the server (the process of client-server communication is also fascinating, but totally another story). It&#039;s certainly quite complicated, but if you can think of a better way to have a distributed network of completely independent machines all communicating with each other in a vast worldwide network, you&#039;re certainly wasting your time here.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Okay, so computers have IP addresses, but the problem with internet service providers like RCN is that they are constantly randomizing those addresses. Your home network will be assigned a new IP every once in a while, through a process called Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP). There are many reasons for this, mainly that it would be a pain in the ass to manually assign an IP address to hundreds of thousands of internet customers. What does this mean for someone wanting to build a web server at home? Well, if your IP address changes all the time, then where do you point the domain name?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Let&#039;s go back to that card catalog metaphor. Say you&#039;re looking for a book, perhaps a copy of &lt;em&gt;Montgumery Rood&lt;/em&gt;, by A Chicken (yes, I&#039;m referencing my own &lt;a href=&quot;http://denyconformity.com/content/news.php?post=00248&quot;&gt;podcast&lt;/a&gt;). Well, it&#039;s easy, right? You just open up the &quot;A&quot; drawer in the card catalog . . . &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;They don&#039;t even use card catalogs anymore, do they? That&#039;s a stupid metaphor.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Okay, say you&#039;re doing a crossword puzzle. Yeah, this is good. You&#039;re doing a crossword puzzle, and you look at the clue for 23 across. It says &quot;Invented the apple, colleague of Borrison&quot; (yes, another &lt;a href=&quot;http://denyconformity.com/content/news.php?post=00245&quot;&gt;podcast&lt;/a&gt; reference). Well, obviously the answer is &quot;Smith,&quot; so you look up at the puzzle for the horizontal row of boxes marked with a little &quot;23.&quot; Simple, now you know that &quot;Smith&quot; goes in those little boxes. That&#039;s not entirely dissimilar to how the internets work. Typing in &quot;google.com&quot; is like saying &quot;23 across.&quot; Your browser figures out what 23 across points to, and fills in the little boxes with the proper IP address.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;But when a server is assigned addresses with DHCP, it&#039;s like that crossword puzzle is constantly shifting around. It would be impossible for you to solve.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images//dhcp_crossword.gif&quot; height=&quot;326&quot; width=&quot;326&quot;&gt;&lt;p&gt;So what you need to do is get your internet provider to give you a static IP address, so that your little row of boxes never changes. You have to pay a little extra to your ISP, but you can always connect to your server.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So okay, back to my phone call with RCN. As an ISP (Internet Service Provider), they know what a static IP address is, and it should be easy to get them to give me one. After I was transferred to the Internet Support division and we figured out which account we were dealing with (it&#039;s under my roommate Sarah&#039;s name), I told the person-on-the-phone what I needed and asked if it was possible and how much it would cost.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&quot;Okay, one moment, we will add a Static IP to this account.&quot; She said, jumping to all sorts of conclusions.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&quot;Uh, well, how much will it be?&quot; I responded, hoping to stop her from charging an account which doesn&#039;t even have my name on it.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&quot;A Static IP is 19.95&quot;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&quot; . . . per month?&quot; (our internet plan is only $30 per month, so that seemed a little much to me)&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&quot;Yes, 19.95 per month, plus a $25 set up fee.&quot;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&quot;Wait . . . &quot; I was about to try to get her to justify why typing four numbers into a router justified a $25 setup fee, but then I realized that was a stupid thing to argue. What was a far better thing to argue, I decided, was the fact that the &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.rcn.com/chicago/high-speed-internet/extras/home-networking&quot;&gt;RCN website&lt;/a&gt; advertises static IP services for only 9.95 / month.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images//Screen%20shot%202010-05-14%20at%2012.05.55%20PM.png&quot; height=&quot;164&quot; width=&quot;616&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Unless I&#039;m seeing it wrong . . .&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;We both took turns walking each other through the RCN website to find the price for Static IP, which I assured her said &quot;9.95&quot; which is not, in fact, &quot;19.95.&quot;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&quot;9.95,&quot; I said, &quot;would be something I would be willing to pay. I would not be willing to pay 19.95.&quot;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&quot;So you don&#039;t want to add Static IP to your account?&quot; She asked.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&quot;No, in fact, I never did want to add it to my account, I was just trying to figure out how much it will cost, and I wasn&#039;t really able to do that, so I guess I&#039;ll have to call again later.&quot;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Meanwhile, it has become increasingly difficult to connect to my website via FTP (so I can upload files to it and stuff), and I am constantly receiving notifications that DenyConformity.com is down. So it would seem that the DenyConformity.com webserver has reach a bit of a predicament. I don&#039;t want to spend an additional $20 a month, but I can&#039;t stand sticking with &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.startlogic.com&quot;&gt;Startlogic&lt;/a&gt; any longer. Maybe I&#039;ll just bite the bullet and get the static IP address.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.DynDNS.com&quot;&gt;Unless there&#039;s a better way.&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

