&lt;p&gt;My parents have been doing some research into my family&#039;s history, recently. They uncovered some interesting things, as well as a genealogical line stretching all the way back to when people had names like GRONGNARD. One of the more interesting things they found, though, was a journal detailing one of my ancestor&#039;s trials as they moved west to start a new life, during, presumably, the Great Depression. I found it fascinating, especially during this time of great economic turmoil. I urge you to read ahead, and get a glimpse at a bit of history. It&#039;s actually somewhat well written, too.&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Week one.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The sun set slowly over the modest parcel of land that held far too much of my family&#039;s future as we arrived this week to start our new life here. I looked across this small farmland which was recently handed to me, and I felt an all to familiar twinge of fear rise in the pit of my stomach. How could my family and I survive on this meager patch of dirt and the few simple crops that were planted here before my arrival? I decided to waste no time, or perhaps decided that there simply was no time to waste. In the fading evening sun, as my wife and children settled themselves in our new house - it still seemed far too small for our four children - I set out to survey what little we had.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I was given a paltry few instructions to aid me. I could only guess what most of my tools were for. Thankfully, a small patch of vegetables was already growing, and I decided that what little I could discover from them could be invaluable when I need to plant more. I only hope the small bit of coin I can get for harvesting these plants will be enough to keep my children fed over the coming weeks.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;My wife and I have been married for almost fifteen years. We met when I was still working for the Bank, back East. It was a simpler time then, and we were blissfully happy, slowly raising a family on my Generous Banker's Salary. Then, as the economy began taking its toll on us all, the warm burn in the pit of my stomach first showed itself. My wife often found me at the window, gazing off at the skyline. She always had the same nervous look on her face, and I knew she was only mirroring my own. I have a tendency to stop blinking when I'm worried, and she knew it. She would stare into my big, pale-blue eyes, and know that something was wrong. Neither of us could have guessed just how bad things were going to become.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It has, in more recent days, become cruelly apparent that I know nothing about raising a farm. I tried several times to replant the small patches of land that I had recently harvested, before I finally felt confident in my work. My oldest son, Jeffery, proved to be invaluable to me by heading to the nearest town, where a market provides me and other local farmers with the resources we need. Unfortunately, he was only able to find soybeans, and we had to spend an unfortunate amount of money to re-plant them. I looked on with great trepidation, hoping to whatever omniscient beings watching over us that these soybeans - our only option - would prove valuable. The planting took a great deal of what little money we had, but I hoped that the investment and the experience gained would more than make up for it. Only time would tell.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;My contact in town, the old man who gave me the few tips I had about farming going into this new life, left me with some words of encouragement. &quot;That&#039;s farming for ya!&quot; he told me, but somehow I am not entirely confident in my achievements so far. I will have to be vigilant, and harvest these little crops as soon as they are ready, which I fear will be the hardest challenge yet.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I still wonder if these new crops will require some sort of maintenance that I have not yet been made aware of. I cannot tell if these tools I have available can help me to water the crops, protect them from weeds or insects, or other seemingly obvious challenges that could present themselves. The old man in town simply told me to harvest the crops before they wither, which struck me as rather obvious, frankly. What little I knew about farms covered the simple concept of plant, wait, harvest, without any wizened &quot;expert&quot; to help me. Do I simply wait, standing here on my new land, my deep, blue eyes staring unblinking at the horizon, until that moment comes that I can spring to action and harvest these crops that my entire family is depending on? Is there nothing I can do to occupy my fretting mind in the meanwhile? This will truly be a difficult time.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I enjoy Photography. Hopefully, and judging by the fact that you&#039;re here (and haven&#039;t said &quot;this website sucks&quot; yet), you enjoy my photography. Well, I have good news.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;No, it isn&#039;t &quot;I haven&#039;t updated my website in like a billion forevers.&quot;&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;I have learned how to use High Dynamic Range.&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;Ok, so what is &lt;a href=&quot;http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/High_dynamic_range_imaging&quot;&gt;High Dynamic Range&lt;/a&gt;? Well, for those of you who haven&#039;t opened that link in another tab and read the Wikipedia article about it, High Dynamic Range Imagery (or HDRI (or HDR)) is a type of image with extremely high . . . dynamic range.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Ok, so a digital photograph is a pretty complicated thing. When a digital camera opens its lens and allows a few billion photons (particles of light) to hit its image sensor, the sensor turns those photons into electrons, and those electrons get processed and stored on a flash card or whatever. That&#039;s, in theory, exactly the same way analog photography happens, except instead of electrons you&#039;re storing image data in magic photo-sensitive chemicals. The problem with digital photography is that when you do that processing, you&#039;re throwing away something like most of the actual image data (I was going to throw a number in there like 75%, but the fact is that I don&#039;t really know exactly how much it is). That&#039;s fine for pictures of your friend&#039;s sweet &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.google.com/images?q=beeramid&amp;oe=utf-8&amp;rls=org.mozilla:en-US:official&amp;client=firefox-a&amp;um=1&amp;ie=UTF-8&amp;source=og&amp;sa=N&amp;hl=en&amp;tab=wi&amp;biw=1186&amp;bih=830&quot;&gt;beeramid&lt;/a&gt; that you&#039;re going to post on Facebook. It&#039;s not, however, good for people who really &lt;em&gt;care&lt;/em&gt; about their photographs.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;For those people, the people who carry around a &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XCumH8LRo1A&quot;&gt;mini-Victrola&lt;/a&gt; and who won&#039;t eat food that was cooked on Thursdays or whatever, there just is no comparison between digital and analog film. Yeah, ok, so CD&#039;s can&#039;t ever sound like records, and analog film will always be superior to digital cameras, no matter how many magipixels you cram in them. Whatever. Eat a bowl of dicks.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Uh, sorry. It&#039;s pretty late and I was up late last night taking pictures of this sweet church (I&#039;ll get to that). Anyway, you can get good pictures from a digital camera (hopefully I am proof of that, I only shoot on digital), and the instant gratification and speedy camera-to-facebook turnaround time makes up for any lack of quality. Also, good digital cameras are pretty much dirt cheap now (compared, at least, to what cameras used to cost). Shooting in &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/content/olds.php?post=00148&quot;&gt;RAW&lt;/a&gt; can make sure that your camera throws away as little data as possible, too. (I just realized that I posted those sweet RAW photos just over four years ago. Sheesh)&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The problem is that there&#039;s only so much information you can cram pack into an image file (particularly JPEGs; you should avoid them and stick with PNGs or TIFFs). What can you do?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;What can you do?!&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Enter HDRI (or High Dynamic Range Imagery (or HDR)). Using this super sweet tutorial (yes, this is a JOHN TURTURROIAL), you can turn three pictures into one picture, and thereby theoretically TRIPPPLE the Dynamic Range of your image.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Firstly, you need a camera that allows you to control the Aperture Value (and probably the Shutter Speed, too). Most cameras these days grant you that. If you camera allows you to use &quot;Exposure Bracketing&quot; you can do this much easier. Look it up in your camera&#039;s manual or on the internet. You&#039;ll also probably need Photoshop, but you can probably do it with some other programs out there (if anybody brings up the &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.gimp.org/&quot;&gt;GIMP&lt;/a&gt;, I will stab you). You&#039;ll need a tripod, too, unless you&#039;re some kind of robot. If you&#039;re some kind of robot, please call me I want to be friends.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So, get your tripod set up and point your camera at something cool. Something like . . . an old church that&#039;s down the street from where I live (I told you I&#039;d get back to that).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;You&#039;re going to take three quick pictures of the same thing, which is why the tripod helps (any difference in the pictures&#039; content will screw things up). Put your camera into either Aperture Priority or Manual mode, and turn off the auto-focus (the aperture value and focal depth cannot change between pictures). I&#039;ll repeat that outside of some parentheses: The aperture value and focal depth cannot change between pictures.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;You see, you&#039;re going to take three identical pictures (with one slight difference). When the three get processed together in Photoshop, they will become one. It is therefore crucial that the pictures be identical as possible (anything moving in the frame can be DISASTROUS).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So what changes? What&#039;s the what? Well, take a look at your camera&#039;s Auto Exposure Bracketing (AEB) setting. It allows you to turn the little bar specifying how to expose your picture into THREE LITTLE BARS! That means the camera will automatically set up your camera to take three pictures: one normally-exposed, one under-exposed, and one over-exposed. Set that to something between 1.5 and 2, depending on how much dynamic range you want. Now, simply push the shutter button three times (waiting for the camera to save the image each time), and it will make sure they&#039;re exposed properly, by changing the exposure setting (and the aperture, if you didn&#039;t force it to use the same one (which is why you need to force it to use a specific aperture (by using the Aperture Priority, or Manual modes) each time) each time) each time.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Ok, so you now have three seemingly identical images, with one minor difference. They&#039;re exposed to different levels, within a specific range. What the dealyo is here is that the under-exposed image will look really sweet in the bright areas, and the over-exposed image will look really sweet in the dark areas, and the normal image will look really sweet in the normal areas. Let&#039;s take a look at three images I took last night.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/hdri/13.PNG&quot; /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Normal, Under-exposed, and Over-exposed. Since this is a night scene, we don&#039;t get a great deal of dynamic range (it works best with a sweet sky and daylight) but whatever. It&#039;s some some dark bits, some bright bits, and some regular bits. What we&#039;re going to do is bring them into Photoshop using a thing called Merge to HDR, which is under File - Automate (in versions since like CS2 or something).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/hdri/0.PNG&quot; /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;You get this dialog box. As you can see, I&#039;ve loaded three images into it already. They&#039;re the three images I took! By the way, you can process these images in the RAW utility to adjust the white balance and stuff like that if you want, just be sure you use the exact same settings on all three so that they don&#039;t get WEIRDED OUT by the merging process.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;After some crazy magic technotronic stuff happens you get another dialog box with a picture in it. Mine looked like this:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/hdri/1.PNG&quot; /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&quot;Wait, that doesn&#039;t really look that good at all. What the crap, Shauvon?!&quot; - You, just now.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Shut up, you, we&#039;re not done yet.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/hdri/2.PNG&quot; /&gt; 

&lt;p&gt;There&#039;s this little dude up there in the corner of your new dialog box, you see. This guy helps you adjust the white point of your new image. Basically, it controls how much of each picture to blend into the final one. Since mine is a little bright (most of mine seem to be pretty bright, probably because I don&#039;t really know what I&#039;m doing), I&#039;m going to slide it to the right. Adjust yours to taste - I mean until it looks good.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/hdri/3.PNG&quot; /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;That&#039;s what mine looked like after I did that thing.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/hdri/4.PNG&quot; /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;See, the little bar is farther to the right.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Now you&#039;re going to freak out some more. I sure did. The problem is that the little preview window can&#039;t really show you what the picture looks like (in fact, once the HDRI is made, no consumer-level monitor on the planet can actually show you what it really looks like). It&#039;s just an approximation, thrown together at the last minute like most of my papers in College. Particularly, black levels look like poop levels.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/hdri/5.PNG&quot; /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;See, total poop level. When I first started playing around with this, disappointment levels were high at this point. I promise you, though, you just have to stick with it. Once you hit OK, and some more fanciful whiz-bang happens, you get your super image.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/hdri/6.PNG&quot; /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;That&#039;s what I got. Yeah, it&#039;s ok, but not really that different from what my regular flat photograph was (the farthest to the left in that trippple-picture up above). The reason this doesn&#039;t look like much is because there&#039;s a &lt;em&gt;substantial&lt;/em&gt; amount of the image that your computer just can&#039;t show you. I think that&#039;s really awesome.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;When a digital camera takes a picture, it throws something like a bunch of the data away. Remember when I said that? Those were good times. Anyway, the reason this happens is because that data is beyond the limits of what human technology, or even biology, can handle. Your eye just can&#039;t see detail beyond that (something that kind of pokes holes in those analog-purists rants). The thing is, though, that what you can&#039;t see, your computer &lt;em&gt;can&lt;/em&gt;. So when we process those three pictures into one mega-picture (or MECHAPICTURE), we&#039;re cram-packing it full of delicious COMPUTER FOOD!&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;For example, a regular JPEG image (or any regular computer format) has 8 bits per channel. Each pixel is represented by three channels, Red, Green, and Blue (and also an alpha channel in the case of images like PNGs or Gifs), and each of those channels gets 8 bits (or one Byte) to describe it. That&#039;s plenty for literally every image you&#039;ve ever seen, because that&#039;s as much as computer displays can display (if you&#039;ve heard the term &quot;32-bit&quot; that&#039;s just adding up the three channels and an 8-bit alpha channel together).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The picture we just Frankensteined together is now 32 bits per channel.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I&#039;ll let that sink in. Yes, this picture has four times the depth of any picture ever (hyperbole!). Remember, you can&#039;t see that extra data, and your monitor can&#039;t display it, which is why it looks pretty similar to the regular old 8 bit per channel image you yanked out of the camera (and the funny thing about this is that when I screen-shotted these HDR images out of Photoshop, I had to save them out at 8 bit per channel to show them here, so I can&#039;t even really show you what I&#039;m talking about). Your computer isn&#039;t limited by crappy human eyes, though, so it can see all the bits it wants (and the funny thing about &lt;em&gt;that&lt;/em&gt; is that most of the pictures on the internet are about looking at all of the bits that the average teenage boy wants). We can tell the computer to process this puppy into something really sweet.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/hdri/7.PNG&quot; /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;And, Mr. Skeptic, there&#039;s that same bit of the sky from before, and it looks substantially less poop-y. I told you to trust me.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;What we need to do is tell the computer to turn that 32 bit per channel MECHAPICTURE into a regular old run of the mill 8 bits per channel PICTUREPICTURE.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/hdri/8.PNG&quot; /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;There&#039;s a screenshot of me doing that!&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/hdri/9.PNG&quot; /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;You get another dialog box, now. This one tells the computer what sort of algorithm to use when it turns all those 32 bits into 8 bits (basically, which bits to use, and which bits to throw out). Normally, your camera does this bit-throwing when it takes a picture, so by having more control over it, we can make a much cooler shot.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/hdri/processed_expgama_small.png&quot; /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;There&#039;s my picture, processed with the default setting: &quot;Exposure and Gamma.&quot; It definitely has more dynamic range than the original, and it is a pretty good picture, but it&#039;s not the best (trust me).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/hdri/10.PNG&quot; /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;We have four options to choose, so let&#039;s see what happens when we try them all.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/hdri/processed_highlightcomp_small.png&quot; /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Highlight Compression takes all the highlights and . . . well . . . compresses them. Basically we have just a darker version of the image from before. Eh.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/hdri/processed_equalize_small.png&quot; /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Equalize Histogram flattens the histogram, which in this case is a bad idea since a lot of the image is black (so it tries to brighten the whole thing). Not the right choice for us.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Spoiler alert: the next option is the awesome one.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/hdri/processed_localadaptation_small.png&quot; /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Local Adaptation, my friends. It takes all of the detail and makes it super sharp and awesomeified. Shut up that&#039;s a word. What&#039;s more, you have a handy toning curve right there that you can use to adjust the image (the default version is a little flat, so I tweaked it to get it a little better). Here are my settings:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/hdri/11.PNG&quot; /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The Radius and Threshold settings are what makes it look super sweet (everything gets a sort of &quot;bloom&quot; effect halo around it), so grind those up nice and high. Here&#039;s what the picture looks like with those settings:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/hdri/processed_localadaptation_curves_small.png&quot; /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Awesome? Yes. Worth the work? Yes.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;And so there you have it. With a little modification and attention, you can turn three pictures into one picture, and look really awesome in the process. I should mention, of course, that this will not make up for you being a bad photographer. A poorly framed High Dynamic Range Image is still a crappy picture. Sorry.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Here is a comparison of three versions of the file. Left is the regular, flat photograph. Center is the HDRI before it was processed. Right is the processed, awesome, MECHAPHOTO.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/hdri/12.png&quot; /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Yes, some more leveling and tweaking can be done to the final image, but I wanted to show you how much was capable just processing the HDR images without any touching-up afterwords.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Here are some more examples. Keep in mind that the only &quot;Photoshopping&quot; that I did to these was a little tweaking to white balance in the RAW files and the processes shown in this Tuturroial.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/hdri/hdr2_small.png&quot; /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/hdri/hdr3_small.png&quot; /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/hdri/hdr4_small.png&quot; /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;HDRI is really sweet. Some dudes even made a &lt;a href=&quot;http://vimeo.com/14821961&quot;&gt;movie&lt;/a&gt; with it. It&#039;s not really practical for taking pictures of your broselburgh&#039;s latest facebook profile picture, but for taking really elegant, highly detailed photographs of big, sweet things (like churches), it&#039;s about as good as you&#039;re going to get.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;What do you think? Is it worth all the trouble?&lt;/p&gt;

