She is my sister too.&lt;br /&gt;
I missed her housing party,&lt;br /&gt;
and it makes me really blue.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
I could go on like this forever. . .

data.summary:
&lt;p&gt;A poem by Shauvon McGill&lt;/p&gt;
		Aili is a girl.&lt;br /&gt;
With boobs and hair and such.&lt;br /&gt;
And she is my sister,&lt;br /&gt;
so I like her very much.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Aili is a girl.&lt;br /&gt;
She doesn&amp;#039;t have a spouse.&lt;br /&gt;
Once she lived with mom and dad,&lt;br /&gt;
but now she owns a house.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Aili is a girl.&lt;br /&gt;
She isn&amp;#039;t var&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/br&gt;...

data.text:
&lt;p&gt;From January 9th to the 16th, 2012, this website (DenyConformity.com) was shut down. Though I would love to say that it was because I was engaging in an extended &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.google.com/landing/takeaction/&quot;&gt;protest&lt;/a&gt; of SOPA, it was actually something far more boring. Since I am making a post today, though, I am bound by the INTERNET CODE to reference how evil SOPA is as much as possible, so I apologize in advance for that.&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p&gt;

We&amp;rsquo;ll have to go back a bit (just for a few sentences, I promise), to the early days of this website. Back in the ye olde days of 2005, I was a young, go-getting amateur web designer looking for a place to put a website that I could use to learn how to set up a website. After a tiny bit of searching, I found the cheapest host I could find, otherwise known as &amp;ldquo;Startlogic.com.&amp;rdquo; I set up my site, and everything worked fine. Over the years I had a few troubles here and there, but most were the fault of my lack of experience with the entire process. Startlogic, it seemed, was perfectly adequate for the task of hosting a low-tech website with an audience of several.&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/dc_down/small_startlogic.PNG&quot; style=&quot;width: 600px; display: block; margin: auto&quot; height=&quot;344&quot; width=&quot;600&quot;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Incidentally, this is the exact same photograph and layout that they had six years ago. They either have absolutely fantastic employee retention (that chick in front does look pretty faithful, despite having to work with the guy on the right side of the back row), or they&amp;rsquo;re - gasp - liars! Other lies on their page (in addition to the &amp;ldquo;Real People&amp;rdquo;depicted therein) include &amp;ldquo;Real Service,&amp;rdquo; and &amp;ldquo;Real Savings.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/div&gt;



&lt;p&gt;

That was a problem solved, then (well, it wasn&amp;rsquo;t ever really a problem, so I guess it was a problem invented and then also solved). Over the last six (and a half) years, my little website has grown to a . . . well, it&amp;rsquo;s still the same hacked together, obviously made by somebody who didn&amp;rsquo;t know what he was doing mess. However, my little web empire has expanded to include quite a few other little kingdoms. I&amp;rsquo;ve pointed a few other domains at my Startlogic webspace, allowing me to host a couple websites for much cheaper than if I set them up separately. These sites include &lt;a href=&quot;http://mynameissmac.com&quot;&gt;mynameissmac.com&lt;/a&gt; (the website for my mediocre music producing alter-ego), &lt;a href=&quot;http://mcgillandhughes.com&quot;&gt;mcgillandhughes.com&lt;/a&gt; (the website for my on again, off again podcast with Will Hughes), and &lt;a href=&quot;http://factorydinosaur.com&quot;&gt;factorydinosaur.com&lt;/a&gt; (the site for the improv comedy group I am a part of in Chicago). I also set up a few sub-domains for some friends.&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p&gt;

In late 2009, things started going rather pear-shaped with good old Startlogic. It was around that time that I started using a service called &amp;ldquo;Pingdom.&amp;rdquo; Pingdom will automatically poll a web domain every fifteen minutes, and notify you (via various methods; my favorite is Twitter) when the domain is down. I set it up to check on DenyConformity.com, just to see how good Startlogic&amp;rsquo;s uptime was.&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p&gt;

This elicits a very quick technical aside. One of the more important aspects of a web host is &amp;ldquo;uptime,&amp;rdquo; or the percentage of time their servers are actively serving content. I would copy the definition from Wikipedia, but it is currently down in protest. Basically, if they have a problem with their servers or they shut them down for maintenance, their uptime goes down (time). Lower uptime means more time that your site won&amp;rsquo;t be visible, which is the opposite of what you want your website to be. It&amp;rsquo;s totally a buzzword, though, like &amp;ldquo;HD,&amp;rdquo; &amp;ldquo;Organic,&amp;rdquo; or &amp;ldquo;Democratic.&amp;rdquo; There&amp;rsquo;s no regulatory committee keeping track of uptime, and there&amp;rsquo;s no burden of proof for anybody who claims &amp;ldquo;99.99%.&amp;rdquo; Therefore, it&amp;rsquo;s pretty easy to just fudge the numbers a bit, and most web hosting providers do, in fact, claim 99.99%. Of course, uptime won&amp;rsquo;t mean anything anymore if SOPA goes through, so you should go call your Senator right now.&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p&gt;

According to WebHostingStuff.com (which isn&amp;rsquo;t blacked out in protest right now), Startlogic&amp;rsquo;s uptime is 99.99%, which is great. That means in the last 2,319 days (which is how long this WebHostingStuff place has been tracking it), Startlogic has only been down 0.01%. Let&amp;rsquo;s look at the numbers. 2,319 days is 200,361,600 seconds, and 0.01% of that is 20,036 seconds, or about five and a half hours.&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p&gt;

Yeah, but who the crap is WebHostingStuff.com, anyway? They aren&#039;t protesting SOPA and so they are evil corporate weiners who are probably in the pocket of Big Webhost. Luckily, I&amp;rsquo;ve been using my own tracking service for the last three years. In that time, Pingdom has recorded an uptime of only 99.68%. Since October, 2009, DenyConformity.com has been down a total of two days, fourteen hours, fifty-nine minutes and fourty-six seconds!&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/dc_down/pingdom%20report.PNG&quot; style=&quot;width: 500px; display: block; margin: auto&quot; height=&quot;554&quot; width=&quot;639&quot;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;It is &lt;strong&gt;very&lt;/strong&gt; important I include this graph.&lt;/div&gt;



&lt;p&gt;

If you know anything about stats and math, you&amp;rsquo;ll know that the more numbers you include in your mean average, the closer that mean will approach 100%. A site could be down quite a bit, but if you look at it over six years it will average out to be closer to that 99.99% that everybody claims. Also, if you know anything about the web, you might realize that downtime is a necessary part of how things work, and if a site is down a few hours a month it&amp;rsquo;s not really a problem if it&amp;rsquo;s always at 5 AM, when nobody will be trying to look at it, anyway. I could try to paint Startlogic as a bad company (though they are also not protesting today) just because they have some downtime, but in truth it&amp;rsquo;s nothing to be concerned about.&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p&gt;

So anyway, it was then, when I started using Pingdom, that I really started thinking that I should look for a new place to hang my @. I was getting almost daily reports of outages at all times of day, and any time I tried to contact Startlogic to figure out just want their deal was, it was like talking to a brick wall. A brick wall that charges you a bunch of money. My biggest push in this regard was to set up my own server to host my site, and thereby avoid dealing with bad third parties entirely. I wrote a &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/content/olds.php?post=00247&quot;&gt;couple&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/content/olds.php?post=00252&quot;&gt;posts&lt;/a&gt; about those efforts back in April, 2010. I still plan on continuing that tale for you, my only audience member, and it is the subject of a different post than this. However, the short story is that the Official DenyConformity.com Web Server is simply not yet (and will likely never be) quite ready for full-time hosting duties. However, it was, among other things, a distraction from the task at hand, namely G&amp;rsquo;ing the F O from Startlogic and their oppressive boot of ineptitude.&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/dc_down/startlogic_closeup.png&quot; style=&quot;width: 185px; display: block; margin: auto&quot; height=&quot;140&quot; width=&quot;185&quot;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;She&#039;s just so happy to do nothing for you.&lt;/div&gt;



&lt;p&gt;

Presented for your perusal, anecdote number one from the history of DenyConformity.com&amp;rsquo;s many outages. The two most basic parts of a website are the Domain and the Server, and though you can buy them (though you&amp;rsquo;re really just renting them) both together, they are basically separate entities. If you aren&amp;rsquo;t quick enough on the draw and your domain&amp;rsquo;s aren&amp;rsquo;t set to auto-renew, after a year or two passes they won&amp;rsquo;t be yours anymore. Who owns them at that point depends on a lot of strange, theoretical conditions, but the world of domains is still very much the Wild, Wild West. Instead of banditos taking over your ranch, it&amp;rsquo;s GoDaddy.com &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.nolo.com/legal-encyclopedia/cybersquatting-what-what-can-be-29778.html&quot;&gt;squatting&lt;/a&gt; on your domain, charging you ridiculous (and illegal) amounts of money to get it back. Instead of revolvers, it&amp;rsquo;s DNS caches, and instead of Will Smith, it&amp;rsquo;s Danika Patrick in extremely misleading ads.&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/dc_down/danica.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 418px; display: block; margin: auto&quot; height=&quot;355&quot; width=&quot;418&quot;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Literally nothing else happens. Godaddy.com fails to deliver even what the Internet was designed for: porn.&lt;/div&gt;



&lt;p&gt;

Anyway, this happened to me around September, 2010. I registered DenyConformity.com in August, 2005, and renewed it perfectly well over the next five years. Apparently, though, I forgot, and in 2010 it expired and was eventually sat (or shat) upon by a cyber squatting fiend. Luckily, DenyConformity.com is a lonely person&amp;rsquo;s seldom visited, angst-filled blog worth almost exactly nothing, so it was somewhat easy to just register it again and point it back at my site. It did mean that for a few days all you got when you went to DenyConformity.com was this garbage:&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/dc_down/small_squatter_1.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 600px; display: block; margin: auto&quot; height=&quot;490&quot; width=&quot;600&quot;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;You tried to visit DenyConformity.com. You probably meant Conformity.com.&lt;/div&gt;



&lt;p&gt;

Particularly amusing is just how these completely automated sites dealt with what they thought DenyConformity.com was for. Apparently the primary categories for my site, according to robots, is &amp;ldquo;Conformity,&amp;rdquo; &amp;ldquo;Deny,&amp;rdquo; &amp;ldquo;Real Estate,&amp;rdquo; and &amp;ldquo;Apartment for Rent.&amp;rdquo; I&amp;rsquo;m glad that for those few days anybody who wanted to see DenyConformity.com immediately got a link for &amp;ldquo;Conformity.&amp;rdquo; I guess I should be glad they weren&amp;rsquo;t making judgements about my life. Well,&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/dc_down/small_squatter_2.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 600px; display: block; margin: auto&quot; height=&quot;561&quot; width=&quot;600&quot;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;If you&#039;re looking for Shauvon McGill, perhaps you would enjoy these other cartoon characters.&lt;/div&gt;



&lt;p&gt;

According to this robot, I seriously need some psychotherapy, and am also, apparently, a cartoon. That was somewhat disconcerting.&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p&gt;

So I lost my domain for a few days and then got it back. Big deal? Well, the question is, how exactly could this have happened? It absolutely shouldn&amp;rsquo;t have is the answer. The fact is that Startlogic made absolutely no attempts to contact the account owner that their domains were expiring. Sure, the domains were still registered on my Purdue email address, and this was a year after I graduated, but my hosting account was definitely updated properly. They were perfectly content to let me continue to pay them for hosting access, even though my primary domain name, at the time the only way to access that web space, no longer existed. That&amp;rsquo;s a pretty great business model, I guess.&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p&gt;

That should have been my sign that the time to G the F was finally N. I pushed forward with my server at home and settled on a complacent, &amp;ldquo;eh, who cares?&amp;rdquo; Eventually, Startlogic dropped the final straw bomb that broke the camel&amp;rsquo;s back.&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/dc_down/site_suspended.PNG&quot; style=&quot;width: 600px; display: block; margin: auto&quot; height=&quot;366&quot; width=&quot;784&quot;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;At least it wasn&#039;t expelled, right?&lt;/div&gt;



&lt;p&gt;

It perhaps wouldn&amp;rsquo;t have been so annoying if Startlogic hadn&amp;rsquo;t picked the absolute worst time to drop this bomb. I just started a full-time job, so my free time immediately went from tons to nones. The very first day on this new job I received an email from Startlogic, saying the following: &lt;/p&gt;



&lt;blockquote&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;denyconf / Cgi abuse [9156098]&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p&gt;Hello ,&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p&gt;

This is to inform you that your website and CGI have been suspended. Your files are causing too many requests to the server and utilizing heavy network/server resources. The files causing the problems are given below:&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p&gt;

/home/users/web/b328/sl.denyconf/public_html/content/olds.php&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p&gt;

I suggest you to delete these files and upgrade your application and then get back to us. I will then revoke the suspension of website and CGI.&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p&gt;

If you have any further questions, please don&#039;t hesitate to contact us. We are available 24x7.&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p&gt;

Sincerely,&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p&gt;

Dylan Martin&lt;br&gt;

Technical Specialist&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;/blockquote&gt;



&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/dc_down/startlogic_closeup_2.png&quot; style=&quot;width: 77px; display: block; margin: auto&quot; height=&quot;101&quot; width=&quot;77&quot;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;This is probably Dylan Martin.&lt;/div&gt;



&lt;p&gt;

That probably doesn&amp;rsquo;t mean much to someone who doesn&amp;rsquo;t know anything about web developing, but don&amp;rsquo;t worry, it doesn&amp;rsquo;t mean much to me, either. Needless to say I did have further questions. I contacted them that evening, mainly to ask fuck, and what about it. I tried to get them to clarify exactly what they meant, or when or how these heavy resources were being used. However, nobody gave me any info outside what was stated in Dylan&amp;rsquo;s email. Let me be clear: this site hasn&amp;rsquo;t changed in six years. That file, /content/olds.php is the same olds.php which has lived right there in /content/ for as long as this site has existed. That&amp;rsquo;s what I needed clarification on. Just what, exactly, has changed? They had no answer for me.&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p&gt;

I understand that they have little room for customers using &amp;ldquo;heavy network/server resources,&amp;rdquo; but this time enough was enough. At this point I had no intention of fixing whatever &amp;ldquo;problem&amp;rdquo; suddenly appeared for no reason after six years. They made no effort to either warn me of the problem or work with me to fix it. Perhaps I&amp;rsquo;m being naive, but I feel like that&amp;rsquo;s not how a company should treat a (until this point) loyal customer of over half a decade. I had no interest in &amp;ldquo;upgrading&amp;rdquo; my application.&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/dc_down/small_bluehost.PNG&quot; style=&quot;width: 600px; display: block; margin: auto&quot; height=&quot;374&quot; width=&quot;600&quot;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Why hello, there, Bluehost lady.&lt;/div&gt;



&lt;p&gt;

After an evening or two analyzing my options, I decided to move my business to Bluehost (.com). I&amp;rsquo;ve worked with Bluehost in the past with no complaints, was referred there by a colleague or two, and had a reasonably positive exchange with one of their support team. Also, hey, they have a big &amp;ldquo;Stop SOPA&amp;rdquo; banner on their site today. After finding the host, it took another evening to go through the process of transferring all of my domain names (a process that is far too complicated). Then, frustratingly, I had to sit and wait five more days for the domain transfers to be processed (for which I blame Startlogic). Finally, though, the site is back up and running (as made clear by the fact that you&amp;rsquo;re reading it now). All that&amp;rsquo;s left to do is somehow get Startlogic to give me as much refund as I can get out of them.&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p&gt;

So, basically, if you need a summary of this post, because I can&amp;rsquo;t keep from writing page after page on the simplest of subjects, it is this: my website was down, for a reason I don&amp;rsquo;t know, and it took a week to get running again. Also down with SOPA.&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p&gt;

The real sad thing is that I was planning on posting the rest of my Halloween costume pictures last week . . .&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I have not forgotten about these pictures! Did you? Remember my Halloween costume from 2011, when I was going as a Tree? No? Remember, I made the whole thing out of paper grocery bags? This really isn&#039;t ringing any bells? Well, I don&#039;t blame you, it&#039;s been like four months since Halloween, and I&#039;m sure nobody cares about that grand old time anymore. Now that we&#039;re huddled in our houses trying not to either freeze to death or drown, depending on what crazy weather Chicago is throwing at us, let&#039;s kill time by just thinking back to when we were still thinking about the Halloween episode of the Office.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Ok, so let&#039;s get down to business, with the torso component of my costume. Better look up the Wikipedia page for &lt;a href=&quot;http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cuirass&quot;&gt;Cuirass&lt;/a&gt; now, because I&#039;m going to be using it a lot.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/costume/torso/torso_1%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;488&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;br&gt;
This is a picture of more paper bags. Hooray!&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/costume/torso/torso_2%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;488&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;br&gt;
The torso would need a much larger piece, though, so I had to glue two pieces together.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/costume/torso/torso_3%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;488&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Bam!&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/costume/torso/torso_5%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;488&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;br&gt;
I used a T-shirt (or teeshirt?) as a template. Soon I would have my own custom-made paper t-shirt (teashirt?).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/costume/torso/torso_6%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;488&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;br&gt;
I loosely traced the shape, and cut it out.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/costume/torso/torso_8%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;488&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;br&gt;
The back was slightly different than the front. It had a different collar and arm holes. They were both instantiated from the same tshirt (t . . . shirt?) pattern, though.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/costume/torso/torso_10%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;488&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Then I did a good old crinkle-crankle-up on them both to give them my patent-pending faux-bark (foe bark?) texture.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/costume/torso/torso_12%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;488&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;br&gt;
I glued the two pieces together just like a real t-shirt (tishirt?). One whole side (the right side in this picture) was un-connected from arpit to waist, to allow me to actually put the thing on. Paper is not nearly as flexible as shirt fabric.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/costume/torso/torso_13%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;488&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Which was quickly made apparent when I tried it on and it ripped in several places. I didn&#039;t want to be some sort of weird Tree / the Hulk costume, so I decided to reinforce the torso&#039;s various orifices (I&#039;m sorry about this sentence).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/costume/torso/torso_16%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;488&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Some rolled / crumpled up paper glued to the neck hole and the two arm holes stemmed the tears. Ooh, I mean dried up my tears. Yes, that&#039;s a much better joke on the word &quot;tears.&quot;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/costume/torso/torso_18%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;867&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Here it is on my body! The look on my face is due to the concentration it took to take this picture without using my hands.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/costume/torso/torso_19%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;488&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;br&gt;
But yes, it was sort of more of a paper apron (papron!) at this point.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/costume/torso/torso_21%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;488&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Anyway, I asynchronously worked on the shoulder structure. I have now used programming terms more than the promised &quot;cuirass.&quot; Sorry about that.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/costume/torso/torso_22%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;488&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Ok, so here&#039;s the idea. I built a framework out of folded-up bag bottoms (they are much more sturdy than the regular parts of bags). The two branches I decided on for the shoulders were well glued to the center piece. My idea was that this would allow the flexibility to move with my body, while still being sturdy enough to keep the branches from having erectile dysfunction.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/costume/torso/torso_24%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;488&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;br&gt;
But oh yeah, how would I be able to put it on with everything else? I sawed the branches off, so they wouldn&#039;t get in the way of working on the thing.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/costume/torso/torso_25%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;488&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Here we have the structure finished. the hexagon shape would go around my head, and the branch-connector would go behind my neck.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/costume/torso/torso_27%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;488&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;br&gt;
I lined it up inside the papron, to make sure all of my measurement were correct. That&#039;s not a typo, the only thing I measured was the gap between my shoulders.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/costume/torso/torso_28%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;488&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Some slits in the shoulders would let the branches stick out through the papron.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/costume/torso/torso_29%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;433&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Then I devised a brilliant scheme to connect the shoulder branches on the spot, after the neck truss and papron were donned. I&#039;m really knocking the crazy word count out of the park on this one.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/costume/torso/torso_32%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;433&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Here&#039;s the big idea. The shorter PVC pipe would be attached to the branch end sticking out of the truss, with the elbow permanently attached to that. The longer PVC part would be attached to the branch. Just with friction, the PVC pipe jammed into the elbow would hopefully be enough to hold the branch up, while still allowing the convenience of quick ass-/dissembly. Woah, I probably shouldn&#039;t use that term anymore, because it makes it seem like I want to dissemble my ass.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/costume/torso/torso_34%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;433&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;br&gt;
This process involved lots of glue. Ignore the wire sticking out of the end, though. I thought having a wire in the middle would add to the stability of it, but that was pretty dumb. It only made it more awkward.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/costume/torso/torso_39%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;433&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;br&gt;
For added strength, I drilled a hole in the connection.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/costume/torso/torso_40%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;433&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;br&gt;
And jammed a skewer in it, sawing off the excess. That puppy was pretty secure.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/costume/torso/torso_41%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;433&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Gratuitous. Seriously, though, the cutest cat.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/costume/torso/torso_44%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;433&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Here I am taking a look at the connection. Again, the wire was just getting in the way. Just imagine it isn&#039;t there, and that I&#039;m great.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/costume/torso/torso_46%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;433&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Here I am trying it on. The placement was pretty perfect, and the shoulder truss structure actually seemed pretty good, for a thing made out of paper and glue. Also, we have Facebook on the TV (TEEvee?)&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;../assets/images/costume/torso/torso_47%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;433&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Here&#039;s a closeup of how it sticks out of the papron. This allowed me to put the costume on pretty easily, by putting on the shoulder truss, then the papron - sticking the PVC elbows through the shoulders - and finally sticking the branches on. This method of donning made things much easier. Well, everything was easier except for the grammar needed to describe it.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Well, I have to get to bed. That&#039;s all for part 4. Hopefully I can get the rest posted without too many more parts! Thanks for sticking it out with me on this saga which will probably end up taking us to Halloween, 2012.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Heads up, here&#039;s another post about my old Halloween costume. Yes, this is the third post titled &quot;Halloween Costume &#039;011, part 4.&quot; This is actually part 5. Now, where was I?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/torso/torso_47%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;433&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Remember this? That&#039;s your recap.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/torso/torso_48%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;433&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;br&gt;
This is what the shoulder branch looked like. This isn&#039;t terribly tree-like.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/torso/torso_49%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;433&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;br&gt;
So I wrapped more tree paper around it to make it transition properly. I hoped that the various layers of paper would make it obvious that it was just paper. Theoretically, though, paper is made out of trees, so it&#039;s all the same anyway.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/torso/torso_51%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;433&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;br&gt;
I could still yank the branch piece out of the socket, so the plan was still good to go.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/torso/torso_54%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;433&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;br&gt;
I got rid of the wire, because I had determined that it was a terrible idea. To attach the branch, I had to maneuver it into the shoulder cone, get that stupid wire to stick in the tiny hole in the branch, and then get the PVC piece to fit into the elbow. It was a difficult thing to do, especially when wearing a full-on papron.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/torso/torso_55%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;433&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;br&gt;
The other side was much smaller than the PVC piece, so I had to add some material to make it fit better.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/torso/torso_56%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;433&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;br&gt;
So I wrapped some duct tape around it.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/torso/torso_58%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;433&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;br&gt;
And with some glue the PVC pipe fit much better.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/torso/torso_59%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;433&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Here&#039;s the finished shoulder truss.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/torso/torso_65%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;433&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Here&#039;s the papron with the other shoulder cone in place. You can also see the detail I added to the collar.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/torso/torso_68%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;433&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Now I had to get to work on the pauldrons. The suit of armor made of grocery bags would soon be fully realized.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/torso/torso_69%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;433&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;br&gt;
That was actually pretty easy. One quick piece of paper, and a little detail work was all it took.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/torso/torso_71%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;433&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;br&gt;
I attached a couple more pieces to fully cover the shoulder joint. I did not want to be a tree with big old armpits.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/torso/torso_72%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;975&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;br&gt;
That night, a friend of Alyson&#039;s stopped by and they wanted to see what the costume looked like so far. This was the first time I wore it all at once, so it was a good test to see how it all fit. It actually worked pretty well. I took a quick note of where the costume needed some more detail work (the beauty of a costume made of paper is that you can just jot notes down right there on your body).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/torso/torso_74%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;433&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;br&gt;
The next day I dug out the velcro sticky backs (which I had purchased for this very purpose), and got to work making it not a papron anymore.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/torso/torso_75%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;433&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;br&gt;
I stuck them right on, using three along the entire length of the side.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/torso/torso_77%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;975&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;br&gt;
They worked perfectly. I could now easily take the thing off while still having the important advantage of not being able to see my shirt underneath.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/torso/torso_82%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;433&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;br&gt;
I still needed to build the shoulder covering on the other side.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/torso/torso_84%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;433&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;br&gt;
So I did. I did that.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/torso/torso_85%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;433&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;br&gt;
There you have it, a perfect replica of a hobo&#039;s tuxedo - I mean a tree torso.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Stay tuned for the next installment, in which I made a few adjustments to things and then paint the whole thing a slightly different shade of brown.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I&#039;m always fascinated by technology and engineering. If it has gears, springs, mechanisms, or otherwise intricate little bits, it stands out, to me, as an artifact of human ingenuity. What is most fascinating, some times, about these seldom thought about tools is just how seldom we think about them. How often do you question the mechanism inside your bedside clock? How often do you contemplate the workings of your furnace, or your electric mixer? You shouldn&#039;t spend time thinking about these things, normally, because that&#039;s exactly what they&#039;re for. Tools, whether as complex as a mechanical clock, or as simple as an upside-down cup for trapping horrifying bugs, exist specifically to allow you to go about your lives with less to think about (or be terrified by, in the case of the bug-trapper). You shouldn&#039;t have to worry about whether your clock is accurate. I like to stop, some times, and appreciate just how much hard work and thought has gone into giving me that luxury. There is a certain strange irony in that; a great deal of thought and, certainly, a fair share of sleepless nights went into creating things just to allow others to think and worry less (or sleep just five minutes more). I guess most of these engineers and thinkers just do it for the fame and fortune, but still, even if the function is a side-effect, it seems worthwhile to me.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;That&#039;s just a long, nerdy way for me to justify and mitigate the inherent nerd-ness of beginning a pedantic exploration of one such tool, writing utensils. I am really sounding like a dork, now.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I&#039;ve always been interested in pens (and pencils). They&#039;re kind of a great equalizer. Even the President uses a pen, when he&#039;s signing his autographs or whatever he does. I know it&#039;s a little strange for somebody who is as obsessed with electronic gizmos as I am to be interested in something blatantly ye-olde-school, but like I said, they&#039;re quite interesting as engineering marvels. I have decided to share my interest with you, my faithful audience. I shall begin collecting pens, using them, and letting you know just how they compare to one another. Does it matter what pen you use, or are they just simple tools that give us yet another thing we don&#039;t have to think about? I seek to find out, and I&#039;ll keep you updated along the way.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;You should know, of course, that I am no expert in the field of writing utensils. I am so much a layman, in fact, that I don&#039;t even know what the field is called. However, I&#039;m not sure what qualifications are needed, if any, to review pens, so I&#039;ll just have to do my best. If nothing else, I&#039;m a normal person who doesn&#039;t mind spending moderate amounts of money to buy as many pens as he can in a quest for the best. Also, I might sometimes make rhymes, so watch out for that.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Still, some questions come up. What questions should I be asking when trying out a new pen? What are important features to consider, or benchmarks I can use to gauge quality? These are, after all, just pens, so perhaps I&#039;m already over thinking this. I shall do my best to answer the most important considerations I can think of, namely the following: &lt;strong&gt;comfort&lt;/strong&gt;, &lt;strong&gt;ink&lt;/strong&gt; and &lt;strong&gt;construction quality&lt;/strong&gt;, &lt;strong&gt;ease of use&lt;/strong&gt;, and &lt;strong&gt;price&lt;/strong&gt;. Perhaps over time I shall develop a set of rigorous tests I can use to quantify these qualities, or perhaps I will be able to develop a loose standard to compare them to, or maybe I&#039;ll just make up some numbers. Whatever the case, I think it will be an interesting diversion, if nothing else. What qualities or tests do you think I should apply?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Are there any pens you&#039;ve used which really stick out as good or bad? Have you seen pens which you want to know more about? Let me know, and I&#039;ll check them out for you. Maybe I can save you from having to spend upwards of several dollars getting a bad pen. Nothing is worse than that.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;You might be asking, Aren&#039;t there other websites which review pens? Aren&#039;t pens just basic implements that everybody uses and which can easily be gotten for free (with sweet company slogans printed on them, too)? Aren&#039;t reviews in general completely useless because they&#039;re based entirely on opinion, which - especially in my case - can vary radically? Who are you, Comrade Question? Maybe you don&#039;t have to read these things if you&#039;re just going to be so negative.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I just want to have some fun, play around with some neat little gadgets, and learn a thing or two. If you stay tuned right here then just maybe you might learn a thing or two, too.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Apparently the thing to do these days is write a catchy pseudo-sci-fi dystopian future novel and then have that novel adapted into a movie. I&amp;rsquo;ve therefore started working on a new novel, which is entitled &lt;em&gt;District Alpha: Government Mandate Zone&lt;/em&gt;. It&amp;rsquo;s about a young woman, named Kate, who gets swept away from her simple life on the robot farm to a grand adventure in a district where they control everything up to how much soda you can drink. Also there&amp;rsquo;s a hot guy named Matt in there. Anyway, here&amp;rsquo;s an excerpt from early in the book, where Kate and Matt are running to a safehouse where they can get some forged documents to help them escape District Alpha. Remember, this is a work in progress - some of the product placement and character descriptions might change as I get a better understanding of what would be best or most profitable in a movie. Also remember that the movie rights are still up for grabs!&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h2&gt;&lt;em&gt;District Alpha: Government Mandate Zone&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Excerpt from Chapter 5&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;. . .&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p class=&quot;firstChar&quot;&gt;Kate and Matt were running through the streets of District Alpha, conspicuous among the Government Mandated zombies shuffling through the street. The Peacecorps airship, which could also just be a car or tank if an airship cost too much to do, scanned the alleyways with its searchlights for any sign of Mandate Runners.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Kate looked over at Matt, a single bead of sweat running down her perfectly curved forehead. She marveled at his ability to keep his hair really well styled in exactly the fashion of the early to mid 21st century, about as much time after this book comes out as it takes to make a movie. &lt;em&gt;How does Matt know so much about the past&lt;/em&gt;? Kate thought. He insisted once that he collected books and movies from the period, and that if his great-grandparents hadn&amp;rsquo;t bought as many books and movies as they could - several copies of each, in fact - he never would have been able to survive. If it wasn&amp;rsquo;t for heroes like Matt&amp;rsquo;s great grandparents, the Government Mandate might have completely wiped out society as his great grandparents knew it. Matt was always grateful for his ancestors buying as much as they could all the time.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Ducking into an alley, the two of them crouched behind a dumpster, because even in the future they still have garbage. The irony - if there was any, I don&amp;rsquo;t really have time to check - was lost on them, so consumed were they by their fear of the Peacecorps Airship (or car, as the case may be).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Suddenly their fears ran straight into cold reality like someone realizing that a mirror was actually a doorway with their long lost twin standing in it. A really, seriously bright searchlight swept the alleyway, and Kate could hear a technotronic voice call out from behind the glaring flash.&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Hey, somebody get that ironic dumpster out of the way!&amp;rdquo; The robotical voice proclaimed. It was a Peacecorps Officer, speaking through his standard issue voice modulating, robotic face mask. Matt had heard rumors that the officers didn&amp;rsquo;t even control the voice which was emitted from their own masks, but it was actually a voice transmitted from the great Peacecorps Central Control Bureau, far away in District Omega. Matt whispered that thing to Kate, in fact, because this is important exposition that anybody would need to hear. Kate was not wondering if it was true, though, as another officer casually walked to the dumpster and began moving it out of the way. Kate was far too scared with fear to be concerned with rumors.&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Hello&amp;rdquo; the Officer said to the two main characters huddled behind the now moved-out-of-the-way dumpster. The officer&amp;rsquo;s menacing robot-like helmet made him look a lot like a robot. This allows Peacecorps officers to be killed en mass without necessitating an R rating.&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p&gt;Even though they were supposed to be crouched in garbage after having run for maybe miles, Kate and Matt still looked really good, like two high-profile movie stars. They were both acting scared, but not acting so much that they would have necessarily been up for an Oscar or anything. They were just regular, normal budget type scared.&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Well, lookie here, Officer Traldo,&amp;rdquo; said the lead Officer, hopping down from the airship / car. He was recognizable because he wasn&amp;rsquo;t wearing a mask like the others. He had the grizzled appearance of a guy who has been cast in a lot of movies as a bad guy, and as she looked up at him Kate got the feeling that this instance was no different. &lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;A couple &amp;lsquo;a&amp;rsquo; Mandate Runners I&amp;rsquo;d say,&amp;rdquo; the Peacecorps Leader said. He spoke with a thick accent, to be determined later. &lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p&gt;The Leader had the same imposing armor that the other Officers had, except he didn&amp;rsquo;t have a helmet as previously mentioned. The standard issue Peacecorps Officer armor had big plates of futuristic techno metal on important areas - Kate thought it looked like the robot feeding troughs they used to use on the robot farm she grew up on. Each Officer had a neat utility belt with all kinds of things that don&amp;rsquo;t really need to be described in detail, except for a gun which is holstered at their hip. The Leader had an additional feature on his left Forearm, a fancy computer interface, which he could use to do all sorts of computer tasks wherever he was. In all, the Leader of the Peacecorps patrol looked really, really cool. Kate thought to herself as he slowly walked toward them that he would be an excellent costume for somebody to go as for Halloween or to a comic convention or something, if only times weren&amp;rsquo;t so dark and dystopian.&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p&gt;The officer who moved the dumpster out of the way - who was apparently called Officer Traldo - looked over at the leader, who was standing in front of a billboard for the Nissan Leaf, a really great car that they still sell in the future because of how great it is. Traldo&amp;rsquo;s robobotnic voice crackled out an affirmative.&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Better have yer shootahs primed to lightnings, mates,&amp;rdquo; the Leader said. The other Officers flipped some switches on their really high tech looking guns, and held them ready in their hands. With a high-pitched whine, each pistol foreshadowed its dangerousness to Kate as she crouched behind Matt in fear. She did not know, as Matt did, that the pistols were high-power peace enforcement techno blasters, able to be switched from shooting geometric laser energy to high-voltage incapacification lightning, at the will of the officer carrying it. In lightning mode, anybody shot by the thing would collapse to the ground in pain and then be dead. Even Matt, with his good looks and knowledge of early 21st-century culture would not be immune to the lightnings&amp;rsquo; literal power.&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p&gt;Matt slowly stood, his hands raised in a clear sign of non-hostility. He wanted to speak to the officers, but he was a very courteous young man and knew that young adults should wait to be addressed by the older, wiser, officers before he could talk back. &lt;em&gt;What a courteous young man&lt;/em&gt;, thought Kate. &lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;So, thinkin&amp;rsquo; you could run your way out &amp;lsquo;a&amp;rsquo; District Alpha: Government Mandate Zone without any official permits, aye?&amp;rdquo; the Leader eyed Matt up and down, giving him the business.&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;No, sir,&amp;rdquo; responded Matt, with clear respectfulness and acquiescence in his voice. Reassured by his calm and courteous demeanor, Kate slowly rose to stand next to him in defiance of these Officers. &amp;ldquo;We were just looking for a little privacy,&amp;rdquo; Matt added.&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p&gt;The Leader eyed Matt with a stern eye. Then he eyed over at Kate with the same eye, still just as stern. Kate still had a look of fear on her face, because she was still afraid. The Leader didn&amp;rsquo;t think it was a look of fear, but actually embarrassment, you see. He then came to a conclusion.&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Oh, I see what&amp;rsquo;s -a- goin&amp;rsquo; on heah,&amp;rdquo; the Leader said with a grin. He elbowed the Officer next to him, sliding his high tech pistol back into his really cool looking hip holster. &amp;ldquo;we better be leavink these love birds alone, Traldo!&amp;rdquo; At that, the other Officers holstered their pistols, some of them even chuckling to themselves, which Kate could tell because their shoulders were moving up and down rhythmically.&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p&gt;Officer Traldo looked at the Leader with an important thing to say. Then he said it, by saying - in his crackled roboticon voice, &amp;ldquo;sir! Protocol indicates that we scan these civilians for Mandate Conformation.&amp;rdquo; Officer Traldo emphasized his pronunciation of &amp;ldquo;conformation&amp;rdquo; because you can tell it&amp;rsquo;s not &amp;ldquo;confirmation&amp;rdquo; when it&amp;rsquo;s written out like this, but if it were actually spoken it would be much harder to tell the difference. They use that word because it&amp;rsquo;s futuristic and cool sounding.&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Ack, so we should!&amp;rdquo; The Leader stepped forward and flipped a technoswitch on his wrist computer input panel. A large beam of orange or blue - whichever would read better on a movie screen - light swept over both Kate and Matt. Then, a readout appeared like a hologram - because it was a hologram - in front of the Leader&amp;rsquo;s face. The effect of the hologram-like hologram was really quite special, and Kate had never seen a special effect quite like it, growing up on a robot farm as she did.&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p&gt;Matt also thought the effect was special, but he had seen it before so it wasn&amp;rsquo;t quite as impressive to him. He stood there, staring into the special effect. His face, which looked just like either Ryan Gosling or Robert Pattinson, looked very determined and chiseled. He knew what the readout was saying to the Peacecorps Leader.&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;I&amp;lsquo;says &amp;lsquo;ere that you&amp;rsquo;ve &amp;lsquo;et your quota of soff&amp;lsquo;rink for this month, you,&amp;rdquo; the Leader said, looking past the hologram at Matt. &amp;ldquo;You better not be thinkin&amp;rsquo; about enjoying any more delicious, refreshing Coke if you don&amp;rsquo;t want to see my pretty mug again.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p&gt;Kate took note that the Leader used the term &amp;ldquo;enjoy&amp;rdquo; to refer to the delicious Coke-a-Cola that she had only recently become acquainted with. She remembered that &amp;ldquo;enjoy&amp;rdquo; was exactly what she had done when she first tasted it. She knew that one of Matt&amp;rsquo;s big character things was that he really enjoyed a good Coke, despite whatever the Government Mandate Zone specified their quota was per month in this terrible District they were stuck in - District Alpha.&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Ha ha ha!&amp;rdquo; the Leader laughed at them. Through a combination of being the future and because he&amp;rsquo;s obviously not a very kind hearted character, the Leader thought what he said about his mug was really funny. His laughs echoed off the alley, which, remember, had a billboard for the Nissan Leaf on it - a really great car of the future. The Officers all climbed back into the airship / car and flew / sped off. If it was an airship, the anti-gravity propulsion system kicked up a bunch of dust and stuff, almost like it&amp;rsquo;s spitting at the two of them in a big insult. I guess a car could do the same thing. Off the Officers went, shining their bright spotlights into the other alleyways ahead of them.&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p&gt;Finally, Kate turned to Matt, confusion replacing the fear that was painted all over her face in the medium of wrinkles and face muscles instead of oil or water colors. &amp;ldquo;I don&amp;rsquo;t understand,&amp;rdquo; she said to him, &amp;ldquo;I thought we had it for sure.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p&gt;Matt looked down at her. She was cute, like Zoey Deschanel, even though she probably wouldn&amp;rsquo;t take a role like this one. Matt was still realizing just how innocent Kate was, having grown up on a robot farm in District Epsilon. Did she really not understand what the Officers thought they were doing? Neither of them, of course, would have dreamed of doing any private type things for real just yet, even though they were both extremely beautiful and in their early- to mid-twenties, which is the most sexually attractive age, according to focus groups.&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p&gt;She looked up at him, patiently awaiting his answer. He looked at her features, which were really well defined and for a moment thought about how great they would have looked on a big movie screen.&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p&gt;Finally he responded to her. &amp;ldquo;I&amp;rsquo;ll tell you later, Kate,&amp;rdquo; he said. &amp;ldquo;Now, we&amp;rsquo;re almost to my old friend&amp;rsquo;s apartment, so let&amp;rsquo;s get going.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p&gt;They left the alley, running the last few blocks to Matt&amp;rsquo;s friend&amp;rsquo;s place. He hoped that she wouldn&amp;rsquo;t be put off by his friend&amp;rsquo;s awkward appearance, because he looked just like Steve Buscemi. He knew he would just have to deal with that as it happened, just like he had dealt with the Peacecorps Officers, when that happened a little while ago. He could deal with anything, except for the feelings he was now starting to have about this really pretty girl who - he didn&amp;rsquo;t know this yet - would probably be sleeping with him later in the story.&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p&gt;Off they went, on their way to the next adventure as they tried to escape &lt;em&gt;District Alpha: Government Mandate Zone&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Welcome to the all new, all awesome DenyConformity.com. What you see here is the culmination of over a year of obsessive, hard work. I know content has been a bit lax over the last year, but now I can finally show what I&amp;rsquo;ve been working on all this time. Welcome to the future. Welcome to DenyConformity.com.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I won&amp;rsquo;t go into depth here about the actual concepts I put to work in the design of the new site. I will continue my design journal entries for anyone out there who is wondering just what I was thinking (I know many of you probably don&amp;rsquo;t feel subject to change, and are therefore a bit lost on this new site). This post, instead, will be a sort of &amp;ldquo;readme&amp;rdquo; document for the site. I will update below with news about new features, additions, and tweaks to the site. Please also consider this post the sounding board for you to let me know what you think of the new layout, and if you have any ideas for ways to make it better. Just find your way to the bottom of the page and hit me up with a comment.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So without further adieu, I give you:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h5&gt;BETA 0.1.1 - &amp;ldquo;Agamemnon&amp;rdquo;&lt;/h5&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/site_beta/agamemnon_screenshot.jpg&quot; height=&quot;718&quot; width=&quot;1000&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The site as it appeared in its original beta version. Yes, you are all my beta testers.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The initial build of the new DenyConformity.com was released to the public on April 1st, 2012 (happy April Fool&amp;rsquo;s day!). This version of DenyConformity.com is still very much a beta release, meaning that it is not guaranteed to work perfectly across the board. The site has been tested and works properly in all modern browsers - Firefox 10+, Chrome 17+, Internet Explorer 10, Safari (probably), Android 2.2+, iOS whatever (I&amp;rsquo;m assuming), and oh, let&amp;rsquo;s just say Opera (who&amp;rsquo;s going to verify that?). The site works best at this point in Chrome or Firefox, and is designed to work at pretty much any resolution between 320 and 5000 pixels wide. Check the site out on an Android or iOS device, it&amp;rsquo;s pretty cool. However, I am very worried about how this site will work on my parents&amp;rsquo; extremely old, un-updated version of Firefox. If you find any bugs or you see something that seems wrong, please let me know via an email to beta[at]denyconformity.com.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Agamemnon&amp;rdquo; contains all the core functionality of the DenyConformity.com website. The main page, arranged to represent a &amp;ldquo;timeline,&amp;rdquo; shows a small summary of each post (split into pages of thirty posts each). Clicking on a post will take you to the post itself, using a dynamic AJAX-driven interface. The primary design imperative of the new DenyConformity.com is that all user experience takes place on a single page, and - except for extreme situations - no content will require a new page to load. Each post&amp;rsquo;s comments are displayed below the post, and a user can easily post new comments, still without ever leaving the page.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Agamemnon&amp;rdquo; ushers in a radical paradigm shift for DenyConformity.com, in a number of ways. First, I am and will be making a conscious effort to produce and gather regular original content. The primary goal of DenyConformity.com has and will always be to be interesting to as many readers as possible. I want the new DenyConformity.com to simply be a really interesting place to visit, and I will be working hard to meet that goal.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Also, the site now features ads on both the main page and next to each post. Though it might seem that DenyConformity.com has &amp;ldquo;sold out&amp;rdquo; or &amp;ldquo;gone commercial&amp;rdquo; or &amp;ldquo;whatever, Cracked is funnier, anyway,&amp;rdquo; the purpose of the ads - as it is on any website - is to allow me to hopefully get a tiny bit of compensation for the vast amount of work I have spent putting the site together. The goal, initially, is to cover the marginal cost for hosting the site. I am not allowed to tell users to click the ads, thereby increasing my potential revenue, because that&amp;rsquo;s against the terms of Google Adsense. I won&amp;rsquo;t tell you to feel free to click on as many ads as possible on my site. You&amp;rsquo;ll just have to use your own discretion.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This day marks a new era for DenyConformity.com (and, frankly my life in general). Continue to check back regularly as the site continues to evolve and grow into this new role.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I have a long list of features and modifications that I will be making over the next few months, so this is absolutely just the beginning. After six years, this fresh start will be the beginning of something truly great. I hope you will be patient with me as I work out the bugs, tweak things, and slowly (but surely) get all of the functionality set up that I have planned.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In the meantime, why not take a moment to follow Deny_Conformity on Twitter, or like my official page on The Facebook? I will share news and updates about the site as it progresses. Also, if you would share the site with your friends (or even enemies), I would definitely appreciate the traffic.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;UPDATE - 4/5/2012&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h5&gt;BETA 0.2 - &amp;ldquo;Bradbury&amp;rdquo;&lt;/h5&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/site_beta/bradbury_shot.jpg&quot; height=&quot;133&quot; width=&quot;449&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The updated timeline badges.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&quot;Bradbury&quot; addresses several bugs and problems with the initial release. New features / tweaks include:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Ads now cast square shadows. Also, ads will have black backgrounds, so the space won&#039;t be invisible anymore. Please disable your ad blockers on my site, as I really need the ad revenue.&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt;The Twitter box on the main page now casts a shadow.&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt;There was a bug on the post page which caused the back button to not work. Hitting &quot;back&quot; would only unload the ad frame, and not actually take the page back. This has been fixed.&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt;The &quot;go to comments&quot; button on the post page - the last button in the upper-left corner of the post - works properly, now.&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt;Navigating to http://www.denyconformity.com/post/[id]/comments will now take you directly to the comments.&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt;The timeline (the main page) now supports generic news items, which might link any old place. You might have used one of those to get to this very spot!&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt;You can no longer hotlink any image on my site (you can&#039;t post an image from my site on another site). It is also harder to save images from my site to your computer, because I don&#039;t want you to steal my pictures. If you want a copy of one of my photographs, I would be happy to help you out, but please do not steal my work.&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt;The new site now has a functional RSS feed. You can see the feed (or add it to Google Reader or something) by using the url http://www.denyconformity.com/rss.xml&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt;I have made a few visual tweaks, including the main page &quot;new post&quot; and &quot;news&quot; banners, and the comment boxes on the post page.&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt;I removed a few console debug messages and alerts contained within catastrophic errors. This will not fix the bug heretofore known as the &quot;Delbert Wilkins Bug&quot; but it should at least clear up some of the symptoms.&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;UPDATE - 4/5/2012&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h5&gt;BETA 0.3 - &amp;ldquo;Crazy Horse&amp;rdquo;&lt;/h5&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/site_beta/new_ad.JPG&quot; height=&quot;292&quot; width=&quot;1016&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;One of the all new post-Google ads.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&quot;Crazy Horse&quot; added three great new features to the site.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;First, all posts that contain images have a cool new image gallery. Just click on any of the images in the post to see them all in an easy to navigate enlarged view.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In addition to that, most of the images on the site can now be ordered as a high-quality print. If you find picture you like, check the lower-right hand corner of the image (when you put the mouse on it). Click on &quot;order print&quot; and you&#039;ll be on your way to your own piece of DenyConformity.com - as well as a really sweet piece of art to hang on your wall.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Finally, I have implemented the first of the new in-house ads. Please let me know if you would like to get your own ad here. Email beta@denyconformity.com for details.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;UPDATE - 4/25/2012&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h5&gt;BETA 0.3.5&lt;/h5&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/site_beta/broken_shadows.JPG&quot; height=&quot;646&quot; width=&quot;955&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;This is an example of how the timeline was broken. I (hopefully) fixed this for version 0.3.5.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I&#039;ve just made some tweaks and fixes, so this one isn&#039;t major. The main things are as follows:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Images won&#039;t break the timeline or post page (hopefully) when they load, now.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;The post controls are tweaked, so the button that takes you back to the timeline looks like a little house, now. I hope that&#039;s a bit easier to understand than an arrow pointing up.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;When you link directly to a post, the post title and description are loaded as page metadata. This will make it much easier to share posts on Facebook and whatever.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;A bug was causing captions to not show up in galleries. I fixed it.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;You can now navigate galleries with the arrow keys. Left and right switches images, up and down shows and hides the caption, and escape closes the gallery.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;UPDATE - 5/23/2012&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h5&gt;BETA 0.4 - &quot;Defiant&quot;&lt;/h5&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/site_beta/tags_page.png&quot; height=&quot;889&quot; width=&quot;1106&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The new tags page.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Version 0.4 - &quot;Defiant&quot; adds a great new feature to the site. For a while I&#039;ve been categorizing posts with a wide assortment of tags, and now you can browse all of those tags and get a list of all of the posts with those tags. The site uses six primary tags, which are as follows: comedy, technology, photo, idea, fiction, and personal. Now you can just see what you want to see out of the website.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;View all posts with a particular tag by going to denyconformity.com/TAG. This way, if you&#039;re only interested in looking at pictures, you can just go to denyconformity.com/photo, and you&#039;ll just get the posts about my photography.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Anyway, have fun browsing the list of tags (click the &quot;Tags&quot; button at the top of the site), and as always, let me know if you find any bugs or problems so I can fix them.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;UPDATE - 6/7/2012&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h5&gt;BETA 0.4.5 - &quot;Defiant&quot; (still)&lt;/h5&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/site_beta/tooltip.jpg&quot; /&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The site&#039;s new tooltip.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Version 0.4.5 isn&#039;t a huge update. It just added a handy new tooltip feature that will hopefully give helpful information about some things when you put the mouse cursor on them. Try hovering over a timestamp in the timeline or here on the post page - it&#039;s neat! I&#039;ve also finally put together an &quot;About&quot; page, which I&#039;m hoping will make it a bit easier to understand what&#039;s going on for visitors who are confused.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Hello, again, and welcome back to the epic story of my 2011 Halloween costume. First, we&#039;ll revisit the hat. You remember the paper shogun kap, right?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This ongoing thing sure is taking a long time to finish, but at least it&#039;s dumb!&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h5&gt;Part whatever: Fixing the kap&lt;/h5&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/hat_2/hat2_1%20copy.jpg&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Remember when the kap just looked like this? We ended up having to throw away that carpet because Elliott kept peeing on it. He&#039;s not a great friend.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/hat_2/hat2_2%20copy.jpg&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;I took the ol&#039; multitool to the head branches. They had to be removable, so the whole thing would fit into a suitcase. Every day I worked on this thing I grew more frustrated that I didn&#039;t decide to go as &quot;guy with tiny hat&quot; for Halloween.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/hat_2/hat2_6%20copy.jpg&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;I drilled a hole in the branch sticking out of the kap. I had to be careful not to drill into my head when I did this. Yes, in hindsight, it probably would have been easier to just take the kap off. It was just so comfortable.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/hat_2/hat2_7%20copy.jpg&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;A wire glued into the branch would make the joint strong. Yes, the thing on the right side of the picture is a sock. I don&#039;t know why there&#039;s a sock there.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/hat_2/hat2_9%20copy.jpg&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Here&#039;s the joint fully assembled, with some paper wrapped around to cover the gap. I would say it looked pretty good. In fact, I would even say that I would say it looked pretty good. I would go so far as to say that I would say that I said how good it would be. You might say that I have been known to talk about how I once said that I was talking to a guy about something . . . wait, what was I saying? Sometimes I get caught up in talking about what I&#039;m talking about.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/hat_2/hat2_10%20copy.jpg&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;With the branches removed, the kap became much easier to work with. I added more paper to the bottom so that my face would be completely framed by paper, and the kap would cover more of my neck. I was desperate to cover as much skin as possible, because obviously any exposed skin would break the illusion of a paper grocery bag tree. I still had to cover the rim of the face hole with crumpled-up paper. Eh, that was a pretty unfortunate sentence.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/hat_2/hat2_11%20copy.jpg&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Let&#039;s be honest. There&#039;s really nothing about this picture that makes me look cool.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/hat_2/hat2_12%20copy.jpg&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;So here&#039;s the kap after I finished the rim-job. There&#039;s got to be a better way to say that.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;h5&gt;Part whatever plus one: Painting&lt;/h5&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/paint/paint_1%20copy.jpg&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Andrew Monkey hooked me up with this pretty great spray paint. All I had to do was give him some money for them. It&#039;s a pretty great deal, if you ask me. I&#039;ve got bags full of the stuff buried in the backyard. I got these two colors, brown and greenish brown, to get a nice texture going. Andrew assured me that it was not glossy. Trees aren&#039;t shiny.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/paint/paint_2%20copy.jpg&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Remember to take these little washers out from under the nozzle before you try to use them. Also remember to take these little washers out from under the nozzle after you pack the cans in a bag with other stuff in it. Forgetting the former will leave you standing there all day getting no painting done. Forgetting the latter will leave you with the inside of your bag and whatever else you had in there nicely coated with a layer of high quality paint.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/paint/paint_3%20copy.jpg&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;I tentatively applied a swath of paint. Painting always makes me a little nervous because it&#039;s so permanent. After this point, there would be no turning back. I would never be able to have my grocery bag armor again.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/paint/paint_4%20copy.jpg&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;I started with the back of the torso, figuring that it would be the least prominent in the event that it didn&#039;t turn out great. I gave it a good coat of brown, hoping it wouldn&#039;t stay so glossy after it dried. Fortunately for Andrew, it did not stay very glossy.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/paint/paint_5%20copy.jpg&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Here&#039;s a closeup of the paint. It was too even and flat. I wanted more texture. I was hoping that the greenish grey color I also had would be able to make that happen for me.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/paint/paint_7%20copy.jpg&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Here&#039;s the kap after a nice coat of the brown stuff.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/paint/paint_8%20copy.jpg&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Here&#039;s one of the arms, with a stick inside to hold it up. I intentionally left a couple areas without much paint, thinking that it would accentuate the bark look. I found that by spraying at a very oblique angle, I could use the crinkles and crankles to get a nice uneven texture in the paint.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/paint/paint_9%20copy.jpg&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Here you see both arms and one of the legs, with the torso just to the left of the shot. I didn&#039;t put much brown at the base of the leg, because I was going to have it be mainly greengray.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/paint/feet_11%20copy.jpg&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Speaking of which, the color was actually called &quot;Manila Dark.&quot;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/paint/feet_12%20copy.jpg&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Here&#039;s the back of the torso, again, after a bit of Manila Dark texturing.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/paint/feet_13%20copy.jpg&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Check out this sweet closeup. I used a paper bag bottom as a mask to get nice straight edges on some of the highlights. Long, straight ridges are very characteristic of tree bark.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/paint/feet_14%20copy.jpg&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;It came out pretty great on the front of the torso, if I do say so myself. In fact, I did say so myself. Actually, I would go so far, myself, to say that I would say so myself. If you must know, I even said - oh, sorry, I&#039;m doing it again.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/paint/feet_15%20copy.jpg&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Another closeup of the texture. You can see the straight edges here.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/paint/feet_18%20copy.jpg&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Here you see one of the legs, one and a half of the arms, the bag bottom that I used as a mask, and my foot. I didn&#039;t paint my foot, but there it is, anyway.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/paint/feet_19%20copy.jpg&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;I also painted the sticks a bit to make them blend in a bit better with the color scheme. This was easier than finding a paint that perfectly matched the color of the sticks.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/paint/paint_10%20copy.jpg&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Back inside, now, it was time to put the finishing touches on the feet. If you&#039;re squeemish about people touching feet, don&#039;t worry, because these aren&#039;t really feet, and the touching is only figurative.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/paint/paint_11%20copy.jpg&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;For this, I turned to my good friend Sheet Moss, or Mousse Florale en Plaqu&amp;eacute;.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/paint/paint_12%20copy.jpg&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Sheet Moss is a messy business. It&#039;s composed of a bunch of sheets all crammed into a little bag. Doing anything with Sheet Moss leaves lots of moss and dirt crumbs all over. At least this party was going to be at a stranger&#039;s house.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/paint/paint_13%20copy.jpg&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The Sheet Moss was surprisingly easy to pull apart and hot glue to the paper. Making a mess with this stuff is inevitable, so it was just a matter of controlling where that mess happened.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/paint/paint_14%20copy.jpg&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;I used the Sheet Moss to cover up the gaps and seams in the foot, and also to provide some cool texture. I think it looked great, but I&#039;m sure not going to say so. Not this time.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/paint/paint_15%20copy.jpg&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Here you see the finished legs, with Sheet Moss expertly applied. It&#039;s &lt;em&gt;really&lt;/em&gt; easy to become an expert in Sheet Moss, especially when - like me - you&#039;re already an expert in making messes.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/paint/paint_16%20copy.jpg&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Did I mention that Sheet Moss is pretty messy? They really should call it Sheet Mess. So funny.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;We have only one more chapter of this epic struggle to get through, but I promise it will be the cool one. You&#039;ll finally get to see this thing on my body, getting down. At least, I got down as well as a dude wearing a suit of grocery bag armor can get down. Stay tuned! I promise the last chapter won&#039;t take me more than a month to post.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I love looking at all of the different shapes in a big city. Just before Christmas, I went downtown to take a few pictures. I wanted to try to capture the cool juxtaposition of lines and curves, the counterpoint of natural and unnatural. Here are some of the pictures I took. Let me know what you think!&lt;/p&gt;

