&lt;p&gt;The time has finally come to put this thing to a close. You&#039;ve stuck with me for five months as I&#039;ve slowly eeked out these pictures I took of my Halloween costume from 2011.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I went as a tree.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/paint/paint_18%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;433&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;This was the suitcase in which I had to fit all of my costume. Also, Alyson&#039;s costume (she went as a tide pool). Also, clothes for a weekend. The big suitcase in the lower left was the suitcase. We have a lot of suitcases, but you can only check one without it costing a billion dollars.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/paint/paint_19%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;433&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;For comparison, here&#039;s the suitcase with one of the legs in it. This was going to be a daunting task.&lt;/div&gt; 

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/paint/paint_20%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;433&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;But I was able to fold and pack and cram it in there. Turns out a costume made almost entirely out of crumpled paper is pretty easy to flat pack.&lt;/div&gt; 

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/paint/paint_21%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;433&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The torso looked pretty great, but I was very concerned about cramming it all into the little container.&lt;/div&gt; 

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/paint/paint_22%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;433&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Elliott insisted that it wouldn&#039;t happen.&lt;/div&gt; 

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/paint/paint_23%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;433&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Hey, I packed it all in. I started to think that maybe this would work out, after all.&lt;/div&gt; 

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/paint/paint_24%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;433&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;From this angle, however, it didn&#039;t look so great.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/paint/paint_25%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;433&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;I shoved and packed and stuffed and crammed it in there, though, and here you see that it all worked out. We headed off to the airport and made our way to Nashville, Tennessee to a super sweet party.&lt;/div&gt; 

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/final/final_1%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;433&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;This has nothing to do with the costume, but it is a sweet jack-o-lantern that I made the day before the party.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/final/final_2%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;433&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;I was holding on to these decorative leaves for a long time (though not as long as I&#039;ve been holding on to this picture). I had to glue them to my sticks to give myself some Autumn realness (trealness).&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/final/final_3%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;975&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;So I did that. This was the last step. The costume was done. All I had to do was put it on, which - granted - was a process in itsself.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/final/final_6%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;975&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Without further adieu. I went back and forth thinking about how to do my hands, but ultimately decided that I would sacrifice a bit of realism to be able to eat candy. I just found some sticks and held them. I was also going to paint my face to look like an owl&#039;s face, peering out from the hole in the tree. At the last minute I decided that I had done enough. At another last minute I had a brilliant decision to attach the foot roots to my shoelaces with wire. It made it much easier to walk. This thing was actually pretty impressive, walking across the room. I was stuck in this room, of course, because at about twelve feet tall, I couldn&#039;t fit through any doorways. I thanked the Halloween Gods for granting me a room with an ample ceiling.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/final/final_7%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;975&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Here is our prom picture. We both went as habitats. You can see here that my shoulder branches were already drooping. My &quot;brilliant&quot; system for holding up the shoulder branches was kind of a dud. To be fair, it was just made of paper. That ceiling fan scared me all night.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/final/final_4%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;975&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Here&#039;s Alyson with two of her friends. In the middle is a luminescent squid, and to the right is an angler fish. The angler fish was the host of the party. I had her to thank for getting a house with high ceilings.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/final/final_5%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;975&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Alyson is introducing herself to this girl with a pretty great monster face-on-her-face.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/final/final_8%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;975&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Here&#039;s a closeup of Alyson&#039;s sea urchin headpiece.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/final/final_9%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;975&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Alyson is explaining something apparently awkward to this witch girl and what was actually a really great Edward Scissorhands made at the last minute.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/final/final_10%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;975&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;I was a pretty stationary object at the party. I was almost, you could say, a tree. That&#039;s just how I am at parties, though. The costume was surprisingly mobile and comfortable, and I found that I could get down pretty hard when the right music came up. The dancing tree was the life of the party.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/final/final_11%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;975&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The crazy lighting at the party made for some interesting photographs.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/final/final_12%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;975&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The little dangler sticking out of the angler had a real LED light on it. It was a pretty great effect. Actually, it was a brilliant costume, because it was just a hat.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/final/final_13%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;975&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The pictures kind of get arty, now. I think they actually came out pretty great.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/final/final_14%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;975&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Each shot sort of captures not just one, but several moments in time. It&#039;s a great way to show the energy and excitement of a party.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/final/final_15%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;975&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Ikea lamp.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/final/final_16%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;975&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;This guy in a camouflage onesey was a pretty cool dude.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/costume/final/final_17%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;975&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;You can only just see it in this picture, but the girl on the right had an entire sleeping back attached to her. She was a slug.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Well, those are all of the pictures I have. Yeah . . . sorry about not having more of me in my costume, but I&#039;m always the one behind the camera, not in front of it. So this whole thing was long, boring, late, and ultimately unsatisfying. See you next year!&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Landscape photography is, perhaps, the last real refuge of the SLR camera. Point and shoot cameras, and depressingly even cellphone cameras these days, are designed to take portraits and light action. Mid- to high-quality point and shoots allow you to adjust aperture settings, shutter speeds, and even sometimes ISO settings, allowing people in bars and family events to claim some level of intelligence and knowledge about photography. However, to take a truly good landscape, you need a high-quality lens, an extremely high aperture setting, the most stable possible tripod mount, and the ability to take shots at mid-range ISO settings without much noise. For all of those things, you really need an SLR. I&#039;ve been living in a city with one of the most recognizable skylines in the world, and I have not taken much advantage of it yet. Well, just before Christmas, I headed out with my SLR to try my hand at some serious landscapes. Take a look at some of my shots.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/skyline/skyline_hdr_7%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1050&quot; width=&quot;700&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;I wonder what the most photographed building is?&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/skyline/path_hdr%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1051&quot; width=&quot;700&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;One really neat thing about landscape photography is that every single picture taken outside in the history of photography has been lit by the exact same light source.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/skyline/skyline_hdr_1%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;466&quot; width=&quot;700&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;It&#039;s wonderfully peaceful out on the Chicago lakefront in December. Quite cold, though.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/skyline/skyline_hdr_2%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;467&quot; width=&quot;700&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Something about the cold and the low azimuth of the sun can make the sky quite beautiful.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/skyline/skyline_hdr_3%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;466&quot; width=&quot;700&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;I had to open my aperture pretty substantially to take these, and as a result I discovered a few specs of dust on my camera sensor.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/skyline/skyline_hdr_4%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1053&quot; width=&quot;700&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;It&#039;s easy enough to fix in Photoshop, but its extremely troubling.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/skyline/skyline_hdr_6%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1051&quot; width=&quot;700&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;They&#039;re only noticeable when my aperture is at the highest setting possible, because that puts everything in as much focus as possible.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/skyline/lake_hdr%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;467&quot; width=&quot;700&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;I suppose this isn&#039;t, technically, a landscape, but it&#039;s still kind of nice.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/skyline/path_2_hdr%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1051&quot; width=&quot;700&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;I couldn&#039;t leave this spot without taking a few shots of these awesome shadows.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;That&#039;s all for today. Which is your favorite?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Not long ago, Alyson was reading a cosmopolitan magazine. I think it was called &lt;em&gt;Cosmopolitan&lt;/em&gt;, actually. Don&amp;rsquo;t worry, she isn&amp;rsquo;t actually into the thing. We were on a bus trip, so neither of us had anything better to do. As she flipped through the magazine, she found a super handy sex tip (that magazine has all kind of tips and tricks for the ol&amp;rsquo; saucy shuffle). The tip was, and I quote, &amp;ldquo;Turn your cellphone off during sexy time.&amp;rdquo; What a great idea. It inspired me to jot down a few of my own handy tips for really maximizing your pleasure-potentials. Here are my top ten, in one particular order (I&amp;rsquo;ll let you decide what the order is!).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Buy a bookmark. That way, you won&amp;rsquo;t be distracted by having to keep your finger wedged in your favorite book.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;If your Mother is visiting this week, tell her to go check out that cool new art exhibit at some building five miles away. By the time she gets there and realizes she&amp;rsquo;s been duped, you&amp;rsquo;ll be able to get your business completed at least once. She&amp;rsquo;ll be mad at you for tricking her, but that&amp;rsquo;s better than having to explain what those &amp;ldquo;strange noises&amp;rdquo; were.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Wash the dishes before you take anybody&amp;rsquo;s pants off. You&amp;rsquo;ll never get anything done with that crusty lasagna pan hanging over your head.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;If you live near a school, you should close your windows. Nothing kills the mood like hearing street vendors trying to sell ice cream and churros to kids at recess. We get it, dude, you&amp;rsquo;ve got flavored ice for a dollar. I&amp;rsquo;m trying to sow some oats here.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;I know it seems like a great time to think out the latest challenge at work or try to figure out what number goes in the corner square of your latest sudoku, but let me tell you something: it&amp;rsquo;s not. When the nasty is being done, you have to keep your mind focused on the task (literally) at hand. You can&amp;rsquo;t just sit there and let your mind wander. It&amp;rsquo;s not like pooping. Just pause to write down what you&amp;rsquo;re thinking about, then you&amp;rsquo;ll be able to pick it right back up in a few minutes when it&amp;rsquo;s all over with.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;It&amp;rsquo;s always a good idea to make sure your potential boots-knocker is actually interested in knocking on your boots before you get started. Nothing is more awkward than hearing &amp;ldquo;ok, that&amp;rsquo;s the last time I deliver a sandwich here&amp;rdquo; when your pants are halfway off.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;I know what you&amp;rsquo;re thinking, but there just is no suitable snack for accompanying a hearty doing it session. You&amp;rsquo;ll just have to wait until you&amp;rsquo;re done, and then have some chippy snack  or ice cream or something (depending, of course, on how the doing it went). Remember to offer your partner some (again, depending on how the doing it went). If you disregarded number 2, make sure you offer your Mother some, too.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;It&amp;rsquo;s always a good idea the first time you get onto the casbah with somebody to make a big chart showing different parts of your bodies along with the relative sensitivity to tickling each part has. It&amp;rsquo;s a time consuming process the first time, but boy is it worth it.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Whatever you do, don&amp;rsquo;t keep paperwork on each of your partners in neatly organized folders labeled with each partner&amp;rsquo;s name in a big file cabinet marked &amp;ldquo;Fornication Files.&amp;rdquo; You might think they will all appreciate your neatness and attention to detail, but man they really don&amp;rsquo;t. You&amp;rsquo;ll apparently never live that one down.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Always make sure you have a full range of the necessary supplies you might need, in case you have occasion to use them. You definitely don&#039;t want to be caught without the right things. You know what I mean. Actually, if you do know, let me know, because I&#039;ve never been sure.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;p&gt;There you go! ten DenyConformity Top Tips for being the best at the beast (with two backs). That&#039;s totally free advice! Here&amp;rsquo;s hoping my Mom doesn&amp;rsquo;t read this and finds out that I thought about sex once!&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I&#039;ve been pleased as punch with the response to the first excerpt from my new novel, &lt;em&gt;District Alpha: Government Mandate Zone&lt;/em&gt;. I was so encouraged by all the positive feedback, in fact, that I have decided to release the next chapter for your consideration! Even though everybody seems to love it, for some reason I still haven&#039;t been sent an offer for the movie rights. Reminder: the movie rights are still available!&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h5&gt;District Alpha: Government Mandate Zone&lt;/h5&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: center; font-weight: bold&quot;&gt;Chapter 6&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p class=&quot;firstChar&quot;&gt;The reports did not look good. District Epsilon was way over quota. Recounting the numbers was not going to help, just as it had never helped before.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Maximum Chamberman of District District 5 Dorald Yugdab pulled at his chin, hoping that the numbers would add up if he counted them all one last time. It didn&amp;rsquo;t work. His thoughtful grey eyes looked up from the Commpadd, burning a hole in Director Pagu, the poor soul whose duty it was to deliver this bad news. Yugdab did not have laser vision, but he might as well have had, as far as Pagu was concerned.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;What do these numbers tell me?&amp;rdquo; The Maximum Chamberman calmly asked. Yugdab spoke with a generic British accent, which obviously made him seem either intellectual, exotic, or aristocratic - it doesn&amp;rsquo;t matter which.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Director Pagu could not adequately respond purely by sweating, but it didn&amp;rsquo;t stop his body from trying. His mouth opened and closed as he tried to determine what Yugdab meant.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The Chamberman looked up at Pagu, his eyes narrowing. Pagu was staring intently at the pile of dogs curled up around the base of of the chamberseat upon which Yugdab sat. Like all Maximum Chambermen, Yugdab surrounded himself with comforts. His affinity for dogs was evident by his host of loyal canine pets. The host of beautiful, scantily clad ladies lining the chamber showed his affinity for scantily clad ladies. Nobody can really resist scantily clad ladies, really, and this grand setting featuring a lot of them would have been right at home as an important shot in a movie trailer. Pagu wondered what else Yugdab had an affinity for. He tried to remember if he had heard anything about laser vision. Pagu was a very nervous man who was always afraid that people had laser vision.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;What do these numbers tell me, Director?&amp;rdquo; Yugdab asked again, saying each word clearly. His voice was level and - to Pagu - terrifyingly relaxed. Pagu hadn&amp;rsquo;t become a District Director without learning an important lesson about what people sound like when they&amp;rsquo;re angry. Yugdab had no reason to not be angry, Pagu knew, so it must have meant that he was really, extra, laser vision caliber angry.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;District Epsilon is . . . over quota . . . ?&amp;rdquo; Pagu answered slowly.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Dorald Yugdab chuckled to himself. Handing the Commpadd to one of the Chamber aides, who were standing in a sweeping arc behind his plinth, Yugdab stood and stepped down to the Chamber floor. Standing level with Pagu, Yugdab still towered over him. History had proven that the tallest people were the best, and so it was no surprise that a man like Dorald Yugdab came to power. Standing exactly six feet eight inches tall, Yugdab cut an extremely imposing figure. He was a thin man, but he had the bearing of a genius, and his rugged good looks made everybody really like him, even if he was kind of a jerk. His red hair, cut short, and his smooth face were the paragon of fashion, and he always wore futuristic suits, which are basically like regular suits except they&amp;rsquo;re kind of shiny and made of space-fabric. Even though Yugdab was pretty old and wise, one of the advantages of his high status was that genetic tampering and age treatments left him looking much younger, as if he were about in his mid twenties.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;District Epsilon is over quota,&amp;rdquo; Yugdab mused as he paced across the Chamber floor, looking absently at the host of scantily clad ladies. &amp;ldquo;That&amp;rsquo;s what the numbers mean, Director. What do they tell me?&amp;rdquo; He was still talking with that cold, condescending way that would have really irritated Pagu if it hadn&amp;rsquo;t terrified him to the point of inventing a new language using sweat.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;I . . . I don&amp;rsquo;t . . .&amp;rdquo; began Pagu, turning to Yugdab who was standing in the middle of the Chamber with his back to the poor Director, picking through some fruit which was piled on one of the scantily clad ladies. Yugdab was that cool - he had a scantily clad lady as a fruit bowl.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Yugdab spun on his heel, throwing a long, narrow finger at the Director, screaming, &amp;ldquo;It means that you haven&amp;rsquo;t been doing your job, Director Pagu!&amp;rdquo; Venom and hatred were overflowing from his once neutral face. Pagu was almost relieved to finally be getting the stern talking-to that he was expecting all along. Pagu was also relieved that the sudden outburst hadn&amp;rsquo;t scared out of him what it almost scared out of him. He silently cursed his uniform standard white pants. He felt as if a thousand scantily clad lady eyes were on him.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Twenty seven districts I&amp;rsquo;m in charge of and every single one of them is under quota except for yours!&amp;rdquo; continued the Chamberman. Pagu flinched at each syllable, still waiting for the lasers to start firing from those deep, grey eyes. The pile of dogs stirred, and some of the dogs raised their heads as their master was getting angry. Suddenly it occurred to Pagu, counting dog heads, that there were quite a bit fewer dogs in that pile than he originally thought. Being torn to shreds by vicious gigantic dogs started to compete in his mind with being charred to a crisp by an angry man&amp;rsquo;s eye lasers. &lt;em&gt;If he cooks me with his eye lasers, those dogs will eat me,&lt;/em&gt; Pagu thought to himself, with a shiver down his spine.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Pagu was not particularly aware of what Yugdab had said, but even if he had, he wouldn&amp;rsquo;t have known that it wasn&amp;rsquo;t true. District Epsilon was not the only district to be over-quota. In fact, many of the districts within District District 5 were over quotas or in some crisis or another. Yugdab was the only man who knew the truth about every district. He was a very shrewd politician and leader, sharing nothing with his subordinates. The ability to not tell your underlings that you aren&amp;rsquo;t doing that great is a sign of a really good leader - something that Yugdab totally was. He slowly walked around Pagu, menacing him.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;You will increase the zombie count in District Epsilon by ten percent,&amp;rdquo; Yugdab said, talking through clenched teeth to suppress the anger that was welling within him. Pagu was weighing the pros and cons of being eaten alive by giant dogs versus being fried to a crisp by angry lasers. Yugdab&amp;rsquo;s clear order snapped the Director out of his mental turmoil.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Sir, that&amp;rsquo;s not going to be easy . . .&amp;rdquo; Pagu began. He wanted so desperately to just say &amp;ldquo;yeah, sure, ok,&amp;rdquo; but he knew it would be much worse to have to face these dogs and these lasers and who knows what else if he failed what was probably an impossible mission. It was obviously the most tactful solution to let Yugdab know now that what he wanted would be impossible. Pagu prided himself on his ability to tactfully find the path least likely to lead to his being lasered.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Then you had better get started, Director.&amp;rdquo; Yugdab responded, returning to his plinth and collapsing back into his chamberseat. The dogs settled into a new pile arrangement.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Pagu&amp;rsquo;s eyebrows furrowed ever so slightly, and he found himself once again fighting the urge to ruin his white pants. He raced through his mind, trying to run the numbers, visualising the spreadsheet displayed on the very commpadd he had just handed his boss. He hardly had enough idlers left in his district to afford mandating that many more zombies. Then he realized a thing he had thought earlier. &lt;em&gt;Who knows what else is waiting to destroy me besides the dogs and lasers?&lt;/em&gt; Pagu thought to himself. He was suddenly aware of the vaulted ceiling above him, and the conspicuously tiled floor below. &lt;em&gt;I bet that ceiling opens up,&lt;/em&gt; he thought to himself. &lt;em&gt;The ceiling opens up and, what, these floor tiles are on little catapults? Oh no, he&amp;rsquo;s going to catapult me out of a 126 story building. He&amp;rsquo;s going to catapult me and then he&amp;rsquo;s going to skeet shoot me with his eye lasers and then his dogs are going to have raining breakfast.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Yugdab simply glared at the young Director. The Chamberman knew what was going through Pagu&amp;rsquo;s head. Not the catapulting stuff - nobody just looking at the guy would know any of that. If someone were there who could read thoughts, they would probably feel extra important with this knowledge that Yugdab didn&amp;rsquo;t have, just like people who watch movies after reading the book feel superior to those who skip the book. Yugdab was more interested Pagu&amp;rsquo;s thoughts about the statistical analysis of his District&amp;rsquo;s zombie counts. Before today, Yugdab had little faith in Pagu, and now he had none. This young Director had proven his inability to understand the nuance of Government Mandate Zones, seeing things purely as numbers on a spreadsheet. Yugdab knew, though, that mandating citizens went far beyond simply running the numbers. Pagu&amp;rsquo;s district, District Epsilon, was a major source of manufactured goods for the rest of the districts in the District. As a result, the workers in District Epsilon were cocky, thinking they could drink all the delicious Coke and eat all the Taco Bell that they wanted. In all fairness, anybody would feel inclined to do that, because those are both really delicious and satisfying things. However, the Government had to make an example of these workers, to show them - and the neighboring districts - that Government Mandate Zones were not to be trifled with.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Would industry suffer? Marginally, perhaps, but the overall increase in productivity as citizens buckled down in fear of the Mandate would more than make up for it. Besides, zombies could work most machinery just as well as many of the citizens in District Epsilon. These sorts of things went right over Pagu&amp;rsquo;s head, but Yugdab was such a great thinker that it came naturally to him - and he was so good at expressing himself that someone just looking at his face as he glared there would have picked up all of this cool background information just from his subtle facial expressions.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Pagu bowed his head obediently, giving Yugdab a &amp;ldquo;yes, sir.&amp;rdquo; He turned with the efficiency of a bureaucrat and nervously walked the long length of the chamber to the grand exit. With each step he became more sure that the tile beneath him would launch him like a clay pigeon.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Yugdab watched the man walk away. He turned to one of his aides and called him by name, which was &amp;ldquo;Cranden.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Cranden obediently responded. Yugdab knew each of his sixty three aides up and down. He knew their strengths and weaknesses, so he would know exactly who would be best suited for each of his myriad tasks. For example, he knew that one of his aides, named Ruddle, was almost completely useless, except for the most basic of tasks, which is why he chose that aide to hold his commpadds for him. Ruddle often even managed to screw that up.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Cranden was an excellent aide, however. He had served the Chamberman for almost six years, and Yugdab knew the time had come for the young man to get the promotion he deserved. With his eyes still fixed on Director Pagu, making his way daintily out of the chamber, he gave the orders that would change two men&amp;rsquo;s lives forever.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;It will be up to you to see that zombie count is mandated.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Yes, sir.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;And see to it that former Director Pagu is the first one.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Yes, sir.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Yugdab leveled his expressive eyes on the aide. &amp;ldquo;Congratulations, District Director Cranden,&amp;rdquo; he said.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The slightest hint of a grin showed on the new Director&amp;rsquo;s face. His time had finally come. All he could say was, &amp;ldquo;thank you, sir,&amp;rdquo; which is why he said exactly that before stepping out of line and heading out of the chamber. It was Cranden&amp;rsquo;s job, now, to set about giving Pagu a fate worse than death - worse even, perhaps, than being launched, cooked, and eaten by catapult, laser, and dog, respectively. It was common knowledge that it was really annoying to be a zombie.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Maximum Chamberman of District District 5 Dorald Yugdab allowed himself a brief moment to reflect. There was much to do, and he could afford very little time to staring off thoughtfully, but those sorts of things really make a character look like they have a lot going on, so that&amp;rsquo;s what he did. Only for a moment, though.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Then he stood, briskly making his way to the side door, which led to his personal offices. &amp;ldquo;Ruddle, come with me,&amp;rdquo; he said, &amp;ldquo;the rest of you are dismissed.&amp;rdquo; He had found that the only way to keep Ruddle from being completely, utterly, sometimes destructively useless was if he kept the dullard at his side at all times. Only under the strictest of supervision could the boy - he was 17 and looked like a poor man&amp;rsquo;s Michael Cera - get anything done without making a mess of it. Yugdab occasionally found himself checking to make sure he hadn&amp;rsquo;t recruited a zombie by mistake. As the two of them approached his office, the other aides, the scantily clad ladies, and the pile of dogs all shuffled offscreen.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Yugdab kept the simple lad around because there was something about the glassy look of his eyes, the blank expression on his face, and the perpetually open mouth that made it easy for Yugdab to open up to him. He was able to talk through his plans, as he paced back and forth in front of his giant office window. Yugdab had always found it useful to voice his ideas, and in the process they would somehow fit together and reform as even better ones, like taking ice out of a freezer to melt a little bit and then putting it back in so that it all froze into one giant supercube. The Chamberman&amp;rsquo;s ideas were like perfectly formed ice cubes, but by sounding them out and fitting them together, he could create the most supercube of ideas.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Really, Yugdab&amp;rsquo;s technique was not unlike that of a writer, blindly stabbing at mixed metaphors and misplaced symbolism in the hope that eventually some words will happen to fit together into a coherent sentence or two. To Yugdab, Ruddle was like a big whiteboard which Yugdab could throw darts at until he happened to collect enough ingredients for an idea-sandwich.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Long ago, when Yugdab was actually younger, and not just synthetically younger, Yugdab had had a stuffed bear, his cherished possession. He spent hours sharing his secrets and his schemes with that bear, in the privacy of his bedroom. He never knew what happened to his beloved Bobo, but he found a certain similarity in the inanimate stuffing of this Ruddle. One difference was that Ruddle wasn&amp;rsquo;t quite as good at holding important commpadds as the stuffed bear, but Yugdab had grown to expect that by now.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;As they came through the office door, Ruddle managed to stumble over the threshold, as he always did, and drop one of the commpadds he was holding, as if doing so specifically to illustrate his incompetence. Yugdab ignored it. He had given up trying to force some sense into the boy. He was already launching into his train of thought for the afternoon.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Another district over quota, Ruddle. These citizens are getting harder to keep under mandate. How do they expect us to survive with what we have if they keep insisting on taking more than their share?&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;I don&amp;rsquo;t know,&amp;rdquo; replied Ruddle.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Yugdab looked over at the blank face, which was breathing through its mouth as always. &amp;ldquo;Do you remember what I told you about rhetorical questions, Ruddle?&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;. . . uh . . . no,&amp;rdquo; replied Ruddle.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Yugdab simply sighed and looked back out the window. The view was quite impressive from the chamber atop the 126-story District District headquarters building, in the heart of District Alpha. Yugdab knew he could see all the way to the edges of his District District, and he glared at the thought of District District 4, and the ever present competition of Maximum Chamberman Auldis Doogon just over the horizon. He went back to the thoughts inside his beautiful little head.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Twenty-seven districts. Each one with countless citizens, all striving to be the best they can. What gives them all the opportunities to prosper, Ruddle? We do! The Government Mandates keep these districts from falling apart. I do. Just think what a difference I could make if I were selected to be Chamberman of District District 1! Chamberman Zeldo&amp;rsquo;s health is declining by the day. It&amp;rsquo;s only a matter of time, now, before someone will be asked to take his place. It should be me! I know I&amp;rsquo;m the best suited. I know the chamber of elders see me as the obvious choice. If only that damned Doogon weren&amp;rsquo;t always one step ahead of me. They&amp;rsquo;re just waiting for one of us to slip up, to give way for the other to take District District 1 and the world. I won&amp;rsquo;t be the one to make a mistake. I won&amp;rsquo;t let Auldis Doogon take what&amp;rsquo;s rightfully mine. What does he know about Government Mandates, anyway? Have you seen the reports of District District 4 Mandate Zones?&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Ruddle was pleased to finally have a question he knew the answer to. &amp;ldquo;Nope!&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;It&amp;rsquo;s like he doesn&amp;rsquo;t even care about quotas! Why, in his wheat processing district, citizens are allowed to shop at Macy&amp;rsquo;s as much as they want! How can they possibly keep order when they can go to such a wonderful and quite affordable under any budget department store for all of their domestic needs? Where&amp;rsquo;s the supply for that? How can everyone in an entire district get fashionable accessories? I can&amp;rsquo;t even imagine! Think of District Sigma, or even Epsilon. Millions of people live in those districts. We don&amp;rsquo;t have enough of this season&amp;rsquo;s hottest styles for everyone in one Mandate Zone, let alone a District, or by damn, the entire District District!&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Ruddle thoughtfully made bubbles with his spit. He was getting quite good.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Don&amp;rsquo;t you see, Ruddle? Every man, woman, zombie, robot, and child out there is a District, and I won&amp;rsquo;t rest until each and every last one of them is mandated! I&amp;rsquo;ll mandate them a hundred times if it means I can stay one step ahead of that blasted Doogon and his free spirited ways!&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Just then, a familiar dingle dongle sounded from the door to the Chamber room. As Yugdab turned, the door opened to reveal one of his aides - a quite tech savvy young man whom Yugdab had stationed in the radio surveillance department. Yugdab expressed his frustration at having his train of thought derailed with a quick, &amp;ldquo;whatisit?&amp;rdquo; The toxic chemicals contained within his train cars of thought were spilling all over the innocent villages of thought inside his vast mind.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Sorry to bother you, sir, but you requested to be notified if a particular set of frequencies was detected.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Yugdab immediately perked up, then composing himself again - careful to hide his excitement from these aides - he asked, &amp;ldquo;What of it?&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Well, sir, we picked it up. It showed up yesterday morning, in the outskirts of District Alpha: Government Mandate Zone, and it took us some time to confirm. It seemed to have come from District Delta, which makes sense, sir. I believe we were unable to pick up the signal before now because it was being masked by interference from the high concentration of robot farms in that district.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Ah, I see. You have a report, there?&amp;rdquo; Yugdab gestured toward the commpadd in the aide&amp;rsquo;s hand.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Yes, sir, I prepared a complete report for you.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The aide began to hand the report to Ruddle, as was customary by now, but Yugdab quickly stepped forward and took the commpadd from the aide himself. He hated having to show the slightest interest in the report, but he just couldn&amp;rsquo;t bear to see Ruddle drop this one on the floor, for the great possibilities that the report could signify. With as much nonchalance as he could muster, he took the commpadd to his desk.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Thank you, that will be all.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The aide left with a nod. Yugdab stared at the report, looking for the specific frequencies indicated. He would have read the data to himself, but this is really important exposition, so he spoke to Ruddle as he processed what he saw.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;There are the frequencies, alright. I had almost forgotten. After all these years . . . Why now? It seems awfully dubious that these frequencies should emerge now, with me so close to being promoted to District District 1. There&amp;rsquo;s only one thing for it, I&amp;rsquo;m afraid. I&amp;rsquo;ll have to get to the bottom of this. I&amp;rsquo;ll have to choose my best aide to find the source of this signal, and bring it back to me.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Riddle got excited. &amp;ldquo;Me sir?&amp;rdquo; he asked.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;No,&amp;rdquo; Yugdab replied. He set the pad down and took another moment to reflect. Two moments in one day was certainly a lot of reflection time, but he certainly deserved it after the last several pages. He had a lot of planning to do. He had just sent his best aide to a new assignment, and now he had to pick another one to waste his time on what could very well be a wild goose chase through the streets and alleyways of an entire District. He wondered if this was a ploy by Doogon to sap his resources. One thing was for sure, though. Life was never dull for the Maximum Chamberman in District Alpha: Government Mandate Zone!&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;For the last few days, there have been no ads on DenyConformity.com. I suppose that isn&rsquo;t really a surprise. Before about a week ago, there had never been ads on DenyConformity.com. However, this is an annoying and frustrating turn of events. I want to be serious about this website, and so far I&rsquo;m pretty proud of myself (this is the ninth day of consecutive updates!). However, to be able to take this seriously, I will need to come up with some way to pay for it. I&amp;rsquo;m afraid I will have to come up with a new solution.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I was using Google AdSense, a pretty simple system to potentially monetize web content. The idea is that you put some code on your website that Google gives you, and then when people go to the site they&amp;rsquo;ll see ads that are tailored to the content on your site. It uses Google&rsquo;s fancy algoribbons to pick ads that are related to the stuff on the site (at least for the most part). When visitors click on the ads, you get a very tiny cut. Through my testing process over the last few months, and the first week of the new DenyConformity.com&amp;rsquo;s life, it worked perfectly.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I have two ad locations. One is on the main timeline, at the top of the page. It&rsquo;s a leaderboard size ad, which falls back to a smaller banner if the screen is smaller, and a mobile banner if the viewer is on a smartphone (or has a tiny browser window for some reason). On the post page (the page you&amp;rsquo;re reading this on), a skyscraper floats to the right side of the content. This ensures that the user has one ad on any page that contains content, and they aren&rsquo;t obnoxious or in the way. With AdSense, I was getting ads for costumes, Chicago businesses, and sci-fi novels, among other things. I felt that those things were pretty accurate for the content I have here.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/site_beta/broken_ad.png&quot; height=&quot;260&quot; width=&quot;1014&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;This is what my ads look like now. How will my readers get access to &lt;em&gt;Cool Runnings&lt;/em&gt; costumes (an actual ad I saw here a few days ago)?&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Well, I guess it didn&rsquo;t exactly work perfectly. The problem is that I made an uncomfortable bed for myself with this ridiculously complicated and ambitious design. There are plenty of reasons why the site looks the way it does, but the problem is that it doesn&rsquo;t really cooperate with Google AdSense. You see, AdSense has some pretty hefty caveats. First, it has to load with the page, so you can&rsquo;t load ads with Javascript after the page has loaded. Second, their ad code is for one specific size, and one specific size only. Third, their crazy terms specify that their ads can&amp;rsquo;t exist inside iframes. They stipulate these things for very specific and justified reasons.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;How is that a problem for me, though? Well, first, since my site only had one page load, and all the content is pulled using Javascript, I have to be able to load ads dynamically. Second, this site is responsive, which means that the same page will load on any size screen, be it a phone, tablet, netbook, or 30-inch cinema display. I can&amp;rsquo;t load the same size ads for a smartphone as I load for a 30-inch monitor, so the ads on my site have to also be responsive. Finally, the only way I can overcome those problems is by loading their ad code in an iframe, which I can then reload dynamically depending on window size, device, user navigation, or whatever.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I figured they would have a problem with what I was doing, but since I was just bending their rules to make it work, I hoped that they could work with me and perhaps make an exception. They say the rule of thumb is, &amp;ldquo;whether you&amp;rsquo;d feel comfortable explaining what you&amp;rsquo;ve done to a website that competes with you,&amp;rdquo; and &amp;ldquo;ask, &amp;lsquo;Does this help my users?&amp;rsquo;&amp;rdquo; Every choice I made was specifically with my users in mind, and I am not ashamed of anything I did on this new design. However, when I started getting impressions and (a tiny amount of) clicks, they simply shut me down. My account is suspended, my ads are disabled, and all of my requests for further information or support have gone unanswered. After perusing the AdSense forums, it is my strong opinion that with what I&amp;rsquo;ve got going on, I&amp;rsquo;m not getting AdSense back.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I can&amp;rsquo;t blame them. This is a world that entire industries have popped up to take advantage of and cheat. We&amp;rsquo;re talking about a thing where you can put ads on a web page and you get money every time somebody clicks on them. I can think of about fifty different ways somebody could screw with that to get free money just off the top of my head. Basically, after years of dealing with garbage, Google isn&amp;rsquo;t messing around, and they don&amp;rsquo;t have time to deal with violators, legitimate or not.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So, fine, I can tell when I&amp;rsquo;m not wanted. Using Google AdSense was a bit of a shortcut, anyway. It was a cheap way out, and that&amp;rsquo;s not the DenyConformity way. If there&amp;rsquo;s anything that defines this website, it&amp;rsquo;s that we do things the very, very hard - and usually dumb (but at hopefully at least entertaining) way. I just need to figure out the proper DenyConformity.com approach to ads.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;To be clear, I&amp;rsquo;m actually all for advertising in general. I think it serves a valuable purpose, namely to give people access to free stuff. If I can maintain this website, get paid for it, and still let people out there come here and get a laugh or two for free, I don&amp;rsquo;t see anything wrong with it. The fact is that this would be a much more expensive world - I mean absolutely anything you spend money on - if we didn&amp;rsquo;t have ads. As long as they aren&amp;rsquo;t getting in the way or making things more difficult, I&#039;m happy to have them around. That&amp;rsquo;s why I don&amp;rsquo;t see it as a &amp;ldquo;sell out&amp;rdquo; move to try to get a little ad revenue here.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Still, I don&amp;rsquo;t want to sit here and defend my motivations for trying to monetize this project, because there&amp;rsquo;s nothing to justify. I&amp;rsquo;ve spent more time working on this website than I&amp;rsquo;ve spent on anything else in my entire life, and I know that I&amp;rsquo;ve provided a respectable amount of entertainment value to the world. The simple fact is that I deserve to be compensated for what I&amp;rsquo;ve done, and I need capital to continue working on it as I move forward. End of story.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So how can I raise that capital? Should I have annual pledge drives, like PBS? Should I quietly but regularly ask for donations from my visitors? That relies pretty heavily on my audience being pretty generous (and have plenty of disposable income). Should I get some t-shirts or other swag and sell them at reasonably marked up prices? That worked for Homestar. Should I start selling prints of the photos I&rsquo;ve posted here? Should I solicit ads myself, personally finding companies to advertise directly to my tens of regular visitors? As the site&rsquo;s presence grows (and I&rsquo;m hoping that with my new focus on regular updates it will), that might actually become somewhat viable. Should I start a subscription service, where most of my content is behind a paywall that requires some sort of modest fee? Should I start trying to write commercially, and sell stuff I write to actual big-time publishers and websites?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The fact is, I&rsquo;m going to start working on looking into all of the above. Stick around and help me try out some of these things that I should have been looking into long before now.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Thanks for your continued support!&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A DenyConformity.com review.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;George Safford Parker is a classic example of the American Dream. In 1888, Parker was fed up with having to constantly repair the fountain pens he sold for the John Holland Pen Company, so he did what anybody back then did - he made his own. In 1891, Parker found his first investor, and went on to forge one of the largest pen companies in the world, from a rickety (and presumably ink-stained) shack in Wisconsin.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;For decades, Parker was essentially the Mercedes Benz of writing instruments (sort of a Mercedes Penz, if you will). Year after year, Parker continued to innovate and perfect the fountain pen, taking a short break at one point to invent the mechanical pencil. Later, just after his death, Parker (the company) released the Parker 51, &amp;ldquo;The World&amp;rsquo;s Most Wanted Pen.&amp;rdquo; It was in every way revolutionary, technologically advanced, and beautiful.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/parker_jotter/parker51.jpg&quot; class=&quot;noprint&quot; height=&quot;625&quot; width=&quot;400&quot;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The most popular fountain pen ever made.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This was a time when perfectly useful pens weren&amp;rsquo;t sitting around pretty much everywhere. To own a nice, dependable pen was a pretty important thing for a gentleman, like owning a nice car or pocket watch fob or something. If you needed a good pen, you had a &amp;ldquo;51.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/parker_jotter/jodl%20copy.jpg&quot; class=&quot;noprint&quot; height=&quot;468&quot; width=&quot;700&quot;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Even if you were a Nazi.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In 1945, Nazi General Alfred Jodl signed the treaty which ended World War II in Europe. He used, of course, his own trustworthy fountain pen - a Parker 51. Remember, Parker started in Wisconsin. Here we were, in the clutches of war, fighting over who could rule the world, and Parker was a trusted name on both sides.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/parker_jotter/rockwell-61%20copy.jpg&quot; class=&quot;noprint&quot; height=&quot;517&quot; width=&quot;700&quot;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Also there&amp;rsquo;s this.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Of course, the American Dream doesn&amp;rsquo;t end there. Parker (the guy)&amp;rsquo;s dream of &amp;ldquo;making a better pen&amp;rdquo; lived on for decades, until it gave way to the new American Dream, a multinational corporation. In 1993 Parker (the company) was acquired by Gillette, and then in 2000 they were purchased by Newell Rubbermaid, parent company of Sanford, which is now the largest stationery company in the world. Sanford (and Rubbermaid) also owns Sharpie, PaperMate, Liquid Paper, Prismacolor, Waterman, and Uniball. In 2009, Rubbermaid decided to close down Parker&amp;rsquo;s factory in Janesville, Wisconsin, where Parker (the guy) originally founded the company over 120 years earlier.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Parker (the guy)&amp;rsquo;s legacy lives on, however, and many excellent pens are still made under the Parker (the name) name. The Sonnet and Duofold continue the legacy of the venerable &amp;ldquo;51,&amp;rdquo; and the Jotter, introduced in 1954, is in its 58th year of production. As far as I can tell, that makes the Jotter the longest running cartridge-based ballpoint pen in history. A few weeks ago, I bought my very own.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/parker_jotter/IMG_9172%20copy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;467&quot; width=&quot;700&quot;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Its design and construction has changed somewhat since it was first introduced. Today the Jotter primarily comes with a stainless steel cap and button with a plastic or steel barrel and a metal nozzle. Beginning a few years after its introduction, Parker fit the Jotter (in fact all of its pens) with the characteristic Parker Arrow clip. Parker makes a big deal about how the Arrow clip will let everybody you see know that you don&amp;rsquo;t have just any pen.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/parker_jotter/IMG_9187.jpg&quot; style=&quot;max-width: 500px&quot; height=&quot;1128&quot; width=&quot;752&quot;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;That&amp;rsquo;s one of the most pretentious things I&amp;rsquo;ve ever heard.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Far more important than the stupid arrow clip is the Jotter&amp;rsquo;s tungsten carbide writing ball. Introduced in 1957, the &amp;ldquo;T-Ball&amp;rdquo; refill was the first of its kind. Pretty much all ballpoints have a similar design today, so the legacy of Parker innovation is right at home.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In the hand the Jotter feels incredibly light, especially compared to similar steel-body retractable pens like the Zebra F-402. That certainly has to do with the fact that the model I have been using features a plastic barrel, but even the all steel model feels just as light. The action of the button is quite heavy compared to other retractable pens (in a good way), and at the risk of sounding pretentious, that satisfying click is the most characteristic feature of the entire pen. It feels louder. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/parker_jotter/IMG_9185%20copy.jpg&quot; style=&quot;max-width: 500px&quot; height=&quot;1050&quot; width=&quot;700&quot;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It looks great, too. The smooth curves and brushed steel give the pen some serious elegance. In the world of retractable ballpoints, you really can&amp;rsquo;t find a classier pen. Faintly etched around the middle seam are the Parker emblem and name, as well as, for some reason, &amp;ldquo;France.&amp;rdquo; They&amp;rsquo;re obviously trying to make the pen seem grander than it is. Let&amp;rsquo;s face it, Parker was founded in a garage in Wisconsin. It was only in 2009 that Rubbermaid moved the company&amp;rsquo;s production to France. Aside from the ham-fisted branding, I doubt the French have had much influence over the pen&amp;rsquo;s classic design.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Take the pen apart, and you get a look at the real Parker legacy, the ink cartridge itself. When the Jotter was introduced, it was the first ballpoint with a serious replaceable cartridge. It originally would last more than five times longer than other ballpoints at the time. Since then, refill cartridges have been standardized and modern industry has perfected their construction, so the &amp;ldquo;Quinkflow&amp;rdquo; ballpen refill isn&amp;rsquo;t as amazing as it once would have been. My pen has the Medium point, but a fine point option is available.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The Jotter&amp;rsquo;s diminutive size and elegant design do come with a downside, of course. The pen features no rubberized grip or ergonomic finger grooves, and those lovely curves actually mean the spot where you grip the pen is relatively small. It&amp;rsquo;s nothing you can&amp;rsquo;t get used to, for sure, but if you&amp;rsquo;re more familiar with more substantial writing instruments (or you have giant monster hands), you&amp;rsquo;ll find your fingers cramping up just a bit. I also noticed a few times while using the Jotter that the tip extends from the barrel just a tiny bit less than most other pens. This must sound terribly pedantic, but it is actually a bit disconcerting. Perhaps it&amp;rsquo;s just me, but there&amp;rsquo;s something ever so awkward about writing with that tip only half-way out.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;These days a ballpoint pen&amp;rsquo;s ink isn&amp;rsquo;t terribly startling. A ballpoint&amp;rsquo;s a ballpoint, certainly as far as most end users should be concerned. The ultimate problem with the Jotter is that it is, in fact, just a ballpoint, and so it is ultimately victim to the problems that beset ballpoint pens. Pretty recently, my Jotter has started doing the thing that most ballpoint pens do at one point or another. Basically, it turns into a sort of embossing pen instead of an ink pen. This is a result of the fact that ballpoints are actually based mainly on luck. The ink will stop flowing over the ball, no matter what kind of carbide it is, and the only marks you get on your paper are the shameful marks of a ballpoint that doesn&amp;rsquo;t work. In other words, you have a bunch of those &amp;ldquo;make it write&amp;rdquo; scribbles in your margins.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It only happens sometimes, but I kind of don&amp;rsquo;t expect it from something from &lt;em&gt;France&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/parker_jotter/IMG_9181%20copy.jpg&quot; style=&quot;max-width: 500px&quot; height=&quot;1050&quot; width=&quot;700&quot;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So since I don&amp;rsquo;t really have metrics to judge pens, yet, and since this is the first pen I&amp;rsquo;ve reviewed, it&amp;rsquo;s hard for me to sum this review up. The Jotter is an excellent pen - perhaps the best ballpoint I&amp;rsquo;ve used in my entire life. It comes down to a few important questions, though. Sanford has really reduced the ubiquity of Parkers since they bought the company. Maybe it&amp;rsquo;s a move to make them seem more &amp;ldquo;prestigious&amp;rdquo; or maybe they&amp;rsquo;re just cutting corners. The end result is that it&amp;rsquo;s supposedly not terribly easy to find Jotters anywhere. I got mine at Office StapleMax or whatever, and there are certainly plenty of Jotters online, so they aren&amp;rsquo;t actually that difficult to find. The real problem is price. At about $6 per pen, they&amp;rsquo;re more than twice the cost of a Zebra F-402, which is a pen I used faithfully for years before somebody &amp;ldquo;borrowed&amp;rdquo; it a few months ago. Sure, $6 is not terribly much, but is it really worth that much more than the Zebra? I guess I&amp;rsquo;ll let you know when I review the Zebra.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The other question is one of morality. What has happened to Parker (the legacy)? What was an American - nay, a Worldwide - tradition has become a boutique novelty. Parker (the company) is now a pretentious arm of a faceless conglomerate bent on world domination. Should we disregard the obnoxious &amp;ldquo;France&amp;rdquo; rebranding? Should you buy this artificially rare object of groan-inducing pretense, shamelessly abandoning the respectable legacy of an almost forgotten man from American history? Will you buy a Parker Jotter and support this cycle of corporate greed?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Well, no. You&amp;rsquo;ll buy a Parker Jotter because it&amp;rsquo;s a really good pen - the stainless steel standard by which all pens shall be judged.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(The Parker ads and the picture of Jodl came to me from Google)&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A DenyConformity.com Guide&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Welcome to the world of public transportation! So you found yourself wanting to be somewhere, and you came to the conclusion that you had to take the bus. Despair no more! A city bus is a logical place, governed by a strict set of rules. Those rules may seem intimidating to someone who isn&amp;rsquo;t a professional bus rider. No longer! With this handy pocket guide (if you open it on your smartphone it is, anyway) you can act like  one of the bus riding elite.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/bus_guide/guide_logo.jpg&quot; height=&quot;215&quot; width=&quot;700&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Fig. 0 - The logo for this guide&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Everyone knows that the moment a member of the non-bus-riding community - a Sidewalker, as bus riders call them - sets foot on a bus full of professionals they will be laughed at and mocked with a precision that is unequalled in other areas of professional public interaction. If you have truly exhausted all other methods of traveling to your destination and you cannot think of a way to get there without riding a bus, you cannot step onto the bus looking like you don&amp;rsquo;t belong. The following steps will not help Sidewalkers turn themselves into professional riders, but they&amp;rsquo;ll at least be turned into professional fakers.&lt;/p&gt;


&lt;h5&gt;Step One: Know your Bus&lt;/h5&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/bus_guide/type_twodoor.jpg&quot; height=&quot;209&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Fig. 1 - The Standard eight-row, two-door Single Decker&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A professional bus rider spends years studying the seating layouts, intertia ratings, smell zones, and average speeds of an entire city&amp;rsquo;s bus armada. Without a lifetime to devote to knowing these minute details, you must do your best to fake this knowledge.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/bus_guide/type_bendy.jpg&quot; height=&quot;98&quot; width=&quot;750&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Fig. 2 - The Middle-Hinged Double Single Decker&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;These diagrams showcase the most standard types of bus employed by cities across the United States. Make yourself familiar with them, to call into your mind as you step onto the bus. When you make your way to a seat with confidence, the scornful eyes of the professionals on the bus will think you&amp;rsquo;re one of them.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/bus_guide/type_eyecontact.jpg&quot; height=&quot;196&quot; width=&quot;750&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Fig. 3 - Two-door Single Decker Variant: &amp;ldquo;The Awkward Eye Contact&amp;rdquo;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Always remember that you can count on a few things being true on every bus you are forced to ride on. First, every bus has wheels. This is something that can be very comforting, because you can know that the wheels on your bus will go round and round all through the town. Unless, of course, the bus breaks down or has a crash. Also, the pigs on the bus go &amp;ldquo;oink, oink, oink&amp;rdquo; e-i-e-i-o. Wait, that can&amp;rsquo;t be right . . .&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/bus_guide/type_inquiry.jpg&quot; height=&quot;206&quot; width=&quot;750&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Fig. 4 - Two-door Single Decker Variant: &amp;ldquo;The Board of Inquiry&amp;rdquo;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It is not a guarantee that the bus you are about to enter has the same layout of seats that you might be ready for - or that it has any seats at all. Bus makers get very bored, because making a bus is really boring, so they will change the seating layout for no reason. Because of this, almost every bus you enter will have a completely different seating arrangement.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/bus_guide/type_noseater.jpg&quot; height=&quot;196&quot; width=&quot;750&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Fig. 5 - Two-door no-seater Single Decker (&amp;ldquo;The Cattle Car&amp;rdquo;)&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;When standing on a bus - which you will have to do if you find a bus with no seats - remember to hold on to something attatched to the bus, and not the person next to you (see &amp;ldquo;Do&amp;rsquo;s and Don&amp;rsquo;t&amp;rsquo;s,&amp;rdquo; below).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/bus_guide/type_aerostar.jpg&quot; height=&quot;368&quot; width=&quot;700&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Fig. 6 - The McCutcheon Family&amp;rsquo;s Ford Aerostar&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The City picks bus sizes based on the population density of the area they are serving. If you live in a tiny city without many people, you might just have to talk to someone who lives down the street from you and treat their car like the bus. You can have fun making their car filthy, and they can have fun yelling &amp;ldquo;exact change&amp;rdquo; at you, and not stopping to pick you up when they see you standing at the corner.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/bus_guide/type_train.jpg&quot; height=&quot;43&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Fig. 7 - The Triple-hinged Tetrabus (nicknamed &amp;ldquo;The Subway&amp;rdquo;)&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Sometimes a bus isn&amp;rsquo;t actually a bus. These are called &amp;ldquo;trains.&amp;rdquo; They are faster and scarier than a bus, but most of the same rules apply.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/bus_guide/type_magic.jpg&quot; height=&quot;319&quot; width=&quot;750&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Fig. 8 - One-door Magic Single Decker&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Many schools employ a bus battalion to ferry students between home and school. Remember that when you see one of these bright yellow affronts to design they will not pick you up. They aren&amp;rsquo;t there to take you to work even if you have the $2.25 for them - unless you work at school, and you&amp;rsquo;re 12.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/bus_guide/type_omnibus.jpg&quot; height=&quot;539&quot; width=&quot;600&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Fig. 9 - The City Omnibus&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The word &amp;ldquo;bus&amp;rdquo; actually comes from the Olde English &amp;ldquo;Omnibus&amp;rdquo; meaning &amp;ldquo;every smell.&amp;rdquo; The first bus was built in 1794, as a transportation device for crates of stinky cheese. The actual content of the bus might have changed in the intervening years, but basically everything else is the same - including the smell.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/bus_guide/type_greyhound.jpg&quot; height=&quot;523&quot; width=&quot;700&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Fig. 10 - The Greyhound&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Some forms of bus go long distances, from city to city. Sometimes these are called a Mega Bus, because they beat up smaller vehicles. However, these are not a city bus, and so they are outside the scope of this guide.&lt;/p&gt;


&lt;h5&gt;Step Two: Behave Like a Pro&lt;/h5&gt;

&lt;p&gt;You might think that everyone on the bus is drunk. This is only partially true. The reality is that everyone on the bus merely looks drunk. When you first set foot on the bus, you will experience a moment of disorientation, as if your entire world were suddenly racing along at around five miles per hour. That is only the bus, meandering down the street to the next bus stop. Try to maintain your composure as you make you way down the bus aisle, but keep in mind that looking like you&amp;rsquo;re having trouble keeping your balance is perfectly natural.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Unlike drunk people, however, bus riders follow very strict rules of conduct. If you want to fit in, and keep your trip from being even more worse than it already is, you should stick to these rules, too.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/bus_guide/rule_1.jpg&quot; height=&quot;529&quot; width=&quot;750&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Fig. 11 - Fill as large a space as you can.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This is the most important rule that all Professional Bus Riders follow. You can use your imagination and be creative. Put your feet up, sit diagonally, or bring a giant backpack with you. Bus riders don&amp;rsquo;t keep score, but if they did, it would be based on how much space you take up. Be the largest person on the bus, and you win!&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/bus_guide/rule_2.jpg&quot; height=&quot;682&quot; width=&quot;750&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Fig. 12 - Don&amp;rsquo;t scoot over unless someone tells you to.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The important distinction here is that you can disregard other passengers who merely ask you to move. The answer is always no.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/bus_guide/rule_3.jpg&quot; height=&quot;650&quot; width=&quot;650&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Fig. 13 - Smell as bad as you can.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;It can help if you know you will be having a bus trip in your future, because you can go without bathing or changing your underpants for a few days. What causes the stink is up to you. Some riders keep urine-soaked towels with them so they always have a perfect bus-worthy stench at all times.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/bus_guide/rule_4.jpg&quot; height=&quot;523&quot; width=&quot;750&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Fig. 14 - When someone gets up from a seat in front of you, do not sit in the seat.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;By all means, there&amp;rsquo;s no reason why you should take that empty seat right in front of you, especially if the bus is full of people. If nobody behind you can sit there, why should you?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/bus_guide/rule_5.jpg&quot; height=&quot;638&quot; width=&quot;750&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Fig. 15 - Always get up while the bus is in motion.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;It may seem counter-intuitive, but real pros don&amp;rsquo;t wait until their stop has arrived. Get up from your seat several blocks ahead of your stop, making sure to only move when the bus is moving. This ensures that you cause the biggest disruption as you leave - your other primary goal aside from taking up as much space as possible.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/bus_guide/rule_6.jpg&quot; height=&quot;707&quot; width=&quot;750&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Fig. 16 - When two adjacent seats open up, it&amp;rsquo;s first come, first served.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Two adjacent empty seats are like a big, delicious Value Meal to bus riders. When someone gets up from a seat, leaving a pair of adjacent seats open, those seats are officially up for grabs. They will become the domain of whoever gets there first, so keep an eye open for these succulent prizes, and grab them before one of those selfish people standing in the aisle get it. Then you can sit on the aisle seat, blocking those whiny Elderly and Infirm from moving in on your domain. Also important: never sit next to someone you are riding the bus with. If you are traveling with a friend, consider sitting a few rows apart, because yelling to each other is much more fun than casually talking to someone sitting next to you.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/bus_guide/rule_7.jpg&quot; height=&quot;878&quot; width=&quot;750&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Fig. 17 - No matter how many people are on the bus, it can always hold more.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;First, it goes without saying that if you&amp;rsquo;re waiting at a bus stop you should make sure you get in front of everybody else waiting at the bus stop, so when the bus stops you get first dibs of any open seats on the bus. When those doors open and you see a solid wall of humanity because the city has cut funding to the bus system so there isn&amp;rsquo;t enough room for everyone, do not hesitate. Only Sidewalkers do something lame like wait for the next bus. You could be standing there, looking like an idiot, for whole minutes!&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/bus_guide/rule_8.jpg&quot; height=&quot;196&quot; width=&quot;750&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Fig. 18 - Maintain the accepted standing zones.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Always stand your ground when you&amp;rsquo;re standing on a bus. That is, awkwardly stagger your ground, because that is most likely the best you can do with the bus driver constantly slamming on the brakes like they&amp;rsquo;re trained to do. If more people start to collect in the aisle, you are in no way obligated to make your way farther back, and you especially don&amp;rsquo;t have to stand in the raised area in the back. Consider it a demilitarized zone.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/bus_guide/rule_9.jpg&quot; height=&quot;217&quot; width=&quot;500&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Fig. 19 - Bring a snack.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Going minutes without eating usually gives most professional bus riders the shakes. Because of this, you should bring a snack along to fit in. As soon as they see you not having withdrawal from McDonald&amp;rsquo;s, they&amp;rsquo;ll know you&amp;rsquo;re not meant to be there. Unshelled sunflower seeds and the smelliest of Italian beef are the best snacks to enjoy on the bus. A good rule of thumb is to ask yourself, &amp;ldquo;would I eat this thing in the presence of someone else when not on the bus?&amp;rdquo; If you say no, you&amp;rsquo;ve found a perfect snack for a crowded bus.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/bus_guide/rule_10.jpg&quot; height=&quot;272&quot; width=&quot;400&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Fig. 20 - Bring the proper entertainment.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Bus Riders don&amp;rsquo;t read books. A newspaper is good, only because it requires you to keep your arms wide while reading it, helping you take up more space - just remember to leave the newspaper on your seat when you get off the bus. A cellphone is another great option, especially if it has a good speakerphone option. The bus is a great place to make personal phone calls. If you find yourself without anything to do, strike up an argument with the empty seat next to you.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/bus_guide/rule_11.jpg&quot; height=&quot;2783&quot; width=&quot;3168&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Fig. 21 - Use proper language.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;You are on a bus, not an elementary school. If anything, you have an expletive minimum. If you are having a conversation with your friend two rows down, someone on your phone, or the empty seat next to you, feel free to shovel d-, a- and especially f-bombs into your parlance as much as you can. You get extra points if you are sitting next to a child.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/bus_guide/rule_12.jpg&quot; height=&quot;3438&quot; width=&quot;2632&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Fig. 22 - Disregard the Elderly, the Infirm, and Expectant Mothers&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;What, are you running a charity? Where do those geezers need to go in such a hurry? Isn&amp;rsquo;t walking a necessary component of physical rehab, anyway? What, her baby daddy couldn&amp;rsquo;t borrow his mom&amp;rsquo;s car for the afternoon? Most Elderly, Infirm, and Expectant Mothers you see on the bus are faking their condition, just so they can cheat and take your seat away from you. Those big walkers and huge bellies? They&amp;rsquo;re just a ploy so these people can take up as much space as possible. Are you going to let them beat you at what is now your own game? While we&amp;rsquo;re on the subject, have you noticed the funny symbols on the seats in the front of the bus? That weird picture of a guy with wheels? It&amp;rsquo;s just there as a joke. Of course you have wheels - you&amp;rsquo;re on a bus!&lt;/p&gt;


&lt;h5&gt;Step Three: Do&amp;rsquo;s and Don&amp;rsquo;t&amp;rsquo;s&lt;/h5&gt;

&lt;p&gt;DO NOT eat anything you find on the bus.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;DO NOT stow your bike on the bike rack. Did you smash your bike? What are you doing on the bus?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;DO take advantage of the fact that the bus is just really big trash can.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;DO assume everybody else on the bus is inferior to you.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;DO NOT utilize your lap. Your stuff has as much right to a seat on the bus as you do, and more right than that grumpy-looking person standing in the aisle.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;DO always give money to anybody on the bus who asks for it. There&amp;rsquo;s a strict honor code among Bus Riders, so that guy who needs a couple bucks will definitely get you back.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;DO whatever the stinkiest, noisiest person on the bus is doing, because they&amp;rsquo;re the best at riding a bus, and if you act like them, you&amp;rsquo;ll get extra respect from the pros.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;DO NOT rely on another person for support while the bus is in motion. That person is teetering on the brink of falling over just as much as you are. If you hang on to him, you&#039;re just going to make him spill his Salisbury steak.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;DO memorize the bus schedules and routes before making any attempt to ride anywhere. You don&#039;t want to be 45 minutes into your trip and suddenly realize you&#039;re on the number 9 &lt;strong&gt;B&lt;/strong&gt;, which for some reason goes to the opposite side of town from the number 9 &lt;strong&gt;A&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;DO whatever you can to avoid taking the city bus in the future. They are universally terrible.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Please understand that everything here is a joke and should not be taken seriously. - Shauvon&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

