&lt;p&gt;Twice a month (or so), I will choose one lucky reader to win an actual prize. I&amp;rsquo;m not making this up - it is a real thing that I will send right to whatever address you want. The only catch is that the prize is a knight - a real Sir Prize. Get it? &amp;ldquo;Sir Prize?&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It&amp;rsquo;s a surprise, okay? I&amp;rsquo;m not telling you what it is. You&amp;rsquo;ll just have to put up with my dumb jokes if you want to find out. Also, you have to jump through a few hoops. You see, I&amp;rsquo;m still working on adding features to the site, and one of the features I&amp;rsquo;m working on is some functionality to share the site with all that newfangled &amp;ldquo;social media.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Yeah, I could put a little &amp;ldquo;F&amp;rdquo; or &amp;ldquo;T&amp;rdquo; button on my posts to let you easily send a link to your friends and followers, but that just seems so - well - &lt;em&gt;conformist&lt;/em&gt;. I&amp;rsquo;m thereby looking for exciting, hilarious, awesome, or downright weird ways to share the site and all its great content to everybody out there. Here&amp;rsquo;s how you come in.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Share the site! It&amp;rsquo;s that easy. Just get the word out - any way you can - and let me know how it worked out. Please email examples of your sharing endeavors to sweepstakes@denyconformity.com, and in a week I&amp;rsquo;ll pick the idea that either worked the best or otherwise appealed to me the most. That&amp;rsquo;s right - you have one whole week to get the word out there and then get word of that word to me.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Invite people to tweet about the site with the #DenyConformity hashtag. Invite people to the DenyConformity.com Facebook page. Burn a giant version of the DenyConformity.com logo into the lawn of your favorite congressman or celebrity (don&amp;rsquo;t actually do that). You have until next Saturday to get the word out, at which point I will choose a lucky person to send this &lt;strike&gt;junk I found&lt;/strike&gt; sweet, sweet prize to.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Once again, please email your ideas, experiences, successes and failures to sweepstakes@denyconformity.com. I will contact you if you are the winner to get your mailing address and other information. Good luck to you all, and thanks for your continued support!&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Yes, the prize is real. I promise that it is not garbage or completely worthless. This will be the first of many Saturday Sweepstakes, so do not miss your chance to go down in the annals of history!&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Just last weekend was the annual Chicago Comics and Entertainment Expo, or C2E2. This is the second year that I&#039;ve gone, and the first year I went on a Saturday. It&#039;s a pretty exciting event, and though it costs $35 ($25 if you buy tickets ahead of time), I think it&#039;s worth it. A comic convention is a pretty interesting place. A large number of people are - for this one weekend - free to finally express their nerdy fantasies. It&#039;s the only time you can see chubby versions of your favorite movie and comic book characters. I really wish I could have gotten a costume together, because it really is a lot of fun. I did, of course, bring my camera.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/C2E2_2012/IMG_9201.jpg&quot; height=&quot;533&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;C2E2 takes place each year in McCormick Place, just south of downtown. Maybe it was just me, but it seemed much bigger this year. Incidentally, those serious looking guards standing to the right are just dudes in costume - unless C2E2 was being protected by S.H.I.E.L.D. this year.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/C2E2_2012/IMG_9199.jpg&quot; height=&quot;533&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The first costume we saw, though, was this positively adorable little dude walking into the convention center. Jedi? Nope, Jawa. I looked for him inside, so I could get a picture of his hood up - and buy a new protocol droid - but I couldn&#039;t find him.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/C2E2_2012/IMG_9203.jpg&quot; height=&quot;533&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;This guy is great. I enjoyed walking around with Alyson because she could point out all of the Harry Potter references and I could point out all of the Sci-Fi references (like this guy).&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/C2E2_2012/IMG_9216.jpg&quot; height=&quot;534&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The place was absolutely packed. This was my view for most of it. I can&#039;t imagine how boring it must be for somebody of normal height. We tried following that Stormtrooper, thinking he would be able to clear a path, but I think it was just a guy in costume.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/C2E2_2012/IMG_9260.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;I was pretty honored that people have already started Cosplaying as District Alpha characters, but Alyson told me they were just &lt;em&gt;Hunger Games&lt;/em&gt; people. You still have to give them props for the timeliness of their costumes. So, in the &lt;em&gt;Hunger Games&lt;/em&gt; everybody caries an expensive camera?&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/C2E2_2012/IMG_9261.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Even Sith Lords have to stand in line to get an autograph from Anthony Daniels?!&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/C2E2_2012/IMG_9264.jpg&quot; height=&quot;533&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;These two dudes spent a lot of time making some Handheld Portable Portal Whatevers, but they don&#039;t even have the leg braces. Come on, guys!&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/C2E2_2012/IMG_9267.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;This girl and her friends just kept saying &quot;Abraham Lincoln. Airplane. Raincloud.&quot; Get it!?&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/C2E2_2012/IMG_9268.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Here&#039;s a really awesome Gamorrean Guard. He barely made it inside before he was mobbed by photographers, which I guess is to be expected. I later saw him with his mask off, and he was a really sweet looking older guy with a great big bushy beard.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/C2E2_2012/IMG_9272.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;This old costume&#039;s still got legs.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/C2E2_2012/IMG_9273.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;You really have to hand it to this guy for the sheer quality of this costume, and his absolute commitment to posing in it. What you have to hand him is, apparently, a cheeseburger.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/C2E2_2012/IMG_9280.jpg&quot; height=&quot;533&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The cool thing about a general comic convention, as opposed to a Sci-Fi or more specific type of convention, is that all bets are off when it comes to costumes. Any time period, real or imagined, is game. &lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/C2E2_2012/IMG_9285.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;It&#039;s really great that dudes who bought or made Stormtrooper costumes a few years ago are getting bored with them, so they&#039;re coming up with fantastic ways to make them fresh.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/C2E2_2012/IMG_9287.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;This picture is great, yes, but what I love is whatever&#039;s going on between that chubby dude and the Stormtrooper.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/C2E2_2012/IMG_9291.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;When you wear a costume to a convention, you&#039;re going to be in a lot of pictures - that&#039;s probably why you do it. The important thing is to really get your pose down. Everybody has their own, and it&#039;s fun to watch them strike it over and over as people all around them take pictures from every angle.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/C2E2_2012/IMG_9296.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;This guy was obviously extremely proud of his homemade Tron: Legacy costume. It looked great, and I&#039;m glad his girlfriend humored him and put on that little number to stand by his side. A comic book convention is a &lt;em&gt;drastically&lt;/em&gt; different experience for a girl like that.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/C2E2_2012/IMG_9298.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Some costumes are always popular, like this kind of awkward example of a Joker / Harley Quinn combo. It&#039;s kind of awkward because he&#039;s a pretty great cartoon-style Joker, and she&#039;s a pretty great Video Game style Quinn. They don&#039;t really go together. This leads me to a bit of an aside. I was looking through the pictures I took last year. They mostly weren&#039;t interesting enough to post here, except for the following one:&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/C2E2_2012/IMG_6983.jpg&quot; height=&quot;533&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;A the time I was more interested in those awesome The Monarch Henchmen, but upon looking back at this, I recognized that Joker. Either he found a much hotter girlfriend in the intervening year, or she got (justifiably) sick of wearing that ugly but thematically appropriate Harley Quinn costume. Joker needs to update his style to match. Or they could, you know, find a new costume pair already.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/C2E2_2012/IMG_9305.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;That Ferrigno-era Hulk was pretty sweet. I try to get more candid shots of people in costume, which is tough with my giant camera. I think it&#039;s fun to see the Hulk looking at pictures on his friend&#039;s camera, or Batman trying to eat a soft pretzel.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/C2E2_2012/IMG_9307.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;This chick had some Hell of great makeup. She&#039;s going to be blue for weeks, probably.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/C2E2_2012/IMG_9318.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;This Catwoman was getting tons of attention everywhere she went. She was obviously loving every minute of it, because who wouldn&#039;t? When you&#039;re in a giant room full of chubby dudes, this is kind of unfair, really.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/C2E2_2012/IMG_9320.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Dr. Doom was in a big group with the Catwoman, an Ares and a lady Dr. Who. This picture shows the contrast between attention that he was getting compared to his Catwoman friend.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/C2E2_2012/IMG_9341.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;If I were at a comic book convention dressed as Godzilla, I would just walk around knocking stuff over until they kicked me out. How can you not do that?&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/C2E2_2012/IMG_9346.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;I got the feeling that these dudes were being paid to wear those beer costumes, but they were still pretty cool.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;That&#039;s just a taste of the costumes that were on display. One popular costume this year was &quot;chick with giant hammer.&quot; I&#039;m not sure what that was about, but I saw several seemingly normally dressed girls with big (like three foot wide) hammers walking around.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I have a lot more cool stuff to show from C2E2 this year, though, so stay tuned!&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Yesterday we looked at some of the interesting costumes that were to be found at C2E2 this year. That&#039;s not the only reason go to a big nerd convention, though. It&#039;s also fun to check out all the neat stuff people are trying to sell.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/C2E2_2012/IMG_9204.jpg&quot; height=&quot;533&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;For example, this awesome poster. I was about to dismiss these things as pretty derivative and uninteresting, but then I saw this one, and thought it was pretty great.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/C2E2_2012/IMG_9207.jpg&quot; height=&quot;533&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;This is a common sight at a comic convention, obviously. If you&#039;re into comics, tables and tables of old comic books would be pretty exciting. To anybody else, it&#039;s pretty boring. It&#039;s best to go to an event like this with one specific thing in mind that you want to get. Otherwise you had better go with lots of cash. It can be pretty tempting to buy lots of stuff - if you&#039;re into this kind of stuff.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/C2E2_2012/IMG_9208.jpg&quot; height=&quot;533&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;However, everybody is into this stuff. If you ever have occasion to buy some Hi-Chew candy from Japan, do it. They&#039;re kind of like Starbursts, except ten times better. I bought $20 worth, because I have been dreaming of them ever since last C2E2.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/C2E2_2012/IMG_9213.jpg&quot; height=&quot;533&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The problem with nerd conventions is that there are tons of booths like this Toy Cave, but they&#039;re all clogged with nerds. You just have to resign yourself to the fact that you can&#039;t really walk through and look at everything. I tried to examine the traffic flows to figure out what works and what doesn&#039;t - in case I need to make another how-to guide - but there really is no rhyme or reason to it. You just have to move as fast as you can, and try be as small an obstruction as possible if you stop to look at a vintage toy or poster or Catwoman.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/C2E2_2012/IMG_9246.jpg&quot; height=&quot;534&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The problem is that there are no organized traffic areas. In this picture, which is about as average a sight as you could find, there are people standing in every possible direction - in what should be a flowing traffic area. I get really irked by crowds not making any effort to maintain proper traffic flow patterns. I will resist the urge to get into details about the way crowds should work.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/C2E2_2012/IMG_9215.jpg&quot; height=&quot;533&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Pepsi seems to have some new version of Pepsi every time I go to a thing like this. This year, they were giving out free samples of Pepsi Next, which I guess is the next Pepsi or something. I wonder what they&#039;ll call the next next.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/C2E2_2012/IMG_9221.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;This booth for some &lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: line-through&quot;&gt;motorcycle garage&lt;/span&gt; really went nuts with the people dressed up like zombies. I would think that people who work on and ride motorcycles would shy away from things depicting mutilated corpses, but whatever. I also don&#039;t think a zombie would have the coordination to walk on stilts like this chick, but also whatever. &lt;strong&gt;Edit&lt;/strong&gt; - I&#039;ve been told that this was a booth for the dungeon of doom haunted house located in Zion IL. That must be one terrifying haunted house.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/C2E2_2012/IMG_9222.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;This other dude at the same booth was happy to pose for a picture holding that ax to somebody&#039;s throat. If you look carefully, you&#039;ll catch a glimpse of the booth that shared a wall with these motorcycle zombies. It was for the Bristol Renaissance Faire. It&#039;s juxtapositions like that which make these things great fun. Heavy metal was blaring on one side, and ridiculous fake British accents were being shouted on the other.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/C2E2_2012/IMG_9227.jpg&quot; height=&quot;533&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Yes, this is a thing. We didn&#039;t buy anything here.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/C2E2_2012/IMG_9250.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;You really have to just become desensitized to inaccurate depictions of women at these things. This was one of many tables covered in stuff like this.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/C2E2_2012/IMG_9252.jpg&quot; height=&quot;533&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Sure, a $190 Magic card. It doesn&#039;t even seem that good.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/C2E2_2012/IMG_9254.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Here&#039;s Computer Engineer Barbie. She&#039;s got some chic glasses, a really cool shiny jacket, and a sweet pink laptop. Yup, that&#039;s me in a nutshell. What&#039;s she working on, there? Some Java applets? Debugging some MVC application? No, she&#039;s looking at a picture of . . . herself. Also she has an iPhone attached to the back of her hand.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/C2E2_2012/IMG_9256.jpg&quot; height=&quot;533&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;This booth had some really sweet video game shirts, but I got pretty annoyed when I saw this one. Nobody uses the Quick Fix! I tried to explain that to Alyson, but for some reason she didn&#039;t care. You see, in &lt;em&gt;Team Fortress 2&lt;/em&gt;, the Medic has a different version of the Medic Gun which - hey, where are you going?&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/C2E2_2012/IMG_9257.jpg&quot; height=&quot;533&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;This is supposed to be a giraffe, I guess. This is kind of the exact opposite of a giraffe, really.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/C2E2_2012/IMG_9258.jpg&quot; height=&quot;533&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;There&#039;s always a corset booth. I am not passing judgement. Seriously, though.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/C2E2_2012/IMG_9259.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;When I rounded a corner and saw this, some primal, instinctual part of me panicked for a short moment. It was just a disembodied head, though, which - frankly - makes this kind of a stupidly easy thing to make.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/C2E2_2012/IMG_6996.jpg&quot; height=&quot;533&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;I&#039;ve seen this master collection Megatron a few times, and boy would I love one. I&#039;ll be damned if I&#039;m going to pay that much, though.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/C2E2_2012/IMG_9302.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;This was a child&#039;s t-shirt, but I still wanted one.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/C2E2_2012/IMG_9304.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Oh, no problem, there&#039;s a whole column of &lt;em&gt;Adventure Time&lt;/em&gt; shirts in this t-shirt tower, right between the &lt;em&gt;Futurama&lt;/em&gt; column and the &lt;em&gt;Family Guy&lt;/em&gt; column. Last year, I was kind of freaked out by how much &lt;em&gt;Big Bang Theory&lt;/em&gt; stuff there was. There was still plenty this year, but thankfully it wasn&#039;t so prevalent. Do actual nerds really watch that show, or are the BBT shirts just designed to make fun of outsiders trying to look like one of us?&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/C2E2_2012/IMG_9309.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;A couple of women were selling these things really hard. I felt sorry for them because these things are pretty dumb.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/C2E2_2012/IMG_9333.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;There&#039;s always a sword booth at these things. If you&#039;re looking for a corset, a sword, a pair of steampunk goggles, or a creepy Japanese wig, go to a comic convention.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;These pictures can&#039;t really do a convention justice, of course. There&#039;s a certain . . . quality that you just can&#039;t get visually. It&#039;s a certain olfactory quality. Let&#039;s just call it . . . Eau De Weeb. Thankfully there are enough normal people (in &lt;em&gt;Big Bang Theory&lt;/em&gt; t-shirts) who kind of help bring the average BO levels up to a bearable level. Anyway, there&#039;s one more set of pictures to go, so come back tomorrow to see more!&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;There are two good reasons to go to a comic convention. You could go to show off your sweet Batman Villain costume, or you could go to spend a bunch of money to complete your Transformers poster collection. However, if you think that&#039;s the only reason to go to a nerd expo, you&#039;ll be missing out on one of the most interesting things - people watching.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/C2E2_2012/IMG_9198.jpg&quot; height=&quot;533&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;This was on the way from our car to the convention center. This guy&#039;s really doing a great job at being a Joker.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/C2E2_2012/IMG_9214.jpg&quot; height=&quot;533&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;This booth was a real gem for checking out nerds being, well, nerds. Who would have thought that girls desperately seeking attention by dressing (and then undressing) as video game characters would be really popular in a room full of socially deprived video game obsessed dudes? Actually, at this moment, the girls were waving and smiling at some children that were walking by. Feel free to discuss that among yourselves.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/C2E2_2012/IMG_9225.jpg&quot; height=&quot;533&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Just down the way, a couple of the girls from the Burlesque booth were walking around handing out fliers. You can&#039;t see them, because they&#039;re behind that wall of dudes.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/C2E2_2012/IMG_9231.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;I remember this R2D2 from last year. He just wanders around the floor checking out the cool stuff, just like anybody else. It&#039;s actually a pretty awesome thing, to be looking at some comic books and have this apparently autonomous robot just wander by.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/C2E2_2012/IMG_9233.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;I think he just wanted to get through, but a solid ring of people gathered to watch him.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/C2E2_2012/IMG_9239.jpg&quot; height=&quot;533&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;He noticed my sweet camera, and posed for me. This picture is actually a lot better than you think. Have you figured it out, yet?&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/C2E2_2012/IMG_9243.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Hey, what&#039;s that thing? I knew robots weren&#039;t real!&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/C2E2_2012/IMG_9276.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Alyson and I were sitting on the floor, sharing a soft pretzel, when I saw an opportunity to get a hot Gamorrean Guard upskirt pic.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/C2E2_2012/IMG_9284.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The Mountain Dew bottle is a great touch.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/C2E2_2012/IMG_9293.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;There were quite a few &lt;em&gt;Assassin&#039;s Creed&lt;/em&gt;s at the expo. This one wasn&#039;t doing a terribly good job at blending. Nerd joke!&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/C2E2_2012/IMG_9300.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;These guys were pretty cool, and this is a good example of one of those poses I talked about in my first set of pictures. I tried taking a few pictures, but the dude on the right had his eyes closed in all of them.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/C2E2_2012/IMG_9314.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Some Stormtroopers were marching around the place holding random people at blasterpoint and checking for credentials. They were looking for some lanyards people could buy to enter themselves into a special raffle. It seemed like a lot of fun, and it was neat to watch kids getting fake harassed by fake stormtroopers.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/C2E2_2012/IMG_9319.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;This guy was a really big fan of Catwoman, or at least of boobs. This is the same guy you can see in the other picture I posted of this Catwoman taking a picture of her with his phone, while his son looks on awkwardly.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/C2E2_2012/IMG_9322.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Here&#039;s a stormtrooper carrying some of those special lanyards. He wasn&#039;t exactly walking with the bearing of a stormtrooper. I think it had been a long day.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/C2E2_2012/IMG_9328.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Here&#039;s Catwoman, again, standing next to her Lady Who friend. That chubby Batman had wandered up and started a fake argument with her. It was kind of funny, but also kind of sad. He was desperately trying to flirt any way he could, and he wasn&#039;t doing a very good job. It was all in good fun, though, and exactly the sort of communal experience that these events are great for. Everybody&#039;s a friend here.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/C2E2_2012/IMG_9332.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Batman went to talk to those Asian Mario twins. Catwoman was obviously still attracting attention just to the left.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/C2E2_2012/IMG_9336.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Only at a comic convention can you get a picture of a My Little Pony girl talking to some nervous nerds while a steampunk dude chats with a guy in full modern combat gear (complete with skull mask) in the background.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/C2E2_2012/IMG_9342.jpg&quot; height=&quot;533&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Also, whatever the heck these dudes were. They were yelling stuff at Godzilla, who was just standing there, probably as confused as the rest of us. Are those guys the Insane Clown Posse?&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/C2E2_2012/IMG_9345.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;This guy was getting a bit of rest off to the side of the place, but when I started taking a picture, he still went into pose mode. These people are really committed to their craft.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/C2E2_2012/IMG_9347.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;These were almost certainly promotional, just from the sheer quality of these costumes, but they were really incredible.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/C2E2_2012/IMG_9349.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Just outside the convention, this girl had to explain to that guy what exactly she was. I&#039;m still not exactly sure what she&#039;s supposed to be, but I bet that guy would have talked about anything just to have the opportunity to talk to a chick in a skintight bodysuit.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/C2E2_2012/IMG_9351.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;I just really like this picture a lot.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/C2E2_2012/IMG_9353.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Only at a comic convention . . .&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So it&#039;s been over two years since I started thinking about getting my very own Web Server, and almost two years since the last time I posted here about it. Needless to say, I haven&#039;t just forgotten about it in that time. Turn the way-back machine to two years ago, then...&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;When last I mentioned this project, I was mired in the difficult process of convincing my Internet Service Provider to get me set up with a static IP address. It started to seem like it wasn&#039;t going to work terribly well, but I decided to go ahead with the project, anyway. One glorious day, I got on the bus to head out to the local Microcenter to buy a pile of computer bits.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/webserver_construction/IMG_4763.jpg&quot; height=&quot;533&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Microcenter: a magical place.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Microcenter is like Newegg.com, except that you don&#039;t have to wait a few days to get anything. They have almost anything you could want in the way of technology or computer bits, and for a lot of stuff their prices are actually better than online. It&#039;s a great place to go on a Saturday Morning to spend hundreds and hundreds of dollars. Later that day, I got a bunch of dudes together to play &lt;em&gt;Twilight: Imperium&lt;/em&gt;, so I&#039;m pretty sure this was the nerdiest day of my life.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I spent a good while browsing the bits at Microcenter, picking out the perfect components for my new server. I decided not to go crazy and actually build a real server. That would be just too expensive and far more powerful than I needed. These days, a basic budget computer (with plenty of hard drive space) is actually perfectly capable of any average home server task. Armed with this knowledge (it was more of a hope than actual knowledge at the time), I got together parts that I hoped would be super stable, power efficient, and inexpensive.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Efficiency is the name of the game with a server, not just in choosing the components themselves, but also in getting absolutely every unnecessary piece out of the way. Almost all desktop and laptop computers are air-cooled, so all of the components rely on fresh air moving over them to keep them from overheating (which is when things break). When building a computer, you really have to pay attention to airflow, and make sure that air can easily get from one side of the case to the other. Any wires inside the case can get in the way of that airflow, so it&#039;s best to get rid of anything you don&#039;t need. On my server, then, I wanted to get rid of everything but the bare necessities. I didn&#039;t want any removable disk drives, unnecessary power cables, or expansion cards of any sort. I knew this thing would need to be on 24/7, so it would have to be at peak form to run as long as possible without any problems.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/webserver_construction/IMG_4765.jpg&quot; height=&quot;533&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;I started with the case, which needed to be able to keep the thing cool and quiet through constant operation. I chose this CM Storm Scout. It&#039;s a mid-tower, so it isn&#039;t ridiculously huge, but it has plenty of fans and vents for airflow. I have a Cooler Master case for my primary PC, and it has worked very well, so I was sure this would be up to the task. Computer case boxes are always really silly. This isn&#039;t some sort of stealth bomber, it&#039;s a budget-level computer case.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/webserver_construction/IMG_4798.jpg&quot; height=&quot;533&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Here&#039;s the back of the case box. Again, this isn&#039;t even a very top of the line case, so it really isn&#039;t that cool at all, even to nerds.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/webserver_construction/IMG_4766.jpg&quot; height=&quot;533&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The power supply is perhaps the most important component, because it will need to maintain performance and efficiency while being powered on all the time. I would have loved to go with a high-end Antec or PC Power and Cooling supply, but I saved a bit of money with this Cooler Master unit. 600 Watts would be more than enough, so it won&#039;t be struggling with a lot of strain. It&#039;s also modular, which means I only have to use the wires that I need. Also, it&#039;s eXtreme, so how could it be bad?&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/webserver_construction/IMG_4773.jpg&quot; height=&quot;533&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The hard drive(s) are perhaps the most important component, because they would need to safely and securely hold lots of important data. The best way to do things is to have the Operating System on one drive, and have another, much larger drive for storage. I had some old Seagate 320 Gigabyte SATA drives laying around, so I wanted to save money by using one of those for the Operating System.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/webserver_construction/IMG_4767.jpg&quot; height=&quot;533&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;I did not want to cut corners with the storage drive, though, so I bought these Western Digital one terrabyte drives. I&#039;ve had nothing but the best experiences with Western Digital in the past, so I knew I could trust these. Yes, I bought two of them, so I could put them in a mirrored RAID array.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;RAID, or Redundant Array of Independent Drives, takes multiple hard drives and through the power of magic turns them into much more powerful drives. In striped mode, the two drives get turned into one super fast drive with the capacity of both smaller drives put together. It&#039;s super fast that way, but also really dangerous because if one drive fails, you lose all your data. In mirrored mode, any data written to the array is identically saved to both drives. It&#039;s not any faster than a single drive, and you have to pay for two drives to get the capacity of one, but it&#039;s super safe. Modern Hard Drives rely on lots of mechanical do-dads that can go catastrophically wrong at any moment, and if they do, any data on the drive is unceremoniously destroyed. If you mirror the drive, though, one of the drives can fail and the other will still have the data. Getting a mirrored RAID array is the best way to cover my butt in the event of hardware failure.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/webserver_construction/IMG_4768.jpg&quot; height=&quot;533&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The motherboard is perhaps the most important component, because it needs to have a lot of the features I need while being super stable. I always go with ASUS components where possible, and every time I&#039;ve gotten a motherboard by another company I&#039;ve regretted it. This particular board has built-in video (so I wouldn&#039;t need a separate video card), built-in RAID (so I wouldn&#039;t need a separate RAID card), and it&#039;s one of the first motherboards to have onboard USB 3, which will come in handy in the future, I&#039;m sure. Also, it has xtreme design, so it should go with the power supply I picked out.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/webserver_construction/IMG_4769.jpg&quot; height=&quot;533&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;I went to Cooler Master, once again, for the CPU heatsink. They make really dependable cooling products, and I really needed something I could depend on for the CPU heatsink, which is probably the most important component of the entire system. The processor needs to run constantly at peak efficiency without overheating, so by using a heatsink that would be perfectly suited to a processor much more powerful than the one I chose, I shouldn&#039;t have any problems.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/webserver_construction/IMG_4770.jpg&quot; height=&quot;533&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;I cut a bit of a corner with the RAM, I&#039;ll admit it. I would have loved to use some RAM I had laying around (with those hard drives), but the motherboard and processor I chose needed DDR 3, so I had to get some new stuff. Though I went with a cheap option, I didn&#039;t get a cheap-o brand. I got a mid-spec 4GB kit, with two 2GB modules. I figured that if I decided the server needed some more RAM, I could always just get another one (the motherboard supports four modules), and bring the capacity up to 8 GB.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/webserver_construction/IMG_4771.jpg&quot; height=&quot;533&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;So here&#039;s the processor I&#039;ve told you so much about. Honestly, I wasn&#039;t as concerned about the CPU as I was about some of the other bits, so I made my choice based on price and potential heat. I went with a dual-core, figuring that a quad would just be unnecessary for these purposes. Getting a processor that was too powerful would only use more electricity and generate more heat inside the case. I went with AMD because Phenom processors are way cheaper than their Intel counterparts, and by getting a Black Edition I could control the clock speed myself. Usually this means you can overclock the processor to get a bit more power out of it, but I actually wanted to underclock it. That way it would be extra stable, cool, and efficient.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;All told, the whole thing cost about $800. Quite a mini-Christmas, indeed. Speccing out the parts on Newegg came out to about the same amount, so I was pretty content with my decision to buy it at Microcenter. The bus ride home wasn&#039;t the most comfortable in the world, however.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h5&gt;Computer Porn: Putting the Bits Together&lt;/h5&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/webserver_construction/IMG_4775.jpg&quot; height=&quot;533&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Here&#039;s the case out of its silly box. Aesthetics were totally unimportant, because this will probably just live in a closet or something, but this case has a few features I like. Having a window might seem like a really stupid thing, but it&#039;s actually really handy for quickly glancing at the inside of the case. You can see if there&#039;s a lot of dust on the CPU heatsink (which is really bad for airflow), or quickly see if anything is amiss. I also really like how the handle / style whatever business up top shelters the fan on top of the case. I can set things on top of the case and it won&#039;t obstruct air flow to the important top fan.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/webserver_construction/IMG_4779.jpg&quot; height=&quot;533&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Here&#039;s a closeup of the heatsink on the motherboard chipset. Whatever, ASUS.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/webserver_construction/IMG_4782.jpg&quot; height=&quot;533&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Those square things in front of that dumb heatsink structure are solid-state capacitors, which run much more efficiently and with a much lower failure rate than the standard cylindrical type capacitors. They&#039;re pretty much standard on ASUS motherboards these days, but it&#039;s yet another component increasing the efficiency of this machine.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/webserver_construction/IMG_4791.jpg&quot; height=&quot;533&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Another cool feature of the motherboard was these little switches, which let you toggle the CPU overclocking. It&#039;s a feature you may never need, but the one moment you do could mean the difference between a computer that works and one that doesn&#039;t, so it&#039;s good to have. The little button lets you turn the computer on without it even being inside a case, which can be handy for debugging purposes.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/webserver_construction/IMG_4794.jpg&quot; height=&quot;533&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;This is the CPU, sitting upside-down on its box. When I got it out, I realized with horror that one of the pins was ever so slightly bent. You can just barely see it toward the right side of the array of pins. This could have meant disaster for the build, because I&#039;m pretty sure all those pins are important. The cool thing about buying this stuff in a store was that I could easily return or exchange it if anything was broken, which is a time consuming process with Newegg.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/webserver_construction/IMG_4797.jpg&quot; height=&quot;533&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;I ever so carefully bent the pin back to vertical with the end of a flathead screwdriver. Back in the day, Processors didn&#039;t come with these big aluminum heat spreaders on top, and you could actually see the processor die and some other bits on top. It&#039;s much easier to install a heatsink now, though, which is why they do it this way.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/webserver_construction/IMG_4801.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;To judge the efficiency of a heatsink, you can look at the bottom of it, where it contacts the processor. The more polished the bottom - and if it&#039;s made of more conductive copper instead of aluminum - the better it is. This little thing needs to make as perfect a seal with the processor as possible, to transfer as much of the heat away as it can. You should also, of course, use a quality thermal paste.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/webserver_construction/IMG_4803.jpg&quot; height=&quot;533&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;And then after some stuff happened, the computer was done. I guess I didn&#039;t feel like taking pictures of the actual process. I really need to get my standards higher. Anyway, here&#039;s the server sitting next to my computer. Don&#039;t let the relative size of this thing fool you, it&#039;s actually pretty big - it&#039;s just that my computer is ridiculously huge. As you can kind of see through the window, there&#039;s only really one bundle of wires going through the interior of the case - the 12 volt connector which goes straight to the middle of the motherboard. There&#039;s no video card, no CD drive, and only a few tiny SATA connectors going to the hard drives.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So for about $800, I built myself a pretty decent home server. Only time would tell how good it would be at actually doing server tasks, but that&#039;s all part of the adventure. Next - probably in about two years - I&#039;ll show how the machine is set up on the software side of things, and then we can get into what I&#039;ve actually used this thing for.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Hey, students, what&amp;rsquo;s up?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;If that&amp;rsquo;s got your attention, you might just be perfectly suited to an action packed internship at the office(s) of DenyConformity.com!&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;What will our intern be responsible for? Why, all sorts of great, exciting, and broadening work around the office. We have lots of organizing to be done here! Sorting stuff out - you&amp;rsquo;ll be an expert in no time. Collating? Yeah, you&amp;rsquo;ll do some collating. We need somebody switch out our Futurama DVD&amp;rsquo;s when we&amp;rsquo;ve watched all of the episodes on them. Also, come to think of it, you would be responsible for bringing us coffee. I mean, just thinking out loud, really. DenyConformity.com Interns will do all kinds of cool stuff, in addition to the coffee thing which I just thought of on the spot. Coffee is just a part of the job. Everybody keeps talking about coffee - that&amp;rsquo;s why I bring it up - and we are totally just as much into coffee as every other productive adult. That&amp;rsquo;s why we need an Intern. Some people have never really had much coffee before, I guess, so they aren&amp;rsquo;t sure what the big deal is - but not me! I&amp;rsquo;m all about coffee, yessir. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Oh, please note that we will not be calling our interns &amp;ldquo;sir.&amp;rdquo; You will be calling me &amp;ldquo;sir.&amp;rdquo; I just want to be clear on that.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;We are looking to hire up to one intern for the Fall 2012 semester, to start immediately. We have only one position available, so get your applications in today! While you&amp;rsquo;re at it, If you stop by to drop off your application in person, you might as well bring me a coffee. I mean, if you&amp;rsquo;re going to be in the area anyway. Any kind is fine. Obviously, I know what kind of coffee somebody would bring a guy, but I want to see if you know.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Applicant must be a go-getter, because they&amp;rsquo;ll be go-getting a lot of stuff. Self starters need not apply; it makes me uncomfortable when things start themselves. Forward thinkers are much preferred over those for whom time is not linear. I&amp;rsquo;ll give perfectionists a try, because it takes balls to lie so blatantly to somebody&amp;rsquo;s face. If you&amp;rsquo;re physically weak, that&amp;rsquo;s pretty great, because one of your duties will be to lose to me at arm wrestling, anyway. Applicant must be capable of laughing at jokes they don&amp;rsquo;t find funny.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Knowledge of Team Fortress 2 is a plus. Applicant must own his or her own computer capable of playing Team Fortress 2. Applicant should not be obnoxiously good at Team Fortress 2.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;We don&amp;rsquo;t need someone with Ruby or Flash experience. We don&amp;rsquo;t need someone with teaching experience. We don&amp;rsquo;t need someone with travel experience. We don&amp;rsquo;t need someone with driving experience. I can&amp;rsquo;t have somebody around here making me look bad. If you think you&amp;rsquo;re here to show how good you are at stuff I don&amp;rsquo;t know you can just get the Hell out.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;An applicant needs enough proficiency with web design paradigms that they can keep up a conversation about it, but still be inexperienced enough to be able to think I&amp;rsquo;m really cool for being able to do stuff. In fact, a strong proficiency in anything is only going to make you seem like you&amp;rsquo;re trying too hard. Be good enough to get something hacked together, not so good that people would be like, &amp;ldquo;jeez, look at that show-off.&amp;rdquo; This is, of course, unless you&amp;rsquo;re really good at making coffee. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Bring to your interview between three and five good ideas for stuff to write about on the Internet. It&amp;rsquo;s probably best if you aren&amp;rsquo;t too terribly attached to them. Also, we&amp;rsquo;ll need some references on your coffee making ability, preferably from anybody who really didn&amp;rsquo;t like coffee until you made it for them.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Please be prepared to answer the following questions at your interview:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;1. &amp;ldquo;What would you say is your strongest?&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;2. &amp;ldquo;How long did you stay in your last position (before you got tired)?&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;3. &amp;ldquo;Why or how did you choose to wear that particular shirt today?&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;We will not ask you any of these questions in the Interview, but if you aren&amp;rsquo;t prepared for them, we will know. Bring a couple copies of your resume, and seven references - Star Wars, not professional.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;After extensive negotiations with local Universities, we can now officially provide you with class credit in &amp;ldquo;please stop contacting us.&amp;rdquo; You will have to deal with the paperwork yourself, though, because they aren&amp;rsquo;t returning my calls anymore. I&amp;rsquo;m not sure how many credit hours we&amp;rsquo;re talking about, here, but you&amp;rsquo;ll be doing stuff for me every day. Just in one semester we&amp;rsquo;re looking at several hundred hours. I mean, every day you&amp;rsquo;ll at least be working long enough to make some coffee. That&amp;rsquo;s like - what - two, three hours a day?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Oh yeah, this is an unpaid internship only - sorry. If hired, however, you will be able to dig through one of two sacks of cables and take whatever you want. Actually, if you know anybody who would want a sack or two of cables, let me know.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Either email your applications to internship@denyconformity.com, or send them directly to:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Back window,&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;1983 Honda Civic parked outside Daley Plaza&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Chicago, IL 60602&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;It&amp;rsquo;s the one with the &amp;ldquo;Oh yeah!&amp;rdquo; bumper sticker&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Respond to the following prompts, in as many words as you see fit:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;blockquote&gt;
Name:&lt;br&gt;
Email address:&lt;br&gt;
Cut of beef (Flank, ground, etc):&lt;br&gt;
Last 4 digits of a number you made up:&lt;br&gt;
Preferred occupation:&lt;br&gt;
School of attendance:&lt;br&gt;
Perfect Sunday:&lt;br&gt;
One thing you wish you could take back:&lt;br&gt;
One thing you wish you could take forward:&lt;br&gt;
Coffee making proficiency (1 - 5, 5 being &amp;ldquo;really great&amp;rdquo;):&lt;br&gt;
Coffee making experience (1 - 5, 5 being &amp;ldquo;never done it&amp;rdquo;):&lt;br&gt;
Suggestions for making good Coffee:&lt;br&gt;
Thank you:
&lt;/blockquote&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Please rate the following sentences based on how much you agree with them (1 is &amp;ldquo;strongly disagree&amp;rdquo; and 5 is &amp;ldquo;strongly agree&amp;rdquo;):&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;blockquote&gt;
&amp;ldquo;I really enjoy coffee.&amp;rdquo;&lt;br&gt;
&amp;ldquo;I would rather make coffee for others than drink it myself.&amp;rdquo;&lt;br&gt;
&amp;ldquo;I often find myself fantasizing about ways to improve how I make coffee.&amp;rdquo;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Finally, please sign (and print) your name.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Thank you, students, for taking the time to apply, and good luck!&lt;/p&gt;

data.summary:
