&lt;p&gt;If that&amp;rsquo;s got your attention, you might just be perfectly suited to an action packed internship at the office(s) of DenyConformity.com!&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;What will our intern be responsible for? Why, all sorts of great, exciting, and broadening work...&lt;/p&gt;

data.text:
&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/saturday_sweepstakes.jpg&quot; height=&quot;951&quot; width=&quot;1333&quot;&gt;&lt;p&gt;Thank you all so much for participating in the first ever Saturday Sweepstakes! I&#039;ve been super excited about all the entries I received in the last week. I&#039;ll go ahead and give you 24 more hours to get your entries in, but after that, I&#039;m going to make my choice of the winner, and send off the &lt;em&gt;special prize&lt;/em&gt;. Email your entries to sweepstakes@denyconformity.com&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I was going to post a picture of the special prize as a sort of tantalizing treat to convince you all that it&#039;s a real thing that you could have sent right to your door. However, I left it in the car, and I don&#039;t feel like walking around the block to get it. Instead, please find enclosed one picture of Alyson&#039;s and my cat, Elliott.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/elliott_happy_saturday.jpg&quot; height=&quot;533&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Happy Saturday.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This is part three (well, technically part four) of an ongoing series about the redesign of this website. Spoiler alert: the new design has been live for three weeks. I originally meant for this ongoing thing to actually go on as I was working on the new site and be sort of a teaser for the new design. Now that the new design is live, though, this will just have to serve as more of an ongoing discussion. Think of it as the audio commentary track for the Internet.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So far in these posts I have talked about the way the site came about, and some of the quirks and problems in the old design. Today I want to discuss some of my thoughts on Web Theory. Just what is the Internet? What is a website? What is DenyConformity.com, and how does it fit into the world?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/design_journal_4/oldsite.PNG&quot; height=&quot;674&quot; width=&quot;1344&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The old (not the old-old, but the new-old) version of this site.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;One major problem with the Internet is its lack of tangibility. We know what a book is and a magazine makes perfect sense, but what is a website? Books, magazines, and other more physical things are limited by the nature of what they are. For example, a book has text on pages, magazines are a certain size, and a TV show has a pretty specific box (figuratively and literaly) that it has to fit in. A website doesn&amp;rsquo;t really have anything to conform to (hey, that&amp;rsquo;s like the name of this site!). There&amp;rsquo;s no limit to the design, content, platform, format, or audience that a website can have. Yes, that&amp;rsquo;s what makes the Internet great, but that&amp;rsquo;s beside the point.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The problem is that we need better terms. We can&amp;rsquo;t just call something a website just like you can&amp;rsquo;t go around bragging about your classic muscle car by telling people you have a &amp;ldquo;vehicle.&amp;rdquo; Think about everything that counts as a website. That old Hanson fan page from 1997 is a website. Homestarrunner.com is a website. Google Docs is a website. Facebook is a website. Engadget is a website. Is there anything that is common between any of those things, aside from some underlying technology and the fact that they all run in a web browser?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/design_journal_4/hanson.PNG&quot; height=&quot;671&quot; width=&quot;1340&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;We are going to leave this page up, but stop working on it. The run-off of this page is Hanson Heaven! it will be updated as often as possible. Come and visit! (&lt;a href=&quot;http://jenilynn.tripod.com/&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;jenilynn.tripod.com&lt;/a&gt;)
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;We have different kinds of websites, then. Google Docs is a web application. Facebook is a social network. Engadget is a technology news blog. We have a whole new vocabulary to describe all this stuff. It just isn&amp;rsquo;t enough, though. Go to your parents and try to explain to them what Homestar Runner is - or Twitter, or Tumblr - in a way that isn&amp;rsquo;t essentially just saying &amp;ldquo;it&amp;rsquo;s a really interesting website place.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The Internet is almost by definition a lack of format. Is it even possible, then, to come up with terminology to describe what we do with it? More importantly, does it even matter?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The Internet doesn&amp;rsquo;t operate like any other medium. It&amp;rsquo;s not like a library, where you browse through great shelves of content. You don&amp;rsquo;t just go to Internet and click on Interesting Website Place. It&amp;rsquo;s like a vast, featureless subdivision, where every house looks the same from the outside, and you can&amp;rsquo;t walk in any front doors. The only way into a house is by going through another house. You don&amp;rsquo;t just walk up to a website, you have to be sent there.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;How did you get to this page? Did you click a link on Facebook or Twitter? Did you stumble upon this page? Did you come here from the RSS feed or the main timeline? How many of you typed &amp;ldquo;http://www.denyconformity.com/post/389/Design_Journal_4&amp;rdquo; into your browser? Certainly very few, if anybody did that. Even the most pure type of traffic - those people who hear about this site and type DenyConformity.com into their address bar - are still only going here because they&amp;rsquo;ve heard about the site from some other source. No traffic on the Internet is original - it&amp;rsquo;s all second-hand.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Because of this, the concept of location doesn&amp;rsquo;t matter on the Internet anymore. Your browser&amp;rsquo;s address bar is becoming less and less necessary - a vestigial organ which only exists to comfort our need for a physical metaphor. Look at Google Chrome, where the address bar isn&amp;rsquo;t really an address bar anymore. It&amp;rsquo;s a search bar, where you can just type &amp;ldquo;interesting website place&amp;rdquo; and then you get Google links to anywhere you might want to go.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So who cares what a website is? It doesn&amp;rsquo;t matter what DenyConformity.com is, because all that matters is the content. The biggest surge of traffic I&amp;rsquo;ve gotten since the new site went live was last weekend, when somebody posted a picture from my &amp;ldquo;How to Ride a Bus&amp;rdquo; guide on their Tumblr page. There was no &amp;ldquo;check out this interesting website place.&amp;rdquo; There was just a link, and that link went right to a particular piece of content. People read that content, and then they continued on to some other link to some other piece of content.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The way I see it, there are three types of websites. There are the sites I use (Google Docs, for example), there are the sites I watch (stuff like Facebook or email, which I regularly check for updates), and there are the sites I &lt;em&gt;consume&lt;/em&gt;. I&amp;rsquo;ll read an article here or watch a funny video there. DenyConformity.com is that kind of website - a thing to be consumed. It&amp;rsquo;s the magazine you pick up while waiting for an appointment. It&amp;rsquo;s the book you read while you&amp;rsquo;re on the bus. It&amp;rsquo;s the art you hang on your wall. DenyConformity.com is here for you to take in. That&amp;rsquo;s all. Maybe it will enlighten you, or maybe it will make you laugh, but it has only one goal: to be interesting. All I deliver is regular content that I find interesting, and that&amp;rsquo;s exactly what DenyConformity.com is here for.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Anyway, that&amp;rsquo;s why I just call DenyConformity.com &amp;ldquo;a really interesting website place.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A(nother) Pen Review.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I believe that everybody should have one good pen. You should keep a dependable ballpoint in your pocket for situations when you need to jot down some notes or sign a receipt. It&amp;rsquo;s as necessary, I feel, as your wallet and keys. Through most of my college career, for me that pen was a Zebra F-402. They come in a two-pack, which is customary at Zebra. I&amp;rsquo;m not sure where the first one ended up, lost to the annals of time. The other stuck with me through quite a few adventures, until just a few months ago when I let somebody borrow it. If you take nothing else away from this post, you should at least learn that if you have a pen you like, you should never let somebody borrow it. Needless to say, that old dependable 402 and I will never cross paths again.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Last week, I was out at the grocery store, and I passed one of those office supply stores - I think it was a Paperclipz (the z in their logo is a paperclip!). After using this Parker Jotter for a few weeks, I figured I might as well get some new pens to have something to officially compare it to.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/zebra_threeway/IMG_9378.jpg&quot; height=&quot;533&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;I got a whole herd of Zebras.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I won&amp;rsquo;t go into a bunch of detail about who Zebra is, because it&amp;rsquo;s not as interesting as Parker (the company). They&amp;rsquo;re a division of another company called Zebra, which is probably a division of another company called Zebra. Zebra (one of them, anyway) makes a bunch of different products, like toner and markers. Basically, if it can totally ruin your Mom&amp;rsquo;s towels, they make it. Zebra has been around since 1982, so they don&amp;rsquo;t have quite the same legacy as Parker (the legacy), but they were founded as an already wholly owned subsidiary of a corporation, so they at least haven&amp;rsquo;t lost any legacy, either.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Zebra makes a pen called the F-301, which which has the awkwardly ambiguous nickname, &amp;ldquo;The Original.&amp;rdquo; It can&amp;rsquo;t be the original retractable ballpoint pen, because Parker was making them for decades before Zebra (any of them) existed. It can&amp;rsquo;t even be Zebra&amp;rsquo;s original pen, because why would they have called it the 301?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Anyway, Zebra specializes in stainless steel bodied ballpoints and Mechanical Pencils. I&amp;rsquo;m focusing on their main fleet of ballpoints.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h5&gt;Welcome to Pens-ilvania&lt;/h5&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/zebra_threeway/IMG_9379.jpg&quot; height=&quot;533&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Today&amp;rsquo;s subjects: &amp;ldquo;The Original&amp;rdquo; F-301, &amp;ldquo;The Gel&amp;rdquo; G-301, and &amp;ldquo;The Aforesaid&amp;rdquo; F-402.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The problem with Zebra is that I&amp;rsquo;m not sure why they have a &amp;ldquo;fleet&amp;rdquo; of ballpoints. Ballpoints are workhorses, purely for taking down notes or writing checks. They lack the smooth uninterrupted lines of felt-tips, the fine, even points of rollerballs, and the visceral grace of fountains. Everybody needs a ballpoint, but you only need one. Why, then, does Zebra have an entire line of them? Where is the market for all of these things?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Zebra has the original 301, the nicer 402, and then the unnecessarily expensive 701. I&amp;rsquo;m skipping the 701, because I&amp;rsquo;m not part of the 1%, but the others are too similar to both exist. They&amp;rsquo;re both stainless steel, and they have exactly the same ink and cartridge (so on paper they&amp;rsquo;re identical). Is the 301 for the ever-so-slightly less wealthy? Do people buying pens think they don&amp;rsquo;t deserve a 402? It doesn&amp;rsquo;t make sense to me.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In fact, for numerous reasons, there&amp;rsquo;s no reason to ever consider an F-301 at all. I won&amp;rsquo;t waste too much time analyzing it. It&amp;rsquo;s the bad kind of light, where it just feels cheap. The textured plastic grip is uncomfortable, and the click action is perfectly generic. At the Paperclipz, a pair of 301s was only $1.20 cheaper than a pair of 402s. Just get a medium fries with lunch, and get the 402.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/zebra_threeway/IMG_9388.jpg&quot; height=&quot;438&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The F-402 isn&amp;rsquo;t usually this out of focus.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The 402 is a much better pen. It&amp;rsquo;s heavier than the 301 (or a Jotter), so it feels more substantial. It doesn&amp;rsquo;t have any subtle curves (or the pretentious arrow clip), and even in spite of that huge rubber grip it&amp;rsquo;s pretty spartan. It&amp;rsquo;s a no nonsense writing utensil, and there&amp;rsquo;s nothing wrong with that. It&amp;rsquo;s probably because I used one for so long, but it&amp;rsquo;s more comfortable to me than the Parker. That shouldn&amp;rsquo;t matter to you, because that&amp;rsquo;s purely an opinion and there&amp;rsquo;s no reason for you to be subject to mine. Still, it&amp;rsquo;s worth noting that when I go to grab a pen in the morning, of these four (including the Parker), I seem to always go for the 402. The 402&amp;rsquo;s action is somewhere between the chincy click of the 301 and the heavy &amp;ldquo;cachunk&amp;rdquo; of the Jotter. It&amp;rsquo;s not as satisfying as the Jotter, but I feel more comfortable clicking the 402 because I&amp;rsquo;m not afraid it will wake up my neighbors.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/zebra_threeway/IMG_9389.jpg&quot; height=&quot;372&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Just imagine it without the &amp;ldquo;gel&amp;rdquo; icon, and this picture can also be for the F-301.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The other pen I picked up looks just like the 301. Okay, so it is a 301, but this one has a G instead of an F. I&amp;rsquo;m not sure what the F stands for, but the G apparently stands for &amp;ldquo;Gel.&amp;rdquo; It has an identical body to the 301, and other than the &amp;ldquo;gel&amp;rdquo; badge, they&amp;rsquo;re completely indistinguishable. That&amp;rsquo;s a mark against the G-301. Everything I said about the F-301 is true about the G-301, except that since the G-301 has slightly different internal mechanisms, its action feels even more chincy. Also, the G-301 was only $4.99 at Paperclipz, which is yet another reason why you should never buy an F-301.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h5&gt;The 10th Circle of Gel&lt;/h5&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I wanted to pick up a gel pen, not just because somebody recommended the G-301, but because gel is pretty popular and I wanted to do a side-by-side comparison to regular ink. The differences are quite interesting.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Gel ink has a few unique properties. It&amp;rsquo;s water-based, as opposed to the dye-alcohol paste in standard ballpoints. This means it&amp;rsquo;s actually more environmentally friendly than standard ink. You would think this would be more common knowledge, since everybody is obsessed with the environment these days. Because of how gel works, you can get a wide range of wacky colors, which is why you can buy hot pink and electric yellow gel pens. Gel ink is more opaque than regular ink, which makes it thicker and darker, and it can supposedly be used on a wider range of mediums - including stuff that isn&amp;rsquo;t absorbent, like paper or your Mom&amp;rsquo;s towels. Gel ink will take longer to fade than regular ink, so if you want to sign some official documents or do some other sort of archival thing, you should use gel. Gel will not, however, last as long in a pen, because it is less efficient than standard ink. You might need to buy as many as eight refills to the G-301 to keep up with a single F-301 cartridge. Gel supposedly also will &amp;ldquo;clump&amp;rdquo; more and cause breaks in your lines, since the gel doesn&amp;rsquo;t coat the titular ball as evenly as standard ink will. Finally, gel uses something called a liquid stopper, which can evaporate. When it does, there&amp;rsquo;s nothing keeping the gel inside anymore, and it will get all over your mom&amp;rsquo;s towels.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;There are some other more technical things about gel, but those are the basics. How does it compare in the real world, though?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h5&gt;The Write Stuff&lt;/h5&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In the world of pens, ballpoints are the blue collar workers. They can&amp;rsquo;t be expected to do anything but the most basic of pen on paper action. That&amp;rsquo;s not to say they aren&amp;rsquo;t good for anything, just that they&amp;rsquo;re never going to be held in as high regard as felt for artists or fountains for writers. Because of this, ballpoint pens have some important features that make them special. Generally you can be pretty cruel to the tip of a ballpoint, and it won&amp;rsquo;t be destroyed as easily as a felt-tip or a fountain nib. They&amp;rsquo;re perfectly suited to hang out in your pocket, waiting for their time to be useful.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I did a series of tests to compare the strengths of these ballpoint pens, on standard college-ruled paper - I figure it&amp;rsquo;s a pretty common media for ballpoints. I then scanned the pages for analysis. These tests are by no means scientific, but I hope they will be a reasonable facsimile of real-world anecdotal evidence.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The first test I looked at was a fill test. I wanted to see how well the ink would fill an area, and how it would look afterwards.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/zebra_threeway/1.jpg&quot; height=&quot;229&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Test 1: the Fill Test&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Again, the F-301 and the F-402 have the exact same ink, so they should be pretty identical here. Interestingly, the Parker ink seems nicer to my naked and admittedly inexperienced eye. It&amp;rsquo;s a warmer black, and it has a better sheen to it. Here you can see the higher opacity of the gel ink showing its colors (literally).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In a similar test, I ran the pens over a fill made by another pen.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/zebra_threeway/2.jpg&quot; height=&quot;543&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Test 2: The Overlap Test&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The 402 and 301 blend together here, which is to be expected. However, you can see how the warmer Parker ink shows up on top of the Zebra ink. The gel is again a darker and more solid color.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Next was a far more important test - the smear test. As a left-handed writer, smearing is an eternal problem for me. I want a brand of ink that will smear the least as I&amp;rsquo;m taking notes in my various notepads and journals. I drew a thick swatch and smeared it with my thumb, and then did the same with a single line. Then I drew a line and counted to five before smearing it, to see how quickly the ink dries.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/zebra_threeway/3.jpg&quot; height=&quot;609&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Test 3: the Smear Test&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The gel suddenly loses its appeal. Since it&amp;rsquo;s water-based, it smears much more readily than regular ink. You can see how the gel &amp;ldquo;globbed&amp;rdquo; at the end of the last line. A bit more ink was absorbed into the page at the end of the line, where I stopped writing. The other three pens seem pretty similar, but thanks to the power of computers I could get a bit more information.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/zebra_threeway/4.jpg&quot; height=&quot;609&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Smear Test modified in Photoshop&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Quite interesting. Here you can see just how thoroughly each line is smeared. The Jotter seems to smear just a tiny bit more than the Zebra ink. The 402 also seems to be a tiny bit more smeared than the 301. This might simply be due to tiny differences in the pressure I used to write them. However, I don&amp;rsquo;t think it&amp;rsquo;s unreasonable to assume that the rubber grip gave me a tiny bit more power in the 402.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It&amp;rsquo;s interesting how the smears are kind of striped. Either the smear streaks are a result of an irregularity in the pens&amp;rsquo; balls, or it&amp;rsquo;s the pattern of my thumbprint. Remember how I said this wouldn&amp;rsquo;t be scientific?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Another important thing about a pen is how much pressure you need to write. This is where ballpoints have a disadvantage, because you actually need a lot of pressure to get the ball rolling, as it were (and it is). With all ballpoint pens, there&amp;rsquo;s a sweet spot, where you get a good distribution of ink. Press too softly and you won&amp;rsquo;t get anything, but press too hard and you&amp;rsquo;ll have an ugly, broken line.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/zebra_threeway/5.jpg&quot; height=&quot;348&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Test 4: Heavy Writing&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;If I had any budget at all, I might build some sort of robot that is able to write things at exact pressures. I don&amp;rsquo;t have a budget, though, so I didn&amp;rsquo;t do that. Instead, I just wrote a thing with each pen, pressing very hard. This was harder than anybody would ever comfortably write - except maybe the Hulk or something. At this level, all four pens heavily exhibited what I call &amp;ldquo;Mosesing.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Let me explain.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/zebra_threeway/diagram_good.jpg&quot; height=&quot;600&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;This is how a ballpoint pen is supposed to work. Basically.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I threw together a couple diagrams to explain this visually. Above is an example of how a ballpoint pen is supposed to work. Ink (in this case it&amp;rsquo;s hot pink) flows over the ball and makes a smooth, even mark on the page. However, that&amp;rsquo;s not how it works all the time.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/zebra_threeway/diagram_bad.jpg&quot; height=&quot;600&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;This is how a ballpoint pen actually works.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Sometimes, especially when you press too hard, the ball is smushed into the page, and ink doesn&amp;rsquo;t fit underneath it. Then you get a line with an odd stripe in the middle, which you can only really notice if you look closely. I call it &amp;ldquo;Mosesing&amp;rdquo; because the ball is like a tiny little Moses parting the ink like a tiny Red (or pink) Sea.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This happens with all ballpoint pens, and it&amp;rsquo;s why they aren&amp;rsquo;t great for anything that needs to look nice. Here you can see it happening randomly with all four pens, even when just writing normally.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/zebra_threeway/9.jpg&quot; height=&quot;243&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;When people see your uneven lines, they&amp;rsquo;ll know that you have a Parker.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/zebra_threeway/8.jpg&quot; height=&quot;334&quot; width=&quot;1132&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The F-301 and the F-402 have the same ink, so they&amp;rsquo;re both equally guilty.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/zebra_threeway/7.jpg&quot; height=&quot;325&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The gel ink has it the worst.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Gel is more viscous than normal ink, so it gets the worst Mosesing. The line drawn by the G-301 is about twice as wide as the line drawn by the F-301, and their tips are the same size. That&amp;rsquo;s why the gel ink runs out faster, and it&amp;rsquo;s twice the surface area to be &amp;ldquo;Mosesed&amp;rdquo; by the pressure of the ball.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I also wanted to see how the pens handled writing softly. This is an aspect where ballpoints really can&amp;rsquo;t hold up, because they rely on the friction of the ball on the paper to get it all to work. However, I was pretty surprised by how well they hung on. This is something that would have been more of a challenge for pens back in the days when Tungsten Carbide was just a wild fever dream.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/zebra_threeway/6.jpg&quot; height=&quot;434&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Test 5: Light Writing&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;There was hardly any Mosesing anymore, but the gel showed a new problem. It could not handle the lack of pressure. In all, I think the Jotter shows the most range of pressure, which translates to a higher chance that you&amp;rsquo;ll be able to write however you&amp;rsquo;re comfortable without having to adjust to what the pen needs. I&amp;rsquo;m sure I&amp;rsquo;m not alone in picking up a foreign pen for whatever reason only to find that it requires an amount of pressure that I&amp;rsquo;m just not used to using. That&amp;rsquo;s a feature you don&amp;rsquo;t want in your trusty pocket workhorse.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/zebra_threeway/10.jpg&quot; height=&quot;243&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Test 6: Extremely Low Pressure&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;For the final test, I held a single sheet of paper by one end, bending it slightly to get it to stand out. I then tried my best to write a few lines on the far margin, where the pen would be able to apply very little pressure. This would really test the limits of the pens&amp;rsquo; ability to write without much force. The three standard ink pens were able to just get some faint lines. However, the G-301 just wouldn&amp;rsquo;t work, and mainly just managed to scrape the paper a bit. What lines the gel ink was able to make were much darker than the other pens, of course, but the plain fact is that the gel ink requires a bit more pressure to work - and with pressure comes Moses.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Finally the Finale&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/zebra_threeway/IMG_9385.jpg&quot; height=&quot;533&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The Zebra fleet - minus the pen for rich people.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So just how does the Zebra fleet stand up against the Jotter? First off, just forget the G-301 exists. I hate it. The 402 certainly offers some serious competition, and it might very well be a full-on toss up between it and the Jotter. Parker (the company) does have slightly better ink, and you cannot beat the build quality and elegance of the Jotter. However, the 402 is mighty comfortable, and it&amp;rsquo;s less than half the cost (per pen) than the Jotter - plus you get an extra 402 to let somebody borrow. Purely on the merit of the pens, though, I think I actually prefer the lighter, smoother, more stylish Jotter - despite my long relationship with the 402.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The outlier is the G-301, with it&amp;rsquo;s crazy gel ink. Some might really appreciate the dark, thick lines that gel gives you. Others will be put off by the higher pressure required and the fact that gel ink smears much, much more. Even if you love gel ink, though, you&amp;rsquo;ll still be stuck with the 301 body, which basically made my hand almost fall off I hated it so much. I&amp;rsquo;m pretty sure I ventured into hyperbole at some point there. The point is that you can get a much better gel pen than the G-301. For example, Parker makes a gel refill for the Jotter.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So ultimately we can disregard most of Zebra&amp;rsquo;s lineup. The 301 is too cheap, the 701 is too expensive, and their gel ink is in the wrong pen. They have too many pens. Like everybody else, Zebra does not need a fleet of ballpoint pens. They only need one good dependable workhorse. Unfortunately for Zebra, though, they can&amp;rsquo;t do what the rest of us do. We already have one good pen, and it&amp;rsquo;s made by Parker.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;(Some of the handwriting examples were written by Alyson)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;While dealing with the amoral practices of the utility companies, as we all do once a month, I started thinking, as I do every month, about the existence of evil. We have to live under the yolk of the power company (among other amoral authorities), forced to pay any fees and put up with uncaring service because we have no power - literally and figuratively - to stop them. It is easy to feel victimized and violated by these obvious corruptions of authority. We can easily travel down a dark road of cynicism, losing all faith in Humanity or Society. However, something dawned on me today that gave me real hope.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;As a living thing - weak, soft, and defenseless - your imperative, ultimately, is to make it to your next dinner. You personally must survive to eat dinner tonight, but you must also see that descendents of your species will live to see dinner tomorrow. What is the purpose of a life? Is there any higher purpose than to merely survive? Humans - at least this modern Society of Humans - are above that type of thinking. Dinner tonight will be provided for us. We can spend the few hours until then watching TV or deciding which tablet to buy. Is our obsession with celebrity and useless technology throwing our purpose away? I present to you that our purpose has already been lost, not because we lost our way in a sea of iPhones and Kardashians, but because we are on the cusp of a new Era of Humanity.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This is high language, I grant you, and you might think that it borders on new-age radical nonsense, but I&amp;rsquo;m actually quite serious.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Hundreds of thousands of Your Earth Years ago, Humans were still animals. They fought, killed, and huddled together in caves to survive. They were weak, soft, defenseless creatures in a vastly hostile world, simply trying to live to see - and catch - dinner. However, Humans had an advantage: reason. They made tools, clothing, and shelter. They domesticated beasts and conquered agriculture. Early Humans were able to adapt so much more quickly than any other living thing. In what is cosmically a microscopic amount of time, we have grown more powerful than everything around us.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In short, we won. We beat nature. Yes, we&amp;rsquo;re still victims to disease and famine and natural disasters, but none of those things threaten our survival any more than buying a gallon of milk threatens someone&amp;rsquo;s bank account. In modern society, we don&amp;rsquo;t have to fight and struggle to see dinner. We have to find something to watch on TV while we wait for dinner to be delivered. No other species in our experience even comes close to pursuing activities that serve no purpose but to occupy the time of the pursuer. What are the Kardashians if not a complete and total admission - dare I say it, celebration - of our victory over survival?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The problem, though, is that we are still animals. We are the same creatures that huddled in caves thousands of years ago, and we have the same instincts to survive. When given the choice, we will take advantage of others to help ourselves. Can you blame the power company or other corporations for ruining lives to make a profit? Deep down, our CEOs are just weak, soft, defenseless creatures letting a cruel beast eat someone else instead of themselves. This is instinctual; built into our being at a primal level. You are not free of blame. As you sit there, a Human Being just as intelligent and logical as you is starving to death. Is your passive evil - cruelty of inaction - any better than a corrupt CEOs active evil - cruelty of action? Is it all simply the circle of life - survival of the fittest?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Humans have always been brutal, pitiless creatures. Humans have always fought and killed each other to get a better piece of the world for themselves. There is no era of Human History in which some entity or group was not trying to destroy another to take what they had.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Listen - er, Read: until recently, active evil was normal. Humans were content to commit intensely cruel actions against each other as a matter of course. It has only been recently that we have even considered the existence passive evil. Nobody in modern Society two hundred years ago would have felt bad eating a full meal when impoverished third worlds were starving around the globe. Today, active cruelty is still common, but the key is that it isn&amp;rsquo;t universal anymore. At this rate, tomorrow it may be gone entirely.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Evil is vestigial. Its is an unnecessary organ - an evolutionary leftover - that we are slowly working to remove. Cruelty and greed is rampant in our society, yes, but they are dying. We are beginning to agree with each other on a global scale. We connect to each other through mind-boggling technology and are truly beginning to see ourselves as a unified species. There are parts of the world now which are legitimately, completely, safe. We are redefining what is right and wrong, and more importantly we are doing it based on a common morality, not supposed divine right. We don&amp;rsquo;t seek the directives of our leaders - we make decisions for ourselves. We are rooting out those aspects of ourselves that are base and evil, and we are slowly smothering them.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Two hundred years ago, Humans fought world wars on the whims of Kings and Emperors. Plagues ran rampant in the streets, completely untreatable. Cruelty went unmatched. News would take weeks, if not months, to travel short distances. Just imagine how far we have progressed as a species in two hundred years. Where will we be two hundred years from now? What glorious achievements of reason and morality will we see?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Imagine how exciting it is to be able to live in this period of history! We are witnessing the death of evil first hand, and these corrupt companies and greedy CEOs are its death knell. My grandchildren might grow up in a world where things like War, Poverty, and even Disease are nothing more than stories. This isn&amp;rsquo;t the wild dreams of new-age radical nonsense, either. This is really happening.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So what is the purpose of a life now? What will my grandchildren live for? When a species defeats survival, what is left for them to do? That, my friends, is the great question of our age. That is the new era of Humanity that we are on the cusp of discovering.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;We Humans have finished our dinner. All we have to do now is find our dessert.&lt;/p&gt;

