&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;(Hopefully it goes without saying, but this is a joke. Don&amp;rsquo;t take my PIN15 too seriously.)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/commuting_simulators/fast_travel.jpg&quot; height=&quot;627&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;So you&#039;re Dragonborn? Go kill three wolves ten miles away and then come back here. Thanks!&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;(Note: I didn&amp;rsquo;t want to dig through a bunch of old games to get screenshots, or deal with Google Image Search to find them, so all of the pictures in this post are artist renderings.)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;My friend and colleague Will Hughes maintains an interesting website place, where he often posts commentary on the video game industry. He posted some postings about open world games recently, and that inspired me to collect some of my similar thoughts into some postings of my own. And lo, that is what I have done. Please visit his website place to read his comments on &lt;a href=&quot;http://amalgamatedwittering.blogspot.com/2012/03/over-flagpole-escape-as-art.html&quot;&gt;&amp;ldquo;Escape as Art,&amp;rdquo;&lt;/a&gt; on the illusion of choice in open worlds, and &lt;a href=&quot;http://amalgamatedwittering.blogspot.com/2012/03/off-script-problem-with-storytelling-in.html&quot;&gt;&amp;ldquo;Off the Script,&amp;rdquo;&lt;/a&gt; on problems inherent in storytelling for open world games. Those are both very important points about this trend we&amp;rsquo;re being force fed more and more. I agree with Hughes that merely making a game &amp;ldquo;open world&amp;rdquo; does not suddenly catapult it into an upper echelon of brilliant gameplay. Really, it just wastes your time.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;When I was in High School, I played a lot of video games. I really enjoyed shooting games like &lt;em&gt;Half Life&lt;/em&gt; and &lt;em&gt;Unreal&lt;/em&gt;, strategy games like &lt;em&gt;Command and Conquer&lt;/em&gt;, and role playing games, like &lt;em&gt;Final Fantasy&lt;/em&gt;. Then a friend introduced me to a game called &lt;em&gt;Gothic&lt;/em&gt;, which was a pretty unique (at least to me at the time) open world role playing game with a fantasy / medieval theme.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/commuting_simulators/gothic.jpg&quot; height=&quot;916&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;And terrible voice acting.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I tried to get back into &lt;em&gt;Gothic&lt;/em&gt; a few months ago, after getting the entire &lt;em&gt;Gothic&lt;/em&gt; collection (they&amp;rsquo;re up to &lt;em&gt;Gothic 4&lt;/em&gt;) on Steam. It was difficult to get back into. The controls, by today&amp;rsquo;s standard, are just weird, and though you can get over the graphics (which weren&amp;rsquo;t great even back then), the voice acting really is hard to get around.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A lot can be said about &lt;em&gt;Gothic&lt;/em&gt;, really. It actually had surprisingly similar features to &lt;em&gt;Skyrim&lt;/em&gt;, which came out ten years later. I&amp;rsquo;m not going to tell you that &lt;em&gt;Gothic&lt;/em&gt; is better than, or even really as good as &lt;em&gt;Skyrim&lt;/em&gt;. I&amp;rsquo;m also not going to belay the point, because analyzing &lt;em&gt;Gothic&lt;/em&gt; is outside the scope of this posting. The point is that &lt;em&gt;Gothic&lt;/em&gt; was a lot of fun, and it sucked me into the world of role playing games - a world with gems like &lt;em&gt;Morrowind&lt;/em&gt;, &lt;em&gt;Anachronox&lt;/em&gt;, &lt;em&gt;Arcanum&lt;/em&gt;, &lt;em&gt;Fallout&lt;/em&gt;, &lt;em&gt;Diablo&lt;/em&gt;, &lt;em&gt;Fable&lt;/em&gt;, and &lt;em&gt;The Witcher&lt;/em&gt;, among many others.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;One day, my Dad saw me playing a role playing game (I don&amp;rsquo;t really remember what it was, but needless to say it was some sort of open world). In the classic way that all fathers say things to their sons when their sons do something they don&amp;rsquo;t understand, he said, &amp;ldquo;I don&amp;rsquo;t get that game. Whenever I see you playing it you&amp;rsquo;re just running somewhere.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;He was right. What&amp;rsquo;s the main thing all the games I listed above have in common? The player spends at least 60% of the game running somewhere.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/commuting_simulators/running.jpg&quot; height=&quot;703&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Sure, you can sprint, but only for thirty seconds at a time for some reason.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Running is the essence of an open world game. You can sprinkle random encounters, crafting ingredients, beautiful vistas, or other marginal player rewards around your world, but in the end when I boot up &lt;em&gt;Skyrim&lt;/em&gt; or &lt;em&gt;ArcaniA&lt;/em&gt; (the awkwardly capitalized latest sequel to &lt;em&gt;Gothic&lt;/em&gt;) I know that it&amp;rsquo;s going to involve me sitting at my desk watching some dude in various levels of armor running for a long time.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Ultimately video games are a waste of time. That&amp;rsquo;s what they&amp;rsquo;re designed to do. Still, there&amp;rsquo;s wasted time, and there&amp;rsquo;s &lt;em&gt;wasted&lt;/em&gt; time. If I&amp;rsquo;m going to watch a movie, I&amp;rsquo;d rather cut straight to the part where the two fugitive cops bust in on the bad guys and have a big shoot fight, instead of watching their entire car trip from New York to Chicago. I&amp;rsquo;d rather have delightfully interesting people to talk to all around me than ten miles between me and my next objective with nothing but some crafting ingredients and GODDAMN CLIFF RACERS.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/commuting_simulators/cliff_racer.jpg&quot; height=&quot;604&quot; width=&quot;700&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The number one reason I&amp;rsquo;m probably never playing &lt;em&gt;Morrowind&lt;/em&gt; again.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Back in the day, roleplaying games were very different. Computers couldn&amp;rsquo;t render big city centers (they could hardly render anything), so games couldn&amp;rsquo;t have sequences where you run around talking to people for hours. Look at the original &lt;em&gt;Mechwarrior&lt;/em&gt; game (or at least what I remember it looking like):&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/commuting_simulators/mech_warrior.jpg&quot; height=&quot;711&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;I tried playing &lt;em&gt;Mechwarrior&lt;/em&gt; recently. It&amp;rsquo;s pretty unplayable.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;You didn&amp;rsquo;t have to go through the tedium of walking from your garage to the place where you get missions. You just clicked a button. For a while, during a time we can call the dark ages of wasting my time, games had no fast travel feature at all. In &lt;em&gt;Gothic&lt;/em&gt; or &lt;em&gt;Morrowind&lt;/em&gt;, we were supposed to be so enamored with the fact that the world is one big open place that we would put up with walking along the same stupid trail from one guy who tells us what to do to an area where monsters hang out so we can kill them. At that point, if anybody ever watched you play one of these games, all they would ever see you do is run somewhere.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Then we get to the modern age of open world games - the age of fast travel. In &lt;em&gt;Skyrim&lt;/em&gt;, you can just click on any village or landmark that you&amp;rsquo;ve already been to and you&amp;rsquo;ll instantly be transported right there. I always start the game thinking, &amp;ldquo;this game is so cool looking, and there&amp;rsquo;s so much to explore that I&amp;rsquo;m never going to use the fast travel.&amp;rdquo; Then about five to ten hours into the game, I fast travel literally everywhere.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/commuting_simulators/map.jpg&quot; height=&quot;458&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Yeah, I&amp;rsquo;m not walking all that way again.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The problem with exploration in video games is that it&amp;rsquo;s so artificial. Okay, so video games are all artificial - fair enough - but it really defeats the purpose. Exploration is about discovering neat little secrets, and the thrill you feel for uncovering them. You&amp;rsquo;re in a world that was entirely put together by a bunch of people, though, so everything was placed there for you to find. You&amp;rsquo;re meant to find it, and that makes it so much less exciting when you do. Skyrim is cram packed with hundreds of little stories and vignettes to find, but to me most of them had this sense that the designers were basically elbowing me in the side and winking the whole time. They just feel like I&amp;rsquo;m being let in on an inside joke. They all end with me shrugging, saying &amp;ldquo;well, there&amp;rsquo;s that,&amp;rdquo; looting all the crafting ingredients I could find, and then moving on to the next cave or hut in the woods.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The fact is that once you see that mountaintop, once you explore those ruins, you&amp;rsquo;re done. Then all you want to do is get to those quest-delivering hotspots as quickly as possible and continue the story. Having to walk to your quest in a video game is just like having to walk to work every morning. Skyrim, then, is not a &amp;ldquo;sticking swords in monsters&amp;rdquo; simulator, it&amp;rsquo;s a &amp;ldquo;commuting to work&amp;rdquo; simulator. I hate commuting to work, and I would probably hate it a lot more if I had to keep killing feral wolves all the time.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/commuting_simulators/lanoire.jpg&quot; height=&quot;559&quot; width=&quot;700&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Or you could be like &lt;em&gt;LA Noire&lt;/em&gt; and both make the world completely uninteresting &lt;em&gt;and&lt;/em&gt; refuse to let me fast travel anywhere.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The game &lt;em&gt;Mount and Blade&lt;/em&gt; is an interesting example. It&amp;rsquo;s nothing but an open world; there&amp;rsquo;s no story or objectives to complete. You&amp;rsquo;re just a dude who can wander around this kingdom recruiting armies and fighting whomever you want. It&amp;rsquo;s kind of neat how you can make your own substance and come up with a bit of a narrative anyway. I&amp;rsquo;m not saying it&amp;rsquo;s some groundbreaking revolution in game design, but I think there&amp;rsquo;s a lot that could be done with it. I&amp;rsquo;ll have to save an analysis of it for a different posting, because that&amp;rsquo;s neither here nor there. What &lt;em&gt;Mount and Blade&lt;/em&gt; does that&amp;rsquo;s relevant is that whenever you enter a town or village, you get a little screen that lets you go straight to the tavern or the shop or whatever.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/commuting_simulators/mountnblade.jpg&quot; height=&quot;563&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Yes, &amp;ldquo;steal cows&amp;rdquo; is an option when you go to a village in &lt;em&gt;Mount and Blade&lt;/em&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It&amp;rsquo;s just like &lt;em&gt;Mechwarrior&lt;/em&gt;. Thirty years later, we&amp;rsquo;re back where we started. You don&amp;rsquo;t get any ability to fast travel from city to city (because then there wouldn&amp;rsquo;t be any game at all), but you don&amp;rsquo;t have to wander around a poorly designed generic village map trying to find some fish to feed to your dudes. It cuts out a completely superfluous, time wasting section of unnecessary gameplay.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;And that&amp;rsquo;s the point, isn&amp;rsquo;t it? Good game design should cut out anything that&amp;rsquo;s unnecessary. What is a game&amp;rsquo;s point? What are players here to do? What is wasting their time and keeping them from doing that?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I suppose the argument is that we might as well just have a button that says &amp;ldquo;play for me&amp;rdquo; and leave it at that. Why not? Why shouldn&amp;rsquo;t I be able to skip boring, tedious parts? &lt;strong&gt;The game designer&amp;rsquo;s job should be to give us that button but do everything he can to keep us from wanting to push it.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/commuting_simulators/push_button.jpg&quot; height=&quot;845&quot; width=&quot;1244&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;You win!&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Make gameplay I want to play, not that I want to skip. If you&amp;rsquo;re going to have an open world, it needs to be a place that I actually want to live in, where stuff happens that I want to experience. If you&amp;rsquo;re going to have exploration, you have to make it feel natural. If you&amp;rsquo;re going to make me walk around everywhere, give me a real companion, with personality and desires - another thing &lt;em&gt;Mount and Blade&lt;/em&gt; does really well. Make your game fun all the time, or give me the ability to skip it when it isn&amp;rsquo;t. Don&amp;rsquo;t waste my time.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Someday I hope I can say to my son, in that way that all fathers say things to their sons when their sons do something they don&amp;rsquo;t understand, &amp;ldquo;I don&amp;rsquo;t get this game. Why don&amp;rsquo;t you ever have to run anywhere?&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Is it Saturday again, already? Time sure does fly, doesn&#039;t it? A new Saturday means it&#039;s time for a new Saturday Sweepstakes!&lt;/p&gt;

