&lt;p&gt;How &amp;ldquo;crowdsourcing&amp;rdquo; could save education.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Imagine that you are in your last semester of college. Yes, most of my readers were probably there not terribly long ago, but just bear with me. How do you feel? You probably feel excited or proud. You&amp;rsquo;re ready to enter the world and make a place for yourself. You feel accomplished. You probably don&amp;rsquo;t picture yourself trapped under an immovable weight.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;You should, though.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;To graduate from college today means entering a terrifying and seemingly endless world of debt. Tuition has skyrocketed over the years, and now it seems a student just can&amp;rsquo;t make it through school without some form of student loan. We have as a society built a system that preys on the youth, telling them that the only way to succeed in life is to go to College. We then hand them a contract that commits them to pay for it for the rest of their lives. Perhaps the story we tell our kids is, indeed, true, but the result is a constant curse from which many graduates will never escape.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;You might see that nihilistic sentiment as an exaggeration. &amp;ldquo;It surely isn&amp;rsquo;t that bad,&amp;rdquo; you might say. You obviously aren&amp;rsquo;t one of my college graduate friends, because if you were you would know that it is. It really is that bad.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Some quick Googling (are we supposed to capitalize that?) raises some startling statistics. College students who graduated in 2010 carried an average of &lt;a href=&quot;http://projectonstudentdebt.org/state_by_state-data.php&quot;&gt;$25,250&lt;/a&gt; in debt. We&amp;rsquo;re not talking about doctors or lawyers, here. This is the average of all college graduates in the US. With unemployment rates among college graduates shooting up, too, many new grads have little hope of paying their debt off any time soon. &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.mint.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/07/StudentLoanRepayment.png&quot;&gt;Here&lt;/a&gt;&amp;rsquo;s an interesting infographic I stumbled upon about it.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So now imagine that you&amp;rsquo;re about to graduate, but you have this $25,000 cloud hanging over your head. If you pay $100 every single month, it will take you Twenty-one years to pay that off, and that&amp;rsquo;s not even including interest. Now how do you feel? You&amp;rsquo;re about to enter a world with the highest unemployment rate for college graduates ever, and you have to somehow pay every extra penny you make for the next two decades. What if you want to move somewhere? What if you want to start a family? Can you? What will you never accomplish because you can&amp;rsquo;t afford to try?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Hopefully I&amp;rsquo;ve scared you enough to stick with me here, because I have an idea that might just save future graduates from a similar fate. It might even save - dare I say it - the world!&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The real question that comes up here is not &amp;ldquo;how could a system like this come about?&amp;rdquo; The answer to that is obvious. As long as the &amp;ldquo;free market&amp;rdquo; economy rules our lives, this type of domination will always happen. I&amp;rsquo;m not saying there&amp;rsquo;s anything necessarily wrong with capitalism - that would have to be the subject of another post - I&amp;rsquo;m just saying that this was inevitable. We built a world designed to target populations that are easily exploited financially, and then convince every single generation of children to get the best education they can, completely ignoring the cost. How is nobody outraged by this yet?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The real question that comes up here is &amp;ldquo;why hasn&amp;rsquo;t anyone done anything to stop this?&amp;rdquo; Sure, we have websites with startling statistics, and we march around complaining about our debt and rising tuition, but awareness doesn&amp;rsquo;t necessarily solve anything. We live in the future, where for the first time anybody with an Internet connection has as much theoretical power as anybody else. The time has come to come up with an Internet solution to this problem.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So now we get to my idea. I propose a Crowdsourced Education Investment System. Students -  both past, present, and future - post their College fees on a secure and tightly regulated website (the tricky part will, of course, be to make sure posted needs are legitimate). This will work like Kickstarter or Ebay, except students are offering up their education expenses. Normal people who have some money they want to invest - people like you or me - can log on to this site and buy stakes in these students&amp;rsquo; education. Eventually the students have to pay back these loans, but they go right back to their average Joe investors, not faceless greedy corporations.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;For students, it will work just the same way as the system does now. You&amp;rsquo;ll apply for loans based on your need, someone pays for you to go to school, and then you have to slowly pay it back after you graduate. The difference is that now the person giving you the money is a real human being, investing in your - and by extension their - future. When you do finally get out into the job market and that education pays off, it&amp;rsquo;s not just paying off for some faceless investment firm like Sallie Mae.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;For investors, this system will have the same effect as putting money in a CD or another long-term investment, except that the potential interest rates could be substantially higher. Yes, it will be years before students pay the money back, but with interest rates of up to &lt;a href=&quot;http://studentlendinganalytics.typepad.com/student_lending_analytics/2008/11/what-is-the-average-interest-rate-on-a-private-student-loan-today.html&quot;&gt;10%&lt;/a&gt;, you&amp;rsquo;ll make far more money than you would with your cash just sitting in a bank (earning less than one percent), with far less risk than investing in the Stock Market, and with infinitely more satisfaction than either. Personally, I would much rather invest a few grand in one of these Student Bonds than a complicated and volatile 401k or IRA plan. Let&amp;rsquo;s face it, even in a worse-case scenario, wouldn&amp;rsquo;t you rather lose money on a kid&amp;rsquo;s education than on some stock in a company you hardly know anything about?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So students get money (and an education), people have a tangible and trustworthy investment opportunity, and our society benefits from a new generation of educated, empowered young minds. Everybody wins.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Effectively, it&amp;rsquo;s a new investment firm, just like Citigroup or Sallie Mae, except that it&amp;rsquo;s just a union of regular people. With outrage over the &amp;ldquo;1%&amp;rdquo; going through the roof (just like these student loans themselves), I&amp;rsquo;m honestly surprised more people aren&amp;rsquo;t clamoring to do things just like this.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The real potential of this, though, is the long-term effects it could have on the world. If greedy fat cats aren&amp;rsquo;t profiting anymore from taking advantage of this &amp;ldquo;College or die&amp;rdquo; mentality, we can finally stop hiking tuition and charging for every penny we can get. Maybe once we take the power away from the Few, College will actually be affordable again for the Many.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Ok, so it&amp;rsquo;s far-fetched and certainly optimistic. A product like this would be incredibly hard to get off the ground. How does it make money? How does it protect itself from inevitable liability issues? That&amp;rsquo;s even before you consider what those big corporations will try to do if something like this actually gains traction. Still, what if? What if students could graduate from college without that crushing weight on their shoulders? What if we could come together as the community that we could so easily be and just support each other? What if it turned out that we didn&amp;rsquo;t need &amp;ldquo;investors&amp;rdquo; at all?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Kickstarter has proven that in this Internet-enabled world, we can do things on Our own. We can take care of Ourselves. We can and in fact have - dare I say it - changed the world! Imagine what today&amp;rsquo;s students would be capable of if they could do anything but worry about their debt. Shouldn&amp;rsquo;t we at least try?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Last weekend I went to a birthday party for a few friends. It&#039;s part of the reason why I neglected to post anything here for a few days. Please excuse this personal indulgence - I took pictures at the party and I want you to see them. Don&#039;t worry, though, they aren&#039;t just boring, &quot;look at how cool I am&quot; pictures. This wasn&#039;t a normal 20-something party.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This party had a Dino Jump.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Anyway, that&#039;s what Mike called it. I took it as a fun photographic challenge. It&#039;s not easy to take pictures when everything (including you) is moving unpredictably and terrifyingly.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/dino_jump/dino_jump_1.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The rental place offered a big fan to inflate the thing, but we just used Andrew&#039;s super power. He has an unnatural control over gasses.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/dino_jump/dino_jump_2.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;We have all been raised with the common knowledge that you take your shoes off before going into a Dino Jump. The red sign says &quot;STOP! Do not enter unless operator is on duty.&quot;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/dino_jump/dino_jump_3.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Inside a Dino Jump, everything is shaded blur.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/dino_jump/dino_jump_4.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Three things surprised me at the end of the night: no bones were broken inside the Dino Jump, no boobs were exposed inside the Dino Jump, and nobody threw up inside the Dino Jump. I wouldn&#039;t have bet against any of those happening.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/dino_jump/dino_jump_5.jpg&quot; height=&quot;533&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;I didn&#039;t really notice it at the time, but upon looking through my pictures I noticed that everyone inside the Dino Jump has a giant smile on. If smiles were operators, we&#039;d all be totally fine.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/dino_jump/dino_jump_6.jpg&quot; height=&quot;533&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;One thing you don&#039;t want to do in a Dino Jump is fall over the side. It&#039;s incredibly difficult to get back up. It was always incredibly exciting, though.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/dino_jump/dino_jump_7.jpg&quot; height=&quot;533&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;I&#039;m pretty sure just a few adults surpasses the weight limit for one of these, but we had at least 10 people inside at one point.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/dino_jump/dino_jump_8.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;It was constant, chaotic, nearly terrifying fun.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/dino_jump/dino_jump_9.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Nobody takes a flattering picture inside a Dino Jump. I quickly gave up trying.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/dino_jump/dino_jump_10.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;What&#039;s more fun than a Dino Jump? Tickling Mike inside a Dino Jump. We are all four years old, you see.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/dino_jump/dino_jump_11.jpg&quot; height=&quot;533&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The guy in the blue shirt is Tom. Tom is like a gravity well. He made the Dino Jump sink wherever he was, and everything around him was drawn into his sink-hole. He also constantly farts. He made the Dino Jump stink wherever he was. When he was inside the Dino Jump, everybody was desperately trying to avoid falling into Tom&#039;s stink-sink-hole.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/dino_jump/dino_jump_12.jpg&quot; height=&quot;533&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;A ball is a fun addition to a Dino Jump. Everybody has to sit down for there to be any ability to not be constantly falling over.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/dino_jump/dino_jump_13.jpg&quot; height=&quot;533&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Somebody (usually Tom) always ends up getting bored, though, and starts jumping, which sends everybody scattering.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/dino_jump/dino_jump_14.jpg&quot; height=&quot;533&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The sheer chaos inside the Dino Jump makes it seem like somebody is going to break a bone (or expose a boob) at any moment.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/dino_jump/dino_jump_15.jpg&quot; height=&quot;533&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Falling into a corner was the most terrifying, because not only would it make the whole Dino Jump collapse onto you, but there were also four giant metal spikes holding the thing down, which were just outside each corner, waiting for someone to fall on them.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/dino_jump/dino_jump_16.jpg&quot; height=&quot;533&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;This picture was taken when it was my turn to jump around. This was the least blurry of the pictures taken at this point.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/dino_jump/dino_jump_17.jpg&quot; height=&quot;533&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Tom is a chaotic individual, and he was in a chaotic situation. It could have been a sitcom. Also he constantly farts. That was less fun.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/dino_jump/dino_jump_18.jpg&quot; height=&quot;533&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;There was also a pinata, but that&#039;s outside the scope of this post. Take note of the brown creature head on the left side of the Dino Jump. What the Hell is that thing? it has three horns, a trunk, and a turkey-ish waddle.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I don&amp;rsquo;t want to get ahead of myself, here, but I am really having a hard time being in favor of gel. Yes, technically gel is better than paste ink. It&amp;rsquo;s darker, it&amp;rsquo;s less vulnerable to fading or washing, it works on more mediums, and it&amp;rsquo;s better on the environment. I just have a hard time getting behind it - especially for a general purpose pen. On paper it might be better, but on &lt;em&gt;paper&lt;/em&gt;, it just doesn&amp;rsquo;t do it for me.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I feel exactly the same way about the Hybrid Technica, a precision gel pen from Pentel. It&amp;rsquo;s branded as a pen for artists, though it doesn&amp;rsquo;t really look like one. It has a very fine point, a smooth line, and a little &amp;ldquo;05&amp;rdquo; on the cap. The problem is, though, I&amp;rsquo;m really not sure what this pen is actually good for.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/hybrid_technica/hybrid_technica_2.jpg&quot; height=&quot;533&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The Technica comes in 0.3, 0.4, 0.5, and 0.6 millimeter sizes. Mine is the 0.5 mm.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;First, there&amp;rsquo;s the name. I have absolutely no idea what makes this a hybrid. Perhaps they are emphasizing the use of gel in an art pen. My guess is that they&amp;rsquo;re just trying to make it sound cool. Think about it. The biggest market for sleek looking capped Pentel pens is not artists - it&amp;rsquo;s offices and students trying to look cool. If you name your pen that you&amp;rsquo;re trying to brand as an artist&amp;rsquo;s pen the &amp;ldquo;Artistic Dingdong&amp;rdquo; you&amp;rsquo;ll scare away your only real customer base. &amp;ldquo;Hybrid Technica&amp;rdquo; belies the fact that this is not an artist&amp;rsquo;s pen at heart.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Then, there&amp;rsquo;s the range of sizes. Certainly artists have plenty of reasons to use both a 0.3 and a 0.4 millimeter pen, but with a ballpoint tip and gel ink, I really can&amp;rsquo;t believe these are precise enough to make that much of a difference. Unfortunately, I don&amp;rsquo;t have the other sizes to really see, so I&amp;rsquo;ll just have to put that aside for now. The point (no pun intended) is that offices and students aren&amp;rsquo;t going to care how many tenths of a millimeter their cool looking pens are. So Pentel makes these in a range of sizes for all of the ballpoint pen artists out there. Maybe the Technica really is an artist&amp;rsquo;s pen, then.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Next, there&amp;rsquo;s the ink. I won&amp;rsquo;t go into tons of detail or comparisons. Needless to say, it compares pretty evenly with the &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/post/391/A_Zebra_Three-Way&quot;&gt;Zebra&lt;/a&gt; gel (though the Technica does, obviously, write a much finer line). Being gel, it&amp;rsquo;s nice and dark, but it smears like crazy. Should an artist take the Technica over one of the other art focused gel pens out there? &lt;em&gt;What other art focused gel pens?&lt;/em&gt; There&amp;rsquo;s your problem. Other art pens have felt tips, because ballpoints just aren&amp;rsquo;t good enough. So this isn&amp;rsquo;t an artist&amp;rsquo;s pen at heart, after all. This is an office pen trying to play in a field it isn&amp;rsquo;t qualified for.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Finally, there&amp;rsquo;s the design. Other than the &amp;ldquo;05&amp;rdquo; on the cap, this thing is about as &amp;ldquo;basic Pentel stick&amp;rdquo; as you can get. Don&amp;rsquo;t worry, the guys in the office won&amp;rsquo;t think you&amp;rsquo;re trying to show off too much by taking this to the next staff meeting. It certainly isn&amp;rsquo;t trying to be convenient, either. I tried carrying it as my standard pocket pen for a few days, which was not extremely enjoyable. It fell out of my pocket at one point and it actually cracked when it hit the floor. I almost lost the cap several times. Don&amp;rsquo;t count on it being well built or convenient (it actually makes the &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/post/391/A_Zebra_Three-Way&quot;&gt;Zebra F-301&lt;/a&gt; feel sturdy). It&amp;rsquo;s definitely meant to sit on a desk, then, but is it meant to sit on a desk in chemistry class, or sketching class?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I wrote out a few pages of text with the Technica, just to see how it wrote. Aside from the blur issue, which is always present, I felt that it was just a bit too fine for my tastes. Some people might like the fine point for writing, but it was too harsh for me. I would take any of the pens in my last post over the Technica for writing, even the F-301.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It&amp;rsquo;s supposedly a pen for drawing, though, so I also wanted to see how it handled the sketch pad. You might have seen some of the &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/post/395/Video_Games_Commuting_Simulators&quot;&gt;sketches&lt;/a&gt; I made with it. It was nice and smooth. It mostly made a crisp line. It didn&amp;rsquo;t feel like I was doing art, though. It just felt like I was doodling in the margins of my chemistry homework.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/hybrid_technica/hybrid_technica_sketch_3.jpg&quot; height=&quot;235&quot; width=&quot;300&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;It could have been what I was drawing, though.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It still has all of the failings of any other ballpoint. Sometimes it refused to draw solid, straight lines - or it refused to draw anything at all - which forced me to re-draw my lines, which quickly makes things look sloppy. It also still commits that most heinous of ballpoint sins - &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/post/391/A_Zebra_Three-Way&quot;&gt;Mosesing&lt;/a&gt;. It may not be quite as pronounced - because of the much finer point - but it&amp;rsquo;s still there, compromising any advantage gel is supposed to have.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/hybrid_technica/hybrid_technica_sketch_4.jpg&quot; height=&quot;446&quot; width=&quot;540&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;I&amp;rsquo;m pretty much the best artist.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In the hands of a real artist, though, it&amp;rsquo;s a bit better. Alyson (somebody with a real art degree) took it for a spin, and in a few minutes came up with a sketch of me that I feel is actually pretty damn good.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/hybrid_technica/hybrid_technica_sketch_2.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1212&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;She really captured my freckles - and steam breath.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This scribble-ey style is much more suited to the Technica, but you still can&amp;rsquo;t erase its shortcomings. It isn&amp;rsquo;t much of a problem anymore, but the Mosesing and broken lines are still there. The simple fact is that these problems just wouldn&amp;rsquo;t be there if she was using a Micron.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/hybrid_technica/hybrid_technica_sketch_5.jpg&quot; height=&quot;521&quot; width=&quot;637&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Imagine turning in your chemistry lab worksheet with this in the margins.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Alyson didn&amp;rsquo;t hate the Technica. She liked the dark lines it put down, and liked its precision. However, she only used it in the first place because I asked her to, and as soon as I&amp;rsquo;m done with this review (which is now), she&amp;rsquo;ll probably go back to felt tips for her line work.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;That&amp;rsquo;s the Hybrid Technica in a nutshell. It&amp;rsquo;s trying to be an artist&amp;rsquo;s pen, but it isn&amp;rsquo;t as good as a felt tip. It&amp;rsquo;s trying to keep to its taking-notes-in-chemistry-class roots, too, but it&amp;rsquo;s straying just a bit too far. It isn&amp;rsquo;t sturdy enough or convenient enough to carry in your pocket. It seems harder and harder to see the Technica filling any role, especially when you consider that it&amp;rsquo;s &lt;em&gt;more&lt;/em&gt; expensive than the same size Micron.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/hybrid_technica/hybrid_technica_3.jpg&quot; height=&quot;533&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Pentel says the Hybrid Technica has a fine point, I say it has no point at all.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This hybrid succeeds at bridging the gap between art and gel pens. Unfortunately, it only manages to keep all of the disadvantages of both. Artists should stick with felt, and leave gel where it belongs, writing checks and taking notes in chemistry class.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h5&gt;And also . . .&lt;/h5&gt;

&lt;p&gt;As a side note - in case you need another reason not to use gel for anything but writing checks, I did another quick test of inks - the &amp;ldquo;back of the hand&amp;rdquo; test. I wrote a quick note on the back of my hand with the Parker Jotter, the F-402, the G-301, and the Hybrid Technica (in that order).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/hybrid_technica/hybrid_technica_1.jpg&quot; height=&quot;533&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;I&amp;rsquo;m just happy that a club finally accepted me as a member.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Even though it&amp;rsquo;s supposed to be better on more surfaces, gel does not work well on skin, and the Technica&amp;rsquo;s fine point made it almost useless. Both gels almost immediately washed away, too. At the end of the day, as I&amp;rsquo;m typing this, only one of the inks has been able to outlast the others, and it probably isn&amp;rsquo;t a huge surprise who it was. You guessed it - Parker (the ink). That&amp;rsquo;s yet another reason to keep a Jotter handy, in case you&amp;rsquo;re the sort that likes to - well - &lt;em&gt;jot&lt;/em&gt; reminders or phone numbers down on the back of your hand, or if - like me - you&amp;rsquo;re trying to recruit more members to your new favorite club.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Have you always wanted a super cool website? Do you want to enter the exciting and unfathomably vast and lonely sea of websites and mostly garbage that is the Internet? Do you look at Me with scornful envy in your eyes, cursing and damning and cursing again at my ability to website a whole bunch of times when you could never hope to website? Well, my friend, the time has come to learn that it isn&amp;rsquo;t that hard to website - in fact, even you can do it! Over the next few posts, I&amp;rsquo;ll show you every step in the process of putting together and deploying a fully functional blog-based website! No longer will you be held back by your technical ignorance. In a few days, the only thing that will be able to stop you from having your own website is your inability to come up with interesting things to write about.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I am a professional websiteman, by trade - that is, I specialize in doing websites. Aside from DenyConformity.com (pretty much the best website), I&amp;rsquo;ve made quite a few others for friends, clients, companies, or myself. The hard part is designing and putting together a unique and interesting site layout, and for the most part that&amp;rsquo;s what I get paid a bunch of money for. It&amp;rsquo;s actually really easy to website, though, if you don&amp;rsquo;t mind using pre-made components. Okay, so it&amp;rsquo;s still pretty complicated, but as long as you follow the proper procedure, for about $100 a year you can have your very own website on your own unique domain name. This is all assuming, of course, that you&amp;rsquo;ve thought about what you actually want a website for, and have a clear goal in mind for what you want to do with it. I&amp;rsquo;ll show you the &amp;ldquo;how&amp;rdquo; but you have to bring the &amp;ldquo;why.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;I should mention that this whole guide is about Windows 7. This is all equally easy in Mac OS or Windows Vista, but I don&amp;rsquo;t have those so I can&amp;rsquo;t really get screenshots of them.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h5&gt;Part 1: Get Ready to Website&lt;/h5&gt;

&lt;p&gt;You could make things easier for yourself by just buying a hosting plan and doing everything there, but that&amp;rsquo;s not the right way to do it. You could end up taking days or weeks (or years) setting up the site, and in the meantime your janky-assed &amp;ldquo;work in progress&amp;rdquo; is fully public for the world to see. Sure, you can set it up to show a &amp;ldquo;coming soon&amp;rdquo; page and block search engines until you get it finished, but it&amp;rsquo;s way easier to just set the site up on your computer and then deploy it to your web space.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/0.jpg&quot; height=&quot;645&quot; width=&quot;905&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;That Bluehost.com lady is really ready to help you website.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;You probably should go ahead and buy your hosting plan right away, though. The sooner you register your domain name, the better, so that nobody else steals it from you. Also, it can take up to a few days for your new domain name to start working, so you might as well do it now. I won&amp;rsquo;t get into explaining what a web host is, but basically you need a little hard drive to put your website on which is visible to the Internet. There are many companies you can use, and most of them are very similar - just make sure your plan includes a MySQL database (you&amp;rsquo;ll be hard pressed to find one that doesn&amp;rsquo;t) and email addresses if you want your own email addresses. DenyConformity.com is hosted on &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.bluehost.com&quot;&gt;Bluehost&lt;/a&gt;, and I&amp;rsquo;m very pleased with them. Whatever you do, avoid  &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/post/361/DC_Down&quot;&gt;GoDaddy or Startlogic&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/0-1.jpg&quot; height=&quot;460&quot; width=&quot;603&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Damn, pin15.com is not available.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The process is different based on who you use, but it should be pretty simple. Just find the &amp;ldquo;sign up now&amp;rdquo; button and fill in the blanks. Most hosting companies will give you a domain name with your plan, and they will help you register it (and make sure it&amp;rsquo;s available). There is really a whole industry around picking a domain name, but don&amp;rsquo;t overthink it. If you&amp;rsquo;re setting up a personal website, just use your name (dot com). If you have a small business, use the company name - or some variation of it (dot com). You can use a .org or .net address if you absolutely have to, but you should stick with a .com. Also try to avoid dashes, underscores, or other awkward characters; it can be harder to tell people &amp;ldquo;something dash something dot com&amp;rdquo; than just &amp;ldquo;something something dot com.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/0-2.jpg&quot; height=&quot;672&quot; width=&quot;974&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;What a waste of a perfectly good domain name!&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;If your preferred domain isn&amp;rsquo;t available, but it obviously isn&amp;rsquo;t a real site (like the picture above), it&amp;rsquo;s probably held by a cybersquatter. These ne&#039;erdowells are the scum of the Internet, but there isn&amp;rsquo;t much you can do about them. Sometimes GoDaddy can help you buy these domains, usually because they&amp;rsquo;re the ones illegally holding them. If all else fails, you can do a WHOIS lookup on the domain to get the contact info for the people who registered the domain. Don&amp;rsquo;t expect much luck, because usually these are very undesirable types, but you never know.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Anyway, once you get the hosting all squared away, they&amp;rsquo;ll send you an email with a bunch of technical gobbledygook in it about your new website. Make sure you archive, print out, or otherwise save that info in a place. Don&amp;rsquo;t worry about it for now, but know that it is important. Now you just have to wait patiently for Magic to Happen so that your new website becomes an Internet (it&amp;rsquo;s all very technical).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Don&amp;rsquo;t just sit back, though, because you still have a lot of work to do! We&amp;rsquo;re going to create your website right there on your computer, which means we have to turn your computer into a sort of makeshift Internet. Unfurrow that brow; it&amp;rsquo;s actually pretty easy.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/1.jpg&quot; height=&quot;701&quot; width=&quot;432&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Open up the Start Menu, and hit the &amp;ldquo;Control Panel&amp;rdquo; button. If you don&amp;rsquo;t have a &amp;ldquo;Control Panel&amp;rdquo; button, then you&amp;rsquo;ll have to get to the control panel a different way. Try just typing &amp;ldquo;Control Panel&amp;rdquo; in the search box. Just get to the Control Panel, and then meet me at the next step.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/2.jpg&quot; height=&quot;529&quot; width=&quot;738&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Here&amp;rsquo;s the default Control Panel view. Click on &amp;ldquo;Uninstall a program&amp;rdquo; under &amp;ldquo;Programs&amp;rdquo; Don&amp;rsquo;t worry about your computer being powerful enough to Internet. If it&amp;rsquo;s running Windows 7 okay, it will be able to Internet okay, at least as much as we&amp;rsquo;re going to ask it to, which won&amp;rsquo;t be much. It won&amp;rsquo;t have to Internet terribly hard.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/3.jpg&quot; height=&quot;547&quot; width=&quot;756&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Look, stop worrying about how many C++ Redistributables I have, and just click &amp;ldquo;Turn Windows features on or off.&amp;rdquo; Click &amp;ldquo;allow&amp;rdquo; or whatever if Windows gives you guff about wanting to use your computer.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/4.jpg&quot; height=&quot;374&quot; width=&quot;429&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Back in the day you would disable some of these things to save precious Megabytes on your hard drive for sweet games, but with today&amp;rsquo;s multifoliate Jiggabytes, you can use your computer for years without ever needing to remove Solitaire. Anyway, we want to click the little box next to &amp;ldquo;Internet Information Services.&amp;rdquo; That&amp;rsquo;s what turns your computer into an Internet! Note: I&amp;rsquo;ll be referring to Internet Information Services as IIS from now on.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/5.jpg&quot; height=&quot;463&quot; width=&quot;435&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;This is what should happen when you click the box. It automatically selects the most common options, which includes &amp;ldquo;Web Management Tools&amp;rdquo; and &amp;ldquo;World Wide Web Services.&amp;rdquo; Also, under &amp;ldquo;World Wide Web Services&amp;rdquo; open &amp;ldquo;Application Development Features&amp;rdquo; and make sure &amp;ldquo;CGI&amp;rdquo; is selected.  If for some reason you already have IIS installed, make sure you have subitems installed like you see in the picture above so you can properly website when we get to steps down the road.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/6.jpg&quot; height=&quot;179&quot; width=&quot;369&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;After a bit of a wait (but not long enough for me to get a screenshot, apparently), you&amp;rsquo;ll have to restart your computer. Make sure you save anything you&amp;rsquo;re working on, like for example a post on your blog that you&amp;rsquo;ve been working on for like an hour but forgot to save. You don&amp;rsquo;t want to have to start from the freaking beginning again even though the second time you write it you aren&amp;rsquo;t anywhere near as funny as the first time.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/7.jpg&quot; height=&quot;712&quot; width=&quot;432&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;When your computer comes back up, it won&amp;rsquo;t look any different - and it won&amp;rsquo;t behave any differently either (it shouldn&amp;rsquo;t, at least). However, your computer is now basically an Internet. First you have to know where to go to change important settings for that, and then I&#039;ll show you how to view your computer&amp;rsquo;s adorable little baby website.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/8.jpg&quot; height=&quot;694&quot; width=&quot;584&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Type &amp;ldquo;Administrative Tools&amp;rdquo; into your Start Menu, and find the Administrative Tools. It might show up before you finish typing the whole thing, so it will save you some precious finger movements.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/9.jpg&quot; height=&quot;311&quot; width=&quot;293&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;This is where you can do some serious Administration on your computer. For now, you want &amp;ldquo;Computer Management&amp;rdquo;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/10.jpg&quot; height=&quot;720&quot; width=&quot;932&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Expand &amp;ldquo;Services and Applications&amp;rdquo; and pick &amp;ldquo;Internet Information Services (IIS) Manager&amp;rdquo; from the list on the left. This is where you tell your computer how to deal with being an Internet. There&amp;rsquo;s a ton to the IIS manager, but we won&amp;rsquo;t need to mess with most of it.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/11.jpg&quot; height=&quot;300&quot; width=&quot;359&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;You should see this &amp;ldquo;Connections&amp;rdquo; section, on the left side of the Management Console. You&amp;rsquo;ll see your computer&amp;rsquo;s name (that&amp;rsquo;s your computer&amp;rsquo;s name, FYI - mine is called SEPTEM for some reason). Expand that and also expand &amp;ldquo;Sites&amp;rdquo; and you should see &amp;ldquo;Default Web Site.&amp;rdquo; Click on it. If you don&amp;rsquo;t have a &amp;ldquo;Default Web Site,&amp;rdquo; something has gone wrong. Try removing and reinstalling IIS. I brought you here to show you that your computer is running a tiny little Internet. You&amp;rsquo;ll need to get back here a few times over the rest of the process, so it&amp;rsquo;s good to know how to get to the IIS console and your Default Site.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/12.jpg&quot; height=&quot;576&quot; width=&quot;740&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Open a web browser (any will do), and type &amp;ldquo;localhost&amp;rdquo; into the address bar. If you see the IIS7 logo, you&amp;rsquo;re in business! You&amp;rsquo;re looking at your very own website running right there on your computer. When you go to &amp;ldquo;localhost&amp;rdquo; you&amp;rsquo;re telling the browser to look for a web server on the local computer. If you set up your firewall to allow it and you knew the IP address assigned to you by your ISP, you could view your new little Internet anywhere in the world (as long as your computer was on and your ISP hasn&#039;t changed your IP address yet). See my ongoing posts about my &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/post/247/Web_server_1&quot;&gt;web server&lt;/a&gt; project for more information about web servers.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So today we (maybe) bought a new hosting plan somewhere and got the ball rolling on getting some real webspace, then we set up IIS and took a look at an adorable little Internet running right there inside your computer. Next time we&amp;rsquo;ll look at setting up and configuring a new local Web Site, and we&amp;rsquo;ll install and configure a MySQL database.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So you&amp;rsquo;ve enabled your computer&amp;rsquo;s secret ability to be an Internet. Big deal! What do you do with that puny little Internet of yours? You make a website, of course! Ok, then, off you go; go have some website. What, you still don&amp;rsquo;t know how to website?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Oh, right, that&amp;rsquo;s what I&amp;rsquo;m trying to teach you. Well, we had better get started, then.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h5&gt;Part 2: PHP Doesn&amp;rsquo;t Stand For Anything&lt;/h5&gt;

&lt;p&gt;We have to start with a bit of a lecture, I&amp;rsquo;m afraid. Essentially, the Internet is made up of two types of computers - servers and clients. Your computer&amp;rsquo;s browser is a client. It connects to websites and downloads HyperText Markup Language (that&amp;rsquo;s what HTML stands for) so you can read about celebrities and check Facebook statuses. A server compiles lots of code and does all sorts of magic on it before sending it out to the client as HTML. As you might imagine, there are therefore two basic types of programming for the Internet - server-side and client-side. The end goal of all web programming, whether on the client or the server, is to generate certain HTML markup for the browser to display. For the most part, then, all languages for making websites are designed to wrangle data somehow, turn it into HTML somehow, and send it to the browser somehow. This is about as basic as I can be without just saying &amp;ldquo;ELECTROBOX DO MAGIC.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;One popular client-side programming language is called Javascript (it&amp;rsquo;s actually a scripting language, but we don&amp;rsquo;t need to get that specific). A popular server-side programming language is called PHP (again, it&amp;rsquo;s a scripting language, but whatever). Neither is better or worse, they have very important strengths and weaknesses and are used for very specific and different things. How this matters to you is that you need to configure your new web server to handle the server-side technologies that you&amp;rsquo;re going to throw at it. Since client-side stuff doesn&amp;rsquo;t happen on the server, your server could not possibly care less about it. By default, Microsoft&amp;rsquo;s web server technology (IIS) doesn&amp;rsquo;t know how to deal with PHP, so we need to tell it what&amp;rsquo;s up.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/16.jpg&quot; height=&quot;263&quot; width=&quot;393&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;There is some contention over what PHP actually stands for. Originally it meant &amp;ldquo;Personal Home Page&amp;rdquo; but now it stands for &amp;ldquo;PHP: Hypertext PreProcessor&amp;rdquo; which doesn&amp;rsquo;t really make any sense. Anyway, just head over to &lt;a href=&quot;windows.php.net/download/&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;windows.php.net/download/&lt;/a&gt; and download the latest Non Thread Safe version of PHP (get the first &amp;ldquo;Zip&amp;rdquo; on the page). Don&amp;rsquo;t worry about &amp;ldquo;Non Thread Safe.&amp;rdquo; That&amp;rsquo;s just technical mumbo-jumbo that means nothing to you.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/17.jpg&quot; height=&quot;401&quot; width=&quot;549&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Open up a Windows Explorer window (do this quickly by holding the Windows Key - the little flag button between the left control and alt keys - and pressing &amp;ldquo;E&amp;rdquo;). Go right to C: and create a new folder simply called &amp;ldquo;php&amp;rdquo; right there.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/18.jpg&quot; height=&quot;403&quot; width=&quot;553&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Extract the contents of that Zip file you just downloaded from php.net into your new php folder. At the time of writing this post the latest version of PHP (5.4.2) has three folders and 41 files to extract into there. I won&amp;rsquo;t hold your hand and tell you how to extract Zip files, but if you&amp;rsquo;re having trouble maybe making a website isn&amp;rsquo;t for you.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/19.jpg&quot; height=&quot;447&quot; width=&quot;551&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;PHP relies on this super config file called php.ini. You should find two versions in your php folder, php.ini-development and php.ini-production. These are sample files that have most of the usual configuration settings for those environments. Since we&amp;rsquo;re setting up a development environment, we can use that one. Just rename that file &amp;ldquo;php.ini&amp;rdquo; You should probably &lt;a href=&quot;http://windows.microsoft.com/en-us/windows-vista/show-or-hide-file-name-extensions&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;disable&lt;/a&gt; the &amp;ldquo;hide file extensions for known filetypes&amp;rdquo; setting in your folder options if you haven&amp;rsquo;t already.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/20.jpg&quot; height=&quot;471&quot; width=&quot;615&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;You can just open php.ini in Notepad, now (right click it and go to &amp;ldquo;open with&amp;rdquo;). This can be a really intimidating file, so try not to get lost in all that crazy stuff. Also, don&amp;rsquo;t touch anything, because you can cause lots of problems if you mess something up here. Just find the following settings and make sure they&amp;rsquo;re set as such (you can hit Ctrl + F to search for each setting). Each setting should be on its own line, and will probably have a semi-colon before it. Make sure you remove that semi-colon, as it tells PHP to ignore the line. To be clear, make sure your php.ini file has the following things all on their own lines exactly as they are here:&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;fastcgi.inpersonate = 1&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;fastcgi.logging = 0&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;cgi.fix_pathinfo = 1&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;cgi.force_redirect = 0&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;

&lt;p&gt;If you are a wimp or something, you can just download the &lt;a href=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/php.ini-denyconformity&quot;&gt;php.ini&lt;/a&gt; file I prepared for this tutorial and put it in your C:/php folder (make sure to rename it &amp;ldquo;php.ini&amp;rdquo; too). It is for PHP version 5.4.2, but it will probably work for any version 5.whatever.whatever.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/13.jpg&quot; height=&quot;241&quot; width=&quot;435&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Remember how to get to the IIS Manager? There&amp;rsquo;s actually an easier way. Just press the Windows Key and &amp;ldquo;R&amp;rdquo; at the same time to open the Run dialog box. Then type &amp;ldquo;inetmgr&amp;rdquo; into the box and hit Enter (or click OK). I told you the slow way before so you get this neat little reward for coming back to read the second part of the tutorial. Good work, you.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/15.jpg&quot; height=&quot;799&quot; width=&quot;1013&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Are you super happy to see the old IIS Manager again? We&amp;rsquo;re going to tweak and add a few settings to your brave little webserver to make it operate the way we need it to in order to host a really great website place. Just follow along, and hopefully this will be as painless as possible. It might also help if you stop sitting on those thumbtacks and get that cat to stop biting you, but I&amp;rsquo;m not going to tell you how to live your life.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/21.jpg&quot; height=&quot;684&quot; width=&quot;944&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Make sure your server is selected under Connections (just select the first node, the one with your computer&amp;rsquo;s name) and open &amp;ldquo;Handler Mappings&amp;rdquo;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/22.jpg&quot; height=&quot;681&quot; width=&quot;934&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Click on &amp;ldquo;Add Module Mapping&amp;rdquo; and fill it out as follows:&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Request path: *.php&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Module: FastCgiModule&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Executable: C:phpphp-cgi.exe (either type it in or hit the &amp;ldquo;OK&amp;rdquo; button - but make sure you switch it from .dll files to .exe files when you&amp;rsquo;re looking for a file to open)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Name: PHP_via_FastCGI&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/23.jpg&quot; height=&quot;392&quot; width=&quot;476&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Click &amp;ldquo;Request restrictions,&amp;rdquo; and check the box next to &amp;ldquo;Invoke handler only if request is mapped to:&amp;rdquo; and pick &amp;ldquo;File or folder.&amp;rdquo; Hit &amp;ldquo;OK&amp;rdquo; a few times, and when it asks you if you want to create a FastCGI application, say &amp;ldquo;Yes.&amp;rdquo; Now you should be back at the IIS Manager, which now has your new Handler Mapping to handle PHP files. Go back (either click your server in the Connections area or click the back button at the top of the IIS Manager).&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/24.jpg&quot; height=&quot;681&quot; width=&quot;926&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Open &amp;ldquo;Default Document,&amp;rdquo; click on &amp;ldquo;Add...&amp;rdquo; and enter &amp;ldquo;index.php&amp;rdquo; This will (after you hit &amp;ldquo;OK&amp;rdquo; of course) make sure that any file called index.php will open by default. This is customary procedure.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/31.jpg&quot; height=&quot;683&quot; width=&quot;930&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Go back to the Server Home section once again and select &amp;ldquo;Error Pages.&amp;rdquo; Click on &amp;ldquo;Edit Feature Settings,&amp;rdquo; change it to &amp;ldquo;Detailed errors&amp;rdquo; and hit &amp;ldquo;OK.&amp;rdquo; This will make your server send more useful error messages which will probably save you a few headaches in the future if you need to debug any problems with server-side code.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Okay, so PHP should be working on your Internet, now. The last thing we&amp;rsquo;ll do is create the world&amp;rsquo;s easiest web page to test that out.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/25.jpg&quot; height=&quot;681&quot; width=&quot;932&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Open your server in the Connections area, open Sites, and then select Default Web Site. Switch to the Content View (the tabs near the bottom of the IIS Manager window). You should see two files: iisstart.htm and welcome.png. Hit the &amp;ldquo;Explore&amp;rdquo; button, and it will open a new Windows Explorer window here.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/26.jpg&quot; height=&quot;598&quot; width=&quot;621&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Right click in the blank area, select &amp;ldquo;new&amp;rdquo; and then &amp;ldquo;Text Document.&amp;rdquo; Rename the file &amp;ldquo;index.php&amp;rdquo; making sure that it isn&amp;rsquo;t &amp;ldquo;index.php.txt&amp;rdquo; because Windows really hates changing file extensions. Make sure you&amp;rsquo;ve &lt;a href=&quot;http://windows.microsoft.com/en-us/windows-vista/show-or-hide-file-name-extensions&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;disabled&lt;/a&gt; the &amp;ldquo;hide file extensions for known filetypes&amp;rdquo; setting in your folder options if you haven&amp;rsquo;t already.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/27.jpg&quot; height=&quot;514&quot; width=&quot;624&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;You can now open this mysterious new &amp;ldquo;index.php&amp;rdquo; file in Notepad (right click it and say &amp;ldquo;open with&amp;rdquo;). This file is much easier to handle than the php.ini file, isn&amp;rsquo;t it (because this one is completely empty)? You don&amp;rsquo;t even need to do much programming to make your first web page. I&amp;rsquo;m assuming, of course, that you&amp;rsquo;ve never made a website before now. If you&amp;rsquo;ve made a website before, I guess you don&amp;rsquo;t need me; I&amp;rsquo;ll just go sit in the corner and make jokes about busses.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/28.jpg&quot; height=&quot;122&quot; width=&quot;236&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Type exactly this into the file, and then save and close it: &amp;ldquo;&amp;lt;?php phpinfo() ?&amp;gt;&amp;rdquo; Seriously, that&amp;rsquo;s it. You just made your first web page.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/29.jpg&quot; height=&quot;710&quot; width=&quot;805&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Just like at the end of part one, open up a web browser (or open a new tab in the web browser you&amp;rsquo;re reading this on), and type &amp;ldquo;localhost&amp;rdquo; into the address bar. If you see a bunch of stuff about PHP, you have successfully completed this part of the tutorial. If not, you&amp;rsquo;ll have to go back and see what you missed. I&amp;rsquo;ll just continue this thing as if it all worked, though.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;You&amp;rsquo;ve actually done quite a bit just now.  First, you installed PHP on your computer, and then you set up your computer&amp;rsquo;s web server to properly use it when somebody accesses a PHP file. You then created a new file that calls a special function in PHP which poops out a bunch of info about your computer&amp;rsquo;s version of PHP.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A website is just a directory on a computer somewhere. Your new &amp;ldquo;Default Web Site&amp;rdquo; is just a folder on your computer (&amp;ldquo;C:inetpubwwwroot&amp;rdquo; by default). Any files inside that folder will be accessible when you go to &amp;ldquo;localhost&amp;rdquo; in a browser, and the server will handle it a different way depending on what kind of file it is. When you tell the browser to open &amp;ldquo;index.php&amp;rdquo; (which it does by default when you don&amp;rsquo;t give it a specific file to open - remember when you told it to do that?), it sends a request to the server for that file. The server is all, &amp;ldquo;woah, that&amp;rsquo;s a PHP file, brah&amp;rdquo; (because you told it that all files with a .php extension are special files in the Handler Mapping, and your computer is apparently kind of a d-bag) and it opens the file with &amp;ldquo;php-cgi.exe&amp;rdquo; just like you told it to.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;PHP and your computer compile the code in the file into delicious beeps and boops, and then process those beeps and boops however they&amp;rsquo;re designed to be processed. In this case, you&amp;rsquo;ve used the function &amp;ldquo;phpinfo()&amp;rdquo; which simply creates this cool little list of all the stuff that&amp;rsquo;s going on in your server, PHP-wise. You computer compiled your script, and the PHP files you installed processed that function into a bunch of Hypertext which get sent along to your browser. All that stuff happened the instant you hit &amp;ldquo;enter&amp;rdquo; in your browser&amp;rsquo;s address bar! Neat!&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/30.jpg&quot; height=&quot;585&quot; width=&quot;840&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;This is the actual Hypertext that your browser is showing.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Try right clicking on the page and select &amp;ldquo;View Source.&amp;rdquo; Look at all that code that your little web server sent to your browser! That shows the power of server-side technology like PHP. The actual code for the page is only one function - &amp;ldquo;phpinfo()&amp;rdquo; - but the code sent to the browser is vastly different. This is only scratching the surface of what you can do with server-side scripting in PHP.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So now we&amp;rsquo;re one step closer to a super cool website, and now you have a really great development platform for playing around with PHP (among other things). Tomorrow I&amp;rsquo;ll be back here with another important step in getting your computer ready to be a super cool Internet, and then we&amp;rsquo;ll get on with doing a website - I promise. Before you know it, you&amp;rsquo;ll be able to website like a champ.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h5&gt;Related Reading&lt;/h5&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In the meanwhile, if you&amp;rsquo;re interested in learning a bit more about client- and server-side languages, there are some great resources online for you to check out. You won&#039;t need to know any of this stuff to complete my tutorial, but it&#039;s all very important stuff to know if you want to really get into doing websites. Feel free to create more files in your Default Web Site to practice any of this stuff, and bask in how genuinely cool what you&#039;re doing actually is.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;First, you should get the basics of HTML, so you can understand how a website is really made. (&lt;a href=&quot;http://w3schools.com/html/default.asp&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;HTML Tutorial&lt;/a&gt;)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Next you can play around with client-side scripting in Javascript. (&lt;a href=&quot;http://w3schools.com/js/default.asp&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Javascript Tutorial&lt;/a&gt;)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Finally, why not play around with some PHP on your new development platform? (&lt;a href=&quot;http://w3schools.com/php/default.asp&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;PHP Tutorial&lt;/a&gt;)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;How&amp;rsquo;s &amp;ldquo;My First Web Server&amp;rdquo; treating you? Have you been playing around with making cool website places? Do you want me to just shut up and get on with the next part of the tutorial?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Well, it&amp;rsquo;s hard for me to explain what to do if I have to shut up, isn&amp;rsquo;t it? Enough jibber-jabber; let&amp;rsquo;s get on with it.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Part 3: The SQL Sequel&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In order to have a really cool website place, you&amp;rsquo;ll need something to store lots of data in. That&amp;rsquo;s what a database is for, believe it or not. Almost every website on the Internet uses some sort of database, and almost all of those use some form of Structured Query Language, or SQL (pronounced &amp;ldquo;sequel&amp;rdquo;). Modern smartphones all have a SQL database on them, too (iPhones and Android phones really aren&amp;rsquo;t that different). The most popular SQL database for websites is called MySQL, and the best thing about it is that it&amp;rsquo;s free! Almost definitely the webspace you bought as part of the first section of this tutorial includes a MySQL database with it, but you need one on your development environment so you can get a cool website set up.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/14.jpg&quot; height=&quot;382&quot; width=&quot;730&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Head over to &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.mysql.com/downloads/installer&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;http://www.mysql.com/downloads/installer&lt;/a&gt; and download the latest version of the MySQL installer package. When it asks you to log in you can just say &amp;ldquo;No thanks, just take me to the downloads.&amp;rdquo; You should then see a list of US mirrors. It doesn&amp;rsquo;t really matter which mirror you pick (they&amp;rsquo;re just different places you can download the file from). Click the little &amp;ldquo;http&amp;rdquo; next to the closest one to wherever you are. It&amp;rsquo;s a couple hundred megabytes, so it might take a while to download.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;While you&amp;rsquo;re waiting for it to download, why not read some funny stuff on the Internet? You can pick up the rest of this tutorial when it&amp;rsquo;s done downloading. I&amp;rsquo;ll wait.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It&amp;rsquo;s done? You&amp;rsquo;re back? Cool. Install that thing you just downloaded.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/32.jpg&quot; height=&quot;611&quot; width=&quot;818&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The process is a bit more automated than the whole &amp;ldquo;just put these files somewhere&amp;rdquo; method that PHP uses. Select &amp;ldquo;Install MySQL Products&amp;rdquo; (duh). Accept the license terms and press Next. If you just downloaded the file you can probably skip the &amp;ldquo;Find Latest Products&amp;rdquo; step, but there&amp;rsquo;s no harm in it, really.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/33.jpg&quot; height=&quot;616&quot; width=&quot;815&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;For &amp;ldquo;Setup Type&amp;rdquo; pick &amp;ldquo;Server only.&amp;rdquo; The other types install a bunch of additional stuff that we won&amp;rsquo;t need if all we want to do is website. If you&amp;rsquo;re thinking you might make some C++ applications or you otherwise need some ODBC connections, go ahead and pick &amp;ldquo;Developer Default.&amp;rdquo; If you don&amp;rsquo;t know what any of that means, just pick &amp;ldquo;Server only&amp;rdquo; please. The default Installation and Data paths should be perfectly fine.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/34.jpg&quot; height=&quot;615&quot; width=&quot;818&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;My computer didn&amp;rsquo;t need any additional requirements, but yours might - it depends on how many C++ redistributables you have installed (among other things). Let the thing do it&amp;rsquo;s thing and get all of its beeps and boops in order before you continue.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/35.jpg&quot; height=&quot;613&quot; width=&quot;814&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;You should just have the one Product to install. Make sure you gird your loins, and then press EXECUTE! The thing will install, it will be very anti-climactic, and then you&amp;rsquo;ll hit Next (twice).&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/36.jpg&quot; height=&quot;612&quot; width=&quot;816&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Ensure that it&amp;rsquo;s set to be a Developer Machine, so MySQL won&amp;rsquo;t take over all of your memories.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/37.jpg&quot; height=&quot;617&quot; width=&quot;817&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Just use the default settings for Port Number. You can turn the Windows Service off, because you won&amp;rsquo;t be needing it. Security isn&amp;rsquo;t a huge concern because this is just going to run on your computer, so just make your password something really easy to remember, like &amp;ldquo;password.&amp;rdquo; It really doesn&amp;rsquo;t matter at this stage (just make sure you remember what you made it). Hit next a couple times until you can hit finish, and then hit that.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So now you have a database running on your computer. You&amp;rsquo;ll hardly be able to find proof of this, but just trust me. Before we can really do anything with it, we&amp;rsquo;ll need to download a really great tool called PHPMyAdmin. It&amp;rsquo;s a whole website that you&amp;rsquo;re going to run on your computer that connects to your MySQL database using PHP so you can create databases, manipulate tables, or do whatever you might want to do. It&amp;rsquo;s going to utilize everything we&amp;rsquo;ve done up to this point, so hopefully you were able to get everything working properly.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/38.jpg&quot; height=&quot;410&quot; width=&quot;674&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Head over to &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.phpmyadmin.net/home_page/downloads.php&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;http://www.phpmyadmin.net/home_page/downloads.php&lt;/a&gt; and pick the file called phpMyAdmin-X.X.X-english.zip (where the X&amp;rsquo;s are the latest version). Right now (as shown in the screenshot above), the file we want is the last one in the recommended version list. I guess you can get the &amp;ldquo;all languages&amp;rdquo; version if you want to manage your MySQL database in French or something.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/39.jpg&quot; height=&quot;544&quot; width=&quot;693&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Just like we did with PHP, you&amp;rsquo;re going to open up this zip file and extract it somewhere. Inside the file should just be one folder, named the same as the zip file itself.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/40.jpg&quot; height=&quot;505&quot; width=&quot;710&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Copy that folder to the directory where your Default Web Site is located (usually C:/inetpub/wwwroot). Once it&amp;rsquo;s done, rename the folder &amp;ldquo;phpMyAdmin&amp;rdquo; (that way it&amp;rsquo;s easier to access).&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/46.jpg&quot; height=&quot;300&quot; width=&quot;325&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Inside this new phpMyAdmin folder, create a new folder called &amp;ldquo;config.&amp;rdquo; PhpMyAdmin needs this folder to save its various beeps and boops in as it works.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/47.jpg&quot; height=&quot;502&quot; width=&quot;392&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Right click the &amp;ldquo;config&amp;rdquo; folder, select &amp;ldquo;Properties,&amp;rdquo; and then go to the &amp;ldquo;Security&amp;rdquo; tab.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/48.jpg&quot; height=&quot;466&quot; width=&quot;389&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Press &amp;ldquo;Edit,&amp;rdquo; select &amp;ldquo;Users,&amp;rdquo; and then check the box under &amp;ldquo;Allow&amp;rdquo; for &amp;ldquo;Full control.&amp;rdquo; Do the same thing for IIS_IUSRS for good measure. This will make sure that phpMyAdmin can do whatever it wants to this folder. Press OK to save the security settings, and then OK again to close the Properties dialog box.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/41.jpg&quot; height=&quot;436&quot; width=&quot;712&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Now you have to go back to your php.ini file and make sure the MySQL extensions are activated. Open php.ini in notepad (it should be in C:phpphp.ini) and find the lines &amp;ldquo;;extension=php_mbstring.dll,&amp;rdquo; &amp;ldquo;;extension=php_mysql.dll&amp;rdquo; and &amp;ldquo;;extension=php_mysqli.dll.&amp;rdquo; Remove the semicolons from those lines (if there are any). Note that there are &lt;strong&gt;three extensions&lt;/strong&gt; that you&#039;re enabling, here.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/42.jpg&quot; height=&quot;346&quot; width=&quot;711&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Now find the setting for extension_dir, and remove the semicolon from the line that says &amp;ldquo;extension_dir = &amp;lsquo;ext&amp;rsquo;&amp;rdquo; (or whatever it says under &amp;ldquo;On Windows&amp;rdquo;). Now save and close the file.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/33.jpg&quot; height=&quot;616&quot; width=&quot;815&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;You will now probably need to recycle your Application Pool for any changes to the php.ini file to go through. In the IIS Manager (type &amp;ldquo;inetmgr&amp;rdquo; into the Run dialog), select &amp;ldquo;Application Pools&amp;rdquo; under &amp;ldquo;Connections,&amp;rdquo; and then right click on &amp;ldquo;DefaultAppPool&amp;rdquo; and say &amp;ldquo;Recycle.&amp;rdquo; Now PHP should be able to connect to your MySQL database.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/44.jpg&quot; height=&quot;618&quot; width=&quot;694&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Now you can point your browser to &amp;ldquo;localhost/phpMyAdmin&amp;rdquo; to get to the phpMyAdmin login. You&amp;rsquo;re telling your browser to open the &amp;ldquo;phpMyAdmin&amp;rdquo; folder inside the Default Web Site, and it then calls for &amp;ldquo;index.php&amp;rdquo; by default. This is a new website you installed inside your Internet. You&amp;rsquo;re really just going to town, making websites all over the place, now.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/45.jpg&quot; height=&quot;431&quot; width=&quot;694&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;You might have tried to log in to phpMyAdmin with the username &amp;ldquo;root&amp;rdquo; and the password you specified when you installed MySQL. You showed good initiative, that&amp;rsquo;s for sure, but we&amp;rsquo;re not quite ready to go to there just yet. We have to actually start your MySQL server, and tell phpMyAdmin how to connect to it.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/52.jpg&quot; height=&quot;522&quot; width=&quot;671&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;First you have to find your MySQL server bin directory. For me it&amp;rsquo;s C:/Program Files/MySQL/MySQL Server 5.5/bin. Just go to there, and open the file mysqld.exe. It should pop up a window which will then disappear. That&amp;rsquo;s it!&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/53.jpg&quot; height=&quot;503&quot; width=&quot;508&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;You can check to see if the server is running in Task Manager (right click on the taskbar and select &amp;ldquo;Start Task Manager.&amp;rdquo; If you can find &amp;ldquo;mysqld.exe&amp;rdquo; inside the Processes tab, your MySQL server is running! You can select it and say &amp;ldquo;End Process&amp;rdquo; to shut it down when you don&amp;rsquo;t need it. That will free up a bit of your precious memories if you need more memories.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/49.jpg&quot; height=&quot;751&quot; width=&quot;844&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Go to &amp;ldquo;localhost/phpMyAdmin/setup&amp;rdquo; in your browser to set up phpMyAdmin. It&amp;rsquo;s this kind of super complicated stuff that I had to go to College to learn. You&amp;rsquo;ll see at this point that there are no configured servers. You can tell that because it says &amp;ldquo;There are no configured servers&amp;rdquo; right there. We better configure ourselves a server.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/50.jpg&quot; height=&quot;639&quot; width=&quot;920&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Press &amp;ldquo;new server.&amp;rdquo; Leave everything as it is except for one setting. Under &amp;ldquo;Server configuration&amp;rdquo; check &amp;ldquo;Allow logins without a password.&amp;rdquo; Press &amp;ldquo;save.&amp;rdquo; You&amp;rsquo;ll see a message that Allow logins without a password causes security risks, but you don&amp;rsquo;t have to worry about that. Only you will have access to this, so you don&amp;rsquo;t have to worry so much about security for now. Hit the &amp;ldquo;Save&amp;rdquo; button at the bottom of the Overview page.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/51.jpg&quot; height=&quot;642&quot; width=&quot;664&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Now there should be a config.inc.php file inside that config folder. Move it out to the phpMyAdmin folder, and then delete the config folder. It is no longer necessary.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/54.jpg&quot; height=&quot;678&quot; width=&quot;1069&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Now the time has come to login to phpMyAdmin. Go back to localhost/phpMyAdmin and log in with the username &amp;ldquo;root&amp;rdquo; and no password. If everything went as it was supposed to, you should now be logged in.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;We&amp;rsquo;re now officially ready to host almost any kind of website you can create. We have PHP support and a fully armed and operational MySQL server. Next time we&amp;rsquo;ll get started setting up your actual website. This is where it gets fun!&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Are you ready to put a website together, now? I bet you&amp;rsquo;re thinking, &lt;em&gt;&amp;ldquo;hey, this hasn&amp;rsquo;t been terribly easy and all we&amp;rsquo;ve done is set up some useless web server that we can&amp;rsquo;t even really use. I don&amp;rsquo;t really know how to PHP or anything. How do you expect me to make a whole website?&amp;rdquo;&lt;/em&gt; The fact is, I don&amp;rsquo;t. It&amp;rsquo;s time to come clean. We&amp;rsquo;re going to cheat.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h5&gt;Part 4: Stop the Wordpresses&lt;/h5&gt;

&lt;p&gt;You&amp;rsquo;ve probably heard of wordpress. It&amp;rsquo;s a pretty big thing on the Internet, and there&amp;rsquo;s a pretty simple reason why. It&amp;rsquo;s powerful, it&amp;rsquo;s easy to customize, it&amp;rsquo;s vastly extendable, and it&amp;rsquo;s free. Unless you have some pretty specific requirements, you have a budget in the hundreds of thousands of dollars, or you&amp;rsquo;re an obsessive idiot like me, there really isn&amp;rsquo;t much reason to make a website without just using Wordpress.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Wordpress isn&amp;rsquo;t just for blogs, either. By building plugins and other modifications you could get it to do absolutely anything you can think of. Well, maybe &lt;em&gt;you&lt;/em&gt; can&amp;rsquo;t (no offense), but you can probably find some plugins and things that other people have made that will do whatever you want. That&amp;rsquo;s Wordpress&amp;rsquo;s true power: it has an incredibly active development community. Also, if you use Wordpress you&amp;rsquo;ll be able to use Google Adsense ads and potentially make money from it, which is more than I can say &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/post/376/Ads_on_DenyConformitycom&quot;&gt;about&lt;/a&gt; DenyConformity.com.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Anyway, we&amp;rsquo;ll get to the plugins and things down the road. For now, we have to get your itsy-bitsy web server set up to host a Wordpress site. Okay, so you can just go to wordpress.com and set up your own blog there, where you can do plenty of stuff for absolutely free. You can even point a domain name to it and save yourself a lot of money and effort by not dealing with a web host. However, hosting a Wordpress site on your own web space puts all of the power in your hands, and you&amp;rsquo;ll be able to do quite a bit more stuff with your site than if you just went with Wordpress hosting. Also, you&amp;rsquo;ll feel much cooler because you have your own website, which is actually pretty cool.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/55.jpg&quot; height=&quot;705&quot; width=&quot;1013&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;First off, you&amp;rsquo;ll need to head to &lt;a href=&quot;http://wordpress.org/download/&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;wordpress.org/download/&lt;/a&gt; and click on the &amp;ldquo;Download WordPress&amp;rdquo; button. It&amp;rsquo;s not huge, so it won&amp;rsquo;t take very long, but it&amp;rsquo;s good to get it downloading so it will be ready for us.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/58.jpg&quot; height=&quot;429&quot; width=&quot;589&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Now first you have to create a new folder somewhere. This will be the folder in which your website will live. Put it somewhere easy to get to, because you&amp;rsquo;ll be hanging out there a lot. I created my own Windows Library for web stuff, because I do a lot of it, but you don&amp;rsquo;t have to go that far. Look, I&amp;rsquo;m not going to pry into your personal organization of your folders, so just make a folder somewhere. Also, remember where you put it.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/59.jpg&quot; height=&quot;526&quot; width=&quot;586&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Right click your new folder and select &amp;ldquo;Properties.&amp;rdquo; Now find the &amp;ldquo;Security&amp;rdquo; tab. You have to give IIS access to read your folder so that you can open it as a website. By default IIS has access to nothing (except the default Web Site folder) on your computer - it&amp;rsquo;s more secure this way.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/60.jpg&quot; height=&quot;530&quot; width=&quot;597&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Click &amp;ldquo;Edit&amp;rdquo; and then &amp;ldquo;Add...&amp;rdquo; and then type &amp;ldquo;IIS_IUSRS&amp;rdquo; into the box. Hit &amp;ldquo;Check Names&amp;rdquo; and it should turn into what you see above (it&amp;rsquo;s your computer name slash IIS_IUSRS). Hit &amp;ldquo;OK&amp;rdquo; and then do the same thing for &amp;ldquo;Users.&amp;rdquo; Now the folder should have the following under &amp;ldquo;Group or user names&amp;rdquo; (there could be more, but it needs at least these): &amp;ldquo;SYSTEM,&amp;rdquo; &amp;ldquo;*Your Username*,&amp;rdquo; &amp;ldquo;Administrators,&amp;rdquo; &amp;ldquo;Users,&amp;rdquo; and &amp;ldquo;IIS_IUSRS.&amp;rdquo; Your folder is set up!&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/56.jpg&quot; height=&quot;622&quot; width=&quot;991&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Now we&amp;rsquo;ll head back to our old friend, the IIS Manager (remember: &amp;ldquo;inetmgr&amp;rdquo;). We could install Wordpress into our &amp;ldquo;Default Web Site&amp;rdquo; and leave it at that, but it&amp;rsquo;s usually best to just create a new website and work with a clean slate. Don&amp;rsquo;t worry about all that work you did to set up PHP. We did that at the server level, so those are all master settings that will be in effect on every website you create.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/57.jpg&quot; height=&quot;628&quot; width=&quot;991&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Open your server, and then select &amp;ldquo;Sites&amp;rdquo; in the Connections area. Here you should see the only website you have running, the Default Web Site. Click &amp;ldquo;Add Web Site...&amp;rdquo; to add a new website, believe it or not.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;You might be wondering how you can have two websites running on one computer. That&amp;rsquo;s pretty astute of you, sport. You only have one address to go to, &amp;ldquo;localhost,&amp;rdquo; so how can we get two websites at once? The answer is by using different ports. Use a port, sport! An Internet is like a bit loading dock, like they have on the big, fat butt of a Wal-Mart (not the big, fat butts of the people shopping at Walmart - those only have one port). You have to back your Internet-truck full of beeps and boops up to a specific door on your computer&amp;rsquo;s loading dock for it to accept you. There are thousands of possible ports, and different programs use different ones. Most beeps and boops for the Wild World of Web - including websites and stuff like that - travel through port 80. Just like how browsers access &amp;ldquo;index.php&amp;rdquo; by default when you don&amp;rsquo;t specify a file, they will access port 80 by default if you don&amp;rsquo;t specify otherwise (specify a specific port with a colon. No, we aren&#039;t talking about fat butts again - I mean &amp;ldquo;localhost:80&amp;rdquo;). All we have to do is set up a new website on port 81, and then we&amp;rsquo;ll be able to call it up by opening port 81 on localhost (which is done by going to &amp;ldquo;localhost:81&amp;rdquo;). Let&amp;rsquo;s do that, shall we?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/61.jpg&quot; height=&quot;535&quot; width=&quot;550&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;So &amp;ldquo;Add Web Site...&amp;rdquo; and then fill out the form. For the name, just put whatever. Hit the &amp;ldquo;Select...&amp;rdquo; button and pick &amp;ldquo;DefaultAppPool&amp;rdquo; from the list (then hit OK). The Physical path needs to be that folder you just created. I told you to remember where you put it. Now, under &amp;ldquo;Port&amp;rdquo; change it to 81. Now this new site will only be accessible from port 81, because the Default Web Site is using port 80. Make sure &amp;ldquo;Start Web site immediately&amp;rdquo; is checked, and hit &amp;ldquo;OK.&amp;rdquo; &lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/62.jpg&quot; height=&quot;528&quot; width=&quot;813&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;If you try to access the site now (by going to &amp;ldquo;localhost:81&amp;rdquo;), you&amp;rsquo;ll see something like this. This is because there&amp;rsquo;s nothing in that folder you created. When there is no default file (no index.php or index.html), the server tries to just send a list of what is in the directory. However, by default it&amp;rsquo;s forbidden from doing that for security reasons, so it has a bit of a crisis. This particular crisis is called an Error 403.14.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/63.jpg&quot; height=&quot;508&quot; width=&quot;507&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;There&amp;rsquo;s still more to do before you can put some files there, though, so your new web site will just have to keep having a crisis. You&amp;rsquo;ll have to start up your MySQL server, if it isn&amp;rsquo;t running. Check your Task Manager for &amp;ldquo;mysqld.exe&amp;rdquo; and if it isn&amp;rsquo;t there, go to C:/Program Files/MySQL/MySQL Server 5.X/bin and run &amp;ldquo;mysqld.exe.&amp;rdquo; You could have your MySQL server run every time Windows starts up by placing a shortcut to mysqld.exe in your Startup folder (which is in &amp;ldquo;All Programs&amp;rdquo; in the Start Menu), but unless you plan on playing around with your MySQL server a lot, you don&amp;rsquo;t need to tie up your memories all the time.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/64.jpg&quot; height=&quot;572&quot; width=&quot;859&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Log into phpMyAdmin again (&lt;a href=&quot;http://localhost/phpMyAdmin&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;localhost/phpMyAdmin&lt;/a&gt;). We need to create two things for Wordpress. First we&amp;rsquo;ll create a new user that Wordpress can use, and then we&amp;rsquo;ll create a new Database just for your new website. PhpMyAdmin makes this really super easy.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/65.jpg&quot; height=&quot;742&quot; width=&quot;1070&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Go to the Users tab and hit &amp;ldquo;Add user.&amp;rdquo; You can name it anything, but &amp;ldquo;wordpress&amp;rdquo; works fine. Select &amp;ldquo;Local&amp;rdquo; from the dropdown box next to &amp;ldquo;Host.&amp;rdquo; The password should actually be something pretty secure this time, because you&amp;rsquo;re going to copy this user to your host when you&amp;rsquo;re ready. Hit the &amp;ldquo;Generate&amp;rdquo; button to get a really strong password, but for Pete&amp;rsquo;s sake write it down so you don&amp;rsquo;t lose it. Next, and this is important, select the option &amp;ldquo;Create database with same name and grant all privileges&amp;rdquo; before you hit &amp;ldquo;Add user.&amp;rdquo; Now you should have a new database on the left, called whatever you called your new user. It&amp;rsquo;s finally time to website!&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/66.jpg&quot; height=&quot;657&quot; width=&quot;963&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Open up the Wordpress zip file you downloaded, and go into the Wordpress folder inside it. Copy everything you find there into your new website folder. You will now have three folders and a bunch of files right there in the root directory of your new website.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/67.jpg&quot; height=&quot;579&quot; width=&quot;844&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Now you can point your browser to &lt;a href=&quot;http://localhost:81/wp-admin/install.php&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;localhost:81/wp-admin/install.php&lt;/a&gt;. It may not look like much, but you&amp;rsquo;re now on your way to your very own website! Press the button to continue the setup process, and then press the button on the next page to continue even harder.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/68.jpg&quot; height=&quot;733&quot; width=&quot;847&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Fill out the form. The database name and username should be the same, and they&amp;rsquo;ll be whatever you named your MySQL user from a few steps ago. Enter that password you wrote down (you did write that down, right?) where it says &amp;ldquo;Password.&amp;rdquo; The last two settings are ok with their default values.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/69.jpg&quot; height=&quot;737&quot; width=&quot;897&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;If you did it correctly, you&amp;rsquo;ll get this screen. Don&amp;rsquo;t let the &amp;ldquo;sorry&amp;rdquo; disappoint you, this is totally normal. Just select everything in that big text box (with all the technical beeps and boops in it), and Ctrl+C it to your clipboard.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/70.jpg&quot; height=&quot;775&quot; width=&quot;1033&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;In your website folder, create a new text file. Name it &amp;ldquo;wp-config.php&amp;rdquo; (remember to be sure it isn&amp;rsquo;t &amp;ldquo;wp-config.php.txt&amp;rdquo;) and open it up in Notepad.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/71.jpg&quot; height=&quot;771&quot; width=&quot;1023&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Now Ctrl+V the text from that text area into Notepad (or just copy and paste the text however you feel most comfortable doing that). Save and close the file. Now, in your browser, you can press &amp;ldquo;Run the install&amp;rdquo; to run the Wordpress install.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/72.jpg&quot; height=&quot;733&quot; width=&quot;896&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Fill out the details on the next page with your information. You&amp;rsquo;re starting to get into actual stuff that will show up on your website, so I can&amp;rsquo;t really tell you what to put here. I&amp;rsquo;m calling my site &amp;ldquo;Alyson Thiel&amp;rdquo; because this whole tutorial is just a guise so I can finally get around to making the website that Alyson keeps asking me to make for her. Make sure your password kung-fu is strong here, because this will eventually (theoretically) be online where all your enemies will be trying to get into your account. Also, uncheck the Privacy option for now, because it&amp;rsquo;s irrelevant as long as the site is living on your computer. When you&amp;rsquo;re ready, hit the &amp;ldquo;Install Wordpress&amp;rdquo; button and you&amp;rsquo;ll be done.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/73.jpg&quot; height=&quot;733&quot; width=&quot;891&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Log in to your Wordpress with the username and password you entered in the last step, and you&amp;rsquo;ll get to your new website&amp;rsquo;s Dashboard. This thing is going to be your new best friend (sorry IIS Manager), so get used to it. You can click on the page title in the upper left corner (or just go to &lt;a href=&quot;http://localhost:81&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;localhost:81&lt;/a&gt;) to see your new website in all its default Wordpress glory.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/74.jpg&quot; height=&quot;594&quot; width=&quot;807&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Your picture may vary, but your site will look just like this, because this is the default Wordpress theme.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So there you go, you now have your very own Wordpress-based website running on your computer. Feel free to play around and see how it all works. The beauty is that since you&amp;rsquo;re running on your own computer you can do whatever you want to explore, and it will be really easy to fix if you break everything.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;If you mess something up and you want to start over, head to the Users section of phpMyAdmin, check the box next to the wordpress user, check the &amp;ldquo;Drop the databases that have the same names as the users&amp;rdquo; option, and hit the &amp;ldquo;Go&amp;rdquo; button underneath &amp;ldquo;Remove elected users.&amp;rdquo; Now you can go back to the step where we created a new user and run the Wordpress installation again. It will be like those mistakes never happened!&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Next time I&amp;rsquo;ll show you all around your new Wordpress site, and we&amp;rsquo;ll get it configured just for you, with a few pages, blog posts, and plugins so you can get exactly the website that you want. Then once it&amp;rsquo;s all configured, all we have to do is deploy the site to your web space. What you do after that is up to you. You had better not be posting your own tutorial about how to website, though, because that&amp;rsquo;s not cool, man. That&amp;rsquo;s not cool at all.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This is where things get a bit tricky - for me, not you. Now that you have a fully functional website running on your computer, how you set it up is entirely up to you. What kind of website do you want? Basically there are two types of websites that we&amp;rsquo;re dealing with here. You could be making a blog, where you&amp;rsquo;ll post some sort of regular content, or you could be making an info-site, where you&amp;rsquo;ll simply describe a product, company, or yourself. Sure there are plenty of other websites, like e-commerce, social networking, content sharing, or web apps. However, those are all way more complicated affairs that you can&amp;rsquo;t really accomplish with a simple Wordpress site, so we&amp;rsquo;ll stick with what is ultimately 75% of websites out there.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;See my ongoing &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/post/389/DenyConformitycom_Redesign_Journal_part_4&quot;&gt;design journals&lt;/a&gt; for more of my thoughts about what a website is.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The problem is that I can&amp;rsquo;t just tell you to &amp;ldquo;go here&amp;rdquo; and &amp;ldquo;do this&amp;rdquo; this time around because it might not apply to everybody out there. Here&amp;rsquo;s what I&amp;rsquo;ll do, though. I&amp;rsquo;m going to build out a complete website, using the Wordpress platform we set up in the last few tutorials. You can follow along with me if you want, just to get a feel for how everything works, or you can pick and choose what you want to use for your site. I&amp;rsquo;ll try to cover as many Wordpress things as I can get to, so we can really get our hands dirty and built exactly the website Gotham needs, as well as the one Gotham wants! First, though, it&amp;rsquo;s best to get a game plan together.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h5&gt;Part 5: Get a Game Plan Together&lt;/h5&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Just for the sake of this tutorial, I&amp;rsquo;ll come up with a random website idea and go through the process of getting it set up. Let&amp;rsquo;s make a website for . . . let&amp;rsquo;s see . . . oh, how about my girlfriend Alyson? Let&amp;rsquo;s pretend that she&amp;rsquo;s been asking me to make her a website for like a year and I&amp;rsquo;m just getting around to it. I mean, that&amp;rsquo;s just a bit of background to give the site I&amp;rsquo;m making some purpose.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Anyway, before we get started, we need to come up with a list of requirements for the new site. Technically we should have done this before we set up IIS or Wordpress, but whatever. The point is just to have a clear idea of what we need Wordpress to do for us. Sit down with your client (in this case it&amp;rsquo;s probably you) and get a list of what they want. Let&amp;rsquo;s just say that Alyson told me what she wanted in a website like a year ago and I made a mental note of it to make it happen some day. It&amp;rsquo;s good to have a sort of mission statement kind of thing so your website has a real purpose. Here&amp;rsquo;s what I&amp;rsquo;m working with:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Alyson Thiel is an independent artist who wants to promote her work and have a platform for sharing ideas and pieces with other artists.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It&amp;rsquo;s that easy. It&amp;rsquo;s not a thesis or anything. Just be clear about generally what kind of content you&amp;rsquo;re making, and whether it&amp;rsquo;s a more static info-site or a regular blog type affair. Technically Alyson just wants an info-site and a portfolio for posting all of her arts, but I&amp;rsquo;ll throw a blog in there too for the sake of tutorialization. Next you should get a list of a few things the site needs to get done. This includes any pages you want to have and any specific functions or visual things you want to see. As far as I&amp;rsquo;ve been able to remember after like a year of putting off thinking about it - er, &lt;em&gt;for the sake of this tutorial, I mean&lt;/em&gt; - this is what I know:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
&lt;li&gt;She wants it to look pretty. This is actually pretty average for what you&amp;rsquo;ll hear from a client as far as art direction goes.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;She wants a home page with a fancy cycling banner that shows off her work.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;She wants a biography page with a - well - &lt;em&gt;biography&lt;/em&gt; on it, I guess.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;She wants a CV page to post her CV on&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;She wants a &amp;ldquo;work&amp;rdquo; page which has image galleries for her art, split into different categories or whatever&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;I&amp;rsquo;ll include a &amp;ldquo;blog&amp;rdquo; page which will be basically a blog, including comments and all that.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Another step you want to take is to get the actual content you want to show on each page. I&amp;rsquo;ll let Alyson write her own biography and CV, and we&amp;rsquo;re working on getting digital versions of her arts, but I can just use placeholder stuff for now.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Okay, so you have all that stuff together? You have a clear concept and you&amp;rsquo;re ready to put it together? Then let&amp;rsquo;s start tackling these things.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h5&gt;Part 5 A: Set that Thang Up&lt;/h5&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I know I said you can just follow along if you want to and whatever, but you should stick with me through this part, because this is universally important stuff. Actually, the next part is pretty important, too. On second thought, forget I ever said you could go on your own. What was I thinking?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/75.jpg&quot; height=&quot;810&quot; width=&quot;1017&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;When you loginto your dashboard, you probably see this &amp;ldquo;Welcome to your blah whatever&amp;rdquo; message. You can ignore that, really. I&amp;rsquo;ll take you through each page in the &amp;ldquo;Settings&amp;rdquo; section, and explain what they do.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/77.jpg&quot; height=&quot;991&quot; width=&quot;920&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;There are a lot of options in the General Settings section. If you don&amp;rsquo;t need a tagline (like me), you can make it blank. Leave the URLs as they are for now, but know that you&amp;rsquo;ll have to change these when you deploy the site. Changing the &amp;ldquo;New User Default Role&amp;rdquo; will change what non-you people will be able to do when they register with your site, so it should probably be left as &amp;ldquo;Subscriber&amp;rdquo; unless you want people to be able to contribute stuff (note that is for posts, not comments - people will still be able to post comments). Pick your timezone carefully, and then set the Date and Time formatting as you like.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/103.jpg&quot; height=&quot;617&quot; width=&quot;957&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;In Writing, you can change some settings for your posts. You can also add a bookmarklet and set up &amp;ldquo;Post via e-mail.&amp;rdquo; Don&amp;rsquo;t worry about the bookmarklet or the email thing for now, because those aren&amp;rsquo;t really usable until you deploy the site to a real web space.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/104.jpg&quot; height=&quot;607&quot; width=&quot;951&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The Reading page lets you control some settings for your blog and whatnot. You can also tell Wordpress to have a static front page instead of a blog. We&amp;rsquo;ll return here when we&amp;rsquo;re messing with pages, in the next part of this tutorial.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/78.jpg&quot; height=&quot;750&quot; width=&quot;918&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The Discussion Settings can get pretty complicated. For the most part the default settings are fine, but if you want any specific options for comments on your posts, you can probably find those options here. By default any commenters have to submit their name and email address, and their comments have to be approved by an admin (you) before they can be seen. This will help stop idiots and spam, but it can be kind of hassle for both you and your commenters. I&amp;rsquo;ll show you how to install a CAPTCHA plugin later (it&amp;rsquo;s pretty simple), so you might be able to turn all that off. One setting I&amp;rsquo;m changing is that I&amp;rsquo;m turning off &amp;ldquo;Avatar Display&amp;rdquo; down at the bottom of this page. I don&amp;rsquo;t see any need to show little icons (which are usually just blank) for every comment.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/105.jpg&quot; height=&quot;601&quot; width=&quot;946&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;In Media you can control settings for images in posts. These defaults are all perfectly fine, and you should only mess with this if you have specific problems with images at some point.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/76.jpg&quot; height=&quot;595&quot; width=&quot;925&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The privacy setting should still be set to &amp;ldquo;Ask search engines not to index this site&amp;rdquo; which is how you want it while it&amp;rsquo;s still in the development environment. Still, it&amp;rsquo;s good to know where this setting lives, so you can turn it on when you&amp;rsquo;ve deployed the site.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/101.jpg&quot; height=&quot;688&quot; width=&quot;904&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;In the Permalinks section, you can control how the URLs for your pages and posts will look. It&amp;rsquo;s a good idea to switch to something besides the default, because if you include the date and post name in the URL it will be much better for search engines and whatnot. I like using &amp;ldquo;Day and name.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/79.jpg&quot; height=&quot;751&quot; width=&quot;920&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;You should also take a look at the &amp;ldquo;Users&amp;rdquo; section of the Dashboard. In &amp;ldquo;Your Profile&amp;rdquo; you can fill out your personal information, which will be attached to each post you make on the site. Personally I don&amp;rsquo;t care about this for the admin account. I will create a separate account for Alyson so she can post things to the site, and she can adjust the personal info for herself. You can go ahead and make the admin you and then you can just make posts right from the admin account, or you can create a new account (&amp;ldquo;Users&amp;rdquo; &amp;gt; &amp;ldquo;Add New&amp;rdquo;) for yourself and make posts with that. It&amp;rsquo;s up to you. Just know that any posts you make are tied to the account you were logged in with when you made the post.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/80.jpg&quot; height=&quot;596&quot; width=&quot;924&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Another thing I like to do is just get rid of all the &amp;ldquo;Sample&amp;rdquo; garbage that Wordpress has when you first set it up. Go to the &amp;ldquo;Pages&amp;rdquo; section (click &amp;ldquo;Pages&amp;rdquo; in the dashboard menu), mouse over the &amp;ldquo;Sample Page&amp;rdquo; page and select &amp;ldquo;Trash.&amp;rdquo; I&amp;rsquo;ll show you how to make a new page later, so don&amp;rsquo;t worry about losing anything.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/81.jpg&quot; height=&quot;587&quot; width=&quot;917&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Do the same thing with the &amp;ldquo;Posts&amp;rdquo; section, removing the &amp;ldquo;Hello World!&amp;rdquo; post from the list. This will also remove any comments that are on the post. One thing about Wordpress is that these Sample items aren&amp;rsquo;t actually gone, they&amp;rsquo;re just in the trash, so you could get them back if you wanted. It&amp;rsquo;s good to know in the future if you ever accidentally delete something you need.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/96.jpg&quot; height=&quot;561&quot; width=&quot;922&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;We also need to set up a couple more folders so we&amp;rsquo;ll be able to upload images to our Wordpress blog. &lt;strong&gt;This is a really important step that I totally meant to wait until now to tell you.&lt;/strong&gt; First go to the directory where you installed Wordpress and find the folder called &amp;ldquo;wp-content.&amp;rdquo; Then go to the root of your hard drive (C:) and create a folder called &amp;ldquo;tmp.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/97.jpg&quot; height=&quot;552&quot; width=&quot;435&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Now do this for each of those folders: right click the folder, select &amp;ldquo;Properties&amp;rdquo; and go to the &amp;ldquo;Security&amp;rdquo; tab. Press &amp;ldquo;Edit&amp;rdquo; and select &amp;ldquo;Users.&amp;rdquo; Check the box under &amp;ldquo;Allow&amp;rdquo; for &amp;ldquo;Full Control.&amp;rdquo; All the checkboxes should be checked now for &amp;ldquo;Users&amp;rdquo; on both the &amp;ldquo;wp-content&amp;rdquo; and the &amp;ldquo;tmp&amp;rdquo; folders. This will ensure that Wordpress can write files to those locations.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Now we have a clean slate that we can move forward with. Let&amp;rsquo;s make it look nice, though, shall we? Now we&#039;ll take a trip through the &amp;ldquo;Appearance&amp;rdquo; section of the Dashboard.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Part 5 B: Theme Heat&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/82.jpg&quot; height=&quot;588&quot; width=&quot;918&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The first page of the Appearance section will show you what themes you have available. The default Wordpress theme is called Twenty Eleven, and it&amp;rsquo;s okay, but we want something a little less default. You might notice you have another theme installed, called Twenty Ten (this is true as I write this, but in the future they&amp;rsquo;ll probably change the default themes at some point). Twenty ten is just like Twenty Eleven, but it&amp;rsquo;s one less.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/83.jpg&quot; height=&quot;589&quot; width=&quot;918&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Wordpress has a built-in system for installing new themes, which is in the &amp;ldquo;Install Themes&amp;rdquo; tab of the Themes page of the Appearance section of the Dashboard. It&amp;rsquo;s a pain to install themes that way, actually, so you should go to &lt;a href=&quot;http://wordpress.org/extend/themes/&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;wordpress.org/extend/themes/&lt;/a&gt; to browse them there. As I write this, there are 1,516 different free themes for Wordpress. That&amp;rsquo;s cool because there are plenty of options, but it&amp;rsquo;s difficult because that can be intimidating (plus let&#039;s be honest, a lot of them are garbage). Luckily, they have a handy Tag Filter you can use to bring the results down to a more manageable size. You can also just browse the latest submitted themes.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/84.jpg&quot; height=&quot;796&quot; width=&quot;1009&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;I want something that&amp;rsquo;s mainly white, so I searched for &amp;ldquo;white&amp;rdquo; and &amp;ldquo;light.&amp;rdquo; I also added &amp;ldquo;Flexible Width&amp;rdquo; (which I recommend that you do, too) and &amp;ldquo;Custom Background&amp;rdquo; to the options. That narrowed the selection down to 20 options. If you know you want a two- or three-column layout, or you know you want a specific feature, you can limit it further. I want to find something that&amp;rsquo;s pretty open so I can still use a lot of Wordpress features. Also, as per the client requirements, it has to be &lt;em&gt;pretty&lt;/em&gt;. That actually rules out quite a few themes.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/86.jpg&quot; height=&quot;794&quot; width=&quot;1012&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Click on a thumbnail to see a preview of the theme in action (you can even click on links and stuff in the preview). I like this theme called &amp;ldquo;Platform.&amp;rdquo; It&amp;rsquo;s very clean, and very simple. Most themes will work just the same, so you should be able to pick any theme you want and be able to do the same sorts of things with it.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/87.jpg&quot; height=&quot;796&quot; width=&quot;1012&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Click on the name of a theme you like, and then hit the &amp;ldquo;Download&amp;rdquo; button to get a zip file with your new theme in it.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/88.jpg&quot; height=&quot;432&quot; width=&quot;791&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Inside the zip file should be a folder called whatever your new theme is called. Just copy that folder to [whatever directory Wordpress is in]/wp-content/themes/ That&amp;rsquo;s all you have to do to install a new theme! That&amp;rsquo;s one of the reasons it&amp;rsquo;s cool to set Wordpress up on your computer first, because installing themes and plugins is super easy.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/89.jpg&quot; height=&quot;795&quot; width=&quot;1021&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Anyway, now if you go back to your Themes page, you should see your new theme under &amp;ldquo;Available Themes.&amp;rdquo; Click the little &amp;ldquo;Activate&amp;rdquo; link underneath it to, well, activate it.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/90.jpg&quot; height=&quot;628&quot; width=&quot;1032&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Uh oh. I activated that &amp;ldquo;Platform&amp;rdquo; theme, and was greeted with a ton of errors. The site is covered with them too. What did I touch?&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I didn&amp;rsquo;t plan on breaking Wordpress in this tutorial, but I&amp;rsquo;m actually glad I did. A similar thing might very well happen to you at some point, and the best thing to keep in mind is to not panic. It&amp;rsquo;s probably not your fault if the site gets broken, especially if you just installed a new theme or plugin. Chances are it was that theme or plugin what done it. The fact is that most of the themes and plugins for Wordpress aren&amp;rsquo;t extremely well made. For example, the person who made this &amp;ldquo;Platform&amp;rdquo; theme seems to have gotten pretty lazy with how they&amp;rsquo;re using classes in some of their files - and they haven&amp;rsquo;t tested the theme with either PHP 5 or with the strict error reporting settings we&amp;rsquo;re using - so it makes PHP have a bit of a crisis. If you see this sort of thing with the theme you picked, you could try to &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RfiQYRn7fBg&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;debug&lt;/a&gt; the code and figure out what&amp;rsquo;s wrong with it, but it&amp;rsquo;s probably best to just find a new theme to try. Welcome to the blunderful world of open source software.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;My site wasn&amp;rsquo;t totally broken by this new theme, but yours very well could be by a theme you tried to install, so here&amp;rsquo;s what you do if errors are making it so you can&amp;rsquo;t get into the Dashboard at all.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/91.jpg&quot; height=&quot;328&quot; width=&quot;526&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Head back to your themes folder ([whatever]/wp-content/themes) and find the folder for the theme that ruined everything. Rename (or just delete) it.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/92.jpg&quot; height=&quot;87&quot; width=&quot;349&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Now you should be able to get into the Themes page, and you&amp;rsquo;ll see this message. It can&amp;rsquo;t find the theme files, because you renamed the folder they&amp;rsquo;re in, so it just reverts to good old Twenty Eleven.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/93.jpg&quot; height=&quot;807&quot; width=&quot;1079&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Anyway, this Lugada theme looks okay, too. Let&amp;rsquo;s give it a shot. Same as before, I&amp;rsquo;ll download it and stick it in my Themes folder.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/94.jpg&quot; height=&quot;319&quot; width=&quot;867&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Success! Okay, so it&amp;rsquo;s installed and running. Now we can customize it. Most themes allow some level of customization, so you can tweak images or colors to your liking. Actually, if you know CSS (the language designers use to style websites) you can tweak absolutely every aspect of a theme, because themes are almost entirely CSS.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/95.jpg&quot; height=&quot;774&quot; width=&quot;1079&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Since this is a pretty minimal theme, there isn&amp;rsquo;t much to customize. I can put in a Twitter ID or Facebook URL (not super useful), and I can add up to 5 images for a sliding banner thingie. I doubt that&amp;rsquo;s going to suffice for what Alyson wants, but I&amp;rsquo;ll take a look later when I upload some images.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/98.jpg&quot; height=&quot;599&quot; width=&quot;1046&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Most themes will let you upload an image for the site header. Usually they will specify what size the header should be. In this case, it&amp;rsquo;s 300 x 70 pixels.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/99.jpg&quot; height=&quot;386&quot; width=&quot;853&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Alyson wanted a hand-written header, so I had her write her name out and then I scanned that into the computer. I had to crop it down to be the right size in Photoshop. You&amp;rsquo;re on your own for making a logo. This is a website tutorial, not a logo tutorial.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/100.jpg&quot; height=&quot;774&quot; width=&quot;1082&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;In the Editor (Appearance - Editor) you can actually manipulate the stylesheets for the theme. If you don&amp;rsquo;t know anything about CSS, you probably don&amp;rsquo;t want to dig around this too much. Luckily, I know a lot about CSS, so I went in and tweaked some of the colors to match what Alyson wanted. I&amp;rsquo;ll have to cover some basic CSS in an addendum or something, because it&amp;rsquo;s just too much for this little Tutorial to bear.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/102.jpg&quot; height=&quot;765&quot; width=&quot;1156&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Most themes allow customizable widgets, another powerful Wordpress tool. In the Widgets page you can drag and drop what widgets you want into the various sections that your theme provides. The theme I&amp;rsquo;m using has a &amp;ldquo;Main Sidebar&amp;rdquo; section as well as two little spots in the footer. Most of the widgets are self-explanatory. Play around with these and find what works best for what you&amp;rsquo;re looking to accomplish with your site.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/106.jpg&quot; height=&quot;688&quot; width=&quot;904&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Now your site should have a bit more character to it. It&amp;rsquo;s a bit barren, sure, but it should be starting to look cool.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Now we&amp;rsquo;re really getting a site together. You can spend a lot of time tweaking the theme and other settings, that&amp;rsquo;s for sure. This is where it&amp;rsquo;s handy to have it running right there on your own little Internet, because it will go super fast and you can mess with all of the files yourself.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Next we&amp;rsquo;ll look at creating pages and blog posts, and we&amp;rsquo;ll do some more serious hands-on manipulation of the page layout. It&amp;rsquo;s a time consuming process, and there are quite a few steps involved, but nobody said this was going to be easy. Well, okay, so I might have said that, but I didn&amp;rsquo;t say it would be quick, did I? Well, we&amp;rsquo;re almost at the finish line, so hang in there.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A website isn&amp;rsquo;t really worth much without any content on it (unless you&amp;rsquo;re like a Pinterest and you have millions of people all over to make your content for you). Right now, our little website may look kind of neat, but it&amp;rsquo;s pretty much blank. Today we&amp;rsquo;re going to do something about that. We&amp;rsquo;ll create some new pages, make some blog posts, and upload some images.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h5&gt;Part 5 C: Paging Dr. Wordpress&lt;/h5&gt;

&lt;p&gt;On the Internet, content is displayed on things called &amp;ldquo;web pages.&amp;rdquo; Currently our little website has one page - we&amp;rsquo;ll call it the Front Page. You haven&amp;rsquo;t created this page, it&amp;rsquo;s just the default page that Wordpress creates for you. It features a blog (which currently has no posts), but you can make it so your Front Page shows whatever you want.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It&amp;rsquo;s time to get some content up in there. This is where you need to refer back to your little game plan, so you are clear about how many pages you need to create. For my website, I want to create five pages (Home, Bio, CV, Work, and Blog). I want the front page to be &amp;ldquo;Home,&amp;rdquo; and I don&amp;rsquo;t want the blog to show up there. Chances are you&amp;rsquo;ll have a similar concept for your site (you might have more or less pages, but I definitely recommend that you include at least an &amp;ldquo;about&amp;rdquo; or &amp;ldquo;contact&amp;rdquo; page or whatever.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/107.jpg&quot; height=&quot;644&quot; width=&quot;935&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;You can create pages in the Pages section of the Dashboard. I know, it&amp;rsquo;s pretty hard to wrap your brain around that idea, but you&amp;rsquo;ll just have to manage. Note that I already have one page (and you probably do, too): the Sample Page which I threw mercilessly in the trash.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/108.jpg&quot; height=&quot;641&quot; width=&quot;1003&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Hit &amp;ldquo;Add New&amp;rdquo; to add a page. The page Title will show up as a link in your site&amp;rsquo;s top navigation (or however the theme you chose lists your pages). You can use Wordpress&amp;rsquo;s&amp;rsquo; really handy text editor panel to create the actual content for the page. You can use the &amp;ldquo;Visual&amp;rdquo; tab to format your text just like you would in any text editing program and Wordpress will generate some HTML for you, or you can switch to the &amp;ldquo;HTML&amp;rdquo; tab to insert HTML code yourself. You can also format it in the Visual tab and switch to the HTML tab to see what the HTML looks like, which can be interesting.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/109.jpg&quot; height=&quot;641&quot; width=&quot;1004&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;So I filled out the info for my &amp;ldquo;Home&amp;rdquo; page. You can modify the Permalink to this page if you want, but keeping it yourwebsite/index.php/pagetitle/ is probably the best way to go. If you want a page to be the Front page (as I do for &amp;ldquo;Home&amp;rdquo;), you will be able to make it so in a bit, so just hold your horses. You can preview the page or save it for later, but you can just go ahead and hit &amp;ldquo;Publish&amp;rdquo; to make it a real page.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/110.jpg&quot; height=&quot;635&quot; width=&quot;1002&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Now if you check out your site, you&amp;rsquo;ll see a new page in your site menu (for my theme, as for most themes, the site menu is right under the header logo). Yes, I want to change the colors of those links from Green to some sort of Red, but let&amp;rsquo;s not worry about that now. Note that it treats your page like a blog post, so readers can post comments on them by default. I don&amp;rsquo;t want that, so I&amp;rsquo;ll have to turn it off, but we&amp;rsquo;ll get to that later. Oh, and don&amp;rsquo;t worry about that &amp;ldquo;edit&amp;rdquo; button (if there is one for you - it depends on your theme). That&amp;rsquo;s just there because we&amp;rsquo;re logged in as the Admin. Most users won&amp;rsquo;t see that.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/112.jpg&quot; height=&quot;638&quot; width=&quot;1000&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;I can just say &amp;ldquo;Add New&amp;rdquo; again to add the next page. Once you have pages, you can make new pages as &amp;ldquo;Sub Pages&amp;rdquo; by selecting a Parent. You can use this to make a page like &amp;ldquo;Contact Us&amp;rdquo; as a sub-menu item from &amp;ldquo;About Us&amp;rdquo; if you want, for example. Themes handle the sub items differently, but most will have a little drop down menu that shows up when you hover over a menu item. You might have noticed that when you were browsing themes - this is how you set that up. Also take note of the order option, because this determines the order your links will show up on the menu. The first page should be &amp;ldquo;0&amp;rdquo; and then they go up from there.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/111.jpg&quot; height=&quot;635&quot; width=&quot;1002&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;You can select &amp;ldquo;Set featured image&amp;rdquo; near the bottom of the right side of the Page Editor to add an image to the page. I&amp;rsquo;m going to upload a picture of Alyson for her Bio page. You could just copy an image directly to your /wp-content/uploads folder, but it&amp;rsquo;s better to use Wordpress to do it, as it will format it properly and include it in a special &amp;ldquo;Media Library&amp;rdquo; that you can use anywhere on your site.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/113.jpg&quot; height=&quot;639&quot; width=&quot;1002&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;You can change the title for the image, where it links to when you click on it, and how it&amp;rsquo;s aligned on the page. Once you insert the image, you can click on it and click the &amp;ldquo;Edit Image&amp;rdquo; button to tweak it further. It can be a little tricky to get the alignment to work right, but Hopefully you&amp;rsquo;ll work it out. You might notice that you can&amp;rsquo;t select a different &amp;ldquo;Size&amp;rdquo; option when you upload a new image to a post. This is because we haven&amp;rsquo;t enabled image editing support in PHP. We&amp;rsquo;ll get into that later, but for now you&amp;rsquo;ll just have to resize the images yourself (you can do that in Paint) or use the &amp;ldquo;Edit Image&amp;rdquo; button after you&amp;rsquo;ve inserted the image to resize it in HTML.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/114.jpg&quot; height=&quot;641&quot; width=&quot;1005&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;I created pages for all of the pages I need to create, and got them all ordered properly. Make sure that when you create a Blog page (which I think you should even if you want it to be the Front Page) just leave the actual content of the page blank.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/115.jpg&quot; height=&quot;856&quot; width=&quot;1005&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Now you&amp;rsquo;ll have a nice looking menu on your site, with all the pages you need. The problem now, though, is that the Front Page is none of these options, which is not only confusing to people visiting the site, but it&amp;rsquo;s not what I need the site to do. Let&amp;rsquo;s set this up now, shall we?&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/116.jpg&quot; height=&quot;699&quot; width=&quot;1002&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Head to the Reading page (under &amp;ldquo;Settings&amp;rdquo; in the Dashboard) to control your Front Page. The default is to show your latest posts, which means that it will show your blog. I don&amp;rsquo;t like this because I believe that every page on the site needs to be clearly represented in the main navigation of the site. What happens if somebody goes to &amp;ldquo;About&amp;rdquo; or whatever and then wants to get back to your blog?&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/117.jpg&quot; height=&quot;109&quot; width=&quot;209&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Here are the settings I used. I want the front page to be &amp;ldquo;Home&amp;rdquo; and the posts page to be &amp;ldquo;Blog.&amp;rdquo; That will make much more sense to a visitor.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/118.jpg&quot; height=&quot;707&quot; width=&quot;1006&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Now when you go to &amp;ldquo;localhost:81&amp;rdquo; you&amp;rsquo;ll go right to whatever page you selected as your front page, and when you go to &amp;ldquo;Blog&amp;rdquo; you&amp;rsquo;ll see &amp;ldquo;Nothing Found&amp;rdquo; because you have no blog entries. Notice that the Front Page (Home) doesn&#039;t have a permalink, anymore, because it&#039;s just &amp;ldquo;localhost:81.&amp;rdquo; We had better do something about that &amp;ldquo;no blog entries&amp;rdquo; thing, though.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;h5&gt;Part 5 D: Rad Blogojevich&lt;/h5&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/119.jpg&quot; height=&quot;701&quot; width=&quot;1003&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Manage your posts in the Posts section of the Dashboard. Wordpress organizes posts into categories, which you can use if you want, or just leave everything &amp;ldquo;Uncategorized.&amp;rdquo; You can also manage the tags you assign to each post.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/120.jpg&quot; height=&quot;707&quot; width=&quot;1008&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;This is pretty familiar. Writing and editing posts works exactly like pages, so you should be able to handle yourself here if you managed to work with the pages well enough. You can also manage what category and tags are associated with this post on this page.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;h5&gt;Part 5 D A: Yet Another PHP Setting&lt;/h5&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So Wordpress has the ability to rezise images when you upload them. This is a cool feature, because you can upload a huge picture and it will resize it to an appropriate size. You don&amp;rsquo;t want to make users download huge images, because it will just be slow and obnoxious for no reason. The problem is that this function relies on an extension to PHP that we didn&amp;rsquo;t activate when we first set up PHP. Do you really need this? Not really, because you&amp;rsquo;ll have it when you deploy your site to any web server (almost definitely). Any images you want to upload in the meantime you can just resize manually, with Paint or whatever. However, if you really want to use it, I&amp;rsquo;ll show you how. It&amp;rsquo;s really easy.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/121.jpg&quot; height=&quot;526&quot; width=&quot;716&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;You have to dig up your good old &amp;ldquo;php.ini&amp;rdquo; file, which is in C:/php, in case you forgot.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/122.jpg&quot; height=&quot;531&quot; width=&quot;765&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Find the line &amp;ldquo;;extension=php_gd2.dll&amp;rdquo; which is in the Dynamic Extensions section. Remove the semicolon from the beginning of that line.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/125.jpg&quot; height=&quot;354&quot; width=&quot;714&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;You might as well also increase the maximum upload filesize, which is on the line &amp;ldquo;upload_max_filesize = 2M&amp;rdquo; (you can search for File Uploads and scroll down a bit from there). Just blast it up to like 100M (the M is for Megabytes) or something silly like that. There&amp;rsquo;s no reason why your local testing environment should have a limit to uploaded files. You&amp;rsquo;ll be hard pressed to upload an image file larger than 100 MB, so that will be more than enough. Save and close php.ini.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/123.jpg&quot; height=&quot;651&quot; width=&quot;940&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Now go to your IIS Manager (inetmgr), find your DefaultAppPool, and recycle it. That will refresh your PHP beeps and boops.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/124.jpg&quot; height=&quot;655&quot; width=&quot;992&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;If you still have that phpinfo() file set up on localhost, you can go there and look for the section called &amp;ldquo;gd.&amp;rdquo; If the &amp;ldquo;gd&amp;rdquo; section is there, you know your system is set up to handle simple image editing.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;h5&gt;Part 5 D B: Where Were We?&lt;/h5&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/126.jpg&quot; height=&quot;656&quot; width=&quot;993&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Okay, so back to the Post section of our Dashboard. I just threw together a simple first post. I&amp;rsquo;ll now attach a picture to it!&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/127.jpg&quot; height=&quot;654&quot; width=&quot;990&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Just hit the &amp;ldquo;Add Picture&amp;rdquo; button just above the post area to, well, add a picture. You can add more than one at once.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/128.jpg&quot; height=&quot;659&quot; width=&quot;992&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Next you can fill out the info about the picture. Give the picture a title and a caption if you want. By default the image will link to itsself, so when a user clicks on the picture they&amp;rsquo;ll just get the picture again. I think this is kind of silly, so unless I want it to link to something, I just click &amp;ldquo;none&amp;rdquo; for Link URL. If you did that PHP thing just now, you&amp;rsquo;ll be able to specify what size to resize the image to. Notice that the original (Full) size is 1341 x 1614, which is really big for a web picture, so I&amp;rsquo;ll resize to the default Medium size image (those sizes are adjustable in the Dashboard Settings). You can make it the featured image if you want - some Wordpress themes can use the featured images as thumbnails for the post - or just insert it into the post.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/129.jpg&quot; height=&quot;412&quot; width=&quot;291&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;You can hit &amp;ldquo;Add New Category&amp;rdquo; under Categories to assign this (or any post) to a new category besides &amp;ldquo;Uncategorized.&amp;rdquo; You can also make a category a subcategory to another category by using the dropdown box there. You can also, also assign a post to multiple categories. You can really go nuts with the whole categories thing.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/130.jpg&quot; height=&quot;197&quot; width=&quot;291&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Use the &amp;ldquo;Tags&amp;rdquo; section to add (or remove) tags from the post. Once you get a few posts under your belt, you can add tags based on tags you&amp;rsquo;ve used before, which is kind of the whole point of tags.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/131.jpg&quot; height=&quot;809&quot; width=&quot;991&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Once you publish your post, you&amp;rsquo;ll be able to see it on your blog page. All themes are a little different about how they display posts, so your experience may vary a little. The theme I&amp;rsquo;m using here doesn&amp;rsquo;t show the tags, but you can see the category down there (although when you click on the post title to see the full post with comments you get the tags). Also notice that this post was &amp;ldquo;by Admin&amp;rdquo; because I posted it with the Admin account.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/141.jpg&quot; height=&quot;661&quot; width=&quot;1070&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Head to the Media Library (&amp;ldquo;Media&amp;rdquo; &amp;gt; &amp;ldquo;Library&amp;rdquo;) to see all of the images you&amp;rsquo;ve uploaded to your site, either through pages, blog posts, directly through here, or elsewhere. You can use &amp;ldquo;Add new&amp;rdquo; to upload more images if you want (which you can then reference in your styles or something). &lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/142.jpg&quot; height=&quot;662&quot; width=&quot;1073&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;When you select &amp;ldquo;Upload / Insert picture&amp;rdquo; when you&amp;rsquo;re working on a blog post, you can switch to the &amp;ldquo;Media Library&amp;rdquo; tab of the box that pops up to insert a picture that you&amp;rsquo;ve already uploaded through the Dashboard.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So now your website is basically a real, live website. It&amp;rsquo;s fully functional, has plenty of delicious content, and has a unique (ish) theme that you picked out yourself. It&amp;rsquo;s just that it&amp;rsquo;s not . . . perfect, is it? There are still some weird things that we don&amp;rsquo;t really want here or there, and there&amp;rsquo;s no setting for them in the Dashboard. What do we do? Looks like we&amp;rsquo;re going to have to get a bit more serious with Wordpress&amp;rsquo;s&amp;rsquo; beeps and boops. It&amp;rsquo;s time to teach this website who&amp;rsquo;s the boss of it, and that boss&amp;rsquo;s&amp;rsquo; name is YOU.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;We&amp;rsquo;re (hopefully) only two posts away from being done with this guide, and then normal operation will resume on DenyConformity.com.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h5&gt;Part 5 E: Getting Our Hands Dirty&lt;/h5&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Wordpress has plenty of settings for changing different things. However, there&amp;rsquo;s a limit to what you can tweak with checkboxes and dropdowns. The real power of Wordpress lies in the fact that it&amp;rsquo;s all built in PHP, which you can completely rewrite if you wanted to. Oh, stop sweating - we aren&amp;rsquo;t going to rewrite anything, but we will be doing some serious haxxxx.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h5&gt;Part 5 E A: The ABC&amp;rsquo;s of PHP&amp;rsquo;s&lt;/h5&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I just want to go over some basic stuff about how PHP works, just so you have a bit of an understanding of what we&amp;rsquo;re going to do. If you went through that PHP primer tutorial I linked a few parts back, good for you. This will be review for you. Otherwise, this will be wild and crazy. WOOAAAHHHH!&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h5&gt;Part 5 E A A: Where the Compiled things are&lt;/h5&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So PHP files are just text files, except they end with a .php instead of a .txt. For all intents and purposes, a PHP file is the same thing as an HTML file, so they can (and usually do) have a lot of HTML tags and whatnot in them as well as PHP code.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;PHP code goes inside of its own special tags, which are: &amp;lt;?php and ?&amp;gt;. If you&amp;rsquo;re looking for some PHP code, look for those thingies, because anything in between them (spanning multiple lines, even) will be PHP. Also, if you want to add any code or whatever, you better make sure it&amp;rsquo;s inside those guys, or you will not get what you&amp;rsquo;re wanting to get.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h5&gt;Part 5 E A B: No Comment&lt;/h5&gt;

&lt;p&gt;When you make computer code, you&amp;rsquo;re just working with text files. Then a computer takes that text and turns it into beeps and boops that it can do stuff with. You can include parts in your code that the computer will ignore, in case you want to leave little messages to future programmers (or yourself). Those are called &amp;ldquo;comments.&amp;rdquo; You can use them to make sections of code no longer work, which can be pretty handy.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Comments in PHP take one of two forms. A double slash (&amp;ldquo;//&amp;rdquo;) in front of a line means that anything on that line after the slashes will be ignored. A slash and an asterisk (&amp;ldquo;/* . . . */&amp;rdquo;) can surround comments as well, and everything in between the asterisks - even multiple lines - will be ignored.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;One of the main things we will be doing will be commenting out sections of the PHP code in our Theme files, so that certain things will be removed. It&amp;rsquo;s a way of removing code without actually removing code, so you can easily undo your changes just be removing the comment thingies.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Note that comments will not &amp;ldquo;get rid&amp;rdquo; of the special PHP tags (&amp;lt;?php or ?&amp;gt;), so don&amp;rsquo;t worry about having to &amp;ldquo;unhide&amp;rdquo; them.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h5&gt;Part 5 E A C: Good Luck, and Don&amp;rsquo;t Fuck it Up&lt;/h5&gt;

&lt;p&gt;PHP is pretty complicated, especially within Wordpress. Unless you know about classes and objects and PHP, don&amp;rsquo;t mess around too much, because you will break something. If you want to change something in a theme file, make a copy of the line you&amp;rsquo;re changing, and comment out the original. That way you can revert your change easily enough if it causes problems. If all else fails, you can just delete your theme folder (inside wp-content in your web site directory), and start over again. All of the settings you made within Wordpress will still be there (your pages and whatnot), just your theme will be reset.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h5&gt;Part 5 E B: Pressing Dr. Pageword&lt;/h5&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Let&amp;rsquo;s dive in, shall we?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/132.jpg&quot; height=&quot;816&quot; width=&quot;993&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;By default most themes treat pages the same as blog posts. This may be okay for some people, but I don&amp;rsquo;t like it. We&amp;rsquo;re going to change it. I&amp;rsquo;ll remove the comments as well as the entire left column from every page. Sure, some themes will let you change page layouts on individual pages, but most don&amp;rsquo;t. This is how you deal with those.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/133.jpg&quot; height=&quot;810&quot; width=&quot;991&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Head to your Dashboard, and find the &amp;ldquo;Editor&amp;rdquo; page of the &amp;ldquo;Appearance&amp;rdquo; section. This is where you can dig into your theme&amp;rsquo;s underpants, as it were. You&amp;rsquo;ll see a big text box where some code is, and a list of all the files in the theme along the right side. You can also edit themes that aren&amp;rsquo;t the active theme, if you want, by using the little dropdown there at the top.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/134.jpg&quot; height=&quot;755&quot; width=&quot;1058&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;I want to edit the Page Template, so I found &amp;ldquo;Page Template&amp;rdquo; (page.php) from the list and selected it. This brings up the theme&amp;rsquo;s page.php file (almost every theme will have the page.php template) into the text box. This is the code that specifies how pages are made in your theme. &lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/135.jpg&quot; height=&quot;512&quot; width=&quot;863&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Most of the components of Wordpress are called with functions. For example, the &amp;ldquo;get_header()&amp;rdquo; function (usually) at the top of every file brings in the Theme&amp;rsquo;s header, including the menu and whatever else. I want to find the function called &amp;ldquo;comments_template()&amp;rdquo; somewhere in this file, because that&amp;rsquo;s the function that brings in the comments. It has a couple parameters, which you can find out more about by selecting it in that little &amp;ldquo;Documentation&amp;rdquo; dropdown and hitting &amp;ldquo;lookup.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/136.jpg&quot; height=&quot;512&quot; width=&quot;725&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;All I have to do is comment out that function, and it will be ignored when somebody tries to view a page. Adding two little slashes (&amp;ldquo;/&amp;rdquo;) before the function is all it takes.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/137.jpg&quot; height=&quot;756&quot; width=&quot;1144&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;So I hit &amp;ldquo;update file&amp;rdquo; and refreshed the tab with the site in it. Check it out, no more comments! Depending on how much PHP (and CSS) you know, making any edits to Wordpress is that easy. That&amp;rsquo;s why Wordpress is so great.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/138.jpg&quot; height=&quot;421&quot; width=&quot;712&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Back in the Dashboard, I want to now find the function called &amp;ldquo;get_sidebar()&amp;rdquo; which is the function that creates the sidebar on the page. This will be a bit more complicated, because since the function is surrounded by that HTML Div tag, I can&amp;rsquo;t just comment out the function.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/139.jpg&quot; height=&quot;755&quot; width=&quot;1129&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;This is why. The content within the sidebar is gone, but the sidebar itself (that HTML Div tag) and all of the associated styling are still there. My page content is still pushed over, but now it&amp;rsquo;s even stupider looking because there&amp;rsquo;s just a big empty space.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/140.jpg&quot; height=&quot;423&quot; width=&quot;708&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;So to get rid of the HTML tag, I have to use an HTML comment. They work just like the other type of PHP comment (/*...*/), but they use &amp;ldquo;&amp;lt;!--&amp;rdquo; and &amp;ldquo;--&amp;gt;&amp;rdquo; instead. If I throw a &amp;ldquo;&amp;lt;!--&amp;rdquo; before the tag and a &amp;ldquo;--&amp;gt;&amp;rdquo; after it, it will be like that tag never existed. I&amp;rsquo;ll also leave that PHP function commented out, because those PHP tags will not be ignored even though they&amp;rsquo;re still inside the comment. There&amp;rsquo;s no reason to make the server do extra work for something we don&amp;rsquo;t even want to see.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/143.jpg&quot; height=&quot;674&quot; width=&quot;1046&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;So there we . . . ah, crap. Okay, so we got rid of the other column, but this one is still hanging out wherever it wants. Looks like we&amp;rsquo;ll have to dig into the CSS a bit, too.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/144.jpg&quot; height=&quot;631&quot; width=&quot;870&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;How can I figure out what to look for in the CSS file? It&amp;rsquo;s a bit tricky to wrap your head around all those HTML tags and CSS properties, but there are handy tools to help you do that. In Chrome (or Safari or Firefox), you can hit &amp;ldquo;Control + Shift + i&amp;rdquo; to open the developer tools for the current page. Now you can get a little view of the structure of the page (you&amp;rsquo;ll have to hit the little HTML button in Firefox), and you can click on the different elements in that list to highlight them in the actual page. It&amp;rsquo;s an easy way to relate the HTML code to what you actually see on the page, and then you can pretty easily figure out that (in the case of my theme) this &amp;ldquo;&amp;lt;div class=&quot;column-content&quot;&amp;gt;...&amp;lt;/div&amp;gt;&amp;rdquo; is the main content area.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/145.jpg&quot; height=&quot;668&quot; width=&quot;1009&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Here it is in Firefox. Where it says class=&amp;rdquo;column-content&amp;rdquo; is how the CSS styles are applied to it. That &amp;ldquo;column-content&amp;rdquo; class is set to be less than the entire width of the window, which is great if you have another column, but we don&amp;rsquo;t, so we need to make it be the full width.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/146.jpg&quot; height=&quot;668&quot; width=&quot;1043&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;I went to the Stylesheet in the Theme Editor (my theme only has one, but yours might have more - you&amp;rsquo;ll just have to look through them to find the one you need) and searched for &amp;ldquo;column-content&amp;rdquo; (Control+F will let you search the page for something). We can&amp;rsquo;t just edit that style, because it will screw up the Blog page, which uses the same styles. We&amp;rsquo;ll just have to create a new one.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/147.jpg&quot; height=&quot;423&quot; width=&quot;708&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Select the style (including everything between the curly brackets - and throw in the curly brackets too) and copy it. Then paste that code right after the original. You can then rename the new style something else, like &amp;ldquo;.column-solo&amp;rdquo; (the period in front of the name is really important, make sure you keep it). Get rid of the margin, change the float to &amp;ldquo;left&amp;rdquo; and add width: 100% to the end of this new style. Make sure every line ends with a semicolon. It&amp;rsquo;s also a good idea to search the page for the name of your new class. Hit &amp;ldquo;Control+F&amp;rdquo; and type your class name into the search box. You just want to make sure the new class doesn&amp;rsquo;t already exist - it could cause huge problems if it does. Class names have to be unique. When you&amp;rsquo;re ready, press &amp;ldquo;Update File.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/148.jpg&quot; height=&quot;452&quot; width=&quot;626&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Now I&amp;rsquo;ll head back to the Page Template and find that Div tag. I just have to change its class name to that new class I just made, and then update this file.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/149.jpg&quot; height=&quot;674&quot; width=&quot;1046&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Check it out, the column is gone, and so is the blank space it left. Sure, it would look a lot better with a bit more content there, but that&amp;rsquo;s an easy thing to do now. Now I&amp;rsquo;m not a huge fan of that search box up there in the header. Most themes have something like that, and I don&amp;rsquo;t really see a reason for it. We should be able to remove it pretty easily, now that we know all about commenting out a bit of PHP, right? Let&amp;rsquo;s try it.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;h5&gt;Part 5 E C: What Else?&lt;/h5&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/150.jpg&quot; height=&quot;671&quot; width=&quot;1046&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The header is built by the header.php file in your theme, if you can believe it. We can scroll down a bit to find something talking about search. Sure enough, here&amp;rsquo;s a couple HTML tags with a PHP function called &amp;ldquo;get_search_form()&amp;rdquo; inside it. Since these things are off to the right side of the page, we should be able to remove them much more easily than the sidebar was.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/151.jpg&quot; height=&quot;419&quot; width=&quot;621&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Throw a few comments in there, and we should be good to go.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/152.jpg&quot; height=&quot;679&quot; width=&quot;1051&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Oh yeah! Nothing is safe from our commenting hammer, now! Oh, but what about those menu colors, what if I wanted them to be red instead of green? It just so happens that changing colors is pretty easy in CSS . . .&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/153.jpg&quot; height=&quot;678&quot; width=&quot;1152&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;First we&amp;rsquo;ll have to use the developer tools to find the HTML behind that button. Then we can see the CSS that&amp;rsquo;s applied to it. We want to find the CSS style which looks like &amp;ldquo;#topmenu ul li.current_page_item a&amp;rdquo; and our color is in there.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/154.jpg&quot; height=&quot;672&quot; width=&quot;1051&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;I&amp;rsquo;ll head over to the style.css file and search for that. There we can see that the color style is set to &amp;ldquo;#8FC73E&amp;rdquo; which might look like some crazy gibberish, but it&amp;rsquo;s actually a color, represented in Hexadecimal format.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/155.jpg&quot; height=&quot;669&quot; width=&quot;1045&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;You can work with colors in Hex format in Photoshop, or you can try to find colors in Hex format online. I like this service called COLOURlovers, which can find you an entire color pallette based on one color. It&amp;rsquo;s a good place to find colors, and get their Hexadecimal format for use on Internets.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/156.jpg&quot; height=&quot;672&quot; width=&quot;1047&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Anyway, once you get a color you like, you can just find every instance of the color you want to replace and then replace it. Usually a theme will use the same few colors over and over in a lot of places, so you can just replace every instance of the color with another one and you&amp;rsquo;ll be able to get all the colors switched. There were quite a few instances of that green color in my theme, but I made them all a sort of pinkish purple, which is more to Alyson&amp;rsquo;s liking. &lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Take great precaution when dealing with CSS stuff. There&amp;rsquo;s a lot to consider about colors in a website, so be careful when you&amp;rsquo;re changing them around all a-willy and a-nilly. You have to deal with mouseover states, active states, inactive states, borders, backgrounds, and lots of other stuff. I&amp;rsquo;m not saying you shouldn&amp;rsquo;t give it a shot, I&amp;rsquo;m just saying it&amp;rsquo;s a can of worms. You can use comments in CSS, just like PHP, using the /* . . . */ method, so put those around old properties when you change them, so you can more easily changes things back.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/157.jpg&quot; height=&quot;669&quot; width=&quot;1043&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;With just a bit of CSS and PHP tweaking, you can really whip that website into shape. Sure, it can be intimidating and complicated, but it can also be really fun and rewarding.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So with just a little bit of technical knowhow, we can remove or change some things on our site. But what if we want to add more features that aren&amp;rsquo;t there at all? For that, we&amp;rsquo;ll need some plugins.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h5&gt;Part 5 F: Check out those Sweet Plugs&lt;/h5&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/158.jpg&quot; height=&quot;671&quot; width=&quot;1043&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Themes are great, but plugins are even greater. Head to the Plugins section of the dashboard to see your plugins. My Wordpress came with two, neither of which are activated. You can check those out if you want, but I&amp;rsquo;m going to show you how to install a new one.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/159.jpg&quot; height=&quot;673&quot; width=&quot;1045&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;If you want Wordpress to do something that it doesn&amp;rsquo;t do, you can google &amp;ldquo;Wordpress plugin&amp;rdquo; and whatever you want to do, and chances are you&amp;rsquo;ll find something useful. Alyson wants an image gallery on her site, so I want to find a good image gallery plugin.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/160.jpg&quot; height=&quot;678&quot; width=&quot;1046&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;That led me directly to this official Wordpress Plugin Directory page for a decent looking Gallery plugin. You could also just search the Plugin Directory for a plugin, but whatever. Here you can see installation instructions, screenshots, and other information about plugins. You can also press that &amp;ldquo;Download Version Whatever&amp;rdquo; button to download it, so I&amp;rsquo;ll go ahead and do that.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/161.jpg&quot; height=&quot;545&quot; width=&quot;763&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Installing a plugin is just like installing a theme. You&amp;rsquo;ll download a zip file with a folder inside it. Just open that zip file and copy the folder to yourwebsite/wp-content/plugins&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/162.jpg&quot; height=&quot;672&quot; width=&quot;1045&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Refresh that Plugins page and you should see your new plugin in the list. That way works really well when the site is located right there on your computer, but there&amp;rsquo;s another easy way to install plugins which you can use even when your site is published to a web host out there in the Internet somewhere.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/163.jpg&quot; height=&quot;674&quot; width=&quot;977&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Go to that Plugins page, click &amp;ldquo;add new&amp;rdquo; and then select &amp;ldquo;Upload.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/164.jpg&quot; height=&quot;678&quot; width=&quot;980&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Point it directly to the zip file you downloaded with the plugin inside it. Yes, just hand it the zip file, and it will do everything on its own. You can install plugins either way, it really makes no difference, but keep in mind that when the site is live you&amp;rsquo;ll have to do it this way.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/165.jpg&quot; height=&quot;677&quot; width=&quot;981&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Okay, so the plugin is installed. Now you just have to activate it (click &amp;ldquo;Activate&amp;rdquo;) and it will be listed in the &amp;ldquo;Active&amp;rdquo; section of the plugins page. In my case, for this image gallery plugin, I also got another section in the Dashboard menu - &amp;ldquo;Gallery.&amp;rdquo; That&amp;rsquo;s where I can create image galleries with this plugin.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/166.jpg&quot; height=&quot;671&quot; width=&quot;1020&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Inside this new Gallery section, I can control just about every aspect of an image gallery.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/167.jpg&quot; height=&quot;675&quot; width=&quot;1087&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The plugin also added a new button to the page / blog post editing window. I can use this button to insert a gallery into a page or blog post. Your plugin might have added a button here as well.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Plugins do all kinds of things, so your experience may be totally different. I won&amp;rsquo;t go into detail about how to use this particular gallery plugin, as it&amp;rsquo;s outside the scope of &amp;ldquo;How to Make a Website.&amp;rdquo; There is one plugin that I would like to show you, though, and I recommend that you install it. It will help prevent spam robots and jerk-wads from wreaking havoc with your website.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/168.jpg&quot; height=&quot;676&quot; width=&quot;1088&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Head to &lt;a href=&quot;http://wordpress.org/extend/plugins/wp-recaptcha/&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;http://wordpress.org/extend/plugins/wp-recaptcha/&lt;/a&gt; and download the plugin there. Install it just like I showed you.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/169.jpg&quot; height=&quot;671&quot; width=&quot;1082&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;When you activate it, you&amp;rsquo;ll see this error telling you that you don&amp;rsquo;t have any API keys. Go ahead and click &amp;ldquo;Fix this.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/170.jpg&quot; height=&quot;724&quot; width=&quot;1088&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Now you will have to go to &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.google.com/recaptcha/admin/create&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;https://www.google.com/recaptcha/admin/create&lt;/a&gt; and log in with your Google account. If you don&amp;rsquo;t have a Google account, you might as well crawl out from under that rock and create one. Enter &amp;ldquo;localhost&amp;rdquo; into the box and hit &amp;ldquo;Create Key.&amp;rdquo; Note that you&amp;rsquo;ll have to get new keys for your actual domain name when you publish your website to your host.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/171.jpg&quot; height=&quot;724&quot; width=&quot;1084&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Now you can go back to your reCAPTCHA options and enter the Public and Private keys into those text boxes. You can also change some options if you want, but the defaults are all fine. The only thing you might want to change is the Theme, which can be changed to whatever color you prefer.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/172.jpg&quot; height=&quot;698&quot; width=&quot;1064&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Now you can go to your website and look at a blog post. You&amp;rsquo;ll have to either log out or check it out from a different browser. You should see the ReCAPTCHA box just above your &amp;ldquo;Post Comment&amp;rdquo; button. Now users will have to fill that out in order to post a comment. It will help keep out robots and stuff.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/173.jpg&quot; height=&quot;725&quot; width=&quot;1081&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Now you can go to your discussion settings page and make things a bit less complicated for your users. I like to turn off &amp;ldquo;Comment author must have a previously approved comment&amp;rdquo; and &amp;ldquo;Comment Author must fill out name and e-mail.&amp;rdquo; The former option makes it so you have to manually approve every comment on your site (which takes time and is annoying to both you and your commenters) and the latter makes it so users can&amp;rsquo;t post comments anonymously. Sure, I wish people would be more open about who they are on the Internet, but you can&amp;rsquo;t force people to do anything they don&amp;rsquo;t want to do.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/174.jpg&quot; height=&quot;843&quot; width=&quot;1115&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;So now you (probably) have a super cool, totally customized website.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;There is nothing beyond your grasp now, so long as it&amp;rsquo;s within the - admittedly vast - purview of Wordpress. I invite you to spend a bit of time now really polishing the bits here and there. Go over all your text, check all your pictures, and make sure there aren&amp;rsquo;t any typos or bugs. Play around with a few plugins and see what sorts of cool features you can wrangle out of your new site.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;We have one step left in this whole process, and it&amp;rsquo;s the big one. Next time we&amp;rsquo;ll publish your whole site to the Wild World of Web, and after that it will be out there for the whole world to see. After that, you can still make changes and whatnot, but it won&amp;rsquo;t be quite as easy as when it&amp;rsquo;s right there on your computer. If there&amp;rsquo;s anything else you want to do, do it now.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I understand, of course, that there are some things you might have trouble with. Some of that PHP and CSS stuff can get really troublesome. I would be happy to answer any questions that I can. Feel free to hit me up at &lt;a href=&quot;mailto:smcgill@denyconformity.com&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;smcgill@denyconformity.com&lt;/a&gt; and tell me what your site is all about, and what you&amp;rsquo;re having trouble with - or what questions you have about PHP, HTML, CSS, or just life in general. I want the Internet to be a better place, and I&amp;rsquo;m willing to do that one website at a time.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I&amp;rsquo;ll see you tomorrow, for the exciting conclusion!&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So here we are. You put together a handy and adorable little Internet, built yourself a pretty neat little website place, and bought yourself some web space. The time has finally come to put that puppy online and be an Internetman just like me. Without further adieu, let&amp;rsquo;s make it happen.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h5&gt;Part 6: The Epic Conclusion&lt;/h5&gt;

&lt;p&gt;You&amp;rsquo;ll need to download and install an FTP program - okay, you can just use Windows if you want, but this program will make things much easier. My favorite is called Filezilla, so that&amp;rsquo;s what I&amp;rsquo;ll be using.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/175.jpg&quot; height=&quot;705&quot; width=&quot;1028&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Head to &lt;a href=&quot;http://filezilla-project.org/download.php?type=client&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;http://filezilla-project.org/download.php?type=client&lt;/a&gt; and click the green &amp;ldquo;Download Now&amp;rdquo; button. Then you just have to wait for the download to start. You shouldn&amp;rsquo;t have to click anything else. You&amp;rsquo;ll get a plain old .exe file, so just run that and install the thing. &amp;ldquo;FTP&amp;rdquo; stands for File Transfer Protocol, and it&amp;rsquo;s the main way to upload files to Internets. Filezilla makes that process pretty easy.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;There are two components to deploying our website. First we have to set up MySQL, and then we have to upload the files. You better dig out that email you got from your web host with all the information you need to access your new space. We&amp;rsquo;ll do the database first.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h5&gt;Part 6 A: I Referred to it as &lt;em&gt;Our&lt;/em&gt; SQL&lt;/h5&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/176.jpg&quot; height=&quot;704&quot; width=&quot;1045&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Remember phpMyAdmin? Well, go to there now. It should still be &lt;a href=&quot;localhost/phpMyAdmin&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;localhost/phpMyAdmin&lt;/a&gt; (remember to start your MySQL server if you need to).&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/177.jpg&quot; height=&quot;704&quot; width=&quot;1041&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Click on the &amp;ldquo;wordpress&amp;rdquo; database in the list on the left, and you&amp;rsquo;ll see a bit list of all the tables that Wordpress has generated for all of its beeps and boops.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/178.jpg&quot; height=&quot;701&quot; width=&quot;1044&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Go to the &amp;ldquo;Export&amp;rdquo; tab, and pick &amp;ldquo;Custom.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/179.jpg&quot; height=&quot;700&quot; width=&quot;1041&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Scroll all the way down - we&amp;rsquo;re going to just use all the default settings - and pick &amp;ldquo;Go.&amp;rdquo; It will then download a file, which will probably be called &amp;ldquo;wordpress.sql.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/180.jpg&quot; height=&quot;701&quot; width=&quot;1042&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Now head to your hosting company&amp;rsquo;s website, and log in however you&amp;rsquo;re supposed to log in. For Bluehost, I have to just go to bluehost.com and click the &amp;ldquo;Control Panel Login&amp;rdquo; button at the top.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/181.jpg&quot; height=&quot;704&quot; width=&quot;1041&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;When you log in to the system, you&amp;rsquo;ll probably see something similar to this (maybe not the top, but the bottom area with all the buttons, definitely). Most basic web hosts use this control panel system called cPanel, which gives you links to all of the features included in your account. If your control panel looks different than this, well, I&amp;rsquo;m sorry. You&amp;rsquo;ll just have to find your way on your own, but it should still have options for doing everything I&amp;rsquo;m going to do with cPanel.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;You might notice that Bluehost has a link in the control panel to automatically install Wordpress onto your web space. This might be pretty easy, but it doesn&amp;rsquo;t offer nearly as much control over things as the way we&amp;rsquo;re doing it, so just ignore it. That button is for puny little baby men, not glorious Internet Champions like us.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/182.jpg&quot; height=&quot;705&quot; width=&quot;1039&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Scroll down until you find the Databases section (or find the Databases section of whatever control panel you have). Things might be slightly different for you, but it should give you the ability to look at (and add) MySQL Databases. For me, it&amp;rsquo;s the first button there under Databases.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/183.jpg&quot; height=&quot;706&quot; width=&quot;1038&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;This experience might be different for you, too, but the same options should be there. We need to create a new database and a new MySQL user. I already have some databases and users in my account, because I&amp;rsquo;m going to be hosting this new website on the same hosting plan as DenyConformity.com (most hosts will let you host multiple domains and sites on one account). One hiccup in our plan is that most hosting companies will add your account username to the beginning of any database names (mine is &amp;ldquo;denyconf&amp;rdquo;), so we will need to keep that in mind later.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/184.jpg&quot; height=&quot;704&quot; width=&quot;1040&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Enter a name for your new database (&amp;ldquo;wordpress&amp;rdquo; for example) and create it. Make a note of what the actual name of the database is (mine is &amp;ldquo;denyconf_wordpress&amp;rdquo;).&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/185.jpg&quot; height=&quot;706&quot; width=&quot;1043&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;I am able to create new users from the same page as I can create databases. You might have to go somewhere else, but it shouldn&amp;rsquo;t be hard to find. Create a new user (mine limits how long the names can be, so it will just be &amp;ldquo;wp&amp;rdquo;) and use the same password that you used when you created a MySQL user on your computer (if you lost that password you can make a new one, but it will be easier in a bit if you use the same password).&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/186.jpg&quot; height=&quot;702&quot; width=&quot;1041&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;You&amp;rsquo;ll also have to add that new user to the new database, so it has access. In Bluehost&amp;rsquo;s system, you have to first create the user, and then go back to this page to add the user to the database. It&amp;rsquo;s kind of a security risk for me to show all of the MySQL users I have for this website, but without any of the passwords there isn&amp;rsquo;t much you can do with them.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/187.jpg&quot; height=&quot;704&quot; width=&quot;1040&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Make sure the new user has &amp;ldquo;All Privileges&amp;rdquo; for the database.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/188.jpg&quot; height=&quot;705&quot; width=&quot;1042&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Okay, now you can go back to the control panel and find the link to phpMyAdmin (our old friend). I can almost guarantee that whatever web host you have will have a link to phpMyAdmin somewhere. Even GoDaddy uses it.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/189.jpg&quot; height=&quot;704&quot; width=&quot;1038&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Now we&amp;rsquo;re in familiar territory. You can probably log in with the same information you use to log into your web hosting control panel. If not, you can log in with that new wordpress user you just created.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/190.jpg&quot; height=&quot;703&quot; width=&quot;1042&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;You probably won&amp;rsquo;t be able to create users or databases through it, but otherwise it should be pretty much the same phpMyAdmin you&amp;rsquo;re already somewhat familiar with. Select your wordpress database from the list on the left (mine is &amp;ldquo;_wordpress&amp;rdquo;).&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/191.jpg&quot; height=&quot;704&quot; width=&quot;1043&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Select the &amp;ldquo;Import&amp;rdquo; tab, click &amp;ldquo;Choose File&amp;rdquo; and select that .sql file you downloaded from the Export you did earlier. Scroll down, cross your fingers, and click &amp;ldquo;Go.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/192.jpg&quot; height=&quot;707&quot; width=&quot;1042&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;It should all go through fine. You&amp;rsquo;ll see all those Wordpress things come up there on the left. If not, you could have a problem with compatibility, or something else causing it to not work. Feel free to either comment on this post or email me (&lt;a href=&quot;mailto:smcgill@denyconformity.com&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;smcgill@denyconformity.com&lt;/a&gt;) if you have any problems.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/193.jpg&quot; height=&quot;608&quot; width=&quot;956&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;We have to change some references to our old domain, though. Select the &amp;ldquo;SQL&amp;rdquo; tab, and paste the following text directly into the text box there and hit &amp;ldquo;Go&amp;rdquo; (change the &amp;ldquo;YOURDOMAIN&amp;rdquo; parts to your actual domain):&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;UPDATE wp_options SET option_value=&#039;http://www.YOURDOMAIN.com&#039; WHERE option_name=&#039;siteurl&#039;;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;UPDATE wp_options SET option_value=&#039;http://www.YOURDOMAIN.com&#039; WHERE option_name=&#039;home&#039;;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;UPDATE wp_posts SET post_content = REPLACE(post_content, &#039;localhost:81&#039;, &#039;www.YOURDOMAIN.com&#039;);&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;UPDATE wp_posts SET guid = REPLACE(guid, &#039;localhost:81&#039;, &#039;www.YOURDOMAIN.com&#039;);&lt;/p&gt;


&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/194.jpg&quot; height=&quot;605&quot; width=&quot;959&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;It should go through without any errors. The first two things will only affect one row each, but the other two will affect quite a few rows.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Now your database is set up and ready to go, so we can turn our attention to your site&amp;rsquo;s files.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Part 6 B: Something about FTP&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/195.jpg&quot; height=&quot;531&quot; width=&quot;751&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Navigate to your website&amp;rsquo;s folder on your computer. Find the &amp;ldquo;wp-config.php&amp;rdquo; file, and make a copy of it. Rename the copy &amp;ldquo;wp-config-production.php.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/196.jpg&quot; height=&quot;544&quot; width=&quot;871&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Open the new file in notepad and change the values for &amp;ldquo;DB_NAME,&amp;rdquo; &amp;ldquo;DB_USER,&amp;rdquo; and &amp;ldquo;DB_PASSWORD.&amp;rdquo; You probably won&amp;rsquo;t have to change the value for &amp;ldquo;DB_HOST&amp;rdquo; because most web hosts set it up to use localhost. It will say somewhere in the control panel for your hosting account if you should change the DB Host to something else. Save and close this file.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/197.jpg&quot; height=&quot;607&quot; width=&quot;737&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Now open up FileZilla and try not to be intimidated by how complicated it looks. It&amp;rsquo;s really not that bad. There&amp;rsquo;s a log window on top, which will tell you when stuff works or doesn&amp;rsquo;t work. There are two file browsing windows - the left is for your local file system, and the right is for the server you&amp;rsquo;ll connect to. Finally you have a transfer queue, which will show the list of files that FileZilla is trying to transfer, as well as the ones it has either succeeded or failed at transferring.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/198.jpg&quot; height=&quot;606&quot; width=&quot;734&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Enter the FTP information for the web host at the top. You&amp;rsquo;ll have to dig that information up from the email they sent you, or find it in the control panel somewhere. Usually you can use &amp;ldquo;ftp.YOURDOMAIN.com&amp;rdquo; as the Host and then the same username and password that you used to get into the control panel. Click &amp;ldquo;Quickconnect&amp;rdquo; and it will hopefully poop out a bunch of stuff in the log window and then eventually show you a list of files on the right side there.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/199.jpg&quot; height=&quot;476&quot; width=&quot;662&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;You&amp;rsquo;ll be looking at all the files in the root of your web space directory. You want to put your website files into the &amp;ldquo;public_html&amp;rdquo; or &amp;ldquo;www&amp;rdquo; folders (they&amp;rsquo;ll point to the same place). Go ahead and double click to get into that folder now.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/200.jpg&quot; height=&quot;511&quot; width=&quot;667&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;There will probably be a few files, and at least one folder already there. Feel free to delete everything there, because it&amp;rsquo;s all just placeholder stuff. You can just drag in the window to select everything, and hit the &amp;ldquo;delete&amp;rdquo; key on your keyboard. It will be all, &amp;ldquo;are you sure?!??!&amp;rdquo; Just coldly say &amp;ldquo;yes.&amp;rdquo; You want to be sure your web server thinks you&amp;rsquo;re stone cold.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/201.jpg&quot; height=&quot;676&quot; width=&quot;1057&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Now navigate to the local website folder on the left side. Select all of the files and folders in there, right click them, and say &amp;ldquo;Upload.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/202.jpg&quot; height=&quot;667&quot; width=&quot;1048&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;FileZilla will start doing its thing (my site has like 1600 files to transfer). This will take up to some minutes, so just sit back and bask in how close you finally are to website.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/203.jpg&quot; height=&quot;663&quot; width=&quot;1043&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Once it finishes, find the wp-config.php file on the remote site section. Just stone cold delete that sucker. You really are cold as ice. Now right click the wp-config-production.php file, and select &amp;ldquo;rename.&amp;rdquo; Rename it to straight up wp-config.php.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/204.jpg&quot; height=&quot;409&quot; width=&quot;342&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Now find the wp-content directory, right click it, and select &amp;ldquo;permissions.&amp;rdquo; Check all of the boxes (it should say &amp;ldquo;777&amp;rdquo; in the Numeric value box), select &amp;ldquo;Recurse into subdirectories&amp;rdquo; and also select &amp;ldquo;Apply to all files and directories&amp;rdquo; and then hit &amp;ldquo;OK.&amp;rdquo; FileZilla will do its thing again, applying those permissions to all of the subdirectories and files.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Now hold your breath as you go to your new domain name in a browser. . .&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/205.jpg&quot; height=&quot;611&quot; width=&quot;962&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;If everything happened properly, your new website should be up and running!&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;What if it doesn&amp;rsquo;t work? Well, you could try deleting your files and emptying your database, and try the whole migration process over again. You could try finding your theme folder on the Remote site in FileZilla and rename it to see if your theme is causing problems. Sometimes for strange reasons some files will get chewed up when they are uploaded. This is extremely rare, but it happens. If your site is totally broken and you can&amp;rsquo;t even get into /wp-admin, you could try uploading the site again with a different FTP program or Windows itself (&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncsu.edu/resnet/file_transfer/ftp-windows-explorer.php&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;here&lt;/a&gt; is a quite old but still relevant tutorial on using FTP in Windows). As always, if you are having problems, feel free to email me at &lt;a href=&quot;mailto:smcgill@denyconformity.com&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;smcgill@denyconformity.com&lt;/a&gt;, or just leave a comment below.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/206.jpg&quot; height=&quot;589&quot; width=&quot;958&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;One more quick thing you could do: If your web host is using Linux (almost all of them are), you can go to your Dashboard and find the Permalink Settings. Here you can pick a new option, this time without the /index.php/ which was in there on your Windows server.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/how_to_website/207.jpg&quot; height=&quot;595&quot; width=&quot;953&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;You&amp;rsquo;ll also need to get new Public and Private keys for your ReCAPTCHA plugin, if you installed it. Just click that little &amp;ldquo;here&amp;rdquo; link and the rest is easy.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Well, there you go, your very own website. Sure, maybe my process was a bit more complicated than it really needed to be. However, I believe that by doing it this way you really get a better sense for how things work, and how to work with them. Sure, you aren&amp;rsquo;t an expert on PHP or CSS or anything, but you (hopefully) have a bit of an understanding of how you can make changes if you want to. By creating your own little web server, maybe now you have a bit more respect for all those other web servers out there.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;There is plenty more to say, surely, and I&amp;rsquo;ll probably publish addendums and extra tutorials for specific things down the road. However, I feel at this point I&amp;rsquo;ve said enough (there were 207 images in all the parts of this tutorial). If you have any questions, comments, or thoughts, if you would like me to explain anything further, or if you are having problems getting it all to work, please email me at &lt;a href=&quot;mailto:smcgill@denyconformity.com&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;smcgill@denyconformity.com&lt;/a&gt;, or leave a comment below.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Thank you very much for sticking around and going through the whole tutorial. It&#039;s been a blast for me to put it all together, and I hope it&amp;rsquo;s helped you website!&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;My birthday is this Saturday. I&amp;rsquo;m going to be 26 years old. I&amp;rsquo;m having a harder and harder time justifying asking my friends and family to buy me toys this year. The problem is that aside from a new $5000 camera or a new $600 camera lens, there isn&amp;rsquo;t really much that I necessarily want or need, and I can&amp;rsquo;t really ask my parents to buy me a $5000 camera when I&amp;rsquo;m not really doing anything productive with the camera I have.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Anyway, I&amp;rsquo;ve been perusing Amazon.com for some stuff that I can ask for my birthday this year. I know this is pretty late notice, but with Amazon Prime you can get free 2-day shipping on most stuff, so if you wanted to get me any of this stuff you probably still could.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So the idea here is to find some stuff that an Adult could get. Obviously I would love to have a new Nerf Gun or a Lego or something, but that&amp;rsquo;s kid stuff. I&amp;rsquo;m an adult, now, which means it&amp;rsquo;s time for me to start getting into adult pursuits.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Item:&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00362MKUC/ref=s9_simh_gw_p21_d0_g21_i1?pf_rd_m=ATVPDKIKX0DER&amp;amp;pf_rd_s=center-5&amp;amp;pf_rd_r=196T5GV6CP1RFEYCPP1T&amp;amp;pf_rd_t=101&amp;amp;pf_rd_p=470939291&amp;amp;pf_rd_i=507846&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Hot Dog Hat&lt;/a&gt;, by US Toy&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/birthday_2012/hotdog_hat.jpg&quot; height=&quot;505&quot; width=&quot;507&quot;&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Product Description:&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ldquo;Catch attention with this funny hat. This hot dog hat is great for a ball game or to wear on funny hat day. Adult size. Made of cloth. Size 18 L.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Okay, so this might seem like a kid thing. How many adults do you know who would wear a hot dog hat? Make no mistake, though, this is Adult size, so it is RIGHT UP MY ALLEY. I love hot dogs, and I love catching attention. This is pretty much made just for me. I absolutely can&amp;rsquo;t wait to wear this to a ball game so the guy behind me will have this hilarious hat in his way through the whole game. I also - wait a minute - &lt;em&gt;there&amp;rsquo;s a funny hat day?&lt;/em&gt; Why did nobody tell me about funny hat day? I WOULD ROCK THE CRAP OUT OF FUNNY HAT DAY. Especially with this hat.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The best part? You don&amp;rsquo;t have to worry about this hot dog going bad (do hot dogs actually go bad?). It&amp;rsquo;s made of cloth!&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The actual best part is looking at the &amp;ldquo;Customers who bought this item also bought&amp;rdquo; section on the Hot Dog Hat&amp;rsquo;s amazon page:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/birthday_2012/hotdog_customersalso.jpg&quot; height=&quot;240&quot; width=&quot;1103&quot;&gt;&lt;p&gt;No, these aren&amp;rsquo;t &amp;ldquo;related items.&amp;rdquo; This is real stuff that people have actually purchased in addition to Hot Dog Hat. There is a man out there (of course he is a man) who owns the triple threat of Hot Dog Hat, Hamburger Hat, and Pizza Hat. That man is my hero, and he is the true champion of Funny Hat Day.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/birthday_2012/hotdog_boughttogether.jpg&quot; height=&quot;194&quot; width=&quot;627&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Oh, thank you, Internet.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Amazon.com Rating:&lt;/strong&gt; 2.5 Stars (3 reviews)&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Here&amp;rsquo;s where Hot Dog Hat kind of loses some of its appeal. Amazon.com user &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.amazon.com/gp/pdp/profile/AOLCKPYFFQMNU/ref=cm_cr_dp_pdp&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Idaho Dave&lt;/a&gt; (you owe it to yourself to click that link) says, &amp;ldquo;NOT ADULT SIZE. KIDS ONLY... SMALL HEADS ONLY... CHEAPLY MADE WITH MUSTARD FALLING OFF.&amp;rdquo; (one star). I mean, as long as the Ketchup stays on, I think I can deal with it. Still, though, what is the point of buying an Adult size Hot Dog Hat if it is only for, as Idaho Dave also puts it, &amp;ldquo;AMAZON TRAVELERS WITH SHRUNKEN HEADS!&amp;rdquo; However, as Amazon.com user &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.amazon.com/gp/pdp/profile/ARGTORKW5T3CC/ref=cm_cr_dp_pdp&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Peter J. Dibonaventura&lt;/a&gt; (in his only Amazon.com review) points out, &amp;ldquo;they do squeeze your head a little- but the good news is THEY stay ON!&amp;rdquo; That&amp;rsquo;s a pretty good point, Peter.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Maybe Hot Dog Hat isn&amp;rsquo;t the best choice, though. I mean, it&amp;rsquo;s only $7.23, but I really need the mustard to stay on for the joke to really land. Maybe there&amp;rsquo;s another Hot Dog Hat on Amazon that&amp;rsquo;s better.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/birthday_2012/hotdog_results.jpg&quot; height=&quot;56&quot; width=&quot;190&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Oh, good.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It&amp;rsquo;s a shame about Hamburger Hat, though. It only has one review, from Amazon.com user &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.amazon.com/gp/pdp/profile/A1IL95JV5QUODY/ref=cm_cr_dp_pdp&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;June L. Smithee&lt;/a&gt;. She says, &amp;ldquo;I wear food hats for work at a school for young children. They like the fact that I&#039;m silly enough to wear them. This one is great for what I wanted it for, [Amazon.com] ask if it is a fun toy, durable toy, educational toy but this is a hat not a toy, just for fun.&amp;rdquo; (One star). Come on, June, you&amp;rsquo;ve singlehandedly destroyed the reputation of this fine novelty hat, just because Amazon.com doesn&amp;rsquo;t have a sepparate category for Novelty Hats?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Obviously this Novelty Hat market is a pandora&amp;rsquo;s box of possibilities, but let&amp;rsquo;s not get mired in deciding which one will be best for funny hat day or which one has the most durable mustard.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;That hat really has me thinking about hot dogs, though. Man, I love hot dogs. Maybe there&amp;rsquo;s something on Amazon.com for me? I mean, something besides a giant novelty hot dog (made of cloth) that I can wear on my head.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Item:&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.amazon.com/Nostalgia-Electrics-RHD-800-Series-Roller/dp/B000XB6LS6/ref=sr_1_3?ie=UTF8&amp;amp;qid=1337193696&amp;amp;sr=8-3&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Nostalgia Electrics RHD-800 Retro Series Hot Dog Roller&lt;/a&gt;, by Nostalgia Electrics&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/birthday_2012/hotdog_roller.jpg&quot; height=&quot;676&quot; width=&quot;665&quot;&gt;&lt;p&gt;I&amp;rsquo;ve always wanted to be able to recreate that real 7-Eleven experience of eating a lukewarm hot dog that&amp;rsquo;s been sitting out all day having people sneeze on it. The only problem that I forsee with this bad boy is that I&amp;rsquo;m not sure if I&amp;rsquo;ll be able to figure out those complicated controls. I mean, &amp;ldquo;OFF - ON&amp;rdquo; I understand (though I don&amp;rsquo;t understand why the knob seems to be halfway between the two), but what is that &amp;ldquo;MIN - MAX&amp;rdquo; dial for? Does it control the amount of food poisoning that the RHD-800 applies to the hot dogs slowly rotating away to oblivion on it?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Product Description:&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ldquo;The old fashioned hot dog roller with griddle brings back memories of carnivals, ball games; family gatherings and more. The unit holds up to eight regular sized hot dogs or 4 foot long hot dogs at a time. Includes convenient bun storage warmer in the canopy top. This hot dog stand is a fun way for guests to select and make their own hot dogs.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Finally I&amp;rsquo;ll have something for my &amp;ldquo;select your own hot dog&amp;rdquo; parties.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Amazon Rating:&lt;/strong&gt; 3.8 Stars (39 reviews)&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Reviews are pretty evenly spread for the RHD-800. Amazon.com user &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.amazon.com/gp/pdp/profile/A1NXBSYO96ZQN5/ref=cm_cr_dp_pdp&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;ZipSmoke20&lt;/a&gt; lauds the RHD-800&amp;rsquo;s easy cleanup (presumably because the filthier it is the more authentic it is) and its ability to make &amp;ldquo;perfectly cooked dogs&amp;rdquo; (5 stars). He says, &amp;ldquo;We run the left knob at 5 o&#039;clock and in 20-25 minutes you&#039;ll have a nice evenly cooked hot dog with perfect color and perfect temperature inside. We&#039;ve cooked more than 100 hot dogs on this unit since my purchase less than a month ago, unit is still going strong with zero issues. . . If you are even a little interested in this item don&#039;t hesitate, order one, you won&#039;t regret it.&amp;rdquo; The dude is a hot dog FIEND. I don&amp;rsquo;t know if I would say I&amp;rsquo;m a &amp;ldquo;little interested&amp;rdquo; but it sounds like a sure thing. Wait - &lt;em&gt;20 - 25 minutes?! I&amp;rsquo;m not waiting 25 minutes for a hot dog.&lt;/em&gt; I could make a real food in that much time.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;There&amp;rsquo;s a flip side to that coin, of course. Amazon.com user &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.amazon.com/gp/pdp/profile/A9BFPSMC0PTKV/ref=cm_cr_pr_pdp&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Michelle A. Kinsey&lt;/a&gt;, in her only Amazon.com review, bought the RHD-800 as a Birthday gift for someone (so I&amp;rsquo;m totally looking in the right place). Michelle&amp;rsquo;s friend was &amp;ldquo;sure she was going to give up her day job and run a hot-dog stand, Perfect gift to get her started.&amp;rdquo; Hey, maybe I could start a hot-dog stand! Michelle goes on to tell a sad (albeit somewhat lyrical) tale. She actually has quite a way with words. As she puts it, &amp;ldquo;1st machine arrived she invited guest over to show her new stand, The roller would only go 1/4 of a turn and stop, Returned the machine for a new one. 2nd machine arrived guest invited for a card game and this new machine the rollers would not turn at all, 1 engineer, 1 contractor and 1 electrician and no rollers to cook the hot-dogs, Thank goodness for the stove. And a very disappointed Birthday girl. we decided we did not want to try our luck on a 3rd machine:(.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I&amp;rsquo;ll just go ahead and post one more review, in its entirety, because of how great it is. It&amp;rsquo;s from Amazon.com user &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.amazon.com/gp/pdp/profile/A2E5V704BZ6J5D/ref=cm_cr_pr_pdp&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Angelica Westry&lt;/a&gt;, and the review is aptly entitled &amp;ldquo;Angelica.&amp;rdquo; Angelica says, &amp;ldquo;TERRIABLE!!!! When I receive my Hotdog Roller it looked like someone took a hammer and smashed it!!!! It still works (Thank God) but it looks teriable, not at all what it says it looks like in the describstion. Very disapointing.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Hey wait, Michelle brought up a good point. I can just cook hot dogs in the stove! Well, I don&amp;rsquo;t need this teriable piece of junk, then!&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Maybe this idea to start my own Hot Dog stand isn&amp;rsquo;t such a bad one, though. I mean, I don&amp;rsquo;t have to limit myself to something teriable, I could put a bit more money up front to get something really nice.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Item:&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.amazon.com/The-Dog-Hotdog-Steamer-Merchandiser/dp/B004E231VK/ref=sr_1_7?ie=UTF8&amp;amp;qid=1337193696&amp;amp;sr=8-7&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;The Dog Hut Hotdog Steamer and Merchandiser&lt;/a&gt;, by Paragon&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/birthday_2012/hotdog_paragon.jpg&quot; height=&quot;508&quot; width=&quot;455&quot;&gt;&lt;p&gt;Now we&amp;rsquo;re talking! I could sell Hell of hot dogs with this baby. Also I could merchandise the hot dogs? What exactly is a merchandiser, anyway?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Product Description:&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ldquo;The Dog Hut is intended to set the standard par excellence for hotdog steamers. It will be ideal for use in rental shops, convenience stores, concession stands, vending carts, breakrooms, fast food restaurants, snack bars, cafeterias or many others. Check out other Paragon Products.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;There&amp;rsquo;s only one review on this guy, but it&amp;rsquo;s aptly titled &amp;ldquo;An excellent macnine for the money.&amp;rdquo; Yes! I will have the best hotdog macnine on the block! &amp;ldquo;I recommend this machine to anyone who needs to have a large number of hot dogs ready at all times&amp;rdquo; (five stars). Thank you, Amazon.com user &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.amazon.com/gp/pdp/profile/A1B1DVT896IJ3/ref=cm_cr_dp_pdp&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Charles H Tupper&lt;/a&gt;, that &lt;em&gt;is&lt;/em&gt; exactly what I need!&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;As the description states, let&amp;rsquo;s see what other fine products Paragon offers. Stuff like . . .&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Item:&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.amazon.com/Paragon-Biotin-Plus-Hoof-Conditioner/dp/B000HHLITI/ref=sr_1_13?s=sporting-goods&amp;amp;ie=UTF8&amp;amp;qid=1337198402&amp;amp;sr=1-13&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Biotin Plus Hoof Conditioner&lt;/a&gt;, by Paragon&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/birthday_2012/biotin_plus.jpg&quot; height=&quot;247&quot; width=&quot;280&quot;&gt;&lt;p&gt;Available in 5, 2.5, or 20 pound buckets. Perfect merchandise to offer alongside your perfectly steamed hot dogs. &amp;ldquo;While you wait 20 to 25 minutes for your hot dog, would you like your hooves conditioned? Five dollars.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Item:&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.amazon.com/Conquer-EC-Long-Lasting-Insecticide/dp/B005665UP8/ref=sr_1_53?s=sporting-goods&amp;amp;ie=UTF8&amp;amp;qid=1337198982&amp;amp;sr=1-53&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Conquer EC Long Lasting Insecticide - 1pt&lt;/a&gt; by Paragon&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/birthday_2012/insecticide.jpg&quot; height=&quot;231&quot; width=&quot;306&quot;&gt;&lt;p&gt;I can mix this with the water I use to steam those hot dogs, and then I&amp;rsquo;ll be able to keep my hot dogs insect free! That can be like my &lt;em&gt;thing&lt;/em&gt;. &amp;ldquo;My Hot Dogs are guaranteed to kill all internal parasites, and I promise my mustard won&amp;rsquo;t fall off like those &lt;em&gt;other&lt;/em&gt; guys!&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Okay, if I&amp;rsquo;m really going to do this hot dog stand, I&amp;rsquo;ll need other stuff, too. Help me out, Amazon!&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Item:&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.amazon.com/Bar-40159X-18-Piece-Classic-Holder/dp/B0043M5RL8/ref=sr_1_4?ie=UTF8&amp;amp;qid=1337194776&amp;amp;sr=8-4&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Mr Bar B Q 40159X 18-Piece Classic Hot Dog Holder&lt;/a&gt;, by Mr. Bar-B-Q&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/birthday_2012/hotdog_holder.jpg&quot; height=&quot;704&quot; width=&quot;661&quot;&gt;&lt;p&gt;Isn&amp;rsquo;t that . . . yeah, that&amp;rsquo;s just a coffee filter.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Product Description:&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ldquo;Classic hot dog holders&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Nope, those are coffee filters. Nice try, buddy. I&amp;rsquo;m not falling for that one. It&amp;rsquo;s the oldest trick in the &amp;ldquo;scam aspiring hot dog vendors&amp;rdquo; handbook.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Obviously running a hot dog stand is serious business. I&amp;rsquo;m going to need to really be careful so I don&amp;rsquo;t fall for a scammer more cunning than Mr. Bar B Q (how many initials does he need, anyway?). Maybe I should do some research or buy a book on the subject.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Item:&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.amazon.com/The-Black-Book-Hot-Stand/dp/1450720765/ref=sr_1_28?ie=UTF8&amp;amp;qid=1337193816&amp;amp;sr=8-28&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;The Black Book of Hot Dog Stand&lt;/a&gt; by Mat Chaundhry&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/birthday_2012/black_book.jpg&quot; height=&quot;504&quot; width=&quot;359&quot;&gt;&lt;p&gt;Perfect. I want to Hot Dog Stand, and so I&amp;rsquo;ll buy the Black Book of it. Plus, hey, you really can&amp;rsquo;t beat that cover.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Product Description:&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ldquo;The Hotdog industry is multi-billion dollar industry. Fact of the matter is that last year the American hot dog vendors collectively earned more revenues than most countries in Asia, Africa and Europe. Hotdogs are in big demand. This offers a real job security. With over 18 billion hot dogs sold every year just in the US. No doubt it is rightly called &quot;Recession Free&quot; business. What is the difference between making $100 day and averaging $500 day? The answer is: knowledge. It is not experience, it is knowledge. The Black Book is the only book in the market which combines the experiences of top hot dog vendors from Seattle, New York and Chicago. These vendors are street fighters who learned how to top the competition.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Hey, Chicago, that&amp;rsquo;s where I live! I&amp;rsquo;ll turn myself into a down and dirty street fighter, blasting the competition with the most powerful hadouken of all: knowledge. Help me, Mat Chaundhry, to earn more revenues than those stupid countries in Africa. Take that, the Congo. Move over, Namibia. I&amp;rsquo;ll make more money than both of you! I bet you could really use some of this insecticide and hoof conditioner, too. Too bad! I have a big demand to fill just in the US.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Hold on a second. The answer is: knowledge, right? It is not experience, it is knowledge. Why is this book the combined &lt;em&gt;experiences&lt;/em&gt; of top hot dog vendors, then? Why would I want their useless, useless experiences when knowledge is the true answer? I&amp;rsquo;m starting to have second thoughts about this. Also, there&amp;rsquo;s this review, from freaking &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.amazon.com/gp/pdp/profile/A71C047PYPUZJ/ref=cm_cr_dp_pdp&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Alec Baldwin&lt;/a&gt;:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;I have to admit that I was skeptical that I could ever make a go of a business after my &quot; Oooh La Waffle-Gourmet French Creme-Filled Waffles&quot; stands failed to turn a profit despite perfect locations (right across the street from the beach? One practically in the parking lot of the local Tennis Club? C&#039;mon!) and an initial investment of over $400,000. But I saw a copy of of this book on the counter of my favorite &quot;Street Meat Bistro&quot;, and although at first of course I thought it was porn, I asked the vendor if I could take a look. This is the book which takes your dream of selling low-cost/high profit margin meat and premium condiments, dangles it in front of your eyes and says &quot;Here it is....your dream is plump and hot....now reach for it!&quot; In six months using techniques outlined in plain meat-vendor lingo, I was buying my second cart! Offering double the condiments and still turning a profit! I am not up to the &quot;Hundred Dollar A Day&quot; mark the author assures me is possible, but I am well on my way to half of that. Not bad for less than ten hours in the fresh air in a not so snowy Detroit winter!&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Great book. Not as much of what we see on the cover as I would like, and not even a mention of how to distribute &quot;pharmaceuticals&quot; discreetly from my cart to supplement the slow weeks (like another book I had read), but a great plan to make it rich in the low cost reheated processed meat biz.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I could never hope to compete with freaking Alec Baldwin. He&amp;rsquo;s totally on the money about that cover, though.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Okay, so a birthday just isn&amp;rsquo;t the time or place to start a new career. I already have a career, making websites. What I really need is something to make my time working in a stuffy, boring office more interesting. Not just on funny hat day, but &lt;em&gt;every&lt;/em&gt; day. Queue the most important Amazon.com product search in history:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/birthday_2012/fake_poop_search.jpg&quot; height=&quot;152&quot; width=&quot;606&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;I can guarantee that you can occupy yourself for an entire day exploring the possibilities of this Amazon.com product search.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Item:&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.amazon.com/Party-Pooper-Fake-Human-Poop/dp/B001O8F0W0/ref=sr_1_2?ie=UTF8&amp;amp;qid=1337186517&amp;amp;sr=8-2&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Party Pooper Fake Human Poop&lt;/a&gt;, by SLC&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/birthday_2012/fake_poop1.jpg&quot; height=&quot;161&quot; width=&quot;212&quot;&gt;&lt;p&gt;There are really only two periods of human history. There was the time before somebody realized he could make realistic fake plastic poop, and there is the time after - the fake plastic poop age. These days, literally the only problem you face is deciding which of the hundreds of fake plastic poops out there is the fake plastic poop for you. Let&amp;rsquo;s see how this one &amp;ldquo;piles up,&amp;rdquo; as it were.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Product Description:&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ldquo;Imagine the look on your girlfriend, friend, or wifes face when she walks in the bathroom and encounters this &quot;Load&quot;. This fake poop provides hours of entertainment and horror!&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Hours of entertainment&lt;/em&gt; is a lofty claim. My attention span has been so destroyed by TV and Video games that I can hardly bring myself to finish swallowing my hoof conditioner treatments. In order for something to give me hours of entertainment, it had better be really, really great. Still, I do have a lot of things I could place fake poop on, and my girlfriend does really hate looking at poop, so you&amp;rsquo;d think the possibilities are pretty endless.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Rating:&lt;/strong&gt; 3.7 Stars (59 reviews)&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The real problem with fake plastic poop is that it&amp;rsquo;s victim to the opinions of viewers. Some people might agree with Amazon.com user &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.amazon.com/gp/pdp/profile/A2IBUE2WR08IBH/ref=cm_cr_dp_qtlb_pdp&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Craig Motsenboker&lt;/a&gt; in saying, &amp;ldquo;Overall this product is pootastic.&amp;rdquo; Others might disagree, however, like Amazon.com user &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.amazon.com/gp/pdp/profile/A2V7V6IPXDKKQM/ref=cm_cr_dp_qtlb_pdp&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;S. Namfukwe&lt;/a&gt;, who says, &amp;ldquo;Looks very fake and very plastic.&amp;rdquo; It&amp;rsquo;s really going to be a crap shoot (sorry) whether or not you&amp;rsquo;ll approve. It&amp;rsquo;s hard to tell whether or not Amazon.com user  &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.amazon.com/gp/pdp/profile/AYLI58QD3VJ4L/ref=cm_cr_dp_pdp&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;MW&lt;/a&gt; likes the product when he wrote a review entitled, &amp;ldquo;crappy product.&amp;rdquo; Isn&amp;rsquo;t that the point?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Whatever you do, heed the warning of Amazon.com user &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.amazon.com/gp/pdp/profile/A1FDYEL18NEO2H/ref=cm_cr_dp_pdp&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;PizzaAttack&lt;/a&gt;, whose review, &amp;ldquo;Caution,&amp;rdquo; is a very cautionary tale indeed. He says, &amp;ldquo;This product was ok until Someone decided to replace it with the real thing. After the laughs I proceeded to collect my toy only to find the real thing in my hands. Still warm too. I suggest keeping a watchful eye on it.&amp;rdquo; To be fair, when you prank you have to expect a bit of pranking back. Somebody got that guy pretty good.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;That brings up a real problem with fake plastic poop, though. I mean, if you&amp;rsquo;re going to prank somebody, why not just go for it? My body produces its own version of fake plastic poop which is, in my opinion, pretty pootastic. I could save myself quite a bit of money by just placing my own poop around to see the look on my girlfriend, friend, or wifes face. I mean, what&amp;rsquo;s the prank, here? We&amp;rsquo;re working entirely off the premise that it&amp;rsquo;s funny just to make somebody look at a thing they kind of don&amp;rsquo;t like to look at? Fake plastic poop is so ubiquitous now that it&amp;rsquo;s not even really a prank anymore. This Someone in PizzaAttack&#039;s story might really be on to something, there. A real prank would be to make somebody think you placed fake plastic poop somewhere, but then have it turn out to be &lt;em&gt;real poop&lt;/em&gt;. &lt;em&gt;That&amp;rsquo;s&lt;/em&gt; funny.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Item:&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.amazon.com/DOMAGRON-Novelty-780984463366-Fake-Stress/dp/B0054QV2A2/ref=sr_1_4?ie=UTF8&amp;amp;qid=1337186517&amp;amp;sr=8-4&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Fake Poop Stress Toy&lt;/a&gt;, by DOMAGRON Novelty&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/birthday_2012/fake_poop2.jpg&quot; height=&quot;198&quot; width=&quot;278&quot;&gt;&lt;p&gt;It does look a bit like poop, but it looks an awful more like something else.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Product Description:&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ldquo;The Fake Poop Stress Toy is the perfect stress toy for when you feel like s***. You can squeeze this ridiculously realistic foam poop toy when you&#039;ve hit rock bottom. Just imagine what your co-workers will think when they see you squeezing poop. For a fun office prank, place the Fake Poop Stress Toy in a common place around the office. Your co-workers will be checking their shoes after seeing poop on the floor. It&#039;s time to have more fun at work with the Fake Poop Stress Toy.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I tell you what, it really &lt;em&gt;is&lt;/em&gt; time to have more fun at work. I really applaud these guys for giving this thing a dual-purpose function. I mean, it eliminates stress and is a really, really great joke. Listen, nothing humiliates coworkers more than being tricked into checking their shoes. When they look down at their feet, they&amp;rsquo;ll just be reminded about how poorly conditioned their hooves are in comparison to mine, so it&amp;rsquo;s like two pranks in one. It&amp;rsquo;s the perfect storm. I could basically sell my computer, TV, comic books, and anything else I use to entertain myself, because Fake Poop Stress Toy is all I&amp;rsquo;ll ever need.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I think we&amp;rsquo;ve got it. For my birthday this year I&amp;rsquo;ll ask my parents to buy me this very particularly shaped rubber &amp;ldquo;stress&amp;rdquo; toy . . .&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;On second thought, I better keep looking.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I was digging through my pictures folder, and I came across some pictures I took back in &#039;09 when I went to the Field Museum. Some of them are kind of neat, so I figured I would post them here. Don&#039;t take this as any sort of sign that I&#039;m running out of content to post here.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/field_museum/IMG_1992.jpg&quot; height=&quot;533&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;They have a big T-Rex skellington at the Field Museum, in case you didn&#039;t know. It&#039;s pretty sweet.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/field_museum/IMG_1996.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;They also have a whole bunch of stuffed animals. They&#039;re not like the type that you sleep with. They&#039;re the creepy kind.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/field_museum/IMG_2000.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Just about any animal you can think of is represented in creepy taxidermy form.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/field_museum/IMG_2006.jpg&quot; height=&quot;533&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The T-Rex is cooler.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/field_museum/IMG_2022.jpg&quot; height=&quot;533&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The Field Museum lives on the Museum Campus, which is a neat place with only one real museum on it. There&#039;s also a planetarium, an aquarium, and a football stadium. And this pole thing.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/field_museum/IMG_2023.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Also this flagpole is there.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/field_museum/IMG_2032.jpg&quot; height=&quot;533&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;There is a really great view of the Chicago Skyline, though.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/field_museum/IMG_2034.jpg&quot; height=&quot;533&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;I got this puppet thing for my Sister, and a friend of mine helped me take a bunch of dumb pictures of it. This is the first of those dumb pictures.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/field_museum/IMG_2038.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;We were pretty bored, I guess.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/field_museum/IMG_2046.jpg&quot; height=&quot;533&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;It&#039;s interesting, if nothing else, to see just how dumb I was three years ago. I would never do something this dumb now.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/field_museum/IMG_2051.jpg&quot; height=&quot;533&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;To be fair, this one is pretty great.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/field_museum/IMG_2053.jpg&quot; height=&quot;533&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Photobombed.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Okay, well, there we go. That&#039;s today&#039;s post. Hopefully I&#039;ll have something actually good for you tomorrow.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I&#039;ve been working on this book for quite a while now, and I&#039;m still very excited about how great it is. However, I&#039;m still waiting on some offers from some movie studios for the film rights. Just let me know when you&#039;re ready to make some fat stacks, movie studios.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Anyway, when last we left our really beautiful heroes, they were running for their lives through the streets of District Alpha, trying to get to a safe house where our hero Matt&#039;s friends lived. Our other hero, Kate, was just trying to get a handle on being in the big city, since she grew up on a robot farm.&lt;/p&gt;


&lt;h5&gt;District Alpha: Government Mandate Zone&lt;/h5&gt;
&lt;h5&gt;Chapter 7&lt;/h5&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Welcome to Exposition House,&amp;rdquo; said the old man in the doorway, grinning from ear to ear at the two of them. &amp;ldquo;It&amp;rsquo;s so good to meet you, Kate!&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The old man had already given Matt a heartfelt greeting, but it&amp;rsquo;s much more interesting to start this scene when the old man meets Kate. They were standing, the three of them, in a dark corridor of a large apartment building. The hall was very dark, and graffiti could be seen on the walls. Bright, warm light cascaded from the open door to Matt&amp;rsquo;s friends&amp;rsquo; apartment. It was very inviting.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Kate looked at the man. He was small and only had hair around the back of his head. Kate had never met this kindly old man before, but his warm greeting made her immediately at ease. She had only met one physically old person in her life, many years ago, so she was fascinated by the lines on his face and the shine of his bald head. He stood aside in the entryway, gesturing grandly to the both of them, ushering them inside. Kate followed Matt inside, left speechless by this onslaught of new experiences.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Kate is from District Delta.&amp;rdquo; Matt filled the silence left by Kate&amp;rsquo;s inexperience.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The old man, whom Kate had just learned was called Pete, held his hand out to Kate, somehow smiling even larger than before. She stared at his wrinkled face and followed the line of his beliverspotted arm to his hand, held vertically with his fingers all pointing at her. She stared, confused, for what seemed like minutes before suddenly remembering the gesture that she had seen her father make to other gentlemen on the robot farm many years ago. With a flash of comprehension on her face, she brought her hand to his and wrapped her fingers around it.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Looking over at Matt, the old man said with a chuckle, &amp;ldquo;she&amp;rsquo;s a naive one, isn&amp;rsquo;t she?&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Pete, take it easy,&amp;rdquo; Matt said, &amp;ldquo;she&amp;rsquo;s been through a lot in the last few days.&amp;rdquo; Matt reached out to gently pull their hands apart. Kate was happy to know how to shake the old man&amp;rsquo;s hand, but she had no idea how or when to end such a gesture. She was very grateful for Matt&amp;rsquo;s tactful interjection, and she smiled softly at his hand on hers. She would have preferred to shake his hand.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Well, you&amp;rsquo;re in safe hands, now, my dear!&amp;rdquo; Pete said to her, his warm friendly face making her smile again. Kate was really displaying a broad range of subtle emotions, but they were all just smiles, so it&amp;rsquo;s not like it was some really expensive Oscar winning moment or anything.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The old man turned into the apartment with the same grand form with which he treated everything, saying, &amp;ldquo;come, you&amp;rsquo;ll have to meet the whole family!&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Kate looked at her surroundings, now, as they stepped into a new corridor. They were now standing in a short hallway, softly lit by an overhead light. The walls were lined with pictures of many things Kate had never seen before, and many people Kate wanted to meet. The people in the pictures were all smiling. Kate marveled at all of the old photographs - some of them were so old that their hologromatic projection was starting to fade -  as Matt and Pete chatted. She hardly paid any attention to them. This corridor was a big contrast from the last few corridors they had gone through.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Oh, your Aunt Kathy and Uncle Tom are going to be so excited to see you,&amp;rdquo; Pete was saying, putting his thin arm around Matt&amp;rsquo;s shoulders.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;How is everyone?&amp;rdquo; Matt asked.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Pete started explaining that times were as rough as ever, but as they reached the end of the corridor they all stopped short at the sound of a high-pitched scream. Kate tensed up.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Matt! Guy&amp;rsquo;s, it&amp;rsquo;s Matt!&amp;rdquo; A young woman was shouting. The corridor opened up into a cozy kitchen, and just beyond Kate could see several figures inside a living room, all excitedly getting up and hurrying to where Pete and Matt were standing.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Kate could only stand and watch as what seemed like a thousand hugs and warm greetings descended upon her new friend. She felt awkward for the first time, in this new social situation she would never have dreamt of. She couldn&amp;rsquo;t keep up with everyone speaking all at once, and she was surprised at the myriad ways each person used to say the same thing. If she had a thesaurus with her, she wouldn&amp;rsquo;t have been able to come up with as many synonyms for &amp;ldquo;good to see you&amp;rdquo; as they had.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Some of the strangers&amp;rsquo; eyes were turning on her. She felt more awkward at first, but these people were so friendly and their smiles were so inviting that she felt safe and decided to just go with it. These people really were friendly, you see.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Matt looked at her and smiled. He said, &amp;ldquo;this is Kate. She&amp;rsquo;s my new friend.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The entire room looked at her then. She smiled awkwardly back at them and lifted her hand in a little half-wave. Pete was all smiles. He has already met the new girl, so he was way ahead of everybody else.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Matt began the introductions. Kate smiled and touched hands with everyone in the room. Some of them were introduced in pairs because they were married or something, but Kate still touched their hands separately. Kate knew she would never remember all of these new names and faces, but most of these people aren&amp;rsquo;t major characters so it doesn&amp;rsquo;t really matter who they are. She was able to tell who was important in the room because they were more attractive and had a few more things to say to her than just &amp;ldquo;hello.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Kate met Matt&amp;rsquo;s uncle Tom and aunt Kathy. Pete mentioned them earlier, so they&amp;rsquo;ll probably be important to the story later.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Then Kate met a girl named Alice. Alice was about Kate&amp;rsquo;s age, but she seemed a lot smarter than Kate about stuff that Kate wasn&amp;rsquo;t so smart about. Kate also really didn&amp;rsquo;t like the way Alice was looking at Matt, but she also really didn&amp;rsquo;t know why. Alice was really pretty, but in a different way than Kate. Alice was the Mila Kunis to Kate&amp;rsquo;s Natalie Portman - but only as an example. Who could afford them?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Then Kate met a really grumpy looking guy. &amp;ldquo;What&amp;rsquo;s your problem,&amp;rdquo; she asked.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Oh, I&amp;rsquo;m not very important,&amp;rdquo; he replied, &amp;ldquo;so my whole part will probably get cut out of the movie entirely.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Kate didn&amp;rsquo;t really understand that, as her furrowed brow implied. At least he got to say something in the book. The guy stepped back to his place and very deliberately milled about, conspicuously being inconspicuous. For example, he chatted with one of the other extra people in the room, but neither of them actually said anything.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Finally Kate met a man named Braiden. He owned the apartment they were all living in, which is only part of the reason she could tell he was a main character. He was also a Steve Buscemi looking guy, and those sorts are always really important. Braiden looked at her with his big, round eyes and welcomed her to his home. Kate was put off at first by Braiden&amp;rsquo;s blatant un-attractiveness, but you know how Steve Buscemi is actually really endearing, especially when he&amp;rsquo;s being a nice guy. He wore an olive-colored shirt, buttoned all the way to the collar even though he didn&amp;rsquo;t have a tie. His olive-colored cargo pants were well worn, and he had lots of stuff in all of his pockets, including the two on the front of his shirt. His quaint little fedora hat was haphazardly placed on his head.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Kate met some other people there but they weren&amp;rsquo;t important so it doesn&amp;rsquo;t matter. They were just extra people. Eventually everybody - people with names and all the extras - filed out of the kitchen and went back to what they were doing. Braiden took Matt under his arm and they went into a back room. Kate felt alone for a moment, left to fend for herself.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;She looked around at this part of the apartment. The kitchen was very nice, with cooking utensils stored all around the granite countertops. Kate noted that the appliances were all made by GE, and she could really tell that they were very high quality appliances. A long countertop separated the kitchen from the next room, which was a sort of living area. When she looked in that direction, she realized that two little girls were standing by the kitchen island, watching her.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Hi,&amp;rdquo; one of the girls said. The other nodded.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Hello,&amp;rdquo; Kate replied. &amp;ldquo;What&amp;rsquo;s your name?&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Ashley,&amp;rdquo; the girl said. The other nodded.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Oh, okay. I&amp;rsquo;m Kate.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;I know!&amp;rdquo; The girls giggled. They had heard her name said a hundred times already. The two little girls wore pigtails and dresses with flowers on them. One of them was white, and the other was black, but it really doesn&amp;rsquo;t matter which was which. The important thing is that nobody is surprised when they show up on a movie screen.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;T!&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Kate gasped in shock when the shout rang out to her side. She had forgotten that Pete was still standing there, and he was looking up at her with his customary smile. She had no idea what he meant.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;What?&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;I&amp;rsquo;ll make some tea!&amp;rdquo; Pete elaborated. &amp;ldquo;Don&amp;rsquo;t tell me you&amp;rsquo;ve never heard of tea.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;She relaxed. &amp;ldquo;Oh! Of course I&amp;rsquo;ve heard of tea. I just didn&amp;rsquo;t understand why you yelled it in my ear.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Oh, you poor naive girl, you have a lot to learn about the city! Here, I&amp;rsquo;ll put the kettle on and make you a cup of darjey. Tea&amp;rsquo;s a bit different, but I&amp;rsquo;m sure you&amp;rsquo;ll love it if you try it.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Kate sighed and decided that this old man wasn&amp;rsquo;t all there. She shrugged and said, &amp;ldquo;okay.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Kate looked back at the two girls. They were still smiling and giggling as if they knew something Kate didn&amp;rsquo;t. Kate might have wondered at that point if her fly was down, if automatic pants hadn&amp;rsquo;t been invented many years earlier. They weren&amp;rsquo;t giggling at anything in particular, though, that&amp;rsquo;s just how kids are.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Do you like Tv?&amp;rdquo; the one girl asked Kate. The other nodded.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Sure. We had a government-issue television on the robot farm. I used to watch it when I was your age.&amp;rdquo; Kate replied. The gratuitous backstory was lost on the little girls.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Do you want to watch with us?&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Okay.&amp;rdquo; Kate replied. She didn&amp;rsquo;t have anything better to do.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The girls ran off, giggling, to the living area, where a big comfy couch sat in front of a screen bigger than Kate.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;The TV on my farm wasn&amp;rsquo;t nearly as big as this one,&amp;rdquo; Kate said, staring at the giant screen.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;One of the girls grabbed a remote and flipped the screen on. They started watching a television show or movie made by whatever production studio buys the movie rights to this book. It&amp;rsquo;s a perfect cross promotional opportunity. Kate sat on the couch next to the girls.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Shortly Pete walked into the living room carrying a steaming mug. He carefully handed it to Kate, who took a quick sip.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Here you are, young lady.&amp;rdquo; Pete said as he sat in the easy chair that was right next to the couch.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Thank you, Pete.&amp;rdquo; Kate replied.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Watching some Tv?&amp;rdquo; Pete asked.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Yes. I haven&amp;rsquo;t seen this show before.&amp;rdquo; Kate replied.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Ah, yes, we only watch old shows here. We have a great collection. We don&amp;rsquo;t watch the Government Tv.&amp;rdquo; Kate realized that he was putting an emphasis on the T in Tv, which she figured was a city thing. Pete continued, &amp;ldquo;all the programs are Mandated by the Government, you know. No creativity. No freedom. No Scott Bakula. Not like the good old days.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;They sat there, sipping tea and watching a great collection of content from the early 2010&amp;rsquo;s for quite a few minutes.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Finally Pete leaned to Kate, and in a sort of mystical, hushed voice said, &amp;ldquo;so you&amp;rsquo;re here for the prophecy?&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Kate looked up at the old man. He was smiling gently, comfortingly, with a look that said, &amp;ldquo;it&amp;rsquo;s okay, your secret will be safe with me&amp;rdquo; except that Kate didn&amp;rsquo;t know what the Hell he was talking about.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A long pause happened then, during which Kate tried really hard to process what the old man had just said. Nothing was working out, though, so all she could say was, &amp;ldquo;what?&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;The prophecy. You&amp;rsquo;re the One, aren&amp;rsquo;t you?&amp;rdquo; Pete replied with a wink.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;That wasn&amp;rsquo;t really much of an elaboration, and it only raised more questions. She decided to choose the question that was in the forefront of her thoughts, which was, &amp;ldquo;what?&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Some say it isn&amp;rsquo;t true, of course, but now they&amp;rsquo;ll believe. Now they&amp;rsquo;ll have someone to put their faith in.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Another pause. Another attempt for her brain to get a handle on things. Another &amp;ldquo;what?&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Pete smiled, and a bony old hand reached out to gently touch hers in a comforting manner. &amp;ldquo;So Matt hasn&amp;rsquo;t told you yet. Well, there&amp;rsquo;s no harm in spilling the beans now, I suppose. You&amp;rsquo;ll learn your destiny sooner or later. I probably don&amp;rsquo;t need to tell you what everybody thinks of that Matt. He always was, you know.&amp;rdquo; he said, kind of trailing off there at the end. He smiled to himself, lost in thought.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Kate was starting to freak out a little bit. &amp;ldquo;What were you saying?&amp;rdquo; she prompted.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Oh, well, he&amp;rsquo;s been with us quite a while, you know. That Braiden, he thinks Matt is -&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;No, not about Matt. What is this prophecy?&amp;rdquo; She interrupted.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Before Pete could respond, Matt and Braiden came back into the room.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Okay, Kate, let&amp;rsquo;s talk about what&amp;rsquo;s going on,&amp;rdquo; Braiden said. The two of them stood there staring at her. She sat, mug of tea in hand, staring at Pete.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Finally Pete leaned gently to her, and with a caring pat on her knee, said, &amp;ldquo;I think they&amp;rsquo;re waiting for you to follow them.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Kate slowly stood, eyes wide, careful not to drop her mug of hot tea. She walked over to Matt and Braiden, through a doorway into a room that Kate thought looked like a meeting room.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;This is our meeting room,&amp;rdquo; said Braiden, as he and Matt followed her inside. It was an old bedroom, repurposed for the repurpose of being a meeting room for this group of whatever Braiden is about to explain that they are. At the far end of the room was a window, but it was covered, giving the whole room a very ominous, shadowy quality. In the middle of the room was a table. Not many table manufacturers seem like the type to underwrite a book or movie so it doesn&amp;rsquo;t matter what kind of table it was, but if there&amp;rsquo;s a company out there that would be up for that then it was totally that kind of table. It was a rather large table, seating eight comfortably. The top was made of a hard wood, and was a deep shade of brown. It&amp;rsquo;s not really important to the plot or anything, it was just a really, really nice table.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Matt pulled out a chair for Kate, and she sat down. Sitting at the other end of the glorious table were the couple introduced to Kate earlier as Uncle Tom and Aunt Kathy. They were holding hands and looking at her with a happy excitement in their eyes, so Kate could tell that she wasn&amp;rsquo;t in trouble or anything.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Did Pete make you some tea?&amp;rdquo; asked Matt as he sat down next to her. Braiden took the seat on the other side of the table. Two adults could sit across from each other at the table without having their knees touch. It was a really, really nice table.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Yeah,&amp;rdquo; responded Kate, hesitantly. She was partially unsure how to feel about that old man, but also just really impressed by the quality of craftsmanship of the table.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;What do you think? It&amp;rsquo;s a bit weird at first, but you&amp;rsquo;ll --&amp;rdquo; responded Braiden, but Kate interrupted him.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;It&amp;rsquo;s a bit weak, really. I&amp;rsquo;m used to having fresh  - not from a tea bag. I don&amp;rsquo;t want to sound ungrateful or anything, but he should really steep Darjeeling for longer than he did, especially since it&amp;rsquo;s a bit older.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;How do you know so much about tea?&amp;rdquo; asked Matt.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;I grew up on a robot farm,&amp;rdquo; Kate pointed out, as if saying, &amp;ldquo;well, &lt;em&gt;duh&lt;/em&gt;.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The others looked at each other. It seemed there was more to Kate than they had expected.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;So,&amp;rdquo; said Kate, &amp;ldquo;Pete was telling me something.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Oh, was he saying something about a phrophecy?&amp;rdquo; responded Matt. &amp;ldquo;Yeah, he does that all the time. Don&amp;rsquo;t take him too seriously.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Yeah,&amp;rdquo; added Braiden, &amp;ldquo;he was selected for zombification years ago. For some reason it didn&amp;rsquo;t take, but ever since then he&amp;rsquo;s been a bit loopy.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Oh,&amp;rdquo; said Kate, &amp;ldquo;that&amp;rsquo;s a relief. I mean, not that he&amp;rsquo;s like that, but I was starting to wonder.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;About prophesies and destiny?&amp;rdquo; asked Braiden. &amp;ldquo;Those are just old cliches from books and movies. Scientists proved a few years ago that destiny doesn&amp;rsquo;t actually exist. It&amp;rsquo;s just mumbo-jumbo that writers use to give their plots a bit of weight. Good writers don&amp;rsquo;t have to fall back on such hackneyed methods like that. Everybody knows the best way to make a story truly interesting is to add more explosions.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Just then, the chair Braiden was sitting on exploded. Splinters scattered everywhere, and he fell to the floor, just barely avoiding getting impaled on a jagged piece of wood. A handful of change fell out of Braiden&amp;rsquo;s pockets and scattered across the hardwood floor. Everybody else in the room stood up in shock.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Are you okay?&amp;rdquo; Matt&amp;rsquo;s Aunt Kathy exclaimed.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Yes,&amp;rdquo; replied Braiden, &amp;ldquo;I&amp;rsquo;m fine. It&amp;rsquo;s just this stupid chair. It was bound to happen one of these days.&amp;rdquo; He stood up and brushed himself off. &amp;ldquo;I&amp;rsquo;ve been eating a bit too many of Amanda&amp;rsquo;s brownies, I guess. Oh, don&amp;rsquo;t worry, the chair wasn&amp;rsquo;t made by the same people that made the table.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;He said the last bit to Kate, who was staring at the shattered remains of Braiden&amp;rsquo;s chair. Reassured, she and the others sat back down. Braiden gathered up the change that was scattered on the floor and took the chair next to the pile of what was once the chair he was sitting on.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;And so the four of them - Braiden, Matt, and Matt&amp;rsquo;s Uncle Tom and Aunt Kathy - began to explain to Kate just what this little group was all about. Kate was pretty sheltered from politics and worldly affairs her whole life, so they had to give her a brief history lesson, too. It&amp;rsquo;s really unique and interesting.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;For a long time - it doesn&amp;rsquo;t matter how long - the area - it doesn&amp;rsquo;t matter what area - was under the dominion of the Government. The aforesaid Government has split the aforesaid area over the course of the aforesaid time into Districts, and then they split those Districts into Districts.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;If They had Their way,&amp;rdquo; explained Braiden, &amp;ldquo;they would split each and every one of us into our own District.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Everything wasn&amp;rsquo;t just happy Districts within Districts, however. It turns out - and this is where things get really original - the Government was actually bad. They keep taxing everybody, and then they impose ridiculous Government Mandate Zones that ration things like sandwiches and Delicious Coke.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Did you want a Coke?&amp;rdquo; Matt&amp;rsquo;s Uncle Tom interjected. &amp;ldquo;&amp;lsquo;Cause we&amp;rsquo;ve got a guy who knows a guy.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;No, I&amp;rsquo;m okay, thanks,&amp;rdquo; responded Kate.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Matt&amp;rsquo;s Family - most of them weren&amp;rsquo;t actually related, incidentally - was part of an underground resistance movement called the Underground Resistance Movement. Their big thing - aside from not coming up with a good name for themselves - was that they wanted to overthrow the Government and bring things back to the Way they were when stuff was great, like the 2010&amp;rsquo;s.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;That was the Golden Age for Humanity, Kate,&amp;rdquo; Matt&amp;rsquo;s Aunt Kathy said. &amp;ldquo;When Coke flowed like water in the 7 Elevens and the absolute best examples of Human creativity were being showcased in Tv, Movies, and especially on independently operated websites. Those were halcyon days.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;They told Kate about the dangerous Peacecorps, which patrolled the Districts hunting down anyone they deemed a troublemaker. Kate had, of course, already experienced a Peacecorps patrol as she and Matt were making their way to the very house they were now sitting in. Braiden told Kate about the high-power peace enforcement techno blasters that the Peacecorps officers carried and about how dangerous they were. He emphasized this point to really drive home the idea that the Peacecorps officers were really scary. Kate was pretty scared, and she said things like &amp;ldquo;I am scared of that&amp;rdquo; and &amp;ldquo;that&amp;rsquo;s really scary to me&amp;rdquo; to clearly indicate her terror to anybody who might have been watching her, just in case her face wasn&amp;rsquo;t expressive enough to carry the emotion on its own.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The URM were the good guys, you see, and everybody in the Government were bad guys.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;You really couldn&amp;rsquo;t write a story this good,&amp;rdquo; Matt very astutely pointed out. &amp;ldquo;Sure, it &lt;em&gt;would&lt;/em&gt; make a really great book, but it would take some sort of genius to come up with a story like this. I mean, the bad guys have guns that can shoot lightning at us. If somebody did write a book about this, it would definitely have plenty of explosions.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Just then, the chair Braiden was sitting on exploded. This chair spontaneously disassembled itself just like the first one did, and with a loud clatter a handful of change once again fell out of Braiden&amp;rsquo;s pockets. Everybody in the room stood up in alarm, but once again Braiden was fine.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;The point is,&amp;rdquo; continued Braiden as he gathered up his loose change, &amp;ldquo;we have made it our mission to get rid of all of those rich aristocrats up in that Chamber Tower.&amp;rdquo; He pointed in an arbitrary direction, as if pointing at the Government Headquarters. Kate looked where he pointed, but it was just at the blank wall. He was just making a point, not actually pointing where the tower really was.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Braiden pulled out the last chair on his side of the table and sat down. &amp;ldquo;We want to make it clear that you can join us if you want, Kate, but if you choose not to you can still stay here with us, where you&amp;rsquo;ll safe from the dangers of the Mandate Zone. We don&amp;rsquo;t expect you to put yourself in any danger if you don&amp;rsquo;t feel comfortable with it.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Kate thought about it for a moment, letting it all sink in. She looked around at all of the expectant faces looking at her, pleading at her. She thought about the ordeals she had gone through to get there. She thought about almost being captured by that Peacecorps patrol and Officer Traldo. She thought about the zombies roaming the streets. She thought about when she was attacked by bandits and how Matt rushed in to rescue her, and how even though it was really awesome it was also really scary. She was so overwhelmed by all of these new things, most of which were pretty terrifying.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;I&amp;rsquo;m sorry,&amp;rdquo; she said, &amp;ldquo;but I&amp;rsquo;m just not cut out for being a freedom fighter. You might think we don&amp;rsquo;t experience much Government Influence in District Delta, but we actually had things just as bad there. My . . .&amp;rdquo; she paused for a moment, obviously hiding a really deep and interesting backstory, &amp;ldquo;. . . family definitely met our share of Mandates. It&amp;rsquo;s not that I don&amp;rsquo;t agree with your ieas, I just . . .&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The others looked at her sympathetically.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;It&amp;rsquo;s okay, Kate,&amp;rdquo; said Matt&amp;rsquo;s Uncle Tom, &amp;ldquo;we understand.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;They all looked at each other, clearly let down by her unwillingness to help them.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;I mean,&amp;rdquo; added Kate, &amp;ldquo;I could probably help you come up with a better name, if you want.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Matt looked at Braiden with a worried look. &amp;ldquo;But how will we . . .&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;We&amp;rsquo;ll figure something out, Matt.&amp;rdquo; Braiden responded, &amp;ldquo;if Kate doesn&amp;rsquo;t want to put herself in danger just for some people she just met, we can&amp;rsquo;t blame her.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Matt&amp;rsquo;s Aunt Kathy added, &amp;ldquo;don&amp;rsquo;t you worry about it, Kate.&amp;rdquo; She was firmly supporting Kate&amp;rsquo;s decision. &amp;ldquo;Nobody will blame you for not wanting to go on some silly dangerous mission like something out of one of those great movies from the good old days. Talking about prophecies and destiny or whatever is all well and good, but let&amp;rsquo;s not forget that the real key to those stories is that they&amp;rsquo;re full of unnecessary explosions.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Just then, everybody looked at Braiden, whose chair remained fully intact. He looked up at Kate and said, &amp;ldquo;Matt&amp;rsquo;s Aunt Kathy is right. I would probably make the same choice if I were in your shoes.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;I guess I can head back out tomorrow,&amp;rdquo; said Matt, &amp;ldquo;and try to find someone else who can help us.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;It&amp;rsquo;s just such a shame,&amp;rdquo; Matt&amp;rsquo;s Uncle Tom was also saying. &amp;ldquo;She would have been so perfect.&amp;rdquo; They were really laying it on thick.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Now, now.&amp;rdquo; replied Braiden. He leaned back in his chair which responded with a slow creak. Everyone in the room held their breath for a moment. &amp;ldquo;She made her decision. Let&amp;rsquo;s not make her feel terrible about it, even if it means that all of our plans might completely fall apart and the bad Government will go on forever.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The rest of them nodded.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Well, that&amp;rsquo;s all there is to it, then,&amp;rdquo; concluded Braiden. &amp;ldquo;You might as well go try to get some rest and we&amp;rsquo;ll figure things out in the morning.&amp;rdquo; He smiled and stood, and then everybody else stood.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Matt and his Aunt and Uncle filed out of the meeting room, but Braiden stayed behind. &amp;ldquo;I&amp;rsquo;m sorry, Braiden,&amp;rdquo; said Kate as she went to the door. &amp;ldquo;Seriously, though, if you need some ideas for names . . .&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;It&amp;rsquo;s quite alright, Kate,&amp;rdquo; responded Braiden. &amp;ldquo;You go along and make yourself at home. I have to look over some of these Mandate reports from the neighboring districts.&amp;rdquo; Kate would have noticed the stack of papers earlier if it weren&amp;rsquo;t for the sheer quality of the table upon which they sat. It really was a very nice table.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Kate smiled sheepishly at Braiden and stepped out of the room, closing the door behind her. She was too absorbed in her own thoughts to notice the other girl Alice, who was standing in the kitchen glaring at her.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;As Kate was walking away, she could hear from inside the meeting room the sound of a loud crash and a handful of change clattering across the floor.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: center&quot;&gt;* * * *&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Later that night, Kate was watching more Tv with Pete and the little girls. Matt and his Aunt and Uncle had left to take care of their own various things which aren&amp;rsquo;t important to the plot. A woman entered the living area and addressed the girls. She was very motherly, and must have been either one of the girls&amp;rsquo; mother or some sort of caretaker for the group&amp;rsquo;s children.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Okay, Ashleys, it&amp;rsquo;s time for bed,&amp;rdquo; the woman said. The girls dejectedly flipped off the Tv and followed the woman down the hall and into another room.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Kate looked over at Pete, who was sound asleep in his easy chair. She wasn&amp;rsquo;t sure what to do, but felt curious about just how big this apartment was. She decided to do a bit of exploring, to figure out where Matt went.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;She got up and looked down the hall leading away from the living area. It branched off to a stairway in one direction, and a few doors in the other. Kate headed up the stairs, which led to another living area and some more doors. There was no Tv in this area, and Kate noticed that a big set of curtains covered the wall behind where the Tv was downstairs. Opening the curtain, Kate was able to see the view of the vast cityscape that was visible from this old penthouse. She stared in wonder, never having seen anything like it. Buildings seemed to stretch off forever, an amazing mosaic of sizes, shapes, and colors twinkling in the night sky all the way to the horizon. A Peacecorps patrol plane (or car) slowly drifted along an avenue below, shining its spotlight at the ground beneath it. Further in the distance Kate could see some great, long vehicle - a transit train - zipping along a rail between buildings.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;She watched this spectacle for what seemed to her like hours. Eventually she heard a voice behind one of the doors down the hall - Matt&amp;rsquo;s voice.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;She closed the curtain and walked quietly down the hall, careful to overhear what he was saying. He was talking to someone. Kate could hear a muffled voice - a woman&amp;rsquo;s voice, but not quite human.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Reaching the door, she carefully turned the knob and opened the door just a tiny bit to see inside. What she saw almost made her scream because of how shocking it was.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Are you ready for it?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Inside the dark bedroom, Matt was sitting on a dirty mattress that had no sheets or blankets. In his hand was an opened can, and he was scooping something out of it with a spoon. Just in front of him, standing ominously in the light cast by the single overhead light bulb was a female zombie.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;These should be a bit more fresh,&amp;rdquo; Matt was saying. &amp;ldquo;I just got these cans today. How is it?&amp;rdquo; He lifted the spoon to the zombie.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The beast before him was slowly swaying, staring half at Matt and half at nothing. Its clothes were a tattered mess, but Matt had obviously made some effort recently to look after them. The creature had clearly been a woman before whatever grim fate transformed it into what it was. It had long, once beautiful hair, and its slender frame must have been quite striking. Now its darkened and scarred flesh hung from its bones in a most displeasing way. It responded to him in a mixture of mumbling and grunting, and Kate couldn&amp;rsquo;t understand what it - or perhaps she - said. It wasn&amp;rsquo;t taking the spoonful of mush that Matt was offering.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Come on, you have to eat your brains.&amp;rdquo; Matt said. Finally he was able to get the zombie to take another spoonful into its mouth. It moaned in response, either approving or disapproving, Kate couldn&amp;rsquo;t tell which.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The zombie replied with another garbled sentence, but Kate could have sworn she heard the phrase, &amp;ldquo;looking for a job&amp;rdquo; Then it began reaching for Matt&amp;rsquo;s shirt. Kate was worried for a moment, and thought about trying to rush to stop this monster from attacking her new friend.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Matt sighed and calmly held the zombie&amp;rsquo;s hand. &amp;ldquo;My shirt is fine,&amp;rdquo; he said. &amp;ldquo;I&amp;rsquo;ll be able to get a job whether I tuck my shirt in or not.&amp;rdquo; He offered it another spoonful of brain mush.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Kate was very confused by what she was hearing. The zombie responded again, and this time Kate was sure it was asking Matt if he needed any money.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;I&amp;rsquo;m fine.&amp;rdquo; Matt responded, choking back a tear. &amp;ldquo;I&amp;rsquo;m just fine.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Kate carefully closed the door again, and stood stunned in the darkness. It had dawned upon her that this wasn&amp;rsquo;t just a zombie. The way Matt was speaking to it, and the way it was attempting to speak back was suddenly quite clear. Matt was sitting in that sparse, cold room, calmly spoon feeding his zombified mother.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;She realized then that this wasn&amp;rsquo;t just a fight of principal for him, this struggle against the Government. For him, this was personal. He was looking for revenge, and at that moment, Kate felt an incredible appreciation for him and his cause. She had lost both of her parents, too. It was clear to her, then, that she had to offer her help to this justified - albeit poorly named - group of freedom fighters.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;She went right down, then, to find Braiden in the meeting room and tell him that she had changed her mind. She had decided that she was going to fight to see those Government aristocrats put to justice. Also, she wanted to get another look at that table. It was a really, really nice table.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;I&amp;rsquo;m so glad to hear that, Kate,&amp;rdquo; Braiden responded. &amp;ldquo;You may very well help us save the whole world, from right here in District Alpha: Government Mandate Zone!&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;About five years ago I posted &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/post/289/&quot;&gt;pictures&lt;/a&gt; here of some alleyways and dumpsters in West Lafayette, Indiana. For some reason I am fascinated by the secrets hiding behind the scenes in urban areas. Well-kept storefronts and urban planning can spruce up a city street, but it&#039;s an artificial beauty. Garbage piles, abandoned vehicles, and dumpsters - there is no superficiality in these things. On the other hand, there&#039;s a whole underground of people who fill these spaces graffiti, just because they can. What we get is a fascinating world filled with garbage and decay that we are programmed to ignore. A city is all slight of hand, distracting us with trees and polished windows to keep us from noticing the unavoidable filth that humanity leaves behind.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;For the last year, I&#039;ve lived in the Wicker Park neighborhood of Chicago. Chicago is a much larger city than West Lafayette, and so it has a great deal more filth to hide away. I&#039;ve been meaning to capture some of it with my camera, and recently I finally did.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/wicker_park_alleys/IMG_9929.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Wicker Park is the area around Milwaukee Avenue, from about Chicago Avenue in the South to about Armitage in the North. Hundreds of stores, from expensive boutique shops that hipsters shop at to the used clothing stores they want us all to think they shop at can be found there.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/wicker_park_alleys/IMG_9834.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1199&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The intersection of Milwaukee, Damen, and North Avenues is like the center of a big, dumb hipster bike. Stupid hipsters.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/wicker_park_alleys/IMG_9798.jpg&quot; height=&quot;533&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The intersection also features quite a few back alleys.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/wicker_park_alleys/IMG_9800.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Some alleys are pretty well organized and reasonably clean.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/wicker_park_alleys/IMG_9801.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Almost any surface that isn&#039;t regularly watched for such things is covered with stickers and labels. Apparently a regular graffiti dude trick is to use stick-on labels to easily tag surfaces. A local graffiti dude called &quot;Weed Wolf&quot; really loves this trick.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/wicker_park_alleys/IMG_9865.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Here&#039;s a window right on North Avenue. Its only shelter is the scaffolding which has been set up around it for a while. I wonder what has to happen to make a surface suitable for graffiti.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/wicker_park_alleys/IMG_9803.jpg&quot; height=&quot;534&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;This dumpster says &quot;Helter Skelter.&quot; I&#039;m not sure what the point of tagging dumpsters is. Maybe that means he owns the dumpster, in graffiti dude circles, or maybe they&#039;re just trying to score as many points as possible. A dumpster certainly isn&#039;t worth that many graffiti points.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/wicker_park_alleys/IMG_9809.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Often alleys haven&#039;t been re-built or resurfaced as much as the streets that surround them. These old bricks have probably been here for a very long time.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/wicker_park_alleys/IMG_9812.jpg&quot; height=&quot;533&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;This truck probably has, too. I wonder if they put it there specifically to be graffiti&#039;d, or if it has just slowly been consumed by graffiti dudes seeking mad graffiti points.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/wicker_park_alleys/IMG_9817.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Here&#039;s a closeup of the front of the graffiti truck. Are the graffiti dudes being nice for avoiding the truck&#039;s windshield, or are they being wimps for not going for the super mega double graffiti points available there?&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/wicker_park_alleys/IMG_9815.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Chicago&#039;s Blue Line travels along Milwaukee avenue through Wicker Park, and (at least where it&#039;s above ground) it&#039;s a great place for people to stash their filth.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/wicker_park_alleys/IMG_9821.jpg&quot; height=&quot;533&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The graffiti dudes have a lot of work to do. I can spot at least six surfaces that haven&#039;t been tagged. Come on, graffiti dudes.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/wicker_park_alleys/IMG_9824.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;This is an example of the pure utility of alleyways. Nobody put that trash there for any reason, it&#039;s just where it ended up.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/wicker_park_alleys/IMG_9825.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;No care was taken to make this place look nice at all. The backs of buildings are built with the cheapest, ugliest bricks. That garbage is strewn wherever is convenient. Even the graffiti is arguably only making it look worse. Is this place beautiful because of its complete lack of beauty?&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/wicker_park_alleys/IMG_9827.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;I wonder how many times these fire escapes have been used.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/wicker_park_alleys/IMG_9830.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Anybody want that broken plastic storage box?&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/wicker_park_alleys/IMG_9835.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;These dumpsters are pretty close to the street, so they have a bit less filth scattered around them. Also, you can see some fliers posted there, trying to advertise to people who like to look closely at dumpsters.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/wicker_park_alleys/IMG_9838.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Here&#039;s a weird wood box, and an old pinstriped suit jacket.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/wicker_park_alleys/IMG_9839.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;I think that&#039;s a bum&#039;s stash there, under the tracks.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/wicker_park_alleys/IMG_9844.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Here&#039;s some strange aperture in this wall, from one of this building&#039;s pas lives. Just beyond you can see where a door used to be, replaced by bricks.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/wicker_park_alleys/IMG_9846.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;In a few places the CTA tracks are so long and straight that you get really awesome views like this. Nothing is ever built underneath the tracks.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/wicker_park_alleys/IMG_9847.jpg&quot; height=&quot;533&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;I&#039;m not sure what this building is used for anymore, but it once had a great deal of loading and unloading going on back here.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/wicker_park_alleys/IMG_9849.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;That dude got some serious graffiti points.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/wicker_park_alleys/IMG_9850.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The building seemed to be pretty empty through these back windows. It&#039;s just begging to be rebuilt into some sweet apartments.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/wicker_park_alleys/IMG_9851.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;A bit further along the tracks you can find this painting on a garage door.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/wicker_park_alleys/IMG_9855.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Here&#039;s another one of those views along the tracks, except with a fence in the way.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/wicker_park_alleys/IMG_9798.jpg&quot; height=&quot;533&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;And another one, going the other way. It just seems to go on forever.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/wicker_park_alleys/IMG_9941.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Years of street art has led to strange collages of bizarre art and torn shreds of paper on a few of the more obscure walls in the area.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/wicker_park_alleys/IMG_9870.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Fuck bitches get $.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/wicker_park_alleys/IMG_9873.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;It&#039;s strange to see something like this pile of cleanly cut tree branches in the middle of a totally urban area.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/wicker_park_alleys/IMG_9908.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Just up Damen, a vine-covered gate sits in front of this alley.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/wicker_park_alleys/IMG_9921.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;This is a small park on Damen. There aren&#039;t any dumpsters here, but you can still see the unavoidable decay of human influence. Years of people walking exactly the same way across this area has killed the grass growing there.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/wicker_park_alleys/IMG_9915.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;There&#039;s also graffiti. This graffiti dude was apparently stopped mid-tag.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/wicker_park_alleys/IMG_9912.jpg&quot; height=&quot;1200&quot; width=&quot;800&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;You only see flowers next to a sidewalk. This bush is about as artificial as you can get a plant to be. Its shape, its color, and its very presence has been carefully chosen by human hands.&lt;/div&gt;

