&lt;p&gt;My parents moved to Arcadia, Indiana a few years ago. Every summer, Arcadia has a little festival to kick off the start of summer or whatever. It&#039;s no C2E2 - in fact it&#039;s kind of the opposite - but it was a chance for me to take a few pictures on a beautiful day.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I call it the Shauvon Festival, because it&#039;s on my birthday.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/shauvonfest/IMG_0079.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Arcadia is really just a few blocks, about an hour north of Indianapolis. For Shauvonfest, people come out and put up a few booths selling, well, junk.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/shauvonfest/IMG_0065.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;At one end of town, a few (really) old cars were being shown off. They were actually pretty neat.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/shauvonfest/IMG_0067.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;There were also some old scooter things.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/shauvonfest/IMG_0068.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Inside was an old MG, which by the looks of this picture was white and had an MG badge.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/shauvonfest/IMG_0070.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Those old cars had tiny little engines, or at least compared to how big the cars are.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/shauvonfest/IMG_0073.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;This old car had a jumpseat. I had my 50mm lens, which can be a bit tough to capture shots with in close quarters.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/shauvonfest/IMG_0076.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;While we were looking at the old cars, a dude hopped into this car (after winding up the engine) and drove off. Right on, dude.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/shauvonfest/IMG_0077.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Down the way was a Native American looking dude selling mostly tie dye t-shirts. Also this t-shirt.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/shauvonfest/IMG_0080.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Another tent had this bucket of $1.00 swords.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/shauvonfest/IMG_0082.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Indiana.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/shauvonfest/IMG_0087.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Yet another tent was selling some dime-store rings. The theme for Shauvonfest is &quot;People in Arcadia love buying whatever random crap you want to sell&quot;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/shauvonfest/IMG_0090.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Somebody get this guy some &quot;O&quot;s - and one &quot;C&quot;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/shauvonfest/IMG_0091.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The lady working the food trailer was selling more different items than there were people at Shauvonfest. Also, and I&#039;m not passing any judgement here, she had a pretty serious mustache. I tried to see what kind of Hot Dog roller she had in there, but I couldn&#039;t see one. Total amateur hour.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/shauvonfest/IMG_0093.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Cornhole is still a thing?&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/shauvonfest/IMG_0094.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Uncle Gary is serious about his Kettle Corn booth.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/shauvonfest/IMG_0096.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The World&#039;s Cheapest Carnival Ride was pretty popular.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/shauvonfest/IMG_0099.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Eventually a couple rambunctious youths rode by on their bicycles. This particular youth obviously thought two wheels was one too many.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/shauvonfest/IMG_0103.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;If you like things depicting wolves, you had a few options.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/shauvonfest/IMG_0120.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Like this pretty awesome shirt.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/shauvonfest/IMG_0105.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;There was even a band. I don&#039;t know what they were called, but it was probably something like &quot;Midge and Boys.&quot;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/shauvonfest/IMG_0107.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Here you can see a dude who brought a little wagon with him to carry all the sweet junk he was hoping to find at the &#039;fest.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/shauvonfest/IMG_0111.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;What leads a man to sell Pimp Hats at little town festivals? I mean, the pot leaf dream catcher is totally awesome, but is there really a market for pimp hats anymore?&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/shauvonfest/IMG_0115.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;This was literally just a junk table.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/shauvonfest/IMG_0117.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Alyson was a bit creeped out by a pile of furs and other dead animal parts.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/shauvonfest/IMG_0122.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;These minerals and jewelry seemed pretty legitimate. The guy behind the table was talking to somebody and I heard him say that he would &quot;never sell plastic.&quot;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/shauvonfest/IMG_0127.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The piece de resistance was this guy with almost an entire block of tables covered in old toys and hundreds of pictures of Marilyn Monroe.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/shauvonfest/IMG_0123.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;It was almost impressive just how completely D-list his toy collection was.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/shauvonfest/IMG_0126.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;He was a pretty nice guy, though. Crazy, but nice.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/shauvonfest/IMG_0128.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;A few houses around town wanted to join in the junk sale fun, so they put some of their own junk out on the lawn for passers by to pick through. I guess somebody just didn&#039;t want these old shirts anymore&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Welcome to DenyConformity.com, a &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/post/389/DenyConformity.com_Redesign_Journal_part_4&quot;&gt;really interesting website place&lt;/a&gt;!&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/about_logo.jpg&quot; class=&quot;noprint&quot; /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;DenyConformity.com uses a unique site design that - aside from making it &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/post/376/Ads_on_DenyConformity.com&quot;&gt;ineligible&lt;/a&gt; for Google Ads - makes it (hopefully) easy and fast to use. The main page is structured like a timeline, so you can get a quick view of the content that has been posted recently, and so you can see posts dating back to the before-times. Also, the site takes advantage of modern browsers so you can always hit &quot;back&quot; and &quot;forward&quot; to navigate just as you would any other site. Posts on DenyConformity.com are categorized by a number of tags, which you can use to see similarly tagged content. Use the tags page (with the link at the top of the site) to see every tag on the site, or click on an individual tag at the bottom of any post to see all the posts with that tag.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;DenyConformity.com is &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/post/367/All_new_for_2012&quot;&gt;currently&lt;/a&gt; in Beta, which means that stuff might not work right. If something doesn&#039;t work like you think it should, report it to &lt;a href=&quot;mailto:beta@denyconformity.com&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;beta@denyconformity.com&lt;/a&gt; with a description of what you were trying to do.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A dude called Shauvon McGill started this website 2005 as a place to write about non-conformity. It quickly became a stupid place where he posted the uninteresting rants of an angst-y college student. More recently he has written much more interesting stuff. It&#039;s not dumb, now, I promise.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Shauvon is interested in Comedy, Photography, Fiction, Technology, and Ideas. Most of the stuff he posts here will fit into one of those categories. Check back daily (mostly) for content ranging from discussions of computer games to satire to beautiful (mostly) photographs - which are all available for sale, by the way - to original hand-drawn web comics.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The only goal of DenyConformity.com is to be an interesting website place. If you&#039;ve been able to kill a few minutes of your day looking at cool pictures or reading a dumb thing and you don&#039;t think it was a complete waste of your time, DenyConformity.com has succeeded. If there&#039;s ever anything you&#039;d like to read about or anything, feel free to make a request by sending an email to &lt;a href=&quot;mailto:requests@denyconformity.com&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;requests@denyconformity.com&lt;/a&gt; or by making a comment down below.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Your continued support is greatly appreciated. Shauvon doesn&#039;t get much out of this other than the satisfaction of being able to entertain people. If you have enjoyed something you saw here, you might consider buying a print of a picture or purchasing an ad on the site. Above all, though, the best thing you can do is share the site with your friends (we&#039;ll even take enemies). It&#039;s really appreciated.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;There&#039;s this thing called the Color Run. It happens in a bunch of cities all over the country, and just this past weekend it happened in Chicago. It also happens that it&#039;s one of the coolest things ever.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It&#039;s just a regular old 5k, except that at predetermined locations along the route, a team of people toss colored powder at you. Everybody (there are thousands of runners) starts perfectly clean, and ends up completely covered in bright colors. It&#039;s truly amazing, and you should go check right now to see if it&#039;s coming to a city near you. Seriously, go to the &lt;a href=&quot;http://thecolorrun.com/&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;website&lt;/a&gt; right now. I&#039;ll wait. It will be an experience you will never forget.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So Alyson ran the thing and I brought my camera. I wrapped it up in a garbage bag ahead of time to try to protect it from being color blasted, in case you worry about that.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/colorrun/IMG_0134.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;I made sure I knew where the Yellow station was (it&#039;s my favorite color), and it just happened to be nearby the starting line (the route was sort of clothespin-shaped). The buckets full of powder looked pretty exciting.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/colorrun/IMG_0136.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The website said that they were going to let off groups of 1000 runners every five minutes for an hour. That&#039;s a lot of runners.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/colorrun/IMG_0143.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The website also said to wear as much white as possible. These lightning-bolt people were pretty neat (though you&#039;ll soon see that it surely didn&#039;t make much difference), but a lot of people thought it would be neat to wear colorful socks or other secondary clothes. That really defeats the purpose.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/colorrun/IMG_0149.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;These Blues Brothers (emphasis on the &#039;blue&#039;) were there to warm up the crowd waiting to kick off at the starting line. The atmosphere at the starting line was really great - like a dance party.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/colorrun/IMG_0150.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Here&#039;s a group setting off. You can see some of the colorful socks there, which I don&#039;t think was a good idea. You can also see a few sunglasses, which is probably a really great idea.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/colorrun/IMG_0176.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;It was a few minutes before any runners showed up at the yellow station. The first few people came through really quickly, like they were just there to run or something. Why you would come to this thing just to run, I have no idea.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/colorrun/IMG_0192.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The people posted at the yellow station had little things like mustard bottles which they used to squirt nice little streams of yellow powder. You can see one just to the left, in this shot.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/colorrun/IMG_0205.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;I think they were told not to aim at the face, but obviously they bent that rule a bit.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/colorrun/IMG_0207.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;There was, of course, collateral damage on the color team. This guy was really enjoying himself. You really can&#039;t blame him.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/colorrun/IMG_0215.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The powder is apparently just cornstarch. The air tasted like cornstarch every time a group of runners came by.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/colorrun/IMG_0221.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;This girl had a sweet X on her face, which was apparently just about to be transformed into an asterisk.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/colorrun/IMG_0226.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The best runners were obviously enjoying the Hell out of it. It has to be the most fun.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/colorrun/IMG_0229.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The color blasters were excited, which really excited the runners, and that made the blasters even more excited. It was pretty exciting. Everybody was having an awesome, colorful time.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/colorrun/IMG_0235.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;There was a bit of a breeze, which helped clear out the clouds.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/colorrun/IMG_0236.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The problem with following the &quot;no faces&quot; rule is that then you just end up color blasting dudes in the junk. Maybe this girl liked that part, though.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/colorrun/IMG_0238.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Everybody ends the race looking different, and it really is awesome to see the different blasts of color, and what must have happened to cause them.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/colorrun/IMG_0239.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;How about this dude? The explosion in the background is from the color blasters getting bored with their little spray bottles and just dumping what&#039;s left of those buckets full of powder on unsuspecting runners.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/colorrun/IMG_0246.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;There were quite a few kids there, and a few mothers even ran the thing with a toddler in a stroller. I&#039;m not sure how I feel about that, but the babies always seem pretty into it, and nobody was dumb enough to dump a bucket of powder on one.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/colorrun/IMG_0254.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;They handed those number things out sequentially. This girl was the 7,916th person to check in.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;That&#039;s the first half of my pictures. Next week I&#039;ll post the rest. Again, do this thing. If you aren&#039;t a runner (like me) just go and hang out. It&#039;s one of those things that&#039;s unlike anything you&#039;ll ever do. Just be sure you&#039;re prepared to be covered in corn starch.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Somehow my email address was signed up for this &amp;ldquo;Apartment Guide&amp;rdquo; newsletter, which basically just sends me random garbage about apartments pretty much every day. I totally don&amp;rsquo;t need that, since I&amp;rsquo;m already an apartment expert. Apparently it&amp;rsquo;s totally cool to post articles about how to Apartment better, so it&amp;rsquo;s time for me to chime in.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Of particular interest is this &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.movingtoday.com/take-steps-to-stay-organized-in-your-apartment/?WT.mc_id=32706&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;article&lt;/a&gt; &amp;ldquo;Take Steps to Stay Organized in Your Apartment&amp;rdquo; which came to me today. I haven&amp;rsquo;t read that article, but I am sure I can come up with a better guide to keeping your apartment organized. For your consideration, I give you my version of that guide (with some marginally relevant pictures I dug up from my archives).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h5&gt;How to Keep Your Apartment Organized&lt;br /&gt;
or, &lt;em&gt;Don&amp;rsquo;t Put That There&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/h5&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/apt_organized/IMG_8417.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;An example of an unorganized apartment. In my defense, most of it was caused by the cat. That little dude never picks up after himself.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It&amp;rsquo;s your apartment. Ultimately, you can do whatever you want. Let&amp;rsquo;s just face the facts, though - hot babes do not want to come hang out in a slob&amp;rsquo;s trash-pile. Cool Dudes are not going to want to chill in an unorganized apartment. If you ever want to run for President - and who doesn&amp;rsquo;t, come on - they will know that you had an unorganized apartment, and when the media gets a hold of that you&amp;rsquo;re done for.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;There&amp;rsquo;s a basic instinct in all of us to avoid unorganized situations. Why do you think we started building houses in the first place? We did it to get the Hell out of Nature. Nature is pretty unorganized. In fact, Nature should really read this guide. You should probably print a few copies of this guide out and staple them to some trees outside. It wouldn&amp;rsquo;t hurt.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/apt_organized/IMG_0137.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;How disorganized.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Anyway, the point is that nobody wants to be with you if you aren&amp;rsquo;t organized. I&amp;rsquo;m not your Mom or anything, I&amp;rsquo;m not going to tell you how to live your life. I&amp;rsquo;m just telling you that people are going to constantly judge you. Here are some tips for you, if you feel like getting off your butt and not putting your garbage just any old place. Unlike some other guides out there, though, this guide will actually help you &amp;ldquo;turn over a new leaf&amp;rdquo; (I&amp;rsquo;m looking at you, Nature) and maintain a more organized apartment - not just for this year, but maybe even into the next.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Don&amp;rsquo;t put that there.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Seriously, that thing doesn&amp;rsquo;t go there. Just put it away now, while it&amp;rsquo;s in your hand. If you put it there, you&amp;rsquo;ll just have to make more of an effort later because you&amp;rsquo;ll have to pick it back up and then put it away. Just put it away now, and you&amp;rsquo;ll be done with it. I mean, unless wherever that thing goes is kind of hard to get to and your favorite show is on TV. You can put it away later.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/apt_organized/IMG_5771.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Some things - lids to hamster cages, for instance - should definitely be put where they belong.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Leave your door open at night.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This might seem counter-intuitive. Sure, initially you&amp;rsquo;ll have some cleanup to take care of, but you&amp;rsquo;ll be really surprised how being robbed can make it much easier to organize your place. Okay, so you can try to sell some stuff on Craigslist or something, but that just takes so long and you have to talk to people. Just get yourself robbed and you&amp;rsquo;ll cut down how much stuff you have really quickly.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/apt_organized/IMG_8076.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;These are actual burglar&#039;s fingerprints.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Fire.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;If you find that you have some areas that just seem to &amp;ldquo;attract&amp;rdquo; clutter, just throw a couple lit matches in the pile and watch as your problems take care of themselves. You might stand by with a bucket of water or something just in case the fire spreads to something you don&amp;rsquo;t want to get rid of, like the walls or the floor. Nothing says &amp;ldquo;unorganized&amp;rdquo; like not having a floor.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/apt_organized/IMG_0785.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Guns don&amp;rsquo;t really work quite as well (nor do tires).&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Designate a &amp;ldquo;garbage room.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This is why I like to get an apartment with one more bedroom than I need. Now when you see some clutter or disorder, just scoop it up in your arms and toss it into your spare room. It can help to have a friend quickly open and close the door for you, so you don&amp;rsquo;t get buried in your own organization technique. You don&amp;rsquo;t want to end up like a cartoon.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/apt_organized/IMG_8097.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Stay in there. I have company coming over.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Lie to yourself / others.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The easiest way to deal with an unorganized apartment is to just redefine the term &amp;ldquo;unorganized.&amp;rdquo; Try out the following handy mantras on yourself next time you find yourself questioning your organization:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;font-style: italic&quot;&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Look, the reason you put things where you put them is because it&amp;rsquo;s easier. Convenience is the whole point of organization, isn&amp;rsquo;t it?&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;What do you mean? That&amp;rsquo;s where that thing goes.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Hey, look, Mythbusters is on.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Sure, that thing is in the way. We could put it away, or we could play some video games.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;It&amp;rsquo;s just that we&amp;rsquo;re out of matches.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This technique works almost as well on others, too. When your friends come over, or you have some special lady company, just tell them something like:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&amp;ldquo;I know, I kind of hate it, too. It&amp;rsquo;s just that I&amp;rsquo;ve been reading these books about ancient Chinese mysticism, and apparently this is best for the energy of the space.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&amp;ldquo;What do you mean? That&amp;rsquo;s where that thing goes.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&amp;ldquo;Oh, like your place is any better.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&amp;ldquo;I actually just moved in, so I&amp;rsquo;m still unpacking.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&amp;ldquo;I&amp;rsquo;m in a feud with the garbage man right now, so he&amp;rsquo;s refusing to take any of it. I can either leave it in here or down on the street where identity thieves and raccoons are going to get into it.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&amp;ldquo;I&amp;rsquo;m getting ready for a yard sale. You want that? Dollar fifty.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/apt_organized/IMG_6195.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Those are my roommate&amp;rsquo;s, I swear.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Stop seeking motivation from the Internet.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Honestly, this place - the Internet - is only for distracting you from your problems. Why are you sitting there reading that instead of just putting stuff away. You aren&amp;rsquo;t going to magically get an email that cleans your room. That&amp;rsquo;s why your parents made you do it when you were a kid - so you&amp;rsquo;d get into the habit. You know what? No more Internet until you finish your chores.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Seriously. We&amp;rsquo;re done. Clean your room.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/apt_organized/IMG_6742.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Then shovel the sidewalk.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A while ago, I received this weird letter in the mail. It was from a company called &quot;Univox Corporation,&quot; and it seemed to be hand typed. I had no idea what to make of it, but I just came across it in one of my desk drawers, and I thought I would post it here to share in the mystery.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I have reproduced it for you, typos and all.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div style=&quot;font-family: courier new, courier; width: 90%; margin: auto;&quot;&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/univox/univox_1.jpg&quot; style=&quot;float: left; margin-bottom: 10px&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;float: right; font-family: Times new roman, times, serif; font-style: italic; text-align: right&quot;&gt;
1446 W. Irving Park Road &lt;br /&gt;
Chicago, Illinois 60613 &lt;br /&gt;
(312) 588-2300
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div style=&quot;clear: both; width: 100%; border-top: 1px solid #666; height: 2px; margin: 20px 0&quot;&gt; &lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Dear valued customer,&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;text-indent: 5em&quot;&gt;It&#039;s the financial year-end inventory clearance season here at Univox, and we have our festive liquidation hats on. THAT MEANS SAVINGS! We&#039;ve been Chicagoland&#039;s #1 UNIX Systems Distributor for over 75 years, and we didn&#039;t get here hosing you like those thieves at Gary&#039;s Tabulators and Adding Machines on 1901 W. Madison.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;text-indent: 5em&quot;&gt;Our 6300 Series Mainframes come with freeinstallation and no money down! Featuring the latest versions of Solaris, HP-UX, and OpenSUSE, the 6300 can even be used with a monitor when configured to use the cutting edge X Windows System. Our code comes pre-compiled and ready to get the job done. Connect to USENET, BBS, ICQ, and Webs 1.0 and 2.0 with our exclusive ISDN service. When you need a computer that fills the room, the 6300 Series Mainframe from Univox gets it done. No money down and financingrates have never been better, 2.9% APR.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;text-indent: 5em&quot;&gt;We&#039;re the only mainframe distributor that lets you shop at home, wkth free samples in your home, and one of our experienced service technicians, with over 350 years of comined installatuin experience on all types of floors, including carpet, wood, laminate vinyl, and tile. (Even on Pergo and Bellawood, availalbe at UNIVOX Discount Flooring Warehouse, 3319 N. Lincoln Ave.)&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;text-indent: 5em&quot;&gt;So whether you&#039;re making a family newsletter you can print on one of our many dot matrix printers, or ironing out the kinks of te interstage on your Teller-Ulam thermonuclear device, you can count on Univox Mainframes and Tele-Terminals. Follow us on Facebook with terminal command &#039;wget http://192.775.22.09/fb/like.js &amp;&amp; ./thumsup.js&#039; and plug your printer into our twitter feed at ///:LPD.192.775.22.09:9100 @univoxcomputrons.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Yours Truly,&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/univox/moinet_sig.jpg&quot; style=&quot;margin: 0; margin-left: 20px; text-align: left; float: none&quot; /&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Danielle Moinet, CEO&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Pretty weird. The address supplied is just some house. It definitely doesn&#039;t look like the sort of place that would supply anything called a &quot;mainframe.&quot; Some time later, a second letter arrived, this time printed like an old-fashioned dot-matrix print.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div style=&quot;font-family: courier new, courier, sans-serif; width: 90%; margin: auto;&quot;&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/univox/univox_2.jpg&quot; style=&quot;float: left; margin-bottom: 10px&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;float: right; font-family: Times new roman, times, serif; font-style: italic; text-align: center&quot;&gt;
1446 W. Irving Park Road &lt;br /&gt;
Chicago, Illinois 60613 &lt;br /&gt;
(312) 588-2300
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div style=&quot;clear: both; width: 100%; border-top: 1px dashed #666; height: 2px; margin: 20px 0&quot;&gt; &lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Dear Univox Customer,&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;text-indent: 2em&quot;&gt;We hope you are enjoying your recently installed 6399 Minecraft Mainframe. We hope you have also noticed our brand-new, 100% computerized letterhead, and you may not believe it, but this proportionally spaced text is also produced by one of our state-of-the-art word processors. The time has never been better to fire that secretary and sell the typewriter, especially with this amazing savings event!&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;All of our word-processing capable computers are on sale! With price reductions of over 50% (Apple II only) it&#039;s big savings season here at Univox. Finally, you can correct your typographical errors with a single keystroke! Let potential employers know how computer-savoir-faire you really are with a cyber-tronic cover letter and resume! What was once the science-fiction dreams of rich men and kings can now be yours with one visit to our showroom.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;If you act now, we will throw in a free ream! That&#039;s right, a whole 500 sheets of Univox Brand Computer Printer Paper! You could write a book, you could find that lost dog you&#039;ve been looking for, you can advertise your blues-rock trio&acirc;€™s upcoming gig. The possibilities are endless with Univox and paper.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;text-indent: 2em&quot;&gt;Getcha on over here,&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/univox/mannheim_sig.jpg&quot; style=&quot;margin: 0; margin-left: 30px; text-align: left; float: none&quot; /&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-indent: 2em&quot;&gt;Darla Mannheim, Sales Director&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Very weird. The whole thing remained a mystery for a while (I&#039;m a bit iffy on the timing of the whole thing, since it was so long ago). In fact, as memory serves, I basically forgot about the whole Univox mystery. I put the letters in some drawer (where I found them just now), and went about my business.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Then I was headed from Lafayette, Indiana up to Chicago with a couple dudes, and we stopped at John Schuster&#039;s house in Valparaiso, Indiana. We were hanging out for a bit, and John went off to do something, so Andrew and I decided to check out his room. Sitting on a desk next to an old fashioned typewriter was a few papers - with the familiar &quot;Univox Corporation&quot; letterhead. The mystery was solved.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The sad thing is that I actually could use some Mainframe computers. It took a few months, but I got my revenge...&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Hopefully by now you&#039;ve looked up your nearest and soonest Color Run and signed up for it on the Color Run website. Please find enclosed additional pictures to make you excited for the cool thing you&#039;ll be doing.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/colorrun/IMG_0261.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;After a while, the air became pretty thick with yellow dust.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/colorrun/IMG_0264.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;It was actually a bit tough to photograph. Aside from the obvious concerns of dust getting in and on the camera, the thick air made it difficult to properly focus, and substantially reduced the sunlight. Luckily it was a beautiful day, so there was still plenty of light and a cool breeze blew the dust away pretty quickly.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/colorrun/IMG_0267.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;This picture, for example, is unfortunately focused on the arms spraying powder instead of the arms groping blindly through the yellow cloud. I still like this picture, though, for some reason.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/colorrun/IMG_0269.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;I believe the spray bottle developed a clog, and so this color blaster just took the top off and went to town. I&#039;m not sure which way this runner is facing.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/colorrun/IMG_0278.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Whenever a group of runners approached, the people at the yellow station began shouting things like, &quot;they aren&#039;t colorful enough!&quot; or, &quot;they have too much green on them!&quot; It was a fun tongue in cheek hostility.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/colorrun/IMG_0286.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;It&#039;s kind of gross, but you could easily tell which people were more sweaty than others, and where.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/colorrun/IMG_0292.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The green station was right before the yellow one. They must have been absolutely crazy, because almost everybody we saw was quite green. It really motivated the yellow blasters to up their game.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/colorrun/IMG_0298.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;In the background you can see someone who is very green. In the foreground you can see the girl who will soon change that.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/colorrun/IMG_0303.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;This guy was really fun. Still.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/colorrun/IMG_0308.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Something about this girl apparently made everybody only want to color blast her head and shoulders.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/colorrun/IMG_0317.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;I just didn&#039;t get the people who seemed completely uninterested in the whole thing. This guy didn&#039;t even seem to notice.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/colorrun/IMG_0342.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Yet more proof of the green team&#039;s handiwork.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/colorrun/IMG_0348.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;It was way better when the runners were having fun.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/colorrun/IMG_0354.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;When one big group went by, this girl started just jumping around flinging dust everywhere. It was pretty epic.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/colorrun/IMG_0359.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;It was like watching an action movie to see all of these runners emerge from a billowing explosion of color.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/colorrun/IMG_0369.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Sometimes you can&#039;t help but smile at some people. Then you get a mouthful of cornstarch. It&#039;s basically a win-win.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/colorrun/IMG_0376.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Here are a couple more pictures of this serious chick.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/colorrun/IMG_0381.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;You can see just how completely the world was shrouded in dust.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/colorrun/IMG_0383.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Those bottles had some pretty good range. Eventually, though, the pathway was completely covered in a solid inch of dust - about half-way through the whole event.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Unfortunately I can only take so many pictures before I run out of space, and I was nervous about taking my camera out of the garbage bag cover I had fashioned, so I just had to call it quits. We met up with Alyson, who was pretty well covered with color, and found our way to the finish line ceremony. Each runner was given a pouch of color. You can probably spot them in some of my pictures. They were all sorts of colors, not just the basic blue, red, green, and yellow of the course. At the finishing line, a huge group of people gathered - probably four hundred by the time we made our way there. Suddenly the call went out, and everybody tore open their pouches and flung the contents in the air. It was an incredible 45 seconds. Afterwords everybody was a tableau of random colors. It was definitely one of the coolest things I&#039;ve ever been a part of.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Maybe you&#039;ve seen some of these silly &quot;spell out things with pictures&quot; items you can get from &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.skymall.com/shopping/detail.htm?pid=204249468&amp;c=&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Skymall&lt;/a&gt; or whatever. I didn&#039;t think much about them when I&#039;ve seen them before, but it recently occurred to me that I could be making them and selling them for fat stacks.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I spent the better part of today running around downtown Chicago trying to build a library of letter pictures. The idea is that you take pictures of architecture and inanimate objects that look like different letters of the alphabet. Then you can spell out your last name or your favorite word or something and hang it in your game room or office. How hard can it be?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/picture_letters/i.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;What letter looks like a penis?&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It&#039;s actually more challenging than you might think. I figured that some letters would be easier to find in the wild than others. Plenty of windows look like an &quot;E.&quot; Street lamps and plenty of other things look like &quot;I&#039;s.&quot; The thing is, though, that in practice it&#039;s kind of hard to get decent versions of those shapes. The real toughies were &quot;G&quot; &quot;B&quot; &quot;J&quot; and &quot;C.&quot; It turns out that those shapes aren&#039;t very common without looking more like other letters instead.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/picture_letters/g.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;I was worried I wouldn&#039;t find a &quot;G&quot; until I came across this little squiggle.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Ultimately, it was a really fun little project, and I especially enjoyed taking strange closeup pictures of random things and then pulling out my little notebook to make note of which letters I&#039;d captured. Finding a perfect example of a letter is pretty exciting, and finally coming across a letter  I had trouble finding is genuinely satisfying. The best way to go is to just keep your eyes peeled for any familiar shapes. Don&#039;t just search for one letter at a time. It&#039;s definitely much more exciting and faster to just get whatever letters you find.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/picture_letters/q.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Q was a fun one to find.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;You should give it a shot some time. If you know somebody for whom this sort of thing would make a good gift, spend an afternoon trying to get some pictures together. It will save you the cost of a dumb Skymall item, and it will challenge your creative side.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Or, if you&#039;re lazy or don&#039;t have the photographic skills to do it or you don&#039;t live in Chicago, you could buy one from me! Send an email to &lt;a href=&quot;mailto:photo@denyconformity.com&quot;&gt;photo@denyconformity.com&lt;/a&gt; if you&#039;re interested. I&#039;m serious. Does anybody know how to start an Etsy store?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Here&#039;s one I put together for myself. What do you think?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/picture_letters/deny.jpg&quot; /&gt;

&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/picture_letters/conformity.jpg&quot; /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Last week I posted a couple letters I received from some strange company called Univox Corporation (&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/post/432/What_is_Univox_Corporation&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;What is Univox Corporation?&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt;). Well, I found out that they came from my old friend John. I was the subject of some weird prank trying to get me to go to a random address in Chicago looking for computer mainframes and looking the fool. Revenge was in order. I decided to respond in kind.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;While at some consignment / used clothing / junk store, I found an old back-issue of PC Magazine - from the late 90&amp;rsquo;s. It was full of articles and ads talking about really old computer stuff that&amp;rsquo;s so obsolete now it&amp;rsquo;s actually a joke. At least, I hoped it would make for a pretty good joke. I knew it would be the perfect random thing to send to my friends at Univox, so I mailed it to John, along with a letter. In the interest of continuing my series on &amp;ldquo;I have nothing to write about so I&amp;rsquo;m just digging up random stuff out of my drawers&amp;rdquo; I have transcribed the letter below.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div style=&quot;width: 90%; margin: auto; text-indent: 3em&quot;&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Danielle Moinet&lt;br /&gt;
Univox Corporation&lt;br /&gt;
1446 W. Irving Park Road&lt;br /&gt;
Chicago, IL 60613&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/univox/futech_logo.jpg&quot; /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Subject: NEW TECHNOLOGISTICS&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Do you have time and money just laying around to waste on any old thing?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The future sure comes on quickly, and the rest of us must struggle to catch up. All you have to do is blink a few times and you suddenly see a new server terminal interface module or a high-baud network protocol. The world is surely a minefield of microchips and capacitirons, and we&#039;re living on the razor&#039;s edge between technologistics that catapault us into the profit zone and those that leave you with no enough space for your PCI option ROM. What you need is a rudder to guide you through the silicone sea. We here at FUTECH LOGISTICS are that rudder.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Our expert team of LOGISTICS MAXIMIZERS will analyze every aspect of your educational outreach program and your upward dynamic revenue synergy. Then they determine exactly the perfect machine type for each of your departments. Most companies settle for a single computer mainframe for the entire staff. At FUTECH LOGISTICS, we envision &acirc;€“ as I hope you do &acirc;€“ a future containing three or even four computers for every man, woman, and child on your EXTREMELY PROFITABLE team.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;We have helped many businesses succeed where others have failed. Using our expert knowledge, our clients don&#039;t waste their time and money buying just any old thing. I ask again: do you have time and money to waste on any old thing? Don&#039;t be like the other guys. Be like the guys of the future. BE FUTECH LOGISTICS GUYS.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;To prove that we &amp;ldquo;know our stuff&amp;rdquo; (one of our many slogans and catch-phrases), I have attached just one of the many super-modern tech magazines that we often have just laying about the office. Inside you&#039;ll find many bizz-words which we use as our bread and butter. Is that stuff intimidating? Don&#039;t be! It&#039;s our job to help you GET HER FINISHED.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Please consider us in the coming business cycle as you decide on your technologistic needs.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Samantha Standles&lt;br /&gt;
Marketing Manager, Futech Logistics&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Is this the last we&amp;rsquo;ll hear of these two technology companies? Will Univox Corporation and Futech Logistics work out a deal? Only time will tell.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Once, when I was a kid, my Dad took me to a gun range. We went with another guy and his kid - their family was sort of friends with my family or whatever. We had an old .22, the other dad had a huge-ass muzzle-loader, and there was some sort of medium-caliber revolver. I don&amp;rsquo;t remember much about the afternoon, other than that the muzzle-loader was pretty terrifying. I fired the .22 a few times, and I gave the revolver a try, but generally I was a pretty scared kid who didn&amp;rsquo;t like doing things that could easily murder somebody. I haven&amp;rsquo;t changed a whole lot, but I kind of want to go back to a shooting range to fire a gun again. Mainly because I don&amp;rsquo;t remember what they sound like in person.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The point is, I totally just heard a few gunshots outside. Admittedly I am not sure what gunshots sound like, but movies have taught me that they can be pretty varied. All I know is that, just now, outside, there was this &lt;em&gt;pop pop pop&lt;/em&gt; sound, like three tiny explosions. It happened all in a row, like one, two, three. I mean, that&amp;rsquo;s totally gunshots, right?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The problem is that it was kind of nice out today, not like the sweltering heat that we&amp;rsquo;ve been having. I&amp;rsquo;ve been worried about the power bill from all this AC action, so I had my window open. That&amp;rsquo;s how I was able to hear this sound so clearly. I bet somebody had a score to settle, and he wanted to take advantage of this nice weather to come on over and settle said score. That is just the sort of calculating individual who would make sure there are no witnesses. I&amp;rsquo;m not completely sure, but I might just count as a witness that needs to be silenced. Don&amp;rsquo;t tell anybody I told you about this, seriously.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I know the Fourth of July just happened. Perhaps they were fireworks, you might posit. Look, you - the Fourth of July was like a week ago. I don&amp;rsquo;t know much about people who launch fireworks in urban areas, but they totally seem like the sort that would get bored easily, so they&amp;rsquo;re certainly on to other crazy illegal things that the police won&amp;rsquo;t do anything about. Not only that, but I know what fireworks sound like. This was not like any firework. There was no fizzle. There was no sizzle. I heard no sparks, nor did I hear any report of a launcher or something like that. Also, there&amp;rsquo;s the fact that there were three of them, in quick succession. Like, it was just &amp;ldquo;blam, blam, blam&amp;rdquo; and then nothing. Who would light three fireworks at once and then do nothing else? I don&amp;rsquo;t know, but I do know that three bullets would totally be enough to settle a score.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I wasn&amp;rsquo;t really paying much attention before the sound, because I was busy looking at the Internet and I don&amp;rsquo;t usually pay much attention to the out-of-doors. However, now that I think about it I think there was actually a scream or shouting or something before the sound. I think I heard a guy shouting, possibly saying something like &amp;ldquo;take it easy bro, let&amp;rsquo;s work this out!&amp;rdquo; I didn&amp;rsquo;t actually hear anybody say that, and I&amp;rsquo;m not totally sure what somebody would really say when a guy is all up on them looking to settle a score, but movies teach me it would be something like that. It was one of those things that I normally wouldn&amp;rsquo;t have thought much about, but then I heard some sounds that were totally gunshots so now I think it must have been a guy yelling. I mean, at the time it sounded like maybe just a car revving, but it could also have been a guy yelling.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I&amp;rsquo;m not totally sure what&amp;rsquo;s going on now, because I can&amp;rsquo;t hear much when I&amp;rsquo;m crammed in between these coats. Needless to say, when I work up the courage to come out of my closet here and try to check the police blotter for info about a score settling gun crime in my area, I&amp;rsquo;ll definitely post the whys and wherefores of the whole thing. On the other hand, it&amp;rsquo;s actually pretty comfortable in here. I have some shoes piled up like a little butt pillow, and these coats aren&amp;rsquo;t bad to lean against. Maybe I&amp;rsquo;ll just spend the night in here.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Oh crap, I should probably have closed that window . . .&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So a lot of talk has been going around about supposed &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/post/439/Opinion_Those_Were_Totally_Gunshots_Just_Now&quot;&gt;sounds&lt;/a&gt; out back and theories about what those sounds were. Sure, we could knock around ideas all day about what we think about this or that sound, but where would that get us? The fact is that there are sounds all the time, and it just doesn&amp;rsquo;t make sense to try to categorize and place each and every one of them. I mean, so what if something outside kind of sounds like it might be, oh, I don&amp;rsquo;t know, gunshots or something, you know? That&amp;rsquo;s just distracting us from the real issue - namely, do you want to order a pizza or something?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I know a pretty good place, or we could Yelp it if you want to try something new. I&amp;rsquo;m totally up for whatever. I&amp;rsquo;m actually pretty hungry - I didn&amp;rsquo;t have much of a dinner last night and I skipped breakfast. You know how it is, sometimes you get really busy and you just don&amp;rsquo;t realize where the time went. It&amp;rsquo;s not really important what I had for dinner last night. Come on, It&amp;rsquo;s not like I only had some old nip chees that were in a jacket pocket in the closet. That would just be weird, man. It was some captain&amp;rsquo;s wafers.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;That&amp;rsquo;s neither here nor there, though. Oh, hey, maybe we could play some Xbox. Do you want to order a pizza and play some Xbox? I&amp;rsquo;ve been playing this one game lately. You play as an undercover cop working in a really dangerous neighborhood. I get pretty into it, but it&amp;rsquo;s really intense. In the game there are these two gangs that are at war, and sometimes dudes will just start shooting at each other out of nowhere and . . . you know what, let&amp;rsquo;s not play that game. Man, I haven&amp;rsquo;t fired up Viva Pinata in a while.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;We&amp;rsquo;re going to have to move the couch really quick, actually. Oh, I was doing some redecorating. I just wanted to see how the room looked if I moved stuff around a bit. I&amp;rsquo;ve been reading up on feng shui lately. You know, feng shui, where sometimes if you pile up a bunch of furniture in front of the back door and windows it charges the room with positive energy. You don&amp;rsquo;t feel that energy? Well, we can put it back for now, anyway. I guess the couch is better in front of the TV. I guess they didn&amp;rsquo;t have TV&amp;rsquo;s back when they invented feng shui, huh?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Let&amp;rsquo;s just order a pizza then, yeah? We can do it online. It&amp;rsquo;s really easy. Just ignore my other browser tabs. I like to check in on the local news sometimes. It&amp;rsquo;s pretty funny what you read on the old Police blotter&amp;rsquo;s website occasionally. I check it all the time. My street is actually one of the lowest crime areas in the city. Did you know that? I totally did - it&amp;rsquo;s why I moved here. Yup, I&amp;rsquo;m glad I checked the old crime reports a long time ago, before this morning.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Oh yeah, the other thing was that my phone died. Just in case you tried to call me - that&amp;rsquo;s why I didn&amp;rsquo;t answer. It&amp;rsquo;s better now, I plugged it in. You know how these smartphones go these days, they just have no battery life. You can never tell if somebody hasn&amp;rsquo;t charged their phone or if they just left it in the other room and for whatever reason they&amp;rsquo;re too scared to go get it. I mean, too scared or lazy. Either one - there&amp;rsquo;s no reason I said &amp;ldquo;scared&amp;rdquo; first.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;How about those fireworks stores, though, huh? Did you know they just keep selling cheap fireworks for like ever? The Fourth was like a week ago! They have those &amp;ldquo;buy one get fifteen free&amp;rdquo; deals, now. You can get a bunch of those popper things that just go &amp;ldquo;pop, pop, pop&amp;rdquo; really quick, like one, two, three. I mean, I&amp;rsquo;m guessing they have a thing like that. It would be pretty exciting. The police sure don&amp;rsquo;t seem to care much about if you launch fireworks in the city, huh?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Anyway, yeah, we should get on that pizza train. We could try this one place. I actually have a coupon. I mean, we could Yelp it, or we could use this coupon. Whatever you want to do - I&amp;rsquo;ve had it a while. I was organizing my closet earlier and I found it. Crazy, huh? Just doing some spring - er, summer cleaning. Oh yeah, I always like to organize my winter coats and sweaters in the middle of summer. Anyway, yeah, I found this coupon and some captain&amp;rsquo;s wafers and a couple bucks in change. We are set for the night.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Well, I already ate the captain&amp;rsquo;s wafers...&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The last two and a half weeks have been pretty rough. I&amp;rsquo;ve been contending with a lot of serious work to do, moving to a new city, and the fact that regularly posting something here is just &lt;em&gt;hard&lt;/em&gt;. As a result of all these excuses, the last three weeks have seen so little content here that I&amp;rsquo;m sure we&amp;rsquo;ve lost our precious tiny audience. This has led to a new development which kind of becomes a sort of good news / bad news situation.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The bad news is that I&amp;rsquo;m going to be losing a certain amount of creative control. I know what you&amp;rsquo;re thinking. &lt;em&gt;Without you, where will I get my fix for dumb jokes and ideas?&lt;/em&gt; you might be asking. Don&amp;rsquo;t worry, I&amp;rsquo;ll still be here. I&amp;rsquo;ll just be getting a little, let&amp;rsquo;s just say &lt;em&gt;help&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Since I started this website, in 2005, it has existed as the centerpiece of my online company, DenyConformity Media. What you may not know is that a few years ago, not long before the site&amp;rsquo;s big April Fool&amp;rsquo;s Day relaunch, my company was bought out. A large, mysterious corporation moved in and put forward a pretty hefty investment to own this mighty empire. It turns out that I might have made this bed for myself, in fact.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Back in 2006, I wrote an ill-conceived &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/post/149/My_ECN_job&quot;&gt;post&lt;/a&gt; about a job I had. It was mainly about some interesting names I had found in a Purdue database. The last name I found belonged to one Harland Fankboner, an Purdue graduate from way back in 1901.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/ECN/pictures10.gif&quot; /&gt; &lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;He still looks like a Fankboner.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Well it just so happens that this enigmatic corporation which wholly owns yours truly goes by the name of Fankboner Industries.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/fankboner_logo.jpg&quot; /&gt; &lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;This is their logo, which I only know from the letterhead on their - frankly quite pushy - letters.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Is it a coincidence? Of course not. As I was told (or at least what I&amp;rsquo;m allowed to tell you) is that my benefactors wanted to maintain a silent role in ensuring DenyConformity.com maintained a &amp;ldquo;more intentional drive for integrity&amp;rdquo; and that it became a &amp;ldquo;more interesting place.&amp;rdquo; Until now I had to follow their directives (such as not talking about their namesake anymore) without acknowledging their presence (or even their existence). I had to keep that up until now.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The new DenyConformity.com was a bit of a &amp;ldquo;last straw&amp;rdquo; scenario for my benefactors. Either I succeeded in finally making this little arm of Fankboner Industries finally successful, or they were going to step in and take over. Unfortunately for me, though I tried my best at the former, the latter has come to pass. Please welcome Fankboner Industries as they step in to really kick this website into shape.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;What can you expect from the new Fankboner Industries Presents DenyConformity.com? We&amp;rsquo;ll just have to wait and see.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;You may not know this, but I sometimes make music. I mainly just do it for myself, but sometimes other people seem to enjoy it, too. Before you credit me with any talent or ability, you should know that it&#039;s all just electronic beeps and boops (0r as my Mom calls it, &quot;Ding Dong Ching Chong music&quot;). Today I put a song together called &quot;Double All the Way.&quot; You can listen to it if you want.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;iframe width=&quot;100%&quot; height=&quot;166&quot; scrolling=&quot;no&quot; frameborder=&quot;no&quot; src=&quot;http://w.soundcloud.com/player/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fapi.soundcloud.com%2Ftracks%2F54019371&amp;amp;auto_play=false&amp;amp;show_artwork=true&amp;amp;color=0087ff&quot;&gt;&lt;/iframe&gt;

&lt;p&gt;You can see more music I have made on my Soundcloud &lt;a href=&quot;http://soundcloud.com/smac&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;page&lt;/a&gt; (I post stuff there under the name &quot;Smac&quot;). If you like it, maybe I&#039;ll make and post more.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Or, How Two Dudes Did a Thing Despite Being a Pair of Bumbling Idiots&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I enjoy riding a bike. They provide cheap transportation (over short distances), they&amp;rsquo;re fun to work on and maintain, and they&amp;rsquo;re pretty good excercise. The problem - especially for me - is that they take up a lot of space. I have a 2009 Specialized Secteur, and it&amp;rsquo;s huge. I have to buy the largest frame Specialized makes. Where can I keep this thing?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I&amp;rsquo;ve had two bikes stolen from me, so I&amp;rsquo;m not interested in leaving my bike outside for any length of time. That means I have to keep it inside my apartment, where space is at a premium. I&amp;rsquo;ve heard about these kits you can buy which amount to a series of pulleys you attach to your ceiling. You can then hoist your bike into the air like you just don&amp;rsquo;t care (though if you have any sense of gravity at all you might be a bit concerned). My new apartment happens to have pretty high ceilings, so I figured the time was perfect to give one of these kits a try.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;My friend Andrew Monkey stopped by to give me a hand installing it.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/bike_rack/bikerack1.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;This is the kit that arrived from Amazon.com. As shown on the box you can also use this thing to hoist ladders. I bet you could probably hoist all kinds of things (as long as they don&amp;rsquo;t exceed the 50 pound weight limit). I was going to make a silly list of things you could hoist - things like pants, children, other hoists, and that kind of thing - but I want to keep this post serious. This is important.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/bike_rack/bikerack2.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;This is my bike. I did those handlebars up in yellow and painted the seat post myself. There is more yellow I wish to apply, but that&amp;rsquo;s neither here nor there. For scale, that lightswitch is a standard light switch height, so you can picture my bike seat being as tall as that.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/bike_rack/bikerack3.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;This is the corner I wanted to put the thing. This way my bike will be up and out of the way and hanging right over the litter box - just so the cat is reminded who&amp;rsquo;s boss around here.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/bike_rack/bikerack8.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The kit came with the two ceiling mounts, two pulleys with little armatures (not pictured), a really long rope (not pictured), and a bunch of screws. The instructions show the thing being mounted directly to a ceiling joist. I&amp;rsquo;m not sure if my ceiling is made of drywall or plaster or what, but I do know that you shouldn&amp;rsquo;t just screw this thing any old place. It definitely has to go right into a joist. The directions say that you can mount the thing to a board and then attach that board to the joists, and that sounded like a good idea to me. I figured it would be easier to attach a board to the ceiling than these cumbersome things. If you have a garage with exposed joists, you can just screw the pieces up there and call it a day, you lucky dog you.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/bike_rack/bikerack4.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The only board I could get was eight feet long, so Andrew helped me measure it in half.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/bike_rack/bikerack5.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The dude knows a good &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/post/378/The_Parker_Jotter&quot;&gt;pen&lt;/a&gt; when he sees one.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/bike_rack/bikerack6.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;A four foot board would be the perfect length for my bike. We have enough board left over to make another one of these (if I got another kit, anyway).&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/bike_rack/bikerack7.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;This is unrelated. If you see my sister, don&amp;rsquo;t tell her that this is her birthday present, but that she should come see me for some reason. Make something up.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/bike_rack/bikerack9.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The board was very much not straight. I figured it wouldn&amp;rsquo;t be a problem, since it was the only board we had, and - you know - whatever.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/bike_rack/bikerack10.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Andrew brought his circular saw to cut the board with. I recommend having a friend who has lots of tools that you don&amp;rsquo;t have. You have to put up with them babbling at you about who knows what, but it&amp;rsquo;s worth it when you need a circular saw.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/bike_rack/bikerack11.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;I very precisely marked out where the two hoist pulleys needed to go. They hang onto the bike (or the bike hangs onto them) at the handlebars and the seat, so I marked those locations on the board.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/bike_rack/bikerack12.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Woah, this is a picture of me. Not many of those around.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/bike_rack/bikerack13.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;I screwed the pulley assemblies onto the board where I marked for them to be screwed. It seemed like the thing to do.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/bike_rack/bikerack14.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Now it was time to figure out where the board needed to go. There are two ways to find studs (or joists) in the wall (or ceiling). You can take a drill and make hundreds of little holes until you drill into solid wood, or you can get a stud finder, which uses magic to tell you where the studs are. I had to run to the Sheller Mart down the street to pick up a 9-Volt battery (the magic kind), and I set about finding where the joist was. Stud finders might seem like a hokey thing, but they work great. Explain that one, science!&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/bike_rack/bikerack15.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;While I was doing that, Andrew fired up some Obama Type.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/bike_rack/bikerack16.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Here are some of the bits I didn&amp;rsquo;t include in the other picture (except the drill, that was in the other picture). The tape measure and drill were not included in the kit but they&amp;rsquo;re good things to have around. Don&amp;rsquo;t rely on your babbling friend to have those things for you - you should have them for yourself.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/bike_rack/bikerack17.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Here I am gloriously modeling the screws I got to attach the board to the ceiling. They were like four inches long and pretty serious. I wanted to be sure they would get through the two-inch thick board and still have plenty of screw left for the joist.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/bike_rack/bikerack18.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;We chose a drill bit to make some pilot holes. We thought were were being really smart by holding it up next to the screws, and we took this picture to document just how smart we were.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/bike_rack/bikerack19.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Then this happened. The drill bit just hauled off and broke inside the board. Now there is a drill bit permanently included with my ceiling hoist, so there&amp;rsquo;s that.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/bike_rack/bikerack20.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;So we picked out a new drill bit, and re-drilled the pilot holes. What a couple of bumbling idiots.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/bike_rack/bikerack21.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;I put all of the screws in position, ready to just go right up into the ceiling. I was really optimistic about that happening.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/bike_rack/bikerack22.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;This picture really belies the fact that it was a pain in the ass (and the arm) to hold the board in place. I was standing basically on top of an ancient ladder (thanks for letting me use that, Andrew) and holding that up about as high as I could. The ceiling is very high. I had to line the thing up, and then commence to screwing. That&amp;rsquo;s no easy feat for an idiot as prone to bumbling as I.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/bike_rack/bikerack23.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;As you can probably imagine - as I can imagine now that I have the magnificent power of hindsight - the screws didn&amp;rsquo;t go into the ceiling joist basically at all. I live in an extremely old building, from back in the day when they built buildings before they started not making things like they used to. We decided that the ceiling joist also needed some pilot holes, which meant marking where they needed to go. This picture shows me putting the screws in a bit further - or farther, whatever.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/bike_rack/bikerack25.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;With all of the screws poking out like this, all I had to do was hold the board in place and give it a good whack - or thwack, whatever - and I would have a mark for each screw. Again, we decided this plan made us some sort of pair of geniouses. Not being able to spell geniuses belies the fact that I am, in fact, part of a pair of them.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/bike_rack/bikerack24.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;I got back on up there and gave the board the aforesaid whack / thwack.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/bike_rack/bikerack26.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Then I hauled off and drilled that sucker with the drill bit that survived drilling the other holes. This was a difficult thing, because man that ceiling joist was one tough mother. I could go an inch or two, but then it felt like I just couldn&amp;rsquo;t drill any further / farther. It was like trying to drill into rock, or like, some sort of heavy metal. Try as I might, I just could not get the screws to go in all the way. The really tough thing was that Andrew was too short to give it a try himself. I was the only person who could make this thing happen. &lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/bike_rack/bikerack27.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;For some reason, Alyson wasn&amp;rsquo;t completely confident.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/bike_rack/bikerack28.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;New plan! We attached a pair of spacers to the bottom of the board. These incredibly high tech components would mean that the ridiculously over-sized screws I bought wouldn&amp;rsquo;t have to go into the joist quite as far, thereby hopefully meaning that I would actually be able to screw them in all the way.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/bike_rack/bikerack29.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The holes in the spacers are very scientific calibration and load-bearing components, not side-effects of the fact that the spacers were once part of a piece of Ikea furniture.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/bike_rack/bikerack30.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;I don&amp;rsquo;t know why I thought you would want to see a picture of some holes in a ceiling, but here you go. Feast your eyes.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/bike_rack/bikerack31.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The spacers did the trick! Using my incredible man-strength, I was able to get all of the monster screws into the ceiling as far as they could go. The people upstairs haven&amp;rsquo;t complained about screws sticking out of their floor yet.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/bike_rack/bikerack32.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;All I had to do now was run the rope through the various pulleys, starting with this little hole where the rope starts.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/bike_rack/bikerack33.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Andrew had a grand old time, and we had only strung one of the pulleys up.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/bike_rack/bikerack34.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Here it is fully assembled. Without a weight like a bike or a child on the little fingers, they don&amp;rsquo;t both go up and down as you pull the rope. This makes it actually not as fun to play with as when there was only one pulley on it, but this isn&amp;rsquo;t some sort of toy.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/bike_rack/bikerack35.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;I hooked my bike up to it and gave the rope a tug. It worked! Both armatures rose at the same time, and it was not terribly difficult to pull the rope with my bike attached. It only took a small fraction of my fantastic man-strength. Here you see the look of terror on Alyson&amp;rsquo;s face as I use the hoist for the first time.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/bike_rack/bikerack38.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Andrew is a normally sized man, and it was well over his head. I can still bump my head on it - in fact I have - but that&amp;rsquo;s just because of my freakish height.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/bike_rack/bikerack37.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Just because the project was finished doesn&amp;rsquo;t mean that I was done being an idiot. Whatever you do, don&amp;rsquo;t assume that the rope is plenty long enough and cut the excess &lt;em&gt;while the bike is hanging there&lt;/em&gt;. Don&amp;rsquo;t you realize (I&amp;rsquo;m talking to myself here) that the excess slack is so you can &lt;em&gt;lower the bike&lt;/em&gt;? Luckily (I&amp;rsquo;m talking to you, again), after doing the stupid thing, the excess rope was actually long enough to work, so after re-doing the whole pulley system, I can actually use the thing.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/bike_rack/bikerack36.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Even though it was installed by a couple of goomers, the ceiling bike hoist system works pretty great. There was a bit of panic right before I used it for the first time that it was too close to the wall (you can see that the front wheel is turned slightly so it fits better). It just barely has enough room, but this is definitely something you should remember to watch out for if you ever try to do this in a less stupid way than I did.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Do you have some bikes (or other things weighing less than 50 pounds) in your way, but plenty of ceiling space in which to hang them? You should definitely consider buying and assembling one of these contraptions. The ceiling bike hoist is a cool thing that is a bit easier to use than it was to install, but it will definitely pay for itself in the convenience it brings. My bike has been hanging up there for about a week, and it&amp;rsquo;s still holding strong.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Make sure you bring a friend along to help you with your ceiling bike hoist. Just try not to bumble quite as much as we did when you go to install it.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A few weeks ago I had the pleasure of attending (and participating in) the &quot;Laugh&quot;ayette &quot;Fun&quot;stival, a really great comedy spectacular hosting by some friends of mine in Lafayette Indiana. They asked me to participate, and I&#039;m afraid there was a bit of a misunderstanding.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So I was under the impression that it was the &quot;Larroquette Fund-stival,&quot; a Fund raising event hosted by John Larroquette. Naturally I figured it would be a great place to try to raise support for my recent business idea. Needless to say, I only found out my mistake a few moments before I was to go on stage, so I didn&#039;t have time to correct my slideshow. Anyway, take a look at the video of my presentation below:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;
&lt;iframe width=&quot;700&quot; height=&quot;394&quot; src=&quot;http://www.youtube.com/embed/XwoDhAp2VzY&quot; frameborder=&quot;0&quot; allowfullscreen&gt;&lt;/iframe&gt;
&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;by Brandon Lionel Kirk&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;[This is the first in a series of posts narrating a single playthrough of the indie game &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ftlgame.com&quot;&gt;FTL&lt;/a&gt;. It&#039;s all made up, but entirely based on things that happen in the game. We open on a aspiring young captain, setting off on a vital mission to save the Federation. . .]&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p class=&quot;firstletter&quot;&gt;Captain&amp;rsquo;s log, stardate . . .&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Does anybody know what day it is? Oh, screw it, I&amp;rsquo;ll start over.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;How do I stop this thing? No, I just want to erase it and start over. This one? Nope, that just made it louder. This is weird. I can hear myself. Here. Okay, that got it, right? Damn it. Ok, whatever. That&amp;rsquo;s fine. Everything is okay. I will just start over.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Ok, um, hello, there. Greetings. This is Captain Brandon Kirk (no relation), of the spaceship Brandon Kirk. Now I have proof that everything in my life is not just a series of completely random encounters, because I have achieved the rank of Captain and gotten my own ship which I have named after myself. Finally, nobody will scoff at the name Brandon Kirk, because it is not only the name of a totally real space captain but also a totally great spaceship. The jerks over at the Milky Way Copy Hut (where I had my new business cards printed) will have to eat their words once the name Brandon Kirk is synonymous with either &amp;ldquo;War Hero&amp;rdquo; or at least &amp;ldquo;Functional Spaceship.&amp;rdquo; I know my therapist, Dr. Wendle, would tell me to stop taking others&amp;rsquo; comments so personally, and I am trying to do that. Those guys were jerks, and that&amp;rsquo;s fine. I am okay with others making comments directed at me. Everything is okay.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/brandonkirk/bk1.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The USS Brandon Kirk, in full military deployment.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;My new crew checked in today. They&amp;rsquo;re all male (or at least malien). That&amp;rsquo;s fine. I am okay with that. I have to revise my Dream Girlfriend Plan, but that will be much easier now that I&amp;rsquo;m a Space Captain (and have the same name as a Real Spaceship). I&amp;rsquo;m sure my crew was assigned to my ship based on their aptitude and ability to work together, not just generated at random. Dr. Wendle is always telling me to remember that our lives are the product of our own choices, and not - despite my theories or perhaps delusions otherwise - just a series of randomly generated encounters and events with no real connection or causation involved. I&amp;rsquo;m sure we will all do just great.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I&amp;rsquo;m getting to know the new team. I assigned Sem to the helm, because that&amp;rsquo;s where he was when I came aboard. I needed somebody I could trust at the shield terminal, obviously, so I sent the other human there. It&amp;rsquo;s not a race thing - he&amp;rsquo;s white. I don&amp;rsquo;t know what the Hell kind of name Rafn is, though. That&amp;rsquo;s fine. I will learn to be okay with having a crew member called Rafn.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;We have two aliens aboard. Willow is some sort of crazy electricity monster, so I put him as far from me as possible, in the engine room. Finally, there&amp;rsquo;s Junpeng. I&amp;rsquo;m absolutely not afraid of him or his crazy-ass name, and I let him do what he asked to do - man the weapons - because he obviously has a natural proclivity to do that. I&amp;rsquo;m not afraid of him. I am not afraid of his arms which are basically just four foot long blades, or the fact that the only personal items he brought on board consist of raw meat and the latest issue of Forbes Magazine. That&amp;rsquo;s fine. I will learn to be okay with living with a creature that personifies my two biggest fears, giant blade monsters and investment banking. As my therapist has pointed out, other people&amp;rsquo;s financial decisions have no bearing on me, so I need to just relax and try not to dwell on that.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;With the crew in place and the power systems allocated, the USS Brandon Kirk and her captain - me, Brandon Kirk - set off on our first big mission, which is important, I think. So, I wasn&amp;rsquo;t exactly paying attention to the mission briefing. That&amp;rsquo;s fine. I spent the time working on the name of my new ship, which is how I came up with the great ship name Brandon Kirk. It works on so many levels, you see. I&amp;rsquo;m sure my therapist would use it as a sign of my supposed &amp;ldquo;narcissistic tendencies,&amp;rdquo; but there&amp;rsquo;s a reason I didn&amp;rsquo;t bring Dr. &amp;ldquo;Broken Record&amp;rdquo; Wendle onto my spaceship. I shouldn&amp;rsquo;t say that about her. I&amp;rsquo;m sorry, Dr. Wendle. You probably have good reason to point out my many narcissistic tendencies and crippling negativity. No, I am okay with myself. I am a powerful Space Captain, now. I am a successful person.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So I&amp;rsquo;m not actually sure what we&amp;rsquo;re doing out here. That&amp;rsquo;s fine. I&amp;rsquo;m okay with that. As Dr. Wendle would say, &amp;ldquo;don&amp;rsquo;t focus on what you can&amp;rsquo;t do - be proud of what you can.&amp;rdquo; So I can&amp;rsquo;t figure out what exactly my mission is. I&amp;rsquo;m sure it wasn&amp;rsquo;t something vitally important, since I&amp;rsquo;m kinda new to this whole thing and I just have a pretty basic ship with a completely inexperienced crew. That&amp;rsquo;s fine. I&amp;rsquo;m not &amp;ldquo;saving the galaxy&amp;rdquo; or anything of that sort. I will just focus on what I can. My ship has four basic lasers - I like to just call them lasers, I don&amp;rsquo;t see the need to focus on the fact that they&amp;rsquo;re &amp;ldquo;basic&amp;rdquo; lasers - so obviously our main mission is to shoot things with lasers. We will set off to find something that we can shoot lasers at.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/brandonkirk/bk2.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The first encounter of the USS Brandon Kirk.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Aha! We took one faster than light jump and came across a poor sap needing help. This light came up on my dashboard indicating that someone was in distress (I call it the distress signal). My therapist told me that when I feel down on myself I should try to focus on helping others, so off we went to the source of the signal. I&amp;rsquo;m . . . not down on myself. I&amp;rsquo;m just saying that&amp;rsquo;s what my therapist told me. I mean, my bed on this ship is more firm than my one at home, and I forgot to requisition any evening primrose oil supplements for the ship so my fatty acid levels have been imbalanced . . . Um, everything is fine, except for this poor sap sending out their distress call. They need help. I am okay, though.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So there it was, this small ship struggling to maneuver through an asteroid belt. I disregarded my first thought which was, &amp;ldquo;couldn&amp;rsquo;t you have just gone over the asteroid belt?&amp;rdquo; As Dr. Wendle would say, that&amp;rsquo;s just &amp;ldquo;stinking thinking.&amp;rdquo; I tried to see if we could just shoot some of the asteroids with our lasers - that being our mission, and all - but the crew assured me it would be impossible for some reason. I ordered Sem to take the ship into the field and escort the poor sap to safety. Obviously what this situation needed was a giant, marginally maneuverable spaceship getting in the way.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/brandonkirk/bk3.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Let&amp;rsquo;s just chalk this one up as a wash.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;That&amp;rsquo;s fine. I am okay with the fact that the ship was embedded into an asteroid and exploded and nobody survived. My therapist told me to stop blaming others for my problems, and so I will try my best to do that even though I&amp;rsquo;m pretty sure it was Sem&amp;rsquo;s fault. I do have to give my guys credit for being quick on the draw with those salvage operations, though. We dug ten scrap out of that asteroid before heading on our way. I&amp;rsquo;m sure Dr. Wendle would tell me to &amp;ldquo;look on the bright side.&amp;rdquo; The bright side here is that we got ten pieces of scrap metal.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Well, okay, then. I have to go sit under my UV lamp for a while. The Brandon Kirk is currently a bit too far from any stars, so I&amp;rsquo;m not getting enough natural sunlight in my cabin. If I don&amp;rsquo;t get enough UV exposure my vitamin D-6 levels will go down. Then I won&amp;rsquo;t be able to sleep, and that means the next time we encounter a serious decision like we saw today (one based purely on the skill and quick reaction of myself and my crew, not entirely on random chance, of course) I won&amp;rsquo;t be able to make the lightning quick decisions that save lives. Well, today&amp;rsquo;s decision didn&amp;rsquo;t save any lives, but that&amp;rsquo;s fine. I am okay with the decisions I made today. Well, I am unhappy that I forgot to pack my white noise machine, but my cabin is close enough to the reactor that I should be okay. Everything is okay.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Everything is okay.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I better schedule an appointment to see Dr. Wendle when we get back.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;To be continued . . . &lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;By Brandon Kirk&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;[This is part two of an ongoing narrative based around a single playthrough I did of the Indie game &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ftlgame.com/&quot;&gt;FTL&lt;/a&gt;. It&#039;s highly abstracted and fictionalized, but it&#039;s entirely based on in-game events and situations. It&#039;s a fun game. You should play it.]&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p class=&quot;firstchar&quot;&gt;Dear Diary. Oh, that sounds so stupid. I really need to figure out how to reset this thing. What if . . . Nope, now it&amp;rsquo;s just louder, again. Whatever. Dear . . . um, Log. The mission is going so great. Well, okay, I don&amp;rsquo;t actually know what my mission was, but that&amp;rsquo;s fine. I have accepted that, and decided to just let my mission find me. As my therapist, Dr. Wendle would say, I&amp;rsquo;m going to just focus on the little victories.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/brandonkirk/bk1.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Business as usual here on the USS Brandon Kirk.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Life is just fine aboard the Brandon Kirk. Well, okay, there are a few things that I will need to remember in the future. For example, when I am leaving the medbay through the port-most doors, I have to remember to turn right instead of left. Turning right will take me to the Air Circulation control room. Turning left will take me into the unsurvivable vacuum of space. It&amp;rsquo;s just little things. Thankfully, the ship has systems in place to prevent anyone from being sucked into space if someone opens one of those external doors. Still, it gets very cold. It also gets very hard to breathe.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Today we continued to venture forth through space, jumping from system to system in search of things to shoot with lasers. Arriving at one system, we happened to run into an automated scout ship protecting some sort of storage cache inside a nebula.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/brandonkirk/bk4.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The USS Brandon Kirk&amp;rsquo;s first hostile encounter.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The dangerous nature of the nebula diminished the capacity of our reactor, so a few of our systems couldn&amp;rsquo;t get power. Fortunately, we had plenty of power for our lasers. &amp;ldquo;Blast it out of the sky!&amp;rdquo; I commanded. Well, no, I didn&amp;rsquo;t sound that heroic. Actually I said something like, &amp;ldquo;fire the lasers at it!&amp;rdquo; My therapist told me to start telling the truth more about things I have done, so I will do that. I need to be more honest with others, and I will then be more honest with myself.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Okay, fine, I didn&amp;rsquo;t say &amp;ldquo;fire the lasers&amp;rdquo; either. I&amp;rsquo;m sorry. What I actually said was, &amp;ldquo;Oh God! Kill it! Kill that thing! What is it! Kill it!&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/brandonkirk/bk5.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The automated scout with disabled weapons.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Junpeng was somehow able to control the lasers even though his arms are just swords. We disabled the enemy weapon system, so it was unable to shoot any lasers back at us. That was a really great thing, because I prefer lasers to be heading away from me, not at me.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/brandonkirk/bk6.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Destruction of the automated scout.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;With a few more shots, we put an end to the craft. Using my vast intellect, I outsmarted this hostile foe. Well, okay, it was just an automated defense robot, and it didn&amp;rsquo;t have any shields and was actually really easy to kill. That&amp;rsquo;s fine. I will take this victory with any others because it is a far better action to remember than almost killing myself by going through the wrong door.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;We salvaged what we could from the storage cache, which was a bit of fuel, a couple missiles, and 15 scrap. It was, therefore, about as fruitful as watching those poor saps collide with an asteroid yesterday. I&amp;rsquo;m not sure if I&amp;rsquo;m supposed to take a lesson away from that, or what that lesson might be.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This nebula we had found was simply full of things to shoot with our lasers. Well, some of those things were just bits of rock and other debris, but that didn&amp;rsquo;t mean they were any less susceptible to our lasers. That&amp;rsquo;s fine.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/brandonkirk/bk7.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Another hostile encounter.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Eventually we came across another drone. This one was a bit more tough than the first, but we were out of the dangerous energy fields of the nebula, and could therefore utilise the full potential of the Brandon Kirk&amp;rsquo;s systems. I quickly ordered that we enable the shields. Well, actually I ordered that we run away, but Sem let me know that we couldn&amp;rsquo;t get away from the drone until the FTL drives were charged. That is fine, though. I was not afraid of being shot at by an automated assault robot.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/brandonkirk/bk8.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The Brandon Kirk finds yet another success.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;And why should we have been afraid? Truly, nothing could withstand the power of our mighty (basic) lasers. Well, to be fair we had yet to face anything with a sentient brain, but whatever. Sure we took a couple hits, but we barely had a scratch. We destroyed the thing before our FTL drives were even charged.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Not that I was watching the FTL status the entire battle, or anything.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/brandonkirk/bk9.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;A poor, naive pirate tries to hustle the mighty Brandon Kirk.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Soon enough we left the comfortable protection of the nebula and we came across some joker trying to collect a &amp;ldquo;toll&amp;rdquo; at an FTL beacon. Sure, friend, we&amp;rsquo;ll just pay your silly scrap toll to head through this empty system. I mean, 17 scrap is a pretty paltry sum. All we have to do is crash a ship into an asteroid and we&amp;rsquo;ll get that. We will just ignore that skull and cross-bones (or for whatever reason, octopus and cross-bones), and hand over our hard earned scrap. Or, you know, we could SHOOT YOU WITH LASERS!&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/brandonkirk/bk10.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Battle with the hostile space pirate begins.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The Brandon Kirk is definitely a very formidable warship. Of course, this filthy space pirate (are space pirates filthy?) did have a drone with them, which was a new experience for me. It had a tiny little beam weapon which couldn&amp;rsquo;t even penetrate our shields. What a pathetic, filthy space pirate this was (it&amp;rsquo;s just seems that there isn&amp;rsquo;t that much in space to make a pirate filthy). I knew this was going to be a cakewalk.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/brandonkirk/bk11.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The Brandon Kirk sustains damage, with shields down.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Well, actually, the space pirate did have a space missile launcher. Missiles will just go right through the shields like they weren&amp;rsquo;t there at all - like the shields weren&amp;rsquo;t there, not the missile. So if they launch a missile at our shield generator, then our shields will go down, and then their stupid drone can begin shooting us. Also the missiles can set the ship on fire, so that&amp;rsquo;s also a problem. Anyway, exactly that happened. Our shields went down, and also our engines caught on fire. Thankfully Willow had equipment to put out the fire, and Rafn set about fixing the shields.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/brandonkirk/bk12.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;More damage is suffered on the Brandon Kirk.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Then they shot a missile at our sensors, which meant I couldn&amp;rsquo;t see anything on the ship (except for rooms that had a crew member in them). That&amp;rsquo;s fine. I didn&amp;rsquo;t need to see anything in those rooms, anyway. There&amp;rsquo;s nothing interesting happening anywhere except the room where the laser controls are.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/brandonkirk/bk13.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;. . . and more damage.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So then they shot at the room where the laser controls are. That&amp;rsquo;s fine. One of the lasers was put offline, but we still had three. Junpeng got to work fixing things, as Willow set about fixing the engines and Rafn made sure the shields were back up. Oh, also the cockpit was damaged, so Sem had to fix that before we could maneuver at all. This meant that our only way of not being hit by missiles - that is, flying out of the way of them - was gone. All in all, things were not going too great for the Brandon Kirk. That&amp;rsquo;s fine, though. I am okay with challenge. As Dr. Wendle would say, that which doesn&amp;rsquo;t kill you makes you stronger. It&amp;rsquo;s just that missiles could very easily kill us.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/brandonkirk/bk14.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Brandon Kirk turns the tide of the battle.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;However, the best defense is a good offense, or something like that, right? We still had three working lasers. Alone, a laser couldn&amp;rsquo;t penetrate a ship&amp;rsquo;s shield, but three of them can overwhelm shields and punch right through to the gooey, delicious center. I had Junpeng put them to work disabling the enemy shields, and then we shot them in their stupid missile launcher that I had really begun to hate.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/brandonkirk/bk15.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;A hard fought victory for the Brandon Kirk.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;And by the skin of our teeth, we (the Brandon Kirk and her captain, me, Brandon Kirk) vanquished that dumb filthy space pirate (they are filthy in the &amp;ldquo;I hate them and their stupid missile launcher&amp;rdquo; sense) and collected their scrap in our, well, whatever we keep all this scrap in. Is it a scrap tank? Is it some sort of pouch? I don&amp;rsquo;t know. Our scrap pouch was now nice and full.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Yes, the Brandon Kirk has made short work of not just automated drones, but also backwater, two-bit space thugs trying to bully small ships for milk money. Well, fine, so we kind of had a hard time with that last one, but we learned some valuable lessons. Mainly we learned about how much I hate missiles (a lot).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/brandonkirk/bk16.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Yet another victory for the Brandon Kirk.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So when we came across another filthy space pirate (their ships do look pretty filthy), this time dangerously close to a star, we knew just how to take them down. So we did take them down. We barely took any damage doing it, so we obviously had things under control, now.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/brandonkirk/bk17.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Now the Brandon Kirk is on fire (again).&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Well, okay, there was the matter of the ship being on fire. That&amp;rsquo;s fine, though. We were too close to the star, so solar flares were setting things on fire. The FTL drive was still charging, so we couldn&amp;rsquo;t just go somewhere else. These fires had to be put out before they spread to important systems, like the room where the laser controls are. I was going to send Willow in there with his trusty fire extinguisher, but then I remembered something I had learned - something involving doors . . . and space!&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/brandonkirk/bk18.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Brandon Kirk&amp;rsquo;s cunning has saved Brandon Kirk.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Aha! I am a hero. By venting the room on fire into space, the fire had no oxygen left to breath, so it all went out. I have to remember to tell my therapist about this, because it will totally shut her up about telling me to be less selfish.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/brandonkirk/bk19.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The fire is put out.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Here is a situation where I could have easily sent somebody into a raging inferno, but instead I did something that made them not have to do that. I might have saved Willow&amp;rsquo;s life, there. Well, actually, I was the one who decided to fly this close to the sun in the first place, but it&amp;rsquo;s hard to see this navigation control, and I couldn&amp;rsquo;t really tell that would happen. It&amp;rsquo;s fine. Small victories, right?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;To be continued . . .&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

data.summary:
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;By Brandon Kirk&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;[This is part two of an ongoing narrative based around a single playthrough I did of the Indie game &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ftlgame.com/&quot;&gt;FTL&lt;/a&gt;. It&#039;s highly abstracted and fictionalized, but it&#039;s entirely based on in-game events and situations. It&#039;s a fun game. You should play it.]&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p class=&quot;firstchar&quot;&gt;Dear Diary...&lt;/p&gt;

data.text:
&lt;p&gt;It&amp;rsquo;s hard not to see or hear people talking about the upcoming Presidential Election everywhere you go. Though it does get a bit annoying, it&amp;rsquo;s refreshing to not hear people talking about Kardashians or Kate Middleton&amp;rsquo;s wedding for a change. If you were hoping that DenyConformity.com would be a place where you could get away from the Presidential Debate coverage, I&amp;rsquo;m sorry to disappoint you. However, I think I might be taking an analytical angle that you won&amp;rsquo;t find anywhere else. It occurred to me while watching the last debate, the one in Florida.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;What kinds of pens are the candidates using?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I am &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/post/364/Pen_Reviews_Prologue&quot;&gt;interested&lt;/a&gt; in pens, of course. I like to collect them and compare them. Examining exactly what pens Obama and Romney chose to bring to take notes during the debate made watching the debate slightly less boring, and also might give a bit of insight into the candidates themselves, if you&amp;rsquo;re so undecided that you&amp;rsquo;ll take absolutely any piece of differentiating information to make a decision.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;First, let&amp;rsquo;s throw a bit of Presidential trivia out there. When a president signs a big bill or other document, it&amp;rsquo;s tradition to actually use &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.time.com/time/politics/article/0,8599,1974490,00.html&quot;&gt;a bunch of pens to make the signature&lt;/a&gt;. I guess they just carefully make bits of each letter with each pen. Once it&amp;rsquo;s done, the President has a bunch of unique souvenirs they can hand out to important people related to the document. Lyndon Johnson apparently used over 75 pens to sign the Civil Rights act in 1964, and gave one of the first ones to Martin Luther King Jr.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/presidentialpens/prespens13.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Bush deviated from this tradition, of course, because he signed all of his bills with crayon.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The President will obviously use special pens for these occasions, not just some off-the-shelf clicky-top. They&amp;rsquo;re high-class capped numbers, with the President&amp;rsquo;s signature engraved on the side. It turns out that Obama&amp;rsquo;s pens are somewhat unique, aside from the fact that they have his name on them. The engraved signature is &lt;a href=
http://www.joehribar.com/blog/2009/12/18/totally-random-presidential-pens/&quot;&gt;right-side-up&lt;/a&gt; only when the pen is held in the left hand. Obama is left handed, just like all of the coolest people.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Let&amp;rsquo;s move on to the debates, though. It happens that the third Presidential Debate is the best one to take a look at. The first debate placed the candidates at big podiums, which made it impossible to see what they were using, and the second, &amp;ldquo;town hall&amp;rdquo; debate had the candidates standing and walking about, not sitting down carefully taking notes. For the last debate, the candidates were sitting at the same table, with nothing but their notepads and pens in front of them. Finally, there will be no secrets about the candidates&amp;rsquo; preferred writing utensils.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/presidentialpens/prespens1.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;While the candidates prattle on about their continuing rhetoric, we can see what pens they like to use.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Let&amp;rsquo;s start with Mitt Romney. He&amp;rsquo;s a businessman, and according to his debate rhetoric, he&amp;rsquo;s looking to make the government more simple and cut out anything unnecessary or expensive. We don&amp;rsquo;t have to go into the facts and figures of what he said at the debate or elsewhere. The point is that he&amp;rsquo;s rooted in business, and - being a very rich man - check writing.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;These principles are actually kind of reflected in his pen choice.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/presidentialpens/prespens2.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;This is a closeup of the pen Romney was using at the last debate.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Romney was using a &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B002BA5WKU/ref=as_li_tf_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=9325&amp;creativeASIN=B002BA5WKU&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;tag=denyconfocom-20&quot;&gt;Uni-ball 207 RT with blue ink&lt;/a&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.assoc-amazon.com/e/ir?t=denyconfocom-20&amp;l=as2&amp;o=1&amp;a=B002BA5WKU&quot; width=&quot;1&quot; height=&quot;1&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; style=&quot;display: inline; border:none !important; margin:0px !important;&quot; /&gt;. It&amp;rsquo;s a very straight forward, simple pen. It also happens to be fantastic (I found one on a chair in college and I still have it and enjoy using it). It&amp;rsquo;s part of Uni-ball&amp;rsquo;s Signo line, which means it has archival, &amp;ldquo;helps prevent check fraud&amp;rdquo; gel ink. It&amp;rsquo;s not quite as smearable as the &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/post/391/A_Zebra_Three-Way&quot;&gt;Zebra gel I tested&lt;/a&gt; a while back, and the pen itself has a really smooth, dependable quality. That being said, there&amp;rsquo;s no pretense about it - it&amp;rsquo;s all very light plastic. It has a clear body to see the level of ink in the replaceable cartridge, and the only design embellishment is on the clip, which features the Uni-ball and Signo logos. All in all, it&amp;rsquo;s a very good choice of pen for a pragmatic, down to earth businessman.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/presidentialpens/prespens3.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Another look at Romney&amp;rsquo;s pen, with some of the archival scribbles it produced.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Uni-ball does produce four point sizes for the 207, and also makes a 0.7mm &amp;ldquo;needle point&amp;rdquo; version as well. I&amp;rsquo;m guessing Mitt was using the standard 0.7mm medium point. Now, there are blue and light-blue versions, but it looks like Mitt has the regular, conservative blue.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/presidentialpens/prespens4.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;This is the Uni-ball 207 RT, for reference.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So how about Barack Obama, then? Obama is pretty much what you could cite as the classic politician. He went to law school, and practiced as a lawyer for many years before moving into politics. He has worked for his position, moving through first state and then national elected offices. He&amp;rsquo;s very well spoken, and pretty verbose, at that. He&amp;rsquo;s earned a reputation as being a very attractive and picturesque man. His image is important.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/presidentialpens/prespens5.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Here is Obama holding his debate pen.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It wasn&amp;rsquo;t as easy to recognize as Romney&amp;rsquo;s choice, but after examining some pictures I have determined that Obama was actually also using a Uni-ball in the debate. Unlike Romney, however, Obama had a &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B000JKR4DM/ref=as_li_ss_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=390957&amp;creativeASIN=B000JKR4DM&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;tag=denyconfocom-20&quot;&gt;Uni-ball Vision Elite,&lt;/a&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.assoc-amazon.com/e/ir?t=denyconfocom-20&amp;l=as2&amp;o=1&amp;a=B000JKR4DM&quot; width=&quot;1&quot; height=&quot;1&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; style=&quot;display: inline; border:none !important; margin:0px !important;&quot; /&gt; a pretty classy capped rollerball. The Vision Elite is not one of Uni-ball&amp;rsquo;s Signo gel pens, but it does have archival quality, pigment-based, water resistant ink. That sounds like gel to me, but who am I to say? I would say that a nice, comfortable rollerball pen would certainly be a logical choice for somebody known to be verbose. Also, for a career politician who is careful to maintain a classy mystique, nothing beats a sleek, black, capped pen. The claim that the Vision Elite won&amp;rsquo;t leak on an airplane is certainly not a bad thing for Obama, either.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/presidentialpens/prespens6.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Here is the best view we get of Obama&amp;rsquo;s pen, but we can clearly see the characteristic, circular &amp;ldquo;uni-ball Vision ELITE&amp;rdquo; branding and clear butt.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I&amp;rsquo;ve used a Vision Elite before, but I don&amp;rsquo;t have any here to refresh my memory. It will definitely go on my list to check out, then. It is a rollerball, though, which means it&amp;rsquo;s very smooth and designed for writing. It&amp;rsquo;s more substantial than the 207, and has a heavier, more imposing (for a pen, anyway) presence. The Vision Elite is also, for what it&amp;rsquo;s worth, a tad bit more expensive than the 207.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/presidentialpens/prespens7.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;It&amp;rsquo;s surprisingly hard to find a picture of this thing with the cap on, instead of stuck on the back end, but here it is.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Pictures of the second, &amp;ldquo;town hall style&amp;rdquo; debate show that the candidates had the same pen choices there, which implies that these really were chosen by the candidates, or perhaps even their own personal pens. I doubt we&amp;rsquo;ll ever really know, but it does seem like these were more than just a last minute, &amp;ldquo;oh, here, better take a pen and paper with you on stage&amp;rdquo; situation.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/presidentialpens/prespens10.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;There&amp;rsquo;s Obama&amp;rsquo;s Vision Elite, while the candidates were discussing five point plans and binders full of things.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Further, It&amp;rsquo;s interesting (or incredibly boring, I suppose, if you aren&amp;rsquo;t a weirdo like I am) that in the last debate, the moderator, Bob Schieffer, was also apparently using a Uni-ball.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/presidentialpens/prespens8.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;It&amp;rsquo;s tough to find a good picture of his pen, but there are plenty of his stern moderator face.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Schieffer&amp;rsquo;s pen has a very characteristic cap (it was, like Obama&amp;rsquo;s, a capped rollerball), and at first I thought it was a &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/post/399/The_Pentel_Hybrid_Technica&quot;&gt;Pentel Hybrid Technica&lt;/a&gt;. However, Schieffer&amp;rsquo;s pen was blue, and the Technica only comes in black. Looking through Uni-ball&amp;rsquo;s selection, however, it seems that Schieffer had a &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00006JNI0/ref=as_li_ss_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=390957&amp;creativeASIN=B00006JNI0&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;tag=denyconfocom-20&quot;&gt;blue Uni-ball Gel Grip&lt;/a&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.assoc-amazon.com/e/ir?t=denyconfocom-20&amp;l=as2&amp;o=1&amp;a=B00006JNI0&quot; width=&quot;1&quot; height=&quot;1&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; style=&quot;display: inline; border:none !important; margin:0px !important;&quot; /&gt;, another in the Signo family of gel pens. I don&amp;rsquo;t know what this pen says about Bob Schieffer, and I don&amp;rsquo;t care to explore it too much since he isn&amp;rsquo;t running for President. However, one interesting fact about this pen is that I can&amp;rsquo;t seem to find it in packs of less than 12 or so. I guess Schieffer likes a pen that comes in bulk, then.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/presidentialpens/prespens9.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Good thing, since they&amp;rsquo;re apparently delicious.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Perhaps all these Uni-balls are part of some grand pen-related conspiracy, or a complex product placement. Considering nobody else is talking about it, it probably isn&amp;rsquo;t. Uni-ball, for the record, is part of the same huge corporation that owns Sharpie, Papermate, and &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/post/378/The_Parker_Jotter&quot;&gt;Parker&lt;/a&gt;. If the candidates were wanting to reassure us that they weren&amp;rsquo;t going to support corporate interests, their pens don&amp;rsquo;t really help their case. Who knows, maybe Sanford helped underwrite the Commision on Presidential Debates. Maybe it was just a coincidence. Whatever the case, perhaps the most interesting thing of all is that these two men who seem to disagree on so many things have at least this one thing in common.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;What about the Vice Presidential Debate, you ask? Well, I looked into that, as well. I won&amp;rsquo;t analyse them, since it&amp;rsquo;s already very late, but here they are, anyway.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/presidentialpens/prespens11.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Paul Ryan makes a point while flanked by two simple pens.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Paul Ryan used a pair of &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B002E34OUS/ref=as_li_ss_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=390957&amp;creativeASIN=B002E34OUS&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;tag=denyconfocom-20&quot;&gt;blue Papermate Flairs&lt;/a&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.assoc-amazon.com/e/ir?t=denyconfocom-20&amp;l=as2&amp;o=1&amp;a=B002E34OUS&quot; width=&quot;1&quot; height=&quot;1&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; style=&quot;display: inline; border:none !important; margin:0px !important;&quot; /&gt; (I&amp;rsquo;m pretty sure that&amp;rsquo;s what they are, anyway). Perhaps the blue thing was a campaign choice. The Flair is a simple felt tip pen. They&amp;rsquo;re unique in the debates in that respect, and though they aren&amp;rsquo;t from Uni-ball, they&amp;rsquo;re still under the Sanford umbrella, so it&amp;rsquo;s all in the family.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/presidentialpens/prespens12.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Joe Biden is the white to Obama&amp;rsquo;s black. I&amp;rsquo;m talking about pens, here, of course.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Joe Biden actually has the same pen as Obama, in white instead of black. I suppose that&amp;rsquo;s awkwardly appropriate, isn&amp;rsquo;t it? It&amp;rsquo;s a very clean, articulate pen, indeed.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Anyway, I find all this more interesting that most of the actual debate talk. Maybe you can go out and pick up your favorite candidate&#039;s pen, and feel like you&#039;re part of the team. Whatever the case, I hope you found this any bit as interesting as I did. Also, you&#039;re welcome for not making any &quot;uni-ball&quot; jokes.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;I guess I should specify that all of these pictures were from Google Image search, since I have no real journalistic integrity to uphold.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Hello. A many years ago I got a huge collection of MAME roms off the electronic Internet. MAME stands for Multiple Arcade Machine Emulator. So these are old (and slightly less old) arcade games from a many many years ago. I&amp;rsquo;m bored tonight, so I&amp;rsquo;m going to select a few random ones and tell you about them. Let&amp;rsquo;s begin.&lt;/p&gt;


&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Psychic 5&lt;/strong&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;1987, by Jaleco&lt;/p&gt;


&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/arcades/psyc0003.png&quot; /&gt;


&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Select Esper&amp;rdquo; is what I&amp;rsquo;m prompted upon hitting start on this side- and vertical- scrolling platformer. I didn&amp;rsquo;t see any Espers on the screen, but not knowing what one is I wouldn&amp;rsquo;t have known if one was there. I didn&amp;rsquo;t have much time to figure it out, though, because the game started.&lt;/p&gt;


&lt;img style=&quot;width: 448px&quot; src=&quot;/assets/images/arcades/psyc0005.png&quot; /&gt;

&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Select Esper&lt;/div&gt;


&lt;p&gt;I&amp;rsquo;m apparently a small boy lost in some sort of old Japanese Haunted House (maybe that&amp;rsquo;s racist - it&amp;rsquo;s of an asian persuasion). I can jump with one button and smash things with apparently a hammer, because all boys have hammers, right?&lt;/p&gt;


&lt;p&gt;I smashed what must have been a priceless antique pot and there was a smiley face inside. I picked that up, like you do, and traveled onward to seek more of these things.&lt;/p&gt;


&lt;p&gt;There&amp;rsquo;s a witch randomly flying by, and what appears to be an angry clock puking smaller, less angry clocks at me. My hammer makes short work of the smaller clocks, and I can use my &amp;ldquo;because this is a video game&amp;rdquo; ridiculously high jumping ability to make it up to the platform with the larger one. I don&amp;rsquo;t want to go near that monstrosity, but if I were puking clocks (or for that matter anything), I&amp;rsquo;d want a boy to put me out of misery with his hammer, too.&lt;/p&gt;


&lt;img style=&quot;width: 448px&quot; src=&quot;/assets/images/arcades/psychic5.png&quot; /&gt;

&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;I&amp;rsquo;m a hero, I guess.&lt;/div&gt;


&lt;p&gt;Okay, so my hammer just dazed the thing for a second, and he pretty quickly woke up and turned me into an angel. There&amp;rsquo;s a lesson in there somewhere.&lt;/p&gt;


&lt;img style=&quot;width: 448px&quot; src=&quot;/assets/images/arcades/psyc0000.png&quot; /&gt;


&lt;p&gt;Of course I have another life, so this time I give the clock monster a wider berth. I find a few more priceless antique pots, but they contain what looks like jewels and other valuables. Why the first one had a smiley face in it I have no idea. Stupid clock monster cornered me and made me another ghost. I&amp;rsquo;m not very good at platformers, as it happens.&lt;/p&gt;


&lt;p&gt;Life number three begins with great promise. I got past my timekeeping nemesis and ignored the witch thing because she apparently doesn&amp;rsquo;t actually do anything. The highlight of the game was finding another smiley face. I then proceeded to spend a solid 90 seconds trying to jump on a moving platform.&lt;/p&gt;


&lt;img style=&quot;width: 448px&quot; src=&quot;/assets/images/arcades/psyc0002.png&quot; /&gt;

&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;I&amp;rsquo;m really not good at platformers.&lt;/div&gt;


&lt;p&gt;Perhaps the story would make more sense if I had played Psychics 1 through 4. I bet they explain what Esper is and how one selects it. This game seems to mainly be about seeking smiles while you avoid the inevitability of time. Hits too close to home for me. Next.&lt;/p&gt;


&lt;p&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Ms. Pac Man&lt;/strong&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;1980 / 81 - Midway MFG CO&lt;/p&gt;


&lt;p&gt;I&amp;rsquo;m tempted to skip this random selection because showing a game people have heard of defeats the purpose of making fun of obscure old arcade games. Then I realized &amp;ldquo;who cares&amp;rdquo; and just played it anyway.&lt;/p&gt;


&lt;img style=&quot;width: 448px&quot; src=&quot;/assets/images/arcades/mspa0008.png&quot; /&gt;


&lt;p&gt;In this game you play as a lemon meringue pie with a fetching red bow and lipstick. You have to make your way around a maze eating tiny white dots and avoiding four differently colored ghosts. You can eat one of four larger white dots to make all the ghosts the same color and susceptible to your gaping, yellow maw. When eaten, the ghosts&amp;rsquo; eyes travel back to their paddock in the center of the level and they come back to life - er, death. They&amp;rsquo;re ghosts, so I don&amp;rsquo;t know why you thought you could kill them by hitting them with a pie.&lt;/p&gt;


&lt;img style=&quot;width: 448px&quot; src=&quot;/assets/images/arcades/mspa0004.png&quot; /&gt;

&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;A female pie, in fact.&lt;/div&gt;


&lt;p&gt;Also there are cherries, so I guess she aspires to be a cherry pie instead of lemon. I&amp;rsquo;m not sure how the ghosts fit into the pie metaphor.&lt;/p&gt;


&lt;p&gt;This isn&amp;rsquo;t my first time around the maze with old Ms. Pie Man, so I know what I&amp;rsquo;m doing (also it isn&amp;rsquo;t a platformer, so I don&amp;rsquo;t have to waste any time trying to jump onto anything). We all know your only escape from this glowing red, ghost-infested hell (I guess that&amp;rsquo;s just regular Hell, actually) is by collecting all those tiny dots. So I do that.&lt;/p&gt;


&lt;img style=&quot;width: 448px&quot; src=&quot;/assets/images/arcades/mspa0004.png&quot; /&gt;


&lt;p&gt;Which of course prompts the game to reset and it all starts over again. So ultimately, a young pie&amp;rsquo;s attempts to feel good about herself and actually accomplish anything meaningful are completely futile. Again, too close to real life for me. Also that incessant &amp;ldquo;wakka wakka&amp;rdquo; sound is pretty excruciating after like five seconds. Let&amp;rsquo;s move on.&lt;/p&gt;


&lt;p&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Ginga NinkyouDen&lt;/strong&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;Unknown year (it&amp;rsquo;s in Japanese or something) - Jaleco&lt;/p&gt;


&lt;img style=&quot;width: 448px&quot; src=&quot;/assets/images/arcades/ging0008.png&quot; /&gt;


&lt;p&gt;Now we&amp;rsquo;re talking. Here&amp;rsquo;s some weird Japanese arcade game about who knows what. Let&amp;rsquo;s do this, Ginga NinkyouDen.&lt;/p&gt;


&lt;p&gt;So within about five seconds of pressing start I see what is apparently the Macguffin for this game (some floating garbage or something) fly away and then some asshole hits me in the face with a pie. Literally, all this happens before I can even move.&lt;/p&gt;


&lt;img style=&quot;width: 448px&quot; src=&quot;/assets/images/arcades/ginganin.png&quot; /&gt;

&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;It&amp;rsquo;s actually an endless stream of these pie-armed vixens.&lt;/div&gt;


&lt;p&gt;Trying to run away from them, into what is obviously a room behind this dude, is apparently impossible.&lt;/p&gt;


&lt;img style=&quot;width: 448px&quot; src=&quot;/assets/images/arcades/ging0001.png&quot; /&gt;

&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;I just realized that building is a face.&lt;/div&gt;


&lt;p&gt;With the police station apparently closed, this horrible town has just fallen into chaos. Why must all arcade games be about pie? Finally I get my bearings and jump over one of the obnoxious pie vixens. Then I run . . . into . . .&lt;/p&gt;


&lt;img style=&quot;width: 448px&quot; src=&quot;/assets/images/arcades/ging0002.png&quot; /&gt;

&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;wat&lt;/div&gt;


&lt;p&gt;Now I&amp;rsquo;m fighting some red thing and also there are Godzillas falling down a hole behind it. Ginga NinkyouDen, you really are full of surprises. I timidly step toward the thing and wail on the button that makes the little dude that I am swing his fist a dangerously small distance in front of his giant head. The red thing surrenders like a chump, and I am ready for my next challenge. Godzilla parade.&lt;/p&gt;


&lt;p&gt;Another one of those red dudes pops up, scratching menacingly at the pavement in front of him. I wouldn&amp;rsquo;t be afraid of the little badger thing if it weren&amp;rsquo;t for all those Godzillas.&lt;/p&gt;


&lt;img style=&quot;width: 448px&quot; src=&quot;/assets/images/arcades/ging0004.png&quot; /&gt;

&lt;div class=&#039;caption&#039;&gt;An endless stream of Godzillas.&lt;/div&gt;


&lt;p&gt;I strike out with my single fist attack (my only attack, unless you count a &amp;ldquo;because this is a video game&amp;rdquo; ridiculously high jump as an attack). It turns out the Godzillas are just as susceptible to my fury as the red thing, and a couple of them fall to my cunning strategy. I even avoid the one that inexplicably attacks me from the left side of the screen. Then I accidentally fall into the hole (platformer), and get killed by some sort of Jason-looking dude with a plasma gun that&amp;rsquo;s also a chainsaw.&lt;/p&gt;


&lt;img style=&quot;width: 448px&quot; src=&quot;/assets/images/arcades/ging0005.png&quot; /&gt;

&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;That escalated quickly.&lt;/div&gt;


&lt;p&gt;With my next of the obligatory three lives I was able to dive right into the hole and charge down the hall toward those Jason-looking dudes. When no Jason-looking dudes showed up I was a little thrown, but then they did so it all worked out. Then they pulled that &amp;ldquo;showing up on the left side&amp;rdquo; trick that the Godzillas pulled earlier, which was a bit more successful because these Jason-looking things can shoot at me. Not fair, Ginga NinkyouDen.&lt;/p&gt;


&lt;p&gt;Life number three went much further. I defeated a few Jason-looking dudes, punched some random guys in their underwear (I don&amp;rsquo;t know how we got from plasma gun and chainsaw to boxer shorts), beat up a few more Godzillas, and then Rambo shot me with a rocket. Seriously.&lt;/p&gt;


&lt;img style=&quot;width: 448px&quot; src=&quot;/assets/images/arcades/ging0006.png&quot; /&gt;

&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Bonus: Motorcycle Ninjas&lt;/div&gt;


&lt;p&gt;Ginga NinkyouDen knows what I&amp;rsquo;m looking for. That is to say, I have no idea what is going on, but I like that. Video games let you do things you wouldn&amp;rsquo;t normally do, and today I punched a Godzilla and got chainsawed by a Jason-looking dude while an angry man in his underwear watched. The music isn&amp;rsquo;t half-bad either - fast paced and innocuous enough to not be obnoxious. Overall, an excellent experience.&lt;/p&gt;


&lt;img style=&quot;width: 448px&quot; src=&quot;/assets/images/arcades/ging0007.png&quot; /&gt;

&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Plus it features this babe in some capacity.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;That&#039;s enough for now. I&#039;ll probably do this again some time.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Hello. A few days ago I posted a thing about some arcade games I played. Well, I was pretty bored that night, so I actually played a few more games than I had room to write about in a single post. Here are my thoughts about a couple more as they were pulled randomly from my library of obscure and old arcade games.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Tazz-Mania&lt;/strong&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;1982 - Stern Electronics Inc.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/arcades/tazm0002.png&quot; /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Back in the day before people really figured out what video games really were, people were free to experiment with all sorts of horrible and almost unplayable gameplay styles. I fear this is one of those experiments. From the early 80&amp;rsquo;s graphics to the &amp;ldquo;PULL STICK FOR INSTRUCTIONS&amp;rdquo; message, I&amp;rsquo;m not getting a good feeling about this one.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I figure I had better pull the stick to see what&amp;rsquo;s up with this, and it shows me a laundry-list of different scores I can apparently get, followed by a screen explaining how the game works. The explanation proceeds to explode before I can read it. No matter, I&amp;rsquo;m a long-time video game player and I basically have infinite quarters, so let&amp;rsquo;s do this, Tazz Mania.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/arcades/tazmania.png&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;wat&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Okay, so I&amp;rsquo;m some green thing, and there are a bunch of red . . . things, and there are some . . . yellow . . . face . . . things . . .&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;And the yellow things touched me and we both exploded. Okay, lesson one: don&amp;rsquo;t touch the yellow face things. What does any of this have to do with Tazmania? With my second &amp;lsquo;up&amp;rsquo; I discovered that I have some sort of gun! A gun that only shoots when I push a button and move in a direction, so I have to move toward the thing I&amp;rsquo;m trying to shoot. Great. Also apparently this is &amp;ldquo;The Face Room.&amp;rdquo; Time to hunt me some faces.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/arcades/tazm0001.png&quot; /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I take out a few of the things before they finally get me. The walls are slowly closing in, but I&amp;rsquo;ll be damned if those yellow face things take me alive. I&amp;rsquo;ll spit hellfire from my gun or whatever at those damned monsters until they pry this little yellow line from my cold, green hands. Tell my green wife-thing or whatever and presumably smaller green children if I have them that I love them. I die like I lived - not really understanding what the Hell. Next.&lt;/p&gt;


&lt;p&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Bells &amp; Wistles&lt;/strong&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;or, apparently, &lt;strong&gt;&amp;ldquo;Detana!! Twin Bee&amp;rdquo;&lt;/strong&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;1991 - Konami&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This is one of many of my arcade roms that comes in multiple versions - in this case an American version and a Japanese one. Obviously I&amp;rsquo;m going to choose the version with all the exclamation marks. Without a clear shtick for how I&amp;rsquo;m going to make fun of this game, I&amp;rsquo;ll just type out my thoughts as I have them.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/arcades/detatwin.png&quot; /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I think this is one of those &amp;ldquo;bullet hell&amp;rdquo; games where you fly around with everything shooting at you and try not to die. It also apparently - from the attractor loop (you know, the gameplay that plays while waiting for some kid to plop in some quarters) - features shooting at a bell for some reason, so like 90% of the sounds spewing out of my speakers right now are this constant horrible lo-fi ringing bell sound. Let&amp;rsquo;s get this over with.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Dear God, just putting in quarters elicits an excruciating sound effect. I don&amp;rsquo;t know why Konami would want to so immediately and severely punish someone for giving them money.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/arcades/deta0004.png&quot; /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Now there&amp;rsquo;s some chick saying Japanese at me. I&amp;rsquo;m starting to regret picking the Japanese version of this game.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This is some epic music, though.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;We&amp;rsquo;re like 45 seconds in and she&amp;rsquo;s still yapping away. That&amp;rsquo;s a crazy long time for an arcade game to go without even an explosion.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This chick isn&amp;rsquo;t even showing any skin.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/arcades/deta0000.png&quot; /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Okay, the chick disappeared and now I&amp;rsquo;m some sort of floating bubble-man with clouds around me. For a &amp;ldquo;bullet hell&amp;rdquo; game there sure aren&amp;rsquo;t many bullets.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I can fix that pretty quick, since I can be a source of bullets.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/arcades/deta0002.png&quot; /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I shot at a cloud and a bell popped out. Sure. I can keep shooting the bell and it travels along with me. Then some strawberries flew by in formation, followed by some turnips, and corn, and then a different kind of corn. Those are carrots, I guess? What the hell is going on?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/arcades/deta0001.png&quot; /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Then a raspberry appeared, summoning its juicy pods or whatever from the very sky around us. Flashing once, it shot at me, killing both me and the bell I had been taking with me this whole time.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I&amp;rsquo;ve lost the will to carry on. I&amp;rsquo;m not sure if I had any to begin with.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I know I complained about games being too much like real life, but this is perhaps a bit too &amp;ldquo;out there.&amp;rdquo; Maybe if the sound effects and music weren&amp;rsquo;t conspiring together to make me want to rip my own ears off and feed them to the designers of this game, I could stand it a bit longer.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I think I&#039;ll go lay down for a bit, now.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Hello. For a few years I&#039;ve had this collection of old arcade roms, computerized versions of arcade games from the 80&#039;s and early 90&#039;s. The other night I was just super bored so I decided to play a few and write down my thoughts about them. You might remember that from when I already made two posts about it, or maybe this is the first one you&#039;ve read because it&#039;s pretty great. Anyway, here&#039;s another game I played and then wrote about.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Mutation Nation&lt;/strong&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;1992 - SNK CORP OF AMERICA&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/arcades/mutn0016.png&quot; /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In 1990, SNK released the Neo Geo, a cartridge-based console you could buy for your home or put inside an arcade machine. I&amp;rsquo;ve never seen one of the consoles anywhere, but the arcades are still in use. Generally speaking, Neo Geo arcade games are the best arcade games. I&amp;rsquo;m just informing you of that so you join me in my high expectations for this particular one. The chrome lettering and ominous skyline on the title screen should add to your high expectations.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;One standard on Neo Geo games is that they&amp;rsquo;re all controlled with a stick and four buttons. Since it&amp;rsquo;s a console it has to have pretty standardized controls. Most games didn&amp;rsquo;t use all four buttons. I think it was required for games to have a sort &amp;ldquo;how to play&amp;rdquo; sequence where you see a magic floating finger push each button to show you what it does. That&amp;rsquo;s a bit more handy than Tazz-mania, but it&amp;rsquo;s not terribly necessary since this game has one button for jumping and another for kicking.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/arcades/mutn0018.png&quot; /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;And oh boy is there kicking! According to the attractor loop, there&amp;rsquo;s going to be some pretty awesome feats of feets in my future.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/arcades/mutn0015.png&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;There&amp;rsquo;s apparently also something called a &amp;ldquo;Torneado attack.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Mutant Nation is an example of some genre they don&amp;rsquo;t make much anymore, where you&amp;rsquo;re a Bad Dude and you&amp;rsquo;re beating up other Dudes of questionable Badness. In this game you play as a real Dude so Bad he has a pair of fists permanently hoisted in combat mode. While this probably makes a lot of things difficult - getting dressed, for instance - it surely leaves him uniquely suited to beating up, well, a nation of mutants I guess.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/arcades/mutn0000.png&quot; /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Upon starting Stage 1, this building behind me immediate exploded. That really set a high bar for the rest of the Stage. Well, it set a high bar for excitement, but a pretty low bar for what&amp;rsquo;s expected of me, effort-wise, if buildings are going to just explode around me from the sheer Badness of my Dude. I think the Neo Geo also had an explosion requirement in its games, so Mutant Nation was doing reasonably well so far.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/arcades/mutnat.png&quot; /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The first Dudes on the express train to Badville are some identically dressed triplets that fell from the sky all around me. SNK was trying to ease me into the whole mutant nation, I guess. In usual &amp;ldquo;beat-em-up&amp;rsquo; fashion, all three of the dudes casually walked off screen where I couldn&amp;rsquo;t see them. Maybe if I knew how to do that Torneado attack I&amp;rsquo;d have been able to bring them back over to me for some kicking.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Or maybe they were just three Dudes trying to make their way in this nation of mutants and some jerk with a leather jacket and blue jeans had just blown up their apartment building. The only context Mutant Nation gives is that you are a Dude in some sort of Mutant Nation (titular, in fact), and since I was apparently a normal looking (albeit Bad) Dude, I have to assume that I was the invader. I&amp;rsquo;m not sure how I feel about that.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/arcades/mutn0001.png&quot; /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Soon my first taste of a &amp;ldquo;real&amp;rdquo; mutant arrived. He had like a fish head with tentacles coming out of it. I punched him until he was flung off the screen from the force of my fist (fistforce). Was he just walking to work? Why was he wearing kneepads? These are questions I don&amp;rsquo;t think this game has answers to. All I knew is that I simply had to collect that glowing &amp;ldquo;B&amp;rdquo; on the ground.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Soon more of those fish dudes showed up. They looked hungry, so I gave them a taste of my knuckle sandwich. I was promised some serious kicking and so far I&amp;rsquo;d primarily only seen punching. I was really starting to root for those mutants. The few fish dudes that didn&amp;rsquo;t get knocked off the screen entirely fall to the ground and dissolve into a pool of some sort of green sludge. I was murdering these people for no reason.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/arcades/mutn0002.png&quot; /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Then this pointy dude showed up. I&amp;rsquo;m not sure what his role was in this mutant society, but he had some sort of strange joint condition and the most awkwardly pointy shoes I&amp;rsquo;ve ever seen. My strategy was to keep punching him until he exploded. That strategy panned out. Still, this pointy dude seemed pretty important. He obviously had a lot going on, and I&amp;rsquo;m now worried there&amp;rsquo;s some weird-looking lady out there with a collection of strangely pointy children who won&amp;rsquo;t get to see their father anymore.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I eventually figured out that you can charge up your power somehow and unleash it in a burst of energy. Maybe I was a mutant after all! I wasn&amp;rsquo;t some racist jerk invading a country to beat up innocent locals, I was just a serial murderer targeting his own kind.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;At least, I hoped so. Alas, though, I was a regular Bad Dude. That glowing &amp;ldquo;B&amp;rdquo; I found is what gave me that power. Now I was using their own weapons against them.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/arcades/mutn0004.png&quot; /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;My fists continued their quest to crack some mutant bones, finding a few more of those triplets, some dudes that transformed into some sort of weasel things, and some guys that transformed into giant beetles only to charge directly offscreen never to be seen again. Life is diverse and fascinating in Mutant Nation, and I was determined to bring that diversity down by the fistfull.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/arcades/mutn0007.png&quot; /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The second boss was a guy with like tentacle arms I guess and a pack of green dogs. They all got the punching of their lives - specifically the end of their lives.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I&amp;rsquo;ve noticed that many of the buildings seen in the background are in various levels of decay or halted construction. Had the Mutant Nation economy been crippled by the invasion of Bad Dudes murdering them? If only a recession could be defeated by punching it. I&amp;rsquo;d put an end to that really quickly. I marched into one of the buildings because these mutants couldn&amp;rsquo;t cower in their puny slums forever.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/arcades/mutn0008.png&quot; /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I&amp;rsquo;d wandered into an old art museum. Most of the paintings were of Dali-esque still lifes or landscapes. This nation of mutants was desperate to find an escape in fantasies as bizarre and twisted as they were. The party was over, though. There was to be no art appreciation while this Bad Dude had anything to say about it.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/arcades/mutn0009.png&quot; /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The next room was full of multiple copies of the same statue of some perfectly sculpted specimen of man. Poor mutant children must walk through this room, a look of shameful confusion on their tentacle-laden fish-faces, wondering why these statues look so different from them and all their friends (except I guess their friends who are all apparently just copies of that one guy).  There was no time for all that, though, because I had to punch this huge dude a whole bunch of times. Punch him hard. Maybe he was the art curator, or perhaps he was just a really big guy trying to enjoy his day off.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/arcades/mutn0010.png&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;His mutant power was apparently &amp;ldquo;being Odin.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This guy sure was big, but that just left me right at crotch-punching level, so I took advantage of that - many times. He jumped at me and the entire floor buckled underneath us. Some curator he was, destroying his own museum. Still, you have to admire his fashion sense. Where other mutants are content with t-shirts and knee pads (the knee pad industry was apparently doing quite well in Mutant Nation), this guy was going full skull-armor.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/arcades/mutn0013.png&quot; /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I kept punching him until his armor grew a head and starts trying to bite me. This fight was getting weird (even for a nation of mutants), so I stopped screwing around and started punching him extra hard. By that, of course, I mean &amp;ldquo;used several continues&amp;rdquo; because I am, after all, not the best at video games. Good thing my mom gave me lots of quarters.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/arcades/mutn0014.png&quot; /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Sated with mutant killing in this Area, the Bad Dude cracked his knuckles and pointed defiantly offscreen. What was he pointing at? This game only raises questions, never answers. I had lost my taste for mutant blood, and found I had a hard time venturing onward without more impetus than a flashing icon shouting &amp;ldquo;GO&amp;rdquo; at me. Perhaps someday we will find peace with the inhabitants of Mutant Nation, but as long as there Dudes eager to prove how Bad they are, I fear there will always be senseless violence and destruction. I encourage you all to contact your local senators and representatives to raise awareness of this awful state of affairs.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Sound design and music were perfectly adequate.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I&#039;ve been working in an office of some fashion for several years, now. In that time, I&#039;ve learned that things can get pretty boring, especially in those couple summer months when everybody just wants to go outside. If you also work in an office with an indeterminate number of coworkers, there&#039;s one sure-fire way around the doldrums. &lt;em&gt;Pranks.&lt;/em&gt; Here are some suggestions, in order of when I thought of them.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Cut the power lines to somebody&#039;s office. No, I don&#039;t mean flip the breaker or something - I&#039;m talking that scene from early in &lt;em&gt;Die Hard&lt;/em&gt; when the big German dude saws all the phone lines clean through.&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt;Cubicle walls are hollow. Fill somebody&#039;s cubicle panels with milk. It takes a few days to pay off, but oh boy is it great.&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt;Hide in a cabinet in the break room. Every time somebody sets a fork or spoon out and opens the fridge, quietly grab the spoon or fork and hide it.&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt;Follow someone home and take pictures of them in private moments, then set those pictures as their desktop background while they&#039;re in the bathroom.&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt;Get an honest afternoon&#039;s work in - but give somebody else credit. Your boss will be expecting that much work from then on, so that guy&#039;s just screwed.&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt;Dress up like your boss and go around telling everybody they can take off early.&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt;Clog every toilet in the building. When everybody goes to see what the fuck, set all their desktop backgrounds as pictures of you clogging every toilet.&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt;Rename just totally every file in somebody&#039;s computer.&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt;Take something off a dude&#039;s desk, and then send them a picture of it in front of the building. When they go to get it, set their desktop background as a picture of, I don&#039;t know, your junk or something.&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt;Unleash a handful of rats on the floor. If you don&#039;t know how to get your hands full of rats, you&#039;re on your own.&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt;Work from home? No problem. Just get yourself a cat, and it&#039;s like somebody&#039;s constantly playing pranks on &lt;em&gt;you&lt;/em&gt; - usually involving poop.&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt;With a small pin or needle, poke a hole in the bottom of somebody&#039;s diet coke cans, so when they grab their afternoon &quot;pick-me-up&quot; they&#039;re all empty.&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt;Pour honey or syrup into somebody&#039;s keyboard, then release a horde of ants on their desk.&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt;Keep replacing something in the break room with laxatives. Give cryptic clues about what.&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt;Set somebody&#039;s desktop background to a picture of you setting their desktop background. When they&#039;re changing it back, take a picture of it and set that as YOUR desktop background. That will really throw them off.&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt;Remove the hydraulic fluid from someone&#039;s office chair. Do office chairs have hydraulic fluid? If not, just remove all of the bolts from someone&#039;s office chair, or saw like 9/10ths of the way through one of the legs or something. When the company charges him for breaking company property, scan the bill and set it as his desktop background.&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt;Straight up set fire to everything.&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Lego is awesome. Really I could probably just say that and be done with it. I don&#039;t think anybody would have any arguments to the contrary, and if they did they suck and I hate them anyway. There&#039;s something so unique, so perfect, about those little pieces - and something so genius about their designers. If you do the math, with just two standard 4x2 bricks (probably the piece you are thinking of when you visualize the quintessential Lego piece), you can combine them in 24 different ways - that&#039;s just two pieces. Take six of those bricks, and you get almost one billion unique arrangements, give or take a few if you happen lose one in the couch or something. Now consider that &nbsp;in 2012 and 2013, the Lego Group produced about 3,600 unique pieces (according to the database on Rebrickable). Now further consider that any of those 3,600 pieces will be able to interact and interconnect with any of the 17,477 unique pieces that have been produced dating all the way back to the 50&#039;s. To put it plainly: pieces you could go out and buy today (or, for example, any of the thousands of pieces I have scattered around me as I write this) are fully compatible - perhaps even identical - to any pieces made over the last fifty years (including all the pieces that have been lost in the couch or the vacuum). Between the Lego Group&amp;rsquo;s extensive attention to detail and dedication to their product&amp;rsquo;s original thesis, the world of Lego offers countless adventures without restriction or limit, and what was once just a child&#039;s toy has evolved into the perfect hobby for adults.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I have always loved Lego. The majority of my childhood was spent building, playing with, organizing, thinking about, or losing Lego bricks. I can&#039;t fathom just how much time I spent flipping through Lego catalogues when I was a kid, memorizing any sets I had the slightest chance of getting some day, and trying to ignore the ones I knew I&#039;d never be able to afford - but obsessing over them anyway. If I had spent as much time studying, I don&#039;t know, physics or something as much as I studied the top of the line Lego sets from the mid 90&#039;s, I&#039;d have had a PhD by the time I was 14. Lego pieces were everything - literally - and though I strayed from time to time to things like Transformers or G.I.Joe, I always came back. I certainly wasn&#039;t alone, either. I doubt any child made it through the 90&#039;s without at least once shaking a wrapped Christmas present to listen for the unmistakable rattle that meant you had struck gold. That sound will always bring me back to that exciting worry-free time when a tiny little square of plastic could be anything. At the time it was certain that the Lego Group was forever, and those days would never end.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Then the 2000&#039;s hit. It was a period of turmoil, both in my relationship with those little plastic bits, and for the bits themselves. The most casual research of Lego will turn up lots of information about what is considered the &quot;dark age&quot; of the toy, around the early 2000&#039;s (probably as little as just opening Netflix might bring you to that &lt;em&gt;Inside Lego&lt;/em&gt; documentary which details the struggles and eventual triumph of the Lego Group through the period). It&#039;s hard not to feel just a little responsible, really, considering the company was close to going under right around the same time that I had moved on in my life, to pointless and futile grownup pursuits (like computer games or girls). I wasn&#039;t a kid anymore, and so I just couldn&#039;t justify spending money on toys. It&#039;s a sentiment apparently reflected by most of Lego&#039;s major audience in the early 2000&#039;s, apparently driving the company to the verge of failure - except that they didn&#039;t fail, and no matter how much I tried to deny it, I was still in love. That enchanting rattle, that satisfying way in which those pieces fit, those years spent playing and collecting and dreaming and finding pieces in the vacuum will never leave me.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;After years (even decades) of denial, I came crawling back. The last several months has seen me spending quite a bit of time and money feeding my passion once again. Perhaps my resurgence has been fueled by the fantastic &lt;em&gt;The Lego Movie&lt;/em&gt; (and its tie-in sets), or the fact that over the years Lego has only gotten exponentially more awesome. Perhaps I&#039;m just being guided naturally by the fact that no video games are really capturing my attention like they used to, or I&#039;m getting over my twinge of shame I have always felt at just wanting to play with a dumb toy all the time. The fact is that though other hobbies and interests have come and gone through my life, Lego has always been the constant - that secret guilty pleasure, maybe my only source of real happiness, that I&#039;m done trying to justify. Frankly it is high time we all stopped fighting our guilty pleasures. Why deny yourself the pleasure if you can just as easily simply deny yourself the guilt? There&#039;s nothing wrong with an adult enjoying a hobby.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The problem any adult with a hobby faces, though, is figuring out just what direction to take that hobby. I have too much disposable income these days to limit my impulse purchases to a few sets at a time, and I&#039;m not quite rich enough to go ahead and buy everything. I love seeing the brand new stuff the Lego Group comes out with every few months, but I also feel like I owe it to Young Me to get my hands on some of those sets from the 90&#039;s that I looked at for hours in those old catalogues - or even the ones from the 80&#039;s that I don&#039;t even really know much about. I want to have my own massive basement world just like in &lt;em&gt;The Lego Movie&lt;/em&gt; (honestly, who doesn&#039;t?), but I have no basement - massive or otherwise - in which to build it. My tastes are too varied and open to limit myself to just Pirates, or just Star Wars, or just any one kind of set. I&#039;m a sort who needs to feel like he&#039;s going somewhere with his toy purchases. I need a plan.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Plenty of &quot;perfectly normal adults&quot; collect Lego, as it happens. Some of those people are collectors who - like with any vintage toy, presumably - buy and sell unopened original sets from history. Today you can find Lego sets on EBay or elsewhere dating from all the way back to the &nbsp;50&#039;s when Lego was first a thing. Vintage collectors spend literally thousands of dollars on what amounts to old cardboard boxes that rattle when you shake them. These people are obviously wackos (although I will admit that they probably have an excellent track record of not losing pieces in the couch). Another type of collector is after minifigures, the little dudes that come with each set. You can find plenty of sets online for huge discounts - because someone bought them simply to add the dudes to their collection and ignore the rest. To me, Lego is about building stuff (and the emotional roller coaster that is searching for lost pieces). For me it isn&#039;t about ticking off checkboxes, so I don&#039;t think minifigure hunting is for me either. I am happy to take those figure-less sets off your hands, though.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Lego doesn&#039;t have to just be about &quot;pure&quot; collecting (not that there&amp;rsquo;s anything wrong with it if that&#039;s your thing). Some Adult Fans of Lego (abbreviated AFOL by the online communities) could be called &quot;displayers&quot; - people who buy all of the sets (or certain ones that pique their interests) so they can put it together once and put it out on a shelf to admire and appreciate. There are also builders, people who post ridiculously complicated custom builds on the Internet that make the rest of us feel inadequate and&nbsp;say &lt;em&gt;&quot;how do you even have that many pieces?&quot;&lt;/em&gt; Ultimately, it seems as if there are as many motivations for collecting Lego bricks as there are Lego bricks. You might find these pieces in classrooms, board rooms, dorm rooms, bed rooms, work rooms, or probably a lot of other places that don&#039;t have the word &#039;room&#039; in their names. It&#039;s so versatile no matter what kind of hobby you&#039;re looking for, chances are you&#039;ll find something to enjoy.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It is this versatility that really excites me about Lego, I think. When I was a kid, I had adventures with cursed mummies in Egypt, explored space, fought over deep-sea crystals or whatever, developed a Space Shuttle program, managed a busy commercial harbor, learned about engineering and mechanics, attacked (and defended) the Death Star, held numerous races, of both Formula One and Pod formats, build detailed working models of things, besieged castles, fought pirates, decorated my entire room (and sometimes house), fought robots, built robots, and planned entire cities - all with &lt;em&gt;the same toy&lt;/em&gt;. Okay, okay, so technically those are all different iterations of the same toy system. When you get down to it, though, they all have the same parts, and as I said up at the beginning of all this rambling, all those parts are the same parts as the parts kids are playing with today. Sure, The Lego Group does introduce new ones all the time - as well as retire older ones. A lot of times, these are just new or old colors to support different themes. They&#039;re still the same basic pieces, and even if they aren&amp;rsquo;t, they fit right in with everything that has come before. The instructions, too, are as open and universal as possible. Literally every single set of instructions from ever is available online for free (most of them through the Lego Group directly, others through a third party). Once you have the instructions, websites exist where you can find basically any Lego set ever made (or any individual pieces) being sold used (or even new) by collectors and retailers all over the planet.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;All that means the Lego System is extremely easy to get into, and it&#039;s even easier to get deeper once you&#039;re in. I was looking through the online Lego databases at some of those old sets I used to pine away for (old habits die hard - even after almost two decades). Lego is Lego, so all those old sets have (pretty much) all of the same parts as these that I have scattered around me right now, and the instructions for them are literally a click away. I started thinking about dudes who, over the course of years, slowly assemble hand-made hot-rods or motorcycles in their garage. The pieces fit together so well. How many other sets or bulk pieces would you have to buy to be able to make any given set? How many sets could I make right now with what I have?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So the point of all this rambling is that I do finally have the answer. I now not only have a clear and specific mission to pursue, but I even have a perfectly viable justification for pursuing it, as well as parallels to established &quot;adult&quot; hobbies that should shut up even the most harsh critic (for example my own nagging requirements for a sense of purpose). It&#039;s cleaner (probably cheaper, too) than building a hot rod in my garage - and it doesn&#039;t even require a garage (or Tim Allen). It allows me to explore the history of my favorite and longest standing passion in life. It gives me a guideline to direct my otherwise random and impulsive usage of disposable income. All I have to do is pick a set, download the instructions, and get to work. Perhaps I had better get going.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So in conclusion, whether you&#039;re a collector, a designer, an engineer, or you just like to play, you have a home in Lego. In fact, even if you aren&#039;t one of those (you boring person, you), you can still probably find a reason to enjoy a Lego brick or two. I&#039;ve been playing with the things for twenty five years or something, and I&#039;m still discovering new ways to enjoy them. I can&#039;t wait to dive into the archives to start building some old-, and really old-school designs. I also can&#039;t wait to see next year&#039;s sets, and to pick up some of the &lt;em&gt;Guardians of the Galaxy&lt;/em&gt; stuff (I have a certain thing for &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/post/372/Halloween_Costume_2011_The_Final_Chapter&quot;&gt;Groot&lt;/a&gt;). After all this rambling, though, there&#039;s still a certain indefinable quality about Lego bricks. How can you describe the satisfaction of connecting two tiny interlocking plastic bits or the pure, blissful anticipation of something as simple as shaking a rattling box? Lego is just, well, awesome. What more can I say?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Keep building, my friends - just make sure you check the couch and vacuum.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In case you &lt;a href=&quot;http://i.imgur.com/HVNBWD5.gif&quot;&gt;didn&#039;t read&lt;/a&gt; my last post about Lego (don&#039;t worry, this one has pictures!), I&#039;m starting a new long-term project involving one of my absolute favoritest things (spoiler alert, it&#039;s Lego): Lego. My plan is to reach deep into the annals of time (why are you giggling?) and pick one of the old-school sets from my childhood that I&#039;ve always wanted to build. I&#039;m then going to slowly, perhaps over the course of years, put that set together. The first step in the process, of course, is picking which set I&#039;m going to be building.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;For me, picking a classic set was quick and there&#039;s no point belaboring it any further (but perhaps you&#039;ll allow me a bit of dramatic embellishment). Thinking back on all those catalogues I used to look at from the 90&#039;s, there was no theme I coveted more than &lt;a href=&quot;http://brickset.com/sets/theme-Model-Team&quot;&gt;Model Team&lt;/a&gt;. If you aren&#039;t familiar, basically once a year through the 90&#039;s, the Lego Group came out with a no-holds-barred, super detailed vehicle with no arbitrary scale or price constraints. They varied wildly in price, since there was apparently no specific guideline on how big they should be. Historically the price points for various themes and set sizes are pretty set-in-stone specific - you can be pretty sure that for any given theme you&#039;ll have a small &lt;a href=&quot;http://brickset.com/sets/70400-1/Forest-Ambush&quot;&gt;set&lt;/a&gt; or &lt;a href=&quot;http://brickset.com/sets/6918-1/Blacksmith-Attack&quot;&gt;two&lt;/a&gt;, a &lt;a href=&quot;http://brickset.com/sets/70401-1/Gold-Getaway&quot;&gt;couple&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=&quot;http://brickset.com/sets/70402-1/The-Gatehouse-Raid&quot;&gt;mediums&lt;/a&gt;, and generally one &lt;a href=&quot;http://brickset.com/sets/70404-1/King-s-Castle&quot;&gt;biggon&#039;&lt;/a&gt; that would basically be all you got for Christmas that year. You couldn&#039;t really be certain about Model Team, though - they ranged from $40 all the way up to $140.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/Lego/modelteam.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The Model Team Logo in the 90&#039;s.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;These were the cream of the crop. Back when a few bricks clumped around some wheels settled (albeit acceptably) for &quot;&lt;a href=&quot;http://brickset.com/sets/1702-1/Fire-Fighter-4-x-4&quot;&gt;car&lt;/a&gt;&quot; these were beautifully detailed, sophisticated, and expertly crafted models consisting of hundreds of pieces. No one 90&#039;s product line stands out more than Model Team, and no Model Team set comes close to the one that dominated the back page of the 1996 Lego Shop at Home Catalog. This set marked the climax for Model Team in both number of pieces and price, and it definitely marked a high point in Lego history. Some might even call it the most unabashedly &lt;em&gt;serious&lt;/em&gt; Lego set of all time.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I&#039;m talking, of course, about &lt;a href=&quot;http://brickset.com/sets/5571-1/Giant-Truck&quot;&gt;5571: Giant Truck&lt;/a&gt;. Even the name was right to the point. With 1742 very specific parts, it&#039;s probably going to take me quite a while to get it finished, the perfect choice for my hot-rod-in-the-garage project. Other sets might have come out that were &lt;a href=&quot;http://brickset.com/sets/theme-Advanced-Models&quot;&gt;bigger&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;http://brickset.com/sets/8258-1/Crane-Truck&quot;&gt;more complicated&lt;/a&gt;, or &lt;a href=&quot;http://brickset.com/sets/10179-1/Ultimate-Collector-s-Millennium-Falcon&quot;&gt;more detailed&lt;/a&gt;. Other sets might have better, more &lt;a href=&quot;http://brickset.com/sets/76023-1/The-Tumbler&quot;&gt;sophisticated&lt;/a&gt; construction or have &lt;a href=&quot;http://brickset.com/sets/4997-1/Transport-Ferry&quot;&gt;more features&lt;/a&gt;. Other sets might even be built using nothing but parts I already own. However, no other set comes close to Giant Truck in my heart.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/Lego/5571-1.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;So cool.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Giant Truck (also called &quot;The Black Cat&quot;) was introduced by The Lego Group (TLG) in 1996. I&#039;m pretty sure it was their attempt to see just what they could come up with given no restraint whatsoever. In the same year, TLG introduced some of the sets I most fondly remember playing with for years afterword - sets like &lt;a href=&quot;http://brickset.com/sets/6335-1/Indy-Transport&quot;&gt;6335: Indy Transport&lt;/a&gt;, a set that saw countless hours of my attention, &lt;a href=&quot;http://brickset.com/sets/6248-1/Volcano-Island&quot;&gt;6248: Volcano Island&lt;/a&gt;, a set that I&#039;m literally looking at on my desk as I type this, &lt;a href=&quot;http://brickset.com/sets/6331-1/Patriot-Jet&quot;&gt;6331: Patriot Jet&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;http://brickset.com/sets/1821-1/Rally-Racers&quot;&gt;1821: Rally Racers&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;http://brickset.com/sets/8230-1/Coastal-Cop-Buggy&quot;&gt;8230: Coastal Copy Buggy&lt;/a&gt;, and &lt;a href=&quot;http://brickset.com/sets/1728-1/Crystal-Crawler&quot;&gt;1728: Crystal Crawler&lt;/a&gt;, one of the best &lt;a href=&quot;http://brickset.com/sets/theme-Aquazone&quot;&gt;Aquazone&lt;/a&gt; sets. 1996 also saw the &lt;a href=&quot;http://brickset.com/sets/theme-Space/subtheme-Exploriens&quot;&gt;Exploriens&lt;/a&gt;, the key Lego space sub-theme from my childhood - &lt;a href=&quot;http://brickset.com/sets/6982-1/Explorien-Starship&quot;&gt;6982: Explorien Starship&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;http://brickset.com/sets/6899-1/Nebula-Outpost&quot;&gt;6899: Nebula Outpost&lt;/a&gt;, and &lt;a href=&quot;http://brickset.com/sets/6856-1/Planetary-Decoder&quot;&gt;6856: Planetary Decoder&lt;/a&gt; saw a lot of adventures in my house. Also released in 1996, of course, was &lt;a href=&quot;http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Star_Trek:_First_Contact&quot;&gt;Star Trek: First Contact&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Super_Mario_64&quot;&gt;Super Mario 64&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Duke_Nukem_3D&quot;&gt;Duke Nukem 3D&lt;/a&gt;, and &lt;a href=&quot;http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richard_D._James_Album&quot;&gt;Richard D. James Album&lt;/a&gt;. The point is, it was a good year full of a lot of things I have spent a lot of hours with. However, I still stared at that catalog, dreaming of the one thing I knew I would never get.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/Lego/from-lego-1996-catalog.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;This is from the German catalog, but you get the point.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So first things first. The Lego group claims to host &lt;a href=&quot;http://service.lego.com/en-us/buildinginstructions&quot;&gt;instructions&lt;/a&gt; for over 3300 Lego models dating back to 2002. That definitely doesn&#039;t include Giant Truck by about six years, but I searched for it anyway.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/Lego/found_one_product.PNG&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Oh, Lego, I love you.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Come on, though, they have to have Giant Truck. It&#039;s probably a matter of national pride in Denmark. I&#039;m pretty sure it&#039;s on their flag.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/Lego/danish_flag.png&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;I don&#039;t really remember what the Danish flag looks like, but that looks right.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Anyway, before I really dive in, we might as well humor the possibility of just buying this thing. There are several places where you can buy old Lego sets. The first, probably most obvious, option is &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ebay.com&quot;&gt;Ebay&lt;/a&gt;. I pulled up a &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ebay.com/sch/i.html?_from=R40&amp;_trksid=p2050601.m570.l1313.TR3.TRC2.A0.H0.Xlego+5571.TRS0&amp;_nkw=lego+5571&amp;_sacat=0&quot;&gt;quick search&lt;/a&gt; and immediately saw a brand new, never opened Giant Truck for - brace yourself - &lt;a href=&quot;http://i.imgur.com/T2gTaye.gif&quot;&gt;$1,325&lt;/a&gt;. In case you&#039;re wondering what sort of investment an unopened Lego model can be, that&#039;s a &lt;a href=&quot;http://i.imgur.com/j74SykU.gif&quot;&gt;946%&lt;/a&gt; return on the $140 investment that set would have been if you bought it new. There&#039;s another brand new Giant Truck auction ending today with a current high bid of $890 - a relative steal! Obviously I&#039;m not going to be buying one of those.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/Lego/ebay-5571.png&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Presumably those 14 watchers are all like I was with that catalog back in &#039;96.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Another source for old Lego stuff is called &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.bricklink.com&quot;&gt;BrickLink&lt;/a&gt;. It even sports a design from the 90&#039;s! Don&#039;t let the general shady appearance of the place fool you - it&#039;s a fantastic resource. I can confirm that to some extent. I have made exactly one purchase from somebody on BrickLink (that&#039;s a bit of a spoiler for later on). Some trepidation for BrickLink wouldn&#039;t be unjustified, I think, but considering just how long it&#039;s been around (since 2000) and how many buyers and sellers they have (312,353 registered users), I&#039;m guessing there are more good experiences than bad. You can certainly find any &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9FA__4fLBos&quot;&gt;Lego or Lego accessory&lt;/a&gt; you might be looking for there, being sold by one or more of the (as noted on the site) 8,563 different stores. It works like Ebay, sort of, acting simply as a broker between Lego sellers and Lego buyers. As a result, I imagine, the quality is more in the court of the specific people you deal with rather than BrickLink itself. There are extensive rating and problem handling tools, though, so like Ebay your reputation is on the line if you try to be a &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.google.com/search?q=knucklehead&quot;&gt;knucklehead&lt;/a&gt;. Everybody there is united in a common love of all things Lego, though, so there&#039;s already a heightened sense of community.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/Lego/5571-bricklink.png&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;I can basically guarantee you&#039;ll find any set you might want there.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The cheapest Giant Truck &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.bricklink.com/search.asp?q=5571&quot;&gt;right now&lt;/a&gt; is $341. That&#039;s if you want one used, without a box, and shipped from the United Kingdom, which probably won&#039;t be cheap (if you&#039;re a dumb American like me). The cheapest one in the US is $600. Basically we&#039;re still looking at a prohibitive expense.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The last real source for used or old Lego would require that you happen to be lucky enough to have an independent used toy store in your neck of the woods - preferably one that deals specifically in Lego. I just so happen to be lucky enough to have had that happen. Out in the rich-people part of town is a store called &lt;a href=&quot;http://bricksandminifigs.com/&quot;&gt;Bricks &amp; Minifigs&lt;/a&gt;. It&#039;s a great store, and it would be the greatest thing ever if the Internet didn&#039;t exist. Their prices are, if you&#039;re careful, decent (though you&#039;d only really buy new sets there if you&#039;re either insane or insanely rich), and they have an ever-changing assortment of used sets from various eras in their display case. It seems to be, for whatever reason, the place to go if you need one of several specific Star Wars sets that they always seem to have several of. It&#039;s not the place to go if you&#039;re looking for a very specific and extremely high-priced set from the 90&#039;s. They do have at least one brand new &lt;a href=&quot;http://brickset.com/sets/theme-Advanced-Models&quot;&gt;10197: Fire Brigade&lt;/a&gt;, one of the highest user-rated sets out there, which was discontinued a while ago. It&#039;s pretty &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.bricklink.com/search.asp?pg=1&amp;q=10197&amp;invNew=N&amp;itemType=S&amp;viewFrom=sf&amp;sz=10&amp;searchSort=P&quot;&gt;expensive&lt;/a&gt;, as you might imagine. They don&#039;t, however, have Giant Truck, so don&#039;t even ask.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/Lego/bricks-n-minifigs.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;I&#039;m very lucky to have this resource nearby. I&#039;m sorry that I took this with my phone.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Bricks and Minifigs does - in addition to making grammar awkward - have three huge bins of random parts that you can buy by the bucket- or bag-full. This might come in handy later if I need any specific, but not terribly rare, parts. I think it&#039;s safe to say I will be needing some parts at some point in this project.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/Lego/5571-stickers.PNG&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;And stickers, I guess. I&#039;m just going to not worry about that right now.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So then the question becomes one of logistics. What ground rules, if any, should I set down for how I acquire those parts that I don&#039;t yet have? I could be strict about where they come from - specifying that they have to be from a certain vintage or that I have to get them all out of actual sets. However, I don&#039;t think I&#039;m going to be that hard on myself. Just a cursory bit of checking parts lists online shows that Giant Truck needs like twenty of several parts that only appear at most in quantities of four in other sets. I&#039;m &lt;a href=&quot;http://i.imgur.com/QgFzD8m.gif&quot;&gt;not&lt;/a&gt; about to buy five copies of a Lego set from the 90&#039;s for a hundred bucks a pop just to have enough of, for example, these guys:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/Lego/609126.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Officially: 609126 Brick 1 x 2 x 11/3 with Curved Top (Black)&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It&#039;s clear then that Giant Truck is not even close to the ideal set for showcasing how easily you could make a particular set using parts out of a bunch of other ones. What Giant Truck might be perfect for, however, is trying out as many sources for parts as I can. Perhaps that will be the central thesis of this whole thing (other than &quot;Giant Truck is awesome&quot;). What method for sourcing particular pieces is the most fun, or the easiest, or the cheapest? I&#039;ll look for parts in my own collection, by buying both used and new sets, in those bulk bins at that store I&#039;m super lucky to have in my town, ordering them online, or even digging through the vacuum - I&#039;ll leave no stone unturned in my quest for all 1,742 pieces of the Black Cat.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In my next article / post / essay / whatever this is, I&#039;ll actually show some Lego pieces being put together. In the meantime, keep on building - and if you happen to find any of those curved brick dudes shown above in your vacuum, maybe drop me a line.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;To recap, I&#039;m working on a new long-term project featuring one of my all time most favorite things, Lego. I have gone back to my childhood and picked out an epic, monumental Lego set that I&#039;ve always wanted to build - 1996&#039;s &lt;a href=&quot;http://brickset.com/sets/5571-1/Giant-Truck&quot;&gt;5571: Giant Truck&lt;/a&gt;. I&#039;m going to slowly, perhaps over the course of years, put that set together. I found instructions for the set and ruled out the possibility of buying it (since it&#039;s crazy expensive in the used toy market). Now it&#039;s time to crack open those instructions and actually get started. Well, the instructions are a digital PDF on my computer, so we&#039;ll be doing whatever the digital version of cracking is - double clicking, I guess.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;They just don&#039;t make instructions like they did back in 1996. That&#039;s purely a statement of fact, you can make your own assumptions about which is &quot;better.&quot; The PDF containing Giant Truck&#039;s instructions is 107 pages long. Only 60 of those cover the construction of Giant Truck. The other 47 pages cover the alternate model, some sort of Also-Giant-But-Not-As-Giant Truck. Compare that to a modern &quot;spare no expense&quot; set, &lt;a href=&quot;http://brickset.com/sets/71006-1/The-Simpsons-House&quot;&gt;71006: The Simpsons&#039; House&lt;/a&gt;, which has about 800 more pieces than Giant Truck. The Simpsons&#039; House has 237 pages of instructions spanning three booklets (and no alternate model). That&#039;s five times the instructions for a set that has only 1.4 times the parts.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/Lego/71006-1.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;I purchased this set right after I had some wisdom teeth removed. I mean right after - on the ride home. Oddly enough, I don&#039;t exactly remember doing that. &lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Obviously you should take that statistic with a grain of salt (and keep your weird salt-eating habits away from me, weirdo). The Simpsons&#039; House is a very different kind of set than Giant Truck, so they maybe shouldn&#039;t be compared to each other. I&#039;m no &lt;a href=&quot;http://simpsonswiki.com/w/images/thumb/4/4a/Mathemagician.png/250px-Mathemagician.png&quot;&gt;mathemagician&lt;/a&gt;, so I don&#039;t know how to make numbers prove my points, but I&#039;m pretty sure comparing two things that are only casually related is not the best argument. It&#039;s undeniable, though, that times have changed. The average number of parts in an instruction step has gone way down. If I were some sort of mathman I would be able to quantify this in a meaningful way, but you&#039;ll just have to rely on my crazy old man &quot;I swear it sure seems like it&quot; claims. Perhaps you&#039;ll get an idea of what I&#039;m talking about as we move forward.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/Lego/simpsons-inst-55.PNG&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Compare this random (but average) page from the Simpsons&#039; House to some of the steps we&#039;ll encounter for Giant Truck.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;As I said in the last post, I&#039;m not going to plan ahead and try to gather resources before getting started. I&#039;m going to save time by just diving in and seeing how far I can get with what I already have in the Ol&#039; Archive. Obviously this is paying off, as I am now over two entire posts into this project and nothing has been built yet. All that is about to change, however. Let&#039;s go for it!&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Step 1&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/Lego/5571-step-1.png&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;This is the first page of Giant Truck&#039;s instructions, including the first three steps, and the customary axle sizing guide.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Actually, I am going to have just one more quick digression before going for it. I want to point out that little thumbnail that always shows up at the start of any Lego instructions of the set you&#039;re building (you can see it on the page posted just above). They do this because sometimes the instructions break out and build certain separate components and this shows exactly what we&#039;re doing right now. They still have those thumbnails in instructions today (for example, in The Simpsons&#039; House there&#039;s a set of instructions for the Simpsons&#039; famous pink car, the garage, and then various sections of the house, and each of those sections has a little thumbnail preceding them). I wonder if they should do this for other things. Maybe if they put little pictures of you as a healthy, happy adult on packages of vegetables, kids would be more into them. A picture at the start of high school of me showing my report card to my parents and having them not be mad at me probably would have motivated me a bit more in class. I mean, it wouldn&#039;t hurt. Anyway, it just feels a little bit silly for Giant Truck.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Instructions for Giant Truck: Chapter One: Giant Truck. In this set of instructions we will be building Giant Truck.&lt;/em&gt; Good to know.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Anyway, the first step requires four pieces. The two &lt;a href=&quot;http://rebrickable.com/parts/3460&quot;&gt;1x8&lt;/a&gt; and one &lt;a href=&quot;http://rebrickable.com/parts/3795&quot;&gt;2x6&lt;/a&gt; black plates are no problem. &lt;a href=&quot;http://rebrickable.com/parts/2719&quot;&gt;The 1x10 Technic Plate with Toothed Ends&lt;/a&gt;, however . . .&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Great, it&#039;s the first step and I&#039;m already stuck.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Digging through the Ol&#039; Archive, I found that I have (at least) eight &lt;a href=&quot;http://rebrickable.com/parts/4262&quot;&gt;1x6&lt;/a&gt; versions of that technic plate, and at least one &lt;a href=&quot;http://rebrickable.com/parts/4442&quot;&gt;1x8&lt;/a&gt;. Cue the first actual picture of Lego pieces that I took (finally):&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/Lego/prog-beams.png&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;In Grey &lt;em&gt;and&lt;/em&gt; Black. I don&#039;t know what that 1x8 plate is doing in this picture.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;According to Rebrickable, part 2719: &lt;a href=&quot;http://rebrickable.com/parts/2719&quot;&gt;Technic Plate 1x10 with Toothed Ends&lt;/a&gt; was in 23 sets in grey including Giant Truck (it&#039;s also in one set in black, and another set in light bluish gray). I have exactly none of those sets in the Ol&#039; Archive. This shall be the first piece I have to hunt for, I guess. In the meantime, I have a couple of part 2711: &lt;a href=&quot;http://rebrickable.com/parts/2711&quot;&gt;1x5 Technic Plate with Toothed Ends, 2 Studs and Center Axle Hole&lt;/a&gt; (it just rolls off the tongue), which can be put side-by-side to make the plate I need. They&#039;re black instead of grey, but they&#039;ll at least make do until I can find the proper piece.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/Lego/prog-step1complete.png&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;I always like when the first step of these old-school sets was basically just &quot;take these pieces and put them generally near each other.&quot;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Step one complete!&lt;/strong&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;&lt;em&gt;How much did I have?&lt;/em&gt; 75%
&lt;br /&gt;&lt;em&gt;How much did I improvise?&lt;/em&gt; 25%
&lt;br /&gt;&lt;em&gt;Does it look like a truck yet?&lt;/em&gt; Heavens no.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Step 2&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/Lego/5571-step-2.png&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Here it is again, in case you forgot.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Each step of the Giant Truck instructions includes a handy little box showing exactly what parts the step requires. This information is incredibly useful, and (pretty much) all Lego instructions today have these boxes on each step. However, this wasn&#039;t always the case. Giant Truck, being obviously the King of Lego was given the honor of these info boxes; other &quot;expert&quot; sets over the years that weren&#039;t specifically labeled with the Technic badge were also bestowed the honor. Regular sets in the 90&#039;s, however, were not deemed worthy. This often (for me, at least) led to moments where you would notice pieces in the instructions and realize that they were supposed to be added several pages ago - or you would end up with pieces at the end of it all with no idea where or when they were supposed to go.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/Lego/5976-page14.png&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Page 14 of 1999&#039;s &lt;a href=&quot;http://brickset.com/sets/5976-1/River-Expedition&quot;&gt;5976: River Expedition&lt;/a&gt;, containing steps 19 and 20. Can you spot all the differences between these pictures?&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Modern sets owe those part info panels to the &lt;a href=&quot;http://brickset.com/sets/theme-Technic&quot;&gt;Technic&lt;/a&gt; line. Instructions for Technic sets included the panels all the way back to the &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.peeron.com/scans/850-1&quot;&gt;70&#039;s&lt;/a&gt; when Technic was first a thing. They slowly trickled down to all of the instructions around &lt;a href=&quot;http://brickset.com/sets/year-2000&quot;&gt;2000&lt;/a&gt; (aught-aught) and &lt;a href=&quot;http://brickset.com/sets/year-2001&quot;&gt;2001&lt;/a&gt; (aught-one), at which point most of the &quot;regular&quot; set instructions have them. Quickly perusing instructions online, I found &lt;a href=&quot;http://brickset.com/sets/8404-1/Public-Transport-Station&quot;&gt;sets&lt;/a&gt; lacking the info panels even into 2010 (aught-ten), but I&#039;m pretty sure those are the exception. Even the cheapest sets today have them. It only makes sense to have that info across the board, and I&#039;m definitely glad the Lego Group listened to 10 year-old me when I was the first person to have that idea.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/Lego/60018-step6.png&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Here&#039;s Step 6 (the entirety of page 10) for &lt;a href=&quot;http://brickset.com/sets/60018-1/Cement-Mixer&quot;&gt;60018: Cement Mixer&lt;/a&gt;, from 2013 (a fantastic little set). Here you see just how comically basic the instructions can be these days.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So Giant Truck Step 2 requires one &lt;a href=&quot;http://rebrickable.com/parts/3010&quot;&gt;1x4&lt;/a&gt; red brick and two &lt;a href=&quot;http://rebrickable.com/parts/3622&quot;&gt;1x3&lt;/a&gt; red bricks. That isn&#039;t a problem at all. I even have the right colors and I think they&#039;re vintage pieces, so that&#039;s a bonus. Hot rod dudes are always looking for the same model year parts, right?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/Lego/prog-step2complete.png&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;So far the improvised piece is working great.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Step two complete!&lt;/strong&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;&lt;em&gt;How much did I have?&lt;/em&gt; 100%!
&lt;br /&gt;&lt;em&gt;Does it look like a truck yet?&lt;/em&gt; Still definitely no.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Step 3&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/Lego/5571-step-3.PNG&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;It looks like Giant Truck is going to rely heavily on those grey &lt;a href=&quot;http://rebrickable.com/parts/4274&quot;&gt;technic half pin&lt;/a&gt; pieces (or as Brickset more awesome-ly calls them, &quot;&lt;a href=&quot;http://brickset.com/parts/427402&quot;&gt;Connector Peg with Knob&lt;/a&gt;&quot;) to attach details to later on.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Now the fun begins. I was worried about these super long Technic beams, since they aren&#039;t at all as common anymore as they used to be. However, digging into the Ol&#039; Archives revealed that I have &lt;em&gt;several&lt;/em&gt;. Additionally, what Lego piece collection is complete without about ten thousand of those &quot;Peg with Knob&quot; pieces? My collection has plenty of them at any rate - they will not be a problem.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/Lego/prog-step3parts.png&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Here are the parts for step 3. So far I have learned that I need a better way to photograph Lego pieces besides just putting them on my filthy, poorly-lit desk.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So &lt;a href=&quot;http://rebrickable.com/parts/3703&quot;&gt;1x16 Technic Brick with Holes&lt;/a&gt; - check. 1x6 plate - no problem. Peg knobs, I&#039;ve got plenty of those. I&#039;m rocking and rolling now (well, I&#039;m not rolling, the wheels don&#039;t get added for quite some time.)&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;According to Rebrickable, the 1x16 Technic brick with holes has 584 instances in 150 sets, going all the way back to 1980. Mine probably came from 1998&#039;s &lt;a href=&quot;http://brickset.com/sets/3038-1/Super-Challenge&quot;&gt;3038: Super Challenge&lt;/a&gt;. That set is noteworthy for being an indicator (perhaps harbinger) of the future of Technic, since it relies heavily on the &lt;a href=&quot;http://rebrickable.com/parts/32278&quot;&gt;studless beams&lt;/a&gt; that have (pretty much) completely replaced their studded counterparts in the aught-aughts and aught-aughteens. Thankfully Super Challenge had a couple 1x16&#039;s of the studded variety for me to utilize on Giant Truck 16 years later.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/Lego/prog-step3problem.png&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The improvised beam is causing a potential problem, now. These stand-ins are missing a stud, so this will reduce the structural strength of the truck ever-so-slightly. We&#039;ll see if this proves to be a problem.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/Lego/prog-step3complete.png&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Three steps in and there&#039;s no serious problem yet.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Step three complete!&lt;/strong&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;&lt;em&gt;How much did I have?&lt;/em&gt; 100%
&lt;br /&gt;&lt;em&gt;Does it look like a truck yet?&lt;/em&gt; No, but it is one piece at least.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Step 4&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/Lego/5571-step-4.png&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;This caption is about as boring as step 4 is.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;We finish up today with what is basically a rehash of step 3. No 1x6 plate this time around, however. In the end, step 4 is a predictable romp with the same old plot points and no surprises. I predict a poor showing at the box office this fall. Wait, what were we talking about?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/Lego/prog-step4complete.png&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Yeah, I had the front assembly a bit too far forward in the last step. I&#039;ve fixed it, so don&#039;t worry.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Step four complete!&lt;/strong&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;&lt;em&gt;How much did I have?&lt;/em&gt; 100%
&lt;br /&gt;&lt;em&gt;Does it look like a truck?&lt;/em&gt; Yes - er, wait - no.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I&#039;ll leave it there for now. The Giant Truck is &lt;strong&gt;7.7% complete&lt;/strong&gt;. After four steps we are left with something that is neither giant nor truck, but it&#039;s . . . well, it clearly has a long way to go, but progress is, as they say, progress (does anybody say that?). Perhaps it&#039;s just nostalgia, but building something from digital instructions loses something from the more tangible counterpart. There&#039;s a certain magic about turning the page and seeing what&#039;s to come, and judging how cool a set is by how thick the book is (which could explain why the instructions are so much longer lately). Indeed, Lego instructions, digital or not, have come a long way in the last twenty-aught years or so. Are we, though, as Lego fans living in the future, any better or worse off than they, the Lego fans living in the past, were in ninety-whatever? It&#039;s difficult to determine without some more sophisticated maths (and without letting those pesky opinions cloud the issue). One thing is easy to quantify, though: &lt;a href=&quot;http://rebrickable.com/stats/sets&quot;&gt;3,755 sets&lt;/a&gt; have come out since the nineties that those poor shlubs never had. I&#039;d say that makes us the winners, better instructions or not. So until next time, you lucky Lego fans of the future, keep on building.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Feel free to let me know if you have any thoughts or suggestions, too. &lt;em&gt;For the sake of full disclosure: stats, part names, set lists, and other data points were taken from &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.brickset.com&quot;&gt;Brickset&lt;/a&gt; and / or &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.rebrickable.com&quot;&gt;Rebrickable&lt;/a&gt;. Images of instructions were taken from official Lego instruction PDF&#039;s (or in the case of super old stuff, the scans available on &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.peeron.com/&quot;&gt;Peeron&lt;/a&gt;), and they&#039;re the property of the Lego Group (obviously). Hopefully they don&#039;t sue me for loving them too much.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;To recap, I have embarked on a new long-term project involving something very awesome to me, Lego. I have gone back to my childhood and picked out an epic, monumental Lego set that I&#039;ve always wanted to build - 1996&#039;s 5571: Giant Truck. I&#039;m going to slowly, perhaps over the course of years, put that set together. I dove right into the instructions (after a lot of rambling) and was able to get the first four steps completed with what I had laying around in the Ol&#039; Archives, only having to improvise once to fashion a piece I didn&#039;t have out of two smaller ones I did. With any luck, Giant Truck will mostly require more common parts - that is, ones that I actually have. Of all the 1,742 parts in Giant Truck, which is the most common, I wonder? What about in all of the Lego world? What is the Champion Part?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/Lego/4/4100457.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;This isn&#039;t it, but a crown seemed appropriate or something.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Finding the most common Lego piece kind of depends on how you want to judge it (and what numbers you can trust). Basically there are two ranking systems. You can rank pieces by how many times they&#039;ve been used in total, in which case multiple instances in a single set will improve a piece&#039;s ranking, or you can  rank them purely by how many sets they&#039;ve appeared in, quantities notwithstanding. Both stats have their merits, but I tend to think of the second one as being a bit more universal. Some sets might take advantage of a whole bunch of one piece or another, but in my opinion the Champion Part is the one that has been used in the most sets. I think that shows more usefulness or versatility - or maybe just the part that&#039;s the simplest. Rebrickable shows both ranks, and I think their numbers are reasonably trustworthy, so I&#039;ll blatantly copy and paste both stats here to make it look like I actually did research.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Let&#039;s get back to the Giant Truck, already in progress.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Step 5&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/Lego/4/5571-step-5.png&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The parts count for each step is starting to go up.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I want to be able to know the origin of every piece I put into Giant Truck, but for some it seems a little &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7Sor0LXiSZg&quot;&gt;un-possible&lt;/a&gt;. This step contains some super common parts that could have come from anywhere. A lot of these parts have been around since the Beginning, or at least as near as makes no difference. They&#039;ve appeared in hundreds - in fact thousands, of sets over the last fifty-or-whatever years. Let&#039;s just take each piece in this step one by one.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/Lego/4/302026.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;First up: this one.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The 2x4 Plate, or Part &lt;a href=&quot;http://rebrickable.com/parts/3020&quot;&gt;3020&lt;/a&gt; as his friends call him, is definitely one of those super common parts. This is one of THE Lego pieces - one of the ones everybody has, even if they don&#039;t collect Lego sets. It appears almost 20,000 times in over 3,400 different sets and 40 different colors. That makes it the 11th most common part overall, and the second most common part included in a set. It&#039;s safe to say that I own at least one of the 1,048 sets that had a 2x4 Plate in black (element ID 302026). This particular one I&#039;m using could have been from quite a few of those. I would list the ones I have, but it&#039;s too numerous for how lazy I feel right now.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It should be a bit easier, however, to track down where my 2x6 Plate (Part ID &lt;a href=&quot;http://rebrickable.com/parts/3795&quot;&gt;3795&lt;/a&gt;) might be from. I was somewhat surprised to see that the 2x6 plate is actually pretty common, at 28th overall and ninth by set use, appearing almost 10,000 times in just over 2,400 different sets in 36 colors since its introduction in 1978. The color I need (specifically &quot;Light Gray&quot;, Element ID 379502) was one of the original colors for the 2x6 plates and has appeared 511 times in 240 sets since 1978 - more than I expected.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/Lego/4/2x6-light-grey-sets.png&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Specifically these sets.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The odds are actually semi-decent that mine came from &lt;a href=&quot;http://brickset.com/sets/1821-1/Rally-Racers&quot;&gt;1821&lt;/a&gt;: Rally Racers, from 1996, which would make this one of those sweet, sweet same-model-year parts. Rally Racers is a fitting set to get parts from because it contains a pair of trucks, so these parts already have some truck experience. For the record, Rally Racers also includes a black 2x4 Plate. That&#039;s quite a useful little set, there.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/Lego/4/1821-1.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Keep racing, fellas, at least until I dismantle you for all your plates.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The 1x3 Brick (Part ID &lt;a href=&quot;http://rebrickable.com/parts/3622&quot;&gt;3622&lt;/a&gt;, in black 362226) is a bit more uncommon. Like the 2x6 plate this piece was first seen in 1978, but in fewer colors. Today it ranks in at 20 overall and 31 by set use. Of course, that&#039;s out of like 17,000 parts, so it&#039;s still quite common. In Black the piece has appeared so far in 365 sets (you could build one a day for an entire year!), so that actually makes that particular color more common than the 2x6 Plate in Gray that I just dug up. Also, since black is a color the Lego Group still produces, this is a part that has appeared in sets all the way into 2014 and (probably) beyond (for example there are a modest 32 of them in &lt;a href=&quot;http://brickset.com/sets/10237-1&quot;&gt;10237&lt;/a&gt;: Tower of Orthanc from 2013). I could very well have pried this one out of &lt;a href=&quot;http://brickset.com/sets/6048-1&quot;&gt;6048&lt;/a&gt;: Majisto&#039;s Magical Workshop, a beautiful little set from 1993. I think Majisto&#039;s Workshop was my sister&#039;s when we were kids and as a result I wasn&#039;t allowed to touch, look at, play with, or think about it, but I have it now so who gets the last laugh?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/Lego/4/suckitaili.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Look eight-year-old me, I totally won! Take that, twelve-year-old my sister!&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So what&#039;s the most common piece to appear in a set? This is apropos trivia, since the part is in fact included in this step of Giant Truck. It&#039;s the Inverted 2x4 Double Slope. Just kidding - it&#039;s the &lt;a href=&quot;http://rebrickable.com/parts/3023&quot;&gt;1x2 Plate&lt;/a&gt;, which has appeared no fewer than 45,500 times in almost 4,000 sets. It&#039;s the second most common part overall, because there is one other part that appears in higher quantities, but at least according to Rebrickable (or at least according to my interpretation of the numbers on Rebrickable that don&#039;t really have any explanation), no part has appeared in more sets than the good old 1x2. I need a yellow one in this step, which is one of the less common colors, appearing in 629 sets (the black 1x2 has appeared in 1,315). This one could have come from &lt;a href=&quot;http://brickset.com/sets/8828-1&quot;&gt;8828&lt;/a&gt;: Front End Loader, a set I somehow had two of as a kid. A yellow 1x2 plate is also in &lt;a href=&quot;http://brickset.com/sets/6335-1&quot;&gt;6335&lt;/a&gt;: Indy Transport (&#039;96 - same model year), but since my one of those is still at Mom and Dad&#039;s house, I don&#039;t think this one came from there. This piece totally tore it up in 2014, actually, appearing in almost 40 different sets (just in yellow), so it&#039;s still super easy to get your hands on.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/Lego/4/302326.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The most common Lego piece to appear in a set.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;What about the part that&#039;s number one overall? This is less apropos, because none of them appear in this particular step (but they will come up in Giant Truck eventually, I&#039;m sure). Interestingly, it seems to be the &lt;a href=&quot;http://rebrickable.com/parts/3004&quot;&gt;1x2 brick&lt;/a&gt;, which has been made in 52 colors since 1959. It just edges out the plate version by appearing 62,633 times (give or take), but falls short of both the 1x2 plate and the 2x4 plate by only appearing in 3,338 sets. Apparently the 1x2 shape is the most useful of all the Lego piece sizes. If this step had called for one of these 1x2 bricks, this could possibly be the easiest step of Giant Truck. Since it isn&#039;t in this step, though, I can&#039;t really justify bringing it up right now, so just forget I did.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/Lego/4/300426.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Not really relevant to what we&#039;re doing.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This step also calls for a couple 1x2 Tiles, which is also a pretty common part. These studless wonders have appeared over 15,000 times in almost 2,000 sets, ranking it 15th overall and 17th by set. The use of this piece is boosted, of course, by the number of different printed versions that exist. This versatile part has been used for keyboards, equipment panels, bus tickets, license plates (for example &quot;&lt;a href=&quot;http://rebrickable.com/parts/3069bpb288&quot;&gt;OUTATIME&lt;/a&gt;&quot;), other random text, dashboards, cash, envelopes, the word &quot;POLICE,&quot; and tons of other things. I need a couple blue ones for Giant Truck, and I was able to find them pretty easily.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The 1x2 tile has come in 50 different colors, including Blue, Medium Blue, Sky Blue, Dark Blue, Maersk Blue, Sand Blue, Trans-Dark Blue, and Trans-Light Blue. I&#039;m pretty sure the ones I dug up are the regular blue that I require. It looks like the Blue 1x2 Tile first appeared in 1992 with &lt;a href=&quot;http://brickset.com/sets/6038-1&quot;&gt;6038&lt;/a&gt;: Wolfpack Renegades. I don&#039;t have that set, but I do have &lt;a href=&quot;http://brickset.com/sets/7553-1&quot;&gt;7553&lt;/a&gt;: City Advent Calendar (2011), which had one, &lt;a href=&quot;http://brickset.com/sets/71006-1&quot;&gt;71006&lt;/a&gt;: The Simpsons&#039; House (2014), which has eight, &lt;a href=&quot;http://brickset.com/sets/5988-1&quot;&gt;5988&lt;/a&gt;: The Temple of Anubis (1998), which has one, and &lt;a href=&quot;http://brickset.com/sets/6331-1&quot;&gt;6331&lt;/a&gt;: Patriot Jet (1996), which has nine. One of these that I&#039;m using might be from the Advent Calendar (I bet you never thought about Advent Calendars as a source for parts!), but I can be pretty sure at least one of these is from the same-model-year Patriot Jet (the Simpsons&#039; house is stored in a separate container, and the Temple of Anubis is two hours away at my Mom and Dad&#039;s house, so it can&#039;t be from those). I&#039;ll look into colors more in a future post.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/Lego/4/306923.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;A very difficult piece to visualize.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;To be extra, pedantically clear, this 1x2 Tile is specifically &lt;a href=&quot;http://rebrickable.com/parts/3069b&quot;&gt;3069b&lt;/a&gt;: Tile 1x2 with Groove, which first appeared in 1974. There&#039;s a tiny, well, groove around the bottom of all of the tile pieces, which gives you just a bit of purchase for pulling them apart (or for wedging that remover tool in there), since there aren&#039;t any studs up top to use for leverage. Indeed, without that simple tiny groove, these would be sucky to remove (but easier to write rhyming couplets about). There was a Tile 1x2 Without Groove (&lt;a href=&quot;http://rebrickable.com/parts/3069a&quot;&gt;3069a&lt;/a&gt;), which appeared in the 60&#039;s and 70&#039;s, while also appearing for some reason in a few sets in the early aught-tens. For the record, the non-grooved 1x2 tile is ranked 309 overall and 868 by set, which isn&#039;t too shabby for a piece that (for the most part) hasn&#039;t been produced in 35 years. Giant Truck will not be using any Tile 1x2 Without Groove, so you can forget I mentioned that one, too.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Unlike the other pieces in this step, the black Inverted 45 degree 2x4 Double Slope took a bit of digging, but I do have one. By my reckoning, this one also came from &lt;a href=&quot;http://brickset.com/sets/6331-1&quot;&gt;6331&lt;/a&gt; Patriot Jet, which is proving to be another pretty good source for parts along with those racin&#039; trucks. The double slope (part number &lt;a href=&quot;http://rebrickable.com/parts/4871&quot;&gt;4871&lt;/a&gt;, if you&#039;re curious) has been used 652 times in 352 sets since being introduced in 1985. It comes in 14 colors, but first appeared in Light Gray in &lt;a href=&quot;http://brickset.com/sets/6377-1/Delivery-Center&quot;&gt;6377&lt;/a&gt;: Delivery Center. The black one (which started its career in &#039;87 as a &lt;a href=&quot;http://brickset.com/sets/6954-1/Renegade&quot;&gt;spaceship part&lt;/a&gt;) is in 76 sets, including at least one Advent Calendar (not the one I have) and a couple sets that came out this year (2014). It&#039;s one of those old standbys that&#039;s always been around (to me that&#039;s literal, since it was first produced the year before I was born).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So anyway, all this is to say that I have all of the parts for this step.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/Lego/4/step5-ready.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;Sheesh, why didn&#039;t I just say that?&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The little rear assembly in this step is, perhaps, the first visual embellishment of the Truck so far. We&#039;ll be able to see how that sloped piece will look as more Giant Truck gets built around it, but it might be our first glimpse of the Giant attention to detail in this set. It&#039;s also interesting that the 1x2 piece inside there is yellow, considering we may never see it in the final product. I always wonder if designers put bright colors in places you&#039;ll never see them like that just for the heck of it, or if they were trying to meet certain color quotas. Perhaps we&#039;ll never know.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/Lego/4/step5-assembled.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;The truck is starting to take shape. It still isn&#039;t a truck shape, but it&#039;s some sort of shape.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Step five complete:&lt;br /&gt;
How many parts were needed? 8!&lt;br /&gt;
How much did I have? 100%&lt;br /&gt;
Does it look like a truck yet? Nope.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Boy, if I can continue to ramble on this much I ought to be able to eek this project out for the rest of my life. The only problem with doing that, aside from the fact that nobody in their right minds would read that much inane information, is that all of the statistics I&#039;m posting in these earlier posts will probably be completely obsolete and incorrect by the time this is all said and done. The Lego world is an ever changing one, and with new sets introduced basically every couple weeks, there are new sources for parts, both common and rare. Who knows, maybe in a few months we&#039;ll have a new set with a whole bunch of some part that drives it up to the top of the charts, or we&#039;ll see some huge paradigm shift that will dethrone the current 1x2 champ. One of the things I love about this world is that like the very creations we can build with them, the parts themselves are ever changing. However, sets that will come out next year will still contain parts I could use in this set from 1996. That 1x2 plate is the champ because it&#039;s the same piece (at least as far as we need to concern ourselves) that they&#039;ve been making for 50 years. This world, then, is as dynamic and fluid as you want it to be. That&#039;s pretty awesome. What&#039;s your champion part - that part you find most useful or important? What piece do you have the most of in your collection? Whether you&#039;re going to go count out your pieces or not, keep on building, my friends. I&#039;ll see you all next time.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It&#039;s worth noting (again) that all of the statistics shown here were taken from Rebrickable and are accurate only inasmuch as that site is accurate. The numbers are almost constantly going up (as new sets are released or catalogued on Rebrickable&#039;s database), so the numbers listed here will not be accurate for long. Still, it&#039;s a reasonable representation of part rankings and history.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Also, remember to let me know if you like these posts or if there&#039;s anything you&#039;d like me to elaborate on in the future (as if I&#039;m not already elaborating far too much).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In case you haven&#039;t seen my website in a while - or you haven&#039;t spoken to me at all - I&#039;ve been working on a new project involving one of my favoritest things, Lego. I&#039;m working on building a particular Lego set that I thought was super cool when I was a kid. The 1,742 piece epic that is Lego Model &lt;a href=&quot;http://brickset.com/sets/5571-1/Giant-Truck&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;5571: Giant Truck&lt;/a&gt;, from 1996, was always my favorite page of the Lego Shop at Home Catalog, and now I&#039;m going to build my very own. I found the instructions online, and through the power of having a lot of Lego bricks laying around, I am hopeful that I can make it happen. Only time will tell how far I will be able to get before I hit the inevitable roadblock of &quot;I just don&#039;t have one of those.&quot; As the steps have worn on and I have been tasked with less common parts, time has begun to tell.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;iframe width=&quot;560&quot; height=&quot;315&quot; src=&quot;https://www.youtube.com/embed/OHqa6q-IReY&quot; frameborder=&quot;0&quot; allowfullscreen&gt;&lt;/iframe&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Watch this video for my latest update, or read below if you prefer reading to watching. Yes, I realize that it took me way too long to post this. While getting Giant truck together, I am also working on getting my life together.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Anyway, my last post completed step six, so now I&#039;m ready for step 7, and I&#039;m nervously awaiting the time when I hit an Inevitable Roadblock.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Step 7&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/Lego/post 6/5571-step-7.png&quot; /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I have hit an Inevitable Roadblock. Now I need two more of those &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.rebrickable.com/parts/2719&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;8x1 Technic plate with toothed end mounts&lt;/a&gt;. I definitely knew that this was coming when the first one of these came up back in step three or whatever, because these Technic plates never travel alone. I have the other parts for this step, but not those Technic plates. This will be the first case where I&#039;ll just have to halt progress until I get them.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So how do I do that?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;As I said in the earlier post about step three or whatever, these parts are featured in 23 sets, so I could look around for one of those. Let&#039;s hit up Bricklink.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The coolest set (aside from Giant Truck, obviously) that these parts are in would probably be &lt;a href=&quot;http://brickset.com/sets/8868&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;8868: Air Tech Claw Rig&lt;/a&gt;, from 1992 (four years before Giant Truck). It&#039;s a super sweet truck with a big crane on the back - or some sort of weird car with a grabber thing on the front (or a lot of other things I guess, if you&#039;re good at building things with Lego). It originally went for $139.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/Lego/post 6/8868-1.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;8868: Air Tech Claw Rig. It&#039;s even fun to say.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Lego is pretty serious about cranes as it turns out; 8868 was neither the first nor the last. In fact, just in &#039;012 they made what is basically a remake of the Airtech Claw Rig, &lt;a href=&quot;http://brickset.com/sets/9397&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;9397: Logging Truck&lt;/a&gt;, which had a retail price of - look at that - $139 (the newer one has more pieces, too). Those of you saying Lego has gotten more expensive can go ahead and eat your hats now, or whatever. The modern 9397 is Hell of more awesome in a literal sense (8868 is arguably more awesome in a uselessly nostalgic &quot;back in my day&quot; sense).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/Lego/post 6/9397-1.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;One of many logging trucks made by the Lego Group. Just why do they hate trees so much?&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Claw Rig is going for a minimum of $105 on Bricklink. At this point in my life (which was several months ago, since these posts take so long for me to make), I had never bought anything on Bricklink before. I wasn&#039;t sure how shipping worked, and the cheapest options were all in Europe. I was pretty worried about that. Through the power of hindsight, I now know that it&#039;s prohibitively expensive to ship any Lego sets from overseas. Anyway, Claw Rig has five - count &#039;em - five of those 8x1 plates-with-whatevers I&#039;ll need, giving me a pretty inefficient surplus of two. However, there&#039;s a good chance I&#039;ll be able to use quite a few other parts from Claw Rig in Giant Truck. Also - I should point out - if I buy a Claw Rig I&#039;ll also then have a super sweet Claw Rig that I can play with.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I&#039;m 29, why do you ask?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;There&#039;s another truck-with-crane option, &lt;a href=&quot;http://brickset.com/sets/8854&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;8854: Power Crane&lt;/a&gt;. This one&#039;s from 1989 and it&#039;s just a little too funny looking for me. This does show just how awesome those pneumatic functions were, considering this set from &#039;89 has very similar pumps and actuators to the ones you can find on sets today. Power Crane is priced in the 70&#039;s on BrickLink (from the Netherlands). It has exactly three of the little plates I need, so there&#039;s no unnecessary redundancy. However, the extensive red-ness of Power Crane leaves little room, I think, for other parts I could use, and I wouldn&#039;t have that super sweet Claw Rig, so I think I&#039;ll pass on this one.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/Lego/post 6/8854-1.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;8854: Power Crane, with a face only a mother could love. A mother crane.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Yet another crane option (there isn&#039;t really anything more Lego than a crane, I guess - except for maybe a &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/Lego/post 6/ferries.png&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;ferry&lt;/a&gt;) is &lt;a href=&quot;http://brickset.com/sets/8438&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;8438: Pneumatic Crane Truck&lt;/a&gt;, from 2003. It&#039;s a re-release of &lt;a href=&quot;http://brickset.com/sets/8431&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;8431&lt;/a&gt; (from 2002), which was a re-release of &lt;a href=&quot;http://brickset.com/sets/8460&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;8460&lt;/a&gt; (from 1995). The early 2000&#039;s were a really weird time for Lego. Still, since this wasn&#039;t actually made in the early 2000&#039;s, it&#039;s a cool set. It&#039;s a bit less truck than Air Tech Claw Rig, but a bit more crane. Like Claw Rig and Power Crane, Pneumatic Crane Truck takes advantage of the titular Pneumatic functionality to operate, just like a real crane! Since it&#039;s smaller than Claw Rig, it&#039;s a bit cheaper. It was originally $85, and you can find them on BrickLink for - as of whenever I looked it up - $73 (from the Netherlands, so that isn&#039;t really a number that applies to me at all).  I really like the look of Pneumatic Crane Truck, and when I put myself into the shoes of younger me (or current-age me, for that matter), it&#039;s a tough choice between it and Claw Rig.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/Lego/post 6/8438-1.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;8438: Pneumatic Crane Truck - surprisingly hard to say.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The real vintage choice is &lt;a href=&quot;http://brickset.com/sets/8054&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;8054: Universal Motor Set&lt;/a&gt;, from 1989. I guess this is the same amount of vintage as Power Crane, but this one feels more vintage to me. They don&#039;t make these &quot;here are some bits, and some things you can do with aforesaid bits&quot; sets anymore in the Technic label, and I think that&#039;s a shame. A lot of things can be learned about Engineering tinkering with one of these, but God forbid we give kids a chance to not know what they&#039;re doing, they might make a mistake. Anyway, Universal Motor Set has a crane and a car and another car and a helicopter, plus whatever else you feel like making with a motor in it. This also has a super old-school motor kit which some collectors might be all &quot;oh baby&quot; over. I&#039;m not super keen on the motor, though, since it isn&#039;t in Giant Truck. Universal Motor Set is going for as little as $39 ($45 from somebody in the US).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/Lego/post 6/8054-1.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;8054: Universal motor set. It&#039;s universal as long as you are building a crane.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Another, much cheaper, option is &lt;a href=&quot;http://brickset.com/sets/8829&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;8829: Dune Blaster&lt;/a&gt;. I had a very similar vehicle to Dune Blaster (&lt;a href=&quot;http://brickset.com/sets/8320&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;8320: Coastal Cop Buggy&lt;/a&gt;, from two years later) - but mine doesn&#039;t have the parts I need. Dune Blaster is a pretty straightforward buggy that also makes a motorcycle. It has suspension and a moving engine, which is kind of neat I guess. Dune Blaster is going for as little as $17 (from the US) on BrickLink, which is also kind of neat.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/Lego/post 6/8829-1.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;8829: Dune Blaster: because dunes don&#039;t blast themselves!&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;If you&#039;re a cheapotron, though, the best choice might be &lt;a href=&quot;http://brickset.com/sets/5279&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;5279: Steering Elements, Plates and Gear Racks&lt;/a&gt;. This was just a little sack of bits that you could get to make your Legos able to steer, I guess. Like I said before, the rack and pinion setup was Hell of common in sets back in &quot;the day&quot; so I really don&#039;t know why you would want to get one of these, since these parts were everywhere at the time. Well, I guess maybe you&#039;re trying to build Giant Truck and need one of those sweet, sweet 8x1 jobs. It just happens that this sack of bits comes with three of them, so that&#039;s handy. It&#039;s $5 (from Germany) on BrickLink, so that&#039;s pretty handy, too - unless shipping ends up being more than the sack itself. For the money, SE, PaGR offers the smallest barrier to having the parts I need.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.denyconformity.com/assets/images/Lego/post 6/5279-1.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;5279: Steering Elements, Plates and Gear Racks. 1993&#039;s nominee for COOLEST NAME EVER.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;If you&#039;re an Omega Cheapotron you might say &quot;just buy three of those parts, dummy.&quot; Well, BrickLink does have a massive (perhaps even Giant) repository of parts for sale from all over the world. I can get those 8x1 plates for as little as $0.07 a piece (that&#039;s seven cents). Most places have a minimum total you have to meet with your order, but I&#039;m sure I could get there just by flipping a few pages ahead in Giant Truck&#039;s instructions to find a few more parts I need.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Something just feels a little cheap (-otron) about just buying parts, though. It is staying true to the &quot;building a hot rod in my garage&quot; aesthetic that I&#039;m going for I guess. I can just order all the parts I&#039;ll need and get this thing done and then I&#039;ll have that Giant Truck I always wanted. However, this endeavor will lose the &quot;look at how universal Legos are&quot; aesthetic that I was hoping to show off, too. There&#039;s something really fascinating about building this big (perhaps even Giant) truck purely from parts scavenged from other sets. Also this whole project may or may not just be an excuse to buy all of the old sets I lusted after but could never get because I was just a Poor Child. Now that I&#039;m a Rich Child I can do all the things I always wanted to do (which is pretty much exclusively buying Legos). On the other hand, is buying some old sets any different than buying old parts, when you get down to it, other than how much more expensive it will ultimately be?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I guess it comes down to what my goal here really is. If this truly is a hot-rod-in-the-garage project, I&#039;d just order the parts I need and get her done, as it were. However, that is a super sweet claw rig.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Spoiler alert: I ordered the Claw Rig.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;My name is Shauvon McGill and I will be your guide through the land of nonsense. Now, I understand that calling it nonsense probably doesn&amp;rsquo;t set it (or me, for that matter) up as a terribly respectable or in fact useful subject. However, just bear with me here, because in my professional opinion, the whole concept of nonsense does not get the respect it deserves. &amp;ldquo;That&amp;rsquo;s nonsense!&amp;rdquo; You might say to me. &amp;ldquo;Yes, exactly,&amp;rdquo; I reply. Then you will probably walk away because that&amp;rsquo;s not a great way for me to retain an audience. I promise that over the next weeks, months, and perhaps years if Kate will keep me around that long, I will show you a thing or two that just might - dare I say it - change the world! I&amp;rsquo;ll also occasionally tell some jokes, so you might at least have a good time.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Nonsense, malarky, &amp;ldquo;hoo-haw&amp;rdquo; - whatever you call it, you can&amp;rsquo;t deny that it&amp;rsquo;s actually kind of everywhere. Let&amp;rsquo;s face it, elevator pitches and business proposals are at least 80% claptrap. Turn on your TV right now - I&amp;rsquo;d bet good money the majority of your stations are going to be playing commercials at this very second (or some sort of news program). That&amp;rsquo;s two hundred channels of hogwash (especially those news programs - am I right?). I have sat through many a business conference whose agenda could easily be rewritten as drivel, prattle, a break for lunch, and finally light babble followed by a session of poppycock. To put it simply: Business is Baloney. You may be denying it right now, but search your feelings - on some level you know it to be true.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Here&amp;rsquo;s the important thing, though: there&amp;rsquo;s nothing wrong with that. That&amp;rsquo;s just how people operate, whether it&amp;rsquo;s business or anything else. Society is baloney. You can have a great idea, an unbeatable passion, or a brilliant mind, but if you don&amp;rsquo;t have the bunk to back it up, you&amp;rsquo;re going nowhere. Nonsense is important because it gives our thoughts structure. It transforms thoughts from mysterious unspoken things into real, tangible ideas. Think about this for a minute: you can think up a completely random thought in your brain and somehow transmit that thought in perfect high definition to someone else&amp;rsquo;s brain using nothing but words. You just mind controlled somebody using pure, homegrown balderdash.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Don&amp;rsquo;t fight that. Unlock it. Shape it. Manipulate it. Be the Emperor of Nonsense. Once you realize everything anybody has ever said has just been words somebody thought up, you have the greatest power of all: the power of nonsense. Once you learn that power, you&amp;rsquo;ll be unstoppable.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I&amp;rsquo;m getting ahead of myself, though (literally). I started this by introducing myself, and I ended up glossing right over that part and going straight to the nitty gritty without establishing just who I actually am. I got carried away with all of my mumbo jumbo. Let me take a step back, then, and establish some of my credentials.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I may be a young whippersnapper, but I am pretty proud of where my career has taken me so far. I graduated from Purdue University with a degree doing computery things back in 2009, at the height of the Great Job Crisis that Christian Bale and Steve Carell created (at least I think so, I haven&amp;rsquo;t seen that movie yet). That job crisis didn&amp;rsquo;t affect computery jobs, as it turns out, so off I went to Chicago to earn fame and fortune making apps and websites and working for high profile marketing and technology companies. I was successful, too. Well, maybe not fame so much, but I was really quite successful as a computery, programmery sort of person. I have worked for small start-ups, gigantic corporations, and many things in-between. I became pretty well versed in the language and methodology of business and of corporate America. To put it another way, I have developed a keen grasp of nonsense.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;All this was merely a day job, though, as I pursued my real passion, which began for me all the way back when I was a kid: goofiness - I mean, comedy. Goofiness is just something I was born with, like my left-handedness or my ridiculous height (though those both probably contribute to the goofiness, now that I think about it). Comedy, though, is a type of nonsense that is particularly special to me. Who doesn&amp;rsquo;t love a good joke? Well, the Germans, I guess, but this isn&amp;rsquo;t Germany. I learned early on how powerful a well-placed punch line can be, and chasing that power led me to study Improv.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I spent four years as a member of an Improv Comedy group at Purdue, and continued to pursue it in Chicago, studying at the prestigious Second City Training Center (people call it the Harvard of Comedy - seriously). I have studied movement, stage combat, Shakespeare, comedy, clowning, and mime (yes, even mime). By day I wore the tie of business and the pants of working in cubicles, and by night I switched the tie with the tie of comedy (they look very similar, but the comedy one is easier to wear on your head). I have discovered that these parallel lives I have been living are not, in fact, so different. Reacting quickly to change, thinking outside the box, solving problems - these are all major parts of Improv, as well as the world of ties and cubicles.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Now it&amp;rsquo;s time for those worlds to collide. I want to share what I&amp;rsquo;ve learned about the strengths of Improv, and how these ideas and methods can - dare I say it - change the world! Join me, and by extension &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.thespeakers-studio.com&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;The Speaker&amp;rsquo;s Studio&lt;/a&gt;, in this new frontier.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;. . . or maybe that&amp;rsquo;s all just a bunch of nonsense - you be the judge.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Imagine floating in space, free from gravity, direction, or orientation (you have a space suit with oxygen, though, so don&amp;rsquo;t freak out). This is pure, undiluted freedom. Where do you go from there? Where &lt;em&gt;can&lt;/em&gt; you go, without any force to direct you or frame of reference to orient you? As humans I think we all need rules of some sort to govern the things we do. It&amp;rsquo;s comforting to have a structure to work within. We want to know that someone has spent time establishing a framework to keep us going in the right direction, or to keep us safe, or to keep everyone on the same page. This is one of the paradoxes of Improv: to experience freedom, we have to embrace our necessary structures. You can&amp;rsquo;t think outside the box without knowing what the box is in the first place. Pure freedom is useless without some sort of structure or guidance. Improv, therefore, needs some structure to work around. Improv, despite being an exploration of creative freedom, still needs rules.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I have been doing Improv for over ten years now. To be fair, I guess, since basically everything is made up, I&amp;rsquo;ve been doing improv for much longer than that. I&amp;rsquo;m talking about official, laugh at me on stage, capital &amp;lsquo;i&amp;rsquo; Improv, not just &amp;ldquo;making stuff up.&amp;rdquo; I&amp;rsquo;m talking about Improv as a performance style. I&amp;rsquo;m talking about Improv as an art form. It really is, too. If you don&amp;rsquo;t believe me, I suppose I should be glad I held back from the argument that it&amp;rsquo;s almost a religion. It&amp;rsquo;s an incredibly deep and complicated system of beliefs and techniques, with millions of hours of study being conducted as we speak and thousands of different exercises, theories, games, lessons, and platforms being consumed, shared, and preached throughout the world.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Let me just take a moment to establish that you might not agree with me in any way on any of this Nonsense I throw out. That is okay. My goal is to establish the Things that I have observed in the world, and collate them into a set of concepts that work for me. What works for me might not work for you. However, I would ask that you open your mind and take a moment to see things my way, and experiment with my observations. Either you will discover new truths that do, indeed, work for you, or you will discover disgusting lies that will not - either discovery is important and valuable. Discovering a thing that does not work can be as important as discovering something that does. It will get you closer to your own truth either way.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Anyway, I&amp;rsquo;m going to assume that anybody reading this is already meeting me halfway on the whole &amp;ldquo;art form&amp;rdquo; thing, or you&amp;rsquo;re at least willing to grant me the olive branch of &amp;ldquo;okay, sure whatever&amp;rdquo; to see just what I have to say about it. I don&amp;rsquo;t want to waste a bunch of time trying to make the very basic foundational argument, I want to move on to the implications of that argument. If Improv is an art form, or even a way of life in itself, what do we do with it?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;At the basic level, though, let&amp;rsquo;s just go ahead and define &amp;ldquo;Improv&amp;rdquo; so that we have that foundation upon which to build this system. Let us, at least for the sake of the next several paragraphs of text, define Improv as, &amp;ldquo;empowering the nature of the Human Mind to drive creativity and success in a given field.&amp;rdquo; Improv lives, of course, in the human mind, and it relies on the natural wiring and functionality of that mind to work. Most, if not all, techniques in Improv are designed to exploit (or perhaps simply direct) the way our minds work. Society conditions us to think in a very specific way, and Improv allows us to unlock that restriction and allow ourselves to think in any way we want. This unlocked mind can then be used to help us do anything, really, from comedy, to general creativity, psychotherapy, emotional awareness, personal development, leadership, public speaking, you name it. Simply put, capital &amp;lsquo;i&amp;rsquo; Improv makes us capital &amp;lsquo;a&amp;rsquo; Awesome. Of course, it isn&amp;rsquo;t enough to simply tell someone that she can do anything, though.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Improv is a very personal thing. It taps deep into that core, animal brain, deep in the sensitive, chewy nougat of one&amp;rsquo;s psyche. This is the strength of Improv, but it also means that everyone who studies it has to develop their own rules. I therefore cannot in good conscience stand before you (or sit behind my keyboard) and declare the definitive, Buzzfeed worthy list of Ten Improv Rules That will Change Your Life. For one thing, it&amp;rsquo;s still a relatively new art form that has not had time to chisel a series of commandments into any kind of stone tablets. For another, I don&amp;rsquo;t know if there will ever be a definitive, ultimate list of rules. It&amp;rsquo;s just too variable from person to person.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;What I can share with you are my own personal rules, collected, adapted and organized from my discoveries and experiences. At least, I can share with you how my list looks right at this moment. It, like me, is still an evolving, living organism, and will probably continue to evolve and adapt for the foreseeable future. Feel free to take notes, consider how these rules might apply to your life (or your own Improv work), and adapt them for your own use. I claim no ownership over the nature of the human mind, and I therefore cannot claim to be responsible for any rules governing it. These are simply observations.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;We start with the Prime Directive of Improv (don&amp;rsquo;t worry, there will be a Star Wars reference later), which is the rather ambiguous phrase, &amp;ldquo;yes, and.&amp;rdquo; This is the most common rule in Improv, and so I will give it the least attention. You can find entire books (not to mention t-shirts) on the subject of &amp;ldquo;yes, and&amp;rdquo; so there is little I can say on the subject that someone else hasn&amp;rsquo;t already said and been paid a lot of money to say. The core concept is that you should always be accepting of ideas, and constructive. &amp;ldquo;Yes, and&amp;rdquo; forms a foundation, where saying &amp;ldquo;no&amp;rdquo; or &amp;ldquo;yes, but&amp;rdquo; do not. In Improv - I would argue in all of life - all ideas are good ideas, and those offered freely and openly should always be built upon. If an idea doesn&amp;rsquo;t sound &amp;ldquo;good enough&amp;rdquo; for you, you can simply continue building on it until it does. Rejection gets us nowhere.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Yes, and&amp;rdquo; is the most common (I won&amp;rsquo;t say important, but you can feel free to) rule in Improv because it really is the foundation for creativity. The fascinating thing is that all action is really reaction. Even the most creative, unique things in the world are still a reaction to something. Improv, too, though a world of freedom and possibility, is almost entirely reactive, not spontaneous. &amp;ldquo;Yes, and&amp;rdquo; is, at its core, a directive simply to react. Listen, pay attention, and respond.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;You can practice saying &amp;ldquo;yes, and&amp;rdquo; at home. Find a friend, or a colleague, or that guy at work that everybody finds annoying. Strike up a conversation with them. For everything they say, respond with, &amp;ldquo;yes, and&hellip;&amp;rdquo; and then build on their idea. Tell them to do the same (probably a good idea because you might get in trouble if they catch onto the fact you&amp;rsquo;re saying &amp;ldquo;yes&amp;rdquo; to everything they say). It doesn&amp;rsquo;t have to be about anything specific, just start brainstorming something. You can quickly get into some pretty interesting territory, where you might not have found yourself otherwise.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I&amp;rsquo;m afraid that&amp;rsquo;s all the time we have for today. I know, I promised you a list and gave you only one thing. Why explain in a single post what I can eek out for several, though? I&amp;rsquo;ll be back very soon with the next rule. Until then, what do you think? Do you agree or disagree with anything I have said so far? How has the concept of &amp;ldquo;yes, and&amp;rdquo; come up in your life? How do you think embracing it could help you? Consider those questions as rhetorical or unrhetorical as you wish, taking into consideration the comment box below.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;For more stuff like this, check out &lt;a target=&quot;_blank&quot; href=&quot;http://www.thespeakers-studio.com&quot;&gt;The Speaker&#039;s Studio&lt;/a&gt;, or stay tuned for more posts here.&lt;/p&gt;

