&lt;/h5&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Yikes, ULDUM, you really got all those keywords in that product name, didn&amp;rsquo;t you? These are pretty noteworthy for just how space-age tiny they are. My mind is boggling just comparing these to that first pair I owned ten years ago. Seriously, though, this whole product page reads like some sort of satire.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/headphones/earpbuds.PNG&quot; /&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;This is a screenshot of the Amazon.com feature list for these headphones. #1 Best Product&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I&amp;rsquo;m not sure how I feel about the fact that they have to promise that these &amp;ldquo;Blustooth Stereo Earpbuds&amp;rdquo; were authorized by the governing bodies making sure consumer products aren&amp;rsquo;t going to murder you. When you buy something from LG or Sony, they definitely have CE, FCC, and UL approval, but they don&amp;rsquo;t have to lead with that on their promotional materials. It&amp;rsquo;s like Taco Bell having to advertise that they use &amp;ldquo;Real meat!&amp;rdquo; That really shouldn&amp;rsquo;t be a selling point.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Still, how cool would it be to go around saying you&amp;rsquo;re wearing your Wyatt Earpbuds? Also, that &amp;ldquo;8 hours of enjoying music time&amp;rdquo; is pretty enticing. The page also has an image promising &amp;ldquo;bilateral magnet adsorption How to exercise will not fall.&amp;rdquo; I don&amp;rsquo;t even know what that means, but I&amp;rsquo;m pretty sure I need it.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I think I&amp;rsquo;ll pass on these. I&amp;rsquo;ll leave them with their own words: &amp;ldquo;and hand shake to say bye bye.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;


&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
